<HEADLINE>
DON'T BUY TRADE DEFICIT DESPAIR 
</HEADLINE>
 COLUMN-KAN   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY JERRY HEASTER, THE KANSAS CITY STAR  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Saturday's wire story on June's record $30.6 billion U.S. trade
deficit showed how badly this economic statistic is misunderstood.
</P>
<P>
   Although it was a reasonably cogent account, it fell into the
trap of calling the shortfall ``the sole blot on an otherwise
vibrant U.S. economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Piffle! If anything, U.S. trade shortfalls are incontrovertible
proof of a vibrant economy. This reality bears repeating with some
frequency, because the trade imbalance invariably gets worse press
than it deserves.
</P>
<P>
   The last time we had a trade surplus, in fact, the economy was
in the doldrums and had been for years. The reason for the surplus
was diminishing consumer power in an economy critically dependent
on consumption for its growth. Between inflation and rising tax
burdens, overall American consumption had stagnated, which meant
less-than-dynamic demand for imported wares.
</P>
<P>
   With the current expansion tracking toward its 10th birthday
early next year, the story these days is one of unprecedented
consumer vigor. This has meant rising demand for foreign goods and
services. Meanwhile, the market for U.S. exports hasn't grown as
much as demand for imports because foreign fortunes have lagged the
record-setting U.S. run of prosperity.
</P>
<P>
   There is, of course, the worry that as foreign holdings of
dollar-denominated assets swell, America is increasingly vulnerable
to having to make good on its mounting debts. This fear, however,
assumes most all U.S. debtors will someday want to be repaid at
once, which isn't likely. This explains why doomsayers so far have
been wrong in warning that chronic trade deficits eventually will
impoverish America.
</P>
<P>
   As long as America remains a bastion of growth and an oasis of
political stability, it will continue to attract foreign capital in
many forms in amounts adequate to U.S. economic needs.
</P>
<P>
   Another misperception the story dealt with was claims that the
deficit reflects failed administration trade policies. Critics
contend these failures represent a betrayal of American workers who
have lost jobs to foreign labor markets.
</P>
<P>
   This contention seems bizarre in the face of the fact that the
jobless rate is lower than it has been for a generation, and since
1980 the U.S. economy has created more than twice as many jobs as
all the rest of the G-7 countries combined. In truth, the jobs that
have moved abroad are those that American workers either no longer
will do or that they can no longer do competitively, which is the
way the world works.
</P>
<P>
   The reality is that anyone in America who wants to work is
working, and those qualified for the best-paying jobs aren't having
trouble getting them.
</P>
<P>
   As it happens, June's deficit was fattened by purchases of
foreign oil at prices nearing 10-year highs. If it hadn't been oil,
though, it would have been something else. The more money we spent
on energy, the less we had to spend on other consumables.
</P>
<P>
   The really good news was that exports surged almost as much as
imports, which reflects continued strength of the U.S. economy.
This will mean more money in consumer pockets to buy more imported
wares, which implies continued humongous trade deficits, which,
despite media reports to the contrary, won't be a bad thing for
Americans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
