<SLUG> BC-LIFE-SCIENCES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKER URGES KANSAS AND MISSOURI TO SEEK MORE FUNDS FOR
RESEARCH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY JULIUS A. KARASH, THE KANSAS CITY STAR  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Amid heightened interest in research and development, Kansas and
Missouri must work together to obtain their fair share of federal
funds for life sciences research, U.S. Sen. Pat Roberts of Kansas
said Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all agree that basic and applied research conducted by
local universities, hospitals and research centers are the economic
development engines for inventions and discoveries that stimulate
creation of start-up companies,'' Roberts said in a luncheon
address at the Kansas City Club.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts' speech was part of a two-day tour of health- and
technology-related facilities in the Kansas City area and Lawrence,
including Midwest Research Institute, Children's Mercy Hospital,
the University of Kansas Medical Center, the Higuchi Biosciences
Center at the University of Kansas and the Stowers Institute for
Medical Research, currently under construction.
</P>
<P>
   Roberts said several major universities on the East and West
coasts receive a total of more than $1.5 billion in federal
research support every year, compared with about $100 million for
the University of Kansas and the University of Missouri.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our respective states are not getting a fair share of federal
research,'' Roberts said. ``Kansas City can garner a critical mass
for life sciences if you will join me in working together to
increase federal funding for life sciences.''
</P>
<P>
   To help achieve that goal, Roberts said, he will encourage
representatives of the National Institutes of Health and other
federal agencies to come to Kansas City and visit various research
and health sites.
</P>
<P>
   Before his speech, Roberts visited with officials of the Kansas
City Area Life Sciences Institute, which is working on plans to
turn Kansas City into one of the nation's top 10 biomedical
research and development sites.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you don't do this, we'll get further and further behind,
because our competition in other states is so fierce,'' Roberts
told John M. Edgar, co-chairman of the Life Sciences Institute.
</P>
<P>
   The Life Sciences Institute aims to raise $300 million for
communitywide research and development over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   Edgar said the institute will submit a business plan to the
boards of its two sponsoring organizations, the Kansas City Area
Development Council and the Civic Council of Greater Kansas City,
on Sept. 8. The two boards will vote on the plan at subsequent
meetings, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a great opportunity for Kansas City,'' Edgar said.
``It's also a great challenge.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
