<HEADLINE>
COMPANIES REPORT THAT 1.1 MILLION HAVE GONE FROM WELFARE TO WORK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 BY KEVIN MURPHY, THE KANSAS CITY STAR  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Chief executives of Sprint Corp. and several other
companies reported Tuesday that a welfare-to-work program they
helped launch four years ago had put 1.1 million people to work for
22,000 employers.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint was among five corporations nationwide that pioneered the
Welfare to Work Partnership, a government-assisted program to train
and employ welfare recipients.
</P>
<P>
   William T. Esrey, chairman and chief executive officer of
Westwood-based Sprint, and other corporate chiefs gave a report on
the program Tuesday to President Clinton, who described it is a key
part of welfare reform passed in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   But the report to the president said welfare recipients who want
jobs still face transportation and child care hurdles, and it
recommended that federal subsidies be extended when the 1996
legislation is revisited in two years.
</P>
<P>
   ``This doesn't mean the job is done,'' Eli Segal, a Clinton ally
and the president of the Welfare to Work Partnership, said at a
news conference Tuesday. ``There are still many people left
behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has touted welfare reform as a major achievement of his
administration, and he was quick to commend corporations Tuesday
for hiring so many welfare recipients.
</P>
<P>
   ``As many of these companies have learned, welfare recipients
are productive workers who want a hand up, not a handout,'' Clinton
said. Overall, welfare rolls have been halved, to about 6.3 million
people, in four years, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sprint has hired about 250 people off public assistance rolls
under the program, including most of about 60 persons who work at a
customer service call-in center opened at 18th and Vine in Kansas
City three years ago, company officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our success has been phenomenal in terms of the quality of
workers we've gotten, the jobs they've done, their attendance and
their reliability,'' Esrey said at the news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Esrey was singled out for addressing the transportation problem
for workers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked at where the potential workers were, and it was
right in the heart of the inner city,'' Esrey said. ``We moved the
jobs where the people were, and that really solved the
transportation problem.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Esrey said in an interview that he doesn't think the
federal government should keep putting the same amount of money
into the welfare-to-work program, as recommended in the report.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a great effort, but there are times when you get
something going and you have to keep it going, but you also have to
get out of the way,'' Esrey said. ``I don't think we should keep
funding at those levels. That's a Washington reaction.''
</P>
<P>
   The Welfare to Work Partnership has gotten about 22,000
companies to pledge to hire at least one person off welfare. The
partnership has used a $10.5 million Department of Labor grant and
private donations to run the program and provide job training.
</P>
<P>
   Employers that hire people off welfare can get federal subsidies
for training, child care and transportation, and are eligible for
tax credits. The program is part of about $16.5 billion in the
federal budget for welfare programs this year.
</P>
<P>
   Federal welfare money is dispersed as grants to the 50 states.
The partnership Tuesday recommended no cuts in funding.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nation's investment should be sustained to help states
tackle the difficult barriers faced by the `hardest to serve'
recipients remaining on the roll and those who have already left,''
the written report said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
