<HEADER>
A9621 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NJ-MINORITY-TROOPERS-     08-23 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-MINORITY-TROOPERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW JERSEY'S EFFORT TO RECRUIT MINORITIES FOR STATE POLICE FALLS
SHORT 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Despite a well-advertised effort to bring more
blacks, women and Latinos into the New Jersey State Police, only 15
of the 105 cadets scheduled to enter the academy next month are
black or Latino, and just one is a woman, according to statistics
released by the agency Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   Early this year, the agency settled a discrimination suit filed
by the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People
by agreeing to scrap several requirements that many black
applicants considered discriminatory. The state also pledged to
make aggressive attempts to advertise and recruit in black and
Latino neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   But in releasing the recruitment numbers Tuesday, the state
police superintendent, Carson Dunbar Jr., said he was disappointed
that the agency's attempt to diversify its ranks would leave the
percentage of minority troopers virtually unchanged, at 14 percent.
About 3 percent of the 2,800 current troopers are women, Dunbar
said, so the new class actually represents a decrease in the
percentage of women.
</P>
<P>
   Dunbar said the strong economy was partly to blame for the
lackluster results, because many female and minority applicants had
found better-paying jobs and decided not to finish the screening
process.
</P>
<P>
   He also acknowledged that the agency's reputation remained
tarnished in many black and Latino neighborhoods because of the
Justice Department's highly publicized investigation into
discrimination by troopers and the state's admission that some
officers had engaged in racial profiling for years _ problems that
preceded his appointment last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish I could tell you there's a quick fix for this
problem,'' said Dunbar, who became a New Jersey trooper himself in
1973 and was the only minority officer in his class. ``The real
answer is, it's going to be a long process.''
</P>
<P>
   He refused to specify what racial breakdown the force ultimately
hopes to reach, saying that he did not want to give the mistaken
impression that the state police were adopting a quota system. New
Jersey's population is about one-third minority, and the settlement
with the NAACP the state agreed to try to broaden the demographics
of the force.
</P>
<P>
   Some elected officials said they were dismayed that the state
had failed to deliver on its promise to increase minority
representation on the force.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state police have missed a golden opportunity to change
its institutional image,'' said Leroy Jones Jr., a Democratic
assemblyman from Essex County. ``Clearly, they need to reassess
their approach and re-examine who they are using as consultants in
recruiting more minorities into the ranks.''
</P>
<P>
   Some current troopers have also complained that the state
lowered its physical fitness requirements for new recruits, in an
attempt to help female applicants. During the last two years, the
state eliminated its pull-up, broad jump and vertical jump
requirements, and applicants who fail the physical test may now
take it repeatedly until they pass.
</P>
<P>
   Dunbar defended the less stringent requirements, saying they
still allow the state police to winnow out those applicants who are
physically unsuited to perform the job.
</P>
<P>
   The state police worked with several consulting firms to revise
the application process and add screening that tests candidates'
temperament and decision-making abilities, according to officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not just about strength, it's about what kind of person
you are,'' Dunbar said.
</P>
<P>
   The state police are scheduled to begin a new recruiting drive
next year and will work with the National Organization of Black Law
Enforcement Executives and the National Association of Women in
Policing to try and expand the number of female and minority
candidates. The state police may place more emphasis on reaching
out to women's sports teams, Dunbar said, and will continue to
recruit at schools and community events in minority neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   But he said that his own experience in law enforcement
recruiting, for both the State Police and the FBI, had taught him
not to expect quick results.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't happen that rapidly,'' he said. ``What I would like
to see is steady increases.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
