r s BC-OLY-DANTZSCHER-GYMNAS     08-23 0849
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-DANTZSCHER-GYMNASTICS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DANTZSCHER ARRIVES HOME TRIUMPHANT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM McCONNELL  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   COVINA, Calif. _ Tuesday, as she has for the past eight years,
Jamie Dantzscher donned her workout clothes, put up her hair,
packed her gym bag and headed to the Charter Oak Gymnastics Center
in Covina.
</P>
<P>
   ``I turned onto the street where the gym is and I saw all these
TV news vans and a couple fire trucks and a bunch of cars parked
out front,'' Dantzscher said. ``I thought 'Oh my gosh, what's
happened?'''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't until Dantzscher entered the gym and was greeted by a
big cheer from her Charter Oak Gliders teammates that it hit her.
</P>
<P>
   ``For me?'' she said, totally surprised.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it was.
</P>
<P>
   The 18-year-old from Palmdale knew then, for real and for
certain, that her Olympic dream had come true.
</P>
<P>
   After receiving a certificate from U.S. Congressman David
Dreier, accepting congratulations from a couple hundred fans and
teammates, doing a half-dozen media interviews and hugging what
seemed like half the kids in Covina, Dantzscher knew.
</P>
<P>
   ``About halfway through all this today it finally dawned on me,
once and for all,'' Dantzscher said. ``I made the team. I'm an
Olympian. All that work, all those years, it all paid off.
</P>
<P>
   ``At first, with all these people and all the flowers and
balloons and banners and the interviews, I just wanted it all to go
away. You know, clear the gym and let me practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I felt all the love here. And that made me realize what
I've accomplished.''
</P>
<P>
   The 5-foot-1, 105-pound dynamo has accomplished plenty. As
perhaps the longest of longshots at last weekend's U.S. Olympic
Trails at the Fleet Center in Boston, Dantzscher overcame her lack
of national recognition and lack of international competition - as
well as two falls during her balance beam presentation - to earn
one of six spots on the U.S. women's gymnastics squad.
</P>
<P>
   She and her Gliders coaches, Steve and Beth Rybacki, depart
today for a week of training in Texas. From there, next stop is
Sydney and the 2000 Summer Games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree with Jamie, all this still hasn't hit home yet,'' said
Steve Rybacki. ``The U.S. Trials were just incredibly stressful.
But she did a great job. I'm so proud of her, all that she has
accomplished.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, up until the past couple years the big star of our
little gym was Vanessa Atler. Everyone just assumed Vanessa would
make the U.S. team. But she didn't, and Jamie did.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jamie kept working hard, kept getting better. She is a quiet
person, but a fierce competitor.
</P>
<P>
   ``People may talk about her falling on balance beam (at the
Trials), but the important thing to remember, and I think the thing
that impressed Bela Karolyi and the U.S. coaches, was the fact she
picked herself up and got right back up there.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, we are going to try to take it that one last step. We
know the Russians are going to be tough, all the competition at the
Games is going to be tough. But Jamie is capable of great things,
of accomplishing the unexpected. She already has.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Trials were an ordeal for Dantzscher, her coaches and
the family members and friends who were in attendance at the Fleet
Center. But she kept her cool, screened out all the politics
involved in the selection process and came through was a solid
all-around performance, especially in floor exercise, her strongest
event.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was confident of her chances, but still I knew I was going
to be a nervous wreck,'' Beth Rybacki said. ``So I told myself to
stay in control, be confident, be patient. Then Jamie fell on the
beam. Then she fell again. At that point, I just looked up and said
to myself, 'OK God, enough with the patience. Help my girl!'
</P>
<P>
   ``You know when all this hit home for me? This morning. I was
getting ready to come over here for the ceremony and the mailman
brought our mail to our door, stared at me for a moment and said
`Hey, I saw you on TV! You're that gym lady!''
</P>
<P>
   Beth Rybacki, as a 14-year-old, made the U.S. Gymnastics team in
1980. Unfortunately, that happened be the Moscow Games, which the
U.S. boycotted. So, 20 years later, Dantzscher will take up the
torch and represent the Charter Oak Gymnastics Center, and the
U.S., in Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jamie making the team does have a special meaning for me,''
Beth Rybacki said. ``It kind of brings things full cycle, completes
the circle that I started back in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, mainly, I am just so happy for Jamie. She has shown
incredible growth since she came to us as an 11-year-old. She
worked hard, never gave up, got better and better, overcame so many
things.
</P>
<P>
   ``And it's a tremendous accomplishment for our gym, and I think
for the world of gymnastics. It shows that the Olympic dream is
still alive, that a little girl from a little gym in a little town
like Covina can achieve a great thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if she'd like to do it all again in six weeks time,
Dantzscher wasn't stumped for an answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, if it gets me out of my workout.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
