<HEADER>
A9628 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-CYBER-PIRACY-SFCHRON &LR;      08-23 0346
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBER-PIRACY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 CALIFORNIA GOVERNOR SIGNS CYBER PIRACY BILL INTO LAW  &HT;     By LYNDA GLEDHILL 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO, CALIF. _ California Gov. Gray Davis on Tuesday
signed a bill that will help protect individuals from being
victimized by ``cyber pirates'' who register the names of other
persons as Internet domain names.
</P>
<P>
   The bill, by state Senate President Pro Tem John Burton, D-San
Francisco, declares that it is an unfair business practice to
register an Internet domain name of another person with ``bad
faith'' intent.
</P>
<P>
   The new law ``makes a simple statement that a person should not
have to pay someone who steals their name to get it back,'' Burton
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Making cyber piracy an unfair business practice gives
individuals whose names are taken in bad faith an important tool to
fight back,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   The law closes a gap in recently enacted federal law by
including protections for names that are not trademarked and for
the names of promising newcomers who may not meet federal
``sufficiently famous'' standards but whose names might be pirated.
</P>
<P>
   It also offers protection for the heirs of celebrities.
</P>
<P>
   This law also makes it illegal to ``squat'' on a name until the
person whose name is being used offers money for the site. The
federal statute applied only if the person ``squatting'' went to
the person and demanded money.
</P>
<P>
   For example, if a ``squatter'' has registered the name of the
local real estate agent, but the agent then wants to start a Web
page using the domain name, the agent could take the squatter to
court.
</P>
<P>
   Under the law, courts can order violators to restore money or
property acquired by such practices and can order a fine of $2,500
per incident.
</P>
<P>
   The bill passed without a dissenting vote in the Legislature. It
was supported by the Screen Actors Guild, the Motion Picture
Producers Association of America and the Recording Industry
Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Lynda Gledhill at  &LR; gledhill(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
<P>
   &LR;  &QL; 
COL. 2 of CYBER23 () &QL;
</P>
<P>
   END OF STORY  &QL;
</P>
