<SLUG> BC-OSTLER-COLUMN-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
X GAME PLAYERS DOIN' THE CHOPSTICK LIKE MICK
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By SCOTT OSTLER 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Aliving wage of $9 an hour seems like a good
idea, although it depends on what your definition of ``living'' is,
and that's tough to define since we still can't all agree on what
the definition of ``is'' is.
</P>
<P>
   An hour of hard labor, nine bucks, after taxes, will get you a
gallon of gas and a triple-frappe-cappa-chilly-cino, and if you can
bum a smoke, you'll be livin' la vida poco.
</P>
<P>
   A few bargains still lurk. The X Games are a sweet deal, free
admission. The Games will cost you an arm and a leg only if you are
a competitor.
</P>
<P>
   And for what might seem like a back-alley, counterculture kind
of event, the crowds seem well-behaved, they aren't terrorizing the
city the way your standard Aluminum Siding Assn. conventioneers
will do.
</P>
<P>
   It was encouraging to watch the X spectators solve the city's
transportation problem. Several hundred of the fans found parking
spots on one small street corner. What they were parking was
skateboards, at a skateboard-check stand, but still.
</P>
<P>
   The X Games are considering a return to San Francisco for a
third consecutive year, and I don't know if that's a good idea. The
Games still have that edgy youthful rebellion feel to 'em, and
there's danger that the athletes might be getting San
Franciscoized.
</P>
<P>
   Last Saturday about 600 of the Games participants partied at Le
Colonial, the hip Vietnamese restaurant in the old Trader Vic's
alley.
</P>
<P>
   I kind of like to picture the X Games stars eating PBJs and Moon
Pies in the shade of the Bay Bridge.
</P>
<P>
   But no, there they were, chop-sticking at a place so hip-chic
that Mick Jagger dined there a couple nights earlier. So it's a
young-youth-meets-long-in-tooth-youth kind of a joint.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, somebody should hire Mick to do S.F. restaurant
reviews, as much as he gets around town. Or beg him to get off the
dining circuit and get back into the studio. I like him better as a
rock mobster than as an eater of rock lobster.
</P>
<P>
   WARRIOR is a term that gets tossed around a lot in sports.
</P>
<P>
   A guy is saluted as a warrior if he plays hard even though he's
in the middle of a contract dispute or a battling a case of
athlete's foot.
</P>
<P>
   Phil Smith fits a purer definition of the term. He battled his
way into basketball. He was a nobody from George Washington High
who, at USF in the early '70s, went from nonscholarship walk-on to
All-American guard.
</P>
<P>
   Then Smith was a second-round draft pick of the Warriors and
helped them win the NBA title his rookie season. He had a great
nine-year pro career.
</P>
<P>
   Now Phil is battling again. In September of '98 he was diagnosed
with multiple myeloma, a form of bone cancer twice as prevalent in
blacks as in whites.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was under the weather for a while,'' is how he explained it
when I talked to him Tuesday. He said his cell count has just taken
a turn for the better.
</P>
<P>
   ``The doctor didn't say `remission,' but I know this is a real
positive.''
</P>
<P>
   Phil lives in San Diego with wife Angela and their five kids,
and he says he does a little fishing and coaches his 10-year-old
son's basketball team.
</P>
<P>
   USF has invited Smith to a luncheon on Sept. 27 to dedicate
scholarship-endowment plaques to Phil and Art Zief Jr., whose dad
is a former USF basketball benchwarmer (and big Phil fan) who is
building the school a new law library.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's USF and Warrior teammates are invited. It's not a
sympathy event, it's a modest celebration of a modest Warrior.
</P>
<P>
   YOU THINK San Francisco is prim and grim when it comes to
smoking, you should check out Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   John Konstin of John's Grill faxes a notice posted in his
Vancouver hotel room warning guests that a British Columbia law
``forbids our employees from entering guest rooms where smoking has
taken place within the past 60 minutes. This includes housekeeping,
guest services, private bars, room service and engineering.''
</P>
<P>
   What if the room is on fire? Do firefighters have to wait in the
hall until the embers cool?
</P>
<P>
   Konstin also reports that a pack of Winstons in Vancouver costs
$7.85, which will really put a dent in a kid's allowance.
</P>
<P>
   IT'S TIME to begin the beguine, but instead, Gore and Bush are
debating the debate.
</P>
<P>
   They can't agree on the where or the when or the who, and given
a chance, they probably would quibble over the why and the
backstage hors d'oeuvre.
</P>
<P>
   The rift is so serious that they're probably going to have to
have a series of debate debates, the ground rules of which will be
harder to hammer out than the U.S. Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   At least the fighting gives the candidates' bobos, lackeys &AMP;
flunkies something to do. And don't ask me which are which. Those
titles are strict designations of the Candidate Toadies Union.
</P>
<P>
   SEVERAL READERS have suggested scrapping the traditional system
of selecting a president in favor of the  &UR; au courant &LR;  ``Survivor''
format. Put the candidates on an island with only essential tools,
like blow-dryers and speechwriters.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fine idea,'' says Lauren Auerbach, ``as long as Cheney doesn't
wear a swimsuit.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be a risk, that one candidate would go Speedo, or
worse, to show that he has nothing to hide.
</P>
<P>
   I'm leery of that after seeing ``Space Cowboys,'' one scene of
which features graphic rear nudity of the four 70-year-old
astronauts _ 280 years of tush.
</P>
<P>
   The scene was artistically photographed and deeply intrinsic to
the plot, but I didn't finish my bon-bons.
</P>
</TEXT>
