 GROW A BUSINESS: NO BUSINESS SITE DOES IT ALL  &HT;     By PETER SINTON 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Scores of business-resource Web sites pitch
themselves as meccas where small businesses can find virtually all
they need to operate successfully.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Cahners In-Stat Group ( &LR; www.instat.com &LR; ) ranks 19 of
these online business centers. Although the sites are making
progress, the Scottsdale, Ariz., high-tech market-research firm
concludes they have a long way to go. Interviews with
small-business leaders show that while many enjoy timely and
relevant information online, ``they are still uncertain about
procuring services online.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For the most part, the right mix of content, community and
services is yet to be found in any one player, though partnerships
promise that this will soon change,'' said Kneko Burney, an In-Stat
research director. She estimates that online business-center
revenues will mushroom from $200 million this year to more than $1
billion by 2003, and traffic will jump from 5 million visitors a
month to tens of millions.
</P>
<P>
   Burney defines online business centers as ``the ultimate
shopping center for business'' _ a place to do everything from
build a Web site to purchase goods and services, to talk with peers
and tap experts and manage operations. In-Stat reviewed 34 business
centers but excluded popular small business sites that are
subsidiaries of companies like Microsoft, Yahoo, IBM or Intuit.
</P>
<P>
   Inc.com and Office.com tied for the No. 1 spot in In-Stat's
ranking of top business-center sites in the first half of 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Here are In-Stat's top 10 online business centers:
</P>
<P>
   -- Office.com, backed by WinStar Communications' chief executive
officer and broadband innovator Bill Rhouhana, reportedly holds the
most promise to deliver business/technology services ``seamlessly''
to the small-business market. The site's partners and in-house
experts provide plenty of services including trends, news and
gossip on 16 industries, 120 subindustries and 10 business
management areas.
</P>
<P>
   -- Inc.com, created ``for the business builder who's long on
work and short on time,'' offers fast and intuitive access to a
range of solutions, products, information and advice.
</P>
<P>
   -- DigitalWork.com provides easy-to-use online services
organized into workshops to let small businesses complete routine
tasks like marketing, finance, sales and human resources easily and
at low cost online.
</P>
<P>
   -- Entrepreneur.com, created to broaden Entrepreneur magazine's
service, aims to provide quality information, tools and community
activities to small businesses.
</P>
<P>
   -- Onvia.com, the first of the online business centers to go
public, is primarily a business-to-business marketplace for
small-business buyers and sellers. It also offers news, how-to
advice, business tools, downloadable forms, worksheets and
checklists.
</P>
<P>
   -- Allbusiness.com offers free tools and content to aid HR,
finance, legal and other work-related tasks. Its experts, strategic
alliances and links to online communities all help ease the strain
of starting and expanding a business.
</P>
<P>
   -- BizToolsPlus.com offers entrepreneurs and small businesses a
range of tools such as Web site building and hosting, business
incorporation and planning, payroll services, discounted long
distance, personal post office, online printing, 401(k) plans,
company health insurance, messaging and communication services,
office supplies search engine, administrative templates and package
tracking.
</P>
<P>
   -- SmallOffice.com helps small-office and home-office owners
build their business online with Web sites and business listings,
advice on marketing, hiring and other subjects as well as lively
discussion boards and product reviews.
</P>
<P>
   -- Dbusiness.com provides industry-specific news, e-commerce
services, business tools, and investment and research resources for
small businesses in major cities.
</P>
<P>
   -- SmartOnline.com offers proprietary online tools and resources
to start a business, build a Web storefront and manage money,
marketing and most everything else.
</P>
<P>
   Cahners In-Stat did not include in its study the scores of
online business sites that do just one or two things like
facilitate online purchases or manage human resource activities.
Burney explained, ``We looked at only 34 companies that try to
bring everything together for small businesses in an integrated
package so users don't have to leave your domain.''
</P>
<P>
   Grow a Business appears every Wednesday in The Chronicle. Send
small-business tips, comments and questions to
 &LR; entrepreneurs(AT)sfgate.com,  &LR; or to Peter Sinton, Grow a Business
column, 901 Mission St., San Francisco, CA 94103.
</P>
</TEXT>
