<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETWORTH-PENDER-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETWORTH: RATING STOCKS BY RATING THE ACCURACY OF ANALYSTS
WHO  COVER THEM
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By KATHLEEN PENDER 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Back on July 5, this column posed the questions:
Are some stock analysts smarter than others? And if so, can
investors make money by following the shrewd ones?
</P>
<P>
   The answers, based on the results of an unscientific experiment
that ran with the column, are yes and maybe.
</P>
<P>
   The column focused on StarMine, a San Francisco startup that
uses data-mining technology to track and rate brokerage-firm
analysts.
</P>
<P>
   StarMine gives analysts stars (one is worst, five is best) based
on the accuracy of their earnings estimates.
</P>
<P>
   Then, StarMine comes up with its own earnings estimates _ named
SmartEstimates _ by using a secret formula that gives more weight
to estimates from top-rated analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Great theory. But does it work?
</P>
<P>
   To find out, StarMine gave me a list of 11 companies that it
expected to beat the consensus earnings estimate for the quarter
ended in June, and eight companies that were likely to fall short
of the consensus. (The consensus is simply the average of all
analyst estimates.)
</P>
<P>
   The results were pretty impressive.
</P>
<P>
   StarMine's predictions were ``directionally correct'' for 16
companies, and wrong for only two. (One company, Roper, is late
reporting earnings and I got tired of waiting.)
</P>
<P>
   That means StarMine was right 89 percent of the time, ignoring
Roper. Of course, StarMine gave me its very best ideas. Over the
long term, on thousands of stocks, StarMine claims it is
directionally correct 74 percent of the time. The company can't
predict by how much a company will beat or miss estimates _ only
the direction.
</P>
<P>
   StarMine's upside picks included three airlines, which blew away
both the consensus and SmartEstimates. Thanks to a strong economy,
everyone wanted to take a vacation, and the airlines didn't have to
engage in their usual summer fare war, explains David Lichtblau,
StarMine's vice president of marketing.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're looking for a hero, analyst Kevin Murphy of Morgan
Stanley Dean Witter was consistently out front in revising in the
correct direction across multiple (airline) stocks,'' he adds.
</P>
<P>
   StarMine also accurately predicted that five energy companies
would exceed estimates. Energy companies did well across the board
as oil and natural gas prices soared.
</P>
<P>
   (Actual and consensus earnings were calculated by IBES, an
earnings research firm, and were from continuing operations.)
</P>
<P>
   That brings us to the second question: Can investors make money
by paying more heed to brighter analysts?
</P>
<P>
   Here the answer is less conclusive, but more intriguing.
</P>
<P>
   StarMine's ``upside predictions'' were up 2 percent on average;
its ``downside predictions'' were down 5.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Not a bad average, but on a company-by-company basis, there was
little correlation between earnings and stock price.
</P>
<P>
   Among companies that met or exceeded consensus estimates, half
showed an increase in their stock price and half showed a decrease.
Among those that missed estimates, four stocks went down and two
went up.
</P>
<P>
   ``That happens,'' concedes Lichtblau.
</P>
<P>
   In the long run, earnings drive stock prices, but in the short
term, stocks react to all kinds of things _ revenue expectations,
profit margins, rumors, fear and greed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our methodology works across all industries in predicting
(earnings) surprises. In terms of stock price movements, it works
better in certain sectors than others,'' Lichtblau says.
</P>
<P>
   In technology, stock prices are highly linked to earnings. ``A
surprise will really move a stock,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   In our little experiment, chipmaker Integrated Device Technology
showed the biggest stock gain _ 35.4 percent _ after it beat
earnings estimates.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, the price of energy stocks are less sensitive
to earnings, and more responsive to oil and gas prices, which
weakened in July.
</P>
<P>
   In general, growth stocks are more likely to move on earnings
surprises than value stocks, Lichtblau adds.
</P>
<P>
   StarMine also has discovered that when the consensus estimate is
a loss, and its SmartEstimate is an even bigger loss, the
SmartEstimate is not a good predictor of stock price.
</P>
<P>
   However, when the consensus is a loss, and the SmartEstimate is
a profit, or when the consensus is a profit, and the SmartEstimate
is an even bigger profit, then the SmartEstimate is a good
stock-picking tool, but only for a large number of companies.
</P>
<P>
   StarMine's products are designed for institutions that invest in
hundreds or even thousands of stocks. Most of its customers are
``quantitative'' investors looking for mathematical anomalies, not
fundamental research.
</P>
<P>
   Pankaj Agrrawal, director of quantitative research at Villanova
Capital, says he tested StarMine's software and found that ``it
does add value. This whole industry is driven by expectations of
earnings. If there's any instrument that can give us a finer
insight into whether a company is going to declare earnings that
are above or below expectations, we'd like to know. StarMine has a
very smart algorithm to predict that.''
</P>
<P>
   But, he adds, ``The power of the system lies in diversification.
If there are 10 stocks, and you buy one, it's not necessarily going
to perform. If you buy seven, maybe it could work.''
</P>
<P>
   He says investment clubs could use SmartEstimates because they
buy a lot of stocks. He also says individuals could use it as one
part of a broader investment strategy.
</P>
<P>
   By late Septemeber, StarMine will start providing SmartEstimates
for most stocks on its Web site,  &LR; www.starmine.com &LR; . It will also
highlight the five companies most likely to surprise on the upside,
and the five most likely to miss estimates.
</P>
<P>
   The information will be free, but probably won't be posted until
a few days after StarMine's institutional clients get it.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, I asked StarMine to give me a few new picks.
With all the usual caveats, here they are:
</P>
<P>
   On the upside, StarMine says Potash Sask Corp. (ticker symbol
POT) will earn 43 cents, better than the consensus estimate of 38
cents. It predicts Micron Technology (MU) will earn $1 per share;
the consensus is 88 cents.
</P>
<P>
   On the downside, StarMine bets Carrier Access (CACS) will earn
30 cents, missing the consensus estimate of 32 cents. And even
though airlines did well last quarter, it says US Airways (U) will
earn only 30 cents; the consensus is 42 cents.
</P>
<P>
   STARS VERSUS PAWS: StarMine isn't the only Web site that will
use top analysts to guide investors.
</P>
<P>
   Bulldogresearch.com, which already rates analysts (with paws
instead of stars), in the next month will add a feature called
``bones.''
</P>
<P>
   When a top-rated analyst makes a dramatic change away from the
consensus earnings estimate, the stock will get a bone.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers will be able to see for which stocks a major shift
has taken place,'' although they won't know by how much or who made
the call, says Brent Johnstone, Bulldog's co-president.
</P>
<P>
   Bulldog uses research from Cornell University finance Professor
Charles Lee, who has found that certain revisions in earnings
estimates are a good long-term predictor of stock prices.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Kathleen Pender at  &LR; kpender(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
