<SLUG> BC-E-TRADE-SANCTION-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 E-TRADE SETTLES REPORTING CHARGES  &HT;     By SAM ZUCKERMAN 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ E-Trade Group, the No. 2 online broker, agreed
Tuesday to pay $20,000 to settle charges it failed to file routine
reports with regulators, the second time in four months industry
watchdogs have sanctioned the firm.
</P>
<P>
   NASD Regulation, the National Association of Securities Dealers
unit that polices the securities industry, censured Menlo Park,
Calif.'s E-Trade and imposed the fine because the broker didn't
provide required data on the short-interest positions of its
customers in Nasdaq stocks during a 28-month period ending in
September 1998.
</P>
<P>
   In May, NASD Regulation also slapped a $20,000 fine on E-Trade
for not responding on time to regulatory requests for information
about customer complaints.
</P>
<P>
   E-Trade's failures to follow standard industry procedures were
products of the firm's headlong growth, plus its roots in the
wild-and-wooly Internet world, analysts said. The firm has recently
adopted policies and hired staff to make sure it obeys the rules,
the analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The company is definitely mindful of the growing pains they
have had in the past and has taken corrective action,'' said
Deutsche Banc Alex. Brown analyst Glenn Schorr.
</P>
<P>
   Reporting short interest to the stock markets every month is an
administrative task all brokers must perform. While brokers are
occasionally punished for filing inaccurate information, ``it's not
common for a firm that has reporting obligations to not report at
all,'' said Stephen Luparello, NASD Regulation's executive vice
president for market regulation.
</P>
<P>
   In settlement documents, the regulatory group accused E-Trade of
failing to put in place a system to ensure that the firm complied
with security laws and regulations. Specifically, NASD Regulation
said, E-Trade didn't identify a company official responsible for
making sure the firm obeyed those rules and didn't have adequate
compliance procedures.
</P>
<P>
   E-Trade said short-interest reports fell through the cracks
after it took over administrative and record-keeping functions from
an outside firm in 1996. ``Procedures were not established to
capture and submit short interest information,'' the company
admitted in a statement submitted to NASD Regulation.
</P>
<P>
   Failing to file the reports ``was absolutely inadvertent,'' said
E-Trade spokesman Patrick De Chiro. ``We of course take our
regulatory compliance responsibilities very seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   After NASD Regulation pointed out the reporting failure to
E-Trade, the firm adopted new procedures and began providing the
data monthly. It took regulators nearly two years to decide on
punishment because they needed to analyze at length whether
E-Trade's reporting failure damaged the stock market, Luparello
said.
</P>
<P>
   E-Trade's actions meant that short-interest data released by
Nasdaq from 1996 through 1998 were inaccurate, though probably not
enough to make a meaningful difference, NASD Regulation eventually
determined.
</P>
<P>
   Investors take short positions when they sell a stock they don't
own, temporarily borrowing it from another account. They do so in
hopes the stock price will fall, allowing them to pocket the
difference when they later buy shares to replace the stock they
borrowed.
</P>
<P>
   Market pros avidly crunch Nasdaq and the New York Stock Exchange
short-interest data each month, looking for signs that investors
expect a company's shares to fall.
</P>
<P>
   From September 1996 to September 1998, about the period when
E-Trade failed to report short interest, the firm's total accounts
skyrocketed from 91,000 to 544,000, swamping the firm's
administrative capacity.
</P>
<P>
   As the firm has matured, it has moved to stabilize its
operations. Two months ago, E-Trade hired security industry veteran
Charles Nalbone as its chief compliance officer. Nalbone previously
oversaw regulatory compliance for Bear Stearns, a well-regarded
old-line Wall Street firm.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
E-mail Sam Zuckerman at  &LR; szuckerman(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
