<HEADER>
A9633 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-HARDWARE-RETAIL-SFCHR     08-23 1109
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARDWARE-RETAIL-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 OLD-TIME SERVICE AT OAKLAND HARDWARE STORE  &HT;     By CAROL EMERT 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, CALIF. _ At Ace Ellis Hardware in North Oakland,
Calif., one-on-one customer service is mandatory.
</P>
<P>
   Personal assistance is not a policy handed down by some
touchy-feely chief executive. It is simply the best way for the
54-year-old store to stay in business in its neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   To deter shoplifters, most of the family-owned shop's supply of
bolts, wire, hammers and spackle are behind a front counter.
Customers line up to ask questions and request merchandise, which
helpful staffers retrieve from the back.
</P>
<P>
   Ace Ellis, of course, is not the first business in a rough
neighborhood to eliminate self-service. Minimarts, liquor stores
and gas stations are known to put up counters and, in extreme
circumstances, bulletproof glass walls.
</P>
<P>
   But in this era of huge, impersonal home-improvement centers,
the counter has become Ace Ellis' secret weapon. A cult of
in-the-know do-it-yourselfers happily drive there from miles around
_ forgoing nearer hardware stores in spiffier neighborhoods _ for
guaranteed face time with Ace Ellis' knowledgeable staff.
</P>
<P>
   ``They know everything _ plumbing, heating, fixtures _ and they
have enormous patience explaining it to you,'' said Greg Greer, a
Lafayette painting contractor and landlord who shops at Ace Ellis
daily.
</P>
<P>
   ``They get what I need quickly and easily and I'm out the
door,'' said Greer. ``The prices are very fair.''
</P>
<P>
   By adapting to its surroundings, Ace Ellis has managed to stay
in business while a neighboring grocery store, bank, restaurants
and pharmacies have all closed their doors.
</P>
<P>
   And the store, crammed from floor to ceiling with merchandise,
is thriving, pulling in annual sales of $200 to $250 per square
foot, said co-owner Paul Eames.
</P>
<P>
   That compares with $88 for the average independent hardware
store, according to the National Retail Hardware Association.
Co-owner Barbara Eames, Paul's sister, says one-on-one service
gives employees a chance to boost sales and help customers at the
same time. ``We always ask, `Do you need gloves with that shovel?'
''
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way, it's a very 18th century model,'' said Paco
Underhill, a retail consultant and author of the book, ``Why We
Buy: The Science of Shopping.''
</P>
<P>
   ``That's how stores used to be _ you walked in and said, `This
is what I need,' and they gave it to you.''
</P>
<P>
   In another anachronistic twist, Ace Ellis, which serves about
250 customers a day, is one of a handful of retailers not using a
computer to track inventory.
</P>
<P>
   Owners Barbara and Paul Eames and their employees carry the
locations of 20,000 items in the store and an adjacent warehouse
around in their heads. When goods are sold, they note it on a
clipboard.
</P>
<P>
   The Ace Ellis business model wouldn't work on a large scale,
said Underhill. However, ``There are people who can buck all of the
trends and be able to create a viable business because they care.''
</P>
<P>
   Ace Ellis has stuck it out through difficult times. The store,
at 5424 Martin Luther King Jr. Way, was built in 1946 by Hubert
Ellis and Bill Eames. As a teenager, Eames worked at Ellis'
hardware store on College Avenue a few miles away. Ellis closed
that shop and, after World War II, the two became partners.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, Martin Luther King Jr. Way was called Grove Street,
and the area was populated by working-class Italian families and
retirees. Eames bought Ellis' share of the store in 1954 but kept
the historic name. (The Eameses joined the Ace buying cooperative
in the early 1970s and added ``Ace'' to the store's name.)
</P>
<P>
   The construction of elevated BART tracks above Grove Street in
the late 1960s and early '70s ``crucified everybody'' doing
business there, remembers Bill Eames, now retired.
</P>
<P>
   Grove Street was torn up for several years. Sometimes Ellis
Hardware brought in as little as $50 a day _ not much for Bill and
Catherine Eames, who were raising nine young children.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, crime was increasing in North Oakland. Many
local businesses, including a Hagstrom grocery store and Bank of
America, closed their doors.
</P>
<P>
   Ace Ellis continued to serve the neighborhood despite growing
racial tension. Black Panther founder Bobby Seale and his father
were customers, remembers Bill Eames.
</P>
<P>
   Through the years, the store suffered a spate of crimes,
including several armed robberies. Once, nighttime burglars melted
the back door with acid. Another time, Paul Eames arrived at work
one morning to find a pool of blood on the floor under a broken
skylight. The store's ceiling still has four patched holes from
robbery attempts.
</P>
<P>
   ``They never really got very much,'' said Eames, because the
store doesn't stock many big-ticket items.
</P>
<P>
   Shoplifting was also a problem, prompting the decision in the
late 1970s to install the counter. ``It was either get out or do
the counter,'' Eames said. Shoplifting incidents dropped from once
per week to about once per year.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the nine Eames children, who were raised in Lafayette,
worked in the store at one time or another, ``kind of like musical
chairs,'' said Paul. In 1985, Paul and Barbara Eames and brother
Patrick, who happened to be working there full time, bought out
their father's interest.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Patrick Eames sold his stake to his two siblings
and opened his own store, Eames Hardware and Supply in Pleasant
Hill.
</P>
<P>
   While it is difficult to gauge the effects of competition, the
Eameses have not noticed any impact from the enormous Home Depot
that opened in nearby Emeryville in 1994. ``We felt it for one or
two months, max,'' said Paul Eames.
</P>
<P>
   Ace Ellis recently stopped advertising _ a practice it had
started when Home Depot opened _ and noticed no change in sales or
traffic, Eames said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We try to stay competitive with good service _ that's the
whole strategy,'' Eames said. ``I hear complaints at the counter
all the time, (with) customers saying, `If I ever go there again,
shoot me.' We'd almost like to be across the street from Home
Depot.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, California's economic boom is starting to hit North
Oakland, and crime appears to be declining. Home prices have
doubled during the past 18 months, and some are going for $450,000
or more, said Greer, who owns rental property in the area.
</P>
<P>
   The neighborhood's rising tide, of course, gives Ace Ellis a
lift, letting it sell even more hinges, switch plates, posthole
diggers and vials of Liquid Wrench.
</P>
<P>
   But for now, there are no plans to remove the counter.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Carol Emert at  &LR; cemert(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
