<SLUG> BC-BUSH-TV-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 TV ADS STAY OUT OF CALIFORNIA _ FOR NOW  &HT;     By JOHN WILDERMUTH 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the third presidential election in a row, California could
be disappearing from the Republican political radar.
</P>
<P>
   While GOP officials continue to insist that they will challenge
Democratic nominee Al Gore for the state's 54 delegates, California
is not one of the 21 ``battleground'' states where Republican
George W. Bush began running television ads this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do expect to have ads in California later in the
campaign,'' said Ray Sullivan, a spokesman for the Bush campaign.
``It's a state that Gov. Bush takes seriously.''
</P>
<P>
   California Republicans have heard that line before. In 1992 and
again in 1996, national campaign directors said they were fighting
for the state while quietly directing their resources elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``With five or six key congressional races in the state, there's
been a lot of pressure for the party to keep someone campaigning in
California,'' said Bruce Cain, a political science professor at the
University of California at Berkeley. ``George Bush has tried to
say all the right things and show the flag ... but it's been
symbolic all the way.''
</P>
<P>
   With the Democrats' post-convention bounce in the polls putting
Bush and Gore in a virtual tie heading into the fall campaign,
Republicans are likely to start focusing their efforts on the
states where they believe they have the best chance of winning.
</P>
<P>
   That's what those 21 states represent, Sullivan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a serious buy in the major media markets of 21
states,'' he said. ``It is a significant and serious ad buy.''
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan said the Bush campaign purposely avoided buying ads in
the nation's three biggest states because of the cost of doing
business there.
</P>
<P>
   A look at those states, however, suggests other reasons
Republicans might want to stay out of the ad wars. California and
New York are considered strong states for Gore, while Bush's home
state of Texas is a slam-dunk for the Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush is running ads in all but one of the nation's next
seven largest states, avoiding only New Jersey, which shares the
expensive New York media market.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, who began running ads Tuesday in 17 states, also is
avoiding the big three of California, New York and Texas. But his
advertising is going head-to-head with Bush's in big electoral vote
states such as Florida, Pennsylvania, Illinois, Ohio and Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Sullivan suggested the Bush ad campaign could be expanding.
</P>
<P>
   ``Labor Day is the typical start of the campaign, so I would
expect to see an ad campaign starting then,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While talk is cheap, television ads in a state the size of
California are expensive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was doing a campaign in Indiana, and I spent $2 million,''
said Arnie Steinberg, a Republican media consultant. ``It would
probably cost $9 million to get the same exposure in California.''
</P>
<P>
   Holding off on spending the millions needed for a California ad
campaign makes sense for both parties, he suggested.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it would be wise to monitor the situation and be
prepared to put money in later if they need to,'' Steinberg said.
</P>
<P>
   That also would allow Bush and Gore to keep the spending at the
minimum if the California contest begins to look like a runaway.
</P>
<P>
   While a poll conducted early this month by the Public Policy
Institute of California showed the presidential contest in the
state tightening up, Gore has shown consistent strength in
California, which in recent years has become a growing Democratic
stronghold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our hope is that the Bush campaign will decide to spend time
and money in California,'' said Bob Mulholland, a spokesman for the
state Democratic Party. ``But if you look at the Republicans in
California, they don't have any deckhands. We'll have Sen. (Dianne)
Feinstein and Gov. (Gray) Davis running up and down the state for
Gore.''
</P>
<P>
   Having the Democratic Convention in Los Angeles last week also
gave Gore a huge boost in the state, Mulholland said. Four nights
of television and page after page of stories in local newspapers
can't help but have an effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't buy that kind of coverage,'' he added.
</P>
<P>
   No one is suggesting Bush will abandon the state completely.
Dick Cheney, the GOP vice presidential candidate, spent the past
two days in Redlands, Bakersfield and Santa Barbara, for example,
while Bush is tentatively due back in California in mid-September.
</P>
<P>
   But in the fight for the 270 electoral votes needed to become
president, the money will be spent where it will do the most
political good. And if Republicans decide that money earmarked to
take on Gore in California would be better spent in the Midwest,
that is what's going to happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Bush could make some ad buys in the Central Valley and
the central coast, swing areas where television is relatively
inexpensive,'' said Cain of UC Berkeley. ``That way he could keep
his finger in the water and also keep the party happy.''
</P>
<P>
   If Bush stays off the California airwaves completely, it would
be another blow for state Republicans, who have had little to cheer
about in recent years. It also could hurt other Republicans when
they come into the state to raise money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't believe California Republicans would donate tons of
money and get nothing in return,'' Cain said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
