<SLUG> BC-ENERGY-BILLS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 DAVIS SEEKS U.S. AID FOR LOW-INCOME ELECTRIC BILLS  &HT;     By DAVID LAZARUS 
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As electricity rates continue to soar in
Southern California, Gov. Gray Davis sought federal funds Tuesday
from President Clinton to help low-income people pay their power
bills.
</P>
<P>
   ``I respectfully urge you to exercise your authority to release
Federal Emergency Contingency Funds to the State of California,''
Davis wrote in a letter to the president. ``My highest priority for
those funds would be to dedicate them to addressing the needs of
those in the San Diego area.''
</P>
<P>
   White House officials could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Davis has been under growing pressure to find ways to relieve
the impact of deregulation of California's electricity market. In
San Diego, the first city to feel the full effects of deregulation,
power bills have more than doubled in recent months.
</P>
<P>
   Davis said the federal assistance would be targeted at families
earning less than 60 percent of the state median income.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, a family of four earning about $33,000 would be
eligible for assistance with its power bills. For individuals, the
income level would be about $17,000.
</P>
<P>
   The governor did not specify how much assistance would be made
available to each recipient.
</P>
<P>
   While acknowledging that low-income people do need help paying
sky-high electricity bills, consumer activists said it appeared
that Davis may have his priorities misplaced.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real issue is that deregulation is not working,'' said
Jamie Court, executive director of the Foundation for Taxpayer and
Consumer Rights in Los Angeles. ``What the governor needs to do is
admit that deregulation is a disaster and undo it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anything short of that,'' he added, ``is like putting a
Band-Aid on an open wound.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda Sherry, a spokeswoman for Consumer Action, a San Francisco
grassroots organization, said she found it ironic that ``the state
went to so much trouble to deregulate its electricity industry and
is now running to the feds for help.''
</P>
<P>
   Consumer groups have warned that the surging power bills in San
Diego will be mirrored throughout the state as other utilities lift
a freeze on electricity rates.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco's Pacific Gas &AMP; Electric Co. has said that its
customers could feel the impact of deregulation as early as next
summer.
</P>
<P>
   Davis has called for investigations of power generators by state
and federal regulators. He has charged power companies with gouging
consumers as California's demand for juice far outstrips available
supply.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, the state Public Utilities Commission voted to cap
electricity bills in San Diego for most ratepayers. Local
officials, however, criticized the measure as too little, too late.
</P>
<P>
   Legislators in Sacramento are now preparing their own
rate-freeze measure to provide relief to Southern California
electricity users while a long-term fix is sought for the state's
energy woes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
