<HEADER>
A9643 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r n BC-NURSING-HOMES-SFCHRON     08-23 0980
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NURSING-HOMES-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEGISLATIVE OVERHAUL OF NURSING HOMES ANTICIPATED
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By GREG LUCAS  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SACRAMENTO _ The Legislature is expected to approve a major
overhaul Wednesday of how the state oversees California's 1,400
nursing homes, after weakening some provisions to satisfy Gov. Gray
Davis.
</P>
<P>
   Among the dozens of changes, the bill quadruples fines for
nursing homes found to have caused the death of a resident and
requires the state to respond within 24 hours to the most serious
complaints about care.
</P>
<P>
   The Democratic governor vetoed a stronger bill last year because
he disagreed with language requiring nursing homes to increase
staffing. Mandatory staffing requirements have been eliminated this
year at his request.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not nearly all it could be, but we pushed the rock
halfway up the hill,'' said Sen. John Vasconcellos, D-Santa Clara.
``We had a great bill last year but the governor vetoed it.''
</P>
<P>
   Assemblyman Kevin Shelley, D-San Francisco, whose tougher
nursing home standards bill was nixed by the governor last year,
described his measure this year as a ``wonderful start.''
</P>
<P>
   There are more than 100,000 beds in California's 1,400 nursing
homes. The state has been grappling with improving care for more
than 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   A 1998 federal study found that 30 percent of California's
nursing homes cause death or serious harm to their residents.
</P>
<P>
   During a June heat wave, two residents of a Burlingame nursing
home died. The Department of Health Services cited Sunbridge Care
and Rehabilitation and fined the home $141,000 for those deaths and
several other serious violations.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the state Department of Health Services issued 29
citations charging nursing homes with causing a patient's death.
That's up from 14 such citations issued in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   There were an additional 253 citations for serious harm caused
to patients.
</P>
<P>
   Under the bill that is expected to pass Wednesday, fines for
those violations increase from a maximum of $25,000 to $100,000
when death occurs and from $10,000 to a maximum of $20,000 for a
serious injury.
</P>
<P>
   To advocates for the elderly, the most significant improvement
in care would be increased staffing _ and better staff training.
</P>
<P>
   Shelley's bill last year required that by 2003, staffing hours
would increase from 3.2 hours to 3.5 hours per patient per day.
</P>
<P>
   In his veto, Davis said that increase would have been too
expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Shelley's current bill merely says the Legislature wants to see
the staffing hours rise _ it does not mandate such an increase.
</P>
<P>
   Training is increased by 10 hours _ six hours of instruction on
abuse and four hours on Alzheimer's Disease.
</P>
<P>
   Under the current bill, nursing assistants _ the people who aid
patients in caring for themselves _ are required to have 150 hours
of training, some on-the-job, some in a classroom.
</P>
<P>
   Federal law requires only half that much training.
</P>
<P>
   ``Manicurists and pedicurists have to have 1,600 hours of
training,'' said Pat McGuiness of the California Advocates for
Nursing Home Reform in San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   ``Someone who cares for your toenails has 10 times more training
than someone who looks after your parents,'' McGuiness said.
</P>
<P>
   This year's budget contains $210 million in state money to boost
the reimbursement nursing homes receive for patients covered under
Medi-Cal, the state's health care program for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   Of that amount, $80 million is earmarked for salary increases
for nursing home staff.
</P>
<P>
   Last year's budget contained money for a 5 percent pay increase.
The $80 million is an additional 7.2 percent increase, Shelley
said.
</P>
<P>
   Before the pay raise, the average hourly wage of a nursing
assistant was $6.90, said Shelley.
</P>
<P>
   McGuiness said the bill started out even weaker than it ended
up. When introduced, it represented what changes Davis was willing
to accept.
</P>
<P>
   ``The governor had a lot of proposals in there we were opposed
to because they would have weakened the enforcement system we have
right now,'' McGuiness said.
</P>
<P>
   McGuiness credited Shelley and Vasconcellos with prodding Davis
to make the bill stronger _ although not as strong as she and other
advocates wanted it to be.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Quicker Response to Complaints
</P>
<P>
   The bill also improves the way the state handles complaints
about care, McGuiness said. The state would now respond to
complaints of possible serious harm or death within 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``There have been real problems with timeliness of response,''
McGuiness said. ``Sometimes the response comes after the death.''
</P>
<P>
   Brenda Klutz, deputy director of licensing and certification at
the Department of Health Services, said this year's bill grants the
department stronger enforcement powers.
</P>
<P>
   The department would have the power to appoint a temporary
manager for a nursing home found to be endangering the lives of its
residents.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also gives the department the power to issue a
probationary license, if a nursing home does not meet state
standards.
</P>
<P>
   If care is not improved within six months, the state can demand
that a new owner take over.
</P>
<P>
   The department also inspects nursing homes to see whether they
meet federal care requirements. But if an inspector finds a nursing
home is not meeting federal requirements, that information cannot
be used to revoke the home's state license.
</P>
<P>
   Shelley's bill would allow inspection findings to affect state
licensing.
</P>
<P>
   The bill also orders the department to stagger the schedule of
annual inspections to better gauge day-to-day living conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no party that's 100 percent happy with the bill and no
party who is 100 percent unhappy with it,'' said Judy Citko, vice
president of the California Healthcare Association, which opposed
the bill because of the increased fines. ``That's the sign of a
compromise.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
