<P>
   NY-CHARTER-SCHOOL (New York) _ While most political debate over
education involves tweaking existing programs, charter schools
present a chance for teachers, parents, management companies and
bright young idealists to sit around a blank blackboard and imagine
a school from scratch. Charter schools, which get public funds but
are run without regulation from the local school district, have
been embraced by conservatives and liberals alike as an outlet for
innovation, what many see as the most dynamic and important
education reform movement in decades. Times reporter Jodi Wilgoren
looks at the opening of one such school in New York, Bronx
Preparatory, one of 380 new charter schools opening across the
country this fall. 1,500 words.
</P>
