</P>
<P>
   LINCOLN-AD-COLUMN (New York) _ While there are plenty of
sponsors at the U.S. Open tennis tournament, which begins on
Monday, one sponsor intends to stand out _ quite literally _ among
visitors to Flushing Meadows, in Queens County, N.Y., where the
event is held. Starting on Sept. 1, Lincoln Mercury, the Ford Motor
unit based in Irvine, Calif., will usher visitors through
elaborately staged exhibits in a pavilion the size of four tennis
courts to promote a more contemporary image. In creating the
unusual exhibits, Lincoln is embracing a new idea in marketing
called experience marketing. It tries to appeal to consumers
through the senses, often through show business-like techniques. By
Patricia Winters Lauro.
</P>
<P>
   NASD-MARKETPLACE (New York) _ Every month, the National
Association of Securities Dealers compiles the short interest table
for Nasdaq stocks, a table that shows just how popular _ perhaps
unpopular is a better word _ a stock is with investors who bet on a
decline in price. The numbers are avidly scanned by investors and
by the companies themselves. Some investment strategies are based
in part on those numbers. But how good are those numbers? Only as
good as the reports from brokerage firms, which are required to add
up short positions of their customers on all trades that have
settled by the 15th of each month. And it appears that the NASD is
doing something less than a stellar job of riding herd on the
brokerage firms. By Floyd Norris.
</P>
