<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THIS TIME, RED SOX HAVE NO PRAYER 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-ANGELS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ As you might expect, the Red Sox were in high spirits
Tuesday afternoon, the pleasure of Monday night's thrilling
overtime comeback as fresh as the uniforms clubhouse man Joe
Cochran and his crew hung in each locker.
</P>
<P>
   Pedro Martinez cavorted around the yard wearing a do-rag in the
colors of the Dominican flag, his baseball cap nowhere in sight.
Carl Everett took batting practice, then donned a headset and
fielded questions on a radio talk show that has been less than
flattering to him.
</P>
<P>
   And Brian Daubach, the architect of not one but two dramatic
late-inning rallies Monday, signed autographs for kids clustered
around the Sox dugout.
</P>
<P>
   Then, regrettably for those who wanted the good times to keep on
rolling, the game began and the Sox were in tall grass once again,
and this time they were in way over their heads.
</P>
<P>
   They spotted Anaheim one too many leads Tuesday &UR;  &LR; night, falling,
11-4, to the Angels and tossing away a chance to move ahead of the
field in the wild-card race before a crowd of 33,163 in Fenway
Park, the 39th straight sellout.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox bounced back once for starter Tim Wakefield, rallying
from a 4-0 deficit to tie the score in the fourth, then
disintegrated in a six-run fifth that assured Mo Vaughn of his
first win in eight tries in Boston since he began wearing a halo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tried to keep us in there as long as I could,'' said
Wakefield, who has allowed 18 hits and 13 earned runs in his last
two starts, in which he has pitched a total of 10 2/3 innings, and
has gone more than a month since running off four straight wins.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the fifth, I just couldn't get an out. It's not easy to
swallow, but I'm still going to work hard and try to keep a
positive attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn, whose single touched off the deciding rally, said even
before the win that he just might have to stop by his favorite
nightclub, the one where customers throw as many dollar bills on
the stage as the Angels sprayed hits around Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``Damn, I missed that plane that came by,'' Vaughn said of the
plane that flew over Fenway Monday night pulling a ``welcome back''
banner from the establishment in which he stopped by a time or two
during his term with the Sox. ``That's what me and Nomar were
laughing about on his way back to the dugout that night.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels had 14 hits, six in the fifth inning, giving Vaughn
as many wins against the Sox here as he has had handshakes with Sox
general manager Dan Duquette. They met behind the batting cage
Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said `Hi' to him when I saw him,'' Vaughn said. ``I told
somebody the other day, `You got to work at being angry at
somebody, and I'm not going to do that.' I'm not focused on
negatives. I'm a happy guy.''
</P>
<P>
   It cheered Vaughn that his reception here wasn't the same wall
of booing that greeted him upon his return a year ago. Cheers could
be heard, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was really surprised by the fan reaction,'' Vaughn said. ``I
just felt like it's been two years, they've taken the time to think
about what happened with the whole situation. I'm not saying they
agree with it, but they took the time to think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels offense gave Wakefield plenty to think about, too.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Glaus, the third baseman out of UCLA who could have served
as the model for Disney's Hercules, had three doubles and scored
three runs. He had reached base on eight straight plate appearances
(four doubles, four walks) until he lined to left in his last
at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   Left fielder Orlando Palmeiro, filling in for Darin Erstad, the
injured major league hits leader, had two doubles and two singles,
driving in three runs and scoring another. Everyone in the Angels'
lineup except Kevin Stocker reached base, and while there were no
home runs on a night the flags were blowing out toward left field,
the Angels had six doubles.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox offense, meanwhile, expired around the same time
Garciaparra was cut down at the plate on a strong relay from
shortstop Stocker after Troy O'Leary's double in the fourth. Lou
Merloni already had scored on O'Leary's hit to tie the score at 4
when Garciaparra was cut down, catcher Bengie Molina holding onto
the ball even as Garciaparra planted his toe in the catcher's
glove.
</P>
<P>
   That was the last Sox hit of the night off Kent Mercker _ the
lefthander whose cameo appearance with the Sox last season included
a Game 1 start in the ALCS _ and two relievers. Mercker, the fifth
straight lefty starter the Sox have faced, stranded six runners in
the first three innings, but combined with relievers Al Levine (two
innings) and Lou Pote (one) to hold the Sox hitless over the final
five.
</P>
<P>
   ``We hit the ball good, we hit a lot of balls good,'' said Sox
manager Jimy Williams, who didn't name names but could have cited
catcher Jason Varitek, who crushed four balls and had only one
single off the pitcher to show for it.
</P>
<P>
   Mercker, who missed three months because of a brain hemorrhage
he suffered in May, won for the first time since he was on the
mound last Sept. 29 in Chicago, in the game that clinched a
wild-card spot for the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was happy to see him on the mound again,'' Red Sox pitching
coach Joe Kerrigan said of the likable Mercker. ``I talked with him
in Anaheim about what happened to him. He said it felt like someone
hit him in the back of the head with a bat, and it stayed that way
for three days. He was on every kind of painkiller. Morphine,
everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``He jokes now about what happened to him. After what he went
through, I'm happy he's OK.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday &UR;  &LR; night, Mercker helped drop the Sox a half-game behind
the surging Cleveland Indians in the wild-card race. Oakland also
fell a half-game back, while the Angels pulled within 2 1/2 games.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn had promised visitors that the Angels were the type of
team not easily brought down, even after losses as painful as
Monday's.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team doesn't get knocked down much,'' Vaughn said. ``Bad
things happen, but they don't affect these guys.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
