<HEADLINE>
A REARMED RAMON MARTINEZ WOULD HELP RED SOX 
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-ANALYSIS-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Shhh. Don't tell Ramon Martinez what it's like to
``Shuffle off to Buffalo.'' Let him experience for himself the
majesty of a bus ride with the Pawtucket Red Sox on the New York
ThruWay. Tell him Bison Stadium is like Fenway Park.
</P>
<P>
   And hope that he gets the message.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox, who are sending the 32-year-old righthander to
Buffalo for a rehab start Friday, will need him at his best for the
September marathon of games that will have great bearing on the
playoff race.
</P>
<P>
   A year ago, Martinez came out of nowhere to help the Red Sox
make the playoffs. He started the season on the disabled list but
by June he not only made the roster but also started four games,
posting a 2-1 record.
</P>
<P>
   In two playoff appearances last year, Martinez was 0-1. He
pitched 5 2/3 innings of a 9-3 victory over Cleveland in the
Division Series but did not get the decision. He was the losing
pitcher in Game 2 of the ALCS against the Yankees, a 3-2 setback in
New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no doubt what the man can do,'' said Red Sox pitching
coach Joe Kerrigan. ``The man is a big-time pressure pitcher, a
clutch pitcher. If there is somebody on this team besides Pedro
(Martinez) you would rather give the ball to, it will be Ramon or
Bret Saberhagen.''
</P>
<P>
   But there have been doubts about Ramon in recent weeks. He is
currently on the disabled list because of a contusion on the right
knee. Adding to that is a growing concern that his delivery is
flawed, so it is clear why the Buffalo trip is a must.
</P>
<P>
   Martinez's 8-6 record is not bad, but a 6.14 earned run average
in 21 games makes the club nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to see Ramon make an adjustment of about 6 inches,''
said Kerrigan. ``That means making an adjustment in his delivery.
The idea is to be more strike-efficient. If you have a good
delivery, you're going to have a better potential to throw
strikes.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox aren't asking him to perform miracles. But they'd like
to see the 10-year veteran tighten up his game for the final month
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   To the same end, Pete Schourek pitched Tuesday &UR;  &LR; night in
Pawtucket, and Saberhagen also will work Friday. The Sox know the
toughest part of the season is ahead.
</P>
<P>
   Manager Jimy Williams, looking to the September crunch, said,
``We have six days and eight games, including back-to-back splits.
So that is why you need starting pitchers. Somebody's got to start.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ours is not like we have a regular rotation. We take one game
at a time. Other than that, I don't know how it's going to line
up.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's why Ramon Martinez will be in Buffalo Friday night.
He can't afford to stay home.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has to make adjustments in this game,'' said
Kerrigan. ``I don't care if it's your first year in the big
leagues, your fifth, 10th year. This game is all about
adjustments.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
