<HEADER>
A9655 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BBA-ANGELS-MERCKER-BO     08-23 0755
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-MERCKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WINNING IS RELATIVE FOR MERCKER NOW 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NANCY MARRAPESE-BURRELL  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ From strictly a numbers standpoint, Kent Mercker's
pitching line for the Angels Tuesday &UR;  &LR; night wasn't bad. He gave up
nine hits and four earned runs in six innings. He was credited with
the win in Anaheim's 11-4 drubbing of the Red Sox, for whom Mercker
pitched last year.
</P>
<P>
   However, raw statistics, without explanation, mean nothing in
the case of Mercker.
</P>
<P>
   His triumph on the field was his first since last Sept. 29 at
Chicago, when he clinched the wild card for the Red Sox. But the
real victory for Mercker has to do with off-field things that most
people take for granted _ such as waking up every day. He truly is
grateful to be alive.
</P>
<P>
   Mercker, who signed as a free agent with the Angels before the
season, suffered a cerebral hemorrhage May 11 and collapsed on the
mound. He said it was a terrifying experience, compounded by the
fact that doctors still don't know the cause.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first thought when that happened was, `Am I going to live?
Am I going to see my kids again and be able to watch them grow up?'
'' said the 32-year-old Mercker, who has two daughters. ``That was
answered yes, and that was fine for me.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if the worst that came through this whole situation was I
could never play baseball again, great. I still had a long enough
career and got to have fun and life goes on. To be able to do that
and play baseball again, every time I take the field now, I look at
it that, `This could be your last time doing it, so have fun doing
it, so go as hard as you can.'
</P>
<P>
   ``Believe me, I don't want to lose. But when you're facing Nomar
(Garciaparra) you don't put so much pressure (on). I'm at inner
peace with myself to say, `You know what? Just make the best pitch
you can make right here, it doesn't have to be perfect, just make a
good pitch and see what happens.' I used to be a little more keyed
up but I'm able to relax a little bit more and I think in the long
run, that's going to help me.''
</P>
<P>
   Tuesday &UR;  &LR; night, he made his third _ and longest _ start of the
year, throwing 91 pitches, 50 for strikes. The Angels jumped ahead,
4-0, after two innings but the Red Sox tied it in the fourth. In
the top of the fifth, the Angels staked Mercker to a 10-4 lead and
in the bottom, he responded with a one-two-three inning to give
Anaheim momentum.
</P>
<P>
   ``I struggled,'' he said. ``I'm just glad we won. Tonight was
erratic. Coming back here and pitching here for the first time, I
was a little excited. I really didn't have much of a clue out
there. It was apparent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Being up, 4-0, I wanted to hold that lead but gave those up.
From my experience, that's what deflates a team, when you put up
four and they get four right back. I was mad at myself for that.
Then, when we got the six, I said, `Whatever I had to do right
there to get three outs in a row, I had to do it.' We had a six-run
lead, just go out and throw strikes, I was able to do that the last
two innings.''
</P>
<P>
   Mercker said he no longer has any health concerns. When he first
came back, he was watched very closely by medical personnel. They
monitored his blood pressure after any activity to make sure it
wasn't elevated. Everything was fine.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was basically the equivalent of being struck by
lightning,'' he said. ``Why that happens, you don't know, and why
this happened to me, nobody knows. But I'm assured that from all
the tests I did, there's no underlying problem that someone missed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel fortunate and blessed every night I get to pitch a
game. Three months ago, I didn't know if I was going to live, let
alone pitch again.''
</P>
<P>
   After his ordeal, a simple headache would cause him to worry
that something was wrong. Now, he says, he knows there isn't.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have the peace of mind to know that when I get a headache or
if I don't feel right, there's nothing wrong,'' he said. ``The
first couple of weeks, if I got one, I kind of sat down and braced
myself a little bit because I definitely don't want to experience
that again. But I was assured by the doctors that I was going to
get headaches like I did before, and I'm going to get lightheaded,
but don't panic.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said, `I've got a thousand pictures here you can take
home and every time you get a headache look at them, you're fine.'
Really, I'm better off than anyone else because no one else has had
those tests. I feel fortunate.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
