<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-LARRIMORE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS ROOKIE DEFENSIVE BACK EMERGES WITH CONFIDENCE INTACT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RAY BUCK 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Rookie Kareem Larrimore emerged from his weekend
trip to the Denver burn center (read: Mile High Stadium) still
holding the job of starting left cornerback for the Dallas Cowboys.
</P>
<P>
   He started, he played, he got toasted.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth-round pick from West Texas A&AMP;M was beaten deep,
stuffed on the run, and inexplicably lost his technique _ but not
his confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Or so he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't have to worry about my confidence. This was my one
learning experience ... (and) I learned,'' Larrimore said of the
job he inherited from Kevin Smith while sitting in front of the
Valley Ranch locker he inherited from Deion Sanders.
</P>
<P>
   Larrimore became a force-fed starter when Smith left the team
two weeks ago to contemplate retirement. And injuries that will
keep fellow rookie cornerbacks Mario Edwards and Dwayne Goodrich
out of the final preseason game against the St. Louis Rams haven't
hurt Larrimore's chances of keeping the job, either.
</P>
<P>
   Larrimore, more than ever, is under the microscope. But he is a
raw talent who has responded slowly in each of his two starts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess I've got to get him ready to go earlier in the game,''
said Cowboys defensive coordinator Mike Zimmer, who saw a
rejuvenated Larrimore in the second half Saturday night against the
Broncos after benching the rookie for the final two minutes of the
first half.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody is looking harder at Larrimore, or wants him to succeed
more, than owner Jerry Jones.
</P>
<P>
   ``Larrimore has inordinate physical skills. I think he had the
third fastest time (4.34-second 40) at the NFL combine,'' Jones
said. ``But a player also has to have instincts to play this game
... and not necessarily will more repetitions make someone a better
player.
</P>
<P>
   ``We think Kareem Larrimore has instincts (to play NFL
cornerback), but we don't know at this time. He has to show
somebody, and show himself, that he's got the instincts to play the
game at this speed.''
</P>
<P>
   Larrimore refuses to use his West Texas A&AMP;M roots as an excuse.
He said he has experienced firsthand the speed gap between Division
II college football _ and junior college before that _ and the NFL
by having to cover Joey Galloway in practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things can't be any faster than Galloway,'' Larrimore said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only reason I was at a Division II school in the first
place was because of my home situation,'' he added, referring to
his family's request that he leave the mean streets of Los Angeles
by any means possible. ``I'm not using Division II as an excuse,
either. I'm here now.''
</P>
<P>
   So, what happened against Denver?
</P>
<P>
   Larrimore played the first half in a Mile High fog. He was worn
out by Ed McCaffrey and Rod Smith, who have 16 NFL seasons between
them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just wasn't focused at first,'' Larrimore said. ``Coach Zim
pulled me. He didn't have to say anything. I knew just by looking
at him, he wanted me to get my head in the game. I did get the
chance to go back in, and I played like I should after that.''
</P>
<P>
   Veteran Ryan McNeil, who has become an instant starter for the
Cowboys at right cornerback _ Sanders' old spot _ can empathize
with Larrimore and what he calls ``growing pains.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, McNeil was Detroit's top draft pick (second round)
among a trio of rookie cornerbacks, including Greg Jeffries and
Kevin Minniefield.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a similar situation. But the disadvantage I had, I
held out and didn't report until a week before our first game,''
said McNeil, who started two games as rookie but did not become a
full-time starter until his second season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kareem is going to be fine as long as he sticks with what the
coaches and veteran players tell him. It's more technical than
anything else. Physically, he's real quick for as big (5-foot-11,
190) as he is.''
</P>
<P>
   In 11 days, the Cowboys begin playing for keeps. Donovan McNabb
and the Philadelphia Eagles are expected to bring a game plan into
Texas Stadium with Larrimore's name written all over it.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's going to get a lot of balls thrown at him because he's a
rookie,'' Zimmer said.
</P>
<P>
   At least Larrimore doesn't have to wonder if he will get a
chance to make amends.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
