<SLUG> BC-FBN-COWBOYS-NOTES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COWBOYS PLACE KEVIN SMITH ON RESERVE/RETIRED LIST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Officially placing cornerback Kevin Smith on the
reserve/retired list topped a flurry of moves by the Dallas Cowboys
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The others included the trading of receiver Jeff Ogden to Miami
for a seventh-round pick in 2002 and the waiving of running back
Michael Black.
</P>
<P>
   The Cowboys roster stands at 71, but it should dwindle by one in
the next couple of days. Only injury concerns are delaying the
release of quarterback Paul Justin, who is bothered by a elbow
contusion.
</P>
<P>
   Cowboys owner Jerry Jones said the move could happen before
Thursday's preseason finale with the St. Louis Rams.
</P>
<P>
   Smith has not made an official retirement announcement. His
agent, Steve Zucker, said the nine-year veteran will take his time
before making a decision. Smith has a congenital degenerative disk
in his lower back.
</P>
<P>
   However, Jones said Smith agreed to being placed on the retired
list to help out the Cowboys. The maneuver frees up about $750,000
in salary cap space, in addition to clearing a roster spot.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said it was just another example of how good the embattled
Smith has been to the Cowboys throughout his career, including
restructuring or reducing his salary in each of the past five years
to help with the salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   Jones also reiterated that he wants Smith to join the Cowboys as
a coach or consultant this season.
</P>
<P>
   Jones said the decisions with Ogden and Black came down to
numbers. The Cowboys liked both players, but neither was going to
make the team's final roster because of better players at their
respective positions.
</P>
<P>
   Ogden's departure likely means that Joey Galloway, Raghib
Ismail, Jason Tucker, Wane McGarity and James McKnight are locks
for the roster with Chris Brazzell and Damon Hodge on the bubble
for the final spot or two.
</P>
<P>
   Black was the odd man out for the third running back spot behind
Emmitt Smith and Chris Warren. Michael Wiley, who pocketed a
$100,000 bonus as the team's fifth-round draft pick, is the
front-runner in the battle with rookie free-agent Troy Hambrick,
who is a likely practice squad candidate.
</P>
<P>
   The kicker with Ogden, who has been sidelined since the
beginning of training camp with a variety of leg injuries, is that
the Cowboys were able to get something instead of letting him go
for free.
</P>
<P>
   Miami was in need of receiver because of a season-ending hip
fracture to Lamar Thomas. The Dolphins wanted Ogden because of his
familiarity with their offense. Chan Gailey, the Cowboys' coach the
past two seasons, is Miami's offensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm excited,'' Ogden said. ``It's a system I'm familiar with.
It's a coach I know. And he knows me.'' BRIEFLY
</P>
<P>
   _ Linebacker Barron Wortham (sprained knee) practiced Tuesday
for the first time in three weeks and could play against the Rams.
It will likely be a game-time decision.
</P>
<P>
   _ Tight end David LaFleur (strained groin) also practiced
Tuesday as the Cowboys are trying to gauge if he can play Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   _ Receiver Jason Tucker, running back Emmitt Smith and
cornerbacks Charlie Williams, Mario Edwards and Dwayne Goodrich
will not play Thursday.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
