<HEADLINE>
HAYES COULD GET SPOT IN COWBOYS' RING OF HONOR
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By CLARENCE E. HILL JR. 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ Dallas Cowboys owner Jerry Jones said Tuesday
that Bob Hayes tops the list of a number former players he's
considering for induction into the team's Ring of Honor.
</P>
<P>
   There's no questioning Hayes' on-the-field credentials. The
former Olympic champion sprinter forced teams to invent the zone
defense to combat his speed. And he still owns 21 team records.
</P>
<P>
   However, there's also no discounting Hayes' off-the-field
issues. Hayes, who played with the Cowboys from 1965-1972, served
10 months in prison for a drug conviction. He also was admitted to
substance-abuse centers on three different occasions.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, who said no decisions on a 2000 Ring of Honor induction
have been made, backed of his consideration of Hayes by saying that
he is the player most mentioned by the fans as a deserving
candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Jones, however, wants it clear that he hasn't gone soft on image
issues and is sensitive to the problem regarding Hayes' possible
induction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really get it when it comes to perception, role model and
off-the-field issues,'' Jones said. ``If it wasn't for those
issues, he'd already be there. I'm grappling with the same things
the Hall of Fame thought about (when considering Lawrence Taylor).
Should the point of emphasis be on the field? You start taking on a
lot when you start looking at judgment after careers. You start
covering areas that society in general hasn't found answers to.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones said it's easy to keep Hayes out but he is trying to
evaluate how he can get a deserving candidate like Hayes in. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
