<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEACHER-RAPE-CHARGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FEMALE HIGH SCHOOL TEACHER INDICTED FOR RAPE PLEADS NOT GUILTY 
</HEADLINE>
  By AL BAKER    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MONTROSE, N.Y. _ Months ago, when a special-education teacher
here said she had unfairly been forced to resign in the face of
salacious rumors that she had had sex with teen-age boys from her
school, many in this bucolic river town in northern Westchester
County rallied to her side.
</P>
<P>
   The rumors became headlines on Monday, when Marci Stein, 28, was
indicted on charges of statutory rape, sodomy and sexual abuse of
three male students, ages 14 to 16.
</P>
<P>
   But as the weight of the allegations sank in around town on
Tuesday, many people said they still supported Stein, a member of a
family with deep roots in the community.
</P>
<P>
   ``I still can't believe it's true,'' said Harry DiPietro, the
owner of Da-Ro's Corner Store. ``You and I know that with
indictments you only hear one side. I would hope that when it all
comes out she'll be all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Stein, who was released without bail, stood silently on Tuesday
in the driveway of her ranch house in the village of Buchanan, her
eyes covered by dark sunglasses, as her husband, Adam, told a
reporter the accusations were false.
</P>
<P>
   ``It couldn't be a bigger lie,'' said Stein, a federal marshal
and a veteran of the Persian Gulf War, waving his arms for
emphasis. ``Everyone supports us _ except for the school board and
the kids and the parents and, of course, the district attorney.''
</P>
<P>
   Adam and Marci Stein and their parents graduated from Hendrick
Hudson High School. Their grandparents were on the school board, he
said. Her father is a well-known local electrician. His father is
the building inspector in Tarrytown, a few miles south on the
Hudson River.
</P>
<P>
   The charges against Stein seemed a touchy subject to many here.
Some people expressed shock; some refused to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Alfred J. Donahue, the mayor of the Village of Buchanan, did not
return calls seeking comment. An aide to Linda D. Puglisi, the
supervisor of the Town of Cortlandt, which encompasses the hamlet
of Montrose, said that on the advice of the town's lawyer, she and
the Town Council would not comment on the matter.
</P>
<P>
   But those who did comment included Jeanine Pirro, the
Westchester County district attorney, who said Stein had taken
three male students to her home for individual tutoring sessions
and wound up raping and sodomizing them in incidents between April
1999 and last January.
</P>
<P>
   The boys were interviewed by the authorities after a teacher
overheard talk in school about the sexual allegations and alerted
school officials, who conducted an investigation and called the
state police.
</P>
<P>
   According to the indictment, Stein fondled the boys as they sat
at their desks in school and at subsequent encounters in her home
after school had sexual intercourse with one of them and committed
sodomy with two others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that this case is pointedly all about a betrayal of
trust,'' Pirro said Tuesday, a day after Stein pleaded not guilty
in Westchester County Court to charges in a 17-count indictment.
``We send our children to school for them to be educated and never
do we expect this kind of thing to happen, nor do we anticipate it
nor do we imagine it.''
</P>
<P>
   In April, Stein resigned and filed a federal civil rights
lawsuit against the district, accusing officials of spreading false
rumors about her and threatening to fire her after she had two
years on the job. Her supporters held a candlelight vigil in front
of the school.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Lovett, Stein's lawyer in the civil rights lawsuit,
said Tuesday that Stein would be acquitted at trial and vindicated.
</P>
<P>
   ``This case is a beautiful example of character assassination
from the school district up to the district attorney,'' he said.
``It is a lot of grandstanding to ruin the reputation and career of
a young woman. And they are going to pay.'' John Mancuso, who is
acting as Stein's lawyer in the criminal matter, did not return
calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   School officials refused to comment, citing the pending lawsuit
against the district. But Joan Thompson, the Hendrick Hudson School
District superintendent, released a statement defending the
district's investigation of allegations of sexual misconduct by
Stein. It said the decision to remove her from her job was
``necessary for the protection of the student body.''
</P>
</TEXT>
