<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-REDSOX-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MERCKER A WINNER FOR ANGELS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ It had been nearly a year since Kent Mercker last won a
major- league game, but to him it was a lifetime ago.
</P>
<P>
   It's not that the 11 months that have passed seem so distant,
but rather what he experienced between then and now. Specifically,
the brain hemorrhage that threatened his life on May 11 when
pitching in Anaheim for the Angels.
</P>
<P>
   Mercker didn't pitch particularly well in the Anaheim Angels'
11-4 victory over the Boston Red Sox Tuesday night at Fenway Park.
But the fact that he was pitching at all and competing is the
recurring theme.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if getting that first win since the hemorrhage was
significant, Mercker said, ``No. What's significant for me was to
pitch, period. If I get no-decisions every game for the rest of my
life and our team wins, that's what matters.'
</P>
<P>
   In his third start since returning to the mound, Mercker gave up
four runs and nine hits in six innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just to see Merck on the mound and see him compete really
gives us a lift,''
</P>
<P>
   Angels manager Mike Scioscia said, ``We've seen what he's been
through. I saw him the day after he had a hemorrhage in his brain.
From not knowing if he'd ever pitch in a major-league game again to
winning a game, that's about as full-circle as you can get.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll always have injuries that threaten a guy's season or
career, but this puts a different perspective on what the game's
all about. It's a great thing to witness.'
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia was also happy to witness the Angels bounce back from
Monday's disappointing loss. The Angels are awaiting word on the
protest they filed, but the players showed they have put that game
out of their minds.
</P>
<P>
   The Angels got 14 hits, including four from Orlando Palmeiro and
three each from Troy Glaus and Garret Anderson. They also played
sound defense and made one play in particular that changed the
momentum of the game.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox had rallied from a 4-0 deficit to make it 4-3 in the
fourth inning. They had two runners on with two out when Troy
O'Leary hit one into the left-center-field gap. Lou Merloni scored
from second to tie the game and Nomar Garciaparra tried to score
from first.
</P>
<P>
   But the Angels' relay - center fielder Anderson to shortstop
Kevin Stocker to catcher Bengie Molina - nailed Garciaparra at the
plate to keep the game tied at 4. The Angels then scored six runs
in the top of the fifth to go up, 10-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``Defensively, we played a real strong game,'' Scioscia said.
``That was a key play when O'Leary hit the ball in gap, but we made
a perfect relay. That's a big play we kept the score tied and it
gives us a chance to get back on top in the next inning.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory was the first for the Angels at Fenway Park since
ex-Red Sox Mo Vaughn joined the team. The Angels went 0-6 last
season here and lost Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   The win moved the Angels to within 2 games of wild-card leader
Cleveland. They remained 5 games behind American League
West-leading Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   It was also the Angels' second win in three games without Darin
Erstad, who is out with a muscle strain in his left ribcage. And
Tuesday's game was significant because Palmeiro - playing in
Erstad's spot in left field and hitting leadoff in the batting
order - had a big game.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the four hits, he also drove in three and made a diving
catch in the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``Orlando's our little secret weapon,'' Scioscia said. ``The
guys were joking with Ersty, calling him Wally Pipp.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's great we can fill holes when guys are hurt,''
Palmeiro said. ``That's what championship teams do when players get
hurt. We don't miss a beat.''
</P>
<P>
   The Angels improved to 4-4 with one to play on what was expected
to be a critical East Coast trip.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
