<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLANOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ZDENEK FINALLY GETS HIS CHANCE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Jason Zdenek doesn't have much to show for his
first four years with the UCLA football team, except maybe a few
bumps and bruises acquired during his time with the scout team in
practice.
</P>
<P>
   All that is about to change, as Zdenek, a fifth-year senior who
has appeared in just two games during his college career, is on the
verge of securing a starting position as the Bruins' free safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's everything I've been preparing for,'' said Zdenek, a
graduate of Chaminade High in West Hills who played with the
first-team defense in Tuesday's brief scrimmage. ``Year after year,
all the meetings, lifting weights and conditioning, and now I'm
getting the chance to actually show it on the field.''
</P>
<P>
   To this point, the list of Zdenek's on-field accomplishments is
brief. He was on the field for 17 snaps during the second half of
the Bruins' blowout of Boise State last year, and participated n
kickoff coverage for one game in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   That's not much glory, especially with all the hours Zdenek
spent toiling away as scout-team fodder for the Bruins' offense.
It's also not much experience, considering the importance of the
free safety position to the Bruins in the past few years.
</P>
<P>
   In each of the past three seasons, the free safety has led or
tied for the team lack in total tackles, including Joey Strycula
(69 tackles in 1999), Larry Atkins (94 in 1998) and Shaun Williams
(68 in 1997).
</P>
<P>
   Zdenek's dedication to the Bruins' off-season conditioning
program, as well as his strong play over the past two weeks, have
helped to calm the nerves of coach Bob Toledo.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at most teams, usually the weak inside linebacker
and the safety are the leading tacklers, for whatever reason,''
Toledo said. ``They are the last line of defense, so you want a guy
back there who's not going to miss a tackle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jason has made great strides. He's got a lot more confidence
(and) he's got a great understanding of what we're trying to do.
He's got great character and he's the kind of guy you want in your
secondary.''
</P>
<P>
   Payback time: Toledo, upset with poor blocking during a
scrimmage Tuesday, decided to teach his offensive linemen a lesson.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo stopped play, handed the ball to one of his linemen and
instructed him to hold it up, like a quarterback preparing to throw
a pass. Then, Toledo told a defensive lineman to ``sack'' the big
man. The defensive linemen didn't hold back, and every offensive
lineman had to receive one crushing tackle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was trying to show the offensive linemen what it's like to
play quarterback,'' said Toledo, who added that it was the first
time he tried the drill at UCLA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically I wanted them to know that it's no fun to be holding
the ball back there and getting hit in the side of the head.''
</P>
<P>
   Improvement: Right guard Oscar Cabrera, recovering from a high
ankle sprain, worked out with a trainer during Tuesday's practice
and hopes to begin light practice with his teammates by the end of
the week.
</P>
<P>
   Cabrera, who participated in agility drills for the second
consecutive day, said he felt no pain and estimated that he is
``about 80 to 85 percent'' healthy. His status for next week's
season opener against Alabama in still in doubt.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is my last go around, my senior year,'' Cabrera said,
``and I was hoping it would be injury free, but that's the way it
goes sometimes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
