<SLUG> BC-NY-MISSING-BOYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2 MISSING AFTER SWIM IN HUDSON
</HEADLINE>
  By ANDY NEWMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two mentally ill teen-age boys from a state
psychiatric center in Brooklyn were missing in the swirling waters
of the Hudson River near Ossining, N.Y., Tuesday night after they
went swimming in a prohibited section of the river during a camping
trip, the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   Two counselors on the trip, from the Brooklyn Children's
Psychiatric Center, were watching when the boys, ages 15 and 17,
went into the water at Croton Point Park, said Sgt. Donald McArthur
of the Westchester County police.
</P>
<P>
   One counselor nearly drowned trying to rescue the boys, McArthur
said, and was being held for observation at a hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The counselors had been told by a park employee earlier in the
day that swimming was forbidden at the spot, but it was not clear
whether the counselors allowed the boys to swim or if the boys
disobeyed them, the sergeant said.
</P>
<P>
   The Coast Guard suspended the search for the teen-agers around
8:30 p.m., after five fruitless hours, said Susan Tolchin, a
spokeswoman for the Westchester County executive's office.
</P>
<P>
   The search was to resume Wednesday morning, though the police
said they doubted that the boys had survived.
</P>
<P>
   The boys, whose names were not released, live in a state-run
residence on the grounds of the psychiatric center, in
Bedford-Stuyvesant, the authorities said. They were part of a group
of six patients and four counselors who went on an overnight trip
to stay in bungalows at the park, a 508-acre county preserve on the
east side of the Hudson about 35 miles north of New York City.
</P>
<P>
   The campers were apparently looking for a place to swim, but
even the official park beach is now closed on weekdays because of a
shortage of lifeguards, McArthur said. ``I believe someone from the
group questioned whether swimming was available,'' he said. ``The
parks people we spoke to said that this particular group had been
instructed that they could not swim just prior to the incident.''
</P>
<P>
   Around 3 p.m., McArthur said, all six of the patients and two
counselors hiked down a steep hill and across a field of boulders
to Teller's Point, a desolate area where the Croton and Hudson
Rivers meet and riptides and crosscurrents twist through the water.
``No Swimming'' signs are prominently posted at the point, Tolchin
said.
</P>
<P>
   It was not clear what led up to the boys' decision to jump into
the river, but they soon began struggling in the current, McArthur
said. A counselor, Lenox Gabriel, 47, went into the water to try to
rescue them, but he started going under, McArthur said.
</P>
<P>
   Two county police officers responding to a 911 call dived into
the water and pulled Gabriel out, but the boys had disappeared, the
sergeant said.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel was in stable condition Tuesday night at Phelps Memorial
Hospital in Sleepy Hollow.
</P>
<P>
   All afternoon and into the evening, by air, by water and by
land, teams searched the area from the Tappan Zee Bridge, five
miles south of the park, to Peekskill, five miles to the north. The
tide was coming in when the boys went into the water but it had
turned by nightfall.
</P>
<P>
   New York City police divers searched the river while a city
police helicopter circled overhead. Dozens of local, county and
state police officers and firefighters scanned the banks, and the
Coast Guard searched in its boat, Tolchin said. As hope and
sunlight began to dim and members of the boys' families began to
arrive, crisis counselors were called to the park, said Roger
Klingman, a spokesman for the State Office of Mental Health, which
runs the psychiatric center.
</P>
<P>
   McArthur said he doubted the boys would be found alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``You like to be optimistic,'' he said, ``but if they haven't
gotten ashore the chances are pretty slim.''
</P>
<P>
   Brooklyn Children's Psychiatric Center, a cluster of nondescript
institutional buildings on Bergen Street near Ralph Avenue in
Bedford-Stuyvesant, serves young people with serious emotional
disturbances.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
