<HEADLINE>
SURGERY CAN'T STOP JOHNSON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Los Angeles Dodgers manager Davey Johnson had
surgery at 8 a.m., was in recovery in the afternoon and arrived at
Dodger Stadium a few hours before first pitch.
</P>
<P>
   You know, just another Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a tough son of a gun,'' Dodgers team physician Dr. Frank
Jobe said. ``I had the same operation six weeks ago and I couldn't
manage a game.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson had arthroscopic surgery on his left rotator cuff to
repair his labrum, remove a bone spur and repair his clavicle, Jobe
said. The recovery time is three to four months.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the thought of taking some time off to recover
crossed Johnson's mind, he was given clearance by the Dodgers'
medical personnel to return to the bench Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm glad that's over,'' Johnson said. ``It's something I
needed to have done because it was getting worse and worse. I'm
glad it's over. The last three weeks it's been kind of painful. If
(bench coach) Jim Tracy can go in and have his knee scoped and show
up at work, I could go in and do the same thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson did take pain medication before arriving at the stadium.
</P>
<P>
   Cora gets call: For the first time this season, Alex Cora
started at shortstop when the opposition started a left-hander.
Cora, in a platoon with Kevin Elster, did make two starts at second
base in place of the ailing Mark Grudzielanek in July.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson tried to protect the 24-year-old Cora in his first
full-blown stint in the big leagues, and Cora's done well in his
limited exposure to left-handed pitchers. He's batting .266 .333 (8
for 24) against left-handers and .258 (54 for 209) against
right-handers.
</P>
<P>
   Perez to start: Lefty Carlos Perez is back in the starting mix.
Well, at least for a day. With the Dodgers facing a doubleheader
Friday in Chicago and games stacked up for the next week
thereafter, the Dodgers are turning to the enigmatic Perez to start
the second game of the twin bill.
</P>
<P>
   Perez is 4-6 with a 5.36 ERA but was yanked from the starting
rotation after giving up five runs in four innings Aug. 1 in
Pittsburgh. Afterward, Perez and Johnson got in a shouting match.
</P>
<P>
   But Perez has found a niche in relief. He's allowed four runs in
22 innings, and was hoping to parlay that, along with a strong
start in Chicago, into a possible return to the rotation.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they make that decision, I'll be happy,'' Perez said.
``It's kind of tough (in the bullpen). Sometimes I have to wait at
least five, six days to pitch in a game. I'd like the opportunity
to pitch two, three times a week, but I don't have that
opportunity.''
</P>
<P>
   Odds and ends: Left fielder Gary Sheffield's run at Duke
Snider's franchise home run mark was put on hold. Sheffield was a
late scratch with flu-like symptoms and replaced by Jim Leyritz,
who made his first start in left field. It was Leyritz's fourth
start since joining the Dodgers in mid-June. ... Grudzielanek is in
a 2-for-22 stretch, so he was rested and F.P. Santangelo started at
second base. ... After throwing out three would-be base stealers
Monday, Dodgers catcher Todd Hundley nailed Fernando Seguignol
trying to steal second in the second inning. ... The Dodgers will
announce the signing of No. 1 pick Ben Diggins (17th overall)
today. Diggins, who will receive a $2.2 million signing bonus if he
passes his physical in the morning, is expected to report to the
instructional league in a few weeks.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
