<HEADER>
A9668 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-DODGERS-EXPOS-LAD     08-23 0723
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-EXPOS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS HIT SIX HOMERS IN ROUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- It was a freaky, crazy night that could be capped
only by the most unexpected of all things, an offensive explosion
leading to a Los Angeles Dodgers win.
</P>
<P>
   MVP candidate Gary Sheffield sat out with flu-like symptoms and
it didn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   Eric Karros had two homers and drove in four runs - in one
inning - and switch-hitting Todd Hundley dropped the right-handed
portion of his arsenal and had three hits, including a three-run
homer against a lefty.
</P>
<P>
   Oh, and Davey Johnson had shoulder surgery in the morning and
managed at night.
</P>
<P>
   All in all, the Dodgers hit a season-high six home runs and
routed the Montreal Expos 14-6 Tuesday at Dodger Stadium in a game
that was about as illogical as can be conceived. It was so strange
the Dodgers even made it possible to forget just how awful the past
three weeks have been.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did Karros and Hundley star, but the Dodgers had two
runners thrown out at home plate in one inning, saw starter Ismael
Valdes hit his first career homer but not hold a three-run lead
after five innings and watched Hundley throw out his fourth
would-be base stealer in two nights.
</P>
<P>
   It made for a jovial clubhouse and brought a smile from Johnson,
whose day began with morning surgery to repair a damaged left
rotator cuff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to cut on the right one tomorrow,'' Johnson said.
``Then I got a couple legs left. Whatever it takes.''
</P>
<P>
   It was a baffling night leading up to the Dodgers' nine-run
sixth inning, capped by their most productive inning since scoring
nine runs in an inning April 24, 1998, against Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Karros homered to break a 5-5 tie to lead off the sixth against
reliever Julio Santana. It was the 500th extra-base hit of Karros'
career. Willie Davis and Steve Garvey are the only other two Los
Angeles Dodgers to reach that mark.
</P>
<P>
   Then Karros hit a three-run homer to finish the inning, making
him the first Dodger to hit two homers in an inning. It's been
accomplished 21 times in the National League, the last coming when
St. Louis' Fernando Tatis hit two grand slams off Dodgers
right-hander Chan Ho Park last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The nice one was the one that broke the tie, leading off the
inning,'' said Karros, who reached 30 homers for the fifth time in
his career. ``The (second) at-bat, I was trying to hit a fly ball.
I was surprised (no other Dodger did it). You think somebody would
do it in the `50s.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Leyritz followed Karros' first homer with a walk and Adrian
Beltre singled. Santana was replaced by lefty Scott Forster, and
Hundley smashed a three-run homer, his 22nd of the season.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Hundley stopped batting right-handed during an
August series in Montreal last season because of frustration. He
worked during the offseason and was off to a strong start this
season, but he slumped lately. Hundley, who was batting .216 (11
for 51) with three homers, 10 RBI and 17 strikeouts right-handed,
is batting .344 left-handed. Hundley said he made the decision to
stop switch-hitting after talking with his dad, former big-league
catcher Randy Hundley.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Monday) night I decided to bag it,'' Hundley said. ``It comes
to a point, where as a team, you have to get it done. Left-handed,
I know at least I can put it in play with runners on base. I just
don't feel confident right-handed. There's no reason to do it. I
feel so confident left-handed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is getting the job done. If I can drive the
ball like that, I might as well stay with it. I hit two balls hard
up the middle and a homer.''
</P>
<P>
   A late replacement for the ailing Sheffield, who was scratched
from the lineup an hour before game time, Leyritz did his best
impersonation of the MVP candidate.
</P>
<P>
   Leyritz homered in his first at-bat, something Sheffield's done
40 times, and had an RBI single in the fourth. He also made a
diving catch along the left field line in the fifth, and slammed
into the wall after catching Fernando Seguignol's bases-loaded
liner in the sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the first time in six years I've been out there,''
Leyritz said. ``It was fun. I hadn't been out there in a while, but
I've been taking fly balls and working.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
