<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARINERS STOP THEIR EIGHT-GAME SKID 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN HICKEY  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DETROIT _ You want easy? Go solve Rubik's cube.
</P>
<P>
   You want hard? Be the Mariners trying to end an eight-game
losing streak.
</P>
<P>
   After scratching, clawing and sweating to build up a five-run
lead entering the ninth inning, the Mariners almost saw it all slip
away.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you're going like this, it's never easy to break out of
it,'' left fielder Rickey Henderson said. ``They always make it
hard on you.''
</P>
<P>
   It was Henderson who supplied the final piece to the puzzle of
the slumping Mariners, running down Dean Palmer's bases-loaded bid
for a grand slam 410 feet from home plate as Seattle survived a
near-firestorm in the ninth inning to score an 8-4 victory over
Detroit Tuesday night.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners rode into the ninth feeling pretty good about
themselves for a team that had lost eight in a row. They'd finally
gotten a break when Mike Cameron's two-out line drive in the eighth
landed on the left-field chalk line for a two-run double that broke
a 3-3 tie. And they'd finally gotten a breakout hit when Alex
Rodriguez crushed a three-run homer in the top of the ninth for an
8-3 lead.
</P>
<P>
   On his way to center field to start the bottom of the ninth,
Cameron said to Henderson that Rodriguez had put the game away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `You can't say that,' '' Henderson said.
</P>
<P>
   And, sure enough, with one out and two on, the eight-game
octopus snared the Mariners in its tentacles one more time.
Rodriguez had a possible game-ending double play ball hit to him,
but the ball kicked away from him for an error.
</P>
<P>
   That brought home a run and led to the exit of reliever Jose
Paniagua. Closer Kazuhiro Sasaki walked the first batter he faced,
Bobby Higginson, and the Tigers, who had won seven of eight, had
the potential winning run at the plate in Juan Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron looked at Henderson and said, ``I never should have said
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Sasaki fell behind former AL MVP Gonzalez 2-1, but after a visit
from pitching coach Bryan Price, came back to strike out Gonzalez
on a nasty forkball. Up stepped Palmer, who got behind 0-2, then
jumped on a low forkball. The ball screamed into the gap in
left-center.
</P>
<P>
   Cameron never had a chance at the ball. But Henderson said he
wasn't letting this game get away.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was going to climb the wall if I had to, to catch this
one,'' Henderson said.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't need to, but just barely. The Comerica left-field wall
juts straight out from near the left-field line, angling deep into
left center, and ``I needed every inch of it,'' Henderson said.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Higginson said in the ghostly quiet of the Tigers'
clubhouse, ``Comerica got us again.''
</P>
<P>
   Sasaki, who made good on a weekend promise by sprinkling salt on
the three sets of steps that lead from the visitors' dugout to the
field before the game to try and drive the malevolent spirits from
the Mariners' doorstep, greeted reporters after the game in
crystal-clear sign language. He symbolically mopped at his brow,
then tapped his heart a couple of times. It had been that close.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just was thinking to myself, `Don't go out. Don't go out,'
'' Sasaki said through interpreter Allen Turner. ``The salt
worked.''
</P>
<P>
   Sprinkling salt is a long-standing superstition among Japanese
baseball players as a way to end a long losing streak. He
sprinkled, and the Mariners finally won. At least for one night,
salt was the spice of life for Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever it took, be it salt or sweat, the Mariners were willing
to go the distance to get this one in the bag. Eight games is a
long time to go without a win. For a first-place team trying to
hold off challengers in its division, it's about two grains of salt
short of forever.
</P>
<P>
   ``To win tonight, that took more than the monkey off our
backs,'' Rodriguez said. ``It was like a 500-pound gorilla. Now we
can go back to work, working on a two-game winning streak.''
</P>
<P>
   To get the win, the Mariners received strong starting pitching
from Freddy Garcia, who gave up three runs early, then pitched
scoreless baseball from the fourth until turning the ball over to
the bullpen with two outs in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   To win, the Mariners got good two-out hitting from Carlos
Guillen, Mark McLemore, Cameron and Rodriguez. Guillen had an RBI
single in the second, McLemore an RBI double in the fourth. Like
Cameron's two-run double and Rodriguez's three-run homer, those
hits came with two out.
</P>
<P>
   To win, the Mariners got good defense, too. Well, sort of.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defense was great tonight, except for me,'' Rodriguez
said.
</P>
<P>
   Paniagua, the winning pitcher, started pounding his glove the
moment he saw Juan Encarnacion's grounder in the ninth head
Rodriguez's way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm saying, 'All right. It's over,' '' Paniagua said. But it
wasn't, the ball eluding a frustrated Rodriguez.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a tough play, but not so tough that I shouldn't have
made it,'' the shortstop said. ``This game will test you.''
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez said things had gotten bleak enough that the Mariners
had held a players-only meeting Saturday in Cleveland, the first of
its kind this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It got pointed out that there aren't many teams that have lost
seven or eight in a row and have still been in first place,''
Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle's lead over Oakland, down to two games in the AL West on
Sunday, is now 31/2 games after the A's lost 14-6 in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   As Price said, ``Now we can exhale.''
</P>
<P>
   Breathing is a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   P-I reporter John Hickey can be reached at 206-448-8004
</P>
<P>
   or johnhickey &LR; seattle-pi.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
