<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-QUIZZICAL-QADDAFI-FISK-INDEPENDENT-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ODD QUESTIONS ABOUT QADDAFI'S LATEST MISCHIEF  
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Commentary Editors)   (This 625-word ``separate-buy'' article is from THE INDEPENDENT
newspaper in London.)  
 &HT;    
 (EDITORS: We regret that this material is NOT available to clients
in Canada EXCEPT to The Hamilton (Ontario) Spectator.)  
 &HT;    
 (To publish this article, it must be purchased from the New York
Times Syndicate's sales representative DEBRA WEYDERT at
732-390-4480, or fax her at 732-390-4697. Her e-mail address is
weyded(at)nytimes.com. If unable to reach Ms. Weydert, please call
800-444-0267, or fax us at 816-822-1444.)  
 &HT;    
 (PLEASE NOTE: This article has been transmitted twice _ into the
``a'' domestic/general news and ``k'' commentary news files.)  
 &HT;    
 By ROBERT FISK  
 c.2000 The Independent, London  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   BEIRUT _ Some very odd questions are surfacing in the Middle
East about Colonel Moammar Qaddafi's latest adventure in the
Philippines.
</P>
<P>
   What exactly is the ``Qaddafi International Association for
Charitable Organizations'' which is run by the colonel's
26-year-old son, Seif, and which is supposedly mediating for the
release of the 24 hostages in the Philippines?
</P>
<P>
   Why does it have no address listed in the Libyan capital of
Tripoli? And why has an organization which can rustle up a jet, a
medical team and negotiators so swiftly never been heard of before?
</P>
<P>
   Why have so few people recalled that Qaddafi sent money and
weapons to the Moro Liberation Front in the Philippines shortly
after he staged his coup d'etat over King Idris in 1969? Qaddafi
turned up to witness the subsequent autonomy agreement with Manila.
</P>
<P>
   And when a breakaway of the Moro Islamic Liberation Front
rejected the autonomy agreement, they changed their name to Abu
Sayyaf: the very same Abu Sayyaf organization which now holds the
hostages in the Philippines. It was this same group which, in 1995,
called for the lifting of U.N. sanctions against Libya.
</P>
<P>
   Colonel Qaddafi has weaved many a tangled web in his time, but
few as complex as this. Nor one as strange in its nomenclature.
</P>
<P>
   Qaddafi's son is called Seif el-Islam, which means, literally,
the two-edged sword of Islam. And ``Abu Sayyaf'' _ the name of the
kidnap group _ means, in Arabic, ``father of the sword-bearer.''
Just a coincidence, no doubt.
</P>
<P>
   And then _ for those who enjoyed the revelations in the French
press last week that France was supporting the Qaddafi initiative
in order to get its own hostages freed _ there is the weird story
of the good ship ``Silco.''
</P>
<P>
   The ``Silco'' was a rustbucket cruising off the North African
coast with five Belgians and a Frenchwoman on board when on Nov. 8,
1987, it was commandeered by members of the ruthless Palestinian
``Fatah Revolutionary Council'' led by Abu Nidal.
</P>
<P>
   Suspicions remain that the ship was in fact seized by a Libyan
naval gunboat. But for two years, the world played along with the
fiction that Abu Nidal's group, which was then based in Tripoli,
was holding its prisoners in an unknown location.
</P>
<P>
   Then on April 10, 1990, one of the Belgians, Fernard Houtekins,
and his French lover, Jacqueline Valente _ along with a child born
in captivity _ turned up in Beirut, courtesy, so we were informed
at the time, of Colonel Qaddafi's ``mediation.''
</P>
<P>
   Sound familiar? Abu Nidal's local office in Beirut even invited
a squad of Belgian diplomats to negotiate for the other hostages. I
was present when they arrived to chat to the local Abu Nidal
representative, who was to be assassinated a few meters from the
same office a few weeks later.
</P>
<P>
   The Belgians diplomats thanked Colonel Qaddafi for his
``mediation.'' French President Francois Mitterand formally thanked
Qaddafi for the ``decisive role'' he played in securing the release
of the Belgian and his French woman friend.
</P>
<P>
   In Beirut, the two were handed over by armed Palestinians to a
senior French intelligence agent called Philippe Rondot.
</P>
<P>
   Rondot, it transpired, had been involved in the negotiations
with Libyan emissaries for the hostages' release. Where is Rondot
now, one wonders? In France? Or in the Philippines?
</P>
<P>
   And where, finally, has the $24 million offered by the Libyans
for the Philippine hostages' release actually come from? It's a lot
of money for a charity to throw around.
</P>
<P>
   And if it goes to the Abu Sayyaf group, will any of it be
returned to the man who so generously supported their parent
``liberation'' organization three decades ago: Colonel Moammar
Qaddafi? &QL; 
 &UR; ___________________ &LR;  &QC; 
