   What follows are the articles that make up this week's
transmission. The stories have been sent to the ``f'' (financial)
category code. Take a look.
</P>
<P>
   PERFORMANCE APPRAISALS WITH TEETH: CAN THEY WORK?
</P>
<P>
   EMPLOYEE-REVIEWS-WITH-TEETH-HARVARD-NEWSLETTERS _ In the past,
performance appraisals were often treated as a charade in which
employees were all rated above average. Not any more. Now many
companies are using performance-management systems to weed out
underachievers and reward star performers. The downside: Companies
run the risk of making employees feel like high school students,
and the rankings can discourage collaboration. What's a manager to
do? 500 words. By the editorial staff of the Harvard Management
Update newsletter.
</P>
<P>
   WEB CONFERENCING
</P>
<P>
   WEB-CONFERENCING-HARVARD-NEWSLETTERS _ There used to be two
choices when it came to getting people together to discuss or
disseminate information: Send them by plane, train or automobile to
meet in person, or set up an audio conference. Now there's an
alternative: Web conferencing. It's essentially an audio conference
with visuals, and a growing number of companies are finding it a
useful way of holding a meeting. 700 words. By the editorial staff
of the Harvard Management Communication Letter.
</P>
