<SLUG> BC-SWARTZ-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER A WASTED OPPORTUNITY, THE ELEPHANT LINGERS 

</HEADLINE>
   By SUSAN SWARTZ   
 The Press Democrat, Santa Rosa , Calif.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   All the vice president's women and all the vice president's men
did their best to make him likable.
</P>
<P>
   The affable Joe Lieberman praised his moral center and the
winning Caroline Kennedy Schlossberg said he cared about the
dispossessed and cute Tommy Lee Jones said he was brotherly and the
charming Karenna said he was fatherly. Twinkling Tipper beat the
drum for him.
</P>
<P>
   The message was, he's decent, good and caring. With all that,
who needs cool and clever. But there's still the elephant in the
living room, the thing he can't lighten up.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton could have chased the elephant, because he's
responsible for its being there. But he tiptoed around it like
everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Clinton also had kind things to say about Al Gore at the
Democratic convention, but he could have done more.
</P>
<P>
   He could have still done the walk, given his dazzling speech and
then asked for quiet. Then he could have said something like, ``Now
I'm going to bring up a difficult subject,'' and shake a teacherly
finger as he does.
</P>
<P>
   He could have said, ``My personal mistakes belong to me, not Al
Gore. I'm paying for them. He shouldn't.''
</P>
<P>
   He could have said, ``I wounded my family and embarrassed my
country. It is my shame. Al Gore had nothing to do with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Imagine. The place would have been so silent you could have
heard a balloon bounce. Everyone else would have looked down at
their knees or chewed their top lip as Clinton does when he's
having an emotional moment.
</P>
<P>
   For those who still didn't get it, he could have explained, ``Al
Gore's job was to be my second. He did what vice presidents are
supposed to do. There are those who think he should have attacked
me. But they don't understand the job of vice president. His job
was to stand in the wings, prepared to run the country. He couldn't
do that if he was also denouncing me.''
</P>
<P>
   He could have added, ``Al Gore didn't just prove his loyalty to
me during those bad times. He proved his loyalty to America. Now
give it a rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Cameras would have frantically sought Hillary and Chelsea, who,
having been tipped to the addendum, would be holding hands and
looking resolute. Reporters would have leaped to their laptops.
</P>
<P>
   Unfortunately everything else that was said that night might
have ended up on the jump page. But it could have chased the
elephant and said ``boo'' to the elephant keepers, because even
though it's the president's elephant, his enemies are feeding it.
</P>
<P>
   They say things such as, Al Gore should rebuke the president
loud and clear for his shameful ways.
</P>
<P>
   They say the two are Tweedle Dum and Tweedle Dee and that no one
will ever be able to look at Al Gore without thinking of Bill
Clinton, by which they mean only the naughty Clinton, not the one
who had anything to do with prosperous times. This guilt by
association concept somehow does not apply to Gerald Ford and
Richard Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   They'd have us fault Al Gore for not going on the Jerry Springer
show and duking it out with his boss.
</P>
<P>
   They like the elephant.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore is said to enjoy metaphors. He sees the elephant, but
it's not his to talk about. It never was.
</P>
<P>
   Some will argue that Clinton already spoke of these things to an
evangelical gathering, but that wasn't L.A. with the whole world
watching.
</P>
<P>
   Some will say that we're supposed to put this unseemly mess
behind us, but how many people have? Even those enraptured by
Clinton's princely speech had flickering thoughts that ranged from
``big jerk'' to ``what a waste of greatness.''
</P>
<P>
   Some day Tipper will write her book and let us know how often Al
came home and hit his head against the wall and wished he could cut
and run.
</P>
<P>
   Right now all we know is that during the very bizarre period
when the White House was everyone's dirty joke and the presidency
was under siege, the vice president played Steady Eddie, stayed the
course and said nothing, even though he might have been thinking,
``Jeesh, Bill. You are such a train wreck.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, things could have turned out entirely differently.
Clinton might have resigned and then Gore would have become
president. By now we would know how equipped he is to run a country
and whether a stiff demeanor and a propensity toward
intellectualizing get in the way of achieving things such as
equitable health care and spending more on education.
</P>
<P>
   By now we'd know if he was good for the economy, good for
working families and committed to fairness. We'd know the guy for
who he really is, minus the elephant.
</P>
<P>
   (Susan Swartz is a columnist for The Press Democrat in Santa
Rosa, Calif. The Press Democrat is a member of the New York Times
Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
