<DOCNO> NYT20000823.0064 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 10:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9774 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w BC-TAX-BLUES24-COX     08-23 0551
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAX-BLUES24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TAX COURT RULING MAY COST TEXAS BLUE CROSS MILLIONS
 &HT;    Attn: Texas papers.
 &HT;    By JERRY MOSKAL
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Blue Cross &AMP; Blue Shield of Texas Inc. may be
liable for millions of dollars in additional federal taxes under a
precedent-setting U.S. Tax Court ruling.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Stephen J. Swift ruled Friday(cq) that the insurer did not
qualify for savings under a rule approved by Congress as part of
the 1990 Omnibus Reconciliation Budget Act (OBRA).
</P>
<P>
   Blue Cross had sought $14.8 million in tax deductions under the
rule for both 1992 and 1993, but the Internal Revenue Service found
it did not qualify, and demanded $5.27 million in additional taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is too soon to know whether we will appeal,'' said Richard
Bromley, one of four Chicago tax attorneys for Blue Cross. ``We
haven't had a chance to talk to our client yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Congress enacted the rule to cushion insurers against huge tax
bills arising from OBRA's change in the way insurance companies
must report reserves set aside for estimated claims.
</P>
<P>
   Previously, the companies used the full original estimated
liability of claims, but the law changed that to a ``net'' basis.
</P>
<P>
   Tracy D. Williams of Chicago, one of the Blue Cross tax
attorneys, explained Tuesday that OBRA required insurers to take
into account amounts they recover from other sources when reporting
their loss reserves.
</P>
<P>
   For example, she said, a company anticipating a $10,000 claim is
required to reduce that by $2,000 it recovers from salvage or
another insurer, and report the reserve at $8,000. The difference
would be taxable.
</P>
<P>
   But OBRA included a rule, invoked by the Blue Cross, that
granted coordination of benefits (COB) deductions to some insurers
affected by the new reporting requirement.
</P>
<P>
   Under COB, two insurance companies insuring the same patient
coordinate the benefits they pay. This is a common situation in
households with two working parents whose dependents are insured by
different companies through the parents' employers.
</P>
<P>
   COB designates the company insuring the parent with the earliest
birth date in the year as the primary carrier, and the insurer of
the other parent as the secondary insurer. COB provides that the
primary insurer pay 80 percent of a claim and the secondary insurer
the balance.
</P>
<P>
   But Swift ruled that the Texas insurer did not qualify for the
special COB deductions. The judge also found Blue Cross could not
take deductions under alternative IRS rules known as ``safe
harbor.''
</P>
<P>
   Bromley, one of the Blue Cross attorneys, said a decision on
whether to appeal would be made later.
</P>
<P>
   First, he said, the company's tax liability under the new ruling
must be computed under Tax Court rules. ``That will take a couple
of months. So we have time before we decide,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Once a decision is entered based on Swift's opinion, either side
in the case will have 90 days to seek a review of the findings by
the U.S. Court of Appeals.
</P>
<P>
   Bromley said the ruling would set a precedent in all similar
cases unless it is overturned by the Court of Appeals or another
insurer obtains a contradictory ruling from another tax court
judge.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
