<P>
   LOST-CLIMBER (Undated) _ Three times in a row, a challenging ice
face up the southern route of a 14,000-foot peak named Cerro San
Francisco in the Andes Mountains had defeated Jim Weinman. The
32-year-old mountaineer and extreme adventurer took a fourth stab
at the glaciated summit in June. It was to be his last. By PAUL
GRONDAHL.
</P>
<P>
   CAFFEINE (Undated) _ The alarm goes off; you stumble out of bed.
And before you grab your toothbrush or let the dog out, you grab a
hot cuppa joe. It's your morning wake-up call. By midafternoon
you're restless and headachy. You grab a crisp dollar and head to
the pop machine for your ``fix.'' It's caffeine, and it seems
harmless enough (in moderation, of course). But could caffeine be
America's ``newest nicotine''? By SCOTT SIMONSON.
</P>
<P>
   FORGED-AUTOGRAPHS (San Antonio) _ Some people look at precise,
carbon-copy forgeries of famous athletes' signatures and are
astounded. Others marvel at the meticulous scientific techniques
now used by experts to determine if an autograph is authentic. But
to veteran San Antonio collector Howard O'Desky, the most amazing
aspect of the sports autograph industry is still the same as it
always was -- plain, old stupidity. By MIKE FINGER.
</P>
<P>
   ALCOHOLISM-DRUG (San Antonio) _ A study by San Antonio
researchers has found a drug used to treat nausea also can curb the
destructive cravings in the type of alcoholic whom doctors find
toughest to treat. Early-onset alcoholics _ those who became
problem drinkers before age 25 _ were able to stop drinking or
significantly cut their alcohol consumption when they took the drug
ondansetron, according to the study by University of Texas Health
Science Center scientists. By CINDY TUMIEL.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCE (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WIRED-CLOTHES (San Francisco) _ Levi Strauss hopes some people
need to be so connected they can't just be carrying their
electronic gadgets; they've got to be wearing them. The jeans maker
and the Dutch electronics company Philips NV will release a line of
jackets branded IDC+. The jackets, which will only be available in
Europe and set the wearer back $600 to $900, come equipped with a
mobile phone and MP3 player, a remote control device plus ear gear
and a microphone integrated into the collar. By VICTORIA COLLIVER.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-EMPLOYMENT (San Antonio) _ It's a familiar story:
Businesses are having a tough time locating workers because the
booming economy has slashed unemployment. So they're recruiting
them from far away and paying higher wages. Except in this case,
it's taking place in Mexico. By BILL DAY.
</P>
