<HEADER>
A9834 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN24-CO     08-23 0542
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JOEMURRAY-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Wash day was hard work in rural Georgia in the '30
 &HT;    (''Dispatches from Dreamsville'' is an occasional series in
which readers share with Cox Newspapers senior writer Joe Murray
their memories of growing up in small-town America. Back then, or
at least the way we remember it, life was like a dream.)
 &HT;    By Eloise Ozburn Riner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox Newspapers
<TEXT>
<P>
   When I was a little girl during the '30s, we lived on a farm in
rural Georgia and had no electricity.
</P>
<P>
   All chores had to be done by hand, and every Monday that it
wasn't raining was wash day.
</P>
<P>
   After Mom cooked a hearty breakfast of homemade biscuits,
country fried ham or sausage, gravy, grits, eggs and coffee for the
family, her wash day would get under way.
</P>
<P>
   My three brothers had the job of filling all of the galvanized
wash tubs and iron wash pots with water drawn from the well and
rounding up firewood to heat water in the iron pots.
</P>
<P>
   All beds were stripped, and the bedcovers hung outside for a
full day of sunshine.
</P>
<P>
   Washing for five children and two adults was hard work. Usually,
the wife of one of the laborers on the farm would help her.
</P>
<P>
   The clothes were sorted as to white and colored. A flat stick
was used to beat the very dirty clothes which had been worn by the
men working in the fields.
</P>
<P>
   The clothes were first scrubbed on a rub board and then boiled
in the wash pots. Homemade lye soap was added.
</P>
<P>
   Next, using the flat sticks, the clothes were carefully lifted
out of the boiling water and into buckets to be carried to the tubs
for a series of rinsing.
</P>
<P>
   After rinsing, the clothes had to be rung by hand, then put into
buckets and taken to the clothes lines where they were hung out to
dry.
</P>
<P>
   On wash day, every clothesline was used and even some low tree
branches. The whole yard was filled with clothes flapping in the
breeze.
</P>
<P>
   On wash day, everybody had to watch the clouds. In case of a
quick shower, we all had to start grabbing the clothes off the
lines and trees.
</P>
<P>
   After they had dried, the next chore was to bring in the clothes
and make the beds. The fresh sheets smelled wonderful after being
in the sun all day.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the clothes could be folded and put away, but a majority
of them had to be starched and ironed. You cooked the starch with
water and then strained it through a flour sack to remove the
lumps. Clothes were dipped into the starch and hung out to dry.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the ironing. The clothes were sprinkled with water,
rolled up and placed in a flour sack to soak. Flat irons had to be
heated on a stove or fireplace.
</P>
<P>
   Ironing was practically a whole day's work in itself, and the
laborer's wife would take a share of the ironing to her house to
finish when she went home that night.
</P>
<P>
   A few years later electricity made its way through rural
Georgia, and wash day was never the same.
</P>
<P>
   (Eloise Ozburn Riner lives in Chamblee, Ga.)
</P>
<P>
   If you have a story to share, send it to ``Dispatches from
Dreamsville,'' c/o Joe Murray, Cox Newspapers, P.O. Box 151108,
Lufkin, Texas, 75915; email, jmurray(at)txucom.net. If your article
is used, you will receive $25.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-00 1134EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000823.0068 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 11:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9835 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k BC-KELSO-COLUMN24-COX     08-23 1633
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELSO-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Rafter will rely on raw skills for trek across Atlantic
 &HT;    By John Kelso
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Steve Kurachi says the jerky he made out of cat roadkill wasn't
all that tasty. But it wasn't the dead cat's fault. Steve figures
he left the cat meat in the freezer way too long.
</P>
<P>
   ``The best way to describe it is, you're eating a litter box,''
Steve said, describing the taste of freezer-burned cat. So how
about dog? He's had that, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dog has a unique flavor; you can't describe it unless you've
eaten it,'' says Steve, 48, a matter-of-fact, and yes, seemingly
sane, single Austin, Texas working man who has a drain- and
sewer-cleaning business called Econo-Rooter.
</P>
<P>
   The rat he ate disappointed Steve because it was so
unremarkable. ``The rats taste like beef. I thought it would be a
unique flavor, but it was just like beef.''
</P>
<P>
   Steve has a logical reason for his unusual dining approach. ``I
wanted to get over the psychological hang-ups of eating certain
foods,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That skill will come in handy. In late November or early
December, Steve plans to launch a small, homemade 12-foot-by-5-foot
Fiberglas and polyurethane foam raft in the Atlantic Ocean off the
Canary Islands, near -- orthwest Africa, and take off across the
Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   He figures he'll be at sea for four months, and he's not taking
any food. He's planning on catching and eating raw fish. And
drinking fish juice and rainwater.
</P>
<P>
   He'll have a small sail to help propel the raft. But he'll be
depending on the winds and the currents to carry him from the
Canaries past Antigua, south of Jamaica, then north to Corpus
Christi, Texas _ a total of 5,000 miles, Steve estimates. Steve
plans to make the trip without making landfall.
</P>
<P>
   Steve is taking basic fishing gear _ line and hooks _ and he'll
have a trap for bait fish. But he won't be carrying ice or other
space-consuming amenities. His living space will be a
4-foot-by-6-foot rectangular hole, a foot deep, built into the
floor of the raft. He'll stretch a pup tent tarp over himself to
get out of the sun. And forget cooking materials. He's not taking
any. He'll be cutting up the fish and downing it raw or dried.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just eat what you can eat and dry the rest,'' Steve said.
And the guy doesn't even particularly like sashimi.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least with sashimi, you've got some wasabi to go with it,''
said Steve, speaking of the hot, green Japanese mustard. But he is
taking along five gallons of water. ``I have to take my blood
pressure medication,'' Steve explained of the 5-gallon water
supply. Six months ago, he had a mini-stroke.
</P>
<P>
   He'll also be taking a small reverse osmosis pump, a unit that
turns seawater into small amounts of fresh water _ in case he comes
up short of rain or fish juice.
</P>
<P>
   Steve says his main concerns are getting flipped over by storms
and going six weeks without vitamin C, which could cause scurvy.
Instead of carrying vitamin C on the raft, he'll dangle a rope in
the water and grow it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would take about six weeks for the algae to start growing
on a polypropylene rope,'' Steve said. So he'll get his vitamin C
fix by eating algae.
</P>
<P>
   Although Steve Kurachi is not like most of us, he certainly
isn't a survivalist nut in the camouflage-wearing sense of the
word. He drives around town in a plain vanilla 1979 GMC van,
answering his cell phone with the words ``Econo-Rooter,'' then
going to people's homes to unclog their plumbing. He's good with
tools. He's building his raft in a friend's back yard in North
Austin. He works with the Boy Scouts. He's even shared his cat
jerky with them. Some kids have all the luck.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me, a survivalist would be a person who takes a drive at
night when it's cold and puts an extra blanket and a jacket in the
back seat,'' Steve said. ``I think people who wear camouflage and
get guns and shoot in the woods, that's crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a pistol,'' said Mike Metschan, leader of Austin Boy
Scout Troop 35, who runs the troop with Steve's help. ``He will
keep crickets in his freezer. You never know when you might need a
cricket to eat. But he's a great guy. He's not overly aggressive.
He's mild-mannered. He would be great on that survival show that
was on TV. If we're going camping, especially if it's freezing,
Steve will be there. He's in his element.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no Survivalists' League covered by writers who keep
statistics. So much of this material can't be documented. But Steve
says the raft trip won't be his first venture into roughing it in
spectacular fashion.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Steve says, he took off across the Atlantic Ocean from
the Canary Islands headed for Antigua on nine king-size,
air-inflated water-bed mattresses lashed together with rope. He
wanted to cross the ocean in a craft made out of common materials.
He says he made it 2,700 miles in two months before he gave up
about 350 miles northeast of Antigua. He had no sail. He depended
on Mother Nature to get him where he wanted to go.
</P>
<P>
   He took some food on that trip, but nothing elaborate. His daily
diet consisted of two large crackers, some bean paste and
Army-issue dessert MREs (meals ready to eat) _ ``like granola bars,
oatmeal bars and Corn Flake bars.'' But it was no picnic.
</P>
<P>
   ``Five of the nine water-bed mattresses popped,'' Steve said.
The sun and the elements got to them. Worrying about the last four
popping got to Steve. ``I was really stressed every time I lost a
mattress, so I only slept three hours a night,'' he said. ``I just
couldn't sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there were those tight quarters. Steve was confined to one
of the water-bed mattresses. The others were along for flotation.
So he slept on top of one mattress _ carefully.
</P>
<P>
   ``A water-bed mattress is flat, but when it's inflated, it's
like a balloon _ oval,'' Steve said. ``So if you roll one way or
another, you better be holding on to something or you'll roll off
into the water. I didn't roll off, but I was thrown off one night.
Around 1 in the morning, I was hit by a wave that was particularly
large.''
</P>
<P>
   He says he woke up about 5 feet in the air, upside down above
the water-bed mattress, then ended up in the drink. ``I slept at
night with my arms under the ropes to hold on after that,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Six weeks out, a large seabird flew by and tried unsuccessfully
to land on one of the mattresses, striking terror in Steve. ``I was
afraid of his talons. So I was flapping a towel and yelling at him
for an hour or two.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there were the large fish _ he figures they were 25- to
35-pound mahi-mahi, although he never saw them _ that kept ramming
his craft at night. They were chasing bait fish under the water-bed
mattresses, and they'd end up crashing into the side of the
mattresses. ``It was like being hit by a baseball bat,'' Steve
said.
</P>
<P>
   Steve gave up the trip before he reached Antigua because he had
been praying and fasting, and he had a hunch he was supposed to
quit. So he set off his only means of communications _ an one-way
emergency signal called an Emergency Position Indicating Radio
Beacon. An Ecuadorean banana boat picked him up and took him to
Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   ``The deal is when you get picked up by a boat, you go where
they go,'' Steve said. ``I had to take a bus through the war zone
to get back.''
</P>
<P>
   So how does a person get into this sort of activity? Steve says
it was a matter of mouthing off when he was a student at McCallum
High School. ``When I was in high school, I used to tell people I
was going to row across the Atlantic. When I got to be 21, I
realized I was living my life as a blowhard. And that's when I
decided to build a boat and try.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1977, Steve says, he tried to row from Wilmington, N.C., to
England in a 16-foot homemade dory. He gave up when he was blown
300 miles off course by a late winter storm. But he says he made it
1,250 miles to a position northeast of Bermuda before he stopped
rowing _ after 49 days at sea.
</P>
<P>
   Three years later, Steve set off rowing in another small
homemade dory from St. John's, Newfoundland, bound for England
again. He didn't make it that time, either. The trip lasted a
couple of weeks before he called it quits after 250 miles. ``I
wasn't prepared for the extreme cold. I spent two months in bed and
a month on crutches because of my feet freezing.''
</P>
<P>
   Compared to the water-bed mattress adventure, Steve figures his
upcoming raft journey will be a piece of cake. ``I consider this
trip like going in a Cadillac instead of a Volkswagen, 'cause I've
got a place where I can lie down flat,'' Steve said. Instead of an
awkward-shaped, blown-up water-bed mattress, he'll be reclining on
a comparatively luxurious 2-foot-by-6-foot sheet of plywood.
</P>
<P>
   To get ready for the feel of it, Steve has been practicing
sleeping on hard surfaces. ``I have spent the last year sleeping
either on the floor or on a piece of plywood,'' he said. ``I have a
piece of plywood under the sheet on my bed. I've gotten to where I
like it. It looks like a normal bed, and I've gotten to where I
throw things on the bed and it goes clunk. I've got to stop that.''
</P>
<P>
   It will get boring out there, Steve admits. But there are mental
games you can play to keep your mind occupied. On the water-bed
mattress trip, Steve says, he built a house from the ground up in
his mind. ``I had to think of the steel and foundation and the
plumbing that went into it, because I didn't have any paper to
write on,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This time he's taking a laptop computer powered by a couple of
marine gel batteries, so he can work on the book on survival he's
writing. It should be one helluva book.
</P>
<P>
   John Kelso can be reached at 445-3606 or at
jkelso(at)statesman.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
