<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Catching summer's last flight
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   My friend Monique has misplaced July. ``What happened to it?''
she demanded.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the first day I've actually spent lounging at the
pool,'' another friend, Debbie, lamented.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we should have six months of summer, and six months of
school,'' my son proposed, counting off the days _ fewer now than
fingers _ till school starts.
</P>
<P>
   Seems like everybody's singing 'em, those end-of-summertime
blues. ``We did a lot, but there was no summer,'' Debbie said.
``Where did it all go?''
</P>
<P>
   It's not the Carnival-Cruise-not-taken that we're mourning. It's
the unstructured time. The time to goof off, to sleep in, to be
lazy.
</P>
<P>
   When we think of the way summer has become, the old lyrics,
``Those lazy, crazy, hazy days of summer,'' seem as quaint as that
maddening melody that reminds you of a polka band on uppers.
</P>
<P>
   Monique frets that she may have misplaced summer altogether.
``Was it really hot? Did I miss it?'' she asked. ``Because if I
did, I'm going to be really mad.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone assured her that she didn't miss the blistering heat _
there wasn't any, to speak of _ but she still knows that she missed
something: ``If I'm going to relax, it's going to be in the
summertime.'' This summer, it didn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   A moment ago it was May, and summer stretched before us,
tempting us like a brand-new book just waiting to cracked. Now,
August is flickering like the last fireflies.
</P>
<P>
   When we were kids, we faced each day like a downhill bike ride.
You careened through the day _ wheeeee! _ letting it take you where
it may: swimming at Crestwood pool, or finding the best hiding spot
during nightly games of hide-and-seek.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with both parents working, many of us are such
schedule-a-holics we feel compelled to plan and schedule our down
time _ which tends to take some of the spontaneity, not to mention
the relaxation, out of it.
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, a Sunday with no plans loomed on the calendar like
a mirage in the desert. A free day!
</P>
<P>
   With might and main, I resisted the urge to fill it. And I was
rewarded when a friend called out of the blue and wanted to see
West Side Story .
</P>
<P>
   My regrets for the summer are not for the plans I didn't make,
but for such unplanned indulgences.
</P>
<P>
   I regret that we didn't eat outside enough, didn't swat enough
flies while eating corn off the cob.
</P>
<P>
   I regret that the kids didn't run through the sprinkler enough,
didn't splash around enough in the backyard pool.
</P>
<P>
   I regret that we didn't take enough evening strolls, enough bike
rides along the river.
</P>
<P>
   I don't want summer to end. Not until I've had my fill of BLTs,
of popsicles melted on the sidewalk, of drives on a country road
with the windows down in the long twilight. I want more yard
parties, more picnics, more time on the backyard chair-swing,
watching the kids play.
</P>
<P>
   As summer steals away from us, we try to wrest it back, try to
cram in as many poolside afternoons and drive-in evenings as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of the summer, Debbie made a ``fun things to
do'' calendar. Now, frantically trying to check things off the
list, she finds herself haranguing the kids, ``Want to go out and
do something fun?''
</P>
<P>
   ``How about we go home and relax?'' her son asked.
</P>
<P>
   What a concept. Kids know, far better than we do, that there
ain't no cure for the end-of-summertime blues.
</P>
<P>
   Except, perhaps, just letting things happen.
</P>
<P>
   Contact Mary McCarty by e-mail at marymccarty(at)coxohio.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
