<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: Nation needs a uniform ruling on sticky issue of
affirmative action
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's neither fair nor constitutional when some American schools
can use race in school admissions and other schools cannot use
race.
</P>
<P>
   Only the U.S. Supreme Court can clear up this mess. The justices
should stop ducking lower court decisions striking down affirmative
action practices in America's schools.
</P>
<P>
   The latest monkey wrench to be tossed into the America's
affirmative action machinery came from a Georgia federal district
court ruling that said the University of Georgia's affirmative
action admission policy was unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   The university, which had been making race-based admission
decisions to boost racial diversity on its campus, now has stopped
the practice.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, the university's regents are appealing the decision
to the 11th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals. If the 11th circuit
upholds Judge Avant Edenfield's decision, all schools in Alabama,
Florida and Georgia will have to use race-free rules in admissions.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to the club.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, the 5th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals struck down a
race-based admission policy once used by the University of Texas
Law School to increase black and Hispanic enrollment. The 5th
circuit court ruled that the law school's admission policy was
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Regrettably, the U.S. Supreme Court refused to review the 5th
circuit's ruling. Therefore, all the colleges and universities in
Texas, Mississippi and Louisiana had to stop using affirmative
action policies that used race as a factor for admission.
</P>
<P>
   These schools are at a disadvantage when they compete for
minority students who can accept race-based scholarships and
admissions from schools not under a court order.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the 1st Circuit Court of Appeals ruled that the
Boston Latin School's race-based affirmative action program was
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Boston school board members first announced that they would
appeal the ruling to the Supreme Court. Then representatives of the
NAACP and other civil rights groups pleaded for the board members
to rescind their decision to appeal the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   The civil rights leaders argued that a Supreme Court ruling
against the celebrated school could shut down all race-based
affirmative action programs throughout the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Boston Latin School officials did an about-face. They voted
unanimously to live with the 1st Circuit Court decision.
</P>
<P>
   The citizens of California can't complain that their colleges
and universities cannot compete on a level playing field for
minority students. They gave referendum approval to Proposition
209, an anti-affirmative action proposal that forbids race-based
admission decisions for California colleges.
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court rejected hearing a challenge to Proposition
209, which prohibits discrimination in state programs based on
``race, sex, color, ethnicity or national origin,'' language that
tracks the wording used in the Civil Rights Act.
</P>
<P>
   The constitutional provision that requires ``equal protection of
the laws'' was used to abolish the South's Jim Crow laws that gave
race-based preference to white people. Now lower-court rulings
across the nation are using the same arguments to strike down
race-based affirmative action programs.
</P>
<P>
   It should be a given that colleges across America need to have
diverse student bodies that reflect the society they serve.
</P>
<P>
   Colleges in Texas and California have shown that extra effort
without using race as a factor can boost minority enrollment.
</P>
<P>
   It remains unfair, however, for colleges to compete for racial
and gender diversity in their schools while using different rules.
The Supreme Court needs to settle this matter.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is the Senior Editor of the Waco (Texas)
Tribune. E-mail: RNethaway(at)wacotrib.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
