 &HT;    EDS: FILE 1 OF 2
 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com. Please include your name and hometown.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Much has been written about the Confederate submarine Hunley,
which was raised recently from Charleston harbor. Where did it get
its name?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Hunley took its name from Horace Lawson Hunley of New
Orleans, who gave not only his name, but also his fortune and life,
to the world's first successful wartime submarine.
</P>
<P>
   Hunley was deputy collector of Customs in New Orleans, as well
as a wealthy lawyer, planter, merchant and legislator. As the Web
site of the organization Friends of the Hunley explains, in the
early months of the Civil War he had realized the importance of
keeping the supply lines with Europe open ``in a way which few in
the new Confederacy understood.''
</P>
<P>
   By the late fall of 1861, Horace Hunley joined two inventors,
James McClintock and Baxter Watson, to begin construction of a
vessel that would travel underwater. In July 1863, the inventors'
third ``submarine boat'' was under construction. It would be named
the H.L. Hunley.
</P>
<P>
   Horace Hunley died when the submarine named for him was trapped
accidentally on the bottom of Charleston harbor on Oct. 15, 1863.
It was one of several times the sub sank. The final time was on
Feb. 17, his second tour was with the Marines).
</P>
<P>
   John Chafee (R-R.I.), one of two senators to die during the
current Congress, was a Marine veteran of World War II and the
Korean War.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I understand that Boy Scouts participating in opening
ceremonies at the Democratic National Convention were booed and
heckled. True? If so, what were the circumstances?
</P>
<P>
   A: As reported by the Los Angeles Times, the scouts were booed
by some of the 434 members of the California delegates while they
were leading the conventioneers in the Pledge of Allegiance.
</P>
<P>
   The reason: The Boy Scouts don't allow openly gay leaders, and
their presence onstage didn't sit well with some of the gay and
lesbian delegates. ``It's such an affront,'' said Assemblywoman
Carole Midgen of San Francisco. ``Wer Tucson, Ariz., where it had
been since retirement in September 1946.
</P>
<P>
   Information online: www.wpafb.af.mil/museum/.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
