<SLUG> BC-SURVIVOR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 -GUIDE23-COX &HT;    Castaway clinches $1 million on one last night of intrigue
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Tonight's two-hour ``Survivor'' finale beginning at 8 will have
a different format from the first 12 episodes, according to CBS.
</P>
<P>
   First, there will be no reward challenges, the contests that
have been held for a night on a luxury yacht, a phone call home or
a slice of pizza.
</P>
<P>
   The four remaining players will compete for an immunity
challenge and then there will be a tribal council vote, eliminating
one.
</P>
<P>
   If there is a 2-2 tie vote (which has been rumored, but CBS
would not confirm), there will be no re-vote. In a tie, the person
who has accumulated the most negative votes in all tribal councils
will be eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   Then there will be an immunity challenge among the three final
players, followed by another tribal council.
</P>
<P>
   One of the immunity challenges is reportedly a trivia contest
about the other players.
</P>
<P>
   At that point, there will be two finalists. The last seven
players voted off the island will form a jury, and they will vote
who will be the winner of the $1 million prize. The final two will
present arguments as to why they should win.
</P>
<P>
   After the two-hour finale, CBS will air a one-hour live special,
``Survivor: The Reunion,'' with all 16 castaways in a Los Angeles
studio talking about the show. Bryant Gumbel hosts.
</P>
<P>
   _ Phil Kloer
</P>
<P>
   ON TV
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor''
</P>
<P>
   8 tonight on CBS
</P>
<P>
   (8149).
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor:
</P>
<P>
   The Reunion''
</P>
<P>
   10 tonight on CBS (7656).
</P>
