 &HT;    Q &AMP; A ON THE NEWS
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q: What state has been the birthplace of the most presidents? In
what states have no presidents been born?
</P>
<P>
   A: No. 1 is Virginia, birthplace of George Washington, Thomas
Jefferson, James Madison, James Monroe, William Henry Harrison,
John Tyler, Zachary Taylor and Woodrow Wilson.
</P>
<P>
   States where no presidents have been born: Alabama, Alaska,
Arizona, Colorado, Connecticut, Delaware, Florida, Hawaii, Idaho,
Indiana, Kansas, Louisiana, Maine, Maryland, Michigan, Minnesota,
Mississippi, Montana, Nevada, New Mexico, North Dakota, Oklahoma,
Oregon, Rhode Island, South Dakota, Tennessee, Utah, Washington,
West Virginia, Wisconsin and Wyoming.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When all was said and done, was there a profit or loss in the
Atlanta Olympics?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Atlanta Olympics broke even and the Atlanta Committee for
the Olympic Games dissolved last year. Although Olympics organizers
originally had projected a $150 million surplus, much of it to fund
amateur athletics in the city, they failed to meet that goal. In
the end, they raised and spent $1.7 billion in private funds to
stage the Games.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I recently turned 50 and immediately thereafter received an
application from AARP. Where did they get my name?
</P>
<P>
   A: AARP acquires names for promotional mailings from various
sources, including public records and large compiled lists of
people believed to be at least 50, a spokeswoman for the
organization told Q&AMP;A. Such lists include, but aren't limited to,
names of magazine subscribers, mail order catalog buyers, survey
respondents, and donors to charities. Public records are the ones
most likely to have a person's age recorded, she added.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Do you know anything about the Hughes Glomar Explorer? It was
a ship financed by Howard Hughes that attempted to raise a sunken
Soviet submarine in, as I recall, the late '60s. Did anyone
consider using it to attempt to rescue the Russians trapped aboard
the submarine Kursk?
</P>
<P>
   A: While the subject of the Glomar Explorer came up in a Defense
Department briefing Aug. 16, nothing conclusive was determined
about its whereabouts or whether it was still a functional salvage
ship.
</P>
<P>
   At last report _ and that was in December 1990 _ the vessel was
among scores of rusting old ships mothballed in a ``ghost fleet''
in an inland bay northeast of San Francisco. If it's still there,
there would have been no way to move it to the Barents Sea in time
to have helped with the Kursk disaster, even if it had been in good
enough shape to be useful.
</P>
<P>
   The Glomar Explorer dates to the cloak-and-dagger era between
the United States and the Soviet Union. It was commissioned in 1973
by the CIA with a cover story that its purpose was to seek undersea
mineral deposits. It was learned later that the ship actually was
designed and built to search for a sunken Soviet submarine off
Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Glomar Explorer found its quarry, an accident
during the lifting operation in 1975 caused the hulk of the Russian
sub to break apart, resulting in the loss of a critical portion of
the boat, its nuclear missiles and codes.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What has become of Leona Helmsley, the so-called ``queen of
mean,'' since she got out of prison? Is she still living?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, she's still living. The latest news in the life of the
80-year-old Helmsley, as reported last month by the New York Post,
is that she's planning to marry. Her beau is said to be Roger
Watkins, 50, a project manager with a New York
construction-management and engineering firm.
</P>
<P>
   Helmsley has been married three times, while Watkins has been
married twice. Her last husband, Harry Helmsley, a billionaire New
York real estate developer, died in 1997. He had numerous hotels
whose advertising featured his wife as a ``queen.''
</P>
<P>
   Leona Helmsley was indicted and convicted of tax fraud in 1989,
and served 21 months in prison. It was during her 25-year marriage
to Harry Helmsley that her temper, tax-cheating and knack for
searing, headline-grabbing lines like ``only little people pay
taxes,'' earned her the moniker ``queen of mean.'' It was a title
``she has relished,'' according to the Post report.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In all the reporting about the West Nile virus, I haven't
seen any mention of the symptoms. What are they? And is it fatal to
humans?
</P>
<P>
   A: Most people infected with West Nile virus will have no
symptoms or may have a mild flu-like illness with a fever, headache
and body aches before they recover, according to the Public Health
Division of the Georgia Department of Human Resources.
</P>
<P>
   In some individuals, particularly the elderly, the virus can
cause a serious illness called encephalitis, which is an
inflammation of the brain. Symptoms of encephalitis may include
high fever, severe headache, nausea, stiff neck, confusion, muscle
weakness, coma and _only in rare cases _ death.
</P>
<P>
   Symptoms usually occur five to 15 days after the bite of an
infected mosquito. There's no specific treatment, medication or
cure for illnesses caused by West Nile virus. And there's no
vaccine to protect humans or animals against West Nile virus
infection.
</P>
<P>
   Information online:
www.ph.dhr.state.ga.us/epi/news/resources/westnile-info.shtml.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It was reported that North Korea is one of seven countries
branded by the U.S. State Department as a sponsor of terrorism.
What are the other six?
</P>
<P>
   A: Iran, Iraq, Libya, Syria, Sudan and Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What will become of the six-million-plus tires that have been
recalled as being unsafe?
</P>
<P>
   A: They will be disposed of ``according to the applicable laws
and in an environmentally sound manner,'' said Walt Sharp of
Bridgestone/Firestone Inc. He didn't elaborate, but noted that
there are many uses for used tires, including recycling into new
tires.
</P>
<P>
   Q: During the Republican National Convention, Tom Brokaw
interviewed someone who referred to ``that famous 40th birthday
party'' of George W. Bush's, after which Bush decided to quit
drinking. If the birthday party was so famous, why have we never
heard about it?
</P>
<P>
   A: There's no secrecy involved. Bush, 54, has often told of how
he quit drinking after his 40th birthday, and it has been widely
reported. Just last month, for instance, the New York Times
mentioned the party in a lengthy front-page article titled ``How
Bush Came to Tame His Inner Scamp.''
</P>
<P>
   As reported, George and Laura Bush went with a half-dozen
friends in July 1986 to celebrate their collective 40th birthdays
at the Broadmoor resort in Colorado. There was one evening when
they all stayed up late, drinking a bit too merrily.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, Bush has recalled, he woke up feeling
befuddled, and quietly resolved that he would never touch alcohol
again. Friends say he told nobody, not even his wife, until weeks
after their return to their home in Midland, Texas. He simply drank
sodas instead of beers, and it was many weeks later that he finally
explained to his friends that he had given up liquor. He also has
credited a conversation with Rev. Billy Graham as a factor in his
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Last January, Bush once again publicly acknowledged his
hard-drinking past in a session with a group of young people at
Teen Challenges of the Midlands, a drug-treatment facility near Des
Moines, Iowa. ``I'm on a walk. And it's a never-ending walk as far
as I'm concerned. . . . I used to drink too much and I quit
drinking. I want you to know that your life's walk is shared by a
lot of other people, even some who wear suits.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush, incidentally, says he never considered himself an
alcoholic.
</P>
<P>
   END
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
