<TEXT>
<P>
   Have a question about the news? Colin Bessonette will try to get
an answer. Call 404-222-2002, or write him at The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution, P.O. Box 4689, Atlanta, Ga. 30302, or e-mail
him at q&AMP;a(at)ajc.com. Please include your name and hometown.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Much has been written about the Confederate submarine Hunley,
which was raised recently from Charleston harbor. Where did it get
its name?
</P>
<P>
   A: The Hunley took its name from Horace Lawson Hunley of New
Orleans, who gave not only his name, but also his fortune and life,
to the world's first successful wartime submarine.
</P>
<P>
   Hunley was deputy collector of Customs in New Orleans, as well
as a wealthy lawyer, planter, merchant and legislator. As the Web
site of the organization Friends of the Hunley explains, in the
early months of the Civil War he had realized the importance of
keeping the supply lines with Europe open ``in a way which few in
the new Confederacy understood.''
</P>
<P>
   By the late fall of 1861, Horace Hunley joined two inventors,
James McClintock and Baxter Watson, to begin construction of a
vessel that would travel underwater. In July 1863, the inventors'
third ``submarine boat'' was under construction. It would be named
the H.L. Hunley.
</P>
<P>
   Horace Hunley died when the submarine named for him was trapped
accidentally on the bottom of Charleston harbor on Oct. 15, 1863.
It was one of several times the sub sank. The final time was on
Feb. 17, 1864, when it rammed the federal sloop-of-war USS
Housatonic, which was blockading the harbor. All nine members of
the Hunley's crew died. Five Union sailors aboard the Housatonic
also died.
</P>
<P>
   Information online: www.hunley.org.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I understand there's a Web site that will set your computer
time automatically. Do you know that address?
</P>
<P>
   A: This is one of several such sites:
http://tucows.cybersouth.com/sync95.html.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Sens. Max Cleland and Bob Kerrey led a tribute to America's
veterans Wednesday at the Democratic National Convention. It was
mentioned in a TV interview that six senators served in Vietnam.
Who are the other four?
</P>
<P>
   A: In addition to Democrats Cleland of Georgia and Kerrey of
Nebraska, the others are Republicans Chuck Hagel of Nebraska and
John McCain of Arizona; and Democrats John Kerry of Massachusetts
and Charles Robb of Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   Q: In addition to Republican Strom Thurmond of South Carolina
and Democrat Daniel Inouye of Hawaii, are there any other current
senators who served in World War II and/or the Korean War?
</P>
<P>
   A: Yes, quite a few. These members of the current Senate served
in the military during World War II, according to Betty Koed,
assistant Senate historian: Daniel Akaka (D-Hawaii), Army; Jesse
Helms (R-N.C.), Navy; Ernest Hollings (D-S.C.), Army; Frank
Lautenberg (D-N.J.), Army; Daniel Patrick Moynihan (D-N.Y.), Navy;
William Roth (R-Del.), Army; Ted Stevens (R-Alaska), Army Air
Corps; and John Warner (R-Va.), Navy. Inouye and Thurmond served in
the Army.
</P>
<P>
   These members served in the Korean War: Ben Nighthorse Campbell
(R-Colo.), Air Force; and Warner (his second tour was with the
Marines).
</P>
<P>
   John Chafee (R-R.I.), one of two senators to die during the
current Congress, was a Marine veteran of World War II and the
Korean War.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I understand that Boy Scouts participating in opening
ceremonies at the Democratic National Convention were booed and
heckled. True? If so, what were the circumstances?
</P>
<P>
   A: As reported by the Los Angeles Times, the scouts were booed
by some of the 434 members of the California delegates while they
were leading the conventioneers in the Pledge of Allegiance.
</P>
<P>
   The reason: The Boy Scouts don't allow openly gay leaders, and
their presence onstage didn't sit well with some of the gay and
lesbian delegates. ``It's such an affront,'' said Assemblywoman
Carole Midgen of San Francisco. ``We're going to pursue who made
this decision (to allow the scouts to participate) and why, and
make sure it doesn`t happen again.''
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Jeri Dilno, a lesbian delegate from San Diego,
disputed news reports that delegates booed the scouts. She also
told the San Diego Union-Tribune that the delegates meant no
disrespect. ``Our intent was to remain respectful and not embarrass
the young people that were up there,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Union-Tribune item, the scouts themselves
reportedly couldn't hear the booing in the noisy Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Q: It was reported several weeks ago that a Blue Hawaiian
helicopter had crashed on Maui. Was the cause ever determined?
</P>
<P>
   A: The twin-engine AS-355 tour helicopter dropped suddenly
before crashing in a remote area of Maui's Iao Valley on July 21,
killing the pilot and six tourists aboard, according to a report
issued by the National Transportation Safety Board.
</P>
<P>
   While the report didn't list an official cause, it said poor
weather conditions had been noted in the crash area. Three other
pilots from Blue Hawaiian Helicopters flying within two miles of
the accident site at the time of the crash modified their tour
routes to avoid the area because of inclement weather, the report
said.
</P>
<P>
   The helicopter involved in the crash dropped 600 feet in 19
seconds before slamming into a mountainside, the NTSB report said.
Gilbert Dela Cruz, manager of Rotor Wing Hawaii, a Honolulu repair
company, told the Associated Press that a rapid drop is not
uncommon. He said that if a pilot saw a bank of clouds, he might
want to ``get it down and dive.''
</P>
<P>
   Weather is significant in helicopter crashes, he said, adding
that an area can appear to be open, but winds can move clouds
quickly in the mountains.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I read that Savannah, Ga., was the birthplace of the cotton
gin. But when I was growing up in New Haven, Conn., I remember
being told by teachers and my family that Eli Whitney invented it
there. Can you clarify?
</P>
<P>
   A: The first of Whitney's cotton gins was developed in Savannah.
He had gone there in 1792 from New Haven, after graduating from
Yale, to teach and study law, but found on arrival that someone
else had taken the teaching job he expected to get. He then met
Catherine Littlefield Greene, widow of Revolutionary War hero
Nathaniel Greene, who invited him to be her guest while he studied
law.
</P>
<P>
   According to the story, guests were discussing greenseed cotton
one evening and said they couldn't grow it profitably because of
the time it took to clean. Knowing that Whitney possessed
impressive inventive and mechanical skills, Mrs. Greene told the
others that he could make a machine to clean it _ and by April 1793
he had built the first cotton gin.
</P>
<P>
   By the next year, Whitney had obtained a patent for his
invention and moved back to New Haven. With the financial backing
of a partner, Phineas Miller, he began to make cotton gins.
</P>
<P>
   So while the first machine was built in Savannah, further
development was in New Haven. Other manufacturers, too, copied
Whitney's idea, so there was more than one early cotton gin.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Two U.S. aircraft dropped atomic bombs on Japan to hasten the
end of World War II. We know about the Enola Gay, its pilot, and
the location of the airplane today. What was the name of the plane
that bombed Nagasaki? Who was its pilot, and where is that plane
today?
</P>
<P>
   A: The plane was a B-29 Superfortress named Bockscar (sometimes
written as Bock's Car), but in either case the name was derived
from that of Capt. Frederick C. Bock, the plane's primary pilot.
</P>
<P>
   But Bockscar was piloted by Maj. Charles Sweeney, along with 1st
Lt. Charles D. Albury, 2nd Lt. Fred Olivi and a crew of 10 others,
when it flew from Tinian Island in the Marianas and dropped a
plutonium bomb over Nagasaki on Aug. 9, 1945.
</P>
<P>
   The plane is on display at the U.S. Air Force Museum at
Wright-Patterson Air Force Base, Dayton, Ohio. It was flown there
in September 1961 from the desert storage facility at David-Monthan
Field near Tucson, Ariz., where it had been since retirement in
September 1946.
</P>
<P>
   Information online: www.wpafb.af.mil/museum/.
</P>
<P>
   MORE
</P>
