<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-INTERNET-BONUSES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEB EXECUTIVES GARNER BIG BONUSES, SALARIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By PETER J. HOWE   
 c.2000 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Back in what now seems like another era of the Internet Age,
going to work for a dot-com company for peanuts in cash _ but piles
of stock options _ was widely seen as the quick route to
millionairehood.
</P>
<P>
   But a survey released Tuesday by PricewaterhouseCoopers
indicates that the collapse in Net and dot-com stocks seems to be
pushing companies to pay their executives more like old-economy
companies, with a somewhat bigger emphasis on salaries and cash
bonuses tied to company results.
</P>
<P>
   And in the short term, the trend is healthy for both the
companies and their stockholders, according to top analysts
withPricewaterhouseCoopers' Unifi Network, which studies executive
compensation.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to a year earlier, the most recent survey of 123
Internet companies found that the value of stock options awarded to
top company executives basically held steady, but salaries have
increased on average 9 percent and bonuses 28 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Generally speaking, the average Net chief executive officer is
making an average of $175,000 to $275,000 in salary, more at
companies with bigger market valuations, and a cash bonus of
$40,000 to $110,000. Cash pay still lags behind pay in long-term
stock options worth $250,000 to $3.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   However, the data suggest that Net companies are starting to act
a little more like their ``old economy'' cousins by increasing
their emphasis on cash pay.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companies are starting to get it: Even if you are a dot-com or
an Internet company, you've got to start acting more like a
business,'' said Edward J. Speidel, a Unifi Network director.
</P>
<P>
   For decades, shareholder advocates have decried
multimillion-dollar pay packages for executives, especially in
cases where the company's shares delivered anemic returns.
</P>
<P>
   Many have successfully pressed companies large and small to make
more executive pay in the form of stock options whose value is
directly tied to company stock performance. A typical option
package would allow an executive to buy company stock in five to 10
years at the closing price last Dec. 31, so that the more the stock
goes up, the more profit the executive can reap.
</P>
<P>
   But Internet and dot-com companies may have overdone it, the
Unifi study suggests, and begun gradually scaling back an excessive
emphasis on options.
</P>
<P>
   Since the March tech-sector rout on Wall Street, many of those
companies' stocks are ``underwater,'' or trading well below levels
at which executives can make money by exercising options to buy
stock.
</P>
<P>
   In the short term, Speidel and his colleague say, a bonus of
something like $250,000 in cash tied to specific financial results
may be a much stronger incentive for Net company executives to whip
their businesses into shape than another 10,000 stock options whose
value is uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bonuses have gotten much larger, and that's a function of the
pressure that they're feeling from shareholders to get closer to
profitability,'' Speidel said. ``If anything, from a shareholder
perspective, that's a positive sign.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides creating stronger incentives to improve company
financial performance _ hard cash instead of more uncertainly
valued stock options _ the trend could also mitigate growing
problems of ``overhang,'' or big troves of unexercised executive
stock options threatening shareholder value.
</P>
<P>
   The 123 companies include a cross-section of ``access and
infrastructure'' gear makers, companies selling Net software,
Internet content sites, and business-to-business and
business-to-consumer e-commerce sites.
</P>
<P>
   Across all companies, there was a median 23 percent stock
overhang, calculated as authorized and unexercised stock options as
a percent of total shares trading.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies reported ``overhang'' rates as high as 64
percent. A typical comparable number for a non-technology, Fortune
200 company would be in the range of 10 percent to 12 percent,
Speidel said.
</P>
<P>
   The reason this is of concern to shareholders is that, in the
case of a company with a 25 percent overhang rate, if executives
exercised all those stock options, people who now own shares would
see their effective share of ownership in the company drop by 20
percent, which presumably would drop the share price.
</P>
<P>
   No numbers for individual corporations were provided. But the
highest overhang rates, over 23 percent, were reported in
``Internet tools'' companies such as multimedia and e-mail software
and ``B-to-B'' sites.
</P>
<P>
   Across the board, compared to last year, Internet companies also
slightly increased the rate at which they gave away ownership of
the company to executives through options packages, with a median
of 8.4 percent compared to 7.3 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I were a shareholder, I'd pull out my company 10-K''
earnings report ``and proxy statement and figure out what level of
dilution might be coming from these options programs, and compare
that to the revenue growth of the company,'' Speidel said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-21-00 2010EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
