<HEADLINE>
HARD FACTS ABOUT REFERENCE SOFTWARE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By ALYSON WARD   
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Now that school has started, there's no doubt there is a
five-paragraph paper about Davy Crockett in your future. Or a
spelling bee. Or a presentation about how thermometers work.
</P>
<P>
   You need resources. You need them now. And you need them to be
reliable.
</P>
<P>
   Because a set of print encyclopedias can cost as much as $1,250
these days, software is the way to go; you can get a good
encyclopedia on CD-ROM for as little as $20 or $30.
</P>
<P>
   But which one? We were overwhelmed by the options we found on
store shelves, so we asked for advice from library specialists in
the Irving, Texas, school district. These people know what they're
talking about _ Irving ISD won the 2000 National School Library
Media Program of the Year award, which the American Association of
School Librarians presents to schools with outstanding library
media programs.
</P>
<P>
   Caroline Kienzle is the district's director of library and media
services. Kienzle, along with library systems administrator Walter
Betts, named some educational software they deem worth the
investment:
</P>
<P>
   For older students:
</P>
<P>
   A CD-ROM encyclopedia is useful for students in the upper
elementary grades through high school.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   1. World Book Millennium 2000 edition ($39.99-$85,99, depending
on whether you buy the Standard, Deluxe or Premiere edition)
</P>
<P>
   This encyclopedia offers clear explanations and well-organized
information. Articles are enhanced by videos, maps, pictures and
sounds, and a ``Surf the Millennium'' disk provides a simulated Web
site for each century of the past 1,000 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``World Book is the bedrock,'' Kienzle says. ``It's kind of the
generic encyclopedia; you can always find what you need.'' The
authority is good and the integrity is solid, she says _ you'll
never have to question World Book information.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   2. Encarta Reference Suite 2001 (Microsoft, $75-$100)
</P>
<P>
   The Encarta encyclopedia series is a pro at reference software.
Encarta was never a set of heavy books _ this company started out
in the electronic medium, but it has established itself as a major
player, comparable to the companies that have published book sets
for decades.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of multimedia attractions make the Encarta Reference Suite
a good choice, Kienzle says.
</P>
<P>
   ``Encarta is very visual,'' she says. This is where you go, she
says, when you need a picture of Martin Luther King Jr., or you
need to know what the Eiffel Tower looks like.
</P>
<P>
   The Suite includes a multimedia atlas with fantastic graphics
and loads of easily accessible information, including facts about
indigenous animals and regional music.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   3. Britannica CD 2000 Deluxe (Broderbund/Mindscape, $79.99)
</P>
<P>
   This is software designed for older students: Britannica
software is solid and complete, but the material is more difficult
to digest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is by far probably the best reference, but it's not
designed for a fifth-grader'' Kienzle says. ``It's really at a very
academic level.''
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   For younger students:
</P>
<P>
   Reference guides aren't as useful for the very young, Betts
says; they need software that is more general.
</P>
<P>
   ``For younger children _ preschool to second grade _ software is
designed to teach them how to use a computer to get the information
they need,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Below, his software suggestions:
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   4. MacMillan Dictionary for Children (MacMillan Publishing USA,
$19.99)
</P>
<P>
   This multimedia dictionary is a strong choice for younger
students, Betts says. It has 12,000 word entries accompanied by
pronunciations (it's a talking dictionary), pictures, sound effects
and word histories. The CD-ROM also features an interactive
character named Zack and educational games, including the
ever-popular hangman, that allow kids to quiz themselves. For very
young children, it's a good literacy tool, Betts says.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   5. Reader Rabbit series (The Learning Company, $19.99)
</P>
<P>
   The Reader Rabbit software series is something young students _
pre-kindergarten through second grade _ might use at school, Betts
says. The programs help kids learn math and reading (as well as
basic academic and interpersonal skills) by playing with Reader
Rabbit and his friends. Games, silly songs, lovable characters and
interactive stories keep kids interested in the activity.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   6. Millie's Math House, Sammy's Science House, Bailey's Book
House (Edmark, each $19.95)
</P>
<P>
   This series is for kids in preschool through second grade, Betts
says. The programs use games and question-and-answer activities to
teach the basics. The math program teaches counting, size and
shape, basic addition and subtraction, for example, and the science
program teaches kids about weather and plants.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-22-00 1631EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
