<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 11:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9880 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CPT-VIDEOGAMES-SHAKEO     08-23 2527
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-VIDEOGAMES-SHAKEOUT-ART-1250&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DESPITE LOSSES, ELECTRONIC ARTS BETS ON VIRTUAL FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  (ART ADV: Photos NYT 1,2 and three graphics are being sent to NYT
photo/graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights
by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In the videogame world, when players face bleak
prospects _ a hero loses ``health points,'' or a spaceship's shield
is depleted _ they have the ultimate recourse: Hit the Reset
button.
</P>
<P>
   It is an option rarely available in the business world, but
Electronic Arts, the world's leading independent game company, has
just such a fresh start in mind.
</P>
<P>
   The company, which makes dozens of sports, action-adventure and
strategy games for PCs as well as for game consoles made by Sony,
Nintendo and others, is weathering a market in great flux. Sales
have been in a lull, awaiting the full emergence of a new
generation of faster, more powerful game consoles.
</P>
<P>
   Consider the bleak outlook on July 25, when Electronic Arts
announced a fiscal first-quarter loss of more than $42 million on
revenue of $154.8 million and warned of losses nearly as great in
the second quarter. The news was in stark contrast to the company's
modest profit in last year's first quarter. And because the report
came after the stock market's close that day, most investors had no
immediate way to vent their emotions.
</P>
<P>
   The next morning, though, investors were ready to pounce _ and
they did so by bidding up the company's stock nearly 15 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Why such enthusiasm for a money-losing quarter? Evidently,
investors share the optimism of Electronic Arts' executives, who
during one of the game industry's cyclical downturns have been
spending heavily preparing for the future.
</P>
<P>
   EA has invested some $700 million on an ambitious two-prong
strategy that its president, 41-year-old John Riccitiello, asserts
will propel EA to new prominence in the video- and PC game
industry. And the intensely focused, hypercompetitive Riccitiello
says the strategy could help move games beyond their core audience
(adolescent males of all ages) to become an entertainment medium in
which people can interact with others across the globe and compete
with one another in a new generation of Internet-based games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Instead of being comatose on the couch, you'll be on the couch
role-playing, fantasizing, competing, shooting or driving,''
Riccitiello said, suggesting that the TV, connected to the Net,
will become the preferred medium for online game play.
</P>
<P>
   He even predicts that the popularity of Internet-based games
could surpass the appeal of TV programming because players will
become immersed in elaborate cyberworlds rather than merely
watching someone else's drama unfold.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'll interact with other people. You'll get to date, marry,
murder _ it's all there,'' Riccitiello said. ``By next summer,
these games will start to look like legitimate competition for
TV.''
</P>
<P>
   The next two months should give some indication of whether EA's
big bets can pay off.
</P>
<P>
   About half of EA's investment, or roughly $350 million, has been
spent developing an online gaming site called EA.com (www.ea.com),
which begins its first public tests later this week or early next
before its official debut in September. EA.com will be going up
against a handful of already well-established game sites and will
soon face additional competition from heavyweights like Sega and
Sony, both of which have major gaming portals planned.
</P>
<P>
   The online investment includes $81 million in cash and equity in
EA.com that the company gave to America Online to make EA.com the
exclusive operator of AOL's game channel. EA plans to spin off
EA.com as a tracking stock in the first half of 2001, Riccitiello
said.
</P>
<P>
   But those millions of dollars do not include the cost of adding
a proposed fourth and fifth building to the company's Silicon
Valley campus _ a proposed increase of 315,000 square feet of space
_ in part to accommodate the expected growth of EA.com. The local
government in Redwood City, Calif., has yet to approve the
expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the company has devoted three floors of an existing
building to the development of online games. In cubicles, engineers
and game writers are preparing games and setting specifications. In
a modest, early-version of the EA.com control room, two engineers
oversee large video monitors that relay traffic patterns from
several sports games EA already operates online, including the golf
games Tiger '99 and PGA Tour, of which tens of thousands of rounds
are played online each month via EA server computers.
</P>
<P>
   But online gaming is only around half the big bet. The other
half is about $350 million placed on producing games for Sony's
next console.
</P>
<P>
   In October, roughly a month after the launch of EA.com, Sony
plans to make the U.S. debut of the Playstation II videogame
console, which is already a best seller in Japan and eagerly
awaited by gamers in this country. EA has gambled heavily that the
Playstation II will be a success, surpassing the 72 million
Playstation I consoles already in use worldwide. It is, in fact,
among those predicting that sales of the new machine could
eventually exceed the 100 million mark.
</P>
<P>
   The $350 million spent developing games for the new Sony machine
is a major investment by game-industry standards. At the same time,
EA made a controversial decision not to make games for the Sega
Dreamcast introduced last year, deeming the system would not be
sufficiently popular to justify the $3 million to $4 million it
costs to develop individual games.
</P>
<P>
   The Playstation II will be a 128-bit machine, meaning its main
chip processes information 128 bits at a time _ or effectively
twice as fast as the 64-bit chip in the current market leader, the
Sony Playstation and the No. 2 machine, the Nintendo N64. The
128-bit speed is supposed to allow startling realism, as with car
racing games that appear to be TV footage.
</P>
<P>
   The losses that EA reported last month reflect the fact that,
for much of this year, the game industry in this country has been
in a lull _ awaiting not just a new version of the Playstation, but
also 128-bit machines expected next year from Microsoft and
Nintendo. While the lull is considered cyclical within the
industry, it has nonetheless slammed the revenues of videogame
companies, sent stock prices lower across the industry, and forced
considerable consolidation among smaller game developers.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as the Playstation II hits the market, the company plans
to have as many as five new games for it _ titles that include SSX
snowboard racing and Madden Football 2001. Four or five additional
new titles are in the pipeline for Christmas, which could mean that
EA may have more than half the available Playstation II titles on
the market by the holidays.
</P>
<P>
   Eventually the company hopes to corner 30 percent of the game
market for the Playstation II, compared with EA's 20 percent share
for the current Sony players.
</P>
<P>
   But Riccitiello insists that EA has not put all its eggs in the
Playstation II basket. He says the company diversified beyond
videogames in the last several years by beefing up its game
business for personal computers. The PC game category now
represents 30 percent of EA's total revenue. The PC share is up
from 15 percent a year ago, an increase attributable in part to the
success of the Sims series, made by EA's Maxis subsidiary. Players
build cities, neighborhoods and control day-to-day municipal
activities in SimCity, or even control individual characters in the
most recent game, the Sims.
</P>
<P>
   Industry analysts, however, believe that the success of the
Playstation II titles will largely determine the success of
Electronic Arts in the next two or three years.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Billy Pidgeon, an analyst with the research firm Jupiter
Communications, said that EA had emerged with a stronger market
position with each transition to a new console. ``The one thing
that could hurt them is if Playstation II doesn't do well,''
Pidgeon said, ``but that's hard to imagine.''
</P>
<P>
   But it is the Internet gambit that presents an even riskier and
more complex challenge, industry analysts say.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of playing computer and videogames online is nothing
new. In fact, online gaming is brimming with competitors, including
uproar.com, iWin.com, Zone.com, a site operated by Microsoft, and
WON.net, which has an extensive following. These, like at least the
initial version of EA.com, are meant for use with PCs. And some
analysts say EA will need to demonstrate it can compete in this
league.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Kasavin, senior editor at Gamespot.com, an online
publication about electronic games, said that so far, EA's online
offerings, including a medieval, role-playing fantasy world called
Ultima Online, had been harder to use than many of its competitors'
services.
</P>
<P>
   But David Cole, an industry analyst and president of DFC
Intelligence, a San Diego market research firm, said the online
game market was still too new and unproven to predict winners and
losers. ``Right now, the online gaming market is fairly spread
out,'' he said. ``There is no dominant player.''
</P>
<P>
   Cole said that Electronic Arts had put EA.com in a good position
by aligning it with with AOL. ``The key to online games is
distribution,'' he said, ``and with AOL they have the key
distribution point.''
</P>
<P>
   Besides operating as a separate Web site, EA.com will be the
``game channel'' on America Online, which will receive 4 percent of
the channel's revenue _ with the first $81 million in payments
already accounted for in the recent stock and cash transfer.
</P>
<P>
   Looking ahead, Riccitiello sees an expanding opportunity in more
powerful videogame consoles and PCs, as well as faster Internet
connections. He notes that people are already playing basic parlor
games and others with simple graphics and action, like pong, on
current computer-based game sites that draw between 5 million and 6
million people. More sophisticated, realistic-looking online play
could double the size of the $13 billion videogame market in the
next five years, he predicts.
</P>
<P>
   The popularity ``is on a curve pointing to the sky, and the
content is miserable,'' Riccitiello said. ``EA is going to change
all that.''
</P>
<P>
   The EA.com site will begin with 50 games, which will include
basic parlor and card games, and sports titles like Running Back
Challenge, a relatively simple game in which players try to evade a
computer-operated tackler. The company concedes it will be several
months before EA.com includes more elaborate, graphics-intensive
games.
</P>
<P>
   Assuming all goes well with the initial free trial of EA.com,
Electronic Arts plans to begin charging money for some levels of
access. Some of the games will remain free. But for the more
elaborate ones, the company plans to use a subscription model,
possibly with two tiers costing $4.95 and $9.95 a month
respectively.
</P>
<P>
   Besides vying with the existing online game operators,
Electronic Arts will also be wading into online competition with
both Sony and Sega, which are also leading producers of game
software. (Nintendo, the other big console maker, also intends for
its upcoming 128-bit console, known as Dolphin, to have online
access and is exploring plans to have a gaming site.)
</P>
<P>
   The Sony Online Entertainment division operates the Station
(www.station.sony.com), a PC-based game portal offering games like
Wheel of Fortune and Jeopardy online. And the Playstation division
plans to introduce an online component for the Playstation II, once
high-speed, or broadband, connections are more widely available.
</P>
<P>
   Sega plans to open its own game site on Sept. 7. Sega's site
will be designed for use only with its Sega Dreamcast consoles. If
users commit to buying two years of Internet access from the
company's SegaNet service, for $21.95 a month, Sega will give them
Dreamcasts at no additional charge.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the intensity of the online play, the offline battle
promises to get nasty between EA and Sega.
</P>
<P>
   EA executives are predicting the Sega site will have limited
demand, since it restricts the potential audience to Dreamcast
owners. But Sega officials fire back that Electronic Arts will be
unable to offer consistently high-quality, realistic game play
because the company has no control over the type of hardware its
players will be using.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Bellfield, a spokesman for Sega of America, said he had
played early versions of EA.com in a closed beta test _ a sort of
private dress rehearsal. The ``experience is awful,'' he said. ``EA
has not been able to rectify that, because it is always dependent
on the hardware'' owned by its users, Bellfield said.
</P>
<P>
   EA executives, meanwhile, say Sega had no business exploring
their company's private beta test. ``It's like breaking into
Lockheed in the '80s, seeing the B2 bomber sketched on the back of
a napkin and predicting it'll never fly,'' said Jeff Brown, an EA
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   He contends that Sega has handcuffed itself by dedicating its
online play to its own hardware. ``Building a site that is tied to
a poor-selling console starts with a tremendous handicap _ they are
building for a limited audience,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The sniping no doubt traces to EA's decision not to develop
games for the 128-bit Sega Dreamcast, which has had sales of 2
million consoles in the United States since its introduction a year
ago, and 5.5 million worldwide.
</P>
<P>
   In the fall of 2001, Nintendo is expected to introduce Dolphin,
while Microsoft plans to jump into the fray with its 128-bit
console, the X-Box, around the same time. Riccitiello predicted
those companies could each sell 50 to 60 million consoles, and he
said EA was discussing with Microsoft and Nintendo whether to
produce games for their new machines. (Nintendo has sold about 28
million N64 consoles worldwide).
</P>
<P>
   People close to Electronic Arts expect the company to support
those platforms, and not only because they could generate
significant sales. If Nintendo and Microsoft do not thrive, Sony
could end up with no viable competition for the Playstation II,
which in turn could allow Sony to charge higher licensing rates to
videogame makers like EA that make software for its console.
</P>
<P>
   And over the long haul, healthy competition could stimulate
continued technological improvement in the machines _ which,
combined with high-speed Internet connections, could bring ever
more lifelike online play. Or so Riccitiello hopes.
</P>
<P>
   He likes to describe a day, not too far in the future, when
instead of tuning in to ABC or NBC, couch potatoes will turn to EA.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe, based on a mountain of evidence, that if we can
create a sports game that also is a place for you to live 24 hours
a day, seven days a week, you might actually have a better life in
cyberspace,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And if that happens, Riccitiello is betting that EA can have a
better life in cyberspace, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-20-00 1638EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
