u a BC-CPT-TECH-LEVIN22-COX &LR;      08-23 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-TECH-LEVIN22-COX </SLUG>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)  
 &HT;    CRITICS DON'T UNDERSTAND AOL MERGER, TIME WARNER CHIEF SAYS
 &HT;    By MARILYN GEEWAX
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASPEN, Colo. _ Time Warner Chairman Gerald M. Levin came out
swinging at his critics Monday, saying they don't understand the
nature of his company's proposed merger with America Online Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Regulators and consumer advocates who worry about the creation
of a new monopoly have ``such (a) misperception about what this is
about,'' Levin said at a high-tech conference here.
</P>
<P>
   The merger is not intended to create a monopoly over what
content consumers can receive, but rather to vastly expand the
choices of programming and to enhance communication, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over time, there won't be any distinction'' between television
and the Internet, he said. ``Because in fact, what we are creating
is really the first Internet-powered media-communications company
of the 21st century.''
</P>
<P>
   By this fall, federal regulators will understand that and
approve the deal, he said. ``I don't think there are any regulatory
issues,'' he said. ``There are no business overlaps'' that would
put a choke hold on consumers.
</P>
<P>
   At the annual Aspen Summit, Levin spoke on the topic of
``convergence,'' the idea that TV, telephones and the Internet are
coming together. The conference is sponsored by the Progress &AMP;
Freedom Foundation, a non-profit organization that does research on
the digital revolution.
</P>
<P>
   Levin recounted how Time-Warner began experimenting with two-way
television long ago. ``In the early '90s, I was obsessed by the
notion of interactive television,'' he said. Though those early
tests didn't pan out technologically, they ``convinced me that
interactive, digital capability will eventually be what consumers
want.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, in January 2000, he saw the chance to move toward
``convergence'' through a merger with AOL, the No.1 Internet
service provider.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very big idea,'' he said, ``a watershed,'' because it
would combine Time Warner's vast media and cable operations with
AOL's 23 million subscribers.
</P>
<P>
   Levin will become chief executive of AOL Time Warner Inc. AOL's
leader, Steve Case, will serve as chairman.
</P>
<P>
   When he first evaluated the proposal to have AOL essentially buy
Time Warner, he was befuddled because the online upstart was much
smaller in terms of revenues.
</P>
<P>
   As he studied AOL's high-flying stock price, he said he had to
ask himself: ``Is that a fluke? Is there substance to these
valuations? So I had to take a long walk in the woods to try and
figure this out.''
</P>
<P>
   When he concluded the deal made sense, ``I was affirming the
value, and the sustainability and the growth trajectory that the
Internet was going to provide.''
</P>
<P>
   Levin says he is taking a gamble, but believes he will win.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am betting my company _ a very significant company,
everything from Time Magazine to Gone with the Wind _ on this
reality of the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   (Story can end here. Optional add follows.)
</P>
<P>
   The merged company hopes to put itself at the center of the
convergence revolution with a black box about the size of a
briefcase. The box connects to a TV and a telephone line and allows
subscribers to a new service, called AOLTV, to surf the Internet
with a wireless keyboard write and send e-mail, and flash instant
messages on the same screen where they are watching television.
</P>
<P>
   This summer, AOL has been rolling out the service in eight test
markets from Baltimore to Sacramento. Within four years, nearly a
third of U.S. households will have access to interactive
television, according to projections by Jupiter Communications
Inc., a research firm.
</P>
<P>
   But critics of the merger fear that the future of
next-generation television could get locked up in one company's
hands.
</P>
<P>
   Many ``old media'' competitors, especially the Walt Disney Co.,
NBC Inc. and USA Networks Inc., have been warning the Federal
Communications Commission that AOL Time Warner would be able to use
its cable wires to force AOL TIme Warner services and programming
on captive consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Such arguments don't ``make any sense at all,'' Levin said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There has been a lot of commentary that we are going to take
Time Warner content and it's going to be exclusively available on
AOL,'' he said. But that would never happen ``because no one has a
monopoly on creativity. And the consumer is in charge, and the
consumer is going to go where there is the best material.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, AOL would never tie its online services too closely to
Time Warner because it wants to serve all Americans, whether their
neighborhoods are served by Time Warner cable or not.
</P>
<P>
   ``AOL's future, like the past and present of (Time Warner
networks) HBO, CNN, TBS, is to get on every platform possible,
whether that is cable, DSL, fixed wireless or satellite,'' Levin
said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-21-00 1757EDT &QL;
</P>
