<HEADER>
A9885 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-CPT-DOWNLOADER-FREELO     08-23 0661
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-DOWNLOADER-FREELOADERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON GNUTELLA SYSTEM, MANY TAKE FILES BUT FEW GIVE ANY BACK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By JOHN MARKOFF   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. _ Software programs like Napster and Gnutella
have achieved a reputation for fostering a communal spirit of
sharing among millions of music-loving computer users.
</P>
<P>
   The reality may be more selfish.
</P>
<P>
   Two scientists at the Xerox Palo Alto Research Center have
surveyed the behavior of anonymous music downloaders on the
Internet and have found that, rather than demonstrating a ``from
each, to each'' ethos, most Internet users are only taking files
and not giving any back to their electronic community.
</P>
<P>
   The survey of use of the Gnutella system during a 24-hour period
this month was conducted by Eytan Adar and Bernardo A. Huberman.
They said their research demonstrates that ``free riding'' is the
most common behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The result, they said, is a ``tragedy of the digital commons.''
</P>
<P>
   For one thing, if only a few users are providing files, they
would require inordinate bandwidth to meet all the requests, so the
system would be more sluggish than one where all users contributed
equally.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since files on Gnutella are treated like a public good and the
users are not charged in proportion to their use, it appears
rational for people to download music files without contributing by
making their own files accessible to other users,'' they wrote.
``Because every individual can reason this way and free ride on the
efforts of others, the whole system's performance can degrade
considerably _ which makes everyone worse off.''
</P>
<P>
   The results also indicate that Gnutella may not be immune from
the legal challenges facing the Napster service. Unlike Napster,
Gnutella has no single database under centralized control. But the
researchers found that the core users providing music through
Gnutella are a concentrated group.
</P>
<P>
   ``About 25 percent of the Gnutella users serve about 98 percent
of the files,'' said Adar, a Xerox computer scientist who
specializes in profiling the Internet. Moreover, the researchers
found that one percent _ 314 computers _of the users in their
survey provided 40 percent of all files made available during the
survey period.
</P>
<P>
   Those providing music through Gnutella are identifiable to other
users by their Internet protocol addresses, so the biggest
providers of files could potentially be made targets of a legal
action that could cripple the network.
</P>
<P>
   The Xerox survey was based on the activity of 31,395 computer
users who shared 3,019,405 files during a 24-hour period over a
weekend earlier this month. The researchers said that there was no
way to determine the precise number of Gnutella users but that they
thought they had surveyed a substantial portion of the network.
</P>
<P>
   The research paper, posted on a Xerox World Wide Web site 
(http://www.parc.xerox.com/istl/groups/iea/papers/gnutella/index.htm
 l), &QL; 
comes during a bitter legal fight between Napster, the most
prominent music-sharing system, and the record industry, which says
the system is a mass copyright infringement. A federal judge's
ruling that Napster must shut down has been temporarily set aside
by an appeals court.
</P>
<P>
   Recording industry representatives said they were studying how
to deal with the Gnutella network.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are basically analyzing it now,'' said Cary Sherman, senior
executive vice president and general counsel for the Recording
Industry Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   And the behavior of the Gnutella users, the Xerox researchers
said, could simply be an artifact of the way large groups function.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very hard to secure voluntary cooperation in very large
groups,'' said Bernardo Huberman, a physicist who is a research
fellow at the Palo Alto center. ``I don't know of a single country
in the world where taxation is voluntary.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-20-00 1717EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
