<SLUG> BC-CPT-NEW-ECON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE NEW ECONOMY: MANUFACTURING HEADED FOR THE INTERNET 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By BARNABY J. FEDER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Until recently, it was obvious which prominent Irwin Jacobs was
the business executive exemplar of the new economy. That would be
Irwin M. Jacobs, the computer scientist and electrical engineer who
founded Qualcomm in San Diego in 1985. He built it into a thriving
Fortune 500 company through pioneering innovations in cellular
communications.
</P>
<P>
   The other Irwin Jacobs, Irwin L. Jacobs, is an irrepressible
deal-maker and bargain-hunter based in Minneapolis. He became
wealthy by taking big stakes in Fortune 500 conglomerates in the
1970s and 1980s, usually with the goal of unlocking value by
breaking them up.
</P>
<P>
   New technology was never high on Irwin L.'s list of
fascinations. His effort to sell goods directly to consumers over
the Web (wgdeal.com, for ``world's greatest deal'') was a bust. The
only major business he retains from his days as a corporate raider
_ Genmar Holdings, the nation's second-largest leisure boat
manufacturer _ is in a labor-intensive segment of the economy that
has been among the slowest to invest in new technology.
</P>
<P>
   Irwin L.'s image may get a cybersheen at the end of this month,
though. That is when Genmar plans to hold an open house at its
Little Falls, Minn., factory to show off a compact, enclosed
computer-controlled manufacturing system that can be remotely
operated over the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Visitors will see 18-foot hulls _ which used to take eight hours
to produce _ pop out every 35 minutes. Pollution, waste and labor
will be sharply reduced, while quality will be so much higher that
Genmar is offering a lifetime guarantee instead of the industry
standard of five years. Genmar says the total cost is comparable to
that for boats made by conventional techniques _ and should become
lower over time.
</P>
<P>
   Time Magazine, given a preview tour and a sales pitch on how the
system could be adapted to many other products, called it ``the
revolution in a box'' and suggested it could make large centralized
factories ``obsolete.'' Bruce Bobbins, Jacob's publicist, calls the
process, known as virtual engineered composite, or VEC, ``the most
important manufacturing revolution in the past half century.'
</P>
<P>
   The technology was invented by Gene Kirila II and Robert
McCollum, two Pennsylvanians who envision scattering leased VEC
manufacturing cells around the world that would produce products
close to where they would be used. The expertise to run the systems
could reside at a central control center thanks to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs was so impressed with how well the virtual engineered
composite process had fitted Genmar's needs that he bought Pyramid
Operating Systems, the company Kirila and McCollum created in 1993
to develop VEC. Genmar's control room is hundreds of miles from
Little Falls, in Greenville, Pa., where Kirila, McCollum and an
expanding team of engineers are searching for new VEC applications.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturing experts say Jacobs would be justified in bragging
about the process at any high-technology gathering. Interest in VEC
could provide the fuel for taking Genmar public, a move Jacobs has
talked about for years.
</P>
<P>
   But Jacobs and other backers of his technology face the
temptation to oversell VEC's future. In addition to underestimating
the costs and risks other manufacturers could encounter in moving
to their new technology, proponents of the process are probably
underestimating the strengths and potential of competing
technologies.
</P>
<P>
   No wonder, as the history of robotics, machine vision and other
innovations shows, computer-based technology generally seeps,
rather than bursts, into manufacturing. The bigger the
manufacturing sector the more cautious are managers to replace
proven technologies and materials with new approaches. There is no
particular reason to believe that any of VEC's attributes,
including its ability to be controlled by remote experts via the
Internet, will change that.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to make numbers every quarter,'' said Paul Dickard, a
spokesman for Ingersoll-Rand, which has been experimenting with VEC
for several years. ``There's always the question of which quarter
you are going to sacrifice on the altar of Internet-enabled
manufacturing.''
</P>
<P>
   Internet capability is central to the vision of
virtual-engineered-composite manufacturing systems which would
serve as remote minifactories that could be set up and running
within days. But that innovation, already available in different
forms on other computerized manufacturing equipment, is only part
of what makes VEC a unique package. The other key element,
developed to keep costs down, is the use of laminated plastic skins
instead of metal as the molding frames.
</P>
<P>
   The skins are attached to supports inside the VEC cell and
composite resins are injected between them. To give the skins the
rigidity that metal would usually provide, Kirila and McCollum hit
upon the elegantly simple idea of water pressure. Before the
molding compounds are injected, the cell is sealed and the cavities
behind the skins are filled with water.
</P>
<P>
   VEC is clearly innovative enough to attract many window
shoppers, but the chances that it will lead to the wide dispersal
in manufacturing that its inventors envision are slim. Plastics
manufacturing experts say Jacobs is likely to have his hands full
simply establishing the process as a reliable system in a few
segments of industry best suited to it. Logical candidates include
other marine products like jet skis as well as bathtubs and
paneling for buildings, trucks, rail cars or specialty vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's suited for about half the volume of the plastics
composites industry,'' estimates Robert Locavara, director of
technical affairs for the Composite Fabricators Association, a
trade group for companies that make industrial components and
consumer products out of fiberglass and other plastic composites.
</P>
<P>
   That could add up to billions of dollars of production, but one
thing is for sure: even if it comes to pass, it will not happen at
Internet speed.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-20-00 1743EDT &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
