<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-COMPUTERS-CYBERSPACE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIRE-BREATHING WRITER VOWS TO FRY NET THIEVES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By PATTI HARTIGAN   
 c.2000 The Boston Globe   
<TEXT>
<P>
   By his own estimation, writer Harlan Ellison exists in a state
of smoldering animosity. He goes from zero to ballistic in about
two seconds and threatens to put ``Harlan-sized holes'' in anyone
who crosses him, especially folks who refer to him as a science
fiction writer. (For the record: He prefers the term ``imaginative
fiction.'')
</P>
<P>
   He's had it with the greasy-thumbed adolescents, the demented
fans, the human offal, the idiots, the morons, and, well, just
about everyone else on the planet. In short, the man despises most
of the human race. ``Any society that allows Pauly Shore to make a
living doesn't deserve to exist,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Angry, are we? Ellison, whose best-known short story is about a
computer that wipes out humanity, hasn't even begun.
</P>
<P>
   He hasn't even gotten to the scheming thieves, the pissant
hackers, the Napster nerds, and the unholy mooches who are pirating
his work online. ``They think they are the smartest people in the
world, like Zorro, James Bond, or Billy the Kid,'' he says, adding
a few choice descriptions that are unprintable in a family
newspaper. ``I say, `You want to be desperadoes? Well, let me take
you down.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Ellison, 66, who still writes with a manual typewriter and
doesn't know the difference between a server and a search engine,
has launched a one-man legal crusade to protect his work online.
(``Don't call me a Luddite! I'm talking to you on a telephone and
not two cups attached by a string!'') So far, his attorney has gone
after individuals and companies, including America Online, that
have allegedly distributed or aided in the illegal distribution of
his work. In June, he won a judgment against Stephen Robertson of
California, who admitted posting Ellison's stories online and
agreed to pay Ellison's legal fees.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC;  But last week, a federal judge in Los Angeles decided
against Ellison in favor of AOL, ruling that the company is
protected by the ``safe harbor'' clause of the Digital Millennium
Copyright Act, which says that Internet access providers act as
mere conduits and are not responsible for material accessed through
their service. Ellison's attorney is considering an appeal; another
case against Critical Path, which runs the news group Web site
remarq.com, is set to go to court next month.
</P>
<P>
   Ellison hardly shies away from a good court battle: He's
supplemented his income over the years with lawsuits, including a
successful case against director James Cameron for appropriating
his work in ``The Terminator.'' But the tough-talking writer who
has written episodes for ``The Twilight Zone'' and ``Star Trek'' is
less than thrilled to find himself aligned with such rock stars as
Lars Ulrich of the heavy-metal band Metallica. ``I hate their
music,'' he says of the band that is suing Napster. ``And I find it
odd that I'm in bed with Metallica, Madonna, and Dr. Dre.'' In his
mind, that scenario is akin to performing bordello gymnastics with
Richard Nixon and Mae West _ just leave it at that.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Ellison is leading the charge for the publishing industry.
So far, most of the focus on online piracy has been on the music
and the film industries and their high-profile cases against
Napster, MP3.com, and Scour. But with the growth of electronic
books, the publishing industry is beginning to take notice of
digital book piracy. The wildly popular ``Harry Potter and the
Goblet of Fire'' was available for free on the Internet within
hours of its release in the stores; works by writers ranging from
Isaac Asimov to Roger Zalazny are readily available in news groups
and on pirate Web sites. Apart from technical manuals, most of the
works offered free online fall into the science fiction _ no,
imaginative literature _ genre; the Science Fiction and Fantasy
Writers Association is supporting Ellison in his suit.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, the Association of American Publishers
launched an anti-piracy Web site and announced a strategy to combat
piracy while also promoting legal, protected books for sale online.
The book industry, which was slow to react to the Internet, was
pushed into the market when Stephen King boldly offered his story
``Riding the Bullet'' and his serial novel ``The Plant''
exclusively as e-books; illicit copies of both were available free
almost immediately after their release.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC;  But the book industry isn't necessarily going to come out
swinging like the film and music industries, which have taken
considerable heat for their anti-piracy crusades. ``We've seen the
public relations fallout, and we are trying to learn from those
experiences,'' says Allan Adler, vice president of legal and
government affairs for the publishers association.
</P>
<P>
   What does Ellison think of that wait-and-see attitude?
``Dinosaurs!'' He has other words, too, as you can well imagine.
</P>
<P>
   Ellison doesn't need to worry about PR fallout: By his very
nature, he's already a publicist's nightmare. This is, after all, a
man who once brought a gun to a story meeting (``But it wasn't
loaded'') and who stormed off the set of WBUR's ``The Connection''
in Boston because host Christopher Lydon asked him why he hated
being called a science fiction writer. (``I don't write about
bug-eyed ants or Godzilla!'') Ellison even rejects the word
curmudgeon because it implies a sort of sweet irascibility; he
prefers to be described as a pain in a posterior body part.
</P>
<P>
   Angry? ``Do you think I deny the bolts standing out in my neck,
the florid countenance, the hyperventilation, the quadruple bypass
I had several years ago? I would much rather live the life of the
happy wanderer, but. . .''
</P>
<P>
   But no. There are leeches and mooches and desperadoes to take
out. Does he seriously think he can singlehandedly change Internet
culture? Does he seriously think he can stop the technology he
writes about in his, um, imaginative works? ``The average citizen
doesn't have the prayer of a snowball in a cyclotron,'' he says
with a dramatic sigh. He likes the phrase. He writes it down. He
may hurl it at someone some day.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
