<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CPT-APPLE-DESIGN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
APPLE THINKS OUTSIDE THE BOX WITH ITS IMPRESSIVE CUBE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Repeating as part of a weekly roundup of computer features)   By ALAN T. SARACEVIC   
 c.2000 San Francisco Examiner   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ For all its breakthrough technology and
acknowledged superiority in desktop computing, Apple Computer's
lasting legacy will be industrial design.
</P>
<P>
   The resurgent computer maker has once again thought outside of
the computer design box, ironically producing a revolutionary Cube.
</P>
<P>
   The Power Mac G4 Cube, a pint-sized powerhouse of a desktop
computer picks up the industrial design legacy established by its
translucent predecessor, the iMac. By all accounts, the Cube
expands on that groundbreaking design, or rather contracts on it,
offering a sleek miniaturization coupled with clean, crisp lines.
Simply put, the Cube is a beautiful machine.
</P>
<P>
   But while the design is revolutionary, the average Mac user
won't experience a huge difference when using the Cube, at least
not until Apple's next operating system, Mac OS X, is shipped in
early 2001. Until then, the Cube is essentially a faster, smaller,
cooler-looking version of the existing G4 Power Macs on the market.
</P>
<P>
   The Cube, which retails for $1,799, is a 8-inch by 8-inch square
computer suspended inside an industrial-strength clear plastic
casing, giving the set-up a floating feel. The machine comes
equipped with Apple's new ``pro keyboard'' and an optical, ``pro
mouse,'' both of which follow the crystalline design of the mother
Cube. Closing out the set are a pair of 20-watt, Harman Kardon
speakers, once again encased in smooth, clear plastic. The Cube
comes with no monitor.
</P>
<P>
   But combined with one of Apple's digital, 15-inch, flat-panel
monitors ($999), the Cube is, indeed, a smaller, cooler-looking
version of the powerful Apple computers that have been dominating
the desks of graphics professionals for the past year.
</P>
<P>
   No other computer company comes close to generating the level of
loyalty and adoration that Apples does. A lot of that has to do
with the commitment to design chief executive Steve Jobs has
ingrained into the company he founded more than 20 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``Interestingly it reminds me of Jobs' original NeXT computer,''
said Creative Strategies President Tim Bajarin, referring to Jobs'
ill-fated company that folded in 1993. ``In some ways (the Cube) is
a new incarnation of that original idea. However, this is much more
innovative and, in many ways, represents the next generation of
computer design.''
</P>
<P>
   Linda McNulty, Apple's director of desktop product marketing,
said size was a critical component when the corporation conjured
the Cube.
</P>
<P>
   ``Reducing the size is the biggest advance,'' McNulty said.
``Having something that powerful, that's essentially silent, is an
incredible move. You have a really powerful tool on your desk, not
taking up too much space and it's unobtrusive.''
</P>
<P>
   The Cube makes virtually no noise when it operates, thanks to an
external power source. That means no fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we design a product, we sit down and look at our customer
profile,'' McNulty said. ``You start with the needs and where you
want to get to. Basically, we got to the point where it was very
efficient.''
</P>
<P>
   Although no one person gets official credit for the Cube's
design in Apple's internal, democratic design structure, Jonathan
Ive, the vice president of industrial design, is unofficially
acknowledged as the Cube's chief creator.
</P>
<P>
   At $1,799, the Cube straddles the space between the serious
computer consumer and the corporate buyer. Luckily for both, the
Cube has the guts to satisfy the professional and the polish to
soothe a new user.
</P>
<P>
   The guts include a 450-MHz G4 processor, 64MB of RAM and a 20 GB
Ultra ATA/66 hard drive. Built-to-order options will include
incremental memory expansions topping out at 1.5 GB and a processor
upgrade to 500 MHz.
</P>
<P>
   Underneath the Cube are relatively few ports for peripherals,
consisting of two USB ports, two FireWire ports, a 10/100Base-T
Ethernet port and a 56K V.90 modem connector.
</P>
<P>
   Internally, the Cube has a DVD-ROM drive, an ATI RAGE 128 Pro
graphics card with 16 MB of SDRAM graphics memory, an AirPort Card
slot and 1 MB of backside level 2 cache.
</P>
<P>
   Mac OS 9 includes a number of software applications, including
Apple's latest home-movie editor, iMovie 2.01, and QuickTime. Both
programs make the most of the Cube's digital roots, allowing for
television-quality viewing of video.
</P>
<P>
   Set-up was extremely easy, as is common with Apple computers.
There are only two wires connecting the Cube and the monitor. The
speakers and the keyboard plug directly into Apple monitors using
USB connectors.
</P>
<P>
   The chief drawback to the stock version of the Cube is the
relative lack of random access memory. With graphics-heavy programs
such as iMovie and QuickTime, it's often impossible to run more
than one at a time with only 64MBs in the tank. In the short-term,
a Cube user can boost virtual memory without major problems, but a
professional user will definitely want to upgrade the machine's
internal chips. To Apple's credit, there are plenty of slots
available.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would probably be nice to have more memory. But for a
professional customer, there's no right number in terms of
memory,'' McNulty said. ``There are people that will load it up
with a gig and a half of memory. We did design it so it's nice and
easy to get in and add whatever memory they need. We also wanted to
make sure we didn't bump the price point up.''
</P>
<P>
   The only other drawback centered on the Cube's ``sleep mode,``
which caused occasional crashes and was a bit sluggish to recede
when trying to revive the machine.
</P>
<P>
   Otherwise, the Cube's nominal negatives were far outweighed by
the machine's positives. The new operating system should make a big
difference, as will the continued evolution of the high-speed
Internet access and programming.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
NYT-08-17-00 1243EDT &QL;
</P>
