<SLUG> BC-20MINUTE-MENUS-ADV13-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV13  
 HEALTHY 20-MINUTE MENUS: BREAD AND TOMATO SALAD A LA AMERICANA 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDITORS: For use Wednesday, Sept. 13, or thereafter.)  
 (ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's 20MINUTE-MENUS. For more information about
becoming a client of 20MINUTE-MENUS, contact one of the New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text.)  
 By MARIAN BURROS    
 c.2000 Foxcraft Ltd.    
<TEXT>
<P>
   When local tomatoes are at their peak each summer I pull out
another of my collection of bread and tomato salads to enjoy and to
share with you.
</P>
<P>
   The Italians have always known what to do with tomatoes whether
they cook them, dry them or serve them raw. Is there anything
simpler or better than tomatoes, mozzarella and basil? And a bread
and tomato salad is based on the famous Italian panzanella.
</P>
<P>
   As the summer draws to an end and you want to get in as many
tomatoes as possible _ but you want something more filling than
tomatoes and mozzarella _ a bread and tomato salad is called for.
The basics are the bread, the tomatoes and olive oil. After that
it's a free-lance dish. This version sticks pretty close to a
classic panzanella with the whole wheat Italian bread. But the
addition of corn is strictly American.
</P>
<P>
   I could make a meal on bread and tomato salad alone, but since
most people would prefer to add a touch of protein, I suggest a
nice spicy Italian sausage, preferably one made of turkey that is
low in fat. If you want just the salad, this recipe will serve two.
</P>
<P>
   BREAD AND TOMATO SALAD A LA AMERICANA
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces whole wheat Italian bread
</P>
<P>
   2 large ears corn
</P>
<P>
   24 ounces ripe tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   1 cup thinly sliced red onion
</P>
<P>
   20 large basil leaves
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup well-flavored extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1. Cut bread into 1/2-inch cubes and dry out either overnight or
toast in 300 degree oven for about 10 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   2. Cook the corn for a minute or two and drain.
</P>
<P>
   3. Wash, trim and cut tomato into 1/2-inch cubes; slice the
onion very thinly and then cut each slice in half. Wash the basil
leaves and place one on top of the other; roll up like a cigarette
and cut crosswise very thinly. In serving bowl combine the tomatoes
and basil. Scrape corn kernels off cobs and stir into tomato
mixture along with the bread.
</P>
<P>
   4. Whisk together the oil and vinegar and pour over salad. Toss
and allow to sit for 15 minutes to moisten the bread.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   SAUSAGES
</P>
<P>
   4 low-fat Italian-flavored sausages
</P>
<P>
   1. Cook the sausages according to directions and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Yield: 4 servings.
</P>
<P>
   GAME PLAN
</P>
<P>
   Prepare salad through step 2.
</P>
<P>
   Cook sausage.
</P>
<P>
   Finish salad.
</P>
<P>
   YOUR PANTRY
</P>
<P>
   Red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Well flavored extra virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   SHOPPING LIST
</P>
<P>
   8 ounces whole wheat Italian bread
</P>
<P>
   2 large ears corn
</P>
<P>
   24 ounces ripe tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces red onion to yield 1 cup thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   Bunch basil (20 large leaves)
</P>
<P>
   4 low-fat Italian flavored sausages
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITION INFORMATION PER SERVING: 480 calories, 20 grams fat,
3.5 grams saturated fat, 70 milligrams cholesterol, 905 milligrams
sodium, 55 grams carbohydrate, 8.3 grams fiber, 25 grams protein.
</P>
<P>
   -----
</P>
<P>
   EDITORS: Visit The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for more information on
20-MINUTE-MENUS articles and other features.
</P>
