<HEADER>
A9906 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-LOST-CLIMBER-2NDTAKE-     08-23 0520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOST-CLIMBER-2NDTAKE-HNS </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; CLIFTON PARK, N.Y.: x x x too late.''
</P>
<P>
   Jim Weinman's green tent was recovered, along with its contents:
his journal, the copy of ``Siddhartha,'' a Spanish/English
dictionary, Irish penny whistle, plate and fork from his mess kit,
brown zipper pants, green fleece pullover, fuel bottle, Boreal
trekking boots, socks, some nylon bags, food and garbage.
</P>
<P>
   Knowing intimately his brother's climbing ritual, Bob Weinman
figured Jim left his tent at base camp early Sunday morning, June
4, after a breakfast of oatmeal and instant coffee. He packed his
ice climbing gear into a large blue backpack: ropes, helmet, ice
axes, ice tools, crampons, sleeping bag, water bottle, stove and
food.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Weinman would have paid special attention to packing his
newly repaired camera, with which he planned to document his ice
climb to the summit of San Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   His brother didn't find the camera or any of his other climbing
gear.
</P>
<P>
   Now, three months after his disappearance, all Weinman's family
and friends are left with is speculation.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Weinman might have been struck by falling rocks or a large
chunk of ice. He might have been caught in an avalanche.
</P>
<P>
   For governmental records in Chile, Jim Weinman remains a missing
person. The case is open.
</P>
<P>
   His family presumes he is dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a terrible feeling not knowing what happened,'' his
mother said.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no closure yet at this point,'' said his father.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Weinman plans to resume a search effort for his lost brother
in several months, after Chile's winter has passed and the snow in
the Maipo Valley has melted.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, having moved through the stage of raw grief,
the Weinmans are struggling to create a fitting tribute to their
son. His mother did not think it appropriate to publish an obituary
or death notice.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, a memory service for Jim Weinman is planned for
Saturday, Sept. 9, at 10:30 a.m. at the chapel of Sacred Heart
Church on Lake George, N.Y., where the Weinmans have a summer home,
scene of some of the brothers' earliest hiking and camping
adventures.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want something good to come out of all this pain,'' Jim
Weinman's mother said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bob Weinman is working through the pain of his loss. ``My
brother was my best friend and the best times in my life were with
him,'' he said. ``It hasn't all hit me yet. It still feels like
Jim's off on a trip and I'll be getting an e-mail from him any day
saying he's come up with a cool climb for us to do together.''
</P>
<P>
   He is left with his brother's voluminous climbing journals,
which Jim had hoped to use as the basis of a book. In one, Jim
Weinman wrote this:
</P>
<P>
   ``In the mountains you are at the mercy of the elements. The
roads, buildings and artificial sense of control is replaced in the
mountains by the will of mother nature. It is both terrifying and
liberating.
</P>
<P>
   ``Returning to the land of man you breathe a sign of relief, but
deep inside you miss the freedom and beauty that only the
desolation of the mountains can provide.''
</P>
</TEXT>
