<HEADER>
A9907 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-LOST-CLIMBER-2TAKES-H     08-23 1167
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LOST-CLIMBER-2TAKES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     ALPINE PASSION CLAIMS A YOUNG ADVENTURER 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (ATTN: Md., N.Y., Ore., Wash.)  
 &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By PAUL GRONDAHL  
 &HT;     c.2000 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLIFTON PARK, N.Y. _ Three times in a row, a challenging ice
face up the southern route of a 14,000-foot peak named Cerro San
Francisco in the Andes Mountains outside Santiago, Chile, had
defeated Jim Weinman.
</P>
<P>
   The 32-year-old mountaineer and extreme adventurer wanted a
fourth go at the glaciated summit in the shadow of the volcano
Maipo.
</P>
<P>
   A year earlier, Weinman and an Australian ice climber had nearly
been crushed by a large rock that broke off from San Francisco's
icy peak. Another time, Weinman had tried a solo ascent and turned
back because the ice was not right. A third time, he'd made a
scouting climb in search of a challenging southern route with
proper ice conditions.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd done a lot of other peaks in the area and this one just
kept beating him,'' said Jim's brother, Bob Weinman, 31, a fellow
alpinist. ``It got under his skin. He really wanted to finish off
San Francisco before he left Chile for good, and he thought he had
good ice.''
</P>
<P>
   Ever since their parents introduced the brothers to New York's
Adirondack High Peaks as youngsters, the pair were nearly
inseparable adventurers who traveled across the Americas and Europe
in search of new alpine challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Together, they climbed Mount McKinley (20,320 feet), the highest
peak in the United States. Often they packed skis up to the summits
of peaks so that they could ski down.
</P>
<P>
   Mount Hood and Mount Rainier in the rugged Cascade Mountains
were their favorite playgrounds during years spent eking out a
living to support their alpine sports in the Pacific Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   In May, the brothers climbed a mountain in Brazil named ``The
Finger of God.''
</P>
<P>
   The brothers' trademark was their climbing mascot, a Barbie doll
they photographed on summits, which earned them a squib in Outside
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Their talk was of the next climb. ``We wanted to do a ski ascent
of the north face of Everest,'' Bob Weinman recalled recently.
``Jim had turned down one Everest expedition already. We wanted to
do it together.''
</P>
<P>
   But after finishing the 2000 season as a guide in the Patagonia
region of southern Argentina, Jim Weinman headed north in early
June to face his nemesis once more in a solo ice climb up Cerro San
Francisco.
</P>
<P>
   During a year in South America, the native of Clifton Park had
earned the nickname ``El James'' among Chileans for his ice
climbing prowess. He had established new ice routes that were
informally named after him.
</P>
<P>
   The strong, wiry former collegiate skier at St. Lawrence
University in Canton, N.Y., stood 5-feet-9-inches and weighed 155
pounds. With a goatee, shoulder-length brown hair and good looks
(fellow climbers kidded Weinman about resembling the model Fabio
when his hair was washed and blown dry), El James was an affable
presence _ one who could travel the globe and count on the
international climbing fraternity whose names he kept in a black
address book to put him up during his adventures.
</P>
<P>
   Finding climbing partners was a different matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jim became so proficient at ice climbing and took such
technically challenging routes that nobody wanted to go with him
anymore,'' said his father, James Weinman, a senior engineer with
Lockheed Martin. Weinman and his wife, Linda, a marketing
consultant, live in Clifton Park.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always safe and planned his routes out very
carefully,'' his mother said. ``He'd never had any problems going
solo.''
</P>
<P>
   In early June, a hint of fall was in the air in Chile's Maipo
Valley. The weather was clear and cool. No precipitation was
predicted. Conditions were perfect for ice climbing.
</P>
<P>
   Weinman had spent the past 12 months guiding rock and ice
climbers for a French company in southern Chile and Argentina and
had earned a few days' vacation, which he planned to use before
flying to England to meet his girlfriend on June 9 and to
contemplate a break from high-altitude adventure.
</P>
<P>
   After years of working just long enough to save money for the
next expedition _ the brothers had lived together in Seattle and
Portland, Ore., and climbed peaks from California to Alaska when
they weren't windsurfing, snowboarding and skiing _ Jim was
thinking of perhaps settling down and getting a real job like his
brother, Bob, who'd become a media buyer for an Internet
advertising company in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   But first, the mountain beckoned.
</P>
<P>
   On June 3, Weinman set up base camp on San Francisco at about
10,000 feet and pitched his green tent on bare ground.
</P>
<P>
   He filtered water from a nearby stream, made a dinner of pasta
and Bolognese sauce and read from his Spanish version of Herman
Hesse's ``Siddhartha,'' a novel of a young man leaving his family
and embarking on a spiritual quest. He played on an Irish penny
whistle.
</P>
<P>
   And then, before going to sleep early in preparation for the
next morning's summit ascent, Weinman made this entry at the top of
a blank sheet in his ever-present climbing journal:
</P>
<P>
   Cerro San Francisco. Pared Sur (southern route).
</P>
<P>
   They were the last words Jim Weinman wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Weinman vanished without a trace on June 4. That day, a freak
storm dumped more than 6 feet of snow in the mountains, set off
avalanches, flooded cities, triggered mud slides and threw Chile
into a state of emergency that delayed any search efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Weinman was not reported missing until June 9 by his British
girlfriend. She and her mother had waited at the airport that day
for his Avianca flight to arrive in London. He was not on the
plane.
</P>
<P>
   Weinman's brother flew to Santiago the next day and organized a
search party with other experienced alpinists he rallied through
appeals among climbing groups in the Maipo Valley region by e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   His search efforts were hampered by a lack of emergency
services, outdated technology and government inefficiencies.
</P>
<P>
   His parents were at home in Clifton Park, desperately seeking
assistance from the U.S. Embassy in Chile, members of Congress and
other government officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so frustrating trying to do things remotely and facing
such difficulties with the weather, the bureaucracy, the lack of
resources,'' Weinman's father said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Chile obviously isn't up to the standards of the U.S. They
just don't have the ability to carry out a real mountain rescue,''
said Bob Weinman, who ended up hiring private helicopter pilots to
conduct aerial searches and to air-drop him onto the side of San
Francisco at 13,000 feet to search, with three other experienced
climbers.
</P>
<P>
   It was June 13, nine days after Jim Weinman set out for the
summit. The few scant footprints they spotted turned out to be
tracks of rabbits.
</P>
<P>
   ``The snow was just so deep,'' Bob Weinman said. ``It was too
late.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS.) &QL; 
</ANNOTATION>
