<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 12:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9917 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-ALCOHOLISM-DRUG-HNS &LR;      08-23 0740
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ALCOHOLISM-DRUG-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     STUDY CITED AS `MILESTONE' IN TREATING EARLY ALCOHOLISM 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By CINDY TUMIEL  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Researchers say that a drug used to treat nausea
also can curb the destructive cravings in the type of alcoholic
doctors find toughest to treat.
</P>
<P>
   Early-onset alcoholics _ those who became problem drinkers
before age 25 _ were able to stop drinking or significantly cut
their alcohol consumption when they took the drug ondansetron,
according to the study by scientists at the University of Texas
Health Science Center in San Antonio.
</P>
<P>
   The research by Dr. Bankole Johnson, a professor of psychiatry
and pharmacology, was hailed as another milestone in the search for
treatments for alcoholism.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just slowly making progress in this, in addressing it
from a biological treatment standpoint,'' said Raye Litten, health
science administrator with the National Institute on Alcohol Abuse
and Alcoholism. ``A lot of people 10 years ago said you can't get a
medication to reduce somebody's urge to drink.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The big picture is that we have so few different kinds of
treatment for alcoholism,'' said R. Adron Harris, director of the
Waggoner Center for Alcohol and Addiction Research at the
University of Texas at Austin. ``This introduces another
possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson's study was published Wednesday in the Journal of the
American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   Ondansetron, marketed by Glaxo Wellcome Inc. under the brand
name Zofran, is used to treat nausea in patients who are undergoing
chemotherapy.
</P>
<P>
   The drug works on the serotonin neurotransmitters, one of the
chemical messengers in the brain that helps regulate pleasure and
pain.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier research by Johnson and others suggested early-onset
alcoholics, who come from families with a marked history of alcohol
abuse, have genetic flaws that produce an abnormality in their
serotonin system.
</P>
<P>
   These people are problem drinkers by their early 20s. They
exhibit reckless and impulsive behavior, often experiment with
other drugs and sometimes find themselves in trouble with the law.
They complete treatment only to relapse.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors estimate early-onset alcoholics account for 25 percent
to 30 percent of the nation's 3.5 million alcoholics.
</P>
<P>
   In the study, 271 subjects took ondansetron or a placebo for 11
weeks, in conjunction with behavioral therapy. The subjects were an
average age of 40 and reported consuming an average of six or seven
alcoholic drinks daily.
</P>
<P>
   After three to four weeks, early-onset alcoholics taking the
drug said they were able to significantly reduce the amount they
drank, compared to the group that got therapy and the placebo.
Blood tests confirmed the self-reports of study subjects, Johnson
noted.
</P>
<P>
   Those taking the drug also were able to abstain from drinking an
average of 70 percent of the days during the study, compared to 50
percent for the placebo group.
</P>
<P>
   Alcoholics in the study who were not early problem drinkers did
not get the same effect from the drug, Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This offers hope for treating the most severe alcoholic, who
is young, who goes through periods of lapses and relapses and has
problems with anti-social behavior,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The finding also takes researchers further into their
understanding of the disease, Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``By knowing what the biology underlying these abnormalities is
likely to be, our hope for the future is that we will be able to
develop an understanding of how a person's genes play a part in
telling whether or not they will respond to a drug,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One other drug, naltrexone, is federally approved for use in
alcohol abuse and has been shown effective with certain types of
alcoholics. Another, acamprosate, is in the pipeline for approval.
</P>
<P>
   The National Institute on Alcohol Abuse and Alcoholism currently
is funding a study to confirm the findings with ondansetron, Litten
said. If the results are validated, the drug could represent
another potential therapy for a selected segment of alcoholism
sufferers. It also opens the possibility that drugs could be
combined to achieve a greater effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is exciting to see this,'' Litten said. ``Its another
compound (that works) at different sites in the brain.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Cindy Tumiel can be reached by e-mail at
ctumiel(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
