<HEADER>
A9930 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-NUTSBOLTS-COLUMN0823-     08-23 0973
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUTSBOLTS-COLUMN0823-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Finish, not type of wood, dictates how to maintain furniture
 &HT;    By James Cummings
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio - Is the chest of drawers in your bedroom finished
in lacquer or oil? Will it damage the surface if you set a wet
glass down on a waxed table? Should you use ammonia to clean a
butcher block?
</P>
<P>
   Most people have houses full of natural wood furnishings, but
very few people are certain about how to care for them. That's why
it's not uncommon for furniture owners to make routine maintenance
mistakes that lessen the beauty of their wood over time.
</P>
<P>
   It's not the type of wood used to make furniture that determines
how it should be maintained; it's the type of finish on the wood,
according to the Michigan State University Extension Service.
</P>
<P>
   Some finishes _ lacquer, shellac, varnish and polyurethane _ are
applied in layers and form a shell-like barrier between the wood
and its environment. Lacquer, shellac and varnish have been used in
furniture making for centuries, while polyurethane is a more modern
material and acts like a clear-plastic shield.
</P>
<P>
   Other wood furnishings are finished in natural oils. The oils
are rubbed onto the surface, and the wood fibers absorb them.
Oil-finished furniture generally has a smooth, warm look and a
soft, natural feel.
</P>
<P>
   Another finish occasionally found is wax. Cindy Stegman, manager
of Arhaus Furniture in Washington Township says natural beeswax is
often used in folk-style pine furniture and is found on many
antiques.
</P>
<P>
   When you buy a new piece of furniture, make sure you ask what
kind of finish it has. That knowledge is critical, because the
maintenance regimen for one type of finish could easily damage
another kind.
</P>
<P>
   Your furniture retailer or the manufacturers of the furniture
should also be able to supply you with care and maintenance tips.
And ask if the retailer sells furniture-care products such as
polishes and waxes, or if he can recommend suitable products.
</P>
<P>
   If you buy your furniture cleaners and polishes outside the
store where you bought the furniture, make sure the products you
buy are compatible. Know the finish on your furniture and check the
container of the product you are considering to confirm it works
well in your situation.
</P>
<P>
   Don Parker, service technician for Bruning Clock Shop in Huber
Heights, said workers at the store regularly dust the grandfather
clocks and other wooden items with a soft white rag.
</P>
<P>
   Every two weeks or so, the wood is polished with Oz Furniture
Polish, a product supplied by a clock manufacturer.
</P>
<P>
   Dusting is important for all wood furniture. Going over wooden
furniture occasionally with a vacuum cleaner using a soft brush
attachment keeps dust from collecting in crevices and patterns
carved in the wood.
</P>
<P>
   Also do what you can to keep dust levels down in the house.
Change furnace filters regularly and use your range hood to keep
dust-collecting grease from spreading.
</P>
<P>
   Stegman from Arhaus suggests keeping an eye on the furniture for
signs of dullness and loss of warmth. She equates polishes, wax and
oils to the moisturizers we use to keep our skin from drying, and
she said furniture in the sun or near a heat source will need to be
moisturized more often than furniture in a cool, dark, humid room.
</P>
<P>
   The moisturizer used must match the finish on the furniture.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lacquer and shellac: Stegman uses a spray polish, Guardsman,
for furnishings in the store that are finished with catalyzed
lacquers. She applies the polish and wipes with a soft cloth about
once a month _ more often for pieces exposed to heat and sun.
</P>
<P>
   Be careful when choosing a polish, not a wax, for use on
lacquered surfaces. Products incompatible with lacquers will
partially dissolve the surface, creating a tacky, sticky feel that
can be hard to correct.
</P>
<P>
   Avoid getting water on furniture finished with shellac. If you
have a spill, wipe it up immediately. Shellac is a high-gloss
finish that doesn't stand up to moisture well. Other surface
finishes are a little better, but you should avoid letting wood get
wet when you can.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Oil: Replenish the luster of oil by rubbing in more oil about
twice a year. You can find oil suitable for furniture where other
furniture-care products are sold. Apply a small amount of oil to a
clean, soft rag and rub it into the surface, taking care not to
apply too much. The surface should not look wet, so you should
quickly wipe away any excess.
</P>
<P>
   Always rub the oil along the grain of the wood. To create an
even smoother surface, you can rub in the oil with ultrafine steel
wool. Minor blemishes should fade with a new coat of oil, but some
damage may require light sanding and re-oiling. If you're unsure if
you can handle a repair, consult an expert.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Polyurethane: This plasticlike, modern coating stands up well
to most abuse and is often used in furniture that is likely to get
wet occasionally. You'll find butcher-block tables and cutting
boards finished in polyurethane, for example.
</P>
<P>
   Polyurethane surfaces maintain a shine and generally don't need
polishing. Wash them with warm water and mild detergent but not
with ammonia, which can dull the surface. You can add layers of
polyurethane if the finish is damaged.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Wax: You replenish wax surfaces as needed by rubbing in more
wax. Again, a good furniture retailer might be your best source for
wax furniture-care products.
</P>
<P>
   Stegman recommends paste waxes that are applied like shoe
polish. Rub in the wax following the grain in the wood and wipe
away the excess. Buff the surface to a shine using a horsehair
brush similar to brushes commonly used to shine shoes.
</P>
<P>
   Email: James Cummings at jamescummings(at) coxohio.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
