turn-of-the-century artist and designer who rose to eminence, then
sank into obscurity, is now on the brink of rediscovery. He was a
pivotal member of Associated Artists, a short-lived design firm
founded by Louis Comfort Tiffany whose specialty was self-conscious
splendor: exotic interiors where brass lanterns hung from stenciled
ceilings and Persian carpets were flung over harem-style
balustrades. By Mitchell Owens.
