<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 13:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9945 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r f BC-MEXICO-EMPLOYMENT-HNS     08-23 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-EMPLOYMENT-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     MEXICAN EMPLOYERS SUFFER AN AMERICAN WOE: HIGH EMPLOYMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By BILL DAY  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ It's a familiar story: Businesses are having a
tough time finding workers because the booming economy. So they are
recruiting them from far away and paying higher wages.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, it is Mexico, not the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Mexican unemployment fell to 2.03 percent in July, the lowest
level since it hit 2 percent in December 1999, the Mexican
government announced Tuesday. That figure was the lowest ever for
any July, and substantially lower than the 2.2 percent economists
had expected. (The unemployment rate in the United States is 4
percent.)
</P>
<P>
   The low jobless rate is a symptom of Mexico's rapidly growing
economy, which jumped by 7.8 percent in the first half of 2000. The
boom is bringing widespread prosperity to Mexico's burgeoning
middle class, but it is putting the squeeze on employers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in Monterrey recently, and I talked to employers who
said they couldn't expand because they couldn't find workers,''
said Jorge Gonzalez, a professor of economics at Trinity University
in San Antonio. ``That's happening in more cities in Mexico.''
</P>
<P>
   Unemployment in northern Mexican states like Tamaulipas and
Nuevo Leon, where many foreign-owned manufacturing plants were
established, is as low as 0.5 percent. In southern states,
joblessness has risen above 3.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   When the state-run petroleum company, Pemex, needed employees in
Nuevo Leon, it recruited unemployed workers from southern Mexico.
This internal migration has helped moderate the hot economy's wage
pressures, but it has caused problems of its own.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Reynosa, Nuevo Leon and Matamoros, people are coming in
from the (southern) state of Veracruz, which has a totally
different culture,'' said Francisco Gonzalez, an acting director at
the University of Texas Pan American's Mexican Business Information
Center. ``Some of them don't have a place to live, so they go build
a shack on the back of their relatives' home, or in their back
yard.''
</P>
<P>
   There are other dangers. Economists fear that an overheating
economy could be sabotaged by inflation. A business group, the
Center for Economic Studies of the Private Sector, last week warned
that the economy couldn't sustain its strong growth, and urged the
government to slow it down.
</P>
<P>
   Trinity's Gonzalez said Mexican banks have made fewer loans in
recent years as more of Mexico's financing comes from outside the
country. Even if the Bank of Mexico raised interest rates, it would
not do much to tighten the money supply.
</P>
<P>
   The federal government could try to effect fiscal policy by
reducing spending, but Gonzalez said President-elect Vicente Fox
would find that a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the campaign, he said he was going to spend a lot of
money,'' Gonzalez said.
</P>
<P>
   The situation might not be as severe as it seems. The government
expects 1 million new employees to join the workforce this year.
And unemployment statistics in Mexico are calculated differently
than in the United States, where a jobless rate of 2.03 percent
would likely panic the Federal Reserve and prompt it to clamp down
on the economy.
</P>
<P>
   When the government compiles the so-called ``general pressure''
rate, which combines the unemployed with those seeking new or
additional jobs, the figure rises to a more manageable 3.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the bountiful job market, Mexicans continue to seek work
in the United States, where wages are substantially higher.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Day can be reached by e-mail at wday(at)express-news.net)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
