<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COOK'S-CORNER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERSATILE RICOTTA FOR PIES, TOO
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Today, we're revisiting the ricotta cheese dessert theme, but
this time via pies. The request for ricotta pies and cakes came
from Angela Turiace of La Crescenta who was unable to locate any.
</P>
<P>
   Hopefully, readers enjoyed the numerous ricotta cake recipes
featured a few weeks back. Now give some of these pie creations a
whirl. There are several to choose from _ ranging from simple to
more complex. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
RICOTTA CHEESE PIE &QL; 
(Shared by Barbara Harsman, Tarzana) &QL; 
3 cups ricotta cheese, drained &QL; 
1/2 cup flour &QL; 
2 tablespoons grated orange peel &QL; 
2 tablespoons grated lemon peel &QL; 
1 teaspoons salt &QL; 
5 eggs &QL; 
1 cup sugar &QL; 
1 tablespoon vanilla &QL; 
1 (10-inch) unbaked pastry crust &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
!netlead-end! &QL; 
Beat ricotta with flour, orange and lemon peels and salt until well
blended.
</P>
<P>
   Beat eggs; add sugar and beat until thick. Beat in vanilla. Stir
beaten egg mixture into ricotta mixture and blend until smooth.
</P>
<P>
   Pour into pastry crust. Bake in preheated 350-degree oven 50 to
60 minutes, until mixture is firm and pastry is golden brown. Cool.
Makes 1 (10-inch) pie. &QL; 
--- &QL; 
RICOTTA PIE &QL; 
(Shared by Anna Labriola Dell, Winnetka) &QL; 
1 1/2 pounds ricotta cheese &QL; 
1/2 cup sugar &QL; 
5 eggs &QL; 
1 teaspoon vanilla &QL; 
1 tablespoon anisette &QL; 
3 tablespoons chopped candied citron OR orange peel &QL; 
1 teaspoon ground cinnamon &QL; 
Dash salt &QL; 
Sweet Pastry Crust (recipe follows) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Place ricotta cheese in a mixing bowl and stir in sugar. Beat in
4 eggs, one at a time, to make smooth, creamy mixture. Beat in
vanilla, anisette, citron and 1/2 teaspoon cinnamon.
</P>
<P>
   Butter a 9-inch cake pan, 2 inches deep. To assemble pie, cut
off 1/3 of Sweet Pastry Crust dough and set aside. Roll remaining
2/3 of crust dough into a 14-inch disk and ease into prepared pan.
Allow dough to hang over edge of pan. Spoon in ricotta filling and
spread evenly. Sprinkle filling with remaining 1/2 teaspoon
cinnamon.
</P>
<P>
   Roll remaining 1/3 dough into a 10-inch square. Cut into 10
(1-inch- wide) strips. Moisten strips with remaining 1 egg beaten
with a dash salt. Moisten rim of dough on pan with egg wash and
arrange 5 strips in each direction, forming a diagonal lattice.
Trim excess dough even with top of pan and push dough off top of
rim so it is completely within pan.
</P>
<P>
   Bake on bottom oven rack, set at lowest level, in preheated
350-degree oven about 45 minutes, until filling is set and pastry
is light golden. Cool in pan before unmolding. Serve at room
temperature. Makes about 10 servings. &QL; 
--- &QL; 
SWEET PASTRY CRUST &QL; 
2 cups flour &QL; 
1/3 cup sugar &QL; 
1/4 teaspoon salt &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon baking powder &QL; 
1/2 cup cold unsalted butter, cut into 8 pieces &QL; 
2 large eggs &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Combine flour, sugar, salt and baking powder in bowl of a food
processor and pulse several times to mix. Evenly distribute butter
over mixture. Pulse until very finely powdered, about 10 times at
1-second intervals. Add eggs and continue to pulse until dough
forms a ball.
</P>
<P>
   Remove dough from bowl and press into a disk. Wrap and chill
until needed. &QL; 
--- &QL; 
RICOTTA CHEESE PIE &QL; 
(Shared by Peter A. Grisanti, Granada Hills) &QL; 
1 1/2 pounds ricotta cheese &QL; 
1/4 cup sugar &QL; 
4 tablespoons rum &QL; 
3 tablespoons heavy whipping cream &QL; 
2/3 cup coarsely chopped mixed candied fruits &QL; 
Graham Cracker Crust &QL; 
1 ounce semisweet chocolate &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In an electric mixer, beat together cheese, sugar, rum and cream
until blended. Stir in candied fruits. Turn into chilled Graham
Cracker Crust.
</P>
<P>
   Shave chocolate with a potato peeler or chop chocolate and
sprinkle over top of pie. Refrigerate overnight. Makes 6 servings.
</P>
<P>
   GRAHAM CRACKER CRUST: In a bowl, combine 2 cups graham cracker
crumbs, 1/3 cup plus 1 tablespoon sugar and 1/2 cup unsalted
butter, melted. Mix until well blended. Press into a well-buttered
10-inch pie plate. Refrigerate 45 minutes. &QL; 
--- &QL; 
HONEY-CHEESE PIE &QL; 
WITH STRAWBERRY COMPOTE &QL; 
(Shared by Ruth Nebron, Valley Glen) &QL; 
CRUST: &QL; 
1/4 cup (1/2 stick) unsalted butter &QL; 
2 tablespoons honey &QL; 
34 vanilla wafer cookies &QL; 
3/4 cup whole almonds &QL; 
3/4 cup walnuts &QL; 
1/4 teaspoon salt &QL; 
FILLING: &QL; 
2 (8-ounce) packages cream cheese, room temperature &QL; 
1 (15- to 16-ounce) container whole milk ricotta cheese &QL; 
1/2 cup plus 1 tablespoon sugar &QL; 
1/2 cup plus 1 tablespoon honey &QL; 
4 extra-large eggs &QL; 
2 teaspoons vanilla &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon lemon extract &QL; 
COMPOTE: &QL; 
3 (12-ounce) baskets small strawberries, hulled and quartered &QL; 
1/3 cup honey &QL; 
GARNISH: &QL; 
Additional honey &QL; 
Strawberry blossoms OR other small nonpoisonous flowers (optional) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Crust, wrap outside of a 10-inch-diameter springform pan
with 2 1/2- inch-high sides, with foil. Bring butter and honey to a
boil in a heavy small saucepan, stirring occasionally. Remove from
heat. Finally grind vanilla wafers in processor. Add nuts and salt
to processor. Add butter mixture and process until nuts are finely
chopped. Press mixture onto bottom and 1 inch up sides of prepared
pan.
</P>
<P>
   Bake crust in preheated 350-degree oven about 12 minutes, until
golden. Transfer to rack and cool. Reduce oven temperature to 325
degrees F.
</P>
<P>
   For Filling, using an electric mixer, beat cream cheese and
ricotta cheese in a large bowl until smooth. Mix in sugar and
honey. Add eggs, one at a time, beating well after each addition.
Mix in vanilla and lemon extracts. Pour filling into crust.
</P>
<P>
   Bake pie about 1 hour 10 minutes, until puffed, golden and
center moves only slightly when pan is gently shaken. Transfer to
rack and cool completely. (Can be prepared 1 day ahead. Cover and
chill.)
</P>
<P>
   For Compote, mix quartered strawberries and 1/3 cup honey in a
large bowl. Cover and chill. (Can be made 4 hours ahead.)
</P>
<P>
   Run a small, sharp knife around sides of pan to loosen pie.
Release pan sides. To garnish, drizzle additional honey over pie in
a zigzag pattern. Transfer pie to serving platter. Using a slotted
spoon, transfer some of strawberry compote to top of pie, if
desired. Garnish pie with strawberry blossoms, if desired. Cut pie
into wedges and serve with remaining strawberry compote. Makes 12
servings.
</P>
<P>
   From Bon Appetit magazine, April 1996. &QL; 
--- &QL; 
RICOTTA PIE &QL; 
Shared by Anna Rametta, North Hollywood) &QL; 
1 1/2 pounds ricotta cheese &QL; 
4 eggs &QL; 
1/2 cup sugar &QL; 
1/2 teaspoon vanilla &QL; 
1/4 cup flour &QL; 
1/2 cup cut-up citron &QL; 
1 (9-inch) Pastry Shell &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Beat together ricotta cheese, eggs, sugar, vanilla and flour
until well blended. Stir in citron.
</P>
<P>
   Make Pastry Shell. Pour filling into Pastry Shell.
</P>
<P>
   Bake in preheated 325-degree oven 1 1/2 hours. Turn off oven.
Leave pie in oven with door ajar until cool. Makes 1 pie.
</P>
<P>
   PASTRY SHELL: Mix 1 3/4 cups flour and 1/4 cup sugar. Cut in 1
stick unsalted butter, 1 egg yolk and 1/2 teaspoon vanilla until
dough forms. Add a few drops water if needed. Fit pastry into a
9-inch pie pan. &QL; 
--- &QL; 
Can you help?
</P>
<P>
   If you have recipes that can help this reader, please send them
along to us at the address below to share in a future column.
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am looking for filled appetizer rolls made with lavosh or
thin flat bread that have been making the rounds. I've seen them
called hye rollers and other names. Does anyone have some recipes
to share with various fillings? _ Florence Feinner, Van Nuys &QL; 
---
</P>
<P>
   Cook's Corner welcomes recipe requests from readers. While we
cannot reply to them individually, we will answer those of general
interest in this column. Also, if you can help another reader with
a recipe request, write to Cook's Corner, Daily News Food
Department, P.O. Box 4200, Woodland Hills, Calif. 91365-4200.
Please be sure recipes specify exact package sizes, can and pan
sizes and baking times and temperatures.
</P>
<P>
   Recipes printed are from the source indicated and have not been
tested by the Daily News Food Department unless noted. &QL;
</P>
