<SLUG> BC-MCNAMARA-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PRESCRIPTION FOR HOPE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EILEEN MCNAMARA  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Srey Mom could neither speak nor sit last May when she arrived
at the home of Sally Stokes and Bob Luoma. At just under age 2 and
just over 10 pounds, she had never seen a toy, never tasted solid
food. Her universe had encompassed no more than she could see over
the sides of the cloth hammock where she lay dying, slowly but
certainly, in the back room of a Cambodian orphanage.
</P>
<P>
   She would be there still had Dr. Nancy Hendrie not rejected a
retirement ``of Bingo and bowling'' in favor of a medical career
re-directed toward the care of children in a country where $300 is
the average annual income.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharing Foundation, the nonprofit organization Hendrie
founded three years ago, has no paid staff, no inflated overhead.
The former pediatrician runs it out of her cottage in Woolwich,
Maine, personally bearing the cost of her many trips to Cambodia to
oversee projects the foundation funds to provide children's basic
needs for food, shelter, education and medical care.
</P>
<P>
   On one trip last winter, Hendrie discovered Srey Mom in a back
corner in Chom Chao Orphanage, outside Phnom Penh, where the
foundation has installed electricity and mosquito screening,
repaired the leaky roof and drainage system and hired a local
doctor to visit every Saturday. Abandoned at birth because of
congenital defects beyond the intercession of Cambodian medicine,
Srey Mom was being given miminal attention by a staff hardened to
the alarming death rate of so many orphans in its care.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't let her die,'' said Hendrie, knowing that the
expertise that could save her was a medical visa away in Boston.
Against bureaucratic odds and the foundation's philosophy of
undertaking projects to aid the maximum number of children, Hendrie
flew out of Cambodia with Srey Mom on her lap. With promises from
old friends at Massachusetts General Hospital, support from her
foundation's board and an offer of temporary foster care from
Stokes and Louma, Hendrie secured a visa for Srey Mom to have
surgery in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   In four months, under the care of Drs. Daniel P. Ryan and Ronald
E. Kleinman, the little girl with the saucer-sized eyes has had
five successful operations at MGH. The extra finger on each hand
and a toe on one foot have been removed. The defects in her
gastrointestinal tract have been repaired. The tumor in her brain
has been determined to be benign and no obstacle to a long life.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, Srey Mom will be re-admitted to MGH for the final
surgery to reverse a colostomy and connect the last link in her
gastrointestinal system. She will recuperate at the comfortable
Stokes-Louma home on a quiet rural road where she is doted on by
the couple's two teenage sons, former patients of Hendrie's, and
members of the family's local Unitarian church. It is amazing, said
Hendrie, to watch ``a child who'd never seen a toy at play in a
field of Fisher-Price.''
</P>
<P>
   The energy Hendrie exerted to save Srey Mom's life she is now
directing toward finding her a permanent home in Greater Boston.
Sally Stokes and Bob Luoma, of Carlisle, Mass., are too close to an
empty nest to provide more than temporary care to the chubby,
cooing imp who takes only seconds to scoot across the living room
carpet and into the tiled foyer. She is no longer the frightened
child who recoiled at the sight of Louma's beard or screamed at the
approach of the family cats. She laughs easily and often now,
turning for approval when she stands upright at the coffee table or
wrests Hendrie's watch from the doctor's arm. Having heard only
Khmer until last spring, she now plays peek-a-boo and waves bye-bye
in response to a request in English.
</P>
<P>
   Hendrie is convinced Srey Mom's developmental delays were caused
by her now resolved medical ills. ``There is a very bright little
girl in there ready to come out,'' said Hendrie, 68, the mother of
five children, one of them adopted. An adoptive family for Srey Mom
must have that rare combination of optimism and realism so crucial
to a child with special needs. ``There are no guarantees, even with
our own children, but Mom is a fighter. She should not be condemned
to life in a Cambodian orphanage when I just know she could do
great things someday! If I don't find her the right home, I'll
adopt her myself.''
</P>
<P>
   Inquiries about Srey Mom should be made to The Sharing
Foundation, Post Office Box 399, Woolwich, ME 04579 or by e-mail to
nhendrie (at)aol.com.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Eileen McNamara is a Boston Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
