<SLUG> BC-ONBUSINESS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THINK WAL-MART OF NET SOFTWARE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Way back in 1995, just a few years out of Macalester College,
Jeremy Allaire had a vision: that the Internet would be a big deal,
and there would be a huge market opportunity for a company that
provided software for the Net.
</P>
<P>
   It turned out he was right _ and early. The combination of the
two allowed Allaire Corp. to establish itself and grow to a
respectable size in a short time. In the second quarter of 2000,
the Newton, Mass. company had $33 million in sales and made a
profit to boot, the third straight quarter the firm has been in the
black.
</P>
<P>
   But the world has changed since 1995. A lot of companies now
realize that Net software represents a tremendous market, and a
long list of them provide something similar to what Allaire offers:
a software platform and applications that let customers do
everything from personalizing their Web sites to tracking
inventory.
</P>
<P>
   Competitors include giants such as IBM as well a host of
successful upstarts: BEA Systems, Silverstream, Art Technology
Group, and Vignette.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are competing in a crowded market that is in the process
of consolidating down,'' said Paul Krieg, an analyst with Legg
Mason.
</P>
<P>
   Does Allaire have a competitive edge that will help it survive
the coming shakeout? Krieg thinks it does. Not surprisingly, so
does the company. And that edge gets back to Jeremy Allaire's
original vision.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is our belief that the Internet is a mass phenomenon,''
said Allaire, now the company's chief technology officer. ``We
believe there will be tremendous growth, not just for 500
customers, but for thousands.''
</P>
<P>
   Allaire is attacking the mass market with products that are
significantly cheaper than those offered by the competition. A
customer who might spend $20,000 with Allaire could easily spend
$100,000 with one of its high-end rivals. Think Wal-Mart versus
Nordstrom, and you get some idea of how Allaire would like to
position itself vis-a-vis the competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are aiming at the fat part of the pyramid,'' said chief
executive David Orfao, a software veteran who has worked at both
Lotus and Apple. Orfao argues that Allaire's low prices will
encourage customers to use its software for more and more
functions.
</P>
<P>
   For now, Allaire thinks it can comfortably coexist with its
higher-ticket competitors. But what about in the future? Could some
of Allaire's rivals move downmarket and sell cheaper versions of
their software?
</P>
<P>
   Richard Davis doesn't think so. ``The big guys have an expensive
cost structure,'' said Davis, an analyst with Needham &AMP; Co. ``It
would be hard for them to retool.''
</P>
<P>
   Allaire has other strengths. Because its original product,
ColdFusion, has been around for a while, several hundred thousand
software developers already use it and know it. More recently,
Allaire has created a line of products that run on Java, a language
that is rapidly becoming the standard in the software world.
</P>
<P>
   On the financial side, Allaire's growth has been explosive. In
1999, sales reached $55 million. They should hit $140 million this
year and $218 million in 2001, said Steven Frankel, an analyst with
Adams, Harkness &AMP; Hill. Frankel expects profits to grow, but not as
rapidly as the top line. Allaire started the year with 350
employees; it should end the year with 700.
</P>
<P>
   The stock price has been moving in the opposite direction. After
hitting a peak of $88 in March, it plunged as low as $28 before
recovering to about $35. ``We like the stock; we wish it were
higher,'' said Davis, who blames much of the decline on the
broad-based sell-off in Nasdaq stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Allaire has consistently exceeded Wall Street expectations. But
like so many other tech companies today, it is facing a more
skeptical and a more cautious investment community.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street doesn't doubt that Allaire can grow rapidly for a
while. But it wants to know if the company is going to emerge as a
winner in the end, one with a distinct advantage that will separate
it from the pack.
</P>
<P>
   Frankel says investors want to see how deeply Allaire can
penetrate the operations of its customers. Will its products become
a standard that is used everywhere, or will they just be one of
many choices on a lengthy menu?
</P>
<P>
   Allaire may have to turn in a string of impressive quarters
before investors are ready to restore much of the market value that
has disappeared over the past five months.
</P>
<P>
   Jeremy Allaire says the opportunity is there. ``It is ours to
grab,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
