<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROUP HOPES FOR PROMISING COMEBACK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL PAULSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Remember the Promise Keepers?
</P>
<P>
   Founded 10 years ago by University of Colorado football coach
Bill McCartney, the controversial movement of Christian men burst
onto the national scene in 1997 when hundreds of thousands rallied
on the Mall in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   But the movement, which raised hackles among some women
concerned that the group undermines women's rights by advocating
for men to take charge within families, almost immediately seemed
to flame out. The group briefly laid off all 345 employees in a
tactic that critics said was just a fund-raising ploy and has since
scaled back some of its most expansive ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   But, quietly but surely, the Promise Keepers is rebuilding.
Their next gathering is scheduled for this weekend in Worcester,
Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The group sees constant evidence for its need. Spokesman Steve
Chavis pointed to the allegations of sexual misconduct against a
church worker in Middleton, Mass. and the death of a man in a
two-dad brawl at a hockey game in Reading, Mass. as evidence that
men are in trouble.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been addressing violence and anger and lust,'' Chavis
said.
</P>
<P>
   After two years of holding free conferences, the group is
healthy enough this year to resume charging fees ($69 for adults).
They retreated from an effort to start men's groups at churches and
decided to concentrate on their men's rallies _ now at mid-sized
regional arenas rather than giant stadiums.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are still drawing, although not to the degree they
were,'' said Dean Allen, a scholar at Andover Newton Theological
School who studies the Promise Keepers.
</P>
<P>
   The organization holds two-day rallies for men with a heavy
emphasis on facilitating personal encounters with Jesus,
encouraging greater attention to families and churches, and
battling racism.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just an amazing, inspirational thing,'' said Leslie H.
Stobbe, who has attended two Promise Keepers conferences and works
as a vice president of the evangelical Christian organization
Vision New England. ``Most churches really don't know how to
minister to men. The Promise Keepers has filled a real void in
men's lives, helping them focus on their spiritual side and their
emotional side, and it also has given them tools for how to relate
to their wife and kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1990, the Promise Keepers say they have reached 3.5
million men through 98 conferences during the decade. The group
encourages men to keep seven promises, from the religious (honor
Jesus) to the personal (pursue vital relationships with other men)
and the familial (build strong marriages and families).
</P>
<P>
   The group is evangelical and takes a conservative position on
many issues. The group believes the Bible is without error and
homosexuality is a sin.
</P>
<P>
   Although there is ongoing debate about the long-term value of
the Promise Keepers movement, the group has clearly tapped into a
new set of questions about the role of men in American families and
churches in the wake of the women's movement. Those concerns,
voiced first through the Iron John movement, are now evidenced in
the increasingly mainstream academic fields of men's studies and
the boomlet in books about the plight of boys.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Promise Keepers appeal to the confusion that men feel,
although I don't know that they addressed it at a deep enough
level,'' said Stephen Boyd, a professor of religion at Wake Forest
University in North Carolina and a pioneer in the study of men and
religion.
</P>
<P>
   Boyd said although the Promise Keepers' emphasis on the
spiritual was attractive, their attitudes toward gender
relationships troubled some, particularly women's groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``They advocate a kind of retreat into more traditional gender
roles as a way of solving issues and crises,'' he said. ``They were
controversial for good reason. But they are addressing some of the
questions men are facing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Can you please tell the history of rosary beads and clarify
their purpose? What is the origin of their use, and is it
appropriate for non-Catholics?
</P>
<P>
   J.M.H., Cape Cod, Mass. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. A rosary is a string of prayer beads used by worshipers as a
manual guide for various forms of repetitive prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Generally, the worshiper fingers one bead per prayer _ in this
way, the string of beads helps lead the worshiper through a set of
prayers.
</P>
<P>
   The most commonly known rosary is used by Catholics to guide
them through a series of devotional prayers honoring Mary, the
mother of Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   The rosary of Mary is not appropriate for use by Protestants,
said the Rev. Robert W. Thornburg, dean of Marsh Chapel and
professor of preaching at Boston University.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a specifically Roman Catholic devotion that prays to Mary
as the mother of God, and that's not an emphasis that Protestants
make,'' said Thornburg, who is a United Methodist minister. ``Mary
is not given the same veneration in Protestant theology as in
Catholic theology. The words of the rosary are not words that would
typically be helpful for Protestants.''
</P>
<P>
   There are other types of rosaries used in other traditions,
particularly Buddhism, Hinduism, Islam, and Eastern Orthodoxy, in
some cases by laity and in some cases by monks.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Encyclopaedia Britannica, the first Christian
uses of the rosary occurred in the 3d Century among Eastern
Christian monks. The Catholic practice of saying the rosary was
popularized by St. Dominic and his followers, and may have been
especially useful for the illiterate among the faithful who could
not read liturgical texts but could memorize the prayers associated
with the beads.
</P>
</TEXT>
