<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-ORTHODOX-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODERN ORTHODOX JEWS BLEND BEST OF BOTH WORLDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICHARD HIGGINS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Once a month the founders of technology start-ups trek
to a private dining room inside the posh Four Seasons Hotel to
pitch their new ideas to a 2-year-old group of Net-savvy investors.
</P>
<P>
   The investors, called the Common Angels, may typify the New
Economy, but the group's founder, David Solomont, has one foot
firmly grounded in a much more ancient world.
</P>
<P>
   Every weekday at 6:30 a.m., Solomont joins an informal
congregation of fellow Orthodox Jews for prayer at the Maimonides
School in Brookline, a Hebrew day school.
</P>
<P>
   Solomont says he easily passes between the old and new worlds in
which he lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``The beauty, for me, is that I don't really think about where
my `religious' life leaves off and my `regular' one begins,'' said
Solomont, part of a growing community of Orthodox Jews in Greater
Boston that today numbers about 6,000.
</P>
<P>
   The nomination of Connecticut Senator Joseph I. Lieberman as the
Democrats' vice presidential candidate has cast a spotlight on
Orthodox Jews, a small and relatively little-known but robust slice
of American Judaism.
</P>
<P>
   It is a world where navigating the sacred and the secular
requires balancing the demands of ritual, tradition, and religious
laws with the realities and challenges of modern life.
</P>
<P>
   And despite common stereotypes of Orthodox Jewry as a monolithic
group of bearded men in black hats living apart from contemporary
society, three out of four Orthodox Jews in the Boson area are,
like Lieberman, modern or centrist Orthodox.
</P>
<P>
   It is a strain of Orthodoxy that stresses engagement with the
world while remaining faithful to Jewish law and practice.
</P>
<P>
   ``Modern Orthodox means having a serious religious outlook
that's rooted in Jewish tradition but that also expresses itself in
a deep commitment to the world today,'' said Barry Shrage, an
Orthodox Jew and executive director of Combined Jewish
Philanthropies of Greater Boston.
</P>
<P>
   For Jeffrey Kosowsky, being an Orthodox Jew means weaving
religious practices that go to the heart of who he is with the rest
of his life.
</P>
<P>
   The Sabbath, from sundown Friday to sundown Saturday, is
inviolate to Kosowsky, who works at McKinsey &AMP; Co., a management
consulting firm. Work is out of the question and he asks his
clients not to disturb him.
</P>
<P>
   But the Sabbath also means not turning lights on and off, no
driving, writing, cooking, handling money, or participating in any
frivolities at odds with ``godlike activities on a godlike day,''
he said. Because he can't drive on the Sabbath, Kosowsky, like all
Orthodox Jews, lives within walking distance of the temple in which
he worships, Young Israel, a modern Orthodox synagogue in
Brookline.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Kosowsky said, ``I really believe I can be a complete
citizen of our society on any number of levels and still be true to
my tradition.''
</P>
<P>
   But being an Orthodox Jew goes well beyond honoring the Sabbath;
it permeates every aspect of Kosowsky's life.
</P>
<P>
   Each morning, he dons a fringed prayer shawl and fastens
(itals)tefilin(unitals) _ tiny cases holding Biblical passages _ to
his head and body, and prays, a time which he calls his most
relaxing time of day. Although he does not wear a skullcap at work,
he does wear a (itals)tzitzit,(unitals) a garment with fringes of
thread next to his skin to remind him of his prayers.
</P>
<P>
   ``My religion is a way of life that affects everything I do, not
just my going to synagogue or performing a certain ritual,''
Kosowsky said. ``It's really all-encompassing.''
</P>
<P>
   About one-fourth of the Boston area's Orthodox Jews adhere to a
more right-wing Orthodoxy, which is more traditional and separatist
than modern Orthodoxy. Followers typically do not read secular
newspapers such as The Boston Globe, and bar television from their
homes. It is often allied with Hasidic or more mystical forms of
Judaism.
</P>
<P>
   These highly observant Orthodox Jews often call themselves
Haredim, viewing the term ``ultra-Orthodox'' as pejorative. At
their schools, Mesivta High School of Greater Boston, a new high
school in Boston's Brighton section, and Bais Yaakov, a
five-year-old high school in Newton, boys and girls are kept apart.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, at the 63-year-old Maimonides School, which is
modern Orthodox in orientation, boys and girls study together.
</P>
<P>
   Some Jews straddle both worlds. Deborah Kram, who founded a
Torah study program for women, belongs to Young Israel, as well as
Congregation Beth Pinchas, which is Hasidic. She said she feels
welcome in both.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up as a modern Orthodox Jew, and that remains my
worldview and where I'm most comfortable,'' said Kram. ``But I
sometimes go to Beth Pinchas because I find the rebbe to be a
wonderful model of loving kindness. I enjoy praying in his four
walls.''
</P>
<P>
   She said the core of Orthodox Judaism is ``the understanding
that the laws we live by are divinely mandated. Of course, they're
given to man to adjudicate, but they are created by God.''
</P>
<P>
   Together, modern and right-wing Orthodox Jews make up between 7
and 10 percent of the nation's 5 million Jews, according to Shrage.
But they account for only 3 percent of the 200,000 Jews who live
within Interstate 495.
</P>
<P>
   Rabbi Jacob Schacter, the founding dean of a new, $10 million
national center for modern Orthodoxy located in Brookline, the
Soloveitchik Institute, said Lieberman's role is raising the public
profile of modern Orthodoxy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that the world in which we live in is an important
place to which we need to contribute and from which we can learn,''
said Schacter. ``Modern Orthodox Jews value openness to the
world.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Kram: ``The touchstone of modern Orthodoxy is involving
yourself in the world in hopes of repairing it, which Lieberman is
a perfect example of.''
</P>
<P>
   All Orthodox Jews agree on the Torah as the divinely revealed
word of God, said Schacter, and reject the liberal Jewish notion
that the word of God can be adapted to modern realities.
</P>
<P>
   Orthodox Jews worship almost entirely in Hebrew, unlike Reform
and Conservative Jews. In contrast to Reform Jews, Orthodox Jews
oppose same-sex unions and unlike Reform and Conservative Jews they
do not permit women to be rabbis.
</P>
<P>
   But modern Orthodoxy permits some flexibility in interpreting
nonbinding matters of tradition, such as in the wearing of a
skullcap or (itals)kippah.(unitals)
</P>
<P>
   And it allows for some creativity, if one can afford it: When
Solomont vacations on Nantucket, he has two traditional Sabbath
meals _ after prayer on Friday night and on Saturday afternoon _
flown directly to him from Levana, a kosher restaurant in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Across this area Orthodox Judaism is surging _ membership at
Orthodox synagogues is rising as is enrollment at Hebrew day
schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``It appears that more people are leading observant lives than
they were 10, 20, or 30 years ago,'' said Solomont, 48, who prefers
the term ``observant'' rather than Orthodox Jew. ``More people are
keeping kosher, going to synagogue, and following a traditional
Jewish way of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Solomont said nothing in his work life interferes with his being
Orthodox. ``If someone wants to do business with me from sundown
Friday to sundown Saturday, they haven't got a prayer of reaching
me,'' he said. ``The Sabbath is strictly my family time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-00 1335EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000823.0125 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 13:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A9961 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a BC-MA-COURTS-EXPERT-BOS &LR;      08-23 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-COURTS-EXPERT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SJC TELLS JUDGES TO EVALUATE EXPERTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RALPH RANALLI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ In a ruling that legal observers say will dramatically
raise the bar for the testimony of expert witnesses in
Massachusetts trials, the Supreme Judicial Court has ordered judges
to take a more active role in evaluating technical claims and
keeping so-called ``junk science'' out of the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the SJC adopted a standard that will make it
much tougher to appeal a judge's ruling on the validity of
scientific or expert testimony. The cumulative effect, legal
experts say, will be to greatly strengthen the role of trial court
judges as gatekeepers separating valid scientific evidence and
testimony from unreliable opinions or even outright quackery.
</P>
<P>
   Observers also predicted that the ruling could restrict the
amount of scientific testimony and potentially shift the balance of
power in both civil and criminal cases. Defendants in product
liability and personal injury cases _ automakers, for example _ may
now have an advantage over those who sue them, lawyers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an important decision,'' said Albert Zabin, a Boston
attorney who has lectured on the use of expert witnesses.
``Essentially it gives the trial court a lot more of the final
decision-making power.''
</P>
<P>
   The ruling came in a case brought by a former Brigham and
Women's Hospital nurse, Theresa Canavan, who was awarded workers'
compensation disability insurance by a state Industrial Accidents
Board judge in 1995. Canavan maintained she developed a disorder
known as ``multiple chemical sensitivity'' from working in the
hospital's operating rooms.
</P>
<P>
   Her claim was upheld by a state appeals court, but on Thursday
the SJC sided with lawyers for the hospital, who said that the
judge incorrectly admitted the testimony of Dr. Thomas LaCava, a
University of Massachusetts Medical School pediatrician who had
made Canavan's diagnosis. LaCava is also a member of the American
Board of Environmental Medicine, but the court found that the field
is not recognized by the American Board of Medical Specialties.
</P>
<P>
   Multiple chemical sensitivity sufferers say that exposure to
chemicals, dyes and even perfumes can trigger allergic reactions
and even seizures. Though opinion in the medical community is
mixed, a growing number of people say they suffer from the disorder
and are spawning cottage industries for dye- and perfume-free
household products and chemical-free ``clean'' houses.
</P>
<P>
   In the original trial LaCava admitted under cross-examination
that 50 percent of doctors who see an alleged case of multiple
chemical sensitivity diagnose it as a psychological ailment, not a
physical one.
</P>
<P>
   The SJC ruled that the judge should not have accepted LaCava's
diagnosis, which was based on his ``experience'' with other
multiple chemical sensitivity cases rather than on a scientific
rationale.
</P>
<P>
   ``That a person qualifies as an expert does not endow his
testimony with magic qualities,'' the justices wrote in a sweeping
18-page opinion that brings state law into line with recent US
Supreme Court decisions on expert testimony.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital's attorney, Matthew Walko, praised Thursday's
ruling, saying that in some prior cases, all a judge would look at
was the expert's credentials, and if he had a great resume, he
could say whatever he wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``This decision says that even if someone is a true expert, the
court must look at the theory they are using, and that theory must
be scientifically valid,'' Walko said.
</P>
<P>
   The last expansion by the SJC of a trial judge's role in judging
expert testimony came in a 1994 case, Commonwealth v. Lanigan,
which paved the way for the use of DNA evidence at trials. In
Lanigan, the justices held that courts could consider ``novel''
scientific evidence even if it had yet to be accepted by the
scientific community.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the high court made it more difficult to
appeal a judge's ruling. Before Thursday, the losing side in a case
could appeal the winning side's use of an expert on a ``de novo''
basis _ essentially meaning that the higher court would start from
scratch and take a fresh look at whether the scientific evidence
was valid.
</P>
<P>
   The justices held that, given the rapid advance of science and
technology, having appellate courts making sweeping legal rulings
on scientific evidence was potentially as bad as admitting junk
science. Such rulings could ``freeze'' outdated scientific opinions
in the law and keep them from being updated by newer and better
science, the court held.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new standard, the losing side will have a more
difficult task _ showing an ``abuse of discretion'' by the trial
judge.
</P>
<P>
   ``In layman's language, the judge has to be off the wall in his
decision,'' Zabin said. Essentially, (the ruling) renders most
questions almost unappealable.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers for defendants in product liability cases praised the
ruling, while attorneys for plaintiffs warned that it could give
corporations an advantage over citizens harmed by their products.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there are going to be fewer decisions that are junk
science decisions,'' said Donald D. Evans, senior counsel for the
American Chemistry Council, which filed a ``friend of the court''
brief in the case. ``We are seeing it around the country. Decisions
not based on sound science are getting thrown out, which we think
is a good trend.''
</P>
<P>
   Boston attorney Michael Weisman, who has sued auto
manufacturers, chemical companies, and equipment manufacturers on
behalf of accident victims, warned that the ruling could take too
much power away from juries.
</P>
<P>
   ``The judge could turn himself into the primary decision maker,
rather than the jury,'' Weisman said.
</P>
<P>
   In the short run, the ruling appeared to be a setback for
multiple chemical sensitivity sufferers, said Canavan's attorney,
Peter F. Brady.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously my client and I are very disappointed in the
decision,'' Brady said. ``When I first started handling these cases
seven years ago I was skeptical, too, but I have found that these
are perhaps the most profoundly disabled people I have ever seen.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
