<HEADLINE>
HAPPINESS ELUDES US; KEANU STILL INSCRUTABLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Since it became a weekly, Us, now technically known as Us
Weekly, has been straining to be a sort of People magazine but with
better boundaries. It's quite eager to track the lives of the
celebrities, but it tries to stalk its Hollywood prey with a veneer
of reportorial distance and good taste. It serves up the dish, from
Angelina and Billy Bob to the ruthless ``Survivor'' castaways, but
it's unwilling to add the popular emotionalism that People thrives
on, and it carefully avoids the appearance of tabloid insinuation _
even in its layout, which is more like the orderly Entertainment
Weekly than the chaotic tabloids.
</P>
<P>
   Can the gossipy People formula work without all the loose affect
and juicy, irresponsible detail? Time will tell Us. This week, Us
attempts a classically People-esque feature about whether our
favorite stars are really truly happy, and whether money and fame
can actually buy contentment. It's the sort of vapid inquiry that
manages to cut to the core of America's love and hatred for
celebrity _ we like to envy the stars' fantasy lives, but then we
also want to look down on them, to feel better about ourselves. The
piece begs for garishness, shameless rumor, and camp.
</P>
<P>
   But Us answers the happiness question with a quasi-scientific
method that's dull as can be. First, the writer chats up the
experts, including Hilary Swank's therapist, Holly Hein,
concluding, ``In the end, then, it seems that when it comes to
happiness, celebrities have it no better than us.'' Then, amid
sidebars including a poll of stylists and caterers (Robert Downey
Jr. is ``extremely happy to have found freedom from drugs and from
prison,'' opines one food-service worker), there are happiness
ratings for a host of stars, denoted by a yellow smiley face whose
expression ranges from ecstatic to blase.
</P>
<P>
   Britney Spears is unhappy because, when her concerts are over,
she's ``all alone (except for those rare moments when reported
boyfriend Justin Timberlake keeps her company).'' Demi Moore is
``semi-happy'' because she's found a new love since Bruce Willis,
but her career has been disappointing of late. Gwyneth Paltrow,
too, is semi-happy, because she is still haunted by her breakup
with Brad Pitt. Pitt, of course, is happy (what about his career
disappointment?), as is his new wife, Jennifer Aniston. Also making
it onto the happy list: Regis and Joy Philbin, Christopher Reeve,
and Ellen DeGeneres and Anne Heche _ ooops.
</P>
<P>
   Well, every scientific methodology has its limitations, if not
its sense of humor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Rolling Stone for Aug. 31 profiles two stubbornly unprofilable
celebrities, Keanu Reeves and Hugh Hefner. Reeves, now in the
middle of a few movie releases and a new album by his band Dogstar,
evades writers Chris Heath's questions with an inane haiku-speak
that allows him to throw out non sequitur comments like ``It's a
particle, it's a wave.'' How does he feel about have been
considered a dumb himbo in the early years of his career? ``There's
something good about it, something bad, something happy, something
sad.'' Something true, too, perhaps?
</P>
<P>
   Heath makes the most of his clammed-up subject, as does Wil S.
Hylton, who finds Hefner inscrutable despite the Silk Pajama'd
One's professed desire to share the real story. All he can find out
is that the Playboy founder is neither an exploitive wolf, nor a
smooth ladies' man. He's a Gatsby-esque shadow figure who sneaks
out of his own infamous parties, and he exudes a fragility that
Hylton never really understands.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the piece, Hylton, who spends plenty of time
partying at the mansion, uncovers a basic conflict about Hefner,
but fails to address it directly. For Hefner believes that a moral
man can be a sexual man, that ``when we repress our sexual
instincts, we enter a world of denial and shame that undercuts the
foundation of civilized society.'' And his party life in the
mansion reflects that believe. But despite all the good times,
despite the ever-present peace pipe in his mouth, he appears to be
a quietly but profoundly unhappy man.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Time throws the quartet from HBO's ``Sex and the City'' onto its
cover, to illustrate its trend piece on women who are embracing the
single life and not feeling compelled to be married. Called
``Flying Solo,'' the article feels dated, thin, and dangerously
promotional, since HBO is owned by Time Warner. Like Ally McBeal,
the women on ``Sex and the City'' don't exactly love the single
life, after all, except the sexually voracious Samantha, who is the
show's comic relief. They are on a constant prowl to find love,
happiness, and breakfast at Tiffany's, and this season at least one
of them, Charlotte, seems to have caught herself a groom who looks
like a wedding-cake figure. There's something 1990s about Time's
package, which might at least have seemed fresh when sitcoms were
deluged by single women in the city, including the great Elaine
Benes of ``Seinfeld.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-00 1338EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
