<SLUG> BC-WIRED-CLOTHES-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     LEVI TO OFFER JACKET FOR THOSE WHO WANT TO TALK, LISTEN 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By VICTORIA COLLIVER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In what Levi Strauss &AMP; Co. is hailing as the
first wearable electronics product, the European division of the
jeans maker and Dutch electronics company Philips NV will release a
line of jackets branded IDC+.
</P>
<P>
   The jackets, which will only be available in Europe and cost
$600 to $900, come equipped with a mobile phone and MP3 player, a
remote-control device plus ear gear and a microphone integrated
into the collar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Loads of people have been talking about wearable technology .
. . but we are the first company to turn this into a commercial
venture,'' said Paola Brandi, a spokeswoman at Levi's European
headquarters in Brussels.
</P>
<P>
   The IDC+ jackets (the name stands for Industrial Clothing Design
Plus) come in four styles and will be available next month.
</P>
<P>
   Each of the four styles has an integrated system with wires
concealed throughout the jacket connecting the Philips Xenium GSM
mobile phone, which has voice command and dialing capabilities, to
a Philips Rush MP3 player. The devices are controlled through a
built-in remote.
</P>
<P>
   Levi Strauss realizes the jacket may have limited appeal.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's going to be mostly targeted to people like film directors
and television crews, people who like to carry their technology
around with them,'' Brandi said.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Beckman, a spokesman at Levi headquarters in San Francisco,
said there were no plans to introduce the jacket in the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a test,'' he said. ``There aren't going to be many
produced initially. It's an opportunity to see what the market
is.''
</P>
<P>
   Philips has been experimenting with wearable technology,
sometimes called smart or intelligent clothing, since 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the research products on the Philips Internet site
include ski clothing that could have built-in ski passes, radio
links, Global Positioning Systems or temperature sensors. Other
ideas include invisible collar microphones and miniature cameras
woven into clothing.
</P>
<P>
   Nike Inc. is designing a line of clothing that can accommodate
an MP3 player. A joint effort between Timex Corp. and Motorola Inc.
has produced a pager-watch-organizer, and Swatch Group Ltd. plans
to come out next Christmas with Swatch Talk, a combined cell phone
and watch.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Mann, a professor in the electrical engineering department
at the University of Toronto, has been experimenting with wearable
technology since 1982. So to Mann, a jacket that allows the wearer
to carry electronic gadgets is not that impressive.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be all well and good, but they have no real
practicality beyond other than, say, putting your cell phone in
your pocket,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the benefit of this, and have they really considered
some of the fundamental concepts such as protection from
radiation?'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   One of Mann's projects involves computers embedded in clothing
that emit radar to help blind people detect stationary and moving
objects.
</P>
<P>
   While Mann admits some of the bulky wearable computers he
developed 20 years ago were considered outlandish, he said the
concept of incorporating technology and clothing is almost
mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, there's so much hype about it,'' he said. ``I don't think
it (public acceptance) is much of a problem anymore.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
