<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CANADA-LOBSTERS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIAN DEFIANCE INFLAMES CANADA'S LOBSTER WAR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By COLIN NICKERSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BURNT CHURCH, New Brunswick _ On the choppy waters of Miramichi
Bay, Indian lobster fishermen wearing bulletproof vests instead of
life vests play cat-and-mouse games with enforcement officers from
the federal Department of Fisheries and Oceans, with both sides'
high-powered craft cutting and weaving in close proximity. From
time to time, the Indians hurl pails of fish guts at the gray
patrol boats carrying the Maple Leaf ensign, hooting and jeering
when an officer is splattered.
</P>
<P>
   Onshore, greasy black smoke billowing from the barricades of
junk vehicles, spruce logs, and scrap lumber blocking Route 11 _
one of the province's most-frequented tourist routes _ signals a
season of anger and defiance on the Indian reserves of Atlantic
Canada.
</P>
<P>
   A dispute over how much lobster Indians should be allowed to
haul from the sea, and _ above all _ whether ``white'' government
has any right to regulate commercial fishing by aboriginal tribes,
has triggered Canada's most dangerous confrontation between natives
and authorities in a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Looming over the violence in the lobster fishery is a larger
question: Do native people possess a special ethnic right to
natural resources precious to all Canadians?
</P>
<P>
   No, answer fisheries officials, who have repeatedly arrested
Mi'kmaq Indians this month for setting hundreds of illegal lobster
traps in New Brunswick's Miramichi Bay and Nova Scotia's St. Mary's
Bay, and have at times subdued violators with pepper spray during
boat deck brawls.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, answer Indians, who have sought to repel enforcement
boarding parties from their boats and docks with fists, baseball
bats, and fishing gaffs. One fisheries officer received skull
injuries Tuesday after being pelted with rocks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only one thing is clear,'' said Jean-Marc Lanteigne, a
spokesman for Canada's Department of Fisheries and Oceans. ``The
situation is highly dangerous, and everyone needs to be very
careful.''
</P>
<P>
   Natives say they are fighting for more than just lobster. Last
week, Matthew Coon Come, militant new grand chief of the Assembly
of First Nations, stunned environmentalists by saying aboriginal
people cannot be forbidden from hunting endangered species.
</P>
<P>
   Coon Come declared that Indians will not be bound by Canada's
new federal endangered species law, which comes into effect this
fall after decades of debate. He said people of the so-called First
Nations _ collective name for the 800,000 Indians and Eskimos
living on 2,370 reserves _ will continue to hunt bowhead whales and
Peary caribou, both near extinction.
</P>
<P>
   Lobsters are not endangered, of course. The big-clawed
crustacean became Canada's most valuable catch in the 1990s after
the collapse of Newfoundland's cod stocks, an economic and
environmental catastrophe caused by overfishing.
</P>
<P>
   The lobster harvest is worth $305 million a year to Nova Scotia,
Prince Edward Island, New Brunswick, and Quebec. But catches have
slumped in recent years, with 90.3 million pounds landed in 1998,
down from 104.7 million pounds at the beginning of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   The decline is not alarming, but fishermen, conservationists,
and fisheries officials say it points to the need to continue
tightly restricting numbers of ``tagged,'' or legal, traps and
limiting fishing communities to lobster seasons lasting only a few
weeks a year.
</P>
<P>
   But Indians, boosted by a landmark Canadian Supreme Court ruling
last fall, are asserting a right to place thousands of new traps in
heavily-fished waters, saying Ottawa has no authority over native
fishing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will fish and fish and fish, as the Supreme Court has shown
to be our traditional right,'' said Chief Reg Maloney of Nova
Scotia's Indian Brook Mi'kmaq band, whose members have been
repeatedly arrested for illegal catches hauled from St. Mary's Bay.
``The fisheries police are dressed for war, and we will meet them.
If tragedy comes, it comes.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-nine of Atlantic Canada's 34 Mi'kmaq and Maliseet bands
have signed temporary agreements with Ottawa, agreeing to abide by
fishing laws for one year in exchange for tens of millions of
dollars worth of free boats, traps, and other fishing gear, as well
as extremely valuable lobster licenses bought from white fishermen.
But there is deepening fear in fishing communities of an Indian
rush to the lobstering grounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any sign of weakening by Ottawa will be a go-ahead for even
more illegal activity,'' said Denny Morrow, a white fisherman from
southern Nova Scotia. ``This isn't just about native rights, it's
about protecting a natural resource. If the lobsters are
overfished, we're all going down, native and non-native.''
</P>
<P>
   But defiance is in the wind at the impoverished Burnt Church
reserve, where self-described Mi'kmaq ``warriors'' last week
blocked sections of Route 11 with blazing barricades. They forced
Royal Canadian Mounted Police to divert thousands of cars, many
carrying visitors from New England, away from the main thoroughfare
to the province's beach resorts at the height of tourist season.
</P>
<P>
   Despite bluster from Ottawa, Burnt Church natives continued to
harvest lobster from Miramichi Bay during the closed summer season,
saying they intend to place 5,000 pots in the water and issue their
own lobstering licenses.
</P>
<P>
   Indian leaders from across Canada, meanwhile, rallied to support
the rebellious reserve. Grand Chief Coon Come pointedly feasted on
illegal lobster after giving a speech of encouragement to Burnt
Church natives.
</P>
<P>
   ``All this hassle because First Nations people, the poorest of
the poor, the most marginalized and dispossessed, are trying to
catch a few lobster to earn a living,'' said Coon Come, a Quebec
Cree.
</P>
<P>
   The fuse was lit last fall when the Canadian Supreme Court sent
shock waves through fishing communities with a historic ruling that
upheld treaties signed by England's King George II in the 1760s
guaranteeing Mi'kmaq and Maliseet Indians of the Maritime provinces
the right to fish and hunt on scale sufficient to earn a ``modest
livelihood,'' not simply put food on the table.
</P>
<P>
   It has long been customary in eastern Canada for natives to
snare small quantities of lobster and fish for their own families,
but the vaguely worded ruling seemed to hold that Indians have a
racial right to catch any fish or crustacean in commercial
quantities without federal licenses or adherence to conservation
laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it told us was that First Nations can make our own
fishing rules and control our own destiny,'' said James Ward, a
firebrand young leader at the Burnt Church Mi'kmaq reserve.
``That's what this is really all about _ control.''
</P>
<P>
   In the aftermath of the high court's ruling, docks and bays in
New Brunswick, Nova Scotia, and Prince Edward Island became the
scene of showdowns between natives and white fishermen. Near the
impoverished Burnt Church reserve, hundreds of native-owned lobster
traps and fishing boats were vandalized; in retaliation, a
white-owned house and several pickup trucks were torched.
</P>
<P>
   As the one-year anniversary of the court ruling approaches, the
threat of violence hangs heavy in the salt air as natives assert
their perceived right to set as many lobster traps as they choose
and to harvest lobster even during closed seasons.
</P>
<P>
   So explosive is the issue that the Supreme Court, after its
original decision, issued an extraordinary ``clarification,''
saying that it meant only to uphold a ``limited'' right for
Indians, and that the goverment has authority to regulate
aboriginal fishing in the interests of conservation.
</P>
<P>
   Fisheries Minister Herb Dhaliwal vowed this week that natives
will not be allowed to fish illegally. But Indian lobster catching
continues, and many white fishermen fret over the prospect of a
``political'' compromise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It worries me what kind of deal is going to be made at the end
of this,'' said Ron Cormier, president of the Maritime Fishermen's
Union. ``The goal should be protecting stocks _ making everyone
fish by the same rules.''
</P>
</TEXT>
