<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KATZENMOYER, VAUGHN KEEP TABS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Two players from different professional sports, friends
for no apparent reason other than a mutual admiration, were 30
miles apart Tuesday: Patriots linebacker Andy Katzenmoyer at
Foxboro Stadium in Foxborough, and Anaheim Angels first baseman Mo
Vaughn in the visitors' clubhouse at Fenway Park in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wait a minute,'' said Vaughn, as he reached into his locker
for a game jersey and pulled out a pen to sign it. ``Give this to
Andy. Tell him I'll catch up to him this winter.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn is a longtime Ohio State football fan; he even befriended
running back Eddie George, the former Buckeye now playing with the
Tennessee Titans. In his Red Sox days, Vaughn would visit Columbus,
Ohio, after the baseball season to take in Ohio State games. On one
such trip in 1996, he noticed a freshman linebacker: Katzenmoyer.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I played linebacker, I'd want to play it like Andy,'' said
Vaughn. ``I just got into his style of play. It was so exciting.
The way he hit people. The energy he had out on the field. He was
just a player that I started to follow and admire.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn expressed his admiration for Katzenmoyer to the Buckeye
trainers, who provided him with Katzenmoyer jerseys. Soon the two
players began sending each other jerseys and game equipment as
souvenirs. A friendship began.
</P>
<P>
   When asked about it Tuesday, Katzenmoyer couldn't recall ever
meeting Vaughn in person, though Vaughn thought the two had said
hello briefly in the Buckeye locker room years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``No professional athlete had ever recognized me like that,''
said Katzenmoyer. ``I had a famous disc jockey, Sugar Ray, wear my
jersey on TV, but never a professional athlete like Mo. I was so
flattered. When you're a kid in school and someone with that kind
of a name pays attention to you like that, that's a thrill.''
</P>
<P>
   It was even more of a thrill for Vaughn when Katzenmoyer was
drafted by the Patriots last year. Vaughn still makes his offseason
home in Easton, not too far from Foxborough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I admire him as a player,'' said Katzenmoyer. ``I've always
liked home run hitters and guys who drive in a lot of runs in
baseball. Mo fits that, all right. I always watch for him on
`SportsCenter' to see what he's up to and followed all of the
things he went through here in Boston when the Red Sox didn't sign
him. I think he's happy in California, but I wish he were here with
the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what impresses me most about him is what a great
person he is. All of the charitable things he does for kids is so
amazing. He's so gracious. I think he sets such a high standard for
everyone else in professional sports to give back and be thankful
for everything we have as professional athletes. That's why when I
knew that Mo was a fan of mine, I thought that's really great
because he's such a good person.''
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn thought that the defensive schemes used by Ohio State
during Katzenmoyer's junior season ``set him back a little bit.''
Last year, said Vaughn, ``Andy got a chance to get his feet wet in
the NFL to see what playing in the league is all about. Now, you
watch, he's going to go back to being the `Big Cat' like he was at
Ohio State. The Patriots are going to find he's going to be a great
player for them in the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Katzenmoyer certainly has had an impressive camp in Bill
Belichick's 3-4 defense. Having two large linebackers in the middle
_ like the 6-foot-3-inch, 255-pound Katzenmoyer and the 6-4,
250-pound Ted Johnson _ is basically what Belichick wants, in the
long run. Johnson, though, has been out for virtually the entire
preseason with a hamstring injury and Katzenmoyer jammed his
shoulder last week, missing the Tampa Bay game Sunday. His status
for Thursday night's game vs. Carolina is uncertain.
</P>
<P>
   After Johnson tore his biceps in a scrimmage last August,
Katzenmoyer got to start 11 games as a rookie, which was great
on-the-job training. He had been penciled in as an outside
linebacker to replace Todd Collins but had to take a crash course
in the middle linebacker position.
</P>
<P>
   After the season, he went back to Ohio State and worked with
Buckeye strength coach Dave Kennedy, who helped him get bigger and
stronger. When he reported for camp this year, it was obvious he
had taken his conditioning and strength work seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I always liked the fact that he worked so hard,'' said Vaughn.
``The guys at Ohio State always said he works so hard in the weight
room. He played like a madman out there. I'd see some highlights on
ESPN and I'd say, ``Man, he's tough.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Katzenmoyer said he played baseball through his sophomore year
in high school before devoting his time to football. He said of
Vaughn, ``I admire him as an athlete because to have the mental and
physical ability to play 162 games in a season, that's amazing to
me. To be able to go out every day and play in a competitive game
that means something and come up with the big hits he's come up
with . . . I mean, that to me is a great athlete. It's something
that's hard for me to understand as a football player who plays
once a week.''
</P>
<P>
   Judging by the way Vaughn is built, Katzenmoyer said, he
probably could have done some damage on the football field.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of these days, I'd like to be able to spend some time with
him, just hang around,'' said Katzenmoyer. ``Our lives are so busy
that we haven't found the time to really just sit down and talk.
I'll always be interested in him.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah,'' concurred Vaughn, ``I'll catch up to him this winter.
Is he playing this week? Make sure he gets the jersey; maybe it'll
give him some good luck.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
