<SLUG> BC-EARLY-CHRISTMAS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ONLINE FIRMS RUSH TO JUMP-START THE HOLIDAYS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEPHANIE STOUGHTON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR; Back-to-school sales have yet to run their course and most
stores are still weeks away from stocking their shelves with
plastic pumpkins and masks. But on the Web, you can see the signs
of Christmas already.
</P>
<P>
   In the heat of summer, Museumshop.com mailed ``Christmas in July
. . . or August'' promotions to tens of thousands of consumers,
encouraging them to shop early for the holiday.
</P>
<P>
   Lillian Vernon, a catalog and online retailer, plans to
redecorate its Web site with Christmas merchandise next month
instead of in October. Online music retailer CDnow.com and
gift-seller Ashford.com also plan to jump-start the season weeks
before consumers begin basting their Thanksgiving turkeys.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our holiday products are coming in now,'' said Mary Lou
Kelley, Ashford.com's marketing vice president. ``We will be
locked, loaded, and ready to go by Nov. 1.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when the Macy's Thanksgiving Day parade
signaled the debut of the holiday shopping season. Those days are
long gone. Today, retailers will do just about anything to prolong
consumer spending and get an early indication of how shoppers will
behave during the fourth quarter, which can account for as much as
80 percent of annual profits.
</P>
<P>
   Web retailers have even more incentive to encourage early
holiday shopping: preventing a repeat of the last-minute crunch
that contributed to last year's bumper crop of online shopping
disasters.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say the dot-coms no longer can afford to make mistakes
now that many of them are running low on cash and having trouble
finding new investment as they struggle to become stable
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, several Internet retailers angered customers by
failing to deliver in time for the holidays. Forced to rush to the
malls just a few days before Christmas, many online shoppers vowed
they wouldn't give the offending sites a second chance.
</P>
<P>
   Federal regulators were displeased, too. Last month, the Federal
Trade Commission heaped $1.5 million in fines on CDnow, KBKids.com,
Toysrus.com, Macys.com, and three other online retailers that
failed to properly notify shoppers about shipping delays during the
past holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   But even large retailers with extensive experience in managing
inventories and shipping orders say the last-minute holiday crowds
on the Web can be daunting. ``Even for us, those four weeks before
Christmas become a challenge,'' said David Hochberg, a spokesman
for Lillian Vernon Corp., which has been in the catalog business
for nearly a half century. ``Your order curve just skyrockets.''
</P>
<P>
   The stakes are high. From the sidelines, investors are watching
to see which Internet retailers deserve their attention. They have
not been impressed with the scores that have been unable to show a
path to profitability.
</P>
<P>
   In the past year, they have pulled support from cash-burning Web
stores such as Toysmart.com, Craftshop.com, and Boo.com. Other
virtual retailers are slashing advertising budgets and laying off
employees in an effort to stay alive. As traditional companies
continue to flex their muscles online, all but the strongest and
smartest virtual retailers will have a tough time surviving after
Christmas, industry observers say.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the explosive growth in the Web marketplace is
expected to continue. Jupiter Communications Inc. estimates that
online retail sales more than doubled to $7 billion in the last two
months of last year from $3.1 billion during the same period a year
earlier.
</P>
<P>
   With online retail sales expected to soar once again this
holiday season, it doesn't hurt to get a few shoppers in the door
months in advance, industry observers said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an admirable goal,'' said Scott Silverman, Internet
retailing vice president with the National Retail Federation. ``If
you can condition some of your holiday shoppers to shop over a
longer period of time, there are a whole slew of benefits.''
</P>
<P>
   Internet retailers say they're only serving the interests of
customers who shop early to avoid the last-minute rush and pick
from the best selection of merchandise. But they may discover that
their shoppers instead want to play a game of chicken, said Kenneth
M. Gassman, a retail analyst with Davenport &AMP; Co. in Richmond.
</P>
<P>
   Each year, retailers try to stick to their original prices as
long as possible, Gassman said. And each year, consumers twiddle
their thumbs, waiting for retailers to begin slashing prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone wants to wait till the last minute,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gassman points out that many Internet retailers are still
learning how to play the retail game _ one reason why some of them
were late focusing on the last year's Christmas season.
Ashford.com, for example, was involved in huge expansion in the
fall of 2000 and as a result was not as prepared to handle holiday
orders as executives would have liked. This year, Web retailers
seem to be leaving nothing to chance.
</P>
<P>
   Still, not all customers like the idea of seeing Santas and
sleds on the Web so early _ just as they might cringe at the sight
of malls decked in holly when they're looking for backpacks and
Dracula capes.
</P>
<P>
   About 62 percent of customers expressed annoyance at stores and
catalogs selling holiday merchandise long before Christmas,
according to a 1998 survey by Maritz Marketing Research Inc. The
poll also found that men were more likely than women to be irked by
the early arrival of Christmas retailing.
</P>
<P>
   Wary of a consumer backlash, some Internet retailers say they
prefer to keep the holiday season under wraps.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not exactly decking our halls with boughs of holly just
yet,'' said John Zimmermann, merchandising vice president for
SmarterKids.com, a Needham online seller of educational toys. ``We
don't use the words Christmas and Hanukkah this early.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Web executives say there's nothing wrong with a little
holiday spirit in summer or early fall if it's done in good taste.
And the ranks of online merchants who agree appear to be widening.
</P>
<P>
   Before Halloween, shoppers at CDnow's Web site will feature a
holiday gift center, which includes a gift registry and wish list.
</P>
<P>
   CDnow also plans to expand its selection of custom-made compact
disks for the holidays. Pick 12 favorite seasonal tunes and the Web
merchant will create a special CD, wrap it and ship it as a gift,
said Tracie Reed, CDnow's merchandising vice president.
</P>
<P>
   Museumshop.com of Arlington will feature corporate holiday
gifts, wrapped and ready to go, in mid-September. It hopes people
will shop for Hanukkah gifts at its site this fall after it adds
merchandise from the Museum of Jewish Heritage and the Jewish
Museum.
</P>
<P>
   But Rebecca Reynolds Moore, founder and president of
Museumshop.com, acknowleges that attempts to convert diehard late
shoppers into early buyers is ``wishful thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ironically, a lot of people do plan early,'' she said. ``I'm
not one of them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
