<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
29-YEAR-OLDS CAN BREATHE EASY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. We are expecting a baby in spring, about the same time we
both will finish our training programs. I expect to take a
six-month maternity leave before returning to work part time. My
husband anticipates a salary of roughly $30,000 a year when he goes
to work. Our current expenses are $50,560 a year, including
assisting my mother, student loan payments, auto loan, and
additions to retirement expenses. Are we investing appropriately
for retirement and rainy-day expenses? How much should we begin to
save for our child's education?
</P>
<P>
   K.G., Jamaica Plain, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. You have a lot on your plate, but you should be in fine shape
in the long run. Since you have amassed considerable savings at
your relatively tender ages, you could enjoy a comfortable
retirement if you did nothing more than continue with your $433
monthly addition to the two retirement accounts. If the current
portfolio averages 10 percent annual total returns in the next 35
years, you would have $9,170,808, which would be roughly equivalent
to $2.75 million in today's dollars.
</P>
<P>
   I know it's hard to see through all of the uncertainties _
future jobs and income levels, the cost of raising and educating
your child, the amount of assistance your mother will need, and so
forth. But it seems people of your age whose current expenses are
only 87 percent of their income should come through all of this in
fine shape.
</P>
<P>
   That said, I would quibble with a couple of your investments. I
can't comment on your investments in the American fund family,
since you don't specify which funds you use. Nor am I certain where
your Pax World investments are in Pax World Balanced or Pax World
Growth. Either way, I would look elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Pax World Growth, a mid-cap fund with a portfolio blending
growth and value stocks, has consistently underperformed its peers
and holds a compact portfolio of 34 issues, according to current
information from Morningstar Mutual Funds. Such a compact portfolio
adds to the risk level. If its concentration on health care stocks
is what draws you to this fund, I'd suggest a switch to either
Fidelity Select Health Care or Vanguard Health Care funds. If its
policy of investing in stocks of companies that it deems are
socially responsible is the appeal, I'd swap for the Domini Social
Equity fund.
</P>
<P>
   If you're in Pax World Balanced fund, it is the more appealing
of the two but it's the wrong kind of fund for your very long-term
investment time frame. Only 62.7 percent of its investments are in
stocks, and in the long run, the cash and bond holdings will be a
drag on your portfolio. This is especially important since this is
the target for the lion's share of your current savings.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not terribly enthusiastic about Parnassus fund, another
socially responsible offering. Its long-term results are strong,
with a 10-year record running ahead of the Standard and Poor's 500
Index, but recent results have been choppy. Moreover, this is
another fund with a compact portfolio, with only 36 issues,
according to Morningstar. I'd be more comfortable with Domini here,
which relies on 399 stocks. It doesn't have a long-term record to
match that of Parnassus, but it has trailed the Standard and Poor's
500 Index closely.
</P>
<P>
   As for college costs, I'll give you some rough parameters. A
month ago, I extended the college cost projections from the current
edition of ``Paying for College Without Going Broke'' to estimate
the cost of a college education starting in 2017. For a public
school, the four-year cost would be $84,636; for a private college,
$220,867.
</P>
<P>
   To amass such sums so the total balance would be on hand after
17 years, you would need to save $159 a month for a public school
or $414 a month for a private one. Those figures presume average 10
percent investment returns. You would have to adjust the figures
higher (by 5 percent annually) to allow for the extra year for the
child born in 2001. But, of course, you could adjust the figures
lower if you assume that, like yourselves, your child will be
willing to assume the debt that goes with student loans.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. Where can I purchase FNMA certificates? Vanguard does not
have FNMAs.
</P>
<P>
   M.P., Malden, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. I can't find any mutual fund that invests solely in Fannie
Maes, the mortgage-backed securities issued by the Federal National
Mortgage Association. However, most government securities funds do
hold some FNMA debt, either in the form of certificates that give
the owners a share of a pool of mortgages, or in debt securities
issued by FNMA. For example, Fidelity Mortgage Securities holds a
large portion of its portfolio in Fannie Mae issues. At Vanguard,
the biggest stake I can find is in the portfolio of Vanguard
Intermediate-Term US Treasury fund, and that's in FNMA debt rather
than mortgage securities.
</P>
<P>
   You can, of course, buy FNMA certificates from a stockbroker,
but be warned that if you do, you're in for a lot of bookkeeping.
That's because the payments from these securities are irregular and
vary in nature. In the routine course of business, part of each
payment from such securities is interest, and the balance is a
return of capital _ the part of the payments made by the mortgage
borrowers that represent their payment of the principal. The
returns can be irregular, because the borrowers may prepay some or
all of the principal on the mortgages. The holders of these
certificates must keep careful track of which payments are taxable
interest and which are returns of their capital.
</P>
<P>
   Many people who are interested in such securities opt for what
is called a unit investment trust. These are much like mutual
funds, established by brokerage firms that buy a bundle of
securities, sell shares in the bundle, and then simply hold the
securities until the last of them is retired, at which time the
trust goes out of business. The owners of shares in a unit
investment trust have the advantage of having a great deal of the
paperwork done by its managers, but the flow of payments is likely
to be just as irregular as if you owned the certificates directly.
</P>
<P>
   One drawback to holding the mortgage certificates (in contrast
to FNMA debentures and other straight debt securities) is that
unless the investor carefully isolates the interest and principal
payments as they come in, he might be under the impression that the
returns are higher than they really are.
</P>
<P>
   If you are relying upon FNMA certificates to supply a long-term
income stream, you must carefully reinvest the portion of your
payments that represents the principal. If you're careless and
simply spend the distributions, by the time your final check comes
in you would have spent the entire principal balance as well as the
interest. With a debt security such as a debenture, you will get
interest payments at the stated level, and when the debenture
matures, your principal will be returned to you.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. A few years ago, I obtained a software program called
Vanguard Retirement Manager, which I found comprehensive and
user-friendly and much better than any other software I could find.
In my attempt to upgrade the software, I discovered Vanguard had
discontinued it. What is the best software to assist future
retirees in financial planning?
</P>
<P>
   R.F., Franklin, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. This time, I'm going to pass the buck to readers. I tried the
Vanguard software but was not as enthusiastic as you are. I've
tried a number of other programs and have always been dissatisfied.
Most of them, although not necessarily Vanguard's, are heavily
tilted toward the issuing company's products or to an online
database to which you must subscribe.
</P>
<P>
   The perfect program would allow you to manage a broad portfolio
of securities, including mutual funds, common stocks, bonds, and
cash accounts. It should allow you to factor in inflation,
historical and future, and to track either all of your finances or
only some. For many years, I used an old version of Quicken, with
varying degrees of frustration. It was the only program in my
computer that did not survive Y2K. I now use Microsoft Money, with
about equal enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   So, readers, does anyone have any recommendations?
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
Kenneth Hooker can be reached at The Boston Globe, P.O. Box 2378,
Boston, MA 02107-2378.
</P>
</TEXT>
