<HEADLINE>
888-603-1036.)  
 POSSIBLE RAW-MILK BAN STIRS CHEESE-LOVERS' PASSIONS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 888-346-9867 or (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SHERYL JULIAN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Imagine a meal made from several of the world's most perfect
foods nestled together on a plate: long strands of al dente
spaghetti tossed with ripe plum tomatoes cooked in olive oil. It's
a simple dish, made even nicer when you sprinkle a nutty
Parmigiano-Reggiano on top. Take a deep whiff of the beautiful
aromas, twist the strands onto your fork, and dig in.
</P>
<P>
   Now picture the dish without the cheese. Or, according to what
findings the government presents, picture life without Italy's
finest Parmesan and pecorino romano, France's Roquefort,
Switzerland's Gruyere, the British Cheddars, and our Vermont
Cheddars. Just suppose that any cheese being made today in this
country or Europe, using certain techniques in existence since
ancient times, was suddenly pulled off the market.
</P>
<P>
   That bleak scenario is a possibility, as the US Food and Drug
Administration reviews its 50-year-old policy on unpasteurized milk
cheeses. Now, any cheese made with unpasteurized milk has to be
aged a minimum of 60 days, which is the case with
Parmigiano-Reggiano, Roquefort, and the others. But the FDA says
that unpasteurized milk, which is used in all the great cheeses of
the world, may carry certain pathogens that can survive the 60-day
aging process. The news has cheesemakers, cheese purveyors,
restaurateurs, and the cheese-loving public up in arms. Even with
the FDA stillin its investigation stage, the cheese enthusiasts
have decided to make a preemptive strike.
</P>
<P>
   Ihsan Gurdal, co-owner of Formaggio Kitchen in Cambridge, Mass.,
known for its selection of fine cheeses, is leading the Boston
group. The cheese involved in the research, he says, ``is a huge
list.'' Any ban on unpasteurized milk cheeses, says Gurdal,
``basically eliminates cheeses as we know them.'' Formaggio Kitchen
supplies its sister store, Formaggio South End, and also sends
cheese to some 120 restaurants, including the French Laundry in
Yountville, Calif.; Emeril's in New Orleans; and, locally, the Blue
Room, Rialto, and Radius.
</P>
<P>
   Unpasteurized milk cheeses are in demand because they're
considered to be the finest cheeses available. ``The best, tastiest
cheeses are made from fresh, raw milk _ just as it comes from the
animal, alive and vibrant with living organisms, which are,
unfortunately, very perishable and open to contamination,'' writes
Steven Jenkins in ``Cheese Primer.''
</P>
<P>
   The 60-day aging period was established so that any harmful
organisms, such as Listeria, Salmonella, and E. coli, would be
destroyed. Aging also hardens a cheese, but certain French
washed-rind or bloom-rind cheeses are also sold here because their
plants in France are on an ``approved producer'' list established
by the FDA.
</P>
<P>
   Cheeses made from pasteurized milk also escape the potential
ban. But, to connoisseurs, pasteurized milk cheeses have no real
flavor. And Gurdal thinks that pasteurization doesn't guarantee
anything. ``When you pasteurize the milk,'' he says, ``you are
creating an environment to destroy the bacteria. But you're not
only destroying the harmful bacteria, but the good bacteria, the
ones that protect the milk against diseases. If the pasteurization
was a shoddy one, the milk has no protection.''
</P>
<P>
   On farms in Europe, animals are milked and within hours cheese
is made with that milk. ``Unpasteurized is the tradition,'' says
Gurdal. Neither he nor the other producers or purveyors are opposed
to the rules as they stand now. ``We like the status quo,'' Gurdal
says.
</P>
<P>
   To unify their opposition to the proposed ban, the
Wisconsin-based American Cheese Society, Boston-based Oldways
Preservation and Trust, and a group of cheese purveyors and
producers banded together as the Cheese of Choice Coalition. They
decided they would be better off voicing their outrage now, rather
than waiting until the federal agency was further along in its
process.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're telling the public what they're about to lose if this
goes into effect,'' says Gurdal. ``What we're trying to do right
now is to have everyone rally together.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Gurdal nor the other purveyors know where the idea of
reviewing the 60-day policy on unpasteurized-milk cheeses came
from. Ari Weinzweig of Zingerman's, a popular delicatessen in Ann
Arbor, Mich., that does $1 million a year in cheese sales,
speculates that ``it's one of those administrative things that
starts in somebody's office.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the decision to investigate the unpasteurized policy
has a scientific background, says Dr. Jack Mowbray, a researcher at
the FDA. There have been some reports of illnesses, Mowbray says.
``A big one in Canada,'' he says. ``Europe and North America are
primarily where the outbreaks have occurred.''
</P>
<P>
   Gurdal's group would like to see the United States use the same
safe-hygiene procedures used in Europe today. ``These things are in
place already,'' says Gurdal. The FDA already inspects
cheese-making producers in this country and has its
approved-producer French list. Mowbray says the agency is not far
enough along in the research process to make any other decisions.
</P>
<P>
   ``To us,'' says Gurdal, ``and to our public, this is an issue
about our right to have a say in what we have to eat.'' If, in
fact, there are some risks, he says, consumers can make the
decision to take those risks. ``They're basically saying that no
one should own knives because you can cut yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   The FDA's Mowbray says, ``We're not even to the point where
we're considering options. We're conducting research, working with
USDA and other institutions to determine the nature of the problem.
Once we do that, we'll draw up a list of risk-management options.''
</P>
<P>
   Zingerman's Weinzweig, who, like Gurdal, has petitions in his
store for customer signatures, agrees that the risk should be up to
the individual. ``It's like crossing the street,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   ``If nobody does anything and this happens,'' says Weinzweig,
``I'm going to feel really bad. Hopefully we can keep it from
happening.''
</P>
<P>
   And keep the food lovers of the world from a fate worse than
death: having to sprinkle their pasta with Parmesan from a little
green can.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
