<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 14:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0002 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r l BC-FORGED-AUTOGRAPHS-HNS     08-23 0883
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FORGED-AUTOGRAPHS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WATCH OUT FOR FOUL PLAYS IN TRADING SPORTS PARAPHERNALIA 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By MIKE FINGER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ Some people look at precise, carbon-copy forgeries
of famous athletes' signatures and are astounded. Others marvel at
the meticulous scientific techniques now used to determine if an
autograph is authentic.
</P>
<P>
   But to veteran collector Howard O'Desky, the most amazing aspect
of the sports autograph industry is still the same as it always was
_ plain, old stupidity.
</P>
<P>
   Take, for instance, O'Desky's story about a man who spent
thousands of dollars on a Tony Gwynn-model Rawlings baseball glove
that was supposedly signed by Hall-of-Famer Jackie Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson died in 1972. Gwynn's first season in the major leagues
didn't come until 1986.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pathetic how many people get taken on stuff like that,''
said O'Desky, the owner of Howie's Sports Cards in San Antonio.
``People are still pretty foolish when it comes to buying
autographs, even with all the evidence about fakes out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Months after a federal investigation revealed that more than
half _ and as much as 90 percent _ of ``autographed'' sports
memorabilia is phony, the $1 billion-per-year industry is still
thriving, thanks to the public's insatiable appetite for such
souvenirs and consumers' continued naivete about the prevalence of
counterfeiting.
</P>
<P>
   Even though card shops and on-line auction houses have flooded
the market with more bogus merchandise than ever before, insiders
say that buyers can still feel comfortable about their ability to
purchase authentic signed items _ if they are careful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Consumers will always have to be diligent in finding out where
the stuff is coming from, and they need to get some certainties
from the companies that they're getting the real deal,'' said Scott
Kelnhofer, editor of ``Card Trade'' magazine. ``I think a lot of
people are starting to ask more questions, and that's a good
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of that questioning was prompted by ``Operation Bullpen,''
an FBI investigation that used athletes such as Gwynn, Sammy Sosa
and Brett Favre as informants to stop illegal dealers nationwide.
More than 50 businesses were raided and 26 defendants have been
charged for crimes ranging from mail fraud to counterfeiting, and
that may be just the tip of the iceberg.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy to see why counterfeiters have found such a home in
the sports memorabilia industry.
</P>
<P>
   Autographs are relatively easy to forge. The demand for such
signatures is huge, especially among children and other fans not
exactly well schooled in the world of investing. And most
importantly, the chances of making money are great, considering
that signed jerseys sell for as much as $20,000 and items as small
as baseballs routinely go for a few hundred dollars apiece.
</P>
<P>
   Because buying autographs can be such a risky proposition, most
professional collectors adhere to two main principles:
</P>
<P>
   _ Don't buy anything that you aren't absolutely sure of.
</P>
<P>
   _ If it seems too good to be true, it probably is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't ever look at cheap stuff, because if it's cheap, it's
probably not real,'' said Charlie DiPietro, the owner of Sports
Cards Plus in San Antonio. ``I don't blame people who are skeptical
about autographs, because there's a lot of bad stuff out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Without actually being present for the signing of an autograph,
there are few ways that a buyer can be absolutely certain that an
item is authentic. Almost all autographs sold in stores now come
with certificates of authenticity, but as O'Desky said, ``If a guy
is willing to fake a baseball, why wouldn't he be willing to fake a
letter of authenticity?''
</P>
<P>
   The safest bet for consumers these days is to invest only in
autographs approved by companies such as Professional Sports
Authenticators and Upper Deck Authenticated, which verify the
authenticity of memorabilia by either witnessing the ``signing
event'' or analyzing the paper, ink and penmanship to ensure that
an old autograph is real.
</P>
<P>
   Demand for proof of authenticity has become so great that there
is even a market for companies such as AuthentiGraph.com, a New
York-based start-up that tracks items for the entire life of an
autograph _ from the time before the athlete signs a ball through
countless sales of the item from buyer to buyer.
</P>
<P>
   AuthentiGraph uses a seven-step system to record the ``signing
event,'' time-stamp the certificate of authenticity, register new
owners and provide a thorough history of the autograph that can be
accessed on the Internet. The company is currently trying to coax
players' associations from a number of different sports to sign
autographs exclusively through AuthentiGraph.
</P>
<P>
   AuthentiGraph Vice President Siupeli Malamala, a former New York
Jets offensive lineman, said athletes have a lot to gain from
signing with such companies, because the abundance of fake
autographs on the market only diminishes the value of the real
ones, and customers often can't tell which is which.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been there before, so I know how important it is for
players to protect their names,'' Malamala said.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Contact Mike Finger by e-mail at mfinger(at)express-news.net)
</P>
