<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 14:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0005 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FBC-O'LEARY0824-COX     08-23 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-O'LEARY0824-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    O'Leary leading the renaissance of Georgia Tech football
 &HT;    By Norman Arey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - When a bank of lights failed at Georgia Tech football
practice in October 1995, new head coach George O'Leary impatiently
had a trainer call for an electrician.
</P>
<P>
   As Donnie Davis took a snap from Mike Cheever, an explosion
rocked the night, and the Yellow Jackets team watched the
electrician tumble, almost in slow motion, down an embankment from
the fuse box. The Rose Bowl Field lights dimmed and went out again.
</P>
<P>
   When the electrician landed, smoke was coming from under his
cap, and he clutched a screwdriver bent at a right angle. As the
Tech trainers rushed to the electrician and he struggled to rise,
O'Leary took one look, saw he was alive and shouted, ``He's OK. Run
the damn play!''
</P>
<P>
   No one is more single-minded than O'Leary. If it isn't about
football, he's not interested. Tech has gone to three bowls in a
row, a feat it had not managed since 1970-72. The Jackets' past
three seasons of 7-5, 10-2 and 8-4 are only one game short of the
total won by Bobby Ross 1989-91, which included a share of a
national championship. O'Leary's 36-25 mark ranks him fourth in
Tech history in wins behind John Heisman, Bill Alexander and Bobby
Dodd. His winning percentage is third, behind Heisman and Dodd.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the Yellow Jackets are back. The renaissance of
Georgia Tech football is happening right now.
</P>
<P>
   Pressed to talk about his success, O'Leary gives the basics.
``When I first started here, the biggest thing lacking was trust,''
he says. ``I wanted the trust of the players back. I was going to
run a program where everybody is treated the same way hard but
fair. I tell them I try to treat them just like I treat my sons. I
also tell them to go find my sons and see how they were treated.''
</P>
<P>
   The 54-year-old Irishman tells the story, not for the first
time, about his daughter in kindergarten, some 20 years ago,
drawing a detailed picture of the family, down to the pet
Dalmation.
</P>
<P>
   No father was in the picture. ``I was never at home,'' he says.
``The kindergarten teacher was upset.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Maloney, the head coach at Syracuse in 1978, hired O'Leary
as an assistant out of Liverpool High School. ``I didn't really
know him,'' Maloney says, ``but I kept reading about him in the
paper. The only regret I have about it now is that I didn't hire
him five years earlier.
</P>
<P>
   ``George was an exceptional recruiter,'' Maloney says. ``He
didn't fit that mold. The recruiters today are a whole lot more
slicked down that that. George was more down to earth.''
</P>
<P>
   Maloney searches for a word to describe the young O'Leary.
``Quiet,'' he finally says. ``He was a low-key kind of guy. He was
like your neighbor next door. He always seemed a lot older than he
was. George was a good listener, a good learner. He adapted. He was
always watching and listening.''
</P>
<P>
   The former Syracuse coach says O'Leary interacted with the
players well but still maintained discipline. ``Sometimes, new
coaches are afraid to be demanding with the players,'' Maloney
says. ``George never was.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell the players the biggest thing they have to learn are
priorities,'' O'Leary says. ``No. 1 is academics. No. 2 is
football. The social life is tough, because they have only so much
manageable time. I tell them you can do two things well, not
three.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think George has changed a bit,'' says Dick McPherson,
who took over the Syracuse program from Maloney. ``He's always been
a very demanding, exact guy. He likes to play golf. He loves his
kids, his wife. He's got his whole life right there in front of
him. All George ever wanted to do was work, recruit and have a good
time.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary hasn't backed down from the top players in recruiting.
He isn't frightened away if FSU or Florida is recruiting the same
guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've isolated players, stuck to our guns of bringing in
players with character,'' O'Leary says. ``I've told our assistants
not to be afraid to walk away from a good player if the character's
not there.'' O'Leary has managed to stay flexible through more than
30 years in the game. He preaches accountability above all. ``All
of our coaches understand accountability,'' he says. ``It's
important we all walk and talk the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I tell all our players exactly what I think,'' he says. ``I
have rules about drinking, about drugs. The most important thing
is, don't lie to me. I won't lie to you, and you don't lie to me.
When they come to me about not being treated fairly, I tell `em
they're not going to like my answer. As long as I'm head coach,
it's not a democracy.''
</P>
<P>
   Today's players aren't like those of the past, O'Leary says.
``There's a whole lot more going on in society today,'' he says.
``Some guys seem to think they've got a right to a scholarship, a
right to play. There are no rights, just opportunities. You earn
everything you get. You earn respect, playing time. What happens in
the classroom is their responsibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Tech moved in 1999 to assure that O'Leary would stay. He signed
a six-year rollover contract with a hefty buyout. The first year
paid him a $200,000 base. He gets a 5 percent raise each year. His
apparel contract is worth $125,000. His radio and TV comes to
$275,000. Incentives make it worth more than $700,000 annually. If
he should leave, Tech is paid $1.5 million. If he is fired, O'Leary
is paid the same.
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary laughs at the rumors that he is the next coach at Notre
Dame if Bob Davies fails. ``One of the main problems in coaching
today is when a coach gets a job, he starts looking for his next
job,'' he says. ``I signed a contract that would keep me here. I'm
happy with Georgia Tech.''
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE O'LEARY FILE
</P>
<P>
   -Full name: George Joseph O'Leary.
</P>
<P>
   -Birthdate: Aug. 17, 1946.
</P>
<P>
   -Hometown: Central Islip, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   -Education: Bachelor's degree in physical education from New
Hampshire and master's degree in education from NYU.
</P>
<P>
   -Family: Wife, Sharon; daughters, Chris and Trish; sons, Tim and
Marty.
</P>
<P>
   -Inside the numbers: In the past 18 ACC games, the Yellow
Jackets are 14-4, with two of the losses to Florida State. Only the
Hall of Fame trio of John Heisman, William Alexander and Bobby Dodd
have won more games as coaches at Tech.
</P>
<P>
   -Coaching experience:
</P>
<P>
   1968-76_Central Islip (N.Y.) High.
</P>
<P>
   1977-78_Liverpool (N.Y.) High.
</P>
<P>
   1978-86_Syracuse University defensive line and assistant head
coach.
</P>
<P>
   1987-91_Georgia Tech defensive coordinator.
</P>
<P>
   1992-93_San Diego Chargers defensive line.
</P>
<P>
   1994-present_Georgia Tech defensive coordinator and head coach.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
