<HEADER>
A0013 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX     08-23 0732
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE: CATCHING THE EYES OF FEMALE VOTERS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By BILL THOMPSON 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Have you seen the latest USA Today/CNN/Gallup Poll, the one that
shows Al Gore turning the election upside down with his
mind-boggling ``bounce'' from the Democratic National Convention?
</P>
<P>
   This is a poll that previously had given George W. Bush a
double-digit lead over Gore in the presidential race. But it now
puts Gore ahead of Bush, 47 percent to 46 percent _ although the
one-point difference is well within the poll's 5 percentage-point
margin of error.
</P>
<P>
   Evidently, the Democrats' convention and Gore's closing-night
speech had voters all across America leaping from their easy chairs
and exclaiming, ``Holy populism, Batman, this guy Gore is
phantasmagorical!''
</P>
<P>
   Or words to that effect.
</P>
<P>
   Some pundits are saying that Gore succeeded in changing his
image _ again? _ from that of a boring, ineffectual second banana
laboring in the shadow of Bill Clinton to that of a confident,
combative national leader ready to charge the hill on behalf of
just plain folks.
</P>
<P>
   Others contend that Gore benefited from the sort of boost that
any struggling candidate would get by turning in a
better-than-expected performance.
</P>
<P>
   Bush-backers are saying that they always expected the race to be
closer than earlier polls suggested and that people should hold
their horses for a week or two before deciding what Gore's
convention did or didn't do to boost his candidacy.
</P>
<P>
   So here's the question: What do these post-convention poll
numbers mean?
</P>
<P>
   And here's the answer: Nobody knows.
</P>
<P>
   But there is something we do know. Something happened during the
Democratic convention that caused Gore's popularity with female
voters to go through the roof.
</P>
<P>
   According to CNN senior political analyst Bill Schneider, in
fact, Gore's dramatic convention bounce was provided almost
entirely by women.
</P>
<P>
   Before the convention, Schneider pointed out, women favored Bush
over Gore. After the convention, women favored Gore.
</P>
<P>
   The numbers, as reported by USA Today:
</P>
<P>
   Pre-convention: Bush 51 percent, Gore 42 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Post-convention: Gore 58 percent, Bush 36 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Holy gender gap! That's a 31-point turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   The gender gap, of course, was crucial in the Clinton-Gore
victories of 1992 and 1996. For reasons that some of us still don't
understand, women voted Democratic in those two elections as if
Republicans had threatened to revoke female suffrage.
</P>
<P>
   In most polls before the Democrats met in Los Angeles, though,
Bush had more or less obliterated the gender gap. Women clearly did
not harbor the misgivings about the Texas governor that they did
about his father, President Bush, and '96 Republican nominee Bob
Dole.
</P>
<P>
   So. What ignited Gore's startling surge of popularity among
women?
</P>
<P>
   The conventional wisdom seems to be that the litany of liberal
policy initiatives served up by Gore in his convention speech
convinced women that his agenda is more attuned to their concerns
than the compassionate conservative programs touted by Bush.
</P>
<P>
   OK. But there had to be something else.
</P>
<P>
   And we all know what that something else was: The Kiss.
</P>
<P>
   It happened last Thursday, but just about everybody is still
talking about it.
</P>
<P>
   USA Today published a front-page story about it. Pulitzer
Prize-winning columnist Maureen Dowd wrote about it. CNN's Jeanne
Moos weighed in with a witty TV essay. Jay Leno lampooned it in a
skit.
</P>
<P>
   The Kiss: Gore sprints into the convention hall, throws his arms
around adoring wife Tipper and delivers a three-second (seemed like
30) smooch right on her eager lips.
</P>
<P>
   Was it the camera angle or did Tipper's knees buckle?
</P>
<P>
   It's obvious what happened. Women from coast to coast glanced at
their snoozing hubbies and tried to remember the last time the bum
burst through the door awash in spousal passion. Each and every
wife had the exact same thought about Gore: ``Now that's the kind
of man we need leading America.''
</P>
<P>
   Say hello to a new political phenomenon: The kissing gap.
</P>
<P>
   Are you ready to rumble, George and Laura?
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can reach him at (817) 390-7787 or
billthompson &LR; star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
