<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 14:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0017 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-FBN-BRONCOS-SLUR-HNS &LR;      08-23 0396
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-BRONCOS-SLUR-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     BRONCOS BACK TEAMMATE ACCUSED OF USING RACIAL SLUR 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By TOM ORSBORN  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Free safety Eric Brown said he and several other black Denver
Broncos teammates had mixed emotions when a published report
indicated that an unidentified white player had accused linebacker
Bill Romanowski of using a racial slur.
</P>
<P>
   At first, ``a lot of us didn't know what to think,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   But after hearing an emotional Romanowski call the accusation
``an absolute lie,'' Brown said he and his teammates decided to
support the man who has been a squad captain the past three
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``We thought, `We've played with this man, and we know how he
acts and behaves around us,''' Brown said in a telephone interview.
``We have faith in him and trust him when he's on the field, so why
not have faith in him and trust him when he's off the field?''
</P>
<P>
   According to a recent Sports Illustrated article, an NFL player
allegedly told a grand jury in Colorado that Romanowski said he
took the drug Phentermine to help him compete with black players.
Phentermine is an appetite suppressant that some people have used
as a stimulant.
</P>
<P>
   Romanowski's ``exact words were, `We have to go up against the
black guys,''' the player told the magazine. ``He said, `They're
faster and stronger, and we have to take advantage of (taking
Phentermine). It is the only way we can compete with the black
guys.' He didn't say, `black guys.' He used the `n' word.''
</P>
<P>
   The 12-year veteran was indicted by a grand jury in Colorado
earlier this month on four felony charges of fraudulently obtaining
massive quantities of a controlled drug. While remaining silent on
the drug charges, Romanowski has denied ever using a slur to
describe black players. His lawyer, Jeff Springer, has threatened
to sue Sports Illustrated, which reported the accusation.
</P>
<P>
   Several other Broncos, including running back Terrell Davis,
also have publicly supported Romanowski.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you know Bill, then you know he wouldn't say something like
that,'' Davis, who is black, told the Denver Post.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said the firestorm has not hurt the team's chemistry or
its camaraderie inside the locker room.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're fine,'' Brown said. ``We sit around and we joke. We are
like one big family.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-00 1436EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
