<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR THURSDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Thursday, Aug. 24:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (``i'' code)
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-PEACEKEEPING (United Nations) _ An international panel of
experts appointed by U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan called
Wednesday for an overhaul of the U.N. peacekeeping department if it
is to effectively confront a new age of multiple civil wars and
failed governments. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-IRAQ-WEAPONS (United Nations) _ As a two-day meeting on
Iraq weapons inspections opened at the United Nations on Wednesday,
Iraq's deputy prime minister, Tariq Aziz, said in Baghdad that Iraq
will not cooperate. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-SUBMARINE-ASSESS (Moscow) _ A news analysis on Russia's
handling of the Kursk submarine disaster. By Patrick E. Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-SUBMARINE (Moscow) _ A poll shows a drop in approval
ratings for President Vladimir Putin, as Russia observes a day of
mourning for the 118 officers and crew members who died on the
submarine Kursk. By Michael Wines.
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-U.S.-FOX (Dateline to come) _ On Mexico's President-elect
Vicente Fox, who will arrive in the United States late Wednesday.
By Ginger Thompson.
</P>
<P>
   COLOMBIA-U.S. (Washington) _ On President Clinton's decision to
sign a waiver allowing $1.3 billion in aid to go to Colombia
despite the country's failure to improve its human rights record.
(Staff byline to come)
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-NEWTON-PAPERS (London) _ Cambridge University has
launched a fund-raising campaign to buy and keep in Britain some
papers of Isaac Newton's that a private collector is about to sell.
By Alan Cowell.
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-POLITICS (Jakarta) _ Heavily criticized for not
solving Indonesia's many crises, President Abdurrahman Wahid on
Wednesday announced a streamlined Cabinet that he promised would be
more professional.
</P>
<P>
   With
</P>
<P>
   INDONESIA-SUHARTO (Jakarta) _ Aug. 31 is set as trial date for
Suharto, the ousted Indonesian leader.
</P>
<P>
   CHINA-DISSIDENT (Beijing) _ China, for third time in recent
weeks, arrests and files serious ``subversion'' charge against
someone who criticized government on a web site. By Erik Eckholm.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (``w'' code)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-RENO (Washington) _ Attorney General Janet Reno held a
press conference Wednesday to explain the decision not to name a
special prosecutor to investigate fund-raising by Vice President Al
Gore. By Neil A. Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (''p'' code)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-FLORIDA (Fort Lauderdale) _ For the next three days the
presidential campaign will focus on Florida. Gore is there today;
Bush will be there for the next two. Signs point to this being one
of the most competitive states in the race. By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-TAX (Austin) _ Bush's huge tax cut was a true winner for
him in the primaries, but now seems to be an enormous target for
the opposition. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-BRIEFS (Undated) _ News from the hustings.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL GENERAL &LR;  (``a'' code)
</P>
<P>
   FLA-STORM (Miami) _ South Florida braces for first major storm
of the year. By Rick Bragg.
</P>
<P>
   MASS-MOM-POLITICIAN (Boston) _ The Massachusetts Ethics
Commission will decide whether Jane Swift, the lieutenant governor
who gave birth two weeks before she was elected, violated ethics
rules by asking aides to babysit, having them help her move and
taking a helicopter home on a day when her baby was sick. By Carey
Goldberg.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   WORKER-WORRIES (Boise, Idaho) _ Few people still talk about
fretting over whether they can find work. Worries over the quality
of those jobs, however, remain a signature part of the economy for
many people. Many say they are concerned that they cannot keep up
with technological changes or that they are working too many hours
or that their health care coverage is inadequate. By David
Leonhardt.
</P>
<P>
   OIL-PRICES (Undated) _ Crude oil prices rise sharply after a
report shows an unexpected steep decline in crude inventories last
weeek. By Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   AMAZON-CARS (Dearborn, Mich.) _ Amazon.com announces a deal with
Greenlight.com to offer online car sales through a co-branded Web
site. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   MARKETPLACE (Undated) _ The daily marketplace column.
</P>
<P>
   VERIZON-STRIKE (Undated) _ Developments in the talks between
Verizon Communications, formerly Bell Atlantic, and the CWA-South
bargaining unit, representing 40,000 strikers. By Simon Romero.
</P>
<P>
   FAST-FOOD-EUROPE (Fregene, Italy) _ While American fast food
products like the hamburger, the doughnut, and fried chicken have
captured the palates of Europeans, the humble hot dog has not had
much success. Hoping to change that, a group of American investors
has acquired an exclusive license to sell Sabrett hot dogs in
Europe, and are making a big push. By John Tagliabue.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-ECON (Sao Paulo) _ Brazil's central bank considers
cutting interest rates on Wednesday for a fourth time since June,
in an effort to spur consumer spending and investment. Earlier in
the day, the monthly unemployment report showed joblessness at a
seven-month low. Interest rates are at their lowest since 1994. By
Jennifer L. Rich.
</P>
<P>
   ECONSCENE (Undated) _ The Economic Scene column. By Hal R.
Varian.
</P>
