<HEADER>
A0035 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-BORDER-BREAKFAST-TEX     08-23 0833
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDER-BREAKFAST-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GET A BREAKFAST BOUNTY IN EL PASO
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By BEVERLY BUNDY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL PASO, Texas _ The sun comes up in this rolling sienna town,
warming 18-wheelers as they leave the cacophony of Juarez to spill
into the Interstate system of America. Heat threatens early; by
evening, dust will be settling onto brows, creating the combination
of grit and sweat that has kept border towns vital for generations.
</P>
<P>
   Before the hot day begins _ as early as 6 a.m. _ petite Mexican
office workers and hulking El Paso city leaders will be tucking
into the same sort of fare. Plates of eggs pumped up with chorizo
or potatoes or shiny beneath a blanket of chile-flecked ranchero
sauce. Usually there are beans on the side, and certainly a
tortilla or three. And a grand cup of coffee, the bitter edges
smoothed with warm milk.
</P>
<P>
   It's the sort of breakfast, in heft if not in heritage, that our
grandfathers ate before going out to face the north forty. It's the
breakfast we ate until after World War II, when egg consumption
tanked as Americans moved from farms to perfectly planned
communities.
</P>
<P>
   Award-winning author Bill Jamison, who is researching an
American breakfast book, says the Mexican big breakfast is a
relatively recent thing.
</P>
<P>
   Breakfast in Mexico used to be two meals: ``Desayuno'' was the
first round, a true ``break fast'' of coffee and a tortilla at
daybreak; ``almuerzo'' came later in the morning and was a little
more substantial.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps in changing their schedules to adapt a little more
to the ``Norte Americanos,'' their strong trade partners and
geographical bunk mates, much of Mexico has rolled the two meals
into one spirited, all-out morning fiesta. The big breakfast also
works into the rhythm of a country where the last meal of the day,
``cena,'' is typically lighter fare. ``Comida,'' the early
afternoon meal, is the day's mainstay.
</P>
<P>
   W. Park Kerr, owner of El Paso Chile Co. and author of cookbooks
including ``Burning Desires,'' says ``the string of cheese hanging
out of a breakfast enchilada is the thread that holds frequently
fragile border communities together. Personally, I think these
wonderful border power-breakfasts at the local joints are the best
eating in El Paso.''
</P>
<P>
   And when faced with the alternative of a bowl of gray oatmeal or
a pallid Hot Pocket, who could argue.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   FOUR PLACES TO START THE DAY IN EL PASO:
</P>
<P>
   H &AMP; H CARWASH, 701 E. Yandell Drive, (915) 533-1144
</P>
<P>
   Brothers Maynard and Kenny Haddad own this carwash-cum-cafe.
(The Haddads are part of the large El Paso Lebanese community that
claims actor F. Murray Abraham as one of its own.)
</P>
<P>
   Laura Bush has eaten here, and probably more important, so has
Julia Child. It's vital to grab a stool at the counter, the better
to be seen by the power brokers who breakfast here and to see the
ballet folklorica that goes on behind the counter. The cooks
silently work the grill, swirling behind one another to flip
tortillas or turn the ``papas.''
</P>
<P>
   Tacos are the thing to order, and the best is carne picada, beef
tri-tip that has been seared on the same grill that Northerners
would use for pancakes. Order the taco plate so that you get a
combination of guacamole and refried beans with the warm meat and
the tortilla wrapper.
</P>
<P>
   TACO SANTA CECILIA, 5500 El Paso Drive, (915) 772-3435
</P>
<P>
   There's little English spoken at this chain restaurant turned to
local ownership. Simply know what to order, and you'll get yourself
a little plate of heaven that needs no translation.
</P>
<P>
   Pork tacos are the deal, with meat roasted gyros-style on an
upright spit over mesquite. Ask for the store-made salsa, pico de
gallo loaded with chunks of avocado. The tiny stone-ground
tortillas, probably imported from just across the bridge, are a
touch of authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   LA NORTENA, 212 W. Overland Ave., (915) 533-0533
</P>
<P>
   This is one of the more mainstream dining rooms, even taking
into account the glittered mirror and tequila label painted on the
wall. Near downtown, you're likely to see locals sipping Tecate
fairly early in the morning and office workers coming in for
after-work drinks. The food is just as noteworthy as the libations.
</P>
<P>
   La Nortena is known for its ojo al diablo (devil's eye) _
stacked red enchiladas sporting a sour cream garnish. Sort of a
Mexican version of the Turkish evil eye to ward off the day's bad
spirits.
</P>
<P>
   LUCY'S, 1305 N. Mesa St., (915) 534-7421
</P>
<P>
   This divey little place is known for its machaca burritos _
boiled shredded brisket mixed with tomatoes, onions, jalapenos and
eggs, and wrapped in flour tortillas.
</P>
<P>
   El Paso's Park Kerr calls these burritos the ultimate food for a
road trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Buy three or four and put them on the dashboard to keep warm.
That's what we all do.''
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
