<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-JACOBS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     AMERICAN RUNNER READY FOR SYDNEY 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By JOHN CRUMPACKER  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Even after winning the 1,500 and 5,000 meters at
last month's Olympic Track and Field Trials, Regina Jacobs knew she
would not be running both events in the Sydney Olympics. The
question was which one she would pick.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs, of Oakland, Calif., provided an answer Tuesday. The
four-time Olympian and Stanford University graduate opted for the
1,500 over the longer race, even though she is the American
record-holder at 5,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has a lot more experience there,'' said Tom Craig, Jacobs'
husband and coach.
</P>
<P>
   Craig said Jacobs, who has asthma, is recovering from a
respiratory infection.
</P>
<P>
   ``She'll be fine,'' he said. ``She's in great shape. The upshot
is it probably helps with peaking. It slowed her down and will
allow her to peak at the right time.''
</P>
<P>
   When Jacobs arrives in Sydney next month, she will have
competition not only from international rivals like Svetlana
Masterkova of Russia, Violeta Szekely of Romania, Kutre Dulecha of
Ethiopia and Carla Sacramento of Portugal, but fellow American Suzy
Favor Hamilton as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's going to be six people going for three medals,'' Craig
said. ``All six of them can medal. Whoever stays calm and under
control will medal.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Jacobs easily defeated Hamilton at the Olympic trials,
4:01.01 to 4:01.81, Hamilton ran a lifetime-best 3:57.40 July 28 in
Oslo. Jacobs has never broken four minutes for the metric mile; her
best is 4:00.35.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs, 36, has said her one remaining goal in the sport is to
earn an Olympic medal. Although she has a pair of silver medals
from the World Championships, in 1997 and 1999, her best Olympic
finish was 10th in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Jacobs' decision to run the 1,500 affects U.S. team membership
in the 5,000. Because neither Jacobs nor Olympic trials
second-place finisher Deena Drossin will run that race in Sydney,
the 3-4-5 runners will make the team instead. They are Elva Dryer,
Amy Rudolph and Anne Marie Lauck.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
