<HEADER>
A0055 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX     08-23 0872
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RECIPES-BUNDY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO MORE SIMPLE CHINESE DISHES _ PLUS DESSERT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By BEVERLY BUNDY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As a follow-up to a recent column about elementary Chinese
dishes, here are two simple but standard offerings that were
requested.
</P>
<P>
   Also, I'm including a peach pie recipe that was not requested
but was sent in by Vera Carter, who writes: ``I think everyone in
Jackson, Miss., and Ruston, La., already has this recipe. I got it
from my sister-in-law in Jackson, so please share it'' with
readers.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   WON-TON SOUP
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6
</P>
<P>
   _ 6 canned water chestnuts
</P>
<P>
   _ 1/4 pound minced lean pork
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 teaspoon minced fresh ginger, see Note
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 teaspoon salt
</P>
<P>
   _ 3/4 teaspoon pepper
</P>
<P>
   _ 2 teaspoons cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 tablespoon Asian sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   _ 24 won-ton skins, see Note
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 egg beaten with 1 tablespoon water
</P>
<P>
   _ 3 cups reduced-sodium canned broth
</P>
<P>
   _ 2 teaspoons soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 scallion, minced
</P>
<P>
   In food processor, mince water chestnuts coarsely. Add minced
pork, ginger, salt, 1/2 teaspoon pepper, cornstarch and 1 teaspoon
sesame oil. Pulse until well-blended.
</P>
<P>
   Lay out won-ton skins. Spoon about 1/2 teaspoon filling on
center of each won-ton skin. Brush edges lightly with beaten egg
wash and fold corners over to form a triangle, enclosing filling.
Press to seal well. Dab egg wash on one corner and stick to
opposite corner to form a little hat-shaped won ton. Continue until
all won tons are made. Place on floured cookie sheet and cover with
a clean kitchen towel.
</P>
<P>
   In large saucepan, bring stock to simmer. Season with soy sauce
and remaining 1/4 teaspoon pepper.
</P>
<P>
   In large pot, bring 10 cups of water to boil. Add won tons and
cook until they rise to surface, 2 to 3 minutes. With slotted
spoon, transfer won tons to simmering soup.
</P>
<P>
   Add remaining 2 teaspoons sesame oil and minced scallion to soup
just before serving. Spoon 4 won tons into each of 6 individual
bowls and ladle hot broth over won tons.
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITIONAL ANALYSIS PER SERVING: 190 calories, 5 grams fat, 24
grams carbohydrates, 11 grams protein, 47 milligrams cholesterol,
773 milligrams sodium, 25 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   TOMATO BEEF
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   Cooking sauce:
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 tablespoon each soy sauce, Worcestershire sauce and
cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   _ 3 tablespoons ketchup
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 teaspoon curry powder
</P>
<P>
   _ 1/4 cup water
</P>
<P>
   Combine ingredients and set aside.
</P>
<P>
   _ 3/4 pound lean boneless beef steak (such as top round, flank
or sirloin)
</P>
<P>
   _ 2 teaspoons each cornstarch and soy sauce
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 tablespoon each dry sherry and water
</P>
<P>
   _ 1/4 cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   _ 1/2 teaspoon minced fresh ginger
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 clove garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   _ 2 large stalks celery, cut into 1/4-inch-thick slanting slices
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 medium-size onion, cut into wedges, layers separated
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 green bell pepper, seeded and cut into 1-inch squares
</P>
<P>
   _ 3 medium tomatoes, each cut into 6 wedges
</P>
<P>
   _ Salt
</P>
<P>
   Cut beef with the grain into 1 1/2-inch-wide strips; then cut
each strip across the grain into 1/8-inch-thick slanting slices. In
bowl, stir together cornstarch, soy, sherry and water. Add meat and
stir to coat, then stir in 1 1/2 teaspoons of the oil and let
marinate for 15 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Place skillet over high heat; when skillet is hot, add 2
tablespoons of oil. When oil begins to heat, add ginger and garlic
and stir once. Add meat mixture and stir-fry until meat is browned
(1 1/2 to 2 minutes; remove from skillet and set aside).
</P>
<P>
   Pour remaining 1 1/2 tablespoons oil into skillet. When oil is
hot, add celery and onion and stir-fry for 1 minute. Add bell
pepper and stir-fry for 1 minute, adding a few drops of water if
skillet appears dry. Add tomatoes and stir-fry for 1 minute. Return
meat to skillet. Stir cooking sauce, pour into skillet and stir
until sauce boils and thickens. Season to taste with salt.
</P>
<P>
   Serve with rice.
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITIONAL ANALYSIS PER SERVING: 308 calories, 18 grams fat, 16
grams carbohydrates, 22 grams protein, 48 milligrams cholesterol,
679 milligrams sodium, 53 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   FRESH PEACH PIE
</P>
<P>
   Serves 6
</P>
<P>
   _ 3/4 cup sugar
</P>
<P>
   _ 3/4 cup water
</P>
<P>
   _ 2 1/2 tablespoons cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   _ 1/2 small (4-serving size) peach gelatin
</P>
<P>
   _ 1 baked pastry or graham cracker pie crust
</P>
<P>
   _ 4 to 5 fresh peaches, peeled and sliced
</P>
<P>
   _ Non-dairy whipped topping
</P>
<P>
   Combine sugar, water and cornstarch in saucepan. Cook over
medium heat until the mixture thickens. Stir in gelatin until
dissolved.
</P>
<P>
   Arrange peaches in pie shell. Pour gelatin over peaches. Top
with nondairy whipped topping. Store in refrigerator.
</P>
<P>
   NUTRITIONAL ANALYSIS PER SERVING: 328 calories, 11 grams fat, 55
grams carbohydrates, 3 grams protein, trace cholesterol, 186
milligrams sodium, 31 percent of calories from fat.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Send recipes and requests to her in care of the Star-Telegram, Box
1870, Fort Worth, TX 76101. Or e-mail to
bbundy(at)star-telegram.com. Include a daytime phone number.
Responses to requests will be made only through this column. Visit
the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
