<SLUG> BC-TV-WEEKEND-ADV26-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
$ADV26 
 FOR RELEASE: SAT., AUG. 26, 2000 
 TV-TONIGHT COLUMN
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: TV TONIGHT, the daily TV column by Boston Herald
TV Editor Joel Brown, is for use by clients of The New York Times
Syndicate's TV TONIGHT feature. For more information about becoming
a client of TV TONIGHT, contact your Syndicate sales representative
at 1-888-269-8796. You may have received an unedited e-mail version
of TV TONIGHT that you should disregard. 
 (Editors: Please check local listings for time and channel. All
times listed are EDT unless otherwise specified.) 
 By JOEL BROWN 
 c.2000 Joel Brown 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With the last days of vacation sadly trickling away, many teens
and 'tweens will find themselves drawn to MTV this weekend for a
few end-of-summer goodies.
</P>
<P>
   A no-brainer, in several senses of the word, will be ``TRL End
of Summer Countdown,'' on MTV Saturday at 8:00 p.m. ``Total Request
Live,'' as only old fogies call it, has become the ``American
Bandstand'' for the pierced-navel crowd or, more correctly, for
their Britney-and-Justin-loving younger siblings. Tonight's
four-hour marathon will bring back all their summer video faves.
Squeal! Expect Eminem as well as 'N Sync. Carson Daly hosts.
</P>
<P>
   Far smarter _ highly entertaining for grownups, too, _ is
``Daria: Is It Fall Yet?'' The 90-minute animated film airing
Sunday at 7 on MTV explains what the mordantly witty Daria and her
best pal, Jane, were up to over the summer. There's actually a rift
between the two pals _ over a boy nonetheless. So while teen-age
social critic Daria is trying to cope with the idea of actually
dating, Jane is off to art camp, where she gets hit on by a female
camper.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Daria's fashion victim little sister finds out that
education is not such a bad thing after all, and her creepy school
counselor opens the ``It's OK to Cry'' self-esteem day camp.
</P>
<P>
   The ``Daria'' series isn't as great as ``The Simpsons'' or as
acute as ``King of the Hill,'' but it's probably third in TV's
animation hierarchy. It loves nonconformists, loathes peer pressure
and cant. It's witty and human. And this movie is an excellent
choice for parents and teens to watch together _ or separately, if
necessary _ before school begins again.
</P>
<P>
   By the way, parents, if you're not familiar with the ``Daria''
series, rerun episodes air 5:30-7 p.m. on Saturday and from 5-7
p.m. Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; HIGHLIGHTS &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Big Brother,'' CBS Saturday at 8: Can we just give the
half-million to Cassandra and get it over with, please?
</P>
<P>
   ``Pigskin Classic,'' ABC Saturday at 8: BYU vs. Florida State,
live from Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   ``The 18th Annual Miss Teen USA Pageant,'' CBS Saturday at 9:
Brian McFayden hosts, and 98 Degrees performs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mad TV,'' Fox Saturday at 11 p.m.: Catherine O'Hara and George
Carlin. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saturday Night Live,'' NBC Saturday at 11:30: Christina Ricci
and Beck. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ''60 Minutes,'' CBS Sunday at 7: Mike, Morley and the rest of
the gang.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Simpsons,'' Fox Sunday at 8: For those of you currently
afflicted with pledge-drive programming chaos on your local PBS
station, this episode should be especially enjoyable. Homer is
forced to join the Peace Corps to escape when he can't make good on
his $10,000 PBS pledge.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who Wants to be a Millionaire,'' ABC Sunday at 9: Regis
Philbin hosts.
</P>
<P>
   ``The X-Files,'' Fox Sunday at 9: Mulder learns more about his
sister's disappearance in part one of a two-parter. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Practice,'' ABC at 10: Bobby and Helen clash over a case
of euthanasia. Rerun.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; FAMILY FARE &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``Rocket's Red Glare,'' Fox Family Channel Sunday at 8: A
teen-ager builds a rocket _ and suddenly NASA needs it! Robert
Wagner, Marilu Henner, Oliver Hudson, Danielle Fishel and Ryan
Merriman star. Premiere.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CABLE CAST &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``National Geographic Explorer,'' CNBC Saturday at 8: Prepping
for the Sydney Olympics next month with a bunch of segments on
hazards Down Under, including death adders, bush fires _ and a
shark attack victim who works to protect Great Whites.
</P>
<P>
   ``High Noon,'' TBS Saturday at 8:05: Remake of the Gary Cooper
classic stars Tom Skerritt as a marshal who must face down a killer
alone. But if this isn't your cup of tea, the original airs at 10
p.m. on Turner Classic Movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Last of the Blond Bombshells,'' HBO Saturday at 9:
Skillful cast _ Judi Dench, Ian Holm, Olympia Dukakis, Leslie Caron
_ in an original HBO film about a widow who tries to reassemble her
World War II all-girl swing band. Premiere.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Sandy Bottom Orchestra,'' Showtime Sunday at 8: Glenne
Headly and Tom Irwin star with Jane Powell and Madeline Zima in
this original cable film about a pianist who gave up her career to
marry a farmer, as she prepares to perform at the local
agricultural fair. Premiere.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inside the Actor's Studio,'' Bravo Sunday at 8: Sharon Stone.
Think someone will ask about the ``Basic Instinct'' interrogation
scene?
</P>
<P>
   ``Sex and the City,'' HBO Sunday at 9: ``Don't Ask, Don't Tell''
is the episode title. Carrie contemplates telling Aidan about her
affair with Big. Meanwhile, the night before their wedding,
Charlotte realizes that Trey may not be the perfect man. But
Samantha's already celebrating with one of the groomsmen.
</P>
