u i BC-CHINA-INTERNET-NYT &LR;      08-23 0302
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-INTERNET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA JAILS INTERNET CAFE OWNER FOR POSTING POLITICAL ARTICLES 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ The owner of an Internet cafe in southern China has
been arrested and charged with subversion for posting articles
critical of the Communist Party, the latest sign of the
government's campaign to tame the explosion of electronic
information.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang Shihua, a high school teacher who operated the cafe in the
city of Nontong in Sichuan Province, is the third person in recent
months known to face serious charges for political statements on
the Internet. His arrest on Aug. 16, five days after he began
posting the articles under a pseudonym, was reported this week by
the Free China Movement in Washington, based on accounts by Chinese
television and Reporters Without Borders, a media watchdog group in
Paris.
</P>
<P>
   China's leaders have embraced the Internet as a key to
development but also fear it, and special ``Web police'' units have
been formed to search for illegal activities like fraud and
pornography as well as outlawed political debate.
</P>
<P>
   In another case, Huang Qi, who ran a Web site from Sichuan that
published statements on the student democracy movement that was
crushed in 1989 and other rights issues, was charged with
subversion in June.
</P>
<P>
   Another man, Qi Yanchen, of Hebei Province, has been charged
with the same crime for posting anti-government messages, according
to rights groups. None of the three arrested men has been tried,
but convictions in such cases are nearly certain and can bring long
prison terms.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the authorities shut down New Culture Forum,
a Web site in Shandong Province that sponsored debate on the need
for democracy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-00 1512EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000823.0167 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 15:13 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0074 &Cx1f; tad-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-SUB-0824-COX     08-23 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-SUB-0824-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    RELATIVES OF KURSK CREW GREET RUSSIA'S PUTIN WITH 'BOOS' ON DAY
OF MOURNING
 &HT;    By MARGARET COKER 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MURMANSK, Russia _ Russians lowered flags to half-mast and lit
candles in special church ceremonies during a national day of
mourning Wednesday for the 118 crewmembers of the sunken submarine
Kursk.
</P>
<P>
   But amid the outpouring of grief rang shouts of anger by family
members who met with President Vladimir Putin for the first time
since the Aug. 12 tragedy plunged the Oscar-II Class nuclear sub
354 feet below the surface of the Barents Sea.
</P>
<P>
   Putin was expected to attend memorial ceremonies at the
Severomorsk naval base and in Murmansk, where the Northern Fleet is
based, but he abruptly cut short his visit after a stormy meeting
with some 600 relatives of the submariners that lasted until early
Wednesday morning.
</P>
<P>
   Met with shouts and some boos, Putin tried to calm those who had
traveled hundreds of miles in the hope of reclaiming the bodies of
their loved ones and finding answers to the question of what
exactly caused the accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``The grief is immeasurable, there are not enough words of
comfort. My heart hurts, but yours hurt even more,'' said Putin,
looking serious in an all-black suit.
</P>
<P>
   But families would not be consoled, according to people who
attended the meeting held in officer's barracks. Instead, they
criticized the president for the lack of information they received
during the crisis.
</P>
<P>
   ``When will we get them back, dead or alive? Answer as the
president,'' shouted a woman, referring to the bodies of the
sailors, in comments taped by state-owned RTR television, the only
press agency allowed to attend the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll answer you when I know myself,'' the president replied.
</P>
<P>
   The mood soured further when the family members requested that
the Navy cancel memorial ceremonies Putin was supposed to
officiate, saying they would not mourn until they had corpses to
bury.
</P>
<P>
   In a further blow to the family members, officials in charge of
salvaging the bodies and the 20,000-ton sub announced Wednesday
that it would take close to one year to raise the Kursk, due to
adverse weather conditions common to this region in the Arctic
Circle.
</P>
<P>
   The decision has not yet been made about whether to retrieve the
bodies separately in a quicker operation that would involve
drilling holes into the sub, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The cause of the accident can not be confirmed until the
wreckage is brought to the surface and examined more closely, the
officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Russian military officers have said the most likely cause of the
disaster was that an initial explosion, either from inside the
vessel or from a collision wrecked the front of the sub, sending it
straight down to the seabed. This impact then led to a detonation
of the Kursk's torpedoes. The crew, Russian officials say, died
immediately.
</P>
<P>
   Military sources, speaking on condition of anonymity,
contradicted this official explanation. They said the more likely
cause of the initial explosion was a misfire during top-secret
military exercises held in the area on Aug. 12.
</P>
<P>
   Naval sources based in Murmansk said the Russian military was
test-firing an experimental torpedo on the day the Kursk went
missing. Only a misfire of this weapon or another incoming weapon
could puncture the hull of the Kursk, one of the newest and most
modern nuclear submarines in Russia's fleet, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Possible causes of the accident have become the main themes of
television news talk shows and editorial columns across Russia's 11
time zones.
</P>
<P>
   In honor of the day of mourning, however, Putin asked television
stations to refrain from running entertainment shows. Most TV
stations canceled usual entertainment and news shows and called for
moments of silence _ but regular programming continued during the
morning, including soap operas. Some stations honored the dead by
showing the names and photographs of the crewmembers.
</P>
<P>
   This silence on television was not matched in the streets of
Murmansk, a town some 1,000 miles north of Moscow where nearly 50
percent of the jobs are associated with the nearby base.
</P>
<P>
   Here, people assailed Putin for taking so long after the
accident to show concern for the crew. But most of all, they
criticized the government for initially resisting international
help, a decision they feel could have saved some lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our leadership doesn't care about individual lives. It lied to
us about our boys. What good do their tears do us now?'' asked
misty-eyed 63-year-old Anna Kudrovna, who was laying flowers at the
town's WWII memorial Wednesday in honor of the Kursk crew.
</P>
<P>
   The government, at Putin's behest, has promised to look after
the relatives. And Deputy Prime Minister Valentina Matviyenko told
reporters in Moscow Wednesday that families would get average
compensation worth US$7,000, an amount that equals more than 10
years' salary for a mid-level officer.
</P>
<P>
   (Margaret Coker's E-mail address is: megc(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   For more information:
</P>
<P>
   http://www.janes.com/
</P>
<P>
   http://www.government.gov.ru/english/
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
