<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 15:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0094 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r s BC-FBN-RAIDERS-HNS &LR;      08-23 0733
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-RAIDERS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RAIDERS NEED TO PLAY RISON AND PLAY HIM HARD 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By RAY RATTO  
 &HT;     c.2000 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Among the underpublicized reasons Richard Nixon
was driven from office with pitchforks were his periodic attempts
to phone in plays to then-Washington Redskins coach George Allen.
Unlike visiting China or helping cover up a burglary, that sort of
thing is best left to the professionals.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, this seems like the perfect time to drop a
quick one in Jon Gruden's in-basket at the Oakland Raiders Galactic
Headquarters. What with the last riveting practice game coming
Thursday night against the Seattle Fighting Kitnas, it is time to
give one, free of charge, to those stubborn Raiders fans who come
out to the Coliseum for the meaningless August game as well as the
meaningless December game, hoping to make the present seem like the
past.
</P>
<P>
   And here it is: first play, Andre Rison, for as far as Rich
Gannon can make him run.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind establishing the run. Never mind taking what the
defense gives you. Never mind giving the boys on the bubble maximum
opportunity to show their wares.
</P>
<P>
   Rison, deep as you can send him, and as often as you can think
of it.
</P>
<P>
   The fans deserve this because, well, because they deserve to
know right off what Andre Rison the Raiders actually signed.
They've had to sweat through Sebastian Janikowski's funky first few
months of Raider-hood, and when they clamored for a 69-yard
what-the-hell field-goal attempt last Friday against Detroit,
Gruden opted to keep his job.
</P>
<P>
   And now they are being handed Rison, who may still have some
Techron in the old tank, or may be just a flatliner waiting for
someone to turn off the defibrillator. Fact is, we don't know what
Rison the Raiders just signed.
</P>
<P>
   And no, his occasional off-field crankiness doesn't count. For
one, nobody really cares as long as he can catch the ball (again,
see Janikowski), and if he can't catch the ball, nobody will care
if he sees Mother Teresa impersonating Paul Tagliabue in his sleep.
</P>
<P>
   This is one of those matters the NFL does best _ football, pure,
simple and utterly egalitarian. You play, you stay. You fail, you
bail. It can't be any more basic than that.
</P>
<P>
   And since the Raiders plainly need a second wide receiver, there
seems no better way to find out if they just acquired the answer
than to air him out immediately. Rison doesn't have to know the
whole playbook yet, just the routes that will give Oakland the
confidence that comes with having a receiving corps that ranks only
slightly higher than Cleveland's.
</P>
<P>
   Thus, using him until he becomes just a waft of blue sulfurous
smoke makes football sense. Gruden and Gannon need to know in a few
days how much to trust his skill and will.
</P>
<P>
   But that's their problem. Rison also needs the work to give the
fans a fresh reason to believe that the draft gambles of Janikowski
and punter Shane Lechler made sense that it will take only one wide
receiver who couldn't get along with the slightly oleaginous Kansas
City general manager Carl Peterson to take the Raiders out of the
``In Other Games'' category once and for all.
</P>
<P>
   And let's face it, those fans have been extraordinarily strong,
if a bit too painted-up for some tastes. The 32,000 and change who
were counted for the practice home opener against Detroit didn't
just happen upon the ballyard. They meant to be there, had to be
there. There's no gentle reasoning with them. Their world has two
colors, and one opinion. They are, in some ways, like the Borg of
Star Trek lore, and not just some of the fellows near the player
tunnel dress that way.
</P>
<P>
   These are the gents and ladies who deserve to know as soon as
possible if Andre Rison is again the real deal, and what the
Raiders intend to do if he isn't. They have endured plenty since
the team blundered its way back north, and they need to know if
they need to order more duct tape for their hearts.
</P>
<P>
   So they need to see Rison straight from the chute Thursday
night. They need to see him run those fade patterns that made him a
name, and the hands that made him a name worth remembering. What's
more, they've earned it. I mean, if they're not going to get a
rebate for playoff games not played, they may as well get a sneak
preview of the next model down the line.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
