<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 15:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0100 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-FOOD-HIGHWAY-TEX     08-23 1037
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-HIGHWAY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INCREDIBLE EDIBLES, FROM CHILE-POWERED NEW MEXICO TO SURPRISING
VEGAS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By BEVERLY BUNDY 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In my continuing quest for noteworthy food of the open highway,
I spun out of Santa Fe, N.M., on a dark morning, heading for the
neon of Las Vegas. Is this a great land or what? In one day, a girl
can go from the wrinkled linen of the art set to the silver lame
halter tops of the Hard Rock Cafe Casino.
</P>
<P>
   A trip to Vegas requires fortification _ a greasing of the
mind's wheels to move from the crystals of Santa Fe to the hard,
cold rhinestones of a gambler's paradise. And so I carefully
plotted my course.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   URANIUM CAFE, 519 W. Santa Fe Ave., Grants, N.M. (505) 287-7540
</P>
<P>
   If the Uranium weren't so organically cool, one would swear it
was a figment of the ``Twilight Zone.'' Opened in 1956 as a
Chinese-American restaurant, the Uranium has morphed with U.S.
dining habits. In the past 50 years, the building has also housed
an Italian and a Mexican restaurant. The tail end of a 1955
Chevrolet still butts out from one wall _ a vestige of theme
restaurants when it held a salad bar in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   Today, the restaurant is owned by Johnie Calahan. He's the cook
and son Jeremiah is the server. And while Christian radio sings its
praises, the pair serve up a righteous breakfast.
</P>
<P>
   The specialty here is the ``quiki,'' a stir-fry of scrambled
eggs beaded with hominy and other mix-ins. A heaping plate is borne
from the kitchen neatly divided into the quiki (in this case heated
up with chorizo) and a mountain of fried potatoes. In the middle is
a dam of spongy biscuits swamped with cream gravy. Then, because
this is New Mexico, a bowl of mud-colored salsa, flecked with
slivers of roasted chile, comes to rest beside the plate.
</P>
<P>
   The loco hominy quiki and all the fixings is $4.75 _ less than
you'll pay down the road for 3 gallons of gas to get you back on
the interstate.
</P>
<P>
   If you've got a miner's appetite, you might try the Uranium
omelet _ it's six, count 'em, six eggs with an assortment of meats,
vegetables, cheese and filling for $7.25. If you stop for lunch,
you can get a bowl of chili _ in this case green chili _ with
biscuits or crackers for $2.75. And if you can't wait to get to
Vegas, the Uranium will pack it up for you for a fee. ``A Ten Cent
Charge will Be Added to All to Go Orders Per Item Except Drinks.''
If you're heading to Las Vegas, you better watch those dimes.
</P>
<P>
   _
</P>
<P>
   Years ago, with a boyfriend in a pickup, I crossed over the
Hoover Dam late at night, with Charlie Daniels playing ``The Devil
Went Down to Georgia'' on the radio. It was one of those
mind-scorching moments of youth.
</P>
<P>
   The lights of this monumental dam, carved out of the rock by men
during a mean time, play on black water that makes toast possible
for much of the Western United States. Never had I felt so small.
</P>
<P>
   And then, right after the dam, are the lights of Las Vegas _
which manages, with its in-your-face silliness, to make us all seem
large. We know the New York facade is bogus, that the canal on the
upper level of the Venetian is tacky, that Siegfried &AMP; Roy make
Michael Jackson seem normal.
</P>
<P>
   But after a $100 glass of wine at one blackjack table, it's time
to feel small once again. To reclaim my equilibrium, I wanted to
get away from the Strip, away from big-small, win-lose, 21 or 16.
And so I arrived, 15 minutes before closing time, at an Asian
enclave just far enough from the Strip to muffle the din of the
slot machines.
</P>
<P>
   LOTUS OF SIAM, 953 E. Sahara Ave., Suite A5, (702) 735-3033
</P>
<P>
   Bill and Saipin Chutima have long been a favorite of foodies in
Los Angeles, where they owned a Thai restaurant specializing in
Isaan fare, the food of northeast Thailand. But now the couple has
picked up roots and moved to Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   Jonathan Gold broke the news in the August issue of ``Gourmet,''
calling Lotus of Siam ``The Single Best Thai Restaurant in North
America.'' ``Gourmet'' must not have heavy penetration in Las
Vegas, because only one other couple was there when I snuck in
under the ``Closed'' sign.
</P>
<P>
   And despite the tired steam tables in the middle of the room and
a menu promoting Menu No. 1 $8.95: Won-ton soup, egg roll, fried
won ton, barbecued chicken and steamed rice or sticky rice and,
further up the food chain, Dinner No. 3 $9.95: Tom yum kai (spicy
and sour chicken soup), egg roll, fried won ton sweet and sour
chicken and steamed rice, this was just what my body needed.
</P>
<P>
   This restaurant could be in a strip center anywhere, and perhaps
that's the charm. The obligatory posters and the silly silk flowers
are real after the manufactured glitz of the strip. And the food is
just as honest.
</P>
<P>
   I overordered because I was keeping the couple late, and, too, I
felt better giving them my money than donating it to a house bank.
</P>
<P>
   Larb, the ground-meat version of Thai salad so perfect for hot
summer nights, is wonderful here. Ground cooked chicken is tossed
with chopped onion, green chiles and lime juice and served with
fresh cabbage. Beef jerky, marinated beef strips deep-fried and
served with a spicy homemade sauce, is an intense dish, both in
flavor and mastication skills required.
</P>
<P>
   The highlight of all this goodness was the crispy mussel omelet
($6.95), a combination of silky mussels playing against the crisp
crust of the plate-size omelet. If there were to be a last meal,
this would make the short list.
</P>
<P>
   Roasted duck was a close second _ and only because this is Las
Vegas, and you've got to name a winner. The moist duck is married
with pineapple, bell pepper and tomato in a red curry base with a
touch of coconut milk. All yours for $8.95.
</P>
<P>
   Dessert was perfect for a hot desert night: a ball of coconut
ice cream wrapped in a hand of sticky rice ($3.25). I was ready to
face the night _ big or small.
</P>
<P>
   All the leftovers went back to the hotel with me, refrigerated
or not, because it's Las Vegas, and for food this good I'm willing
to bet the odds.
</P>
<P>
   (Beverly Bundy is food editor for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-00 1543EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
