<SLUG> BC-COWBOYS-OFCOLOR-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PUTTING SOME COLOR INTO THE RODEO IMAGE
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By CECIL JOHNSON 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Give some African-Americans enough rope, and they'll catch and
tie a calf.
</P>
<P>
   That is Cleo Hearn's favorite pastime. He's been roping calves
for more than four decades. And for three decades, he's been
helping minority cowboys to exhibit their rodeo skills.
</P>
<P>
   The Oklahoma native began organizing black rodeos in the early
'70s, having discovered in the Big Apple a ripe and ready audience
for the spectacle of dozens of black cowboys riding, roping and
getting up close and personal with bucking horses and bulls.
</P>
<P>
   But Hearn wanted to make his rodeos more representative of the
ethnic composition of the cowboy life during the heyday of the
cattle kingdom. About 25 percent of the cowboys who trailed cattle
from Texas to the northern railheads were African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   So in 1991, Hearn started the Cowboys of Color rodeos, which
include Hispanic and Native American cowboys as well as
African-Americans. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   He has a few choice words about the economic impact of rodeos in
a community: the value (in terms of money and entertainment) of
rodeos like his, and the role played by cowboys of color in the
days of cattle drives and in contemporary professional rodeo.
</P>
<P>
   Hearn, who earns his living as a big wheel for Ford Motor Co.,
got a rodeo scholarship to Oklahoma State University and then left
because school officials decided that they'd rather have him play
football.
</P>
<P>
   He later graduated from Langston University with a degree in
business.
</P>
<P>
   He was drafted into the Army during the Korean War and expected
to be discharged quickly because of rodeo injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Wrong. He wound up in the spit-and-polish ceremonial honor guard
in Washington, where he achieved a kind of southpaw celebrity by
stepping on President Kennedy's foot. That miscue led to continuing
chitchat between the president and the soldier, which always began
with: ``I know where my feet are;
</P>
<P>
   do you know where yours are?''
</P>
<P>
   He was in the right spot at the right time and was the right
color when Marlboro cigarettes, and later Ford, needed a black
cowboy for an ad campaign. The latter commercial led to his
longtime employment with Ford.
</P>
<P>
   Rodeos like his and Bill Pickett's, he said, allow cowboys of
color to compete.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that role models like All-Around World Champion
Fred Whitfield will inspire African-American youths to take to the
sport, especially since some colleges offer rodeo scholarships.
Four of his sons, Hearn said, went through college on rodeo
scholarships.
</P>
<P>
   Anyone who has ever attended a Cowboys of Color rodeo knows that
they are highly educational and entertaining. But be warned about
the music. The performers may wear boots and big hats, but the
sounds aren't country and western. Cowboys of Color is rodeo with a
beat.
</P>
<P>
   (Cecil Johnson is a former ``Star-Telegram'' columnist and
editorial writer. You may contact him at cecil &LR; star-telegram.com.
Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide Web:
www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
