<SLUG> BC-INDONESIA-SUHARTO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIAL DATE SET FOR FORMER PRESIDENT SUHARTO 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
(This article does not carry a byline)  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ A Jakarta judge said Wednesday that the
trial of former president Suharto on corruption charges would start
on Aug. 31 and that the ex-dictator must appear in court.
</P>
<P>
   Suharto, who ruled Indonesia for 32 years before being forced to
resign in 1998, was officially charged with corruption this month,
accused of skimming nearly $500 million from the state.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Lalu Mariyun, chief of the South Jakarta District Court,
said Suharto, 79, must appear at his trial despite assertions by
his lawyers that he is too ill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have ordered the Jakarta prosecutor's office to bring
Suharto to appear on August 31 at the court,'' he told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   President Abdurrahman Wahid has promised to pardon Suharto if he
is found guilty, but only if he returns any ill-gotten wealth to
the state.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-00 1544EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000823.0177 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 15:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0107 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV2     08-23 0875
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-$ADV27-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     GORE'S DOMESTIC POLICIES BUILD ON THOSE OF FDR, LBJ 
</HEADLINE>
  
 &HT;     (For release Sunday, Aug. 27)   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 &HT;     By ROBERT E. THOMPSON  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Many of Al Gore's strong populist appeals to the
poor and the middle class in his acceptance speech in Los Angeles
and his orations on the campaign trail originated long ago with
Franklin Roosevelt's New Deal and Lyndon Johnson's Great Society.
</P>
<P>
   Gore did not say that his grand design for America in the early
21st century was rooted in the far-reaching, controversial and
sometimes revolutionary programs created in the 20th century. But
the truth is that, if elected, he would build on foundations laid
by earlier Democratic presidents.
</P>
<P>
   In promising to ``fight for people,'' Gore appropriated the
weapon that won massive election victories for Roosevelt and
Johnson and greatly influenced their domestic policies.
</P>
<P>
   Astute observers of history could envision Gore's impassioned
convention message being delivered in the accent of FDR, the
Harvard-educated New Yorker of impeccable lineage, or the colorful
jargon of LBJ, the dynamic Hill Country politician who got his
degree at Texas State Teachers' College. These observers would have
little difficulty believing that many of Gore's proposals are
actually extensions of those advanced by Roosevelt and Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Social Security, which has become one of the
untouchable pillars of our society, was launched by FDR in 1935 and
supported, to one degree or another, by every subsequent president.
</P>
<P>
   Gore would channel money _ more than his Republican opponent,
George W. Bush _ from the budget surplus into Social Security to
make the program solvent far into the future.
</P>
<P>
   It should be noted that when Bill Clinton presided over a budget
surplus in fiscal 1998, he was the first president to do so since
Johnson submitted his last budget to Congress, the one for fiscal
1969.
</P>
<P>
   When Gore spoke of boosting the minimum wage, he was seeking to
expand an important program launched by the New Deal in the dark
days of the Great Depression.
</P>
<P>
   Like Roosevelt in 1936 denouncing the ``economic royalists,''
who he said regarded economic slavery as ``nobody's business,''
Gore repeatedly attacked the ``powerful interests'' that he said
block progress for today's working men and women.
</P>
<P>
   Gore echoed both Roosevelt and Johnson when he told Democratic
convention delegates, ``Together, let's make sure that our
prosperity enriches not just the few, but all working families.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Johnson, the former school teacher, Gore decreed that
education will be a priority if he is elected president. The
Elementary and Secondary Education Act, which Gore has promised to
protect, was one of Johnson's most prized legislative
accomplishments. Its passage in 1964 marked the first time that the
federal government agreed to provide funds to schools in depressed
neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   In announcing his support of affirmative action, Gore adopted
another program pushed by Johnson, who was the greatest civil right
president in history.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson would be pleased to see that many of the issues Gore
chose to showcase in his acceptance speech were those that he had
pioneered as part of the Great Society, including Medicare and
improvement of air and water quality.
</P>
<P>
   Tragically, because he was president during the horrible Vietnam
War, the only one that America lost, LBJ has become a non-person to
many of his fellow Democrats as well as Republicans and
independents.
</P>
<P>
   It matters not that John F. Kennedy dispatched 16,000 U.S.
military advisers to Vietnam and that Richard Nixon pursued the war
for four years after Johnson's retirement. That brutal conflict in
Southeast Asia is seen by many Americans as Johnson's war.
</P>
<P>
   Republicans and liberals have made Democrats wary of paying
homage to Johnson, although the distinguished economist and
diplomat John Kenneth Galbraith wrote last year: ``Next only to
Franklin Roosevelt, and in some respects more so, Lyndon Johnson
was the most effective advocate of humane social change in this
century.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson could be crude, overbearing and deceitful. But he was
also compassionate and dedicated to the concept that government can
_ and does _ improve the lives of millions of Americans from all
walks of life. He saw that it can help especially the poor and the
young, the African Americans and Hispanics and others who, for one
reason or another, have been denied a share of the American dream.
</P>
<P>
   Roosevelt's and Johnson's philosophy on domestic matters appears
to have greatly influenced Gore's thinking. So have the guiding
beliefs of Kennedy, Harry Truman, Jimmy Carter and Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is not opposed to business and wealth. He is opposed to
those powerful forces of business and industry _ ``big tobacco, big
oil, the big polluters, the pharmaceutical companies and the HMOs,
as he put it _ that endanger the lives and lay a heavy financial
burden on poor and middle-class Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Although he announced to the world from Los Angeles that he is
his own man, he has borrowed greatly from the past to update his
plans for the future.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-00 1550EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
