<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 16:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0128 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r d BC-MADISON-RECIPES-TEX     08-23 1121
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MADISON-RECIPES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VEGETARIAN RECIPES FROM DEBORAH MADISON
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Books by Deborah Madison &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``This Can't Be Tofu: 75 Recipes To Cook Something You Never
Thought You Would _ And Love Every Bite'' (Bantam, $15)
</P>
<P>
   ``Vegetarian Cooking for Everyone'' (Broadway, $40)
</P>
<P>
   ``The Savory Way'' (Bantam, $20)
</P>
<P>
   ``Greens Cookbook: Extraordinary Vegetarian Cuisine From the
Celebrated Restaurant'' (Bantam, $29.95)
</P>
<P>
   ``The Vegetarian Table: America'' (Chronicle Books, $22.95)
</P>
<P>
   ``Bengali Cooking: Seasons and Festivals'' with Chitrita Banerji
(Interlink Publishing, $15.95)  &QL; 
Cooking with Deborah Madison  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BUTTERMILK SOUP WITH CHICKPEAS AND HERB OIL &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4-6
</P>
<P>
   2 cloves garlic
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   1 quart buttermilk
</P>
<P>
   1 large cucumber, peeled, seeded and finely diced
</P>
<P>
   15-ounce can chickpeas, rinsed well
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons snipped chives
</P>
<P>
   1/3 cup chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons chopped marjoram
</P>
<P>
   Grated zest of 1 lemon
</P>
<P>
   Freshly milled pepper
</P>
<P>
   Lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Pour garlic with 1/2 teaspoon salt into mortar and mash until
smooth. Combine buttermilk, garlic, cucumber and chickpeas into a
bowl and chill well. Combine oil, herbs, a few pinches of salt and
the lemon zest in another bowl. When the soup is cold, taste for
salt and season with pepper and lemon juice. Serve garnished with
the herbed olive oil.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 228 calories, 12 grams fat, 22
grams carbohydrates, 10 grams protein, 6 milligrams cholesterol,
181 milligrams sodium, 47 percent of calories from fat.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BLACK-EYED PEA AND TOMATO SALAD WITH FETA
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4-6
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups canned black-eyed peas
</P>
<P>
   2 scallions, including an inch or two of the greens, thinly
sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 tomato, seeded and chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   1 tablespoon chopped marjoram or 1 teaspoon dried oregano
</P>
<P>
   Lemon vinaigrette, recipe follows
</P>
<P>
   2 to 3 ounces feta cheese, diced or crumbled
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly ground pepper
</P>
<P>
   Rinse black-eyed peas and shake off excess water.
</P>
<P>
   Put drained peas in bowl along with scallions, tomato, parsley
and marjoram. Pour vinaigrette over peas and toss gently with a
rubber spatula. Add cheese and pepper and toss again. Taste for
salt. Serve chilled or at room temperature.
</P>
<P>
   Lemon vinaigrette:
</P>
<P>
   Yields 1/2 cup
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons fresh lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon finely chopped lemon zest
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   1 shallot, finely diced
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons extra-virgin olive oil or to taste
</P>
<P>
   Freshly milled pepper
</P>
<P>
   Combine lemon juice, zest, 1/4 teaspoon salt and shallot in
small bowl. Let stand for 15 minutes, then whisk in oil and season
with a little pepper to taste. Taste and correct the balance,
adding more oil if needed.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 212 calories, 14 grams fat, 17
grams carbohydrates, 6 grams protein, 8 milligrams cholesterol, 112
milligrams sodium, 58 percent of calories from fat.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TOMATOES PROVENCAL
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   4 medium or 8 small firm, ripe tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   3 to 4 garlic cloves, to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 cup parsley leaves, preferably flat-leaf
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons chopped fresh basil
</P>
<P>
   3/4 cup bread crumbs made from day-old bread
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly milled pepper
</P>
<P>
   Extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Preheat oven to 400 degrees. Lightly oil a gratin dish.
</P>
<P>
   Cut tomatoes in half around their equators and gently remove
seeds with your fingertips. Chop garlic, parsley and basil
together, then mix them with bread crumbs and season well with salt
and pepper. Lightly fill tomatoes with this mixture, set them in
gratin dish and thread olive oil generously over the tops. Bake for
30 minutes. They'll be soft, so remove them carefully from the
dish.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 85 calories, 6 grams fat, 8
grams carbohydrates, 2 grams protein, trace cholesterol, 36
milligrams sodium, 61 percent of calories from fat.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   YELLOW SQUASH AND GREENS GRATIN
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4
</P>
<P>
   2 large leeks or a combination of leeks and onions, sliced into
rounds or chopped
</P>
<P>
   2 garlic cloves, peeled, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 1/4 pounds summer squash including zucchini, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1/4 pound mushrooms, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 tablespoons olive oil
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped dill or 1 teaspoon dried
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons chopped parsley
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   1 large bunch of tender greens (spinach, mustard, chard, beet
greens), well washed, with tough stems trimmed
</P>
<P>
   Custard:
</P>
<P>
   1 cup part-skim ricotta cheese
</P>
<P>
   2 eggs
</P>
<P>
   1 cup milk or cream
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup freshly grated Parmesan cheese
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Wash and cut all the vegetables as suggested. Preheat the oven
to 350 degrees. Warm the oil in a large skillet and add the leeks.
Saute for about 1 minute, then add the squash, mushrooms, half the
herbs and several pinches of salt.
</P>
<P>
   Cook over medium-high heat for about 4 to 5 minutes, stirring
frequently, until squash begins to color just a little; then
transfer the mixture to a gratin or casserole dish.
</P>
<P>
   Add the greens to the same skillet and cook just long enough to
wilt them down. Press out as much of the liquid as possible,
roughly chop the greens, and distribute them over the vegetables in
the gratin pan.
</P>
<P>
   In a medium bowl, beat the ricotta with the eggs; stir in the
milk or cream, the cheese and the remaining herbs. Season with salt
and pepper, then pour over the vegetables. Bake until the custard
is set and lightly browned on top, about 40 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Allow the gratin to stand 10 minutes before serving; serve warm.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 323 calories, 17 grams fat, 26
grams carbohydrates, 21 grams protein, 141 milligrams cholesterol,
371 milligrams sodium, 46 percent of calories from fat.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   RICOTTA FRITTATA
</P>
<P>
   Serves 4-6
</P>
<P>
   4 to 6 eggs
</P>
<P>
   Salt and freshly milled white pepper
</P>
<P>
   1 cup ricotta
</P>
<P>
   1/4 cup freshly grated Parmesan
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons chopped marjoram
</P>
<P>
   1 small clove garlic, crushed
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons of mixture of olive oil and melted butter
</P>
<P>
   Bread crumbs
</P>
<P>
   Preheat broiler.
</P>
<P>
   Beat eggs with 3/4 teaspoon salt and white pepper to taste. Stir
in cheeses, marjoram and garlic. Heat oil and butter in 8- or
10-inch skillet. Add egg mixture and lower heat. Cook until set,
about 12 minutes, then brown 4-6 inches under broiler. When done,
slide frittata onto a plate, sprinkle with bread crumbs and serve.
</P>
<P>
   Nutritional analysis per serving: 201 calories, 16 grams fat, 2
grams carbohydrates, 12 grams protein, 236 milligrams cholesterol,
456 milligrams sodium, 71 percent of calories from fat. &QL;
</P>
