<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 16:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0131 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-ONLINE-REVENGE-AR     08-23 1206
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ONLINE-REVENGE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVENGE AMONG THE NERDS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
(ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By JOYCE COHEN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   What do you do when someone stands you up? You stew. You steam.
Or perhaps you write a curt note. Douglas Anderson of Manhattan has
taken another approach: He sends a virtual voodoo doll.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have stood me up for voice lessons,'' said Anderson,
who is a music teacher. ``They never show up or call.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Anderson discovered PinStruck.com, an online service that
allows him to send offenders a curse in the image of a grinning
voodoo doll, and lets him stay anonymous while doing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the most therapeutic thing,'' Anderson said. ``It gives
me a channel to get it out of my system. As soon as I send off a
little effigy, I completely forget about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Anderson has company. On a typical day, PinStruck sends 2,000 to
3,000 curses. The messages are rendered in spidery handwriting, and
senders like Anderson can choose among 19 curses. The top choices,
said Tyson Liotta, who designed the site for Steem, a Web company
in Gaithersburg, Md., are ``You know you like it,'' ``I love you,''
``Look what you have become'' and ``It's not over yet.''
</P>
<P>
   The site recently deleted a popular curse that said, ``This is
the end of you.'' ``People interpreted it as a death threat,''
Liotta said.
</P>
<P>
   Revenge is not the noblest impulse but, with the Internet to
hide behind, it has certainly become easier to act upon. Web sites
for virtual vengeance give vindictive sorts plenty of ways to get
back at the objects of their disaffection. They can drive people
crazy with anonymous messages, disparage their enemies and deliver
bouquets of dead roses (or worse). It all comes with little effort
and almost no chance of exposure.
</P>
<P>
   ``The senders love the fact it is anonymous, and the victims
hate it,'' Liotta said. ``We get so much mail saying, `I really
need to know who sent it.' We have never known or been able to tell
anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Some revenge sites, like Mother-In-Law Stories, simply offer a
forum for well-targeted gripes (motherinlawstories.com). Other less
savory sites encourage people to upload unflattering pictures, to
ask for suggestions on how best to take revenge or simply to vent
in a way that might make a sailor blush.
</P>
<P>
   A few enterprising people have even set up Web sites dedicated
to individuals. ``You're not going to say something hateful to
somebody's face, but on a Web site, hey, why not?'' said Matthew
Joseff of Reston, Va., who runs a site that allows retribution
seekers to post photographs and comments.
</P>
<P>
   Like flaming, Internet revenge is convenient, nonconfrontational
and anonymous. ``People can find in the Internet a means of
expression they never could otherwise,'' said Dr. Paul Ciborowski,
a psychologist at Long Island University in Brookville, N.Y.
Ciborowski said some of his patients had used the Internet for
revenge. ``It allows for impulsivity unchecked,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Some sites serve as clearinghouses for the vengeful by running
message boards where people can malign those who have done them
wrong, glean sympathetic responses, share stories of real-life
revenge and gather tips for future use.
</P>
<P>
   ``We rattle people's cages,'' said Michael Baumgartner of Fort
Lauderdale, Fla., who runs a revenge site. ``The best revenge does
not hurt but merely drives someone crazy. Remember, the people you
are doing revenge to deserve it. They've done something wrong.''
Baumgartner, whose day job is in human resources, also has an
online store featuring flowers _ dead, wilted or painted black, all
sent anonymously.
</P>
<P>
   Ciborowski said anonymous postings could be a sort of therapy.
``There's an `I got it off my chest' kind of thing,'' he said.
``This is a validating group. They understand what you're going
through. Otherwise, they wouldn't be on this Web site.''
</P>
<P>
   But what is funny or therapeutic to the sender can be anything
but to the recipient. Ciborowski drew a distinction between
anonymous postings and anonymous e-mail messages, which he called
vindictive and potentially frightening. ``You don't know who sent
it or why,'' he said. ``You're suspicious of anyone who might have
a grievance against you. Individuals who do this kind of thing tend
to be passive-aggressive.
</P>
<P>
   The anonymity of a nasty message makes it especially
threatening, said Sheila Heen, co-author of ``Difficult
Conversations: How to Discuss What Matters Most'' (Viking Press,
1999). ``I don't think we appreciate the impact it has,'' said
Heen, who teaches negotiation at Harvard Law School. ``You're
thinking, `Why does someone hate me so much?'''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you're slashing someone's tires,'' she added, ``it's easier
to know you're stepping out of the normal bounds of behavior. On
the Internet, the action is consistent with a million other actions
you take in the course of a day. You click to sell stock, to
transfer money, to e-mail a friend, to e-mail an enemy.''
</P>
<P>
   Although many revenge sites emphasize that they are to be used
only for entertainment, said Liotta, the designer of the virtual
voodoo doll, ``no one respects that.
</P>
<P>
   ``They send it to the most fearful person they know,'' he said.
``That person freaks out, but there's nobody to yell at except us.
Some people take it a lot more seriously than we anticipated.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite frequent requests, Liotta refuses to allow senders to
write their own messages. Nor can senders choose _ for technical
reasons _ where on the doll to stick the pins.
</P>
<P>
   Another variation on anonymous revenge comes from ManicMail.net,
a service that allows users to send e-mail messages that appear to
be coming from someone else.
</P>
<P>
   One satisfied user of ManicMail is Sam Downing of Chatsworth,
Calif. ``I have always enjoyed practical jokes,'' Downing said.
When a colleague showed off his brand-new Honda Accord a few months
ago, Downing couldn't resist a trick. ``I sent him an e-mail from
the dealership saying the car was being recalled,'' he said. ``It
was the first car he had ever bought.''
</P>
<P>
   The colleague, Jeffrey Tani, was so upset that co-workers, who
were in on the joke, made Downing confess.
</P>
<P>
   Tani said, ``It looked authentic.''
</P>
<P>
   A disclaimer at ManicMail warns against using the service for
abusive, offensive or illegal purposes. The disclaimer started out
as a lighthearted admonition, but it grew increasingly severe
because people abused the service, said Antony Robbins, a computer
programmer in England who runs ManicMail with his brother, Peter.
</P>
<P>
   Since the brothers started the site last year, they said, they
have been queried about a half-dozen times by the FBI and police
departments, mostly, Robbins said, about teen-agers harassing
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   In many cases, ManicMail can trace the sender. And if a
recipient complains, no more ManicMail can be sent to that address.
</P>
<P>
   ManicMail sends about 300 e-mail notes a day. Activity spiked a
few months ago when it was mentioned on a syndicated radio show.
Baumgartner said: ``The world is filled with miserable people. They
all have the same theme.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-00 1616EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
