<SLUG> BC-CHAPTER-&AMP;VERSE-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REVIEWS OF RELIGIOUS BOOKS AND MUSIC
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CD REVIEW &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``One'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Various Artists &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Myrrh Records &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   About 1.5 million Christian youth gathered in Rome last weekend
for World Youth Day 2000, the 15th edition of the annual events,
which Pope John Paul II began in 1985. The theme of the conference
was unity between people of different races, denominations and
backgrounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``One'' is the official album of the conference, and the lyrics
and the roster of artists accurately reflect what the event tried
to achieve.
</P>
<P>
   The CD contains a mixture of original songs and previously
released cuts from diverse artists. It includes the Austin-based
Salvador, a Latin-pop group; Burlap to Cashmere, with its
Mediterranean influences; Gabriel's Harp, a French-American rock
group; the R&AMP;B-influenced sound of Winans Phase 2; and the pop/rock
band Sixpence None the Richer.
</P>
<P>
   One of the best cuts is ``Peace Has Broken Out,'' a hopeful duet
by Marie Brennan and Booley, Irish singers from different sides of
the border, about reconciliation.
</P>
<P>
   The theme song of the album is ``Emmanuel,'' a ballad about
unity in Christ, in English and multilanguage versions.
</P>
<P>
   The goal of ``One'' and the quality of the songs make this CD a
winner. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Simon Gonzalez &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   BOOK REVIEW &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The Consequences of Ideas'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By R.C. Sproul &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Crossway, $19.99) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   My family would tell you that if I had been Rene Descartes, ``I
think, therefore I am'' would have been changed to ``I read,
therefore I am.'' So if R.C. Sproul stops writing, do I cease to
exist?
</P>
<P>
   ``We are amused when Descartes labors so long and thinks so
deeply in order to conclude that he exists. ... we think it a
foolish waste of time,'' Sproul writes in ``The Consequences of
Ideas.'' But the Reformed theologian argues that considering basic
truths ``lays bare all of our assumptions so that we may discover
those assumptions that are false and often lethal.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Ergo'': Sproul's brief overview of major Western philosophers,
begins with Plato and his predecessors and proceeds to Friedrich
Nietzsche and Jean-Paul Sarte. ``The Consequences of Ideas''
concentrates more on the ideas than the consequences, although one
hardly needs much reminding about what Karl Marx hath wrought in
Russia and elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Sproul writes for ``educated laypersons,'' so expect some
unfamiliar words and concepts. But the book is almost as
reader-friendly as the topic will allow. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Reviewed by Alan Cochrum &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
