<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are considering for
the Page 1 of Thursday, Aug. 24. The N.Y. Times News Service night
supervisor is Pat Ryan; phone: (888) 346-9867; e-mail:
patryan(at)nytimes.com.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-SUBMARINE-ASSESS (Moscow) _ A news analysis: With the
public confession Wednesday night by President Vladimir Putin that
he feels ``responsibility and guilt'' for the loss of the nuclear
submarine Kursk, Russia's political evolution seems to be taking a
new kind of post-Soviet turn. Military commanders are offering to
resign. The government and the private sector are competing to
raise millions of dollars to comfort the families of the Kursk's
crew. The air waves are ringing with the mea culpas from the
haughty admirals of the once mighty Red Banner Fleet of the north.
It didn't start out that way. By Patrick E. Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-PEACEKEEPING (United Nations) _ A panel of international
experts recommended Wednesday that the U.N. peacekeeping
department, under attack for a series of disasters in recent years,
be enlarged and professionalized, with intelligence-gathering
functions that were essentially forbidden during the Cold War. The
panel of experts, appointed by Secretary General Kofi Annan, urged
that more effort go into preparing for crises before they spin out
of control _ not waiting for instructions from the Security Council
_ and also recommended that peacekeeping officials resist big-power
domination over their day-to-day activities. It is a vision certain
to upset both Americans isolationists as well as some Third World
leaders who fear a that stronger, more independent organization
would mean a new kind of colonialism. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT10.
</P>
<P>
   U.N.-IRAQ-WEAPONS (Baghdad, Iraq) _ Iraq said Wednesday it will
not permit a new U.N. weapons inspection team to visit, promising
that the country would stand firm even if threatened with the use
of force. (Summary from wires) By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   GORE-FLORIDA (Fort Lauderdale, Fla.) _ For the next three days
the presidential campaign will focus on Florida. Gore is there
today; Bush will be there for the next two. Signs point to this
being one of the most competitive states in the race. By Kevin
Sack.
</P>
<P>
   With photo.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-TAX (Austin, Texas) _ Bush's huge tax cut was a true winner
for him in the primaries, but now seems to be an enormous target
for the opposition. By Frank Bruni.
