<P>
   WORKER-WORRIES (Boise, Idaho) _ Few people still talk about
fretting over whether they can find work. Worries over the quality
of those jobs, however, remain a signature part of the economy.
Many say they are concerned that they cannot keep up with
technological changes or that they are working too many hours or
that their health care coverage is inadequate. By David Leonhardt.
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EMBRYO-RESEARCH (Undated) _ The National Institutes of
Health has issued rules that will permit federally financed
researchers to work on human embryonic stem cells. The cells,
because of their ability to form every tissue of the body, are
believed by scientists to hold great promise in treating many
diseases. But because the cell lines are derived from human
embryos, although discarded ones that the parents do not intend to
grow to term, opponents of abortion had objected to federal
approval of the research. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DIABETES-RATE (Undated) _ The incidence of diabetes in the
United States increased markedly between 1990 and 1998, researchers
said, with the increase particularly marked among people in their
30s, among whom there was a 76 percent rise in incidence of the
disease. And they said the new cases will exact a harsh toll in
disability, death and medical expenses in decades to come. The
increase is almost entirely in Type 2 diabetes, commonly called
adult onset diabetes, which accounts for 90-95 percent of all cases
of the disease. Inactivity and weight gain can bring on Type 2
diabetes, and doctors blame much of the current rise on obesity,
which is also increasing steadily, with more than half of Americans
now overweight. By Denise Grady.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-WOMEN-HEART (Undated) _ A new study finds that estrogen
replacement therapy, which doctors and women have long hoped would
prevent heart disease in postmenopausal women, does nothing to slow
the disease's progression in women whose arteries have already been
partially blocked by the disease. By Gina Kolata.
</P>
