<HEADER>
A0159 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-VIDEO-EMAIL-NYT &LR;      08-23 0997
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-VIDEO-EMAIL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VIDEO DRESSES UP E-MAIL ADS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By KAREN J. BANNAN    
 c .2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Shereef Moustafa has always been cautious about opening e-mail
notes containing attachments because he worries about viruses, but
when he received a video e-mail message about an Oracle conference,
his curiosity got the better of him. He clicked on the e-mail's
attachment, and a crisp video began to play almost immediately.
</P>
<P>
   The 30-second video invitation was so intriguing that Moustafa,
a marketing manager for an e-business company based in Los Angeles,
not only signed up for the advertised conference but also forwarded
the message to several of his colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I got it,'' Moustafa said, ``I was quite honestly blown
away. It was tight, easy to watch and didn't waste my time. I
really got a feeling for what the conference would be about in a
short period of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Moustafa is not alone. Jay Stevens, marketing director for
RadicalMail, the company in Marina Del Rey, Calif., that created
and sent the conference video via e-mail, said the Oracle
conference invitation had been sent to 27,000 people and had been
opened 41,000 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before we sent out the invitation, FirstConferences was
getting 10 people signing up for the conference per day,'' Stevens
said. ``After the video e-mail, they got 40 to 50 signups a day.''
</P>
<P>
   Video e-mail messages contain video clips or links to clips that
have been created for an advertiser or an organization. Video
e-mail can be used to send news and information to users who
request it. Video e-mail is relatively new, but the Discovery
Channel, the pop singer Britney Spears and Nissan automobile
dealers in the Atlanta area have already jumped on the video
bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   The reason is simple: Video e-mail lets advertisers tell a story
and gives consumers access to extra features that all-text e-mail
cannot provide. For example, Britney Spears' video e-mail, which
was sent to members of her fan club, contains a short clip of the
singer's latest single as well as a contest link, an e-commerce
component that lets users order her latest CD and an automatic
forwarding option.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're really providing people with entertainment that they can
use to educate themselves and gain access to things that they are
really interested in,'' said Tom Blakeley, the co-chairman of
MindArrow Systems, a company based in Aliso Viejo, Calif., that
provided the technology behind the Britney Spears campaign. ``We
create a way to deliver content that makes people say Wow and gives
them a reason to open their e-mail.''
</P>
<P>
   That factor is what Michele Slack, a senior analyst with Jupiter
Communications, based in New York, says will add to the
proliferation of video e-mail. ``We're seeing more and more
companies utilizing e-mail for marketing,'' Slack said. ``With more
than 268 billion e-mail messages being delivered in a year by 2005,
any type of e-mail that can stand out and break through the clutter
is going to be increasingly powerful.''
</P>
<P>
   But even with the wow factor, there are two potential problems
with video e-mail. The first is the bandwidth required to view the
videos. Today, more than 70 percent of consumers use a
low-bandwidth, dial-up connection to the Web, according to
Dataquest, a research firm in San Jose, Calif. Video e-mail,
especially streaming e-mail, requires large chunks of bandwidth.
High-quality video clips are often as large as 800 kilobytes.
Trying to watch a video that large over a dial-up line can be
difficult, if not impossible, depending on the speed of a
connection.
</P>
<P>
   Although most Web-based video is optimized for people with
high-speed connections, who are expected to be a minority for at
least several years, Slack said, most people with dial-up
connections will be willing to wait for videos to be downloaded, at
least in the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the forefront of any new technology there is an increased
factor of tolerance,'' she said. ``Customers are willing to
experiment more, and they are willing to be more accepting.''
</P>
<P>
   The companies that develop video e-mail _ like MindArrow
Systems; RadicalMail; InChorus.com, in Santa Clara, Calif.;
Media1st.com, in Atlanta; and helloNetwork in Las Vegas _ are
trying to circumvent bandwidth limitations by pushing video only
when a user opens a message. That helps advertisers avoid the
possibility that large e-mail messages will be sent to people who
do not want them. It also helps companies track when a video is
viewed and for how long it is viewed, something that critics say
could lead to privacy problems.
</P>
<P>
   Because companies can track who is watching, how long they stay
with the message and to whom they forward the files, the companies
can theoretically create databases containing preferences and
personal information.
</P>
<P>
   Stevens, of Radical E-Mail, played down the threat of customer
profiling, saying that most video e-mail companies send these
messages only to consumers who ``opt in,'' or agree to accept them.
``If someone has opted in, they can just as easily opt out,''
Stevens said. ``In addition, they have already provided a great
deal of demographic information to begin with.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Dody, the chief executive of Media1st.com, agreed. ``We
always tell consumers right up front that we're collecting the
information that we do,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   And there is an upside to this type of business model, Slack
said. Because most people getting video e-mail choose to do so, and
because video messages are more expensive to produce than text
messages, consumers will see little if any video e-mail spam, she
said.
</P>
<P>
   For Moustafa, giving up a little bit of personal data is a small
price to pay for compelling information that he actually wants.
``Video is definitely a differentiator,'' he said. ``It was totally
like watching television. I would definitely want to see more of
this kind of e-mail. It certainly beats spam any day.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-00 1651EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
