<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-GTECH-0824-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    BRITISH LOTTERY OPERATOR'S TIES TO GTECH RESULTS IN LOSS OF
CONTRACT
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (f) Financial categories.
 &HT;    By BERT ROUGHTON JR. 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ British lottery officials Wednesday said they intend to
drop a company associated with GTECH, the world's largest lottery
operator, in favor of a consortium led by Virgin Group tycoon
Richard Branson.
</P>
<P>
   The Rhode Island-based GTECH, which has a history of
controversy, operates the lotteries in many U.S. states _ including
Georgia, Florida and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Problems with GTECH's software contributed heavily to the
British Lottery Commission's surprise decision to end its
relationship with Camelot, the English company that has held the
lottery contract since 1994, Commission Chairwoman Helena Shovelton
said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   Shovelton also expressed reservations because of ``unresolved
concerns about the long-term propriety of the arrangements made
with GTECH, and between GTECH and Camelot.''
</P>
<P>
   She did not elaborate, but the commission is investigating
Camelot's handling of a technical problem that caused errors in
thousands of prize payments between 1994 and 1998.
</P>
<P>
   GTECH, which at the time had a 22 percent stake in Camelot, did
not tell the company about the glitch until earlier this year,
according to British press reports. Camelot could be fined if the
probe reveals breaches in its agreement with the commission. The
results are expected to be made public next month.
</P>
<P>
   Even though it no longer owns part of Camelot, GTECH remains its
key technical supplier.
</P>
<P>
   While the proposal by Branson's People's Lottery consortium also
had problems, Shovelton said they probably could be resolved
through negotiation.
</P>
<P>
   Branson, who has been eager to win the lottery contract, was
stranded on his Caribbean island by Hurricane Debby and could not
make the announcement. Branson competed with Camelot for the
contract in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Branson accused former GTECH Chairman Guy Snowden of attempting
to bribe Branson into dropping his bid. Branson later sued Snowden
for libel over the affair and won a 1998 judgment that was upheld
on appeal.
</P>
<P>
   The British Parliament also reprimanded a former lottery
regulator for accepting hospitality and free trips in a private jet
owned by GTECH.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, questions have been raised here about Camelot's
profits _ which have run more than US$105 million a year _
directors' bonuses and the way money was distributed to good
causes.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the criticism, Camelot insists it runs the most
successful lottery in the world. It has sold more than US$40
billion worth of tickets and distributed about US$15 billion to
good causes.
</P>
<P>
   Branson has pledged that he would not profit from the lottery,
saying any surpluses would go to good causes.
</P>
<P>
   Included in his consortium are KPMG Consulting, Energis, Compaq,
Kellogg's, Microsoft and Cisco Systems, who will supply the
technology, and advertising agency J Walter Thompson and AWI _
GTECH's chief rival.
</P>
<P>
   Cadbury Schweppes PLC, De La Rue PLC and Thomson-CSF unit, Racal
owns Camelot.
</P>
<P>
   Both Camelot and People's Lottery had pledged to raise nearly
US$23 billion over the next seven years. Branson also proposed
running two online games and pledged to create 2,500 new
millionaires with his proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's decision caught Camelot by surprise. ``We are
bitterly disappointed and stunned by the news,'' the company said
in a statement that also suggested that the matter may not yet be
closed.
</P>
<P>
   GTECH's activities have been the subjects of investigations in
Georgia and Texas, but neither has revealed any criminal
wrongdoing.
</P>
<P>
   (Bert Roughton Jr.'s E-mail address is: bertr(at)coxnews.com)
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
