<HEADLINE>
INDONESIAN PRESIDENT ANNOUNCES NEW CABINET 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This early version will be updated as needed.) 
(This story does not carry a byline) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JAKARTA, Indonesia _ President Abdurrahman Wahid unveiled a
revamped Cabinet Wednesday in a move to revitalize his faltering
administration and tackle acute social and economic woes that are
threatening to tear Indonesia apart.
</P>
<P>
   The new lineup had been widely anticipated since Wahid promised
an angry national assembly two weeks ago that he would make
significant changes to improve his erratic performance and
leadership style _ issues that had concerned some legislators so
much that they had demanded that he step down.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid announced that he was cutting his Cabinet to 26 ministers
from 35, and that the group would include eight new people. Vice
President Megawati Sukarnoputri will supervise the new team and run
the day-to-day business of the government, a move that legislators
had also demanded. Wahid said earlier that he wanted to concentrate
on foreign affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Since taking office in October 1999, Wahid has been criticized
for failing to turn around Indonesia's worst economic slide in
decades. He was also blamed for failing to end corruption within
his government, stop a bloody religious war in the eastern Maluku
islands and halt separatist movements in far-flung provinces.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the problem, Wahid said, was the larger Cabinet, which
had been comprised of politicians from main factions of the
People's Consultative Assembly, which put him into power. He said
that the setup had immediately created disunity as political
rivalries and self interests paralyzed the government.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid said during brief comments to reporters Wednesday that his
new team was mainly composed of professionals who would concentrate
on results, not politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``My consideration was that they must be experts in their
fields,'' he said. ``I know them one by one.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, the appointments of Rizal Ramli, the head of Bulog,
Indonesia's national food distribution agency, and Priyadi Prapto
Suharso, a banker, to run Wahid's economic team raised concern
among some analysts.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Wahid had nominated the new finance minister
to run a state-owned bank, but he was ruled ineligible because of
his earlier involvement with a bank that had failed.
</P>
<P>
   Wahid defended his selections, saying, ``I know exactly about
Priyadi because I have had observations about him for 16 years, not
only now.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The president did not re-hire his economic minister, Kwik Kian
Gie, who resigned last week, or the finance minister, Bambang
Sudibyo. He did name Soesilo Bambang Yudhoyono, the current mines
and energy minister, to the coveted post of coordinating minister
for political and security affairs.
</P>
<P>
   Key Cabinet members including Foreign Minister Alwi Shihab, a
confidant of Wahid's, and Attorney General Marzuki Darusman kept
their jobs, but several others were not retained as Wahid merged
some portfolios.
</P>
<P>
   Hasballah M. Saad, believed to be the first-ever human rights
minister of a sovereign nation, and Defense Minister Juwono
Sudarsono were among a handful of ministers who were ousted.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-00 1710EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000823.0202 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 17:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0170 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l BC-VACATION-HOUSE-870(2T     08-23 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VACATION-HOUSE-870(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HOUSE TRANSFORMS ITSELF, AND A FAMILY 
</HEADLINE>
   By SYDNEY LEBLANC    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   VALLEY CENTER, Calif. _ If you were to choose a place to
construct a high-concept vacation house, it would probably not be
Valley Center.
</P>
<P>
   This remote desert hamlet, beautiful though it is, seems more
suited to the citrus groves, avocado orchards and ostrich ranches
that cover its rolling hills. Two and a half hours south of Los
Angeles, it's a world away from that capital of architectural
creativity.
</P>
<P>
   But here on a Valley Center hilltop sits a brazenly modern
structure with metal-wrapped walls cantilevered over a luxuriant
orange orchard. Mysteriously ambiguous, it could be an exotic
construction trailer _ or a miniature Getty Museum poised against
the sky.
</P>
<P>
   ``If my father was shocked by the new architecture he's never
said so,'' Penny Cuff McNulty said of the ingenious house that
provides new horizons for three generations of her family.
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago the house on this hill was a typical ranch
belonging to her father, Charles Cuff, now 85. It went up in flames
in a raging wildfire, and in three hours the Cuffs lost a home and
the heart of the family's century-old citrus-growing operation.
</P>
<P>
   The Cuffs felt they had to rebuild in the same place to
recapture a vital touchstone. But the family itself had changed.
Cuff was semiretired in Los Angeles; his three daughters had
married, moved away and had children, ranging in age from 7 to 30.
Making Valley Center a getaway offered a saving grace, and a hub
where the far-flung clan could reconnect.
</P>
<P>
   ``The family became an unwitting client,'' explained Kevin Daly,
43, a Santa Monica architect who is married to Cuff's daughter Dana
Cuff. The residence he designed with his partner, Christopher
Genik, has introduced startling new ideas into a traditional
landscape. Perforated aluminum screens form a protective shell over
long glass walls. These screens are architecture in action. Some
glide side to side like shiny bifold doors. Others are motorized to
move up and down with the push of a button. Set in their
stop-action positions, they resemble shimmering silver visors
cocked at jaunty angles.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because they came to the project so unexpectedly, they had no
preconceptions about what it should be,'' Daly said. ``But first,
we had to figure out what had been lost.'' To Cuff, the loss seemed
devastating. ``I lost everything _ pictures, piano, antiques all
went up in smoke,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The insurers naturally had their ideas. A replacement-cost
settlement, the family learned, meant replicating the old ranch
house, at $120 a foot. But the architects of the family (Dana Cuff
is a professor in the architecture department at UCLA) eventually
wooed them with a different design within the replacement-cost
calculation.
</P>
<P>
   ``All my father-in-law asked was that we keep it flat,'' Daly
said. ``And I'm sure he would have been just as happy if we had
come up with an adobe-style house with a red tile roof, like those
you see all over Southern California.''
</P>
<P>
   But Spanish Mission was not Daly, Genik's hidden agenda. Daly
worked in Frank Gehry's office before joining forces 11 years ago
with Genik, a former Rice University classmate.
</P>
<P>
   The partners are best known for designing simple, boxlike
buildings that are wrapped in screens and layers to alter the
viewers' perception of structure and space.
</P>
<P>
   Their approach connects them with larger forces sweeping the
international architectural scene. Closely watched trendsetters
like the Swiss team of Herzog &AMP; de Meuron and the French architect
Jean Nouvel have become famous for creating semitransparent facades
that change the nature of walls, selectively reveal the interiors,
manipulate light and evoke mystery, and no small point, for making
beautiful buildings that delight the senses.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told Charlie that if we were going to change anything, we
might as well change everything,'' Daly recalled. ``Fortunately, he
was willing to suspend disbelief.''
</P>
<P>
   In contemplating the new design, the architects faced a creative
contradiction. The 3,000-square-foot house had to be flexible
enough to accommodate three generations of Cuff family members,
including spouses, children and grandchildren. They might visit at
any time and in any combination and wanted a place that was always
vacation-ready.
</P>
<P>
   But a house that was too open would not be secure, and security
_ especially fire protection _ was a vital concern for the family,
whose memories of the big fire lingered.
</P>
<P>
   The phoenix, it seemed, would have to have a split personality:
airy and open one moment, tough as nails the next. Surprisingly,
the fire issue became the catalyst for the new design.
</P>
<P>
   Daly, Genik's solution could be called an open-and-shut vacation
house, a Transformer-like structure that springs to life in an
instant, then closes completely.
</P>
<P>
   The transformation is accomplished with large moving parts:
perforated screens on the central living and dining area move up
and down. Screens along the two bedroom wings, which form a U
around the courtyard, are manual and slide side to side with a
twist of the wrist. All of them can be adjusted through the day in
accordance with the sun's movement, or to allow a little siesta at
any time.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all so easy the kids can do it,'' Dana Cuff said. When
it's time to leave, the screens shift into reverse, restoring the
protective shell that helps provide peace of mind.
</P>
<P>
   The unique silver screens were inspired by two ordinary building
elements _ the overhead garage door and the sliding bifold door.
These doors could be made to pass the architects' personal
ingenuity test, that every element they designed should accomplish
more than one thing. Their screen doors provide security, shade,
interior light control and stunning visual effects.
</P>
<P>
   When the screen bifold doors on the courtyard-side bedroom wings
are opened, they resemble great books wrapped in shiny metal
jackets. Most striking are the massive vertical screens protecting
the living and dining area, which occupies the taller, central part
of the U. Deployed three across on the eastern and western
exposures, these monumental 10-foot-by-24-foot screens hang from
cross-braced steel tracks, extensions of the interior ceiling's
I-beams. Each screen is powered by a small motor that tilts it up
and out, angled away from the house.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those living room doors looked so enormous at first,'' Dana
Cuff exclaimed at the memory. ``It was a relief to find that they
were actually under our control.''
</P>
<P>
   The silvery sunscreens work wonders with the desert light, and
it's the mutable visual perception, the architects say, that is
their favorite feature of the design.
</P>
<P>
   Sunlight filters softly in through the thousands of tiny
perforations, charging up the atmosphere; you can almost put your
finger on it, like phosphorescence. Looking out through the
screens, the dazzling desert light becomes slightly veiled. ``It's
like using camera apertures to step down the light,'' Daly said.
</P>
<P>
   Shades in summer, in winter they bounce light back into the
interior. In a sunset, the house looks radiant with the pink, blue,
purple and gold desert light alternately washing over its silver
surfaces. Later, it glows like a lantern in the night.
</P>
<P>
   The screens, with designed-in breathability, Genik said, make
the house habitable in the desert and help with cross-ventilation.
All the exterior surfaces reflect sunlight, and the siting captures
cooling breezes.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, there is a simple plan and desert-spare decoration. The
main living and dining area floats freely between two long glass
walls, with a fireplace to anchor the space and provide seismic
stability. An open kitchen is separated from the space by an island
counter.
</P>
<P>
   ``We love to cook,'' said Penny Cuff McNulty, who visits from
her home near Washington. ``Sometimes, we have four cooks in the
kitchen, and it always works.''
</P>
<P>
   The bedroom wings are also transformable. Thanks again to
sliding doors, there can be from four to seven bedrooms, sleeping
as many as 14 people. These sleeping alcoves are arrayed single
file, like Pullman cars. Birch plywood sliding doors close them off
for sleeping or open them to the courtyard's glass walls; other
sliding doors, between rooms, allow suitelike spaces for parents
with children. The end bedrooms in each wing are private. Some of
these rooms have tiny desks for adults to work and for children to
play with their computers.
</P>
<P>
   In lieu of artwork, shots of color enliven the cool,
monochromatic shell. Bedroom doors and concrete floors are painted
shades of chartreuse, purple, blue and yellow. Kilim rugs brighten
bare concrete floors. Dining chairs are candy-coated colors.
Bathrooms, tiled in squares of Mexican glass, are vibrant aqua or
sapphire. Window frames in the bedroom wings are painted canary
yellow.
</P>
<P>
   The architects' open design plays to the big-sky landscape.
Oriented westward, the twin wings of the house frame a long view of
the Pacific Ocean, 20 miles away. To the east, Palomar Mountain
rises behind the house. From almost any spot it's easy to feel on
top of the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like a Donald Judd sculpture placed in the desert,'' said
Cameron Armstrong, a Houston architect who clads his houses in
corrugated metal. ``It's minimal without being minimalist. You're
left alone with the essentials of the place: earth, water, light
and sky. There's the potential for a clean moment here.''
</P>
<P>
   Open and relaxed as it is, the Cuffs' house attempts to erect a
fortress against fire. The aluminum screens, while not fireproof,
are fire resistant. They prevent ignition that could be caused by
sparks or flying embers piercing the interior. Every exposed
surface, including outer bedroom walls of corrugated concrete
board, is made of a noncombustible material.
</P>
<P>
   If a fire should start, there is a large-radius rooftop
sprinkler system that drenches the surrounding landscape. The
swimming pool has a special pump and an independent generator so
that its water can be diverted for firefighting.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to forget how savage the fire was,'' Daly said.
Still, the rebuilding process was restorative. ``The whole family
lost a house and now the whole family has built it back,'' said
Cuff, who visits weekly from Los Angeles. ``It has bound us
together in a new way.'' Now, when family members exchange gifts,
they're usually presents for the place they've all come to share.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's difficult to characterize a vacation house as something
other than a luxury, a bauble,'' Kevin Daly concluded. ``But this
house is different.The entire family had an emotional tie to the
ranch. In this case, it's all about being there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
