<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILDFIRESANIMALS0824-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Greenville residents aid in effort to save animals threatened by
wildfires
 &HT;    By Cynthia Kopkowski
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. - Wildfires gobbling up land out west this
summer are leaving many farm animals and family pets in danger.
</P>
<P>
   With the memory of animal rescues during Hurricane Floyd still
fresh in their minds, two Greenville residents packed their bags to
lend a hand in Montana.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Scott and Cora Tyson joined volunteers from around the
country working with the Emergency Animal Rescue Service in
Hamilton, Mont., 25 miles away from the edge of the fires. EARS is
the rescue division of the California-based United Animal Nations.
</P>
<P>
   The team began its efforts Aug. 16 at fairgrounds in one of the
state's western border counties. Firefighters from Winterville,
Greenville, Kinston and Trenton also arrived in Hamilton on Sunday
to battle the blazes.
</P>
<P>
   EARS volunteers are working with 325 animals that were brought
to the facility by families forced to evacuate. Animals brought to
the shelter are assigned a number and photo ID to ensure easy
retrieval by their owners.
</P>
<P>
   Scott was on the other side of the animal rescue fence last
year, when EARS volunteers rescued his two dogs trapped at his
family's flooded Belvoir home. When he saw the Montana fires
getting worse, Scott got in his car and drove 2,545 miles to work
at the makeshift menagerie.
</P>
<P>
   He arrived Monday morning after a 48-hour trip that carried him
past charred fields and was hindered by roads closed due to the
fire. First on his list in Hamilton was a tour of the fairgrounds
facility.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's kind of like a zoo here now,'' Scott said. ``That's what
it looks like at least, but it's quiet. Right now I'm standing in
front of where all the animals are kept, and it's very full.''
</P>
<P>
   While in Montana, Scott will sleep in a tent neighboring 37
horses, 47 goats, one llama, four alpacas, 18 cows, one wolf, 120
chickens, one bull and 32 dogs and cats.
</P>
<P>
   During long work days, he and other volunteers will do ``what
their owners normally would do,'' he said, including feeding and
nursing the animals.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the stranger sights Scott and Tyson witnessed at the
camp included a dog taking cough medicine for a smoke-induced sore
throat and calves drinking milk from goats standing on top of a
table.
</P>
<P>
   Along with veterinarians, the volunteers are working with a
rabbit with a broken leg, an injured cat and a badly burned bull
that was a nearby resident's pet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has a job to do and all of them here with EARS know
what to do,'' Scott said. ``And just like in Greenville they have
people that walked in to volunteer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of people out here that care about the
animals.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the fires sweeping through nearby counties and states,
Scott said a low gray ceiling of smoke is a choking reminder.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is smoke all around; you can't turn in any direction and
not see it,'' he said. ``I've never seen anything like this. We're
in the middle of a bunch of mountains, but you can't even tell
they're there.''
</P>
<P>
   Scott is working side by side with fellow Greenville resident
Tyson, the Pitt County coordinator for EARS. She flew to Montana
after the group's national director requested help.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson is adapting to a schedule dictated by Mother Nature.
</P>
<P>
   ``Winds can shift quickly, so when an evacuation order gets put
out people will bring animals in at all hours, many around
midnight,'' Tyson said.
</P>
<P>
   For the animal rescuers, days ending at midnight usually begin
before dawn.
</P>
<P>
   ``We get woken up about 6 in the morning by the rooster,'' Tyson
said with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   A typical day for Tyson and other volunteers consists of three
hours of morning animal feeding and cage cleaning. The group grabs
a quick breakfast and then meets with the U.S. Forestry Service
officials for an update on evacuation orders and the fires' status.
</P>
<P>
   After a short afternoon break the whole process begins again,
Tyson said.
</P>
<P>
   Tyson said she has to be back in Greenville by Sept. 1 but will
stay until that time if she is needed.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
