<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILDFIRESNCVOLUNTEER0824-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Infrequent phone calls are only link to husbands battling blazes
 &HT;    By Cynthia Kopkowski
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GREENVILLE, N.C. - Some Pitt County residents are keeping a
closer eye on wildfires out west than most. That's because their
family members are battling the blazes.
</P>
<P>
   The families of Derrick Moore and Tom Harris, two of 231
firefighters from North Carolina that have gone to the fires since
the end of June, are keeping an eye on the situation. A team of 57
firefighters from 10 area counties, including Pitt, Beaufort,
Martin and Greene, traveled west in the last two months.
</P>
<P>
   Sporadic phone calls and news reports provide Suzanne Moore with
a tentative link to her husband, a North Carolina Forestry Service
assistant ranger who is fighting fires in Idaho. She has seen her
husband only four days in the past month, in between his trip to
Colorado at the end of July and his Aug. 13 flight to Pocatello,
Idaho. She expects him to return next week.
</P>
<P>
   Waiting and watching are roles familiar to Moore, whose husband
fought fires in Florida and Montana in 1998 and 1999 and did rescue
work in Belvoir during Hurricane Floyd.
</P>
<P>
   When an early morning call came from the state's forestry
service to the Moore's house on July 24, Derrick was packed and
ready to go. He passed a physical and skill tests at the beginning
of the year to become eligible for volunteer wildfire duty.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's rough, but I know it's something that he has wanted to do
since he joined the forestry service,'' said Suzanne, a paralegal.
``And they really need help out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters from North Carolina sent west are working under the
direction of the U.S. Forestry Service, said John Shepherd, a
section chief with the state forestry office's Raleigh
headquarters. A group of about 20 North Carolina firefighters is on
standby to head to the fires this week, Shepherd said.
</P>
<P>
   Harris, a 25-year veteran of the forestry service, is fighting
fires near the Bitterroot River in southwestern Montana. His calls
home have been limited due to few phones and long work days.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way I look at it is, no news is normally good news,'' said
Harris' wife, Darlene, who last talked to him Sunday. ``I've really
become accustomed to it.''
</P>
<P>
   The Harris' have been married 26 years and managed to celebrate
their anniversary Thursday before Tom left for Montana. Darlene
watched her husband fight fires in California in the 1970s, went
eight days without seeing him during Hurricane Floyd and spent
several weeks alone while he battled blazes in Florida this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Darlene, an employee with the U.S. Bankruptcy Office in
Greenville, even takes on the challenge of helping her husband get
out the door.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once he gets the call, it's a mad dash to help him get packed
and ready,'' she said. ``This time I had to get a pup tent, a
sleeping bag and 14 days worth of clothes in one suitcase. That's
not easy _ it's a lot of smushing.''
</P>
<P>
   The most recent phone call Darlene got from her husband was
Tuesday morning from the side of a mountain in Idaho. He was on one
of his five-minute breaks in what he told her were 12- or 16-hour
days trying to uncover hot spots and build fire-slowing fire lines.
</P>
<P>
   ``Phone calls are very important,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But long days and a three-hour time difference means those calls
may come late at night just before Tom crawls into his tent, she
added.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some mornings they're up by 4:30, on the mountain at 6 and not
back at camp until 9,'' Suzanne said. ``He eats, takes a quick
shower and then calls quickly to say, `This is where I'm at, this
is what's going on.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I know they're all tired,'' Suzanne said, ``but they realize
that they're there for a good reason.''
</P>
<P>
   Understanding the necessity of her husband's work doesn't always
make his absence easier, Darlene said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Companionship is what I miss the most,'' she said. ``We just
purchased a place on the (Pamlico) river. Last time I talked to him
he asked why I wasn't up there when he called and I said, `It's not
any fun,''' without him.
</P>
<P>
   For Suzanne, waiting for her husband means focusing on work,
singing with the church choir, eating dinner with neighbors and
taking care of the couple's dog, Casey.
</P>
<P>
   Missing from the long-distance relationships is fear, both wives
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I'm not nervous,'' Suzanne said of her husband, a
four-year veteran of the forest service. ``He's got a very good
head on his shoulders.''
</P>
<P>
   Back home, descriptions of the wildfires in newspapers and on
television are supplemented by their loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   Suzanne said the photos from Derrick's first trip to Mesa Verde,
Colo., put the images of burned trees and fields in the palm of her
hand.
</P>
<P>
   Hearing her husband's stories about the fires reinforced
Darlene's commitment to supporting his work.
</P>
<P>
   ``He takes a lot of pride in what he's doing; it's a calling to
him,'' she said. ``I'm pretty independent, and that allows him to
keep doing what he needs to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
