<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 17:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0181 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-U.N.-TIMOR-315&AMP;ADD-NY     08-23 0457
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-TIMOR-315&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATTACKS PROMPT UNITED NATIONS TO SUSPEND RELIEF WORK IN WEST
TIMOR 
</HEADLINE>
   By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ The U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees said
Wednesday that all aid operations in West Timor have been suspended
following the severe beating of three relief workers by
pro-Indonesia militiamen.
</P>
<P>
   When the attack took place on Tuesday, the three workers were
distributing plastic sheeting to East Timorese refugees in West
Timor, which is still ruled by Indonesia. All three were assaulted
with machetes, clubs and stones, and one worker had his head held
under water in a rice field until he choked and nearly drowned,
officials in Geneva said. All suffered severe injuries, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   Soren Jessen-Petersen, the assistant high commissioner, accused
the Indonesian government of allowing the pro-Indonesia militiamen,
at least some of whom are thought to be backed by the Indonesian
military, to behave with impunity, making ``a mockery of statements
by responsible officials in Jakarta guaranteeing security for aid
workers and refugees.''
</P>
<P>
   U.N. officials said that Indonesian military units in the area
failed to respond to calls for help during the attack, at
Kefamenanu, about 130 miles from Kupang, the capital of West Timor.
</P>
<P>
   There have now been more than 100 cases of assaults on aid
workers in the year since the East Timorese voted for independence
from Indonesia and many fled or were driven from their homes in the
militia-led violence that ensued. Officials say that Tuesday's
attacks may have been the worst.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations was sending a senior refugee official to West
Timor to investigate the attack, the refugee commissioner's office
said.
</P>
<P>
   About 125,000 East Timorese remain in West Timor. The United
Nations has been trying to register them to determine how many want
to stay on Indonesian territory and how many want to return to
their homes. Nearly 170,000 East Timorese have already returned to
their homeland to be resettled.
</P>
<P>
   The Indonesian government periodically announces that it will
close all the refugee camps in West Timor and resettle some of the
East Timorese in other parts of Indonesia if they want to stay in
the country, but there has been no action. An Indonesian official
in Dili, the East Timorese capital, on Wednesday promised to close
down refugee camps in West Timor in three to six months.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. refugee agency has repeatedly asked that the militiamen
be removed from the camps and not be allowed to intimidate
refugees. Many of the remaining displaced East Timorese are thought
to be afraid to voice their wishes to return home for fear of
attack by the roving militia groups.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
