<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Thursday, Aug. 24, sent to computer graphics clients of The New
York Times News Service. For information call: 212-556-4204.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Drier and slightly cooler air will circulate from the Great
Lakes into New England on Thursday as a cold front pushes off the
northeast coast. However, clouds and showers will persist in Maine,
and the sky will clear slowly along the New England coast. The
leading edge of this Canadian-born air will reach into the Middle
Atlantic states, where thundershowers will erupt along a cold
front.
</P>
<P>
   Sultry weather will dominate the South under hazy sunshine.
Afternoon storms will develop near the central and western Gulf
Coast as sea breezes push farther inland. Showers and a few
thunderstorms are expected in the lower Ohio and Tennessee valleys.
</P>
<P>
   The center of a very hot air mass will be over the Oklahoma
panhandle. Most of the upper Plains will be hotter and more humid.
The flow of moisture from the Gulf of Mexico into the Southwest
will bring widespread thundershowers from the mountains of Arizona
to western Wyoming.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: SPUTTERING STORMS
</P>
<P>
   Warm, moist air rising from near the ocean's surface is the
lifeblood of hurricanes. On Wednesday, two Atlantic hurricanes were
deprived of their essential fuel. Once-mighty Hurricane Alberto
dissipated over the cold waters of the North Atlantic, having
become the third longest tropical storm recorded in the Atlantic.
Meanwhile, Hurricane Debby weakened to a tropical storm as dry air
descending from the mountains of Hispaniola was drawn into the
circulation of the storm.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
