<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000823.0210 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0183 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-POL-TICKER0824-COX     08-23 1524
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0824-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Entering the Florida battleground
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Already peppering the state with new campaign ads, the
presidential candidates are making live appearances in south
Florida this week. First was a trip today to Kings Point, a largely
Jewish and politically active condominium community between Fort
Lauderdale and Boca Raton, by Al Gore and Joe Lieberman. After
that, they were attending a fund-raiser for the Democratic Party at
a private home in Fort Lauderdale. The Democrats will be followed
by George W. Bush, set to campaign Thursday and Friday in
Miami-Dade County. It will be the first visit for both campaigns
since the conventions. Florida, with 25 electoral votes, could go
either way this year.
</P>
<P>
   EDUCATION, AND SOME FUND-RAISING
</P>
<P>
   Mixing fund-raising with photo opportunities, Dick Cheney was
continuing his Southern California swing today in Bakersfield and
Santa Barbara. The tour is part of a campaign to promote George W.
Bush's education message of accountability and high standards
across the nation. The centerpiece of his public appearances today
was a leadership forum with Junior ROTC students at Bakersfield
High School. After that, he was going to the opening of a GOP
headquarters in Kern County, then to Santa Barbara for a
fund-raiser.
</P>
<P>
   JUST TAKE HER HAND AND FOLLOW ALONG
</P>
<P>
   When Dick Cheney went to an elementary school in Redlands,
Calif., to discuss education policies, he brought along a secret
campaign weapon: his wife, Lynne. Her role became clear almost the
moment they arrived. It was she who gamely worked the crowd of
fourth-graders as she and her husband toured a computer laboratory
in front of the cameras. The Republican vice presidential
candidate, meanwhile, stood quietly in the center of the room, his
hands in the pockets of his pinstripe suit, smiling. His brand of
small talk was with teacher Viola Perez, asking her about the
federal Title I program for disadvantaged students and training for
teachers.
</P>
<P>
   DEBATES IN THE TALKING STAGE
</P>
<P>
   The chairmen of the Bush and Gore campaigns have begun tentative
negotiations on debates. Chris Lehane, spokesman for Al Gore, said
the campaign chairman, William Daley, had spoken with Donald Evans,
an oil entrepreneur and longtime friend of George W. Bush. Bush has
said he's willing to debate Gore three times, but has not accepted
the dates, sites or formats of the October events proposed by the
bipartisan Commission on Presidential Debates. Gore's aides have
said he will accept those debate invitations as well as numerous
others.
</P>
<P>
   ELECTRIFYING UTILITY RATE HIKES
</P>
<P>
   Calling on citizens to fight corporate dominance of the country,
Green Party candidate Ralph Nader advised Californians to take
regulatory control of their state's electricity industry and demand
their money back. Nader called on the state Legislature and Gov.
Gray Davis to pass a rate rollback law that doesn't include a
balloon payment to compensate utilities for the money they would
lose during a rate decrease. In San Diego, the first city in
California to feel the effects of subjecting customers to free
market prices for electricity, rates have almost quadrupled in the
last two months. Today, Nader was taking his campaign north to
Santa Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   PLAY US A SAD POLITICAL SONG
</P>
<P>
   Some country music stars aren't standing by Al Gore because he's
from Tennessee. Some of Nashville's biggest acts _ Brooks &AMP; Dunn,
Wynonna Judd, Hank Williams Jr., Loretta Lynn, Travis Tritt, Lorrie
Morgan and the Oak Ridge Boys _ are lining up with Texan George W.
Bush. But Gore, whose family farm is 50 miles east of Music City,
isn't without down-home support. He's got Pam Tillis, Mary Chapin
Carpenter, Kathy Mattea, John Michael Montgomery, Ricky Van Shelton
and Marty Stuart on his side. Representatives for Faith Hill and
Tim McGraw, Garth Brooks and the Dixie Chicks _ some of the
industry's chartbusters _ say they're too busy with their careers
to choose sides.
</P>
<P>
   REFORM PARTY FEUD GOES TO COURT
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of Pat Buchanan launched a suit in federal court in
Virginia against rival Reform Party presidential candidate John
Hagelin, seeking to bar him from referring to himself as the
party's nominee. A hearing for a temporary restraining order has
been set for Aug. 30 before U.S. District Judge Norman Moon. Each
candidate claimed the Reform mantle this month at the party's
convention, a raucous gathering that ended with supporters of each
naming him as the nominee. At stake is $12.6 million in federal
matching funds for the real candidate.
</P>
<P>
   OR, THEY COULD FLIP A COIN
</P>
<P>
   While opposing Reform Party factions fight over who is the
party's true presidential nominee, Montana Secretary of State Mike
Cooney will use a lottery to settle the issue for his state's
general election ballot. A drawing will be conducted Thursday to
determine whether Pat Buchanan or John Hagelin will be listed as
the Reform candidate in November. Cooney said that process is
dictated by state law when a party's choice of nominee is unclear.
He added, however, that his office would have to abide by any court
order, regardless of the outcome of the lottery.
</P>
<P>
   TIPTOE THROUGH THE TWO LIPS
</P>
<P>
   Sooner esident pro tem Yusuf Salaam, are the key. Smitherman
says he'll have to receive at least 400 of Salaam's votes on Sept.
12 to have a chance to win.
</P>
<P>
   OKLAHOMA OK FOR INCUMBENTS
</P>
<P>
   A car salesman who compares representing voters to providing
good customer service will lead Republican efforts to keep a House
seat in eastern Oklahoma. Andy Ewing, retiring Rep. Tom Coburn's
hand-picked successor, beat six other GOP candidates in a primary
in a district where Republicans are outnumbered 5-to-2. Democrats
sent two candidates _ state Rep. Bill Settle and James ``Jim Bob''
Wilson, who campaigns on the fact he is not a lawyer _ to a Sept.
19 runoff. Reps. J.C. Watts, Ernest Istook and Steve Largent easily
defeated inexperienced and underfunded GOP challengers. But each
faces opposition in November.
</P>
<P>
   SPARSELY POPULATED PRIMARIES
</P>
<P>
   Besides Oklahoma, there were primaries in two other states.
Wyoming's first-term GOP Sen. Craig Thomas faced no primary
opposition, and mine worker Mel Logan beat a retired businessman
for the Democratic nomination to challenge Thomas in the fall.
Three-term Rep. Barbara Cubin easily won her nomination against two
poorly funded fellow Republican challengers. She will face office
clerk Michael Green, who won the Democratic nomination. In Alaska,
the state's lone House member, GOP Rep. Don Young, had no
challengers for his party's nomination. He has represented the
state since 1973.
</P>
<P>
   IN THE FOOTSTEPS OF THE SUFFRAGISTS
</P>
<P>
   Invoking the legacy of the suffragists at every turn, Hillary
Clinton sought to portray herself as a champion of women and
working families and to bolster her support in Rochester, N.Y.,
where Susan B. Anthony once fought for the right to vote. Clinton
toured Anthony's red-brick home, boasted of her own efforts to
promote women's issues like breast cancer and child care, and even
appeared with Ruth Dyk, 99, who once marched alongside the
suffragists and likened Clinton to them. ``If I've learned one
thing, it's this: New York needs a woman's touch,'' said Dyk.
</P>
<P>
   DEMOCRATS' ADS FADE TO BLACK
</P>
<P>
   Responding to Republican threats, television stations in two
congressional districts have pulled Democratic attack ads on the
grounds that they distorted the GOP candidates' voting records.
Both the cable company Comcast in New Jersey and four network
stations in Lexington, Ky., have decided in the past week to stop
airing ads funded by the Democratic Congressional Campaign
Committee questioning the GOP candidates' votes on education bills.
The candidates are Rep. Ernie Fletcher in Kentucky and ex-Rep. Dick
Zimmer in New Jersey. TV stations cannot be held legally liable for
the content of ads funded by candidates for federal office, but
they can be sued for defamation in the case of issue ads funded by
outside groups.
</P>
<P>
   FIRST REVLON, NOW THIS
</P>
<P>
   A group that wants to get women elected to the White House
offered a job to Monica Lewinsky _ then quickly dropped it.
American Women Presidents, formed in March to promote the election
of women as president and vice president, faxed a letter to
Lewinsky's lawyer, Plato Cacheris, offering her the post of
corporate vice president. But a few hours later, the offer was
rescinded. The fax had said the group was disturbed that Lewinsky's
``life and career have been sidetracked'' since her affair with
President Clinton ``while the lives and careers of most of the
others involved in our national tragedy have remained intact.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Compiled by Ernie Freda from staff and news reports.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
