<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 17:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0184 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-SOCCER-WEB-NYT &LR;      08-23 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-SOCCER-WEB-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON THE NET, SOCCER WAITS FOR PRIME TIME 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 (DUPLICATION WARNING: Also filed in category `s.')  
 By JACK BELL    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   A soccer game lasts 90 minutes, but the global passion for the
sport is never governed by the clock. And it's a good thing,
because watching a European match on American television usually
means staying up very late or getting up very, very early.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, the mainstream news media cover only the
big events, like the men's and women's World Cup. Other than a
pilgrimage to Old Trafford, the soccer stadium in Manchester,
England, to see a Manchester United match or to Nou Camp in Spain
to see F.C. Barcelona, perhaps the best way to slake the obsession
for soccer is on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet is emerging as the talk radio of soccer, providing
statistics, chat rooms and Web sites dedicated to individual
players.
</P>
<P>
   Staying current with European and other results from around the
world once meant tuning in the crackly and elusive signals of a
shortwave radio. Now it is more likely that soccer aficionados
marooned on these shores can tune to matches on the Internet via
streaming audio.
</P>
<P>
   Broadcast.com from Yahoo offers live matches, but only from a
handful of teams in Italy (A.C. Milan, Juventus and Parma) and
Britain (Manchester United, Arsenal, Derby County and Glasgow
Celtic). Internetsoccer.com takes a more local approach,
broadcasting the regional World Cup qualifying matches now being
played by the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Most European club teams have official (and many, many
unofficial) Web sites, some of which, like Paris Saint-Germain
(www.psg.fr), also offer an English version. In general, the sites
have a club's history, schedules, news releases, player roster and,
of course, merchandise (most European clubs have the nasty habit of
changing their uniform style every season).
</P>
<P>
   Another excellent way to follow a match (whether it is a regular
league game on the weekend or a match in continental cup
competition) in real time is with the Match Tracker. It is used at
the official Web sites of two of the most famous European clubs:
Manchester United (manutd.com) and Barcelona (fcbarcelona.com).
</P>
<P>
   Launching Match Tracker calls up a window on the screen that
will give you a second-by-second, text-based play-by-play of the
match, including statistics, lineups (with player pictures and
information) and an audio link (if the match is being broadcast
over the Internet). It is probably the closest you can get to the
match without actually being there.
</P>
<P>
   A straight tickertape of scores can be found at Livescore.com.
There, you can follow matches in 18 European countries as well as
continental and international cup competitions like the European
Champions League, the UEFA Cup and qualifying matches leading up to
the 2002 World Cup finals in South Korea and Japan. Scores are
updated every few minutes. A small flashing green square denotes a
match in progress, and there is also a notation of how much time
has elapsed in the match. When a match ends, the site provides a
link to a news service report about the match.
</P>
<P>
   As more young American players like Landon Donovan (on the Bayer
Leverkusen team in Germany), Joe-Max Moore (Everton in England) and
Claudio Reyna (Glasgow Rangers in Scotland) seek fame (but mostly
fortune) playing soccer in Europe, the Internet has made it
possible, even easy, to follow their weekly performances.
</P>
<P>
   The site with the most extensive information on Americans
playing overseas is Soccerspot.com. The site's research is now
being picked up and distributed by the U.S. Soccer Federation (on
its Web site, www.us-soccer.com, and via e-mail messages) and
ESPN.com.
</P>
<P>
   Video broadcasts on the Web are probably still a couple of years
away, but soccer fans can use the Internet to find listings of
soccer on TV (primarily satellite TV) by checking out the listings
at Soccertv.com.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-00 1729EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000823.0212 </DOCNO>
