<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 17:34 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0189 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-PALM-HOTELS-NYT &LR;      08-23 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-PALM-HOTELS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPENING DOORS AT HOTEL WITH A PALM IN THE HAND 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md., Mass., Utah)   (Circuits)  
 By CATHERINE GREENMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   They won't beam fresh towels up to the room, but Palm handhelds
that can send and receive infrared signals will soon function as
check-in desks and even room keys for travelers who stay at some
hotels.
</P>
<P>
   The system will beam room numbers and door lock codes from the
computer network at the hotel's registration desk to a guest's Palm
through infrared ports. When the guest gets to the room, the Palm
will transmit an infrared signal to a chip in the door lock to open
the room. The system was developed by Suite Technology System
Network, based in Salt Lake City, and Micros Systems, in Columbia,
Md.
</P>
<P>
   Technology is already an important part of the amenities offered
by major hotels, many of which let guests use their television
remote controls to do things like checking out. The next wave of
technology is expected to let hotels offer many more services to
guests and tailor those services to match personal needs and
preferences.
</P>
<P>
   The first installation of the Palm-based communication system is
at the Charles Hotel in Cambridge, Mass. The hotel's general
manager, Michael Doyle, said each guest would also be able to
choose the room temperature, the type of pillow and the time for a
wake-up call through a keyboard wired to the hotel network and the
Internet. A high-definition television acts as a monitor in each
room. Guests will also be able to order room service and use their
Internet accounts via the keyboards. Each guest's preferences will
be stored, along with information like bookmarked Web sites, so
they can be called up if the guest returns.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll be looking at how we can communicate with these devices
and set the tone for a customer's arrival,'' Doyle said. The Palm
system and network for rooms will be available at the Charles early
next year.
</P>
<P>
   Palm-based door openers are also being used in the real estate
industry. Last year, Palm Inc. and Supra Products, a company that
makes electronic locks, introduced the eKEY, a devices that
attaches to the Palm Vx to give a real estate agent access to a
house (as well as access to market information through the device's
wireless and cradle connections).
</P>
<P>
   Many hotels are working on ways to provide automated wireless
services to their customers. Joe Lazlo, a senior analyst at Jupiter
Communications, said the Charles Hotel was taking a small but
innovative step toward wireless personalization, while much of the
hotel industry seemed to be waiting for the widespread adoption of
a single wireless platform.
</P>
<P>
   ``Attempts to do these cool wireless applications have been
somewhat limited,'' Lazlo said. ``Wireless communication is neat
stuff, but deployment on a nationwide basis really begs a reliable
standard that vendors in a whole bunch of different industries can
agree on.''
</P>
<P>
   Many in the hotel industry say they believe that the winning
platform will be Bluetooth, which is being developed by Intel,
Nokia, Ericsson and other electronics and telecommunications
companies and will connect cellular phones and handhelds with
computers. The companies involved include 3Com, which recently spun
off Palm Inc., and Microsoft, which makes Pocket PC software; not
surprisingly, both Palm and Pocket PC devices are expected to
become compatible with Bluetooth.
</P>
<P>
   Employees at the Sheraton New Orleans Hotel are using Pocket PC
handheld computers that link wirelessly to the hotel network to
enter housekeeping information. W.J. Kitchen, chief executive of
Amaranth Technology Systems, which makes the software to link the
Pocket PC devices to the hotel network, said the system would
ultimately run on Bluetooth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll start to see Bluetooth-equipped handhelds and cell
phones,'' he said, ``which will both automatically check in
customers and transmit information to the hotel staff to let them
greet returning customers by name or offer them a bottle of their
favorite wine.''
</P>
<P>
   Hotel industry experts say wireless technology will let
personalized customer service become more automated in the next few
years. ``The Palm application is somewhat dependent on the number
of people who have a wireless Palm device,'' said David Moon, a
partner in the hotel industry group at Arthur Andersen in Phoenix.
``But we think the wireless Web offers a very significant
opportunity in terms of automating not only check-in, but services
within the hotel, like authenticating entry into the health club.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for hotels, Moon said, will be to integrate their
current networks with the new wireless applications.
</P>
<P>
   He said there was also the question of how hotels with a high
level of personal service would incorporate these technologies.
``The higher-end hotels often rely on the front desk interaction as
one of the most meaningful interactions with the guest,'' he said.
``And they don't want to lose that because it could dilute their
brand identity.''
</P>
<P>
   That is a real concern, said Tim Harvey, the chief information
officer for the Hilton Hotels Corp., based in Beverly Hills, Calif.
``We've tested things from check-in kiosks to curbside check-in to
check-in on airport buses, and I think there needs to be a
balance,'' he said. ``There are going to be customers for a long
time who are going to want to walk up to the front desk and talk to
a person. I think people are going to go toward a more expeditious
check-in, but it's a long way out.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
