<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    TRADE, DRUGS, BORDER LIKELY ON AGENDA FOR CLINTON MEETING WITH
MEXICAN PRESIDENT-ELECT FOX
 &HT;    Moving in both (i) International and (w) Washington categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DEANS 
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Each rose to national leadership by overturning the
political status quo after storming the gates as reform-minded
centrists ready to carry the next generation into a bold new era.
</P>
<P>
   When they meet at the White House on Thursday, President Clinton
and Mexico's president-elect, Vicente Fox, are sure to find fertile
common ground around those shared political roots.
</P>
<P>
   There's certain to be some talk on the contentious triad of
substantive issues _ drugs, trade and immigration _ at the core of
U.S.-Mexican relations.
</P>
<P>
   The hour-long Oval Office get acquainted session, though, is
more likely to focus on the challenges Fox, 58, will face when he
takes office Dec. 1 and tries to administer a corrupt and largely
calcified bureaucracy installed over seven decades of rule by his
political opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a daunting task,'' said a senior administration official,
speaking on condition of anonymity. ``One thing is to win an
election, and the other is to govern . . . He (Fox) probably wants
to hear the president's insights.''
</P>
<P>
   Like Clinton, Fox is a former state governor who strode onto the
national political stage by convincing voters that it was time for
change at the top.
</P>
<P>
   A one-time Coca-Cola Co. executive, Fox won a stunning upset in
elections July 2, ending 71 years of single-party rule in Mexico by
vanquishing the PRI, the Spanish acronym for the Institutional
Revolutionary Party, headed by current Mexican President Ernesto
Zedillo.
</P>
<P>
   Fox takes office just seven weeks before Clinton leaves, so the
two are expected to have little time for official business.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly eight years spent trying to manage U.S.-Mexican
relations from Washington, Clinton is certain to have advice to
offer Fox on how to avoid early missteps in dealing with the United
States, and perhaps even a suggestion or two on how best to
approach his own domestic political challenges.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to get to know him, and I want to reaffirm the support
of the United States, which I think is bipartisan, for good, strong
relationships with Mexico,'' Clinton told reporters on the South
Lawn on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been impressed with what I've seen and heard about him so
far,'' said Clinton, ``and I'm anxious to meet him and do what I
can to get our relationship off to a good start.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton also said he was interested in the vision Fox has for
closer U.S.-Mexican relations, even though analysts say there's
little near-term potential for the president-elect's goal of
establishing open borders between the United States and Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I want to hear what he has to say about it, and how we
would go about dealing with the problems that we have with the
trade arrangement we have now, whether they would be amplified,''
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like everything else, the devil is always in the details here,
so I want to talk to him about it and see what he has in mind,''
Clinton added. ``I would imagine most of this work would have to be
done by the next administration.''
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Fox told reporters in Mexico that he was looking
forward to meeting Clinton, ``Dos metros a dos metros.''
Translating literally into ``two meters to two meters,'' the phrase
is suggestive of two tall men getting together as powerful equals.
</P>
<P>
   Fox also meets Thursday with Vice President Al Gore, attends a
luncheon hosted by Secretary of State Madeleine Albright and holds
a press conference at the National Press Club. Thursday evening,
Fox is to be honored by the Center for Democracy, a non-profit
activist group in Washington, for his contribution to advancing the
role of elective government in Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Fox was to arrive here late Wednesday from Canada, where he met
earlier this week with Prime Minister Jean Chretien on Tuesday,
part of a four-day swing through Canada and the United States.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, Fox is to travel to Dallas, where he is scheduled to
meet with Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the Republican presidential
nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Fox wants to informally establish his credentials and lay the
groundwork for what he hopes will be a series of significant steps
forward in Mexico's relations with its giant neighbors to the
north.
</P>
<P>
   Fox has said he would like to see that relationship follow the
model of the European Union, with open borders and a single market
for trade and investment.
</P>
<P>
   It's an idea with little near-term potential, owing to the broad
social and economic gaps between Mexico _ a poor country where
per-capita income hasn't quite reached US$5,000 a year _ and its
wealthy neighbors north of the border.
</P>
<P>
   In some U.S. political quarters, in fact, the proposal is
regarded as preposterous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bad idea,'' said Mark Krikorian, executive director of
the Center for Immigration Studies, a conservative, largely
anti-immigration, Washington think tank.
</P>
<P>
   Relying chiefly on U.S. Census data, Krikorian's group estimates
that there are about 7.1 million people in this country who came
here from Mexico _ about 3 million of whom are here illegally.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about 54 percent of the total illegal alien population,''
said Krikorian.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 150,000 Mexicans migrate illegally to the United States
each year, drawn by the prospect of higher pay and better living
standards than they might find back home.
</P>
<P>
   Loosening immigration restrictions, analysts like Krikorian
fear, could open the floodgates.
</P>
<P>
   Others believe the 2,000-mile-long U.S.-Mexico border is already
too porous, owing to the burgeoning trade relationship between the
two countries.
</P>
<P>
   The economies of the United States, Mexico and Canada were
wedded in 1994 by the North American Free Trade Agreement, or
NAFTA, which reduced tariffs and other cross-border trade barriers
and encouraged investment among the three countries.
</P>
<P>
   This year, two-way trade between the United States and Mexico is
on track to top $240 billion. That's second only to U.S.-Canada
trade, headed toward a record-breaking $413 billion, and it's ahead
of U.S.-Japan trade, likely to top $206 billion this year,
according to the pace set in the first six months of the year.
</P>
<P>
   With increased trade, though, has come a surge in cross-border
transit, including trucks, automobiles, container vessels and other
vehicles. That has made it increasingly difficult for U.S.
