<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 17:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0193 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-ONLINE-SHOPPING-N     08-23 1001
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-ONLINE-SHOPPING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SITE INVITES SHOPPERS TO WAX ELOQUENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By MICHELLE SLATALLA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   I am looking for a piano lamp that has a long arm that you can
adjust to cast really strong light on sheet music. The lamp has to
be small enough to fit on a small shelf, and it should not tip over
and fall onto the floor constantly like the last one (which broke).
Also, it cannot be ugly. Is that too much to ask?
</P>
<P>
   For a long time, I thought the answer was yes. In search of
leads, I scoured all my usual haunts, including lighting stores and
antique stores, yard sales and thrift shops.
</P>
<P>
   I tried online search engines, too. But although you can quickly
hunt down certain kinds of products on the Internet _ books and
CDs, for example _ simply by entering a title in a query box, you
are less likely to succeed with more idiosyncratic requests. My
favorite search engine, Google, laughed at my request: ``Your
search, `small piano lamp that casts good light,' did not match any
documents.''
</P>
<P>
   Ask Jeeves responded to my question as if it were one of my
children trying to avoid telling me who left the car door open in
the rain. (``Umm, Mom, I don't know, but would you like to look at
this cool Web site that has information about the movie `The
Piano'?'')
</P>
<P>
   So after the old lamp broke, I just swept up the broken light
bulb and told my daughters to squint through ``Fur Elise'' until
further notice. Then one day last week I heard about a free
shopping service called Respond.com, where shoppers can type in the
most idiosyncratic, finicky words they can think of to describe the
specific product or service they want (www.respond.com).
</P>
<P>
   ``If you would have an easier time finding what you are looking
for if you could say it in your own words to a lot of people all at
once, then it could be helpful to use Respond,'' said Will Clemens,
Respond.com's chief executive.
</P>
<P>
   Respond.com acts as a liaison between shoppers and merchants. It
protects shoppers' anonymity while it forwards requests via e-mail
to more than 70,000 merchants selling items in more than 4,000
categories, like bicycle components and fresh mussels. Respond.com
is paid for leads by both big and small merchants, like Lands' End,
Annie's Costume and Magic, and ABT Electronics.
</P>
<P>
   Sellers reply by e-mail to Respond.com if they think they can
fulfill a request, and Respond.com forwards the responses to the
shopper. If a lead looks promising, the shopper can get in touch
with a seller to ask questions, negotiate or make a purchase.
</P>
<P>
   The service was simple and easy to use. At the top of the home
page was a query box that prompted me to finish the phrase ``I'm
looking for ...''
</P>
<P>
   For some reason, the suggestive ellipses made me think of the
Miss America personality test, in which contestants are asked to
reveal their deepest desires. Momentarily carried away, I tried to
type, ``I'm looking for world peace, or at least a scholarship and
free use of a convertible for the next year,'' but that turned out
to be too many characters for the search function to handle.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, ``I'm looking for a small piano lamp that casts good
light,'' fit just fine. After I clicked on ``Go!'' the site offered
me a choice of a couple of dozen categories to search, including
Antique Lamps and Lights, Desk Lamps and Wall Lamps. I chose the
Antique Lamps and Lights category, then typed a detailed
description of my dream lamp and set a one-week deadline for
replies.
</P>
<P>
   Just sending such a specific request made me feel so powerful
that I started to remember other hard-to-find items that have
eluded me. So I filed five more requests, for things like ``a hotel
in Miami with a big, free-form swimming pool that will entertain
children all day,'' ``a free-standing bamboo magazine rack to sit
next to an armchair,'' ``old cookbooks from the first half of the
20th century'' and ``biographical information about the author
Louise Dickinson Rich.''
</P>
<P>
   Within a day, I had received at least one response to each
request (after three days, the most I received was three, from
online travel agents who offered to help me book a trip to Miami).
Some responses to queries for books, for instance, came from
individual booksellers and turned out to be less comprehensive than
if I had simply used a specialized search engine like
Bookfinder.com to look for the same material.
</P>
<P>
   But responses to my quirkier requests offered good leads. Some
of the best, in fact, came from Respond.com's customer service
staff, which sends e-mail responses to queries in categories where
Respond.com has fewer merchant partners (to ensure that shoppers
get at least one response within 72 hours). The staff will hunt
through databases of previous requests and, if necessary, conduct a
Web search to find promising online retailers' sites. While I could
have done such a search myself, I was happy to sit back and let
them do the work.
</P>
<P>
   That's how I learned about Tuthilllighting.com, the
informational Internet site (www.Tuthilllighting.com) of a company
that sells piano lamps, including a model that clips onto a music
rack. On the company's Web site, I also happened to notice a
battery-operated, wall-mounted picture lamp, which had no messy
cord to dangle down behind a picture frame. That reminded me that I
had been looking for months for two of those, too. Although
Tuthilllighting.com doesn't sell products online, the Web site
referred me to a local retailer, N&AMP;S Dcor Fixture on Long Island,
N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   I phoned N&AMP;S to get prices, discuss bulb requirements and ask
what the finish ``statuary bronze'' could possibly look like. Over
the phone, the clerk told me that the piano lamp had a cord (messy,
now that I had seen the cordless picture lamp) and cost $240.
</P>
<P>
   To make the visit to Respond.com worth the effort, I ordered the
picture lamp. Downstairs, I heard someone stumbling over ``Ode to
Joy'' in bad light.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail address: Slatalla(at)nytimes.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
