<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INSTANT-LIKEABILITY-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YOU HAVE 90 SECONDS TO MAKE PEOPLE LIKE YOU. START SMILING
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By JESSIE MILLIGAN 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   I promised my editor I'd do this. I'd follow the tips in ``How
to Make People Like You in 90 Seconds or Less.''
</P>
<P>
   Author Nicholas Boothman's book, released in paperback last year
and picked up by Workman Publishing for hardcover distribution in
September, tells me to beam, say ``Hi!'' point my heart toward my
prospect and mimic his or her body language. Start conversations
with open-ended questions. Listen. Maintain eye contact.
</P>
<P>
   He wants me to put my personality in a microwave and zap it on
``Hi!''
</P>
<P>
   With this, I am to bond instantly. Boothman could have named
this $14.95 book ``Super Glue for the Soul.''
</P>
<P>
   It's depressing when I realize that within 90 minutes of reading
the first chapter of his book, I have made two people dislike me in
90 seconds or less. Both instances involved discussions of
politics. I resolve to try harder.
</P>
<P>
   The first rule from the book is that time is precious. In the
space of a few heartbeats, assumptions register, opinions are
formed. The human attention span, he says, is 30 seconds and no
longer if there is not stimulation. Don't believe it? He says stare
at an inanimate object for 30 seconds. Don't choose a great work of
art. Stare at something ordinary. I gaze at a glossy white pot of
cascading ivy. At the count of 10, my mind starts to wander. By
golly, he is right!
</P>
<P>
   I set out to prove I am more interesting than a pot of ivy.
</P>
<P>
   To attract people, Boothman says, we must be open with our body
language. Don't cross your arms. Don't button your jacket. Point
your heart toward the person and say ``Hi!'' Lean forward slightly.
If you don't shake the person's hand, then at least practice what
he calls the handless handshake. This involves all the posturing
and pleasantness of an actual handshake, only without actually
having to touch anyone.
</P>
<P>
   I need to meet someone new so I can practice. I give 50 cents to
a man asking for money on the street in downtown Fort Worth. I lean
forward, smile and say ``Hi!'' He looks frightened, suspicious,
confused.
</P>
<P>
   I need a new target.
</P>
<P>
   I try the technique on a co-worker. She looks frightened,
suspicious, confused.
</P>
<P>
   Then I get into the aforementioned discussions of politics. I
don't get instant bonding, I guess.
</P>
<P>
   I read the next chapter, the one about establishing rapport.
</P>
<P>
   This is more complex. First, you have to start with what the
author calls a ``Really Useful Attitude.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In face-to-face situations, your attitude precedes you. It is
the central force of your life _ it controls the quality and
appearance of everything you do,'' Boothman says.
</P>
<P>
   We are what we think. As Boothman says, ``I don't want my boss
yelling at me'' causes a person to reflect an entirely different
attitude than ``I want a promotion,'' or, I might add, ``I want a
promotion in 90 seconds.''
</P>
<P>
   Once we have our attitudes switched to ``positive,'' Boothman
wants us to copy the body language and tone of voice of the person
we hope to charm. Such similarity of gesture and style sets up an
unspoken bond. ``We are alike,'' it suggests. It creates a comfort
zone with which to start conversations.
</P>
<P>
   Boothman says people won't pick up on the fact we are copying
them, unless we do really obvious things such as stick our fingers
in our ears when they do.
</P>
<P>
   I fold my hands when my co-worker folds hers. I gesture when
another uses his hands to talk.
</P>
<P>
   Is this working? I see no sign that they are reacting, for
better or worse. Of course, they know me, so it may be too late to
establish rapport.
</P>
<P>
   Worse, I feel like an ape. Worse yet, I feel like an insincere
ape.
</P>
<P>
   I try listening to tone of voice. As Boothman says, if a person
says, ``That's brilliant'' in an indifferent tone of voice, it is
far removed in meaning from ``That's brilliant!'' I find imitating
tone of voice to be too phony, almost patronizing. So I don't try
this tip.
</P>
<P>
   I do try some of his conversation-starting tips. Boothman says
to begin by making a statement that reflects a common interest,
then ask an open-ended question, one that cannot be answered with a
``yes'' or ``no.''
</P>
<P>
   Aha! There is the classical music critic. He is wearing
turquoise and black, the very same colors I am wearing. I stand
next to him and point this similarity out. He and the office
manager smile in response. I then have one of those regrettable
Sally Field moments when I think: ``They like me! They really,
really like me!'' Then, to my horror, I completely fail to link the
Boothman tips. I am unable to come up with an open-ended question!
So I leave. Later, the theater critic tells me that the classical
music critic and I look as if we are on the same bowling team.
</P>
<P>
   I decide that ``How to Make People Like You'' has some practical
tips. Salesfolk probably could practice these ideas with good
results. I may be able to apply them with more grace, if I
practice. But I think, for my own purposes, I am better off
developing more gradual rapport.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
