<SLUG> BC-ATTRACTING-BUTTERFLIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOW TO DRAW BUTTERFLIES TO THE GARDEN
</HEADLINE>
 
 (Accompanies GROWING-BUTTERFLIES)  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By JESSIE MILLIGAN 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Monarch (Danaus plexippus) caterpillars like milkweed. The good
news for monarchs is that birds tend to find milkweed-laden
caterpillars distasteful. After tasting a monarch caterpillar, a
predator might associate the brightly colored, striped caterpillars
with an unpleasant meal and avoid them in the future, saving the
lives of monarchs everywhere. Organic gardening stores often sell
seeds for milkweed.
</P>
<P>
   Monarch butterflies sip milkweed nectar. When milkweed isn't in
season, monarchs drink flower nectar from dogbane, lilac, red
clover, lantana and thistles. In the fall, they visit goldenrods,
blazing stars (liatris), iron weed and tickseed flowers.
</P>
<P>
   A gulf fritillary caterpillar likes the passion vine, including
Passiflora incarnata and Passiflora foetida. The orange and black
butterfly it becomes likes nectar from lantana, shepherd's needle
and daisylike flowers.
</P>
<P>
   Mourning cloak caterpillars like willow trees, cottonwood and
hackberry. The adult black butterfly prefers tree sap, particularly
that of oaks.
</P>
<P>
   Black swallowtail caterpillars enjoy plants from the parsley
family, including Queen Anne's lace, carrot, celery, dill and
fennel. The adult black, yellow and orange butterfly drinks nectar
from flowers, including red clover, milkweed and thistles. Source:
Texas A&AMP;M and U.S. Geological Service Wildlife Research Center &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
