<HEADER>
A0198 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r l BC-GROWING-BUTTERFLIES-T     08-23 1173
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GROWING-BUTTERFLIES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUTTERFLY BREEDER WINGS IT IN UNUSUAL BUSINESS
</HEADLINE>
 
 (Accompanied by ATTRACTING-BUTTERFLIES)  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By JESSIE MILLIGAN 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the morning, when the shade dapples her yard and the
temperature is not yet searing, Leslie Lange of the Fluttering B
Butterfly Ranch in Colleyville releases her butterflies into an
outdoor tent for exercise.
</P>
<P>
   Orange and black wings flicker in the air around her head. They
brush against her cheek. The butterflies flit, impossibly graceful
and lovely.
</P>
<P>
   These butterflies don't look as if they could be in the middle
of a controversy, but they are.
</P>
<P>
   Lange's ``ranch'' in her suburban back yard is her new business,
one that provides monarchs or painted ladies or gulf fritillaries
for ceremonial releases at birthday parties, weddings or schools.
</P>
<P>
   Children love them. Newlyweds sigh. Pretty much everyone feels
good about these fluttering symbols of rebirth _ except
conservation groups that are bugged by the increasingly popular
fad.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, this is treating butterflies as confetti,'' said Nancy
Greig, director of the Cockrell Butterfly Center at the Museum of
Natural Science in Houston. ``This is butterflies as baubles.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the ethical argument against releasing commercially
raised, mail-order butterflies into the wild. There's a biological
argument as well. Commercial, mail-order butterflies can be
released into inappropriate climates or environments, where they
can die too quickly, introduce disease or compete for food with
native populations that already face vanishing habitats, says the
National Wildlife Federation, the American Museum of Natural
History and the Washington State Department of Wildlife. Those
groups also are concerned that commercially raised butterflies will
be too confused to migrate properly. They may have romantic
liaisons with their wild counterparts, causing unforeseen ripples
in the genetic pool. Or they may be injured in shipping, the groups
say.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, back at the butterfly ranch, Lange is saying
``Whoa!''
</P>
<P>
   Armed with a bachelor of science degree in biology from Texas
Woman's University in Denton and an affiliation with the
International Butterfly Breeders Association, Lange, 36, says she
overcomes conservationists' concerns by using thorough research,
careful breeding techniques, cautious shipping and detailed
instructions on when and how to release butterflies.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, she says, she's very, very careful.
</P>
<P>
   Texas has no policy on butterfly releases, says John Jackman at
the Texas Agricultural Extension Service.
</P>
<P>
   ``We aren't very concerned about the release of native species.
It could cause some genetic shifting, but I think the number of
butterflies released is small enough that it wouldn't create a
problem,'' Jackman said.
</P>
<P>
   Lange raises and releases butterflies that are native to Texas.
When she ships butterflies out of state, she says, she sends only
butterflies that have been approved by the U.S. Agriculture
Department for release in that state.
</P>
<P>
   Lange collects eggs from the butterfly garden in her back yard.
She washes the eggs in a solution of 90 percent water and 10
percent bleach to kill bacteria. She also buys butterfly eggs from
other breeders, of which about a dozen operate in Texas. Lange
mates the stock she purchases with the stock that found its way to
her yard. That way, she says, no inbreeding problems will emerge
from her ranch.
</P>
<P>
   A spare bedroom in her home has been converted into a butterfly
rearing barn with full-spectrum grow lights mounted on posts. In
the ``barn,'' Lange stores the eggs of native Texas butterflies in
white plastic containers covered with paper towels. The eggs hatch
and turn into caterpillars, which she feeds milkweed and parsley
from her yard. They form cocoons, then emerge as butterflies. The
egg-to-butterfly progression takes three or four weeks.
</P>
<P>
   For the first 24 hours after their hatching, Lange lets the
butterflies stay in the spare-bedroom-turned-barn in a homemade
cage her husband built from plastic pipes and white netting. Once
their wings harden, she places them in a cage and takes them
outside for daily exercise. At night, she brings them indoors to
avoid predators, including mockingbirds, wasps and bacteria.
</P>
<P>
   In a family room converted into the Fluttering B Butterfly Ranch
headquarters, Lange stores permits from the U.S. Agriculture
Department that allow her to ship her butterflies to 27 states.
Each state has separate laws governing which types of butterflies
it will allow. No Texas-raised monarchs can be sent west of the
Rocky Mountains because Eastern U.S. monarchs can carry a parasite
that has yet to invade their Western relations.
</P>
<P>
   Lange is fastidious about her monarchs. She raises milkweed,
picks it and washes it in a bleach solution before giving it to the
orange and black beauties. As she readies monarchs for shipping,
she swabs each butterfly's tummy and checks the swab under a
microscope to make sure she isn't releasing any monarchs with
parasites.
</P>
<P>
   Her other butterflies _ mourning cloaks, the gulf fritillary,
black swallowtails _ aren't as sensitive to parasites, she says.
</P>
<P>
   Then comes the packing. Each butterfly is slipped inside a box
about 3-by-3- inches square and a quarter-inch thick. Those boxes
are placed inside a larger box lined with foam and filled with foam
pellets. An ice pack is slipped inside the box so that the
butterflies don't overheat. Instructions are included. She advises
clients to store the box in a cool, dark room until the big day.
She tells the buyers to plan their release for daylight, because
butterflies, unlike moths, do not fly at night. She ships April
through October and advises clients not to release butterflies on a
cold or rainy day. And then she ships the box via the U.S. Postal
Service or Airborne Express.
</P>
<P>
   Lange says she's shipped hundreds of butterflies since she
started in February, and she says she's never heard from a client
that a butterfly had died during shipment.
</P>
<P>
   She doesn't believe that the migrating monarchs become so upset
they can't find their way to overwintering grounds. She's heard of
monarchs that were tagged in the United States being found in
Mexico, so they must make it, she says.
</P>
<P>
   Lange says she believes the release of commercially bred
butterflies ultimately has a good effect on the environment. She
sends information on habitat to clients, advising them on which
types of plants draw the pretty insects to a garden. Recently,
while preparing a shipment of 27 butterflies for a little girl's
birthday party in Illinois, Lange included 27 packets of seeds, so
the kids could go home and grow butterfly gardens. She often
includes the seeds, and she realizes that she and other breeders
just don't see eye to eye with the folks who would prefer that she
release just the seeds.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
