<SLUG> BC-WINE-BRATPACK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRAT PACK HOSTS SWEET PARTY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DAVID BLOOM 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The business of wine, and the drinking of same, have long been
regarded as stodgy, stuffy and traditional. That's certainly what
the scions of several Sonoma County winemaking clans heard when
they went off to college and were ridiculed by classmates for their
far-from-plebian tastes.
</P>
<P>
   When they returned to the family businesses _ at wineries like
Bundschu, San Giacomo and Sebastiani _ they started agitating for
different approaches to selling wine, and to loosening up that
oh-so-uptight image. The result was a nickname, and then a group,
now national, called the Wine Brats.
</P>
<P>
   And tonight, the Brats will be putting on their annual L.A.
WineRave, to raise money for Sweet Relief, the charity that
benefits ailing musicians.
</P>
<P>
   The event at the sort-of-open Knitting Factory Hollywood
nightclub will feature wines from 24 vineyards, food from five
restaurants (including the Knitting Factory), a short experimental
film by Matthew Konicek of Chicago, fashion and art by designer
Nicole Moss in collaboration with painter William Quigley, and
dance music by DJ Freedom Fighter.
</P>
<P>
   There'll be a silent auction to benefit Sweet Relief, a
give-away trip to the Australian wine country and souvenir stemware
to commemorate all that good wine.
</P>
<P>
   Tickets were about gone, though a few will be available at the
door for $50 each, said Wine Brats executive director Joel Quigley.
Even if you can't make the event, a newly energized Los Angeles
chapter of the group is planning to hold monthly events. Best of
all, membership in the group is free. For more information, go to
www.winebrats.org.
</P>
<P>
   The event runs from 7 to 11 p.m. at the Knitting Factory, 7021
Hollywood Blvd., tucked behind the Hollywood Entertainment Museum
at the corner of Sycamore in the heart of Hollywood. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
