<HEADLINE>
VOTERS FACE MAJOR DISTRACTIONS AS CAMPAIGN SEASON HEATS UP 
</HEADLINE>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: This article from NEWHOUSE NEWS SERVICE for
WEDNESDAY, Aug. 23, is available as a ``separate-buy.'' For
information about purchasing the article, contact DEBRA WEYDERT of
The New York Times Syndicate at 1-212-499-3401; fax, 732-390-4697;
e-mail: weyded(at)nytimes.com.) 
 By MILES BENSON  
 c.2000 Newhouse News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON -- Al Gore and George W. Bush would love to have the
voters' undivided attention. They are not going to get it.
</P>
<P>
   The presidential race is about to be overtaken by a big wave of
diversions and distractions, forcing Gore and Bush to compete with
the Summer Olympics; the U.S. Open tennis matches; the start of
football, basketball and hockey seasons; major league baseball
playoffs and a World Series stretching into late October.
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates want people to believe this election really
matters. But pollsters report a deep and continuing attention
deficit among voters that is likely to get worse before it gets
better as America's romance with the excitement of televised
sporting events intrudes on a comparatively dull election.
</P>
<P>
   The tennis championships begin Aug. 28. Pro football season
opens Sept. 3. The Olympics in Sydney, Australia, will devour two
weeks of prime campaign time -- Sept. 15 to Oct. 1. Baseball
playoffs begin Oct. 3, pro hockey starts Oct. 4, the World Series
will open Oct. 21 and could run through Oct. 28, and professional
basketball play commences Oct. 31.
</P>
<P>
   Election Day is Nov. 7.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves precious little time for the candidates to hold
their debates, maintain momentum and energize a disinterested
electorate that as yet exhibits no sense of urgency about its vital
responsibility for choosing the new leader of the free world.
</P>
<P>
   Just before the national political conventions, The Pew Research
Center for the People and the Press, which has been tracking the
high level of voter apathy all year, predicted that voter turnout
would slip lower than the disappointing 49 percent level of 1996.
Pew pollsters found that 44 percent of respondents did not follow
election news closely or at all, and 30 percent believe it does not
make much difference who is elected.
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen Media Research, which measures viewership among the
three major television broadcast networks, said the combined
audience dropped for both major conventions -- an estimated 11
percent below 1996 for the Democrats and 4 percent below 1996 for
the GOP. The CBS show ``Survivor'' drew an audience well in excess
of aggregate ratings for Gore's speech on all competing networks
combined.
</P>
<P>
   Naturally, the challenge looms even larger for whichever
candidate is behind on Labor Day, Sept. 4, since it will be very
difficult to catch up while the focus of many voters is directed
elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are always distractions, and these are bigger than most,
but you can't do anything about it,'' said Ari Fleischer, campaign
spokesman for Bush, the Republican nominee. ``You can't pause,
can't stop, you just run just as hard as you always do.''
</P>
<P>
   Democratic strategists claim to be unconcerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``People have more than one attention span,'' insisted former
Democratic National Chairman Roy Roemer. ``They know this is an
important election. Nobody I know gets so absorbed in baseball or
the Olympics that they tune out what's happened to their schools,
what happens on their city council, or what's happening in the
political race.''
</P>
<P>
   William Daley, Gore's campaign chairman, brushed aside questions
about how Gore will cope. ``There are no distractions,'' Daley
insisted. ``This happens every four years.''
</P>
<P>
   Not exactly. The Olympic games usually are held much earlier in
the summer. The last time they came in the midst of a fall
presidential campaign was in l988, when Republican George Bush,
father of this year's GOP candidate, beat Democrat Michael Dukakis.
</P>
<P>
   And while there is nothing new about the football, basketball,
hockey and baseball schedules, those attractions inevitably shift
media and public attention away from arguments over the intricacies
of campaign finance reform, tax policy, budget priorities, school
vouchers and privatization schemes for Social Security, political
experts believe.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a problem we've been talking privately about all year,''
said Sen. Charles Robb, D-Va. ``It really interrupts the dynamic of
the campaign. The candidates struggle for notice and, of course,
that makes the debates even more important.''
</P>
<P>
   Almost certainly, Gore and Bush -- as well as Green Party
nominee Ralph Nader and Pat Buchanan, standard bearer of one fork
of the Reform Party -- will be, at least temporarily, eclipsed by
the likes of Marion Jones, Jenny Thompson, Michael Johnson and
Lance Armstrong, all strong U.S. gold medal contenders in running,
swimming and cycling events at the Olympics. Not to mention the
entire U.S. women's soccer team.
</P>
</TEXT>
