<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENO-GORE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     RENO DEFENDS DECISION AGAINST APPOINTING GORE COUNSEL 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By ERIC ROSENBERG  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno on Wednesday strongly
defended her decision against appointing a special counsel to
investigate Vice President Al Gore's fund-raising efforts four
years ago, removing a potentially troublesome obstacle in Gore's
quest for the White House.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because further investigation is not likely to result in a
prosecutable case I have concluded that a special counsel is not
warranted,'' Reno said at a news conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``This goes to the heart of everything we care about in this
country _ that you don't pursue a case where there is no basis for
concluding that you can make a case,'' Reno added.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign welcomed the decision. If Reno had appointed
an outside counsel, the vice president could have been dogged by
investigators while campaigning for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Gore is running in a close race against Texas Gov. George W.
Bush, the Republican presidential nominee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are pleased with today's Justice Department announcement,''
Gore spokesman Chris Lehane said. ``But our focus is going to
remain where it has always been _ which is on using our prosperity
to help America's families.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno's decision marked the third time she has rejected an
independent investigation of the vice president. In this instance,
Reno shot down the recommendation of Robert Conrad, head of a
Justice Department campaign task force.
</P>
<P>
   Conrad wanted Reno to appoint an outside counsel to determine
whether Gore lied during an April interview with investigators
about a fund-raising event at a Buddhist temple in California and
fund-raising ``coffees'' held at the White House. The events were
part of efforts to raise money for the Clinton-Gore re-election
campaign in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Asserting that she personally reviewed the transcript of the
Gore interview, Reno said the vice president's comments are
``neither false statements nor perjury.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I've concluded that there is no reasonable possibility that
further investigation could develop evidence that would support the
filing of charges for making a willful false statement,'' she
added.
</P>
<P>
   While Reno praised Conrad as ``an excellent prosecutor,'' she
said her decision amounted to a ``disagreement among lawyers.''
Conrad was not alone in recommending an outside counsel. Reno said
at least two other advisers agreed with him.
</P>
<P>
   Reno said she ``struggled'' with the decision, which she
finalized over the weekend, and conceded that Republicans might
renew attacks on her for protecting the vice president, the
Democratic candidate for president.
</P>
<P>
   But Reno countered that the action was based on legal
considerations, not politics. ``I don't do things based on
politics. I realize that politics will be hurled around my head. I
just sit there and duck as it comes,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Reno's decision is a relief to the Gore campaign,
Republicans are not likely to let the vice president off the hook
as the presidential campaign tightens.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, in a statement, reiterated Republican contentions that
Gore ``engaged in a number of questionable fund-raising activities
and gave the FBI statements that continue to raise the issue of his
credibility.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush added that ``the American people are sick and tired of all
these scandals and investigations. The best way to put all these
scandals and investigations behind us is to elect someone new.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Eric Rosenberg can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address eric &LR; hearstdc.com).
</P>
</TEXT>
