<SLUG> BC-WESLEY-SNIPES-STARBEAT-ART-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE 'CAT FROM THE BRONX' IS A CLASSICAL ACTOR AT HEART
</HEADLINE>
  (Includes a color photo of Wesley Snipes in ``The Art of War.'') 
 ATTENTION EDITORS: This article is for use by clients of The New
York Times Syndicate's STARBEAT feature service. For more
information about purchasing this article as a ``separate-buy'' _
or becoming a client of STARBEAT _ contact one of the New York
Times Syndicate sales representatives listed at the end of the
text.) 
 By JEANNE WOLF 
 c.2000 Jeanne Wolf 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features.) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With chiseled features and a well-honed body _ which he's
displayed in more than a few films _ Wesley Snipes says he didn't
know he was a sex symbol until he got into movies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had women come up to me and say, 'When are you going to
do something in which you take off your clothes again?' he says
with an ingenuous smile.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jean-Claude (Van Damme) and all of them might want to do that
kind of stuff ... But I'm not that anxious to put my booty on the
screen anymore,'' he declares.
</P>
<P>
   In his current appearance in the action-thriller, ``The Art of
War,'' from his Amen Ra Films production company, Snipes doesn't
undress or even have a love scene with the heroine played by
Asian-American actress Marie Matiko.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guy I play has no time to get it on with a woman,'' he
points out. ``It's like, 'Yo, the man is on the run.' He's too busy
saving himself to end up in the sack at some hotel! That would be
stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Snipes, who plays a covert agent for the United Nations, goes
underground after he's falsely accused of murdering the Chinese
ambassador. As the plot thickens with international intrigue, he's
placed in constant jeopardy _ and in the middle of some
death-defying action scenes.
</P>
<P>
   Stunt coordinator Michael Scherer says Snipes enthusiastically
participated in everything from martial arts combat to jumping from
buildings. ``Sometimes he scared the bejesus out of me because he'd
get right in there,'' Scherer confesses.
</P>
<P>
   Snipes allows that he was often in a little peril. ``But that's
OK, I don't mind it,'' he says. ``I've been working with most of my
stunt men for 10 years and they know how far I'll go. We know each
other's styles and rhythms.''
</P>
<P>
   But on this movie he was a producer. So, when he wanted to take
too big a chance on a stunt, they'd remind him that if he got hurt
the whole production would be shut down. ``And I'd end up having to
pay everybody to sit around!'' he laughs.
</P>
<P>
   ``That got my attention!''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, when Snipes first signed on to ``The Art of War,''
originally developed for Asian action star Jet-Li, he made sure
that he'd be doing some of his favorite things: martial arts and
motorcycles.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I also wanted to beef up 'The Art of War,' which is the
title of an ancient handbook written by a very powerful Asian
general, Sun Tsu,'' he explains.
</P>
<P>
   ``The principles he lays down to win a war still apply today _
and my character embraces them,'' he continues. ``Then, you add the
action and, oh man, it's icing on the cake!''
</P>
<P>
   Snipes doesn't deny that being an action hero, and scoring with
audiences, in such thrillers as ``Passenger 57,'' ``Drop Zone'' and
the hugely successful ``Blade,'' has given him the clout he wants
in Hollywood.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't get into the business to do action,'' he reveals.
``I'm a classically trained actor, and I love the more dramatic
stuff whether it's on Broadway or in film.
</P>
<P>
   ``But doing films like 'The Art of War' has afforded me the
opportunity to do other projects that have more heart and
sensitivity. So I'm not knocking it!''
</P>
<P>
   Describing action scenes, he said he doesn't like ``straight up
formula stuff. I do fights that are right to the core, right to the
money.
</P>
<P>
   ``For instance, nobody thinks about hitting a guy in the side of
the thigh. But it works. Pow! You hit him there and he's going to
stop what he's doing for at least a minute.''
</P>
<P>
   Snipes, who has studied martial arts as well as capoeira
(Brazilian dance-fighting), draws on his own street sense to keep
his screen fights authentic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up in the Bronx,'' he says. ``The Bronx teaches you to
survive. It's like, 'Bring it on!'''
</P>
<P>
   And he added: ``If you took me on, it wouldn't be easy. That's
part of my image. People don't mess with me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Snipes was less a fighter than a performer when he
was in his teens. He enrolled in Manhattan's High School for the
Performing Arts where he flirted with the idea of becoming a dancer
or singer. Instead he decided on acting because it came easy to
him.
</P>
<P>
   When his mother abruptly moved the family to Orlando, Fla.,
Snipes completed high school while teaming up with friends to form
``Struttin' Street Stuff,'' a traveling puppet troupe that
performed in parks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did everything. We created the puppets, we painted them, we
wrote the scripts,'' he remembers. ``I was just a whippersnapper
but I learned a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Snipes readily concedes he also learned a lot from the
performance that opened the doors to his career _ an appearance in
Michael Jackson's ``Bad'' video. ``I was amazed by Michael's level
of concentration,'' he recalls. ``I thought if I could achieve
that, then people might react to me like they were reacting to
Michael.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the tabloid headlines that dogged his rise to fame _
including his celebrated arrest in Florida after a high-speed chase
on his motorcycle, Snipes admits, ``No one can train you to be
famous.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you deal with the loss of anonymity, the loss of
privacy? You have to be disciplined. You go back to what works.''
</P>
<P>
   Snipes readily admits the biggest influence on his life and
career was his mother.
</P>
<P>
   ``My mom told me something very simple _ 'Whatever you do, try
to be the best at it,''' he reveals.
</P>
<P>
   ``She made me study and read _ read, read, read. I remember
having a library card when I was about seven. It was mandatory that
I go to the library. My mom helped lay a foundation for me that I'm
now reaping with my success.
</P>
<P>
   ``And she gets the benefit, too. I get to send her around the
world. It's like, 'You want to travel, Mom? Go ahead. Wherever you
want.' It's a great feeling being able to do that.''
</P>
<P>
   Snipes shared the thrill of his star on the Hollywood Walk of
Fame with his mom. ``I thought someone was joking,'' he says.
``Nobody's nominated me for an Academy Award or even a People's
Choice. I didn't really think I was in the running. But it was a
hell of a thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Not too many cats from the Bronx have that kind of
experience!'' he chuckles.
</P>
<P>
   When he's not on location Snipes is usually at home in Malibu.
He shares custody of his son Jelani, 11, with his ex-wife, April,
from whom he was divorced in 1990. ``It's tough to be a good
father, and I'm definitely not cut out to be a stay-at-home dad,''
he says candidly, ``But Jelani and I have some nice times together,
and he would probably like to have me around a little more.''
</P>
<P>
   Snipes pauses to consider how he'd define what's behind his
screen image. ``If I end my career tomorrow,'' he says finally, ``I
don't want people saying, 'Oh, he's just an action guy, a sex
symbol ...
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be thought of as an actor.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jeanne Wolf is a Los Angeles-based free-lance writer.) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &UR; EDITOR: For further information on Wesley Snipes in ``The Art of
War,'' consult the official web site at www.artofwarmovie.com. And
check out The New York Times Syndicate Web site at
http://www.nytimes.com/syndicate for information on StarBeat and
other features. &QL;
</P>
