<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 17:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0218 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-BOULEZ-SALZBURG-MUSIC     08-23 1168
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOULEZ-SALZBURG-MUSIC-$ADV27-1,120(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN SALZBURG, A BENEVOLENT ELDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Aug. 27)  
 By ANTHONY TOMMASINI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SALZBURG, Austria _ Pierre Boulez' ``Structures,'' Book 2, for
two pianos is music of uncompromising complexity. In this landmark
exploration of rigorous serial techniques, composed over several
years beginning in 1956, the pianos go at each other nonstop,
exchanging volatile volleys of notes with a ferocity that seems
almost free-form. At the time of its premiere, in 1961, the work
galvanized composers in the avant-garde and in academic circles.
Few people could have thought that it would ever reach outside to
mainstream audiences. Certainly not audiences at the Salzburg
Festival, then the most tradition-bound of all the prestigious
international music festivals.
</P>
<P>
   So it must have been deeply satisfying for Boulez _ or
perplexing, or amusing, or who knows what? _ when, at the
conclusion of the third of four recent concerts at the Salzburg
Festival in honor of his 75th birthday, an audience that nearly
filled the 1,500-seat Felsenreitschule burst into cheers after a
brilliant performance of that very work, the gnarly ``Structures,''
Book 2. The superb pianists were Pierre-Laurent Aimard and Florent
Boffard. Joining them on stage for the ovation, Boulez was called
back four times.
</P>
<P>
   Among the listeners were many younger people, the kind of music
lovers who would never have been at the Salzburg Festival 10 years
ago. But also in the audience were patrons dressed in evening
finery, the type of veteran festivalgoers who are more typically
seen next door in the best seats (about $320 each) at the Grosses
Festspielhaus for performances of Mozart and Strauss operas.
</P>
<P>
   All of the Boulez 2000 concerts, including two programs that
Boulez conducted with the London Symphony Orchestra, were well
attended and enthusiastically received. Once a cocksure
revolutionary, Boulez has become the benevolent elder of the
Salzburg Festival. On a particularly humid morning, one saw an
amazing thing: Latecomers, flushed and perspiring, scurrying into
the Festspielhaus, hoping that good seats were still available for
a free talk by Boulez.
</P>
<P>
   What's going on? Naturally, Boulez deserves most of the credit
for his own success. Perhaps he knew all along that there could be
a potential audience for work like his, even among concertgoers
reared on mainstream repertory.
</P>
<P>
   But Boulez's ascendancy at the Salzburg Festival is also due to
the efforts of Gerard Mortier, its artistic director since 1992.
When he arrived, Mortier vowed to shake the place up, to present
the opera repertory in boldly rethought productions, but most of
all to make the festival, finally, a hospitable place for living
composers as well as musicians from cultures far outside the
Austro-German heritage. One of his first acts was to appoint Boulez
composer in residence in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Mortier has also relied on Hans Landesmann, the unsung hero of
the Mortier era. Landesmann is officially the intendant, or
executive director, of the festival. But since he has a musical
background, he has also served as the de facto artistic director of
concerts there. Under his leadership, the festival has complemented
Boulez's work by introducing other new-music offerings, like the
Composer Portraits programs, and the Next Generation series,
financed by the Los Angeles arts patron Betty Freeman.
</P>
<P>
   There was new music at Salzburg before Mortier's era, but not
much, and that, Landesmann explained recently, was kept to the
side, done out of obligation rather than enthusiasm. The climate
has changed for good.
</P>
<P>
   The most anticipated event last summer was the premiere of
Luciano Berio's opera ``Cronaca del Luogo.'' Similarly, the most
important event of this summer was the premiere on Aug. 15 of Kaija
Saariaho's opera ``L'Amour de Loin,'' to a libretto by Amin
Maalouf, commissioned jointly by Salzburg, the Theatre du Chatelet
in Paris and the Santa Fe Opera. And prodding Mortier along in his
commitment to new opera has been Boulez, who praised Mortier's
sense of mission during his recent talk. As of now, a new opera
commissioned by the festival will be a highlight of every season:
Works by Matthias Pintscher, Wolfgang Rihm, Hans Werner Henze and
Olga Neuwirth.
</P>
<P>
   At least that is the plan. Mortier is leaving after the season
next summer amid much contention. From the start, he faced
resistance among the festival's entrenched supporters, both public
and private, who had been content to see the event showcase lavish,
regally cast productions of operas by Mozart and Strauss, and
elegant concerts of traditional symphonic repertory performed with
silken excellence by the Vienna Philharmonic.
</P>
<P>
   But last year, as is well known, the backlash became more
pointed when the national elections gave the right-wing Freedom
Party the clout to claim a role in Austria's governing coalition.
Some talk from party leaders suggested that its members were a
little less than condemning of Nazi politics. And now, along with
alarming anti-immigrant cant from the government coalition have
come troubling cuts in social services.
</P>
<P>
   Mortier and his staff were appalled by the turn of events. They
also faced a dilemma. The Salzburg Festival has relied on
government funds, though much less than is generally thought. The
combined allocations from four public sources _ the Austrian
republic, the Salzburg tourist bureau, the city fund and the county
fund _ account for only 28 percent of the festival's budget (which
this year amounts to roughly $42 million). Over 50 percent comes
from ticket sales, a worrisomely high figure.
</P>
<P>
   Mortier's artistically exciting programs have proved costly and
run up deficits. But the government's pleas to rein in costs have
come amid political rhetoric about elitist contemporary music and
injunctions to maintain the country's artistic nationality. ``We
are told by some that the festival should be more Austrian,
whatever that means,'' Mortier said disdainfully, while introducing
the creators of ``L'Amour de Loin'' at a panel.
</P>
<P>
   Mortier's first response to the new government's challenge was
to announce his resignation as of this year. Among those who
persuaded him to change his mind was Boulez, who urged him to use
the post to make a point. So Mortier will turn the festival next
summer, his last, into a veritable celebration of multiculturalism,
then cede his post to Peter Ruzicka, a German composer and
conductor, and also an admiring colleague of Boulez, who
increasingly seems a power behind the scene.
</P>
<P>
   If Ruzicka continues to give Boulez a central role in the
Salzburg Festival, he should enjoy public support. Elsewhere
Boulez's very name may rattle classical-music audiences, but here
listeners seemed genuinely intrigued by his challenging music and
disarmed by his charming intelligence.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   On one level, the performances themselves assured a strong
response. In 1976, Aimard, then just 19, began an 18-year
association with Boulez's cutting-edge Ensemble Intercontemporain.
He is an extraordinary technician and a compelling musician. His
solo recital at the Mozarteum, the first of the Boulez 2000
concerts, was astonishing. He gave impressive accounts of works by
Messiaen, Bartok and George Benjamin. But especially in two early
works by Boulez, ``Notations'' and the First Piano Sonata, Aimard
brought lucid clarity, impetuosity, tenderness and great dabs of
color to fiendishly difficult piano music. As an encore he played a
work even many pianists consider formidable listening, Webern's
Variations (Op. 27), in a sensitive, involving and beguilingly
fanciful performance.
</P>
<P>
   In the third Boulez 2000 concert, at the Felsenreitschule the
next day, Aimard made Berg's harmonically wayward Sonata (Op. 1)
seem positively Brahmsian, gave a gripping account of Schoenberg's
breakthrough Five Piano Pieces (Op. 23) and, with the excellent
flutist Sophie Cherrier, offered a continually imaginative
performance of Boulez's early Flute Sonata.
</P>
<P>
   Then Aimard's younger colleague, Boffard, a member of the
Ensemble Intercontemporain since 1988, joined him in
``Structures,'' Book 2. Music gets no more formidable than this.
But no matter how many musical events tumbled on one another _
darting contrapuntal lines, splatterings of notes, undulating
shimmers, hellbent outbursts of chords that climaxed with clusters
played with the flats of the hands and forearms _ the music sped by
with uncanny clarity. This work may be tough to comprehend, but as
played here, it made you giddy with amazement.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the impact of Boulez's music was in part a reaction to
the soupy neo-Romanticism that has become so fashionable in the
last 20 years. However momentarily placating, some of those
sumptuously scored neo-Romantic works just don't stay with you. But
Boulez's music is something genuine and ingenious. Everyone must at
least concede that.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, listeners may be more willing to take a chance on
Boulez's music because over the years he has earned their gratitude
as a conductor. His conducting was always technically deft and
intellectually solid. In his mature years he has allowed his
music-making, and his own works, to become more elegant, pliant and
playful.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the pieces he performed here with the London Symphony he
had already presented with the orchestra at Carnegie Hall last
season, including Mahler's Sixth Symphony, given a somewhat fussy
account. Peter Eotvos' ``zeroPoints'' and Neuwirth's
``Clinamen/Nodus,'' works commissioned for these birthday tours,
are stronger for their explorations of tremulous colors and sounds
than for their motivic cogency and rhythmic sway. Emanuel Ax made
Schoenberg's 12-tone Piano Concerto seem the most lyrical music
ever written. Boulez's performance of Stravinsky's ``Petrouchka''
was a revelation; I heard intricate inner voices and layered
happenings in this familiar music that I had never known were
there.
</P>
<P>
   It's easy for outsiders to say that Austria must come to terms
with its fears of immigration and cultural change. Boulez is an
outsider himself. And in helping Mortier open the festival to new
music and bracing works by living composers, he has made it a more
stimulating place to hear the ``Jupiter'' Symphony and ``Don
Giovanni.'' Their opponents should remember that in his own day
Mozart was a challenging composer of contemporary music. It's safe
to say what side he would be on in Salzburg today.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-00 1757EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
