<P>
   RUSSIA-SUB _ MURMANSK, Russia _ Russian President Vladimir Putin
has called for a national day of mourning Wednesday, but will not
be here with relatives for a church service to remember the 118
crewmembers of the sunken submarine, Kursk. Putin, who left town
after visiting for only six hours early Wednesday, has been sharply
criticized for taking so long to show concern for the crew.
Developing. (Coker, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Location, Atlanta; Category, International; Subcategory,
Other.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Expected to move by 3 p.m. EDT on the NYT wire.
</P>
<P>
   US-MEXICO _ WASHINGTON _ Mexican President-elect Vicente Fox is
scheduled to meet with President Clinton and Vice President Al Gore
Thursday. It will be the first time that a U.S. president has met
with any Mexican president that is a not a member of the former
ruling party, the PRI. Fox, who is popular among Mexican immigrants
in the United States, has made issues such as immigration and
foreign investment key issues in his presidency. What does the U.S.
want, or expect from this maverick? (Deans, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   WAN: Location, Atlanta; Category, International; Subcategory,
Other.
</P>
<P>
   EDs: Expected to move by 4 p.m. (EDT) on the NYT wire.
</P>
<P>
   BRITAIN-GTECH _ LONDON _ Camelot, the company that has done the
lottery in Britain was not awarded a new contract because of
concerns over its ties to G-tech. The government is expected to
give the contract to a company owned by Virgin empire owner Richard
Branson. (Roughton, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   WILDFIRES-GAVOLUNTEERS _ MISSOULA, Mont. _ When the call came,
the retired U.S. Forest Service couple from Acworth, Ga., were
sunning themselves on Tybee Island on the Georgia coast. They have
spent the month of August in a tent when not helping thousands of
other fire fighters battle the raging wildfires in Montana. They
join other Georgians on the scene, like Bobby Kitchens. The
Chatsworth, Ga., resident is a biologist for the U.S. Forest
Service usually. But trained as they all are to fight fires, he was
pulled from his day job to join the front line. (Seabrook, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution).
</P>
<P>
   WILDFIRES-ANIMALS _ Wildfires gobbling up land out west this
summer are leaving many farm animals and family pets in danger.
With the memory of animal rescues during Hurricane Floyd still
fresh in their minds, two Greenville, N.C., residents packed their
bags this week for Montana to lend a hand. (Greenville Daily
Reflector). 25. WITH PHOTOS. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WILDFIRES-NCFAMILIES _ Some Pitt County, N.C., residents are
keeping a closer eye on wildfires out west than most. That's
because their family members are battling the blazes. (Greenville
Daily Reflector). 24. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WILDFIRES-NCVOLUNTEER _ Pitt County, N.C., resident Tom Harris
doesn't need to read a newspaper account of the fires tearing
through the western United States. He's standing right in front of
them. (Greenville Daily Reflector). 14. MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   CANE-MAIN _ Debby's track: heading straight at West Palm Beach,
Fla., or taking a miracle turn? In response, what are people doing
here: Has state put its evacuation plan into effect? How is plan
different from last year? What are airlines and PBIA doing.
(O'Meilia, Palm Beach Post).
</P>
<P>
   FIRESTONE _ The Firestone tire models voluntarily recalled Aug.
9 are also failing on sport utility vehicles other than the Ford
Explorer, but when an Explorer loses its tire tread it is six times
as likely to roll over and kill someone, federal accident data
shows. An analysis of the of 642 Firestone and Explorer-related
accident reports that the National Highway Transportation Safety
Administration has collected since early this year shows that the
rate at which tire treads are coming apart are comparable whether
the Firestone tires are on Ford's popular Explorer or on other
sport utility vehicles. However, the analysis indicates that what
happens after the tread peals away is strikingly different. The
results of the analysis, which was performed by the American
Statesman, appeared to support the allegations of lawyers and
safety advocates who have claimed that the Explorer has played a
role in the catastrophic tire failures being reported nationwide.
(Carmody, Austin American-Statesman). 45. WITH CHARTS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
</P>
<P>
   FIRESTONE-SIDE _ The Blossie family of Austin lost their
11-year-old daughter in an Explorer/Firestone accident last month
in Arizona. The accident fits a pattern emerging nationwide. We
talk to that family and other Explorer owners. (Carmody, Austin
American-Statesman). 18-20. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   RESTSTOPS _ Georgia's interstate rest stops have helped boost
the state's image to travelers. Some are so clean that mothers have
said they let their babies crawl on the floor while they coif in
the mirrors. South Carolina, by contrast, is facing a rest-stop
crisis. Many rest areas along South Carolina's highways are filfthy
and some are even considered dangerous. A rash of robberies that
began in February and culminated with a violent attack on an
elderly woman in Sumter County in June has forced South Carolina's
politicians to sit up and take notice. And today, a task force
formed by Attorney General Charlie Condon is visiting Georgia to
get some lessons in rest-stop safety and housekeeping. (Scruggs,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution),
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-BLACKCOLLEGES _ George Bush visits Dillard University
Thursday, a historically black college in New Orleans.. Bush has
been heavily criticized for short-changing historically black
colleges in Texas, but the state settled a 30-year desegregation
suit this year. Texas pledged more equitable funding and Bush's
critics spoke of an election-year conversion. (Sherman, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 25.
</P>
<P>
   KING-DCMARCH _ Racial profiling and police brutality will take
center stage on Washington's Mall on Saturday when Martin Luther
King III, president of the Southern Christian Leadership
Conference, hosts the ``Redeem the Dream'' march. King is spending
this week hyping the march and will take part in a Town Hall
meeting in D.C. on Wednesday night to discuss the mass gathering,
which takes place on the 37th anniversary of the March on
Washington, and which also takes place during the annual SCLC
conference, in Arlington, Va. (Eversley, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) MOVED.
</P>
