   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   MCCARTY-COLUMN _ A moment ago it was May, and summer stretched
before us, tempting us like a brand-new book just waiting to
cracked. Now, August is flickering like the last fireflies.
(McCarty, Dayton Daily News) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NETHAWAY-COLUMN _ The latest monkey wrench to be tossed into the
America's affirmative action machinery came from a Georgia federal
district court ruling that said the University of Georgia's
affirmative action admission policy was unconstitutional. The
university, which had been making race-based admission decisions to
boost racial diversity on its campus, now has stopped the practice.
(Nethaway, Waco Tribune-Herald). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   KELSO-COLUMN _ In late November or early December, Steve Kurachi
plans to launch a small, homemade 12-foot-by-5-foot Fiberglas and
polyurethane foam raft in the Atlantic Ocean off the Canary
Islands, near northwest Africa, and take off across the Atlantic.
(Kelso, Austin American-Statesman). MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   JOEMURRAY-COLUMN _ When I was a little girl during the '30s, we
lived on a farm in rural Georgia and had no electricity. All chores
had to be done by hand, and every Monday that it wasn't raining was
wash day. After Mom cooked a hearty breakfast of homemade biscuits,
country fried ham or sausage, gravy, grits, eggs and coffee for the
family, her wash day would get under way. (Joe Murray, Cox News
Service).
</P>
