<HEADER>
A0230 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-STAPLES-KIOSKS-BOS &LR;      08-23 0496
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-KIOSKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STAPLES TO TRY `BRICK AND CLICK' KIOSKS IN 20 STORES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHRIS REIDY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Looking to offer customers more convenience through a ``bricks
and clicks'' strategy, Staples Inc. it will test kiosks linked to
its retail Web site in about 20 of its 1,200 office-supply
superstores.
</P>
<P>
   Called ``business solutions centers,'' the kiosks let customers
order online with or without the help of a Staples associate. If an
item is out of stock at a store or the customer wants to place an
unusually large order, the customer can opt to buy it from the
Staples.com Web site and get next-day delivery.
</P>
<P>
   A kiosk linked to Staples.com gives a customer access to a much
wider range of goods than can be stocked in a store.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our business solutions centers are the ultimate in
bricks-and-clicks retailing,'' Staples chief executive Thomas G.
Stemberg said Wednesday. ``We are transforming our business by
bringing the online world to store shoppers. By integrating our
stores with Staples.com and its extensive offering of both products
and business services, we are truly becoming a one-stop destination
for all the needs of small business.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Rebecca Zitomer, director of Staples business solutions,
``Many of our customers don't know Staples.com yet. The business
solutions centers are a way to introduce those customers to
Staples.com and show them how easy it is to use.''
</P>
<P>
   Part of Staples' recent focus has been to offer services such as
business-tax preparation, payroll processing, and Web-site design
to the same small-business customers who buy its paper clips and
pencils. The store kiosk is another way to raise awareness about
these new services Staples is offering.
</P>
<P>
   In e-commerce circles, it was once thought a retailer that
launched a Web site might take away business from its stores. But
now the conventional wisdom is that the best retailers will offer
customers three ways to buy merchandise _ in a store, from a retail
Web site, and through a catalog.
</P>
<P>
   Under this model, the customer gets to choose which is the most
convenient way to make a purchase.
</P>
<P>
   Staples originally placed Internet-linked kiosks in its handful
of airport stores. Business travelers could order what they needed
at Logan International Airport and have it delivered to a hotel or
business meeting in another city.
</P>
<P>
   Now a larger variation of that kiosk will be tested in Staples
conventional superstores. If tests are successful, business
solutions centers will be installed in more stores.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet has made some Staples investors nervous. While
store sales continue to be strong, the company's investment in
Staples.com has been a drag on recent earnings.
</P>
<P>
   On Nasdaq, Staples shares have lost nearly 20 percent of their
value since the beginning of the year. Wednesday shares of the
Framingham, Mass. company closed down 27 cents at $16.38.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-00 1810EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
