<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-EXPEDITION-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEAD FOR HOUSTON FOR A ROAMIN' ROMAN HOLIDAY
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By ANDREW MARTON 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   If you can't possibly hop an Alitalia flight to Rome to do as
the Romans do, or if the Rome of the Trevi Fountain and the
Vatican's St. Peter's Square is about as accessible as sharing a
gelato with Sophia Loren, here's the next best thing. Rent a Fiat
or splurge on a Lamborghini, and head on down the highway to
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   DESTINATION: ``The Splendor of Rome: The 18th Century,'' at the
new Audrey Jones Beck Building of The Museum of Fine Arts, Houston,
at 5601 Main St. The exhibit runs through Sept. 17. For more
information, call (713) 639-7540.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT TO READ BEFORE LEAVING: It might not strike one immediately
as ``travel guide lite'' but the German writer J.W. Goethe took the
time to pen ``Italian Journey'' (available in a glorious
translation by W.H. Auden), which covered many things rustic and
refined in Italy in the latter part of the 18th century.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT TO LISTEN TO WHILE DRIVING DOWN: Rapturous melodies of
almost anything by Domenico Scarlatti or, better still, ``The Four
Seasons'' by Antonio Vivaldi.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT YOU'LL SEE AT THE SHOW: A staggering presentation of 400
paintings, sculptures, prints, drawings, maps, architectural
models, furniture and decorative arts.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT YOU MIGHT BUY: Peruse the museum store's cache of
hand-painted Italian pottery, ceramic plates and urns ($80-$400).
Or, take home a $15 CD titled ``Music, 18th century and Rome''
featuring uplifting melodies by Mozart and Handel, among others.
And for those who can't possibly leave the gift shop without a
little something, there is always the $45 necktie festooned with a
map of 18th-century Rome.
</P>
<P>
   WHAT TO EAT AFTER A DAY AT THE EXHIBITION: Drop in on the Grotto
restaurant, 20 minutes away from the museum at 3920 Westheimer.
Grotto will replenish all the gray matter exhausted by the
exhibition with such signature dishes as trout Mandorlata (the fish
is almond-crusted and embellished by artichoke hearts and tomatoes,
all swimming in a white wine sauce); or orecchiette con rapini,
little-ear pasta gussied up with broccoli rabe, olive oil, garlic
and Italian bread crumbs. Or take the credit card out for a more
vigorous walk at the nearby River Oaks Shopping Center, and stop in
at La Griglia (2002 W. Gray St.) to sample its shrimp-and-crab
cheesecake or ``snapper La Griglia,'' grilled fish crowned with
lump crab meat and napped in a grape essence.
</P>
<P>
   ``''Buon appetito e buon viaggio.''''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-00 1810EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
