<SLUG> BC-CIR-Q&AMP;A-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSTALLING A SCANNER WITH WINDOWS 98
</HEADLINE>
 (Circuits)  
 By J.D.BIERSDORFER 
  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. How difficult would it be for a mere novice to add a photo
scanner to a Windows 98 computer?  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. All things considered, it is probably not as hard to add a
scanner to a Windows 98 system as it is with earlier versions of
Windows. Windows 98 can even detect and install the needed driver
software for several scanner models, including ones made by UMAX,
Hewlett-Packard and Logitech. That is not to say that only scanners
by these manufacturers will work with Windows 98; it just means
that you may have to do a manual installation for the drivers from
the floppy disks or CD-ROM that come with a new scanner.
</P>
<P>
   After you have followed the manufacturer's instructions for
attaching the scanner to your computer, restart it and see if
Windows detects the new hardware. If you do not get a message
saying that Windows has found new hardware, go to the Start menu,
then to Settings and Control Panel, and double-click on Add New
Hardware. Follow the instructions of the New Hardware Wizard as it
takes you through the process.
</P>
<P>
   After you are finished with the wizard, you will probably need
to install additional software for the scanner itself, following
the manufacturer's instructions. Once you have completed the
installation process described in your scanner's instructions, you
may want to test the new hardware. Go back to the Start menu, then
Settings and Control Panel, and double-click on the Scanners and
Cameras icon. Pick the name of your new scanner from the list and
click on Properties. Click on Test Scanner or Camera, and Windows
will check whether your scanner is hooked up and working properly.
If you encounter difficulties, you may want to take advantage of
the scanner's technical support contact information.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I've heard of something that is referred to as WAP. and
believe that it is related to the wireless world, but I'm not
really sure. Can you explain?  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. WAP stands for Wireless Application Protocol, and it is
indeed related to the world of wireless devices. Just as there are
standards for regulating how data is sent around the Internet, WAP
sets a standard for how data is sent between wireless devices like
handheld computers, Web-enabled cell phones and pagers.
</P>
<P>
   Since the monochrome screens on these types of mobile devices
are quite small and are not generally navigated with a mouse or
full-size keyboard, the pages displayed on them are created
differently. The WAP system uses something called Wireless Markup
Language _ a sort of optimized version of the Hypertext Markup
Language, or HTML, used for regular Web pages _ to display the
content on the wireless units. For more details on WAP, visit
www.wap.com or www.wapforum.org.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I am thinking about adding more RAM to my computer, and I
would like to know how I can find out how much it can take. Where
can I look for that information?  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The manual that came with your computer, if you still have
it, is one of the best places to find out how much and what kind of
RAM you can add to your system. If you no longer have the manual,
you might try looking up your model on the manufacturer's Web site.
</P>
<P>
   There are many kinds of RAM, and some computers need to have the
chips installed in a specific manner or quantity. An excellent
place to look for information is on the Web sites of the memory
makers, like Kingston Technology (www.kingston.com) and Viking
Components (www.vikingcomponents.com). Both sites have interactive
configuration worksheets that will let you select your computer
maker and model, then will tell you how much RAM your system can
hold and what kind to buy. You can usually buy RAM right there on
the site.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Circuits invites questions about computer-based technology, by
e-mail to QandA(at)nytimes.com or mail to Questions, Circuits, The
New York Times, 229 W. 43rd St., New York, NY 10036-3959. This
column will answer questions of general interest, but letters
cannot be answered individually.
</P>
</TEXT>
