<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HELEN-THOMAS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;     WHERE ARE THE FEMINISTS IN THIS CAMPAIGN? 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 &HT;     By HELEN THOMAS  
 &HT;     c.2000 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Where are the prominent women activists in this
election? Their silence is deafening. They are not high-voltage
players this time around.
</P>
<P>
   They are invisible except for the ever-loving wives and
daughters of Vice President Al Gore and Texas Gov. George W. Bush,
whom they tout as perfect husbands and fathers.
</P>
<P>
   Laura Bush, featured at the Republican National Convention,
praised her husband as a family man, not like you-know-who. She
also took a few veiled potshots at President Clinton, saying the
American people want someone they can ``respect'' in the White
House, someone who will uphold its dignity.
</P>
<P>
   Tipper Gore, before introducing her husband, boogied on the
stage of the Democratic National Convention and brought the
delegates to their feet.
</P>
<P>
   Then she told them she and her husband were high school
sweethearts. The scene was a throwback to the '50s when political
wives fixed their adoring gazes on their husbands. And much has
been made of the prolonged, passionate kiss Gore gave his wife
after she introduced him.
</P>
<P>
   But we're asking about other women, successors to the feminist
leaders _ the Bella Abzugs, Betty Friedans and Gloria Steinems _
who helped break through the gender barriers in the '70s and then
hit a plateau in the Ronald Reagan '80s. We're talking about those
women who insisted on being heard politically and who took up the
cause of the ill-fated Equal Rights Amendment that would have put
women on a par with men.
</P>
<P>
   Midge Costanza, who headed the women's liaison office in the
Jimmy Carter White House, said that while a lot of women now have
good jobs, many others still face tough challenges.
</P>
<P>
   For instance. women at work earn about a quarter less per dollar
than men do in comparable jobs. And while women have made some
progress in gaining state and national offices, Costanza cited the
sorry statistics showing that there are only 58 women in the
435-member House and only nine women in the 100-member Senate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to mobilize women,'' she said. ``But there is no
leadership.''
</P>
<P>
   Costanza contends that a ``backlash'' against feminists is
keeping would-be activists in the background in this election.
</P>
<P>
   Another prominent woman, who was in the trenches in the women's
movement years ago, said, ``We have disappeared. We scare people.''
Then she added, ``There is such a backlash against Hillary,''
referring to the first lady, bidding for a U.S. Senate seat from
New York.
</P>
<P>
   The antipathy to the president's wife by some women in New York
City is baffling, she said. Another source noted that some women
even use the word ``hate'' to express their feelings against Mrs.
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently they liked her better when they felt sorry for her as
the betrayed wife.
</P>
<P>
   But her supporters are predicting that in the coming weeks Mrs.
Clinton will ``connect'' with women voters, who they say will
realize that she can be an effective senator because of her
national stature and her focus on issues women care about _
education, children, gun control. Still, the carpetbagger issue
can't be discounted.
</P>
<P>
   In the presidential race, Gore, who had trouble winning over
women voters at the start of the campaign, seems to have found the
key with his appeal to ``working families.'' A new USA Today/CNN/
Gallup poll showed Gore, who had been down 9 points among women,
has leaped to a 22-point lead over Bush with female voters, 58
percent to 36 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Gore gained points with women when he stressed that he was
pro-abortion-rights, pro-gun-control, pro-patients'-bill-of-rights
and pro-family-and-medical-leave. Furthermore, with his
``I-am-my-own- man'' acceptance speech, Gore seemed to be free at
last. Now he is sporting a warmer persona and is taking time out to
shake every hand, even schmoozing with reporters on the campaign
trail, tearing a page out of his rival's ``likeability'' guidebook.
The new Gore is trying to erase the impression that he is wooden
and dull compared with the more engaging, back-slapping Bush, who
is viewed as the kind of guy you want to sit down and have a couple
of beers with.
</P>
<P>
   Marie Wilson, head of Project White House, a campaign dedicated
to electing a woman president someday, put it this way: ``Bush is
the guy you want to date, and Gore is the man you would trust to
babysit with your children.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Gore's momentum may be helped by the abortion rights
leaders who are trying to transform the Clinton 1992 campaign
slogan ``It's the economy, stupid'' into a new call to arms: ``It's
the Supreme Court, stupid.'' Their aim is to evoke fears that
Bush-appointed justices would overturn Roe v. Wade, the 1973 ruling
that legalized abortion.
</P>
<P>
   Women should answer this call. They should realize they have a
big stake in the coming election. They are in the majority, and
their votes do count. But if they want to be heard, they are going
to have to speak up.
</P>
<P>
   (Helen Thomas can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address helent(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
