<HEADLINE>
COMPUTERS NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   RCA to Offer E-Books, The Next Generation
</P>
<P>
   RCA, which made its name in stereo equipment and televisions,
wants to get its consumers reading again. To that end, the company
is releasing two new electronic readers, or e-books.
</P>
<P>
   The two models RCA will begin selling this fall are, in effect,
the next generation of the Rocket eBook and Softbook Reader. The
companies that made those two devices, NuvoMedia and Softbook
Press, were bought earlier this year by Gemstar International,
which also owns TV Guide. Gemstar, in turn, has licensed the
technology to Thomson Multimedia, RCA's owner.
</P>
<P>
   RCA's eBooks, like their ancestors, can handle only electronic
books and magazines produced in a special format that is also
controlled by Gemstar. The REB1100 will hold about 20 novels with
its standard 8 megabytes of memory, but a 64-megabyte memory
expansion card will also be available. Its 5.5-inch black-and-white
screen has about six times the resolution of screens on most
monochrome personal digital assistants, according to Thomson. More
muscular users might like the REB1200, with a full-color 8.5-inch
display. The advantages of full color come at the expense of
resolution, which is slightly lower.
</P>
<P>
   Both devices will feature built-in modems, and the REB1200 will
also have a high-speed Ethernet connection for downloading reading
material without a computer. ``The mass market is what RCA is good
at doing,'' said Lou Lenzi, vice president for new-media business
development at Thomson. ``To bring this to the masses, we need the
experience to be as simple as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Lenzi expects that the basic model will not cost more than $300.
</P>
<P>
   New Programs Remove Unwanted Internet Files
</P>
<P>
   Hard-disk space may not be as expensive as Manhattan real
estate, but it can be equally precious to computer users who like
to squirrel away as many files on their machines as they can. Web
browser programs are notorious for hoarding disk space with saved
graphics files and other data from previously visited Web sites.
</P>
<P>
   But a new category of software is emerging to help clean up hard
drives. One such program, iClean by Aladdin Systems, has just been
released. The software, which runs on Power Macintosh computers
with Version 7.5.3 of the Mac operating system or later, promises
to seek out and delete unnecessary browser cache files safely and
to wipe out Internet history and cookie files for privacy-conscious
Web surfers. The iClean program will scan the Mac, inform the user
of how much space can be saved and will even empty the Trash if so
instructed. The software will also fix broken alias files (the Mac
equivalent of shortcuts) that are scattered around the hard drive.
</P>
<P>
   The iClean program by itself is available for $29.95, and it
also comes with Aladdin's Spring Cleaning 3.5, a suite of Mac
maintenance and uninstaller tools that sells for $49.95. Curious
Mac users who would like to try iClean before buying can download a
free 15-day demo version at www.aladdinsys.com/iclean/index.html.
</P>
<P>
   Windows 95, 98 and NT users who have the same urge to tidy up
may want to pick up a copy of Norton CleanSweep 2000 by the
Symantec Corp. The program usually sells for about $40 in stores,
but it can be purchased online and downloaded from
www.symantecstore.com for $26. Norton CleanSweep 2000, which
features an application that will thoroughly uninstall unwanted and
outdated programs, will also remove old cookies, plug-ins, ActiveX
controls and other debris that can wash up on the hard drive after
serious surfing sessions.
</P>
<P>
   You Know How to Whistle, Don't You? Use the Smart Card
</P>
<P>
   ComSense Technologies, a company in Tel Aviv, has developed a
secure way for customers to log on at an online banking or trading
site by using a sound bite instead of a password. The new product,
called Comdot, consists of a credit card with a flat button on it.
When the button is pressed, it sends a sound code to a Web site
through any built-in or plugged-in microphone. The sound code is
used to authenticate the identity of the cardholder.
</P>
<P>
   The code changes every time it is sent, which prevents someone
from recording the code and playing it back to gain access to an
account. Further security is provided by a PIN.
</P>
<P>
   ``Using the Comdot code is equivalent to swiping your card
through a reader, but it's online,'' said Alon Atsmon, the founder
and chief executive of ComSense. It can be used on a personal
computer or on a cell phone or regular phone, he added. The sound
code could even be used for phone-card calls and to get access to
personal calendars on sites like AOL or Lycos.
</P>
<P>
   The sound button, which will have a battery life of three years,
will begin appearing on credit cards sometime toward the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Atsmon envisions his technology as the logical end to the
process of miniaturization in Internet transactions, from the
personal computer to the laptop, the PDA and the cell phone. He has
plans far beyond the sound button.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to put more on the card,'' he said. ``Maybe a tiny LCD
screen so you can view your transactions, or a PDA-type calendar.''
</P>
<P>
   Apple Trade-In
</P>
<P>
   Owners of the Apple PowerBook 5300 and 190 models can trade in
their old computers for a significant discount on one of the
company's 400-megahertz G3 laptops if they act quickly. From now
until Aug. 31, Apple is offering $700 off the price of a new G3
PowerBook (usually $2,499) for those who choose to send their old
5300 or 190 models back to the company. The 5300/190 series, which
was released in 1995, gained a measure of infamy because of a host
of design and technical problems, and its overheating _ and
occasionally combusting _ battery. Those interested in taking
advantage of the offer should call Apple at (800) 767-2775.
Although not so dramatic as bursting into flames, the discount
seems a much safer way for the 5300/190 series to go out in a blaze
of glory.
</P>
</TEXT>
