<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories New York Times editors are planning for
Thursday, Aug. 24 Page 1. The NYT frontpage advisory, with layout
description, will move by 7:30 p.m. ET. The NYT News Service Night
Supervisor is Pat Ryan (888-346-9867).
</P>
<P>
   SCI-EMBRYO-RESEARCH (Undated) _ The National Institutes of
Health on Wednesday issued its long-awaited rules that will permit
federally financed researchers to work on human embryonic stem
cells, cells derived from the very early embryo. Because of their
ability to form every tissue of the body, the cells are believed by
scientists to hold great promise in treating many diseases. But
because the cell lines are derived from human embryos, although
ones due to be discarded, opponents of abortion had objected to
federal approval of the research. By Nicholas Wade. (1075 words)
</P>
<P>
   SCI-DIABETES-RATE (Undated) _ The incidence of diabetes in the
United States increased markedly between 1990 and 1998, researchers
said, with the increase particularly marked among people in their
30s, among whom there was a 76 percent rise in incidence of the
disease. And they said the new cases will exact a harsh toll in
disability, death and medical expenses in decades to come. The
increase is almost entirely in Type 2 diabetes, commonly called
adult onset diabetes, which accounts for 90-95 percent of all cases
of the disease. Inactivity and weight gain can bring on Type 2
diabetes, and doctors blame much of the current rise on obesity,
which is also increasing steadily, with more than half of Americans
now overweight. By Denise Grady. (1100 words)
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   CHENEY-BUSINESS (Undated) _ Dick Cheney's record as a chief
executive at Halliburton has become a political issue in recent
weeks, with the Bush campaign defending his multi-million dollar
retirement payment as fair compensation for a job well done. But
the scope of that success is a matter of considerable dispute among
present and former company executives. By Diana B. Henriques, with
reporting by Michael Moss and Lowell Bergman. (3250 words)
</P>
<P>
   TEACHER-TRAINING (Boston) _ Convinced that teacher education
schools are not producing candidates for a world of higher
standards, a growing number of states and school districts are
taking training into their own hands, short circuiting the
traditional process with crash courses that put new teachers in the
classroom after as little as three weeks of training. By Kate
Zernike. (1750 words)
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-SUBMARINE-ASSESS (Moscow) _ A news analysis: With the
public confession Wednesday night by President Vladimir Putin that
he feels ``responsibility and guilt'' for the loss of the nuclear
submarine Kursk, Russia's political evolution seems to be taking a
new kind of post-Soviet turn. Military commanders are offering to
resign. The government and the private sector are competing to
raise millions of dollars to comfort the families of the Kursk's
crew. The air waves are ringing with the mea culpas from the
haughty admirals of the once mighty Red Banner Fleet of the north.
It didn't start out that way. By Patrick E. Tyler. (1350 words)
</P>
<P>
   NY-SUBWAY-OBSESSION (New York) _ If Darius McCollum were a
millionaire, he might be excused as an eccentric. If he were a
genius, allowances probably would be made as well. But McCollum is
neither. And his unusual problem _ his obsession, as he calls it _
has gotten him in so much trouble that people aren't even laughing
anymore. Since he was a high school freshman, McCollum, who grew up
in Queens and is now 35, has been in and out of jail for
masquerading as a New York City transit worker. New York is a city
of quirky people. It is also a place where train buffs rank among
the quirkiest. Even so, the authorities say McCollum towers above
the best of them, so expert at his chosen quirkiness that he has
repeatedly fooled riders, subway employees and the police into
believing he belongs in transit blues. By Dean E. Murphy. (1800
words)
</P>
<P>
   With photo, NYT6, sent Aug. 22.
</P>
