<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 18:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0252 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-RAMBLIN'-JACK-LADN &LR;      08-23 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAMBLIN'-JACK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACK OF HEARTS
</HEADLINE>
  Daughter captures Elliott's ramblin' ways on film and builds a bond
with the man she's only starting to know 
(For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GLENN WHIPP 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Aiyana Elliott always had it in her mind that she would make a
film about her folk singer father, Ramblin' Jack Elliott, one day.
She just didn't figure it would be her first movie.
</P>
<P>
   But in the year that she graduated from New York University's
film school, a host of her father's friends and contemporaries,
people like Beat poets Allen Ginsberg and William Burroughs, folk
singer Townes Van Zandt and country's John Denver, died. And Aiyana
realized that if she was going to tell the remarkable story of the
cowboy singer who acted as folk music's bridge from Woody Guthrie
to Bob Dylan, she'd better make it her first priority.
</P>
<P>
   The resulting labor of love, ``The Ballad of Ramblin' Jack,''
came after Elliott spent two years traveling down America's back
roads with her father, trying to find out what makes him tick. She
admittedly didn't have a clue because she never has really known
her father. He lived up to his nickname during her formative years,
and even as adults, Aiyana admits that she had never enjoyed an
``actual conversation'' with Jack until after the documentary
premiered this year at the Sundance Film Festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always been a struggle to talk to him, and that's been
baffling and hurtful to me because my dad has such a natural gift
with people,'' Aiyana, 31, says. ``The challenge has always been to
get him to share that gift with me.''
</P>
<P>
   And, in a large way, that's what ``The Ballad of Ramblin' Jack''
is about _ a daughter trying to bond with her charming, but
distant, father. That personal aspect gives the documentary a
universality that made it a hit with audiences at Sundance (the
movie won the special jury prize for artistic achievement) and at
subsequent film festivals. Moviegoers' enthusiasm has, in turn,
finally helped the Elliotts communicate for the first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``The journey we've taken since completing the film _ sharing
the movie with audiences and talking about it with them and each
other _ has brought us a long way,'' Aiyana says. ``It has totally
improved our communication. In fact, in recent weeks, we've started
to talk more and more freely and kind of gotten to know each other.
I'm sure the problems we have communicating will persist in certain
ways, but it feels to me that we've begun a great new chapter in
our relationship. It has been a wonderful gift.''
</P>
<P>
   Ask Jack about that, though, and you're likely to get a more
veiled response, not because he doesn't feel the same way but
because _ well, he's Ramblin' Jack Elliott. And as friend Kris
Kristofferson says in the movie, Ramblin' Jack earned his name as
much for his storytelling as his wandering ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen the movie 10 times, and each time I see it, I get
more and more little laughs out of it,'' Jack, now 69, says. ``I
see more funny things that I didn't think were funny before. But I
don't ever get used to seeing myself. I'm too ugly to be able to
tolerate looking at myself that much. But there's parts that are
beautiful and I'm amazed by that and tickled by that and fascinated
by that. I don't ever get tired of watching it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ballad of Ramblin' Jack'' mixes current interviews and
concert performances with extraordinary archival footage to present
a portrait of a man who's truly one of a kind. Born Elliott Charles
Adnopoz, the son of a Brooklyn doctor, Jack rebelled from an early
age against his parents' expectations (when his mother saw him in
concert for the first time, she remarked, ``Look at those hands.
What a fine surgeon he would have made'') and the confines of city
life.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see the footage of him as a little boy and it's amazing to
see how much his personality was already formed,'' Aiyana says.
``His love of adventure and the West and his desire to explore the
world are all fully there.''
</P>
<P>
   Jack ran away from home at 15 and joined a traveling rodeo. He
soon fell in love with cowboy songs and folk and roots music, and
became fast friends with Woody Guthrie after showing up at
Guthrie's Coney Island home one day. Elliott learned much from
Guthrie (Guthrie once said that ``Jack sounds more like me than I
do''), but his flat-picking style of guitar playing was all his
own.
</P>
<P>
   A decade later, it was Elliott's turn to teach, acting as a
mentor to a young Bob Dylan. In fact, at Dylan's first concert at
the legendary New York folk venue Gerde's Folk City, a sign was
posted outside reading: ``Now appearing: The Son of Jack Elliott.''
</P>
<P>
   However influential, Elliott has never aspired to be a star,
although he hasn't necessarily desired the periods of obscurity
that have distinguished his long career, either. He has received
some recognition late in the game, including a Grammy for his 1995
folk album ``South Coast.'' In 1998, President Clinton gave him the
National Medal of Arts.
</P>
<P>
   The film includes footage of Elliott receiving that award as
well as fascinating, never-before-seen clips from the Guthrie
family's private collection and raw material from filmmakers D.A.
Pennebaker (who made the Bob Dylan documentary ``Don't Look Back'')
and Bobby Neuwirth. Elliott's favorite scene revolves around an
appearance on the Johnny Cash Show, where he had to simultaneously
tune and play his guitar during a duet with the Man in Black.
</P>
<P>
   After fashioning a two-hour film from the 100 hours of material
she shot and the 50 hours of archival footage, Aiyana kept the
movie from her father until its January premiere at Sundance. The
reason? Self-preservation.
</P>
<P>
   ``My dad is somebody, if left to his own devices in a room with
this movie, could easily convince himself that it is a terrible
indictment of his own character,'' Aiyana says. ``He's paranoid
that way. But seeing it with an audience helped give him some
perspective on it.''
</P>
<P>
   Has it ever. Jack calls the movie ``great'' and appreciates the
attention it has given his music. And even though he recently
married (for the fifth time) and, for the first time, truly has a
home to call his own, Jack Elliott is ramblin' more than ever these
days.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wouldn't call it a dramatic explosion, but I'm getting a lot
more gigs,'' Elliott says. ``And I still like performing in front
of a live audience, providing that the audience is alive. And they
seem to be these days.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Aiyana: ``Wavy Gravy called my dad the Lee Strasberg of the
Lone Prairie, like a Method folk singer. I think people respond to
that. He's just up there telling a story, but he does it in a way
unlike anybody else. There's nobody else like him, I can tell you
that.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
