<DOCNO> NYT20000823.0259 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 18:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0266 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-DARK-FACE-REVIEW-LADN     08-23 0859
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DARK-FACE-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PLANTATION OEDIPUS
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 1/2 stars 
By EVAN HENERSON 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's nothing quite like the feeling of being a couple of
steps ahead of the characters you're watching. Call it the
theatrical equivalent to talking-back-to-the-screen syndrome: Don't
do it, buddy! Open your eyes!
</P>
<P>
   Or blind yourself. That works, too.
</P>
<P>
   Despite its dramatic unlikeliness, the Oedipus myth can
successfully be transported to another time in another place, as
Pulitzer Prize-winning poet Rita Dove has done with her play ``The
Darker Face of the Earth.'' ``Darker Face'' may be accustomed to
having more sprawl space, but director Anthony J. Haney's
production for the Fountain Theatre is confined, compact and very
much in your face. As it should be: There is nothing quiet or small
about Dove's examination of slavery and identity. This is a
production that finds a way to celebrate despair.
</P>
<P>
   A joint venture between the Fountain and Black Artists Network
Development, Haney's production is the California premiere of a
work that has played to great success at larger venues in Ashland,
Ore.; Washington, D.C.; and London. The Fountain was lucky to get
it, and the NoHo district more fortunate still that the Fountain's
Hollywood venue was too small to hold it. Here it is, then, with
all of its ironic punch.
</P>
<P>
   A free-form adaptation, ``Darker Face'' is as much a story of a
proud man's quest for freedom as it is the story of how that same
man is struck down by forces outside his control. The wheels of
fate _ or of a curse _ are as powerful in the pre-Civil War South
as they were when Sophocles was drawing the noose around his
misguided king.
</P>
<P>
   Consequently, Augustus Newcastle, a well-spoken slave, acts as
he does because he exists on a South Carolina plantation in 1840.
Because he has no choice. Built into the play is the knowledge that
Newcastle's assignation with a white female plantation owner,
Amalia LaFarge can come to no good. What Dove's story lacks in
suspense it makes up for in tragic irony. Newcastle believes he is
healing the land even when people are telling him he's actually its
downfall.
</P>
<P>
   At the American Renegade, Edward Haynes' set is an
often-crowded, two-level stage, hung with bits of white linen. Up
above is the ``big house,'' the LaFarge estate where blacks come
only when invited. Down below are the cotton fields. Characters
enter all corners of the theater, often singing, occasionally in
chains. When Amalia (Jacqueline Schultz) gives birth to a son, the
slaves down below wait eagerly for news and for the first cry. But
when the baby is the wrong color, a plot is hatched by plantation
patriarch Louis LaFarge (played by William Schenker), the doctor
and a very reluctant Amalia. The child will be carried off, but it
doesn't take an oracle to know we haven't seen the last of Amalia's
sewing basket or its precious cargo.
</P>
<P>
   Fast forward 20 years. Hector (Michael McFall), the father of
Amalia's child, has fled to the far reaches of the swamp. Louis has
taken to boozing and bouts of isolated madness, leaving a hardened
and bitter Amalia to treat her slaves with a newly discovered
cruelty. Everything changes when she purchases Newcastle (Jason
George), a slave with a reputation for intelligence, breeding and a
fighting spirit. With his idea-planting stories of rebellion aboard
the Amistad, the literate and well-spoken Newcastle is fascinating
to his fellow slaves. All except Scylla (Denise Dowse), a kind of
slave priestess who has been talking about a curse on the land
pretty much since the curtain rose.
</P>
<P>
   As he is starting to receive overtures from a group of
conspirators, Newcastle finds himself summoned to the ``big house''
for a meeting with the mistress. Their talk turns to literature.
``The Greeks were too predictable,'' Newcastle says. Fires back
Amalia: ``A slave doesn't have opinions!'' You can probably see
where this is headed.
</P>
<P>
   The 19-person cast is strong pretty much across the board.
George is steely-eyed but charismatic Newcastle, while Schultz
guides Amalia from despair to near tyranny and back to warmth, no
easy task particularly since the character drops out of sight for
most of the first act. Particularly noteworthy among the ensemble
are Joy DeMichelle Moore as Phebe, a slave willing to help
Newcastle fan the flames of revolt; Clinton Derricks-Carroll as the
musical Scipio; and, particularly Michael McFall, a towering,
silent and potentially menacing Hector.
</P>
<P>
   Dove tells her story not through verse, but through song. Cast
members sing traditional and gospel renditions performed a capella
and beautifully arranged by musical director DeWayne Knox. Equally
affecting is the lighting design by Kathi O'Donohue. &QL; 
___ &QL; 
What: ``The Darker Face of the Earth.'' &QL; 
Where: American Renegade Theatre, 11136 Magnolia Blvd., North
Hollywood. &QL; 
When: Through Sept. 17. Performances at 8 p.m. Thursdays through
Saturdays, 7 p.m. Sundays; also at 3 p.m. this Sunday and Sept.
10. &QL; 
Tickets: $18 to $22. Call (323) 663-1525. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
