<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 18:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0273 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-ASSESS-2TAKES-     08-23 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ASSESS-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANALYSIS: HINTS OF POLITICAL EVOLUTION IN AFTERMATH OF SUBMARINE
CRISIS 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also RUSSIA-SUBMARINE) 
 By PATRICK E. TYLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ With a public confession Wednesday night by President
Vladimir Putin, who said he feels ``responsibility and guilt'' for
the loss of the nuclear-powered submarine Kursk, Russia's political
evolution seems to be taking a new kind of post-Soviet turn.
</P>
<P>
   Military commanders are offering to resign. The government and
the private sector are competing to raise millions of dollars to
comfort the families of the Kursk's crew. The airwaves are ringing
with mea culpas from the haughty admirals of the once mighty Red
Banner Fleet of the north.
</P>
<P>
   And on the surface of the Barents Sea, Russia for the first time
cracked open the door to Norwegian and British seamen and asked
them to enter the inner sanctum of a powerful Cold War leviathan
named Kursk and to help retrieve the 118 crewmen _ sons of Russia,
Ukraine and other lost fragments of the Soviet empire.
</P>
<P>
   It did not start out that way.
</P>
<P>
   When the Kursk exploded and crashed to the bottom of the Barents
Sea on Aug. 12, Russians spontaneously reacted with indignation
when military leaders dropped into a familiar defensive crouch,
distorting and withholding information and paying little heed to
the human dimension of the tragedy for the crew members and their
families, many of whom live in rank poverty in Russia's far north.
</P>
<P>
   And they were even more appalled when Putin, instead of rushing
home like the disciplined and pragmatic public servant they voted
for in March, tarried at his favorite resort on the Black Sea. Day
after day he remained there, as one of the most extraordinary
rescue dramas at sea unfolded. Lives were at risk. Last breaths
were being drawn, but still Putin vacationed.
</P>
<P>
   Parallels to the Soviet era raged from the front pages of the
Russian press, and many Russians harked back to Chernobyl, where
the worst nuclear accident in history spewed radiation into the
heavens for days in late April and early May 1986 before Soviet
leaders begrudgingly admitted that something had gone terribly
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   But in the din of recriminations of the loss of the Kursk and
with the sudden awakening of Putin, what many have missed is the
repudiation of the Soviet era that is also present in this crisis.
</P>
<P>
   The Kursk families have expressed their outrage and pain, and
Putin elevated their plight this week to a national priority.
Politicians have said that officials must be held accountable, but
Putin said Wednesday night that the old Soviet game of laying blame
gratuitously would be set aside. ``It has been like that before,''
he said Wednesday on national television, adding that ``nothing
will be done'' until ``a full understanding has been gained about
what happened and why.''
</P>
<P>
   Though Russia's military made mistakes and was too slow to ask
for Western help, its officials also became surprisingly accessible
and accountable. One admiral admitted that rescue gear was not
available because it has been rented to oil companies. And a
Russian television reporter was given exclusive access to the deck
of a Russian cruiser from which to make his reports.
</P>
<P>
   It was also impossible to ignore the moment when former Soviet
President Mikhail Gorbachev joined the ranks of critics chiding
Putin for delaying Russia's request for Western assistance too
long. For it was Gorbachev who in 1986 let the flames of Chernobyl
burn without warning his countrymen _ not to mention Europe _ that
a radioactive cloud was headed their way. And, of course, Gorbachev
refused all Western assistance to contain the worst nuclear
disaster ever.
</P>
<P>
   But with his criticism, Gorbachev showed that he, too, is well
beyond the Soviet era.
</P>
<P>
   Above all, the sinking of the Kursk foreshadows that some
reckoning is ahead for the pared-down remains of the armed forces
of the former Soviet empire, whose once vaunted technological
prowess was already looking battered and bloodied by rebels in the
breakaway republic of Chechnya.
</P>
<P>
   Whether an investigation proves that Russia's nuclear-powered
leviathan Kursk was sunk by a collision with a so-far illusive
foreign submarine, or by a misfired torpedo or a World War II mine,
the lasting image from the surface of the Barents Sea will be the
hapless attempts by otherwise heroic Russian rescuers to reach the
Kursk's escape hatch in outdated mini-subs powered by batteries too
old to hold a charge.
</P>
<P>
   When the Norwegians and the British arrived with their shining
technology _ underwater cameras and command centers that looked
like an electronics store showroom _ these ``foreigners'' went to
work in the deep-diving suits and cracked the stubborn hatch in 36
hours.
</P>
<P>
   The wrenching drama of the Kursk has been another painful step
in the education of Putin, the youthful president and longtime KGB
officer who had vowed to strengthen the Russian state and rebuild
its military forces to defend Russia's interests, whatever those
turn out to be in the transition that still is underway.
</P>
<P>
   Putin is discovering in the most poignant way that invoking the
imagery of Russia's military tradition is not the same as
exercising it effectively _ and safely _ every day. In his visit to
Severomorsk on Monday, Putin was reminded again that although
Russia possesses the nuclear arsenal of a global power, the
infrastructure of the Russian military has gone to rust and that
most of its personnel live in poverty.
</P>
<P>
   ``The conditions in which our nuclear submarines are maintained
do not meet any standards, and we could witness another serious
accident at any moment,'' Alexsander Rutskoi, the former vice
president and a war hero who led a political rebellion against
Boris Yeltsin in 1993, said on Monday. In a fiery denunciation of
the navy, Rutskoi, now the governor of the Kursk region for which
the submarine was named, added, ``When the Russian fleet does not
have the necessary means to conduct rescues, the very fact that
submarines go to sea is already a crime.''
</P>
<P>
   After the end of the Vietnam War, U.S. commanders complained
that a ``hollow'' military was the cause of a significant decline
of U.S. prestige in the world, one that would invite challenge from
any adversary. And what ``hollow'' came to mean was the loss of
synergy between recruiting and training professional cadres of
soldiers and a high level of spending on maintenance, spare parts
and ever-improving technologies for weaponry and on safety for the
most important weapon in any arsenal _ the soldier.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Russia now faces a much broader hollowing of its military
forces. Putin speaks as if he is determined to come to terms with
this reality, but without acknowledging that rebuilding the Russian
armed forces can only be accomplished through an inevitable
contraction of Russian power and global pretension. Overreaching
for the glory days of the Soviet past, when Moscow supported a blue
water navy that could compete for power and influence in the
Atlantic and Pacific Oceans, could easily lead to the disasters
that Rutskoi predicted.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's defense minister, Marshal Igor Sergeyev, venting his
frustration on national television on Monday night, said the
``whole reason'' why there were no Russian deep sea divers to race
down to save the Kursk's crew was that the military ``over the
course of the past several years'' has been ``robbed and stripped''
and the armed forces are being funded at ``less than 50 percent''
of their requirements.
</P>
<P>
   But requirements for what?
</P>
<P>
   Putin must now answer that question for the Russians and for his
neighbors in Europe, whom he has alarmed with his ``strong state''
rhetoric.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, flags over the Kremlin flew at half staff Wednesday,
a sign of mourning not only for the lost sailors but for the lost
pride that so many Russians feel.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
