<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 18:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0275 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-MONITOR0825-COX     08-23 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONITOR0825-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Monitor fighting a losing battle on ocean floor
 &HT;    By Mike Toner
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Off the coast of Cape Hatteras, in the graveyard of
the Atlantic, time and tide are erasing the remains of a naval
legend.
</P>
<P>
   The USS Monitor, the icon of Civil War ironclads, is
surrendering to the natural forces and maritime mishaps that have
dogged it since it sank in a storm on New Year's Eve, 1862.
</P>
<P>
   Like the H.L. Hunley, the Confederate submarine raised from
Charleston Harbor this month, the Monitor _ the first ship built
entirely of iron _changed the face of naval warfare and sounded the
death knell for wooden warships. Like the Hunley, the Monitor was
lost at sea for more than a century. And like the Hunley, it is the
object of a multi-million dollar effort to save as much of it as
possible for posterity.
</P>
<P>
   There, however, the tale of these two ships diverges. The Hunley
is now safely ashore, tucked securely in a laboratory built to help
conserve it. The Monitor will not be so easily plucked from the
sea. And its caretakers fear that time is running short.
</P>
<P>
   At first glance, the Monitor, which lies in the heart of a
federal marine sanctuary 16 miles offshore in more than 200 feet
deep _ a depth which divers need specialty gear to reach _ might
seem supremely secure. It's not.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have found fishing trawl nets snagged on the hull,'' says
John Broadwater, director of the Monitor National Marine Sanctuary.
``A while back, a boat pulled some pieces loose with its anchor. We
don't really know how many artifacts have been removed by divers,
but we sometimes hear rumors of items for sale.''
</P>
<P>
   Broadwater says there has been a marked increase in naturally
occurring damage too. ``The hull is deteriorating at a rapid
rate,'' he says. ``The armor plating is falling off. If we let
these things go on much longer, we are going to loose an awful
lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Since its discovery in 1974, underwater archaeologists have
retrieved what they can from the Monitor one piece at a time. The
ship's anchor, a red signal lantern, the three-ton propeller and
more than 100 other artifacts are on display at the Mariner's
Museum in Newport News, Virginia.
</P>
<P>
   But as the ship crumbles, there is a growing sense of urgency to
save more massive artifacts _ components that were unique to the
fleet of Monitor-like ironclads turned out by Union shipyards in
the 1800s. There are no plans to raise the entire ship, but the
U.S. Navy and the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration
(NOAA) are in the midst of a $20 million project _ funded primarily
from the Department of Defense's legacy program _ to save the
engineering essence of the historic vessel.
</P>
<P>
   This month, as Civil War buffs celebrated the Hunley's recovery
in Charleston, divers were struggling in the heavy seas off Cape
Hatteras with the latest phase of the decade-long effort.
</P>
<P>
   Because it came to rest upside down on the bottom, the weight of
the Monitor's hull rests on top of its distinctive ``cheesebox''
turret, putting enormous strain on the corroding, 138-year-old
hull. To keep it from collapsing, divers this summer shored up the
wreck with massive concrete-filled bags to buy a little more time.
</P>
<P>
   During three expeditions to the wreck in July and August, they
retrieved a 10-foot section of the ship's propeller shaft, the
21-foot portion of the ship's skeg, which held the rudder and
propeller shaft in place, and a number of smaller artifacts. They
also erected an underwater crane that is a vital part of next
year's expedition. Broadwater says if weather and his budget
permit, divers next summer will slice through the ship's hull and
hoist the Monitor's 36-ton steam engine.
</P>
<P>
   The engine was the first of a generation of coal-burning engines
whose low profile made it possible to locate them safely below the
ship's waterline. It was designed by Swedish engineer John
Ericsson, who so passionately championed the revolutionary design
of the Monitor that it was known for a time as ``Ericsson's
folly.''
</P>
<P>
   Cutti year.
</P>
<P>
   In a world of wooden ships, however, the fact that an iron ship
floated at all was enough to earn it a place in maritime history.
Modern navies were never the same afterward.
</P>
<P>
   The legacy of the Monitor, in fact, can still be seen in the
U.S. Navy's million Zumwalt-class destroyers, the first of which is
expected to be delivered in 2010. Although the new ships fire
Tomahawk missiles and artillery shells with a range of 60 miles,
the sharply pointed hull, the low, virtually empty deck and
enclosed superstructure make the new ship look surprisingly like a
21st century edition of the Monitor.
</P>
<P>
   These days, however, the Navy doesn't call the sleek new look a
``cheesebox on a raft'' _ the nickname given to the Monitor. Today,
it's called stealth technology. Inf
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
