<SLUG> BC-TEN-OPEN-DRAW0824-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    U.S. Open draw leaves possibility of all-Williams final
 &HT;    By Todd Holcomb
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Beginning Monday, winners and losers at the U.S. Open will be
decided on the court, but on Wednesday, the luck of the draw had
its way. Venus and Serena Williams got their wishes, while dreams
of a Pete Sampras-Andre Agassi final were shattered.
</P>
<P>
   The Williams sisters, who have lost just one match to other
opponents since Wimbledon, were placed on opposite sides of the
women's bracket in the random-draw selection at the National Tennis
Center.
</P>
<P>
   It keeps open the prospect of the first sister-sister final in
the modern history of the Open.
</P>
<P>
   Serena Williams, the defending U.S. champion but seeded only
fifth, could run into 1999 champ Lindsay Davenport as early as the
quarterfinals.
</P>
<P>
   The news is more disappointing for Davenport, however. The No. 2
seed, who has a sore foot and a five-match losing streak against
Serena, also is seeded to meet Anna Kournikova in the round of 16.
</P>
<P>
   Serena Williams, who has a sore foot of her own, opens against
No. 61 Tina Pisnkik, while Davenport faces No. 30 Gala Leon Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   Venus Williams' path appears easy to the semifinals, where she
could meet No. 1 Martina Hingis. Venus' first match is against No.
32 Anne-Gaelle Sidot. Hingis opens with No. 100 Alina Jidkova.
</P>
<P>
   Also in the women's draw is Atlanta's Ansley Cargill, who got a
favorable draw when matched with another wild-card entry, former
Florida All-American Dawn Buth. Cargill, a new Duke freshman, is
the first Georgia native in a U.S. Open main draw of singles since
Shannan McCarthy in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   On the men's side, Agassi and Sampras are in the same side of
the draw and would meet in the semifinals. Otherwise, the biggest
names in men's tennis had to be pleased with their paths.
</P>
<P>
   Agassi's first match is against NCAA champ Alex Kim of Stanford,
and Sampras faces No. 67 Martin Damm. Both are seeded to face
clay-courters in the round of 16.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the other tournament favorites are on the opposite side
of the draw, including Marat Safin, Alex Corretja, Gustavo Kuerten,
Patrick Rafter, Nicolas Kiefer, Todd Martin and Magnus Norman.
</P>
<P>
   In a qualifying match Wednesday, Melanie Schett of Austria
defeated Jewel Peterson of College Park 6-2, 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
