<HEADLINE>
KENNEDY LIBRARY RELEASES MORE PAPERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TATSHA ROBERTSON  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Thousands of pages of classified material, documenting
foreign policy issues during the Kennedy presidency, were released
Wednesday by the John F. Kennedy Library and Museum.
</P>
<P>
   More than 4,500 documents were opened to the public, including
memos between Kennedy and his National Security Council adviser,
McGeorge Bundy, and US efforts at political subversion in Cuba,
according to Maura Porter, an archivist at the library.
</P>
<P>
   While library officials said the material will provide the
general public with a look into the inner workings of the
government, they expect the information will be far more useful to
historians.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is nothing you could really call ground-breaking but
historians will really enjoy researching it,'' said Porter.
</P>
<P>
   Officials at the library said the disclosure is part of a
massive ``declassification'' effort started in 1995 by President
Clinton. During that time, Clinton ordered all secret documents 25
years and older be reviewed for disclosure.
</P>
<P>
   As a result of that order, the Central Intelligence Agency came
to the Kennedy Library in 1998 with scanners to examine hundreds of
thousands of pages of declassified material.
</P>
<P>
   ``The CIA took the disks and brought them back to Washington to
be reviewed. Other agencies reviewed the disks and the disks were
returned to the library. It's sort of a long process,'' said
Porter.
</P>
<P>
   Since Clinton's 1995 order, more than 600 million pages of
secret documents on subjects ranging from the Cold War to the
failed Bay of Pigs have been released. The information has helped
researchers and historians to rewrite chapters of American history.
</P>
<P>
   Some members of Congress in 1998 slowed down the disclosure
process after they worried classified documents may contain
top-secret information on nuclear weapons. Since then, the federal
government mandated that the CIA scan the documents page by page
for nuclear secrets.
</P>
<P>
   The documents opened Wednesday include memos concerning US
relations with the Dominican Republic, The Congo, Germany, Vietnam,
India, and the Soviet Union. Cables sent from the US Embassy in
Laos to the State Department during the height of the Vietnam War
were also released.
</P>
<P>
   Other documents remain classified, but officials expect more
releases soon.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
