<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPRING-WIRELESS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPRINT PCS TO OFFER FIRMS E-MAIL OVER CELL PHONES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER J. HOWE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sprint PCS plans to become the first wireless carrier to offer
businesses a service giving access to company e-mail systems over
cell phones, reflecting the rapid evolution of the wireless Net
from limited phone ``Web surfing.''
</P>
<P>
   The service, to be launched Sept. 1, will give firms that sign
up for premium Sprint calling plans the capability to give
employees access over their phones to their company Lotus Notes and
Microsoft Outlook e-mail and other corporate software and a popular
airline reservation system.
</P>
<P>
   The move reflects a growing consensus that the first generation
of wireless Net phone offerings, including access to news, weather
forecasts, and stock quotes, is unlikely to be sufficiently
compelling to build a big market.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two things that business customers really want are
connections to the (whole) Internet and connections to their own
network,'' Richard S. Cremona, president of business sales for
Sprint PCS, said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Subscribers with AT&AMP;T Wireless, Nextel, Sprint, and Verizon can
now use Net phones to gain access to e-mail accounts such as
Hotmail and Yahoo or special accounts with the phone company.
</P>
<P>
   A number of start-ups have launched services giving wireless
phone access through security ``firewalls'' to corporate computer
networks, but Sprint contends it is the first carrier to promote a
service directly in that market.
</P>
<P>
   Besides access to the most popular company e-mail systems, the
service will also link to Siebel Systems sales management software
and the Sabre airline reservation system, allowing subscribers to
use the phone to book flights and hotel and car rental
reservations.
</P>
<P>
   The cost per employee using the system is $40 a month for
unlimited usage as long as they have a voice calling plan costing
at least $50 a month. Companies would typically have to pay $40 to
$60 a year per employee to Lotus or Microsoft for a special
wireless-access license to the e-mail system.
</P>
<P>
   Howie Waterman, a spokesman for Verizon Wireless, said his
company has been able for more than three years to offer companies
wireless access to corporate networks through laptops and hand-held
devices, ``but we haven't found many business customers who want to
go through the phone.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If customers want it, we can get it for them, so in some ways
Sprint is just coming late to the wireless data party with a
slightly different marketing tack,'' Waterman said.
</P>
<P>
   Gaugarin Oliver, vice president of marketing for Ultiverse, a
Waltham, Mass. start-up offering wireless access to company
networks, said the Sprint announcement is ``good for the industry
as a whole,'' promoting awareness of capabilities for wireless
phone access.
</P>
<P>
   Oliver said he believes there will still be a big market for
companies that want to provide wireless access without limiting
their employees to one carrier. Ultiverse's system can also offer
access to a unified mailbox with voice mail and faxes blended in
with e-mail, something Sprint does not now offer.
</P>
<P>
   In October, Cremona said, Sprint will also offer a $400 wireless
connection device for laptops that, with special ``compression''
software installed at business sites, can provide the equivalent of
56 kilobit per second Internet access.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
