<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAFFEINE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAFFEINE: IS IT THE ``NEW NICOTINE'' ?
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By SCOTT SIMONSON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
The alarm goes off; you stumble out of bed. And before you grab
your toothbrush or let the dog out, you grab a hot cuppa joe. It's
your morning wake-up call.
<TEXT>
<P>
   By midafternoon you're restless and headachy. You grab a crisp
dollar and head to the pop machine for your ``fix.''
</P>
<P>
   It's caffeine, and it seems harmless enough (in moderation, of
course). But could caffeine _ as headlines indicated recently _ be
America's ``newest nicotine''?
</P>
<P>
   Johns Hopkins Institute researchers suggested that caffeine in
soda pop is the equivalent of nicotine in tobacco _ an additive
intended to ``hook'' consumers. They published the results of
research in August's Archives of Family medicine, a publication of
the American Medical Association.
</P>
<P>
   One of the study's authors was quoted calling caffeine ``a
mildly addictive, mood-altering drug, one which accounts for the
fact that people drink far more sodas with caffeine than without.''
</P>
<P>
   The soft drink industry's reply can be roughly summarized as
``hogwash.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is simply incorrect to compare caffeine with the effects of
serious drug abuse,'' said Jeff Nedelman, a spokesman for the
National Soft Drink Association.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the dispute, the public's response seemed to be a
collective ``pour me another pop.''
</P>
<P>
   But what exactly is caffeine? What does it do, and why do we
love it so? And despite what scientists say, are all of those
caffeine lovers out there really addicted?
</P>
<P>
   ``The basic thing is that it's the world's most widely used
psychoactive drug, and has been for thousands of years,'' said G.
Ken Goodrick, a psychologist at Baylor College of Medicine in
Houston. ``And if used in moderation, there's nothing wrong with
that.''
</P>
<P>
   This is one nation under caffeination.
</P>
<P>
   The average American adult drinks 54.5 gallons of soft drinks
per year. For every 16-ounce bottle of water consumed, Americans
drink the equivalent of a 64-ounce soda, according to the soft
drink association.
</P>
<P>
   The fastest-growing soft drink in 1999 was Mountain Dew, which
has the highest caffeine content among major brands.
</P>
<P>
   Caffeine occurs naturally in coffee beans and tea leaves. It
tastes slightly bitter, and a synthetic version traditionally has
been used as flavoring in soft drinks and chocolate.
</P>
<P>
   It can produce a short-term increase in energy. Caffeine
triggers a reward response from the brain, Goodrick said, but it
comes from a different part of the brain than the one affected by
drugs like cocaine.
</P>
<P>
   Caffeine also is a diuretic, which accelerates dehydration.
Caffeine stimulates production of stomach acids. In large quantity,
it can cause restlessness, insomnia or irregular heartbeat, not to
mention disqualification from the Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   And while the scientific consensus is that caffeine doesn't
qualify as an addictive drug, habitual users can experience
withdrawal symptoms. Headaches can occur, along with restlessness
or insomnia.
</P>
<P>
   Douglas Fleckman, a certified clinical nutritionist for Whole
Health Associates in Houston, said clients who drink three or four
sodas a day can feel immediate effects if they stop drinking
caffeine.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally, when we pull the sugar and caffeine, it's almost
like a withdrawal,'' Fleckman said. ``They don't have that joie de
vivre, that push or that charge.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that people with low energy should change their diet to
gain more energy from fuels like carbohydrates, instead of
resorting to caffeine.
</P>
<P>
   Goodrick, an avowed coffee drinker whose 1999 book ``Energy,
Peace, Purpose'' talks about ways to find energy without caffeine,
said people should avoid more than three cups of coffee per day.
That's equal to about 72 ounces of soda. To get off caffeine
without headaches, he said, reduce caffeine intake by one serving
per week.
</P>
<P>
   ``My advice is moderation, and be sure you select quality
beans,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
