<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATRIOTS NEED HELP AT TIGHT END 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FOXBOROUGH, Mass. _ Maybe the Patriots are holding back their
tight end game. Maybe Eric Bjornson is about to turn into a
pass-catching machine and big Rod Rutledge will turn from blocker
to pass catcher extraordinaire starting with Thursday night's final
exhibition game against the Carolina Panthers.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe the true star is Harvard's Chris Eitzmann, who grew up
playing seven-man football in Nebraska.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, but unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   After four preseason games, there's been nary a glimpse of
anyone being able to hold up the franchise's legacy for tight ends.
Bjornson, Rutledge, and Eitzmann have two receptions total. Such
stats pale before the legacy of players like Ben Coates, a
five-time All-Pro in the 1990's; Marv Cook, an effective player
prior to Coates's tenure, and 1970's stars like Don Hasselbeck and
Russ Francis.
</P>
<P>
   Tight end has become the lost position in New England. The War
Room, a publication in which NFL scouts rate every player, team,
and position, ranked the Patriots 25th out of 31 teams at tight
end. The Patriots also received poor grades at running back (29),
defensive line (29), and offensive line (31).
</P>
<P>
   While the Patriots thought Coates's career was over and that
they'd easily be able to replace his 32 catches, that may now be
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   ``Neither of us has done much so far,'' said Rutledge.
``Basically, we've been concentrating on our blocking.''
</P>
<P>
   Rutledge has been typecast as a blocker, but Coates always
thought that with work, Rutledge could become something more.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he had a lot of balls thrown his way, he'd get better and
better,'' said Coates. ``He's big and strong and he runs alright.
Keep throwing it to him and he might develop into a good tight
end.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether that commitment will be made by the coaching staff
remains to be seen. Bjornson is the more nimble _ an H-back type
who can be set into motion, split wide, and look more like a
receiver as he draws one-on-one coverage with linebackers and
sometimes safeties. On paper, Bjornson could be a decent pass
receiver. But he needs to get open. The veteran dropped a clear
touchdown pass in the end zone during the game against the Detroit
Lions, and since then hasn't had many balls thrown his way.
</P>
<P>
   Rutledge is playing a pure tight end position, on the line as a
blocker when the Patriots are trying to run the ball. But he'd like
more opportunities to act as a receiver.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a new experience for me and I'm trying to learn as
much as I can,'' said Rutledge. ``They've asked me to help control
the line of scrimmage and I've been happy to do that, but I'd also
like to touch the football.''
</P>
<P>
   There's been some school of thought that coordinator Charlie
Weis's offense doesn't incorporate the tight end as much as other
team's schemes, but that can only be true if he feels he doesn't
have enough talent at the position. Weis coached Coates when he
caught 94 passes to set the NFL season record for tight ends.
</P>
<P>
   Weis understands that the tight end can bail the quarterback out
of tough spots. He's seen the chemistry between Coates and Bledsoe
over the years. Having a tight end who can be a threat opens the
field for the outside receivers, but the Patriots aren't showing
any of that capability. Also helping the tight end get open would
be the threat of the quarterback being able to dump the ball off to
the fullback. Tony Carter is capable of catching the ball, but that
hasn't happened much, either.
</P>
<P>
   Rutledge was a second-round draft choice out of Alabama, and the
experts have said that Rutledge shouldn't have been picked that
high because he was one-dimensional, clumsy, and lacked
concentration.
</P>
<P>
   But Rutledge was ranked in the top five tight ends in the 1998
draft class which also included Alonzo Mayes, Stephen Alexander,
Cam Cleeland, and Blake Spence, who was recently released by the
New York Jets. None of them have set the world on fire. Alexander
and Cleeland have been hamepered by numerous injuries, while Mayes
has been an uninspired backup for the Bears and Spence had served
mostly a special-teams player the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   The rap on Bjornson has been that he runs average routes and
doesn't do enough to get himself open. Also, his lack of bulk has
always paid a part in his inability, at times, to get off the line
of scrimmage.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots also took a blow when they couldn't get fifth-round
pick Dave Stachelski to play because of physical and personal
problems, eventually releasing him. Stachelski has since hooked up
with the New Orleans Saints, which lost Cleeland to a season-ending
injury.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the league is weak at the position, which is why Ozzie
Newsome, one of the greatest tight ends in NFL history and now the
vice president of player personnel with the Baltimore Ravens,
signed Shannon Sharpe and Coates.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots thought that Coates's skills had diminished to the
point where he was no longer worthy of his $2.5 million paycheck, a
smart move if the team had found suitable replacement(s) or had
sought to reduce his salary.
</P>
<P>
   The chances of the Patriots having the complete tight end again
is slim, but most teams face that. They have either a good
receiving tight end or good blocking tight end. Tony Gonzalez and
Rickey Dudley types are few and far between.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots can only wish they had a right end named Rod
Bjornson.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
