<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 19:12 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0294 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-NY-SUBWAY-OBSESSION-A     08-23 0994
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SUBWAY-OBSESSION-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR BOGUS SUBWAY WORKER, ANOTHER EXPRESS TRIP FROM FANTASY WORLD TO
JAIL 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT6 was sent Tuesday to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DEAN E. MURPHY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ If Darius McCollum were a millionaire, he might be
excused as an eccentric. If he were a genius, allowances probably
would be made as well. But McCollum is neither. And his unusual
problem _ his obsession, as he calls it _ has gotten him in so much
trouble that people aren't even laughing anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Since he was a high school freshman, McCollum, who grew up in
Queens and is now 35, has been in and out of jail for masquerading
as a New York City transit worker. He is back behind bars, for the
19th time in as many years, on charges that he pulled a subway
emergency brake during rush hour and then, dressed for the part,
came to the rescue as a phony transit supervisor.
</P>
<P>
   Though little known outside the underground world he craves,
McCollum is the transit agency's biggest personal headache. Police
say his shenanigans are dangerous and have distributed his picture
to thousands of subway and bus workers with a stern warning: Be on
the lookout. He has a sprawling rap sheet and has spent five years
in prison. Still McCollum refuses to be just a passenger.
</P>
<P>
   Even in a city of quirky people, the authorities say, McCollum
stands out, so expert at his chosen quirkiness that he has
repeatedly fooled riders, subway employees and police into
believing he belongs in transit blues. At wit's end, his elderly
parents have turned to a lawyer who is bent on proving that
McCollum is not in his right mind. A done deal with the city's No.
1 subway nut? No one is expecting an easy ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not insane,'' McCollum said recently in an interview at
the Rikers Island jail. ``I am just your average guy who doesn't
mind helping out. To tell you the truth, I wish they would just put
me to work on the trains. It would be a lot easier.''
</P>
<P>
   Take a careful look. That self-satisfied smile is the only
giveaway. You may know him as Manning or Morning, two of his most
engaging personas, who, with a friendly wave and knowing nod, have
driven off with city buses and transit agency trucks. He first got
caught at the controls of a subway train at the age of 15, picking
up passengers at the World Trade Center before he had ever sat
behind the wheel of an automobile.
</P>
<P>
   He has signed out two-way radios and cheerfully collected fares
at ticket booths. (The radios have always been returned, and never
has a penny gone missing from the till; his most costly blunder was
leaving a commuter bus with a flat tire, police say). He has
cleared debris from tracks and put out fires. He has glad-handed
commuters in full uniform and has even reported sick to the transit
authority's infirmary to get aspirin for a headache.
</P>
<P>
   At last count, McCollum had the keys to three crew lockers at
subway buildings, where he has kept everything from protective
goggles to mud guards for his boots, all official transit agency
issue. If someone questions his credentials, McCollum not only
flashes an identity badge (he says he found it) but he produces a
letter of authorization on official stationery (he admits to
writing it himself, but insists the paper was a gift).
</P>
<P>
   When police are in hot pursuit, as they have been on nearly two
dozen occasions, his favorite hideout is at the transit agency
headquarters in Brooklyn. He exudes the confidence of someone who
belongs there, and it is usually the last place the police think to
look.
</P>
<P>
   ``How can I describe it?'' McCollum said. ``It is one of those
things, I guess I want to be seen, to get attention toward me. I
like the activity. I like the noise. I like the people. I like the
people who work there. There is not something that I can say I like
the most. I like everything involved with it. I like the
operations. I like the scenery. I like the schedules.''
</P>
<P>
   McCollum is in custody awaiting trial on a host of charges,
including criminal impersonation. If found guilty, it will be his
sixth felony conviction, according to correction officials, all
related in one way or another to play-acting as a transit worker.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer, Tracey Bloodsaw, says McCollum needs help. He has
been living in a ``fake world'' and nobody has bothered to do
anything about it, she says. She has filed notice with the state
Supreme Court in Manhattan that she intends to fight the latest
charges with an insanity defense, the first time his state of mind
has been raised as an explanation for his behavior, she said.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't think he is doing anything wrong,'' Bloodsaw said.
</P>
<P>
   Why nobody has offered such an argument before is anyone's
guess. A spokesman for New York City Transit, the unit of the
Metropolitan Transportation Authority. that operates the city's
buses and subways, would not comment. A police official familiar
with his cases said ``something is wrong'' with McCollum, but ``it
is not like he has a condition where he needs to be medicated or
anything like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Bloodsaw blames indifference on the part of McCollum's previous
court-appointed lawyers and the judicial system bureaucracy. ``They
just screwed up,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   McCollum, though skeptical, says insanity is worth a try. He was
twice admitted to a psychiatric hospital as a child, according to
records kept by his family, but he is lucid and articulate and
knows how to chat up just about everyone. He serves on an inmate
grievance committee at Riker's Island and volunteers to do typing
and other work for a variety of prison programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to admit what this guy does is kind of wacky, but he
is very much on the ball,'' said an official with the City
Department of Correction.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Most judges have considered McCollum more of a curiosity than a
menace. During one sentence hearing, he said, the judge joked that
he would like McCollum as his chauffeur. On another occasion,
McCollum said he got rave reviews when he appeared in court in full
transit uniform.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know she is going to ask me that question, about why I do
this,'' McCollum said of Justice Carol Berkman, who is hearing the
current case. ``I will have to come up with something the best I
can. I will say, `Listen, I have an obsession with trains.' That is
just it.''
</P>
<P>
   In the most recent incident, on Feb. 21, the authorities say,
McCollum dressed up in transit blues and tripped the emergency
switch at the 57th Street station, bringing a Queens-bound train to
a screeching stop. He then went down on the track to sort out the
mess, which, as in his previous escapades, caused no injuries but
plenty of consternation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has been doing this for so long that he knows all the
terminology and he knows how to operate the equipment,'' said Sgt.
Jack Cassidy, who heads police investigations of transit crimes.
``Honestly, just looking at him, you'd think he was an employee.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The truth, however, is that McCollum has never held a steady
job. He says he has applied to the transit agency, but his name
does not appear on any Civil Service lists. He once volunteered as
a tour guide at the transit museum in Brooklyn, but was let go when
police figured out who he was and became concerned that he would be
inclined to take exhibits on he road.
</P>
<P>
   ``He called me up and begged me to get that job back,'' Cassidy
said.
</P>
<P>
   Transit officials say there are umpteen train buffs who on
occasion break the law, but none with the repeat compulsion that
drives McCollum. His arrest in February came just six weeks after
he was released from state prison for a previous offense, taking a
joy ride in a transit agency vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   McCollum has been in custody 17 times in the last 15 years, city
correction officials say. He has also served in state prisons in
New York and North Carolina, where his parents moved 10 years ago
and where McCollum once stole a car to sneak back to New York.
Samuel and Elizabeth McCollum have given up posting bail for their
only child. His fiancee, Nelly Rodriguez, a clothing designer from
Ecuador who met McCollum on a subway platform in January, has
called off their intended nuptials because there is no telling when
he will be free again.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can't let him out,'' said Samuel McCollum, 79. ``He is
like an alcoholic or a drug addict. He has to first admit that he
has a problem. Until he does that, we can't help him.''
</P>
<P>
   At first, the train thing seemed funny. As a teen-ager, McCollum
ended up in family court in 1981 for taking the controls of a
subway train for six stops from 34th Street to the World Trade
Center. In the days that followed, so many reporters and camera
crews staked out his home in Jamaica, Queens, that the boy missed a
week of school.
</P>
<P>
   McCollum said the trip was ``really very routine for me''
because he had been driving trains in the rail yards since he was
12.
</P>
<P>
   ``It came to a point, where on different occasions, people would
come to me and would say, `Want to cover the yard for me?' I would
say, `Cool.'''
</P>
<P>
   Elizabeth McCollum said she was advised at the time not to talk
about her son's troubled childhood, but her calendar from January
1981, which she still keeps in a dog-eared manila folder, speaks
volumes about his torment. Thursday, the 29th, is clearly marked as
the day Darius drove the E train. But the rest of the tiny boxes
are also scribbled in, 14 of them with the word ``OUT.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Those are the days Darius did not come home,'' Mrs. McCollum
explained. ``He would run right down there into the subway. I would
go down there and look for him, but the workers would say he wasn't
there. But he was there.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. McCollum was right, said a former track worker who left a
transit job two years ago on a disability pension. The man
described McCollum as more Boy Scout than criminal, someone always
looking to do a good deed.
</P>
<P>
   ``He never felt part of anything, and people in transit made him
feel welcome,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. McCollum said that her son always had trouble fitting in at
school, but that his troubles spiraled out of control when, at 10,
he was stabbed in the back with a pair of scissors by a student in
his special education class. Darius became so frightened, she said,
that he would sit at a desk only if his back was against the wall.
</P>
<P>
   The McCollums sued the Board of Education for negligence over
the stabbing but lost. They tried a half-dozen schools, including a
military academy. He also got therapy and psychiatric treatment.
But nothing helped. After class, Darius would descend into the
subways. By 10th grade, he had dropped out.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is a good kid,'' McCollum said. ``He doesn't drink. He
doesn't smoke. He doesn't gamble. His thing is to go down into that
subway system. In his mind, he is still 15 driving that train.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
