<SLUG> BC-PEDOPHILE-VERDICT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FAMILY WINS $328M VERDICT AGAINST PAIR WHO KILLED SON 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RALPH RANALLI  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ A jury has awarded the family of Jeffrey Curley, the
10-year-old Cambridge boy raped and smothered by two men, a
stunning $328 million in their wrongful death suit against the
boy's killers.
</P>
<P>
   In practical terms, the award is little more than a moral
victory, since neither man convicted of the murder, Salvatore
Sicari or Charles Jaynes, has any assets to speak of, the Curley
family's lawyer said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, as probably the largest award ever in the United States
for the wrongful death of a murdered child, attorney Lawrence
Frisoli said, it sends an ``important'' message to other
pedophiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a measuring stick by which to judge people who rape
kids and get caught,'' Frisoli said. ``We can't stop pedophiles
from raping children, but we can make it harder on them.''
</P>
<P>
   The Curley family, which spent an emotionally-wrenching day on
the witness stand Tuesday testifying about how they have dealt with
their son's murder, was not in the Cambridge courtroom for the
verdict and declined comment afterward.
</P>
<P>
   But Frisoli said they were ``grateful'' to the Middlesex County
jury for the symbolic gesture and were ``ready to fight on'' in
their $200 million federal lawsuit against the North American
Man/Boy Love Association, a group which the family blames for
inciting and nurturing Jaynes' obsession with Jeffrey Curley.
</P>
<P>
   The scene in the courtroom as the verdict was read was surreal,
given the magnitude of the award. Neither the family nor the
defendants were in the courtroom. And Jaynes' attorney -- who was
told by his client to essentially offer no meaningful defense in
order to ``make it easier'' on the Curley family -- actually
praised the verdict.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a statement to deter future conduct by others,''
attorney Robert Bonsignore said of the jury award. ``This is an
example of how the justice system can affect positive societal
change.''
</P>
<P>
   Bonsignore, who accepted a court appointment to the case from
Superior Court Judge Allen van Gestel to represent Jayne's
interests, refused payment. Sicari, who has appealed his
first-degree murder conviction, essentially ignored the civil case
altogether.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the jurors left through a side entrance of the
courthouse without commenting, but one female juror stopped long
enough to describe the verdict as ``self-explanatory,'' given the
horrifying testimony and evidence they saw during the two-day
trial.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors heard how Sicari and Jaynes lured the boy into their car
with the promise of a new bike, tried to molest him, then smothered
him by stuffing a gasoline-soaked rag into his mouth and sitting on
him after he fought their advances.
</P>
<P>
   They then brought the boy up to New Hampshire, had sex with his
lifeless body, and then dumped his body in a river in Maine, police
witnesses said.
</P>
<P>
   Jurors were shown the 50-gallon Rubbermaid storage container
Curley's body was stuffed in and an underwater police videotape of
the plastic coffin being recovered from the river bottom.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm sure people can use their own imaginations about why we
came up with the decision we did,'' said the juror, who asked not
to be identified.
</P>
<P>
   The jury awarded Robert and Barbara Curley and their surviving
sons, Robert Jr., 22, and Shaun, 20, a total of $128 million for
pain and suffering and loss of consortium, and $200 million in
punitive damages.
</P>
<P>
   Technically, Jaynes, a 25-year-old from Brockton, and Sicari,
24, of Cambridge, now owe the Curley's $164 million each, but
neither has any money, Frisoli said. Both are serving life terms,
although Jaynes will eventually be eligible for parole on his
second-degree murder conviction.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no money to get,'' the family's attorney said. The
real importance of the verdict, he said, will be its affect on the
federal lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   Frisoli said the family cannot stop NAMBLA from advocating for
changes in the laws governing sex with children, but will now press
in federal court for an injuction barring NAMBLA from ``telling
people how to get around the laws'' protecting children from
pornography and sexual assault.
</P>
<P>
   The large damage award is important, he said, because it
``quantifies the family's loss'' for the federal lawsuit. Frisoli
said the Curleys now hope that a large award against NAMBLA in
federal court will effectively shut the organization down in the
same way pro-choice groups forced the founder of Operation Rescue
into bankrupcty with civil damage awards.
</P>
<P>
   Telephone calls to a NAMBLA answering service in New York City
went unanswered Wednesday. A recording described the group as an
organization that ``speaks out against societal oppression and
celebrates the joy of men and boys in love'' and is ``serious about
empowering all people to love those to whom their hearts lead.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
