u i BC-BRITAIN-NEWTON-PAPERS     08-23 0747
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRITAIN-NEWTON-PAPERS-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMBRIDGE SEEKS DONATIONS TO PURCHASE COLLECTION OF NEWTON'S
PAPERS 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALAN COWELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Cambridge University opened a campaign Wednesday to
keep the papers of its alumnus Sir Isaac Newton in Britain, seeking
donations to prevent part of the scientist's legacy from falling
prey to the gravitational pull of outside buyers and market forces
as powerful as the natural laws he chronicled.
</P>
<P>
   At issue is the privately owned Macclesfield Newton Collection,
an assemblage of letters, notebooks and autographed texts relating
to Sir Isaac's work on calculus, optics, mathematics and gravity.
The collection, held by the Macclesfield family since the 18th
century, complements a Newtonian archive that has been at
Cambridge's University Library since 1872.
</P>
<P>
   The current Earl of Macclesfield _ the ninth _ is offering to
sell the collection, through Sotheby's, to Cambridge University for
around $9.56 million. Britain's National Lottery has offered to put
up three quarters of the cost. The remaining quarter, $2.39
million, needs to be covered by the university, which is seeking
benefactors to foot the bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we can't raise this money, the danger is that the
collection might go abroad and be split amongst private collectors,
which would be a tragedy for scholars and a great loss for the
nation as a whole,'' said Peter Fox, the Cambridge University
librarian.
</P>
<P>
   In a joint statement, Cambridge and Sotheby's called the
collection ``arguably the most important and valuable collection of
scientific papers in private hands in Britain.''
</P>
<P>
   To reinforce the campaign, Cambridge has enlisted a string of
supporters ranging from Carol Vorderman, a television game-show
presenter with a vaunted gift for mathematics, to professor Stephen
Hawking, who holds the same Lucasian chair at Cambridge that Newton
secured in 1669. ``These papers are important to show how his ideas
developed,'' Hawking said. ``Science doesn't appear out of the
blue. It's a series of steps.''
</P>
<P>
   Lord Macclesfield is selling the collection to raise money to
maintain his family seat and its art collections at Shirburn Castle
in Oxfordshire, according to Sotheby's. He said in a statement that
Cambridge _ where Newton first studied in 1661 _ was ``clearly the
best place'' for the archive.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Quarrie, the senior specialist in Sotheby's book
department, said the collection was donated to the Macclesfield
family in the 18th century by William Jones, an astronomer who had
acquired them from a friend of Newton. He said the collection
comprised ``some bound volumes of letters,'' notebooks and loose
papers. ``The most valuable are 50-plus letters and a great number
of autographed documents'' dealing with calculus and gravity, he
said. Until now, Quarrie said, the collection had been kept ``in a
cupboard'' at the Earl of Macclesfield's home.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Newton's contribution to science lay particularly in his laws of
motion, which established the modern science of mechanics, gravity
and calculus. His discoveries were challenged by 20th-century
science, notably by Einstein's theories of relativity, but are
still held to be valid for most purposes.
</P>
<P>
   Cambridge is especially keen to obtain the collection because it
already holds the Portsmouth Collection, presented by the fifth
Earl of Portsmouth in 1872, and the two archives complement one
another. ``Many of the letters included in the Portsmouth archive
have their replies among the documents held by the Earl of
Macclesfield,'' Cambridge University said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
   The Portsmouth collection was initially handed over to the
university part as a gift and part as a loan. The Portsmouth family
put the loaned papers up for auction at Sotheby's in 1936, and
Cambridge bought the bulk of them back, according to Sotheby's. The
present sale of the Macclesfield collection is the most important
transaction involving a privately-owned scientific archive since
then, according to Quarrie.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Chris Hesketh, a fund-raiser at Cambridge, said the university
was looking for a small number of private benefactors _ or possibly
a single benefactor _ in Britain or the United States to support
the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Sotheby's said it had set an unspecified time limit for
Cambridge to raise its share of the money but, Quarrie said, `'we
are not going to quibble over a month or two.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
