<SLUG> BC-FILM-BRING-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
``BRING IT ON'' IS A ROUSING SLICE OF EXUBERANT HIGH-SCHOOL LIFE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BRUCE WESTBROOK 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
After so many mundane and miserable teen movies _ from slasher
flicks to guy-meets-chick _ cynical disdain may await ``Bring It
On,'' yet another comedy about high school high jinks.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Yet this film stands out _ not as an original (its focus on
fierce competition is nothing new), but as a well-executed story
with likable characters and fresh flourishes.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of the cliche-littered sports arena, ``Bring It On''
concerns those who bounce, bound and cheer jocks on: cheerleaders.
</P>
<P>
   Yet cheerleading itself is considered a sport, especially in
this affectionate film, which resists the notion that cheerleaders
are vain airheads.
</P>
<P>
   The peppy kids at upscale Rancho Carne High in San Diego aren't
just leading yells for their lousy football team. They're five-time
national champs in cheerleading competition, which involves not
just school spirit, but inventive choreography and tough
gymnastics.
</P>
<P>
   The Toros' new captain is Torrance (Kirsten Dunst), a
good-hearted girl who wisely recruits sullen transfer student Missy
(Eliza Dushku of ``Buffy the Vampire Slayer''), a top gymnast,
while fending off power plays by Heatheresque girls in the group.
</P>
<P>
   But her chief rivals turn out to be 100 miles away: an
ethnically diverse squad from Los Angeles, embittered because
Torrance's predecessor stole their routines.
</P>
<P>
   Led by prideful captain Isis (Gabrielle Union), the underdog
Clovers are naturally destined to meet the Toros in competition.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, director Peyton Reed doesn't play this for an
inflated sense of inspiration. Both squads have flaws, and
tunnel-visioned drive is arguably one of them.
</P>
<P>
   We also see cheerleading from the other side, via Missy's
brother (Jesse Bradford), a rocker-intellectual who sneers at
cheers.
</P>
<P>
   Torrance's sibling (Cody McMains) shares his perspective, and he
does his little-brother duty by mocking sis with hearty enthusiasm.
</P>
<P>
   But largely, this is a happy teen fantasy, marked by the usual
wealth trappings and almost utter absence of parents.
</P>
<P>
   Besides bolstering cheerleaders' image, screenwriter Jessica
Bendinger has an ear for witty youthful repartee. Her dialogue
often adopts the wordplay of cheers and is combative without being
mean-spirited.
</P>
<P>
   In such ways, ``Bring It On'' avoids the tiresome belligerence
of so many teen movies. Its infighting subsides in the face of team
spirit, and the film settles into the more manageable rivalry
between the Toros and Clovers.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, Torrance hires a choreographer (Ian Roberts) for
fresh material. Branding his charges ``sweater monkeys,'' he's a
crazed, abrasive and hilarious Bob Fosse-wannabe who steals the
show.
</P>
<P>
   But so do the crisp, elaborate and highly athletic routines. In
tone and execution, ``Bring It On'' plays like a recruitment film
for the cult of cheerleading.
</P>
<P>
   Dunst, 18, was a cheerleader in high school, and it shows. But
beyond making the moves, she has smiling good spirits atop a
grounded grasp of reality.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the former child star of ``Interview With the Vampire''
has grown up to be a lovable actress. Known for her professionalism
on the set, on screen Dunst radiates warmth, girlish femininity and
a spry sense of fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bring It On'' (meaning: put your best foot forward) also
injects a budding romance between Dunst and Bradford. They adore
from a distance, sharing a weird courtship ritual while brushing
their teeth and locking eyes from the stands at a game.
</P>
<P>
   That prompts one girl to taunt, ``Don't play dumb. You're having
cheerleader sex with him.''
</P>
<P>
   But the boy-girl maneuvers are minimized, and sex is brushed
over.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, ``Bring It On'' is a rousing slice of exuberant
high-school life, played with enough energy, spirit and sassy
attitude to make any cheerleader proud _ and perhaps to make jaded
viewers cheer, not jeer. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``Bring It On'' &QL; 
Starring: Kirsten Dunst &QL; 
Rating: PG-13, for sex-related material and language &QL; 
Running time: 100 minutes &QL; 
Grade: B+  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   X X X END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-00 1916EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
