u w BC-RENO-GORE-HNS &LR;      08-23 1159
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RENO-GORE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO WON'T NAME SPECIAL COUNSEL TO PROBE GORE'S 1996 CAMPAIGN
ACTIVITIES 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By STEVE LASH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Attorney General Janet Reno said Wednesday that she
will not name a special counsel to examine Al Gore's 1996 campaign
activities, prompting Republicans to suggest the American voters
would have the final say on his credibility.
</P>
<P>
   Defending her decision, Reno said her own review of the vice
president's comments to investigators gave no indication that he
was untruthful when he denied knowing that a Buddhist temple event
and White House coffees were fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's fund-raising in 1996 had been at the center of a lengthy
political storm and resurfaced when he began his drive to become
the Democrats' presidential nominee this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because further investigation is not likely to result in a
prosecutable case under applicable criminal law and principles of
federal prosecution, I have concluded that a special counsel is not
warranted,'' Reno said. ``I've concluded that there is no
reasonable possibility that the further investigation could develop
evidence that would support the filing of charges (against Gore)
for making a willful false statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, locked in a tight race against Republican Texas Gov.
George W. Bush, said through a spokesman that he was ``pleased''
with Reno's decision _ the third time she has rejected an internal
Justice Department call for an independent investigation of the
vice president's 1996 fund-raising activities.
</P>
<P>
   ``Al Gore is going to keep doing what he has been doing all
along,'' said spokesman Chris Lehane, referring to the vice
president's focus on education, social security and other national
issues. ``It's illuminating that Republicans seem more interested
in talking about this than George W. Bush's tax-cut plan.''
</P>
<P>
   But Bush, dismissing Reno's decision, said Gore continues to be
marred by scandal.
</P>
<P>
   ``While it's clear that Al Gore engaged in a number of
questionable fund-raising activities and gave the FBI statements
that continue to raise the issue of his credibility, the American
people are sick and tired of all these scandals and
investigations,'' Bush said. ``The best way to put all these
scandals and investigations behind us is to elect someone new. I'm
running to uphold the honor and dignity of the White House.''
</P>
<P>
   With her decision, Reno rejected calls from Robert Conrad, the
department's chief investigator of campaign abuses, that she name
an independent, outside counsel to investigate Gore.
</P>
<P>
   But Reno said she concluded last weekend that an outside inquiry
is unnecessary after reading a transcript of Gore's April 18
interview with federal investigators. Naming a special counsel to
review such flimsy evidence of lying would violate the American
concept of justice, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This goes to the heart of everything we care about in this
country: that you don't pursue a case where there is no basis for
concluding that you can make a case,'' the attorney general said.
``You don't put people through an investigation where you don't ...
think that you can find the evidence that would justify further
action.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno has rebuffed similar requests for a special counsel to
investigate fund-raising calls Gore made from his office and
whether he truthfully told investigators that he thought the money
raised was for general Democratic purposes and not for President
Clinton's 1996 re-election, which would be illegal under federal
law.
</P>
<P>
   Reno reiterated that her decisions not to name special counsels
were motivated solely by the facts and law and not by any desire to
prevent embarrassment to Gore and his presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't do things based on politics,'' Reno said. ``I realize
that politics will be hurled around my head. I just sit there and
duck as it comes and continue to look at the evidence and the law
and make the best judgment I can after consultation with as many
people as possible who have relevant information.''
</P>
<P>
   While Conrad's call for an outside investigator was shared by
many in the department, Reno said many other aides were just as
forceful in arguing that an independent inquiry was unnecessary.
</P>
<P>
   But Reno's spirited defense of her decision drew sharp criticism
from Republican senators who have strongly opposed her refusal to
name special counsels to investigate alleged Democratic
fund-raising abuses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Janet Reno has steadfastly refused to follow the
recommendations of her career law enforcement officers and allow an
independent investigation of high-ranking administration
officials,'' said Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., who chaired Senate
hearings on alleged campaign improprieties. ``There was never any
reason to believe that she would do any differently in this case.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., a frequent and outspoken critic of
Reno, said the attorney general's refusal to name an outside
investigator ``flies in the face of strong evidence'' that Gore
knew the California temple event and coffees were fund-raisers.
</P>
<P>
   Specter said he would not call for a congressional investigation
of Reno's decision until after the presidential election in
November, saying such an inquiry now would ``politicize'' the
important issues of whether an attorney general can ever conduct an
unbiased investigation of administration officials.
</P>
<P>
   ``As to what happens to Mr. Gore, we will leave it to the voters
to decide the issue of the vice president's honesty,'' Specter
said.
</P>
<P>
   Political donations by religious organizations are illegal under
federal law. The Hsi Lai Temple luncheon netted more than $65,000
in illegal donations for the Democratic Party, federal
investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   When news of Conrad's recommendation that Reno name an outside
counsel surfaced in June, Gore quickly released a 124-page
transcript of his occasionally rancorous interview with federal
investigators.
</P>
<P>
   Gore at one point told the investigators that prior to his
temple visit he ``sure as hell did not have any conversations''
that would indicate it was to be a fund-raising event. ``I still do
not know that any funds, that any money changed hands there,'' Gore
said.
</P>
<P>
   With regard to the coffees, Gore said he understood the events
to be merely friendly get-togethers that might be followed by
Democratic Party requests that those in attendance contribute to
the party.
</P>
<P>
   Conrad's campaign-finance investigation is continuing, the
Justice Department said.
</P>
<P>
   To date, Conrad's task force has prosecuted 25 people outside
the administration for alleged fund-raising violations. In March,
Maria Hsia, who helped organize Gore's visit to the temple, was
convicted of hiding $109,000 in illegal contributions and causing
false statements to be made to the Federal Election Commission.
</P>
<P>
   She awaits sentencing next month.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
