<HEADER>
A0304 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-UN-PEACEKEEPING-BOS &LR;      08-23 1194
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UN-PEACEKEEPING-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UN CRITIZICED FOR PEACEKEEPING METHODS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   United Nations peacekeeping operations failed abjectly
throughout the 1990s due to wishful thinking, poor strategic
planning, and insufficient use of force, senior international
peacekeepers and relief officials reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   As their report was submitted, the United Nations was forced to
suspend some of its operations on the strife-torn south Asian
island of Timor after Indonesian militias attacked peacekeepers
with machetes and terrorized the occupants of West Timor refugee
camps the United Nations was supposed to be protecting.
</P>
<P>
   Two peacekeepers have been killed in the Timor operations, and
militias are operating with growing boldness in the border region
between West Timor, which is part of Indonesia, and the former
Dutch colony of East Timor, which voted for independence in
UN-sponsored balloting a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's setbacks in Timor underscored the findings of the
international panel that the UN, namely that the world organization
has not learned the lessons of its disgraces and defeats in Bosnia,
Rwanda, and Sierra Leone _ all places where inept or impotent UN
forces contributed to the deaths of innocents.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a major red flag to member states,'' said J. Brian
Atwood, former head of the US Agency for International Development
and the only American on the panel. ``The job (of peacekeeping) is
not being done. We're saying if it can't be done well, don't
attempt it at all.''
</P>
<P>
   The most profound change advocated by the panel was that the
United Nations discard its traditional neutral posture in
situations with clear victims and aggressors. Reluctance to do this
was a major failing of recent UN operations and contributed to
hundreds of thousands of deaths.
</P>
<P>
   ``(W)here one party to a peace agreement clearly and
incontrovertibly is violating its terms, continued equal treatment
of all parties. . . may amount to complicity with evil,'' the
report stated. ``No failure did more to damage the standing and
credibility of United Nations peacekeeping in the 1990s than its
reluctance to distinguish victim from aggressor.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the panel's other major recommendations:
</P>
<P>
   _ Member states should create several multinational,
brigade-size military forces, with support units, so that effective
force can be swiftly deployed. The United Nations should maintain
lists of field officers who could beginning planning and organizing
operations as soon as it appears a deployment is likely.
</P>
<P>
   _ The United Nations should develop a capacity for military and
political intelligence-gathering so that it can assess more
realistically what dangers its missions face and what level of
force will be needed to deter what the report called ``spoilers'' _
parties that agree to a UN intervention only to gain time to
prepare for renewed aggression.
</P>
<P>
   _ The Security Council should not authorize new operations until
member states have pledged sufficient troops, but the
secretary-general should be authorized to spend up to $50 million
to prepare an operation in advance of the authorization. The aim
would be to keep preparations moving swiftly but avoid dispatching
understaffed missions.
</P>
<P>
   Atwood said the main reasons missions are dispatched slowly and
with insufficient manpower are that, currently, little can be done
before a Security Council resolution is passed, and there is little
cooperation between the diplomats in the council and the military
and administrative leaders the United Nations sends to
troublespots.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a disconnect between the diplomacy of negotiating
peace and the mechanisms of upholding peace,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Rotberg, director of the program on intrastate conflict
at Harvard University's Kennedy School of Government, praised the
panel's effort to distinguish between traditional peacekeeping
efforts and peacemaking.
</P>
<P>
   The report stressed that UN operations in the 1990s have shifted
from the concept of peacekeeping that developed before 1990.
Because of the US-Soviet standoff, Cold War-era operations on which
major powers disagreed were almost never launched. Those that were
launched generally involved two sides that wanted a peace monitored
by a third, neutral party so that ceasefire violations would not
escalate into renewed warfare.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those operations involved unarmed Fijians and Canadians
essentially verifying that people weren't harming each other,''
said Rotberg, author of an upcoming book on peacekeeping and peace
enforcing in Africa. ``Nowadays we need people capable of imposing
peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Michael T. Corgan, a former political and military planner for
NATO planner who now is associate professor of international
relations at Boston University, agreed, and added that ``we have to
recognize that peacemaking essentially involves war. You must be
able to convincingly threaten full combat even if doesn't come to
that, and you incur many of the costs of a war.''
</P>
<P>
   The panel's report was commissioned by Secretary General Kofi
Annan in response to earlier, highly critical reports on the
failings of UN missions in Bosnia and Rwanda. It will be presented
to international leaders at the Millennium Summit at the United
Nations in early September.
</P>
<P>
   In Rwanda in 1994 hundreds of thousands of people were
slaughtered when undermanned UN forces failed to stand between the
Hutu ethnic group and its target, the Tutsi ethnic group. In Bosnia
in 1995, more than 7,000 Muslims were massacred when peacekeepers
withdrew from Srebrenica, a town which had been under UN
protection.
</P>
<P>
   But, Atwood said, the UN debacle in Sierra Leone earlier this
year _ when 500 UN troops were taken hostage and robbed of their
vehicles _ ensured that the panel would reach consensus on a
bluntly worded analysis recommending major changes.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we first met in New York, I thought maybe there would be
trouble reaching concensus,'' Atwood said, ``but by the next
meeting, in Geneva, the full extent of the Sierra Leone problems
were apparent, and it was never again in question that we would
reach concensus.''
</P>
<P>
   While the report does not make specific references to the Sierra
Leone mission, references to the need for UN units to be capable of
defending themselves and for the Secretariat not to ``apply
best-case planning to situations where local actors have
historically exhibited worst-case behavior'' reflect the Sierra
Leone situation.
</P>
<P>
   By lagging in paying its UN fees and constantly pushing to lower
its contributions to the organization, the United States has become
a major obstacle to more robust UN operations, but Atwood said the
result is costing the United States more and delivering less for
the money.
</P>
<P>
   ``The US is going to pay a lot more training Nigerians and
others now going into Sierra Leone than it would have paid had the
UN been equipped to do the job in the first place,'' he said. ``And
the killing and humiliation of US forces in Somalia _ people forget
that they were there as the result of a failed UN mission.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-00 1919EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
