<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000823.0287 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 19:21 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0305 &Cx1f; tad-z
r f BC-AIRLINESTATS0824-COX     08-23 0844
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRLINESTATS0824-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Air delay data flies erratically
 &HT;    By Nancy Fonti
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Making sense of the government data that track airline
delays and late arrivals isn't nearly as frustrating for the
average traveler as an unexpected stay in an airport terminal, but
it's no trip in first class either.
</P>
<P>
   The Department of Transportation and the Federal Aviation
Administration each produce monthly numbers but use different
metrics in assessing the airlines' performance.
</P>
<P>
   Delay statistics have received more attention than usual this
summer as labor troubles and stormy weather boost cancellations and
late arrivals, even as some airlines add minutes to flight
schedules to better the odds of being on time.
</P>
<P>
   Rising delays prompted Transportation Secretary Rodney Slater to
summon airline executives and labor leaders to Washington this week
to discuss the problem.
</P>
<P>
   With all the statistics flying around in political discussions
and media reports, it's easy to lose sight of what the numbers
actually show.
</P>
<P>
   The DOT statistics, which rank airlines according to arrival
performance, have been published monthly for years and are most
closely followed in the industry. But this summer the FAA delay
data, which track late takeoffs, have generated more chatter and
criticism of the industry.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA's statistics are based on the time a plane leaves the
airport. A flight usually is labeled delayed if it takes off more
than 15 minutes past the scheduled departure _ even if it goes on
to reach the destination on time.
</P>
<P>
   The standard taxi time _ about 11 minutes at Hartsfield
International Airport _ also is factored in before a plane is
considered delayed. The FAA logs delays related to air traffic
control issues, including bad weather, crowded skies, air traffic
control equipment and closed runways, but not airline-specific
issues such as maintenance problems. Weather generally accounts for
about 70 percent of all delays.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA, which generates the numbers itself, doesn't rank
airlines' results. ``We're looking at the big picture,'' said FAA
spokeswoman Tanya Wagner. ``We're not looking at the individual
airlines to make a statement.''
</P>
<P>
   Based on FAA numbers for January through June, delays rose to
251,874 this year, or 2.59 per 1,000 flights, from 227,719 delays,
or 2.38 per 1,000 flights, in the same period of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   The DOT each month publishes a consumer report on its Web site,
dot.gov/airconsumer/, including on-time percentages for the 10
biggest U.S. airlines.
</P>
<P>
   The DOT considers a flight on time if it arrives at the gate
within 15 minutes of the scheduled time, regardless of any delays
en route. Airlines supply the raw data through automated reports;
the DOT compiles the data and ranks the carriers.
</P>
<P>
   The DOT has not released statistics for June or the first six
months of the year because it is changing the computer system that
produces the data. But in May, Atlanta-based Delta Air Lines
sported the best numbers of the major airlines with slightly more
than 80 percent of flights on time. Facing labor trouble and stormy
weather, Chicago-based United Airlines was last at 56.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   At 10 major airlines as whole, 74.3 percent of flights arrived
on time in May, down from 76.2 percent a year earlier. The DOT
hopes to report June numbers before the end of August, a spokesman
said. For the industry as a whole, on-time performance slipped in
four of the first five months of this year compared with the same
months in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   So which numbers mean more? John Talmadge, Delta manager of
customer excellence, said the DOT's data are more widely accepted
in the industry, although the FAA numbers, which break down the
reasons for delays into categories, help airlines understand which
types of complaints to expect from travelers.
</P>
<P>
   For travelers on deadlines, an airport delay might not cause as
much damage as a late arrival. If a plane is stalled in an airport,
it can easily make up the lost time if it hits favorable tailwind,
Talmadge said.
</P>
<P>
   The DOT's list might seem like a handy guide for people
concerned with punctuality, but for business travelers paying top
dollar for tickets, on-time performance probably ranks third or
fourth in importance, said Chris McGinnis, an Atlanta travel
consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Business people generally are more concerned with schedules and
frequent flier perks, but trends don't go unnoticed, McGinnis
noted. ``Everyone knows that Southwest Airlines has the best
numbers,'' he said, ``and when Delta was really bad a few years
ago, I think people recognized that.''
</P>
<P>
   Terry Trippler, a consultant for Web site Onetravel.com, said
consumers are most concerned with arrival time. Most don't mind if
airlines pad flight times to boost on-time performance if it means
they'll reach the destination at the advertised time.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know the rules of the game, and that's all consumers can
ask,'' Trippler said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
