<SLUG> BC-GLF-TIGER0824-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Woods' success sparks more interest in East Lake's Tour
Championship
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA - Timing is everything. In a golf swing. In a golf
tournament's anxious preparation for the arrival of the sport's
mega-star.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday night at the peak of the PGA Championship telecast
and the riveting battle between Tiger Woods and Bob May, a
promotion ran on CBS-TV for the Nov. 2-5 Tour Championship at East
Lake Golf Club, featuring you-know who.
</P>
<P>
   Timing is everything. The Tour Championship's defending
champion, Woods, had just sunk a birdie putt at the first playoff
hole prior to the commercial break. A half hour later, Woods, 24,
had secured his third major of the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Monday morning,'' said Ron Cross, the Tour Championship's
tournament director, ``the phone was ringing off the hook.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's Tour Championship, which also will bring the other 29
top PGA Tour moneywinners to East Lake, is only 66 days away, as
Woods was reminded Wednesday during a teleconference from Akron,
Ohio, where he is (what else?) the defending champion at the NEC
Invitational.
</P>
<P>
   The Tour Championship pre-tournament mood and the Sunday
leaderboard are expected to be much different this time.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, when Hal Sutton won at East Lake, Woods finished
20th, getting most of his attention for wearing a gag Halloween
Afro wig walking to the 18th green. The raging debate in late '98
was whether David Duval or Mark O'Meara would win PGA Tour player
of the year. Woods had it won this year by June.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember the golf course was playing difficult,'' Woods said
of East Lake. ``You had a lot of bermuda rough that was pretty deep
and it was pretty high. The ball settled down to the bottom and you
never got a good lie. The guy who drove the ball in the fairway was
doing to have a lot of success. Hal is a wonderful driver of the
ball and he proved that by winning the tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Tour Championship officials Wednesday also unveiled the first
Payne Stewart Award, which will be awarded during tournament week
to the player most upholding the late U.S. Open champion's conduct
and commitment to the game.
</P>
<P>
   GOLF
</P>
<P>
   tour champ box for thurs
</P>
<P>
   TOUR CHAMPIONSHIP
</P>
<P>
   -- When; where: Nov. 2-5; East Lake Golf Club
</P>
<P>
   -- Purse: $5 million ($900,000 to winner)
</P>
<P>
   -- Field: PGA Tour's top 30 moneywinners
</P>
<P>
   -- Defending champion: Tiger Woods
</P>
