<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-TAO-REVIEW-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN `THE TAO OF STEVE', STEVEHOOD IS THE STATE TO WHICH ALL MEN
ASPIRE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By ERIC HARRISON 
c. 2000 Houston Chronicle 
It probably is tempting _ if you're male and single and of a
certain mindset _ to try to commit to memory The Tao of Steve's
rules for attracting women. After all, they work well enough for
Dex.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dex is the overweight, underemployed lothario at the center of
the movie who is never at a loss for female companionship. Not only
has he mastered the art of seduction, Dex has broken down its
components and worked up a set of principles.
</P>
<P>
   ``We pursue that which retreats from us,'' he tells an acolyte,
quoting philosopher Martin Heidegger. ``You must learn to eliminate
your desire.''
</P>
<P>
   This is important, he says, because women can always detect a
man with an agenda.
</P>
<P>
   One minute Dex (Donal Logue) seems like just a roly-poly,
fun-loving guy, the next minute he's still a roly-poly, fun-loving
guy but he's dispensing wisdom like a holy man. Not for nothing
does a statue of Buddha sit at the head of his bed.
</P>
<P>
   Central to his philosophy is the notion that ``Steve is the
prototypical American male.'' Super-cool Steve McQueen was the
``ultimate Steve,'' but there's also Steve Austin (television's
``Six Million Dollar Man'') and Steve McGarrett (the hero of
``Hawaii Five-O''). Stevehood is the state to which all men aspire.
</P>
<P>
   ``Michael Jordan is a Steve,'' Dex says.
</P>
<P>
   If all of this sounds a bit like a religion, then Dex is the
high priest of Steveism.
</P>
<P>
   Watching the movie, one soon suspects that this elaborate
philosophical framework may be nothing more than his way of
justifying a lifestyle that consists primarily of pursuing women,
smoking dope and hanging out with friends.
</P>
<P>
   ``Doing stuff is overrated,'' Dex says when someone suggests he
do something with his life. ``Like Hitler _ he did a lot, but don't
we wish he'd stayed home and got stoned?''
</P>
<P>
   Dex seems to genuinely believe the things he says, and he makes
the Santa Fe slacker lifestyle seem an attractive choice. Still,
it's hard to shake the notion that he's self-deluded. Especially
when he becomes enamored with Syd, a woman he'd known 10 years
earlier in college and whom he doesn't remember.
</P>
<P>
   She retreats, and he pursues, thus proving the validity of his
teachings. Meanwhile, he continues to teach the tao of Steve even
as he himself violates most of the principles.
</P>
<P>
   This is an amiable little film about an amiable large man.
Neither is in much of a hurry to get anywhere, which can be either
mildly bothersome or one of the movie's chief charms.
</P>
<P>
   Once it starts to amble with a greater sense of purpose, you
might want to put on the brakes _ not because it's going in the
wrong direction (although it doesn't feel quite like the right
one), but because Dex's teachings about Steve get called into
question. And the single men in the audience who are still jotting
down notes haven't even had a chance to try out what they've
learned.
</P>
<P>
   Greer Goodman, who plays Syd, also co-wrote the movie with
Duncan North, a kindergarten teacher from whose life the film is
drawn. Goodman's sister directed it, which probably accounts for
all the adoring close-ups.
</P>
<P>
   The movie has fun with the notion that Dex easily gets women who
are much better looking than he is. Goodman resembles Farrah
Fawcett without the Fawcett hair, only her body is more angular and
her face isn't perfect.
</P>
<P>
   One of the good things about the film is that most of the
characters look the way real people look. Real people put on weight
and have too-thin lips and eyes that are set too close together.
It's good to see a movie about people like us.
</P>
<P>
   What is most unbelievable about the Dex-Syd relationship isn't
that they aren't a good physical match, but that their lifestyles
and values seem completely different.
</P>
<P>
   She's athletic, has a good job and an apparently healthy sense
of self-esteem. He's a slob who smokes grass for breakfast and
works just enough to get by.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe ``opposites attract'' is one of the Steve principles that
never gets mentioned. &QL; 
 &QL; 
``The Tao of Steve'' &QL; 
Starring: Donal Logue, Greer Goodman &QL; 
Director: Jenniphr Goodman &QL; 
Screenwriters: Duncan North, Greer Goodman &QL; 
Rating: R, for language and some drug use. &QL; 
Running time: 87 minutes &QL; 
Grade: B &QL; 
XXXEND OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
