<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 19:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0312 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHINA-CORRUPTION-820&AMP;     08-23 1208
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-CORRUPTION-820&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN BEIJING, A MUSEUM EXHIBIT ON THE EVILS OF AVARICE 
</HEADLINE>
  (Foreign Journal) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ The multitudes visiting Beijing's newest museum
exhibit are greeted by pretty young guides in neat white dresses.
Providing nonstop fact-filled commentary through a half-hour tour,
the escorts cheerfully explain highlights of the posters and
showcases that fill two large halls of the Military Museum.
</P>
<P>
   The scene resembles a commercial fair or a convention, and you
would hardly guess that the show is devoted to an evil that
Communist leaders call one of the gravest threats to China's
stability.
</P>
<P>
   This oddly toned ``Beijing Exhibition on Attacking and
Preventing Economic Crime'' has been staged by the city government
together with the police, prosecutors and courts. Ostensibly
intended to educate the public about bribery, embezzlement and
fraud, it will run for a month.
</P>
<P>
   It is part of a growing national propaganda campaign that
officials hope will scare off potential miscreants and _ most
important to the party's survival _ convince an angry and skeptical
population that the authorities are resolutely battling corruption.
</P>
<P>
   While would-be voyeurs did not find any mink coats or pictures
of errant officials' secret love nests, some of the tens of
thousands who crowded the show in its opening days this week did
shake their heads at the stories of audacious swindles. As one
woman studied the picture of an embezzler sentenced to life in
prison, she muttered, ``He should be shot.''
</P>
<P>
   Others were intrigued by the suitcase of counterfeit bills on
display or fascinated by the re-created living room, with fine
furniture and liquor bottles, of a now-executed official of a state
enterprise and his wife who stole millions in company assets.
</P>
<P>
   But the exhibition also pulls its punches, reflecting the
party's unease with full exposure of a cancer that has spread so
deeply in its own ranks. And as a result, many concerned citizens
left the halls expressing dissatisfaction.
</P>
<P>
   As he fanned himself outside the museum, Li Yushu, a retired
teacher in his late 70s, said he had come ``because corruption is
such a serious problem,'' but he added that ``exhibitions like this
one can't get at the root of the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dealing with corruption requires building up the rule of law
and reforming the government,'' Li said. ``Ordinary people like me
feel that the government's crackdown is not intense enough.''
</P>
<P>
   The most glaring omission in this exhibit of 70 major ``economic
crimes'' is the infamous case of Chen Xitong, Beijing's former
mayor and Communist Party chief as well as a member of the party's
all-powerful Politburo, who is now serving time for his giant
bribery schemes.
</P>
<P>
   This decision to ignore the country's most sensational and
politically sensitive case did not escape notice. Many Beijing
residents are skeptical about the consistency of law enforcement
anyway, often repeating stories about senior well-connected
officials and their relatives who escaped prosecution for misdeeds.
</P>
<P>
   One notorious case does get good exposure: that of Cheng Kejie,
until recently a vice chairman of the national Parliament and the
former kingpin of a backward southern province who is now on death
row for extorting $5 million in payoffs. The crowds lingered
longest before a giant photograph of the handcuffed Cheng in court
and a small one of his mistress, Li Ping, who shared the money and
got a life sentence.
</P>
<P>
   But many other examples in the exhibition involve private crimes
like credit-card fraud or consumer swindles rather than the gross
abuses of official power that are of greatest public concern. And
lumping these two categories together as ``economic crimes'' tends
to blur the crucial distinction.
</P>
<P>
   An editor with a government publication who brought along her
teen-age daughter said she had found the exhibit disappointing in
ways she couldn't quite put her finger on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody already knows about these kinds of cases anyway;
they're in the newspapers every day,'' said the editor, who would
give only her surname, Li. ``I was expecting something more.''
</P>
<P>
   ``For example, the papers said that the largest display was
devoted to Cheng Kejie,'' she said, referring to the convicted
legislator, whose bribery scandal had implicated many other
officials. ``But it didn't tell us anything new at all. I'd like to
know more of the inside story, more detail about what really
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Unwilling to permit a free press or free elections _ which
foreign analysts say are most vital to curbing corruption _ the
government is relying on propaganda, showcase executions and the
fitful strengthening of law enforcement. This week, officials
trumpeted a new policy that could make a difference if consistently
enforced: routine financial auditing of retiring senior officials
and heads of state enterprises. An assumption is that officials
facing retirement are especially likely to stash away money to
supplement their pensions.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE; OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Fighting back any qualms about a double-edged message, top
officials have also publicly endorsed a gripping new feature film
that portrays the noble stand of a fictional city mayor against the
corruption all around him _ vice that engulfs his brother, his
party patron and even his wife.
</P>
<P>
   The movie, ``A Life and Death Choice,'' was adapted from a
popular novel and produced by the Shanghai Film Studios. It has
already opened in several cities and appears to have struck a
chord. In Shanghai alone, the producers say, more than a million
tickets have been sold, to individuals as well as to government
employees required to attend.
</P>
<P>
   The film is to open in Beijing theaters on Friday, after a
drumbeat of anticipation in the local papers. Last week, after an
advance screening, Beijing's mayor, Liu Qi, and Communist Party
secretary, Jia Qinglin, publicly praised the film and instructed
all city workers to see it.
</P>
<P>
   By now, China's leaders can hardly avoid acknowledging that the
party has harbored many bad apples. But a potential danger, as they
strive to cleanse the one-party system while preserving it, is the
unleashing of uncontrollable resentments.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the new exhibition, next to the stack of fliers
telling citizens how they can report examples of fraud or bribery
without fear of reprisals, is a sign of the new, more open China.
Several city officials and private attorneys sit in a row, offering
free legal consultations to museum visitors.
</P>
<P>
   An official from the prosecutor's office got more than she
bargained for the other day. A man who had traveled from Jilin
province, in China's remote northeast, to pursue his grievance in
the capital sat before her, waving old legal papers and a map of a
forest area. Corrupt local officials there had cheated him out of
land and logging revenues, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The legal official said she could only give him the phone
numbers of authorities back in Jilin _ who, the man pointed out,
had already refused to help. He became louder and more agitated,
and refused to give up his seat. Finally, a policeman came and led
him away.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
