<SLUG> BC-GLADSTONE-HOME-IMPROVEMENT-art-ADV10-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR RELEASE: SUN., SEP. 10, 2000. 
 HOME IMPROVEMENT QUESTIONS AND ANSWERS
</HEADLINE>
  By BERNARD GLADSTONE 
 Includes illustration. 
 c.2000 Bernard Gladstone 
 (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) 
 (PLEASE NOTE: To publish Bernard Gladstone's ``Home Improvement
Questions and Answers'' it must be purchased _ the rate is not
prohibitive _ from New York Times Syndication Sales. For purchase
information call toll-free 1-888-269-8796.) 
 (The NYTSS sales representative also has information on how to
subscribe to Gladstone's ``Home Improvement Questions and Answers''
weekly column which moves on Wednesdays.) 
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: When installing wallpaper around a window I have trouble
fitting it neatly against the edge of the wood frame.
 &HT;    No matter how carefully I measure, cut or trim this strip to the
correct width before I apply it, it still doesn't hang as evenly as
it should.
 &HT;    What am I doing wrong?
 &HT;    A: When less than a full width of wallpaper is needed it is best
not to cut and trim until you actually hang it on the wall and
paste it in place.
 &HT;    Here's what most pros do:
 &HT;    If less than half a width of wallpaper is required to fit right
up against the window molding, cut the strip lengthwise to several
inches wider than necessary (if more than half the width is needed,
don't bother to cut it).
 &HT;    Hang this strip on the wall, allowing the excess width to lap
onto and over the window frame as though it were not there.
 &HT;    Smooth the paper against the wall, and use a smoothing brush to
crease the paper firmly against the edge of the molding along its
full length.
 &HT;    Then run a razor blade down the joint to trim off the excess.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: My house has aluminum panels installed over the overhanging
eaves around the outside.
 &HT;    During hot weather these panels expand and buckle slightly
between the nailing points, leaving gaps between them and the wood
fascia boards.
 &HT;    When it cools off the panels return to their flat position.
 &HT;    What do you think causes this? And what should I do about it?
 &HT;    A: It sounds as though the panels were not nailed up properly.
 &HT;    Aluminum always expands in hot sun so when installing panels or
siding the nails should never be driven in all the way.
 &HT;    They normally go through slots in the aluminum, rather than
small holes, which allows the aluminum to ``move'' or stretch
lengthwise as it expands.
 &HT;    One solution now would be to pull out the old nails and use
these slots to drive in new ones _ but do not drive them in all the
way.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: My wood kitchen cabinets are stained a light mahogany color
and I want to lighten them by giving them a bleached or ``limed
oak'' look.
 &HT;    How can I do this without completely stripping and refinishing
the cabinets?
 &HT;    A: Start by cleaning off all wax and polish, then sand lightly
and apply a coat of thinned-down white flat paint, brushing it on
directly over the existing finish.
 &HT;    As you finish each section, partially wipe it off with a coarse
rag or wad of cheesecloth so as to leave some of the darker color
still showing through the white coat.
 &HT;    This will create something like a bleached or ``limed oak''
finish, although the final tone will depend on how opaque the white
stain is and on how much of it you wipe off.
 &HT;    Experiment first on the back of a door or the inside of a drawer
until you get the effect you want.
 &HT;    After you are done protect the finish with a coat of clear satin
finish varnish.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Q: The cedar siding on my house has turned dark and is weathered
looking _ in spite of the fact that we applied two coats of wood
preservative.
 &HT;    What can we do to lighten the siding and make it look nice
again?
 &HT;    A: Cedar weathers and changes its color unevenly, sometimes
turning darker and sometimes fading and turning lighter.
 &HT;    A clear sealer doesn't prevent this, but a pigmented shingle
stain would have helped prevent this, especially if you had
initially applied something like one of the ``weathering gray''
stains that are made by Cabot.
 &HT;    Your best bet now is to have the wood professionally cleaned by
power washing, then apply two coats of a light colored,
semitransparent, pigmented shingle stain.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    Questions about home-repair problems should be addressed to
Bernard Gladstone, care of The New York Times Syndication Sales
Corp., 122 E. 42nd St., New York, N.Y. 10168. Questions of general
interest will be answered in this column; Mr. Gladstone regrets
that unpublished letters cannot be answered individually.
 &HT;    
 &HT;    NOTE: Drawing captioned ``USING BRUSH FOR A FLUSH WALLPAPER
FITTING '' goes with this column.
 &HT;    CAPTION: Wallpaper smoothing brush is used to crease paper
snugly against window frame so that excess paper can be trimmed off
neatly with a razor blade.
 &HT;     
 -0- 
 c.2000 Bernard Gladstone 
