<HEADER>
A0318 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-WEB-EXTORTION-BOS &LR;      08-23 0751
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEB-EXTORTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FLORIDA MAN CHARGED IN WEB EXTORTION PLOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROSS KERBER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Federal agents have charged a Florida computer consultant with
trying to extort $1 million from a Massachusetts software company,
after he allegedly threatened to post on the Web a password that
would allow people to use the company's programs for free.
</P>
<P>
   The defendant, Michael Pitelis, was arrested late Tuesday based
on a series of threatening e-mails he allegedly traded with
executives at Parametric Technology Corp. of Waltham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   Pitelis, of Tarpon Springs, Fla., near Tampa, was freed on a
$25,000 bond, prosecutors said. He couldn't be reached for comment
Wednesday. He is expected to enter a plea at a hearing set for the
first week of September.
</P>
<P>
   The case is among an increasing number of actions brought in
response to complaints from software makers who fear blackmail.
Though it is still unclear exactly how Pitelis allegedly obtained
the company's secrets, prosecutors praised Parametric for bringing
the threat to their attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Internet has created new opportunities for crimincal acts.
This prosecution is an indication that federal law enforcement
intends to meet the challenge,'' said US Attorney Donald K. Stern.
</P>
<P>
   If convicted on a single count of extortion, Pitelis faces a
maximum of 20 years in prison and a $250,000 fine, prosecutors
said.
</P>
<P>
   Parametric, also known as PTC, develops and sells
three-dimension mechanical design software. Last year, it reported
net income of $119 million on sales of $1.06 billion, the bulk of
which came from its Pro/Engineer product line priced from $5,000 to
more than $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   Every customer receives the same CD-ROM, but users who pay more
receive special installation codes that allow them to use
additional software contained on each disk.
</P>
<P>
   According to an FBI agent's affidavit filed in US District Court
in Boston, the matter began on Aug. 3 when Parametric's chief
executive, Richard Harrison, received an unsigned e-mail asking,
``What would be the ramifications to PTC of releasing this software
installation procedure over the Internet through all the
Pro/Engineer user group bulletin/news boards?''
</P>
<P>
   Sent from an account hosted by Yahoo Inc., the message also
contained a password given to Parametric engineers that would yield
access to all the program's functions, the affidavit states.
</P>
<P>
   Harrison passed the email to Parametric's general counsel, David
Friedman, and he traded further messages with the sender who once
signed himself ``mr. Bill Myers.'' On Aug. 11, the sender wrote
that he expected Parametric to pay $400,000, plus $40,000 a month
to keep the information confidential.
</P>
<P>
   The sender later wrote that ``one or more of our associates,
under our payroll, is also under the payroll of PTC.'' On Aug. 21,
the sender wrote that it would cost the company $1 million to learn
this person's identity.
</P>
<P>
   Friedman, meanwhile, conducted an investigation of his own,
analyzing the header information of each e-mail sent to trace them
back to an Internet service proider, UUNet. He then obtained a
civil subpoena to discover the telephone lines used by computers
that dialed into the network.
</P>
<P>
   The affadavit says one was registered to Pitelis, who also
seemed to maintain a Web site for a company, Pitelis &AMP; Associates,
described as ``Pro/Engineer Consultants/Application Engineers.''
Clients include Colt's Manufacturing Co., and units of Thermo
Electron Corp. and Lockheed Martin Corp., according to the site.
</P>
<P>
   Another telephone line was registered to a public library in
Tarpon Springs, near Pitelis' home, according to the affidavit.
Friedman then turned over the information to the FBI, who obtained
a photo of Pitelas from driver's license records and spied on him
using the libary computer to send at least part of the text of an
e-mail received by Parametric.
</P>
<P>
   Based on that evidence, Pitelis was arrested late Tuesday in
Florida and his passport was confiscated. Assistant US Attorney
Stephen Huggard said he doubted the Pitelis' alleged claim he had
an accomplice inside Parametric. Huggard said none of the company's
employees are targets of an ongoing investigation.
</P>
<P>
   Parametric spokewoman Roberta Carlton Hefferman said the
incident was the first case like it for the company. Aside from
exposing the threat, she said, ``We never considered having any
dealings with this person.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
