<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-IRAQ-WEAPONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OFFICIAL SAYS IRAQ WON'T COOPERATE WITH INSPECTION TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
   By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ As a two-day meeting of international arms
inspections experts convened on Wednesday to review new monitoring
operations for Iraq, a leading Iraqi official denounced the
inspection commission and vowed again never to cooperate with it.
</P>
<P>
   The official, Tariq Aziz, Iraq's deputy prime minister and the
person considered to be the most authoritative spokesman for
President Saddam Hussein, said in Baghdad that his government would
not allow the new arms inspection team to visit the country, as
called for in a U.N. Security Council resolution last December.
</P>
<P>
   Hans Blix, the executive chairman of the new arms panel, the
U.N. Monitoring, Verification and Inspection Commission, said this
week that a team of 44 inspectors from 19 countries have been
trained and are ready to go to Iraq to restart inspections after a
20-month lapse. The last inspectors of an earlier commission were
withdrawn from Iraq in advance of American and British bombing in
December 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Aziz said in Baghdad: ``I have said that Iraq will never
cooperate with resolution 1284. This means it will not receive Blix
or any person related to this resolution.''
</P>
<P>
   Iraq has also refused to allow Yuli Voronstov, a Russian
diplomat charged with studying the cases of 600 Kuwaitis and others
still missing since the 1990 invasion and occupation of Kuwait by
Iraq, to enter. And Peter van Walsum, the Dutch ambassador to the
United Nations and chairman of the Security Council sanctions
committee on Iraq, has also been refused entry. He said he has been
eager to see for himself what effects a decade-long embargo is
having on the people of Iraq. The embargo was imposed by the United
Nations after Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Blix, a former Swedish foreign minister and director general of
the International Atomic Energy Agency during the period when it
was discovered that Iraq had been working on a secret nuclear
weapons program, was widely assumed to be more acceptable to Iraq
as a chief inspector than his predecessor, Richard Butler of
Australia, who headed the now-defunct commission known as Unscom.
</P>
<P>
   Nuclear inspectors under Blix had concluded several years ago
that Iraq was free of nuclear weapons, but needed long-term
monitoring. Butler's inspectors, who were responsible for
destroying and monitoring biological, chemical and long-range
missile programs, still had a list of questions for the Iraqis
about missing arms components and materials for germ warfare, and
were aggressive in demanding answers. Iraq objected, demanding more
diplomatic treatment, which some U.N. officials also advocated.
Butler now says this undermined his work and gave the Iraqis the
opening to become more defiant of all inspection systems.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq must be declared free of all prohibited weapons of mass
destruction in order to have sanctions lifted, although the new
commission, in a gesture to Iraq, is permitted to recommend a
suspension of the embargo if the Iraqis cooperate on
still-undefined ``key'' disarmament tasks for six months.
</P>
<P>
   Blix was expected to report on Wednesday to his international
advisory board, called a college of commissioners, on his readiness
to return inspectors to Iraq and Iraq's rejection of the new
program.
</P>
<P>
   Aziz's comments underlined the problem the Security Council will
face when it receives a report from Blix on Sept. 1. The report is
being discussed this week by the commissioners in a closed meeting,
with no information was made available.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, officials were searching for a response to Aziz
short of threatening Iraq. Richard Boucher, the State Department
spokesman, said Iraq's attitude will only mean that it will face
sanctions indefinitely.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
