<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 19:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0326 &Cx1f; tad-z
r s BC-FALCONS-JAGS0824-COX     08-23 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FALCONS-JAGS0824-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Falcons at ease even though cuts will be made soon
 &HT;    By Matt Winkeljohn
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   JACKSONVILLE, Fla. _ Michael Booker and Winslow Oliver seemed at
peace Wednesday after the Falcons finished their last preseason
practice even though the ``Grim Reaper'' might visit both this
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven players who will dress for tonight's preseason finale
against the Jaguars will be cut in the next few days, and Booker
and Oliver are players ``on the bubble,'' said Oliver, a running
back.
</P>
<P>
   When 12 players were cut last Saturday, word got out. Booker, a
cornerback whose departure has been publicly speculated about for
many months, could smile while telling the story.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was in the weight room working out, and all of the sudden
guys were saying they were cutting people,'' he said. ``I went and
took a shower and just waited. You never know when the 'Grim
Reaper' is going to come and tap you on the shoulder.''
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons trim their roster from 64 players to the NFL
regular-season limit of 53, perhaps as early as Friday. Oliver, who
has returned eight punts for a 13.8-yard average in relief of Tim
Dwight, will be waiting and wondering.
</P>
<P>
   ``Teammates talk about it lot, trying to figure out numbers,''
he said. ``I can't see how it will work out. But I keep my ear to
the ground, and there have been a lot of dropped punt returns
(around the league). I believe I'm a starting punt returner.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know, it might be a good thing, because I don't know
if I'd ever start here.''
</P>
<P>
   Here's a look at possible cuts:
</P>
<P>
   Secondary: Five safeties and six cornerbacks are on the roster,
and 10 defensive backs probably will make the team. Most likely,
the last spot is among Booker, rookie cornerback Anthony Midget and
third-year safety Omar Brown.
</P>
<P>
   The Falcons drafted Midget and Darrick Vaughn. Booker, the
team's first-round draft choice in 1997, has played well this
summer, but Eli Williams apparently has won the nickel cornerback
job. Then, Booker would be a No. 4 cornerback with a $1.65 million
price tag.
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, Midget ($231,000 cap charge) and Vaughn
($204,667) are cheap.
</P>
<P>
   ``The salary cap makes it difficult sometimes,'' coach Dan
Reeves said. ``The way the league is set up today, you have to
count on younger players quicker.''
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback: Reeves has said that Danny Kanell ($1.29 million
cap charge), who will play the second half tonight, and fourth-year
pro Tony Graziani ($472,000) are competing for the backup job, with
the implication that the loser will be cut.
</P>
<P>
   Rookie free-agent Doug Johnson is expected to be kept as a
developmental project.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pushing to keep four quarterbacks,'' Kanell said. ``We'd
like to hang out for another year together, but I also realize this
is a business.''
</P>
<P>
   Offensive line: The roster has 11 linemen and the team will keep
nine or 10.
</P>
<P>
   The last slot or two appear to be coming down to guard/center
Evan Pilgrim, rookie free-agent center Matt O'Neal, and
guard/tackle Jose Portilla.
</P>
<P>
   Wide receiver: The roster has eight, and the team will keep five
or six. Sixth-round draft choice Mareno Philyaw is a longshot
unless he is kept for a few weeks while Jammi German (sprained left
ankle) gets healthy.
</P>
<P>
   Ronnie Harris, who like German is of value on special teams, and
Eugene Baker, who is perhaps the most pure receiver of the group,
are the other candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Running back: Oliver and Gary Downs, probably the team's best
all-around special-teams performer, appear to be competing for one
spot.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive tackle: The fourth and final spot will come down to
third-year veteran Shawn Swayda ($358,000), who has seven preseason
tackles, and rookie free-agent Adriano Belli ($194,500), who has
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was weird last week, seeing guys you've gotten to know not
around any more,'' Belli said. ``I'd be happy even if I was on the
practice squad because I'm the type of player who gets better each
week, each year.''
</P>
<P>
   Linebacker: Seven are on the squad, and all of them might make
the team. If anybody goes, free-agent acquisition Marcus Buckley,
working behind weakside linebacker Keith Brooking and reserve Chris
Draft, is the leading candidate. Buckley,6-3, 240 pounds, also can
play the strong side and in the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Special teams: It is not likely, but Reeves has kept two kickers
before, both in Denver and with the Giants, where Brad Daluiso and
David Treadwell shared the job for the better part of two years.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-year-old kicker Morten Andersen ($1.045 million)has been
impressive. He is in the final year of his contract, though, and
rookie free-agent Jake Arians ($195,000) looks as if he might have
a future in this league.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever happens, players are trying to keep from letting it
worry them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sit around and think,'' Booker said. ``I know something's
got to happen. I know they like to keep the rookies they draft, and
I've been here a while.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I'm saying is, if I'm going to get cut, just be, you know,
cool about it. Don't say, `Mike, this and that.' I know I've played
well. If I don't make it here, I'll be on the market and will get
picked up by somebody else. Atlanta will still be my home.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
