<SLUG> BC-LEVIS-AD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ADVERTISING: LEVI STRAUSS LAUNCHES MULTIMEDIA CAMPAIGN FOR
SILVERTAB LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   By JANE L. LEVERE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Levi Strauss &AMP; Co. is introducing a multimedia campaign to
promote its Silvertab line of clothing, part of a continuing effort
to stimulate steeply declining sales.
</P>
<P>
   Directed at young adults 18 to 22, the new campaign, which has
been dubbed ``Lost but not lost,'' follows the adventures of three
young Americans traveling through Morocco. Eye-catching and exotic,
the ads show the travelers on camels, in a beaten-up bus and on the
beach wearing the new Silvertab line, which is made of the latest
high-technology materials, and using Sony electronic equipment like
a portable CD player and digital video camera.
</P>
<P>
   Photographed by Albert Watson, who has collaborated with Levi
Strauss since 1990, the new Silvertab advertising replaces a
two-year-old campaign, focused on teen-agers 15 to 19, that used
illustrations to depict what the company called ``youth tribes''
with a ``blending of ethnicities.''
</P>
<P>
   Morocco was chosen as the setting for the campaign ``because
it's a place where there's little technology,'' said Sean Dee,
director of marketing for the Levi's brand. ``It was a great way to
showcase our product and introduce our positioning, which is that
Silvertab is equipment for modern living.''
</P>
<P>
   Sony equipment is also featured because it ``helps us deliver on
that premise,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the key things that differentiates Silvertab from the
Levi's brand is its positioning,'' Dee added. ``Silvertab is not
what you expect from an old, reliable pair of Levi's. It allows us
to expand what we offer the consumer.''
</P>
<P>
   Levi Strauss is employing both traditional and new media to
promote the new line. Magazine advertising, which will run through
December, is appearing in magazines like Rolling Stone, Source,
Spin, Vibe, GQ, Maxim and Jane. Postcards that reproduce images
from the print advertising will be distributed through the fall and
early winter in restaurants in 15 cities nationwide, as well as in
stores like Saks Fifth Avenue, Dillard's and J.C. Penney. Outdoor
ads will also appear in Manhattan through the fall.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, Levi Strauss will introduce the Internet component
of the campaign next month. It will tell the ``Lost but not lost''
story through various Web sites, including www.lostbutnotlost.com
and www.sony.com, and has created 15-second commercials for movie
theaters to promote the Web campaign. Levi Strauss also has joined
forces with Imoviestudio.com, a site that brings visitors behind
the scenes when films are made; Shockwave.com, a game and
entertainment site; and Omnipod.com, a new company that makes
multifunctional desktop software.
</P>
<P>
   Levi Strauss executives would not disclose the budget for the
new campaign but said it would exceed previous spending. According
to Competitive Media Reporting, Levi Strauss spent $5 million to
promote Silvertab last year, $2 million in 1998 and $1 million in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Levis Strauss is counting on advertising to help reverse a
decline in sales. Overall sales for the company, which is privately
held, dropped to $5.1 billion last year, down 28.2 percent from a
peak of $7.1 billion in 1996. Sales also declined 6.4 percent in
the second quarter of this year, compared with results in the
period a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   The new Silvertab campaign is being conducted by the San
Francisco office of TWBA/Chiat/Day, whose new campaign for Levi's
Red Tab jeans was introduced late last month. The agency is part of
the Omnicom Group.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts of the apparel industry and youth market gave the new
campaign mixed reviews.
</P>
<P>
   Kurt Barnard, president of Barnard's Retail Trend Report, called
the campaign part of a ``near-desperate attempt by Levi's to change
its image from dowdy to with it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The traditional Levi's product has come on hard times, and
they're now beginning to realize that their salvation lies in
addressing a completely new audience, college students and
younger,'' he added. ``That's who they're apparently addressing
now.''
</P>
<P>
   Harry Bernard, a partner in Colton Bernard Inc., a fashion
consulting firm based in San Francisco, said that if Levi Strauss
could make Silvertab work, ``the line will become more important
than ever. It will be the fulcrum that brings them up over the top,
if it becomes a desirable brand for the younger individual.''
</P>
<P>
   The advertising ``does the right thing, in terms of getting the
target audience's attention, but it doesn't tell me that this is
something I have to have,'' he noted. ``They've got to take it
another step beyond sheer imagery, focus on the product itself. If
a line doesn't have its own raison d'etre and identifiable
signature, it isn't working.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just beginning that process,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Irma Zandl, who runs a research firm in New York that tracks
spending by consumers younger than 30, said the advertising had ``a
very European sensibility; it looks very sophisticated, arty,
aloof.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's so aloof and unengaging, I doubt it will really connect
with American teens and young adults,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
