<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-RENO-(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RENO WILL NOT NAME PROSECUTOR TO INVESTIGATE GORE'S '96 FUND
RAISING 
</HEADLINE>
   By DON VAN NATTA Jr. and NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The decision by Attorney General Janet Reno not to
appoint a special prosecutor to investigate Vice President Al
Gore's statements about his role in 1996 fund-raising activities
means Gore is essentially free and clear from any criminal
jeopardy, law enforcement officials said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because further investigation is not likely to result in a
prosecutable case under applicable criminal law and principles of
federal prosecution, I have concluded that a special counsel is not
warranted,'' Reno told reporters Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   In acknowledging that she had rejected the advice of a top
Justice Department investigator to name a special prosecutor, Reno
sought to portray her decision as a narrow one that cleared Gore
only of making false statements in an April 18 interview with
law-enforcement officials. She said the four-year inquiry into
fund-raising would continue.
</P>
<P>
   But some law-enforcement officials said Wednesday that the
reasoning Reno used in declining to seek a special prosecutor for
Gore meant that it would be difficult, if not impossible, to
investigate the vice president for any issue related to his role in
raising campaign donations during the 1996 campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Reno said she had concluded that the transcript of the April 18
interview did not show that Gore was lying when he insisted that
White House coffees and his 1996 visit to a Buddhist temple were
not fund-raising events.
</P>
<P>
   ``The transcript reflects neither false statements nor perjury,
each of which requires proof of a willfully false statement about a
material matter,'' Reno said. ``Rather, the transcript reflects
disagreements about labels.''
</P>
<P>
   In June, Robert J. Conrad Jr., the head of the department's
campaign finance unit, recommended that a special counsel be named
to investigate whether Gore had made false statements in describing
his role in the April 1996 visit to a Buddhist temple in Hacienda
Heights, Calif., and numerous coffee sessions at the White House
with potential donors. Both the appearance at the Hsi Lai Temple
and the coffees resulted in campaign donations to the Democratic
Party or the national ticket.
</P>
<P>
   Gore told Conrad in the April interview that he did not regard
any of those events as fund-raising events. Gore initially said
that he was at only one such coffee. Conrad then told him that the
record showed that he had, in fact, been the host at 23 of them and
had attended an additional eight with President Clinton as the
host.
</P>
<P>
   In rejecting Conrad's advice, Reno said, ``Mr. Conrad's
recommendation did not go to the underlying events, it went just to
the statements.'' She said the campaign task force headed by Conrad
was free to pursue any violations that might have been committed
during the coffees or the temple visit.
</P>
<P>
   But the law enforcement officials said Gore's only potential
legal liability was whether he had misrepresented the events, not
his participation in them.
</P>
<P>
   ``She has now cleared him of that,'' said one official who spoke
on the condition of anonymity. That means that Gore is inoculated
from new efforts to prosecute him as he heads into the final months
of his presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Some Republicans reacted angrily to Reno's decision.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Arlen Specter, R-Pa., said the decision ``follows a pattern
of the attorney general protecting the vice president.''
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Fred Thompson, R-Tenn., who headed a committee which
investigated allegations of fund-raising improprieties in 1996,
said, ``Janet Reno has steadfastly refused to follow the
recommendations of her career law enforcement officers and allow an
independent investigation of high-ranking administration officials.
There was never any reason to believe that she would do any
differently in this case.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, the Republican presidential
nominee, said in a statement, ``While it's clear that Al Gore
engaged in a number of questionable fund-raising activities and the
gave the FBI statements that continue to raise all the issues of
his credibility, the American people are sick and tired of all
these scandals and investigations. The best way to put all these
scandals and investigations behind us is to elect someone new.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On two previous occasions, Reno rejected advice to seek an
outside criminal inquiry of Gore. She did so on those occasions
over the objections of Louis J. Freeh, the director of the FBI, and
several senior Justice Department officials, including Charles G.
LaBella, who was a predecessors of Conrad.
</P>
<P>
   Reno said Conrad was ``an excellent prosecutor'' with whom she
had an honest disagreement.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Reno's opening statement was devoted to complimenting
Conrad, a longtime federal prosecutor from North Carolina. ``I am
impressed with his judgment, his management of the task force and
his knowledge of the law,'' she said. She said her ``regard for Bob
Conrad has only increased as I have dealt with him on this issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Reno acknowledged that Conrad was supported in his
recommendation by others in the Justice Department, disputing news
accounts today that quoted a senior department official as saying
Conrad was alone in his view that a special counsel was warranted.
</P>
<P>
   Associates of Conrad said he was deeply troubled by Reno's
decision and concerned by what one said were ``attempts to
marginalize'' his role. Another associate said Conrad was ``angry
and disappointed'' by the decision.
</P>
<P>
   Conrad declined to comment Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Lehane, a spokesman for Gore, said, ``We are pleased with
today's Justice Department announcement. However, Al Gore is going
to continue to do what he has been doing all along _ focus on
America's families.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
