<SLUG> BC-HERBERT-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: STANDING IN THE WAY 
</HEADLINE>
   By BOB HERBERT    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``We think there is a parallel between federal involvement in
education and the decline in profit over recent years.''
</P>
<P>
   -Ronald Reagan in 1983
</P>
<P>
   For those who haven't noticed, American schools are becoming
more and more crowded. The Department of Education reported this
week that the nation's elementary and secondary schools would
enroll a record 53 million students this fall. By the end of the
century, student enrollment in the United States is expected to
soar past 90 million, and could reach a phenomenal 100 million
students.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a century of growth ahead of us, a crescendo of
children,'' said Education Secretary Richard Riley. Americans would
be wise, he said, ``to figure out where we will put these children
and who will teach them.''
</P>
<P>
   Education is one of the hot issues in the presidential campaign.
All the candidates are in favor of enhanced student achievement,
tough standards, rigorous testing. And all agree that steps have to
be taken to improve the performance of black and Latino students.
</P>
<P>
   No one wants school kids to grow up spelling like Dan Quayle.
</P>
<P>
   That being the case, the report this week from Riley's office is
ominous. Overcrowded schools undermine two critical components to
improving student performance _ smaller classes, especially in the
early grades, and widespread access to pre-kindergarten programs.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton made a stop in South Brunswick, N.J.,
Wednesday to visit a school that will be holding some classes in
portable trailers this fall. He was pushing his school construction
initiative. If you want kids to do better, the president said,
squeezing them into overcrowded classrooms is not the answer.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican Party has traditionally been absent on the issue
of federal education assistance. Ronald Reagan wanted to abolish
the Department of Education, and GOP hostility to a federal role in
education remained ferocious right through the Gingrich era. School
lunch programs, Head Start _ you name it, top Republican
politicians were against it.
</P>
<P>
   This year is supposed to be different. The ebullient George W.
Bush wraps his arms around the education issue at every
opportunity. Dick Cheney, who voted against funding for Head Start
when he was in Congress, said this week that education was probably
``the single most important issue'' in the presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But when you look closely at the proposals that would help
students most _ federal assistance in building and modernizing
schools and putting more teachers into classrooms _ the enthusiasm
for education aid among top Republicans evaporates.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican leadership in Congress is standing in the way of
the initiative touted by Clinton Wednesday _ a $25 billion tax
proposal to help states finance the building of new schools and the
renovation of old ones in need of repair. Such federal help is
crucial if smaller classes are to become a widespread reality.
</P>
<P>
   There are 226 co-sponsors of the legislation, which means more
than half the members of the House support it. But the Republican
leadership is blocking a vote on the measure.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore strongly supports the legislation, but
Bush does not. He has derided it as a ``bricks and mortar''
approach to education reform.
</P>
<P>
   The GOP leadership in Congress is also blocking Clinton
administration efforts to provide federal funding for the hiring of
100,000 teachers. This is part of an effort by the administration
to help reduce the average class size in grades one through three
all across the country.
</P>
<P>
   The Republicans do not have a lot of credibility on the
education issue. That will hardly improve if Bush and Cheney travel
the country claiming to be education champions while at the same
time standing in the way of those programs that would help children
most.
</P>
<P>
   ``Overcrowding is not simply an issue of inconvenience,'' said
Leonie Haimson, an education consultant and author of a recent
report on class size reduction in New York City. ``We now know for
certain how critical smaller classes are for improving achievement
levels among kids, and specifically for reducing the achievement
gap. We are just not giving a fair shake to the kids in these
overcrowded and falling-apart schools.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-00 1945EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
