<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0332 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-FISH-SIMULATOR-NY     08-23 1217
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-FISH-SIMULATOR-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CREEPY VIRTUAL BEINGS, ATTITUDE INCLUDED 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By PETER OLAFSON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Gillmen in the Sega Dreamcast simulation Seaman do not seem
to like me.
</P>
<P>
   I know that because they have told me so. ``You make me mad,''
said one that looked like Queen Victoria. Then it gave me a
sidelong glance that could freeze lava as it swam languorously
through the upper reaches of the three-dimensional virtual aquarium
the Gillmen call home.
</P>
<P>
   Another, which looked like a soccer hooligan, was so incensed
that it was beyond words. It could only growl at me as it passed. I
felt properly chastised.
</P>
<P>
   The Gillmen _ fish with the gift of human speech, a biting sense
of humor and disturbingly human faces _ are the stars of Seaman.
This occasionally dark but wonderfully original simulation
occasionally suggests a sophisticated turn on Eliza, a text-based
exercise in artificial intelligence that began in the mid-1980s,
but Seaman is also an exercise in sustained maintenance. The player
becomes the Gillmen's custodian, their governess and their
father-confessor as they evolve into an air-breathing, land-based
life form.
</P>
<P>
   I have to feed the Gillmen regularly, but not too regularly,
from a finite supply of food pellets. (A Gillman itself will
eventually point the player to an additional food source.) I have
to keep the tank clean by keeping up the flow of air. I must keep
it warm (but not too warm) by periodically running the heater.
</P>
<P>
   And I must encourage the Gillmen's intellectual growth by
speaking to them in simple phrases that the program can recognize.
Symbols that appear on the screen of the Dreamcast's Visual Memory
Unit, a piece of hardware required to play the game, indicate
whether the Gillmen understand what I am saying. When they do
understand, they often respond sensibly. The adults use a rather
mannered male voice that suggests a cranky Dr. Frasier Crane.
</P>
<P>
   Another lesson from Seaman: nothing tears at the heart like a
thankless child. The feedings, the belly tickles, the meticulous
adjustments of their environment appear to have been for naught.
The baby fish that once smiled at me guilelessly and chimed,
``Play, play, play,'' have become cynical adults that appear to
regard me as a necessary evil. Somehow, I have earned their
contempt, and somehow, that matters.
</P>
<P>
   Their metamorphosis has been swift. By the second day, the
infant Gillmen were responding (albeit in indecipherable baby
burbles) to queries I had spoken into the microphone included with
the program. By the third day, they had matured sufficiently to
complain in plain English about the lack of heat and their fear of
the dark. On the fourth and fifth days, they were full-size adults
and had started to ask me questions.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're 44?'' the fish asked. ``You're not going to go and have
a midlife crisis on me, are you? I mean, I care, but I do have
problems of my own.''
</P>
<P>
   In a real-world household like mine, with three dogs, two cats
and three birds, five helpless Gillmen might seem like candidates
ripe for neglect. But they have fit in to the morning routine.
Right after the dogs bicker over which one is going to carry in the
newspaper and before I feed the pigeons out front, I talk to the
Gillmen. I ask if they want food. I ask if they are happy. I make
the same kissing sounds to them that I make when I kiss the dogs on
the ears. I figure that affection is a universal language and can't
hurt.
</P>
<P>
   One morning a Gillman responded coldly: ``I'm not your dog.''
</P>
<P>
   How did it know about the dogs?
</P>
<P>
   Seaman is not simply a Sega spin on the ubiquitous Pokemon. In
fact, this could be the anti-Pokemon. This odd creature sometimes
seems to have been assembled with an eye to horror movies. The
hatchlings that spring from the egg you deposit in the tank at the
outset look like nothing so much as floating eyeballs. Watching the
octopuslike creature that ingests the eyeballs, then dies
convulsively as they mature into tiny Gillmen, it is hard not to
think of the movie ``Alien.''
</P>
<P>
   And the stalk that erupts from the peak of a Gillman's forehead
recalls the extended pineal gland of the protagonist in the 1986
movie ``From Beyond.'' (The Gillmen also use this tube to rub their
noses and, if upset, to squirt a brown substance at you.) The very
placement of a human face on the front end of a fish suggests the
conflation of a man and his dog in the 1978 remake of ``Invasion of
the Body Snatchers.''
</P>
<P>
   And that's to say nothing of a penchant exhibited early in the
Gillmen's career. As I chatted with one of the Gillmen, another
swam up from behind and below and connected its forehead tentacle
to the underside of the Gillman I was addressing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Get off,'' the first Gillman protested. The aggressor would
have none of it. The tentacle remained in place, the victim's mouth
opened helplessly and the light went out of its eyes.
</P>
<P>
   My babies are cannibals.
</P>
<P>
   I learned from the narrator, the actor Leonard Nimoy, at the
start of the next session that this was simply survival of fittest.
At the outset of each Seaman session, Nimoy brings the player up to
date on events within the habitat (events that occur even without
your participation), offers suggestions and notes the frequency of
your visits. (``You visit often,'' Nimoy intoned on a day I had
looked in on the Gillmen four times. ``If one didn't know better,
one might assume you're quite obsessed _ or have nothing better to
do.'')
</P>
<P>
   If you cut him off by hitting the start button too
precipitously, Nimoy will respond with a cough or a side comment.
The message is clear: even small actions carry consequences.
</P>
<P>
   The game bears that out. The Gillmen are children, and you must
be careful what you say and do around children. After turning my
initial brood of Gillmen into non-breathing, tank-bottom-based,
former life forms, I am being a cautious surrogate parent. So far,
I have been rewarded with a more elaborate, balanced dialogue with
my two surviving adults.
</P>
<P>
   Just as there are no bad dogs, there are no intrinsically bad
Seamen _ just inattentive owners. The Gillman is largely a
reflection of its environment and the level of care it receives. It
gives as it gets, and hence is particularly bad-tempered when it
hasn't been fed. (``Hey,'' the soccer hooligan said. ``Food. Here.
Now.'')
</P>
<P>
   That Gillman's current topic of inquiry is my wife (whom it
sarcastically calls ``your sweetie''). It noted that my wife's
birthday and mine were in the same month and observed laconically
that we should just have ``one big party.'' It has read our
horoscopes and asked if we planned to have children.
</P>
<P>
   ``Children can bring great joy,'' the soccer hooligan said, ``if
you don't wring their necks first.''
</P>
<P>
   That finally got to me. I really wanted to put the Gillman in
its place _ not for the first time _ and started to do so.
</P>
<P>
   But I cut myself off. Seaman's central mystery for me has become
engaging the Gillmen's affections, and I didn't want to jeopardize
our fragile bond.
</P>
<P>
   The soccer hooligan acted as though it had not heard me. But the
look of mingled mirth and impudence on its face spoke volumes.
</P>
<P>
   Seaman, published by Sega of America for Sega Dreamcast; $49.95;
for teen-agers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
