<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 19:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0336 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f BC-MCDONALDS-CHICKENS082     08-23 0330
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCDONALDS-CHICKENS0824-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    McDonald's egg suppliers must give hens more space
 &HT;    By Scott Leith
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It's not often that a single customer changes an
entire industry.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, not every customer is a behemoth like McDonald's
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning soon, the fast-food giant will only buy eggs from
suppliers that provide more space for hens. McDonald's also wants
egg suppliers to put an end to ``forced molting,'' in which hens
aren't fed as a way to spur production.
</P>
<P>
   Walt Riker, a spokesman for McDonald's, said the change has been
in the works for several years. ``Animal welfare comes first,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Gregory, senior vice president of United Egg Producers, an
Atlanta-based trade group, said the entire industry will likely
move toward larger cages. UEP worked with McDonald's to develop the
new guidelines and wasn't surprised by the announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're willing to make these changes,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The move, announced to suppliers Tuesday, comes after lobbying
from groups such as People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals, or
PETA.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without that pressure, McDonald's would be satisfied,''
Gregory said.
</P>
<P>
   PETA has long pushed for animal rights and maintains a Web site,
www.mccruelty.com, that focuses on McDonald's. A PETA spokesman
said the group welcomes the move by McDonald's but would prefer
that hens roam free rather than live in cages at all.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new guidelines, McDonald's suppliers must provide 72
square inches of space for each hen, up from 50 now.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory said it will take a decade or so for the entire industry
to adapt. ``These things can't happen immediately'' or egg prices
would skyrocket, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory doesn't expect the criticism to ebb. ``The pressure is
coming from groups that are vegetarian,'' he said. ``They are
groups that don't even eat eggs.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
