<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    2ND UPDATE
 &HT;    EDs: Adds: FIRES-OVERVIEW, POLTICAL-ADBUYS, FBC-FLA-PALMER,
FBC-MIAMI-PALMER
 &HT;    
 &HT;    CoxNet Cox News Service budget
 &HT;    FOR SUNDAY, Aug. 27, 2000
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   For questions, please call 404-526-5456.
</P>
<P>
   Photo and graphics information and editors' names can be found
at the end of this budget.
</P>
<P>
   THE WEEKEND DUTY EDITORS ARE:
</P>
<P>
   IN ATLANTA: Dane Fall at 404 256-5144
</P>
<P>
   IN WASHINGTON: Elliot Jaspin at 410-224-7695.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   FIRES-OVERVIEW _ It was a dramatic week in Montana as
firefighters from across the country tried to stem wildfires that
have left much of the West dark and shrouded in smoke. (Seabrook,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 30.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-BATTLEMAP _ Al Gore began a new ad campaign this week,
and almost state for state and dollar for dollar, the ad buy
matches presidential rival George W. Bush's new ads on education
and making tough choices, which also began running this week. From
the ad buys, a map of 17 battleground states emerges. We look at
the map and its significance. (Sherman, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) 25. WITH MAP.
</P>
<P>
   BILINGUAL-AMERICA _ CHICAGO _ ``Welcome. We speak Spanish,''
said the sign in Spanish beckoning customers to get a haircut at a
suburban Chicago salon. But somewhere along the way, former
employees allege, the Regis Hairstylist Salon decided that Spanish
spoken among employees made its English-speaking customers
uncomfortable. The sign disappeared and employees were ordered to
speak only English. Several hairstylists allege that they lost
their jobs for speaking their native tongue. As immigrants from
non-English-speaking countries flow into the United States,
businesses and institutions increasingly face a foreign-language
test: How best to cope with new workers and new customers whose
first language is not English. (Holmes, Cox News Service) WITH
PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   WITH
