<DOCNO> NYT20000823.0313 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 20:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0343 &Cx1f; tie-z
u a BC-CIR-DVR-3TAKES-NYT &LR;      08-23 0899
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CIR-DVR-3TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIVO AND REPLAYTV MAY CHANGE VIEWING HABITS, BUT NOT YET 
</HEADLINE>
   (Circuits)  
 By ROY FURCHGOTT   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Leonard LaFrance, an engineer in Lake Tahoe, Nev., was intrigued
when he heard about a new product for his television, a gadget that
would search for the programs he wanted, automatically recording
them on a hard drive, and would allow him to put live programs on
``pause'' and skip commercials at the press of a button.
</P>
<P>
   But last winter, when he rushed to the salespeople at a local
electronics retailer, Good Guys, searching for one of the devices,
known as a digital video recorder, ``they didn't know about it,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Not one to give up easily, LaFrance walked around the store
until he found one.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had it on the floor, and they didn't know about it,'' he
said. ``They didn't even put it next to the VCRs _ it was somewhere
else.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no question that digital video recorders _ also known
as personal video recorders or by the brand names of the two
competing services, TiVo and ReplayTV _ are a powerful and, for
many, an attractive technology. Online reviews at Web sites like
Deja.com, ePinions and Amazon.com brim with glowing testimonials on
the order of, ``How did I watch TV before this?''
</P>
<P>
   Some analysts even suggest that the DVR will help reshape
commercial television by giving people the power to program their
own personalized networks, watching programs whenever they want and
completely avoiding commercials. With a DVR, for example, a
Humphrey Bogart fan can instruct the machine to find and record all
Bogart movies that are broadcast, then can watch them at will,
skipping the advertisements.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their promise, however, DVRs have not flown off the
shelves since they were first introduced a little more than a year
ago. Philips Electronics and Sony devices use the TiVo service,
while Panasonic and Sharp receivers use the ReplayTV service, and
ReplayTV also offers its own hardware. TiVo devices, the most
highly promoted of the brands, sold about 48,000 units in their
first year. ReplayTV shipped about 9,500 of its own boxes to
retailers in 1999. Panasonic started selling ReplayTV devices in
May, and sales figures were not available; Sharp is just getting
into the market.
</P>
<P>
   The DVR is a good example of how even relatively easy-to-use
technology with a huge potential market can be slow off the mark.
While price is an issue _ the units cost from $99, with a monthly
fee of $9.95, to $499 _ there are thornier problems, like getting
consumers to understand a product that has too many features to sum
up neatly in an advertising slogan.
</P>
<P>
   And even if consumers understand the product, will millions feel
that it is useful enough _ and different enough from a VCR _ that
they cannot do without it? Or will DVRs go the way of, say,
quadraphonic sound, which was introduced in the 1970s as the next
big thing in audio but was rejected by consumers?
</P>
<P>
   The companies are betting that the DVR will not fizzle.
(ReplayTV's partners include Time Warner and the Sundance Channel,
and TiVo's include America Online, CBS and Disney. Showtime and NBC
are partners of both services.) The companies point to a high level
of satisfaction among early adopters, some of whom liked it so much
that they bought a second or third unit. The companies have little
doubt that more consumers will eventually see how convenient the
DVR is, and how much more it can do than a VCR. But they
acknowledge that DVR's can be a tough sell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until people get their hands on it,'' said Rebecca Baer, a
spokeswoman for TiVo, ``they don't understand why they need this.''
Salespeople who want quick sales often do not have the time to
promote a new technology, she said. ``The retail environment is an
extremely hostile one,'' she said, ``especially for products that
require education.''
</P>
<P>
   One problem facing DVRs, as LaFrance found, is that salespeople
often know little about the machines, even though they have been on
the market for more than a year. ``The retailers that sell it don't
push it,'' LaFrance said. ``I don't understand it because it's a
big ticket item.'' LaFrance was so happy with DVR that he now owns
two and has a third on order _ one for each one of his televisions.
A fan of science, he uses one just to search for and record science
programs.
</P>
<P>
   To educate salespeople, the companies are sending out marketers
to conduct demonstrations in stores.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Hollingsworth, the senior vice president for sales and
marketing at ReplayTV, said his company would put on 10,000
demonstrations nationwide _ in stores like Circuit City, Best Buy
and The Wiz _ between now and end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   TiVo plans about 1,000 demonstrations this year. It has just
built a traveling demonstration theater in a tractor-trailer that
will tour 25 cities this year.
</P>
<P>
   One barrier to consumer acceptance may be that in addition to a
cable or satellite hookup, each DVR needs access to a phone line to
download information about broadcast schedules. While that phone
line can still be used for calls or data transmission, some
consumers may be reluctant to hook up another device to a phone
line or install another jack. Stores have also been slow to hook
showroom DVRs up to phone lines, even though a DVR needs a phone
line to show how it can track programs.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   To address consumers more directly, both TiVo and ReplayTV have
commissioned advertising campaigns. One TiVo advertisement was
banned by CBS because it tried to make the point that network
programmers were obsolete by showing a pair of bouncers marching
into a programmer's office and throwing him out the window. An
advertisement for ReplayTV shows a boxing match in which a viewer
hits Pause to freeze the action, leaving the boxers standing
around, waiting to resume. The punch line is, ``Pausing live TV _
weird, isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   Both companies say their goal is to stir up attention. The
difficulty is that neither advertising campaign really answers the
question as to what a DVR is. What they are, and how they differ
from VCRs, is not an easy question to answer in 30 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a logical prospect does not understand the product,'' said
John Roberts, a former marketing executive with Sony who is now
with Gotham Advertising in New York, ``it's hard to say the produce
is well served _ unless there's so much buzz and hype that the
information is already being taken cre of.''
</P>
<P>
   DVRs are, in fact, both a piece of hardware (each one has a hard
drive that can hold 20 to 30 hours of low-resolution television, or
seven to 10 hours of high-resolution programs, for later viewing)
and a service that tracks down the programs a viewer wants even if
they are delayed or rescheduled.
</P>
<P>
   The hardware is plugged into a telephone line so it can call the
service daily for schedule updates and software enhancements. It is
also plugged into the homeowner's cable or satellite box.
</P>
<P>
   One of the DVR's big attention grabbers is the ability to make a
live television program pause, then continue the show without
skipping a single word of ``NYPD Blue,'' for instance _ even if a
pizza arrives in the middle of the show. That is possible because
the device is recording whatever is being watched. When viewers
resume watching, they are actually seeing recorded material. But
more compelling to viewers is the DVRs ability to sort through the
numerous channels to find programs the viewer likes so they are
never missed.
</P>
<P>
   Brian Kusler, a product manager at a software company,
CrowdBurst.com in San Francisco, bought the first model of TiVo so
he would not miss his favorite sports event, the Tour de France
bicycle race. ``ESPN treats it one step below soccer, and they
would move it without telling you,'' he said. ``Now even if the
listing changes, TiVo still finds it.''
</P>
<P>
   Both TiVo and ReplayTV allow users to configure the listings to
display only programs of the type they want to watch, so there are
fewer listings for the viewer to scan. The daily schedule of shows
is then available in an on-screen guide. The DVRs can be set to
record specific programs, or any shows it finds with a specific
actor.
</P>
<P>
   The services will also monitor what the viewer watches and
suggest that similar programs be recorded. With TiVo, the
suggestions become more refined as the viewer approves or
disapproves of the suggestions, using a button on a remote control.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to get used to it,'' said Charles Weiss, a photo
assignment editor at The Baltimore Sun. ``It changes the way you
watch television. I sit down with the remote and my impulse is to
channel-surf, but then I go to the listings, very quickly find out
what is on, and go to the show I want to watch.'' He keeps a cache
of ``Seinfeld'' and ``Drew Carey Show'' episodes on hand.
</P>
<P>
   A DVR's recording capability may not seem that different from a
VCR's, but a viewer can make a DVR recording with one push of a
button and without setting a timer. Most VCR owners cannot even set
the clock, and they seldom _ if ever _ use the timer to record a
show. With a DVR, the viewer chooses programs from an on-screen
menu, and the machine does the rest. The machines are not intended
for the long-term storage of programs _ for that, the programs can
be transferred to a VCR.
</P>
<P>
   The DVD's recording feature was particularly important for
Kusler, who keeps a stock of ``Star Trek: Voyager,'' ``Ally
McBeal'' and ``South Park'' on hand. ``I don't watch a lot of TV,''
he said, ``but I'd come home and the things I wanted to see weren't
on.''
</P>
<P>
   DVRs also let viewers skip commercials. TiVo has a fast forward
button that is similar to the one on a VCR. ReplayTV has a button
that skips ahead in 30-second chunks (if the program is running at
least 30 seconds ahead), which was the main reason that LaFrance
bought his. ``I was so fed up with commercials,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, those features do not necessarily come cheap. And
consumers who are not familiar with the features of a DVR are
likely to look at the price and buy a VCR instead, Roberts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Think about VCRs,'' he said. ``Everyone has one, and it's
cheap. You have to be an idiot to spend more than $200.'' Even
entry-level DVRs with a recoding time of 14 hours were selling for
about $500 during the critical Christmas sales period last year.
</P>
<P>
   The companies have responded by lowering prices. This year, a
low-end TiVo unit sells for $99, not including the program-listings
service, which is $10 a month or $199 for the life of the unit (
for a total of $298).
</P>
<P>
   Basic ReplayTV units start at $299, with service included.
Top-of-the-line models, which record up to 30 hours of television,
sell for about $600.
</P>
<P>
   That $299 price may be a pivotal number, according to Gordon
Hodge, a media analyst for Thomas Weisel Partners, an investment
firm in San Francisco. ``When DVD and MP3 moved into that range, it
seemed to be a magic price point,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Another barrier is the ``teeter factor,'' said Hodge, who owns a
TiVo and uses it to record sports events. ``There's a lot of
clutter in the family room,'' he said. ``Do you really want to
stack another box on the others teetering on top of the TV?''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Both DVR companies say that before Christmas, they will release
``combo boxes,'' which will put a DVR in the same box as a
satellite television set-top controller (Sony's combo box will cost
$399, the same price as the stand-alone recorder). The combo box
will not only reduce clutter but will also piggyback DVR sales on
the high sales volume of satellite television service. Hodge
estimates that TiVo will sell more than 100,000 units on the
strength of the combo box. ReplayTV is not a public company yet and
has not fully divulged its balance sheets, so Hodge had no
projections for its sales.
</P>
<P>
   DVRs may be easy to use, but some buyers have complained that
they are not easy to set up. Not every configuration of devices is
covered in the manuals, and even the basic instructions might be
daunting for someone who just wants to plug in the device and turn
it on.
</P>
<P>
   In a test, setting up the TiVo initially required two phone
calls to customer service, about an hour to configure the system
and about three hours for the system to download and install its
software. The ReplayTV, which allows more programming customization
than TiVo, took less time to download its software, but it required
a lot of time poring over the manual to configure and learn its
features.
</P>
<P>
   Of the two units, the TiVo was easiest to use. It has an curvy,
comfortable remote control with an intuitive arrangement of
buttons. The ReplayTV remote control had more features, but lots of
small buttons that could vex someone with less than perfect vision.
It also required an occasional look at the manual to locate a
feature on the remote control (the quick skip, which jumps 30
seconds at a clip for excising commercials, eluded the tester for
two days).
</P>
<P>
   As with any new electronic product, some users have reported
technical difficulties. One of them is Robert Hill, an executive
recruiter from Leesburg, Va., who likes to tape old ``Saturday
Night Live'' shows and vintage movies. ``I had the thing for about
six weeks,'' he said, ``and all of a sudden the thing wouldn't _
the phrase I would use is boot up.'' He exchanged it for a new unit
but still experiences some problems, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes when it is recording it will switch off early,''
Hill said, ``so you'll get 1} hours for a Hitchcock movie, then it
changes channels. So you miss the last 15 minutes.'' But he does
not mind. ``To tell you the truth, I've seen most of them before,''
he explained.
</P>
<P>
   The companies are hustling to iron out glitches while still
introducing new products. ReplayTV has announced that it will make
personal programming available on the Internet so people can tell
their units to tape shows their co-workers discussed at water
coolers that day and have them ready for viewing after work. TiVo
is working on a similar service.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the promotion, the companies say that when it comes
to brand-new technology, the public cannot be rushed. ``We have an
educational challenge to help people understand what TiVo is,''
said Mike Ramsey, the chief executive of TiVo. ``It's more than
just spending money on marketing _ it takes time.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, the best salespeople may be users like Kusler.
</P>
<P>
   ``People come over, I forget I have it and pause the TV, and
they want to know how I did that,'' he said. ``I think I've
personally sold about five of them, maybe six.''
</P>
<P>
   REPLAYTV OR TIVO?  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Following is a comparison of the Panasonic ShowStopper 2000,
which is a ReplayTV unit, and the Sony SVR-2000, a TiVo model.
</P>
<P>
   PRICE: Panasonic/ReplayTV: $599 (programming service included);
Sony/TiVo $399 plus $199 for service.
</P>
<P>
   RECORDING TIME: Both models allow 30 hours of recording at
lowest quality, 10 hours at highest quality.
</P>
<P>
   SEARCH FEATURES: Panasonic/ReplayTV: Search by actor, director,
title, program description; Sony/TiVo: Search by title, time,
channel and preset genres.
</P>
<P>
   FAST FORWARD: Panasonic/ReplayTV: 5 speeds Sony/TiVo: 3.
</P>
<P>
   SKIP FORWARD: Panasonic/ReplayTV: 30-second jump; Sony/TiVo: Not
available.
</P>
<P>
   PARENTAL BLOCKING: Panasonic/ReplayTV: Not available; Sony/TiVo:
Available in next software upgrade.
</P>
<P>
   SETUP AND PROGRAMMING
</P>
<P>
   Digital Recorders Aren't Quite Plug and Play &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It has been said that connecting a digital video recorder is as
easy as hooking up a VCR. Let that be a warning.
</P>
<P>
   Although connecting and programming these units is not
especially daunting to the technically adept, they are not quite
``plug and play.'' At their simplest, the units require that the
user connect a coaxial cable and a phone cable to the box, then
follow a series of commands on the TV screen. Such a setup can take
as little as an hour. But setup can be more complicated when a
digital recorder is used with a home entertainment system, a cable
box or any number of devices that can be hooked to a television.
</P>
<P>
   In a test, the TiVo receiver (a Sony model) was the easier to
set up, requiring the user to answer questions on a series of
screen menus. There were confusing moments _ when the machine asked
for the selection of a cable provider, it did not provide the
correct name. And several days after the machine was set up and
operating, it suddenly could no longer complete its nightly call to
update the TV schedule. The machine had switched the dial-in number
from a toll-free number to an incorrect local one. The machine had
to be configured all over again.
</P>
<P>
   SETUP OF THE REPLAY
</P>
<P>
   TV receiver (a Panasonic model) required more time, largely
because it had more customizable features. The manual did not make
it easy. Take the section on setting recording options, which
includes this passage: ``Guaranteed. Choices are yes and no.
Guaranteed means space is reserved for the show. Nonguaranteed
means the show will be recorded if there is space available (after
space is reserved for Show-based Replay channels). See Guaranteed
and Nonguaranteed Recording on Page 40.''
</P>
<P>
   As easy as a VCR indeed.
</P>
</TEXT>
