Kursk, Russia's political evolution seems to be taking a new kind
of post-Soviet turn. Military commanders are offering to resign.
The government and the private sector are competing to raise
millions of dollars to comfort the families of the Kursk's crew.
The air waves are ringing with the mea culpas from the haughty
admirals of the once mighty Red Banner Fleet of the north. It
didn't start out that way. By Patrick E. Tyler. (The analysis has
moved in ``i'' news file.) 1,350 words.
