<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 20:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0348 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-FLA-STORM-ART-NYT &LR;      08-23 0705
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-STORM-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STORM WEAKENS, BUT COULD STRENGTHEN ONCE AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Tropical Storm Debby lost momentum as it spun westward
through the rough mountains of the island of Hispaniola and headed
toward the northern coast of Cuba, where the storm was expected to
weaken even more before threatening the Florida coast or moving
into the Gulf of Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   South Floridians, who have tensely followed the arrival of the
first hurricane this season to threaten the state's coastline, were
relieved when the storm was downgraded Wednesday morning to a
tropical storm, but forecasters here warned that the state is still
in danger.
</P>
<P>
   Winds had slipped to below 60 mph by Wednesday evening as the
storm moved across the Dominican Republic and then Haiti, dumping
heavy rain and tearing the tin roofs off homes.
</P>
<P>
   The rugged terrain broke up the already weakening storm, which
was good news for Florida and the rest of the coastal United
States.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mountains of Hispaniola have really disrupted the
circulation,'' said Max Mayfield, the director of the National
Hurricane Center in Miami. ``Not only has it not strengthened, it
has weakened and will likely continue to weaken as the center moves
up onto Cuba.''
</P>
<P>
   The hurricane is already looking ragged _ a tight spiral of
clouds denotes a stronger, more dangerous storm _ as it seems
headed, forecasters tentatively predicted, for the Florida Straits
and then on into the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   That would carry the storm over or close to the Florida Keys,
where emergency management officials Wednesday ordered an
evacuation of tourists _ a move that they hoped would open up the
roads for Keys residents if they are ordered to leave later this
week.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're just asking residents right now to put their hurricane
plans into effect,'' said Becky Herrin, a spokeswoman for the
Monroe County Emergency Operations Center.
</P>
<P>
   The worst thing that could happen, said the state's emergency
management officials, is for people fleeing the coast to be trapped
in traffic as a storm bears down.
</P>
<P>
   Keys residents, who are accustomed to such things, boarded up
windows with plywood, stocked up on water and flashlight batteries,
and watched their televisions for the latest weather updates. But,
as the storm weakened, some residents relaxed, let their dogs out
for a run on the unusually quiet streets, and waited.
</P>
<P>
   In the usually boisterous bars on Duval Street, people who rely
on the tourists for their living said they definitely were not
better off alone.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's dead, for us,'' said Kathy Wolfort, a bartender and
waitress in the famous Key West bar, Sloppy Joe's. ``Usually right
now, our whole dining room is full.'' Of the 65 tables in the
restaurant, only 15 were being used.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasters warned that the good news about Debby might not
last, and that the storm could strengthen once it heads back over
water, perhaps in the Straits or the Gulf, and said it could
threaten the west coast of Florida, or the Panhandle, or elsewhere
in the Gulf.
</P>
<P>
   The storm skirted Puerto Rico, but brought only minimum damage
there and in the U.S. Virgin Islands.
</P>
<P>
   In Miami, some residents went to buy plywood and other emergency
supplies, but the threat, at least for the city and surrounding
area, seemed to have evaporated.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't look to us like there is any chance this will
become a hurricane, at least in the short term,'' said Mayfield.
</P>
<P>
   But there was still a chance that the storm would turn slightly
more north, and threaten South Florida.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to let our guard down,'' said Mayfield.
</P>
<P>
   If the storm does pass through the Straits and heads into the
warm waters of the Gulf, it could pick up strength and threaten the
Gulf Coast, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Hurricane Frederick in 1979 did just that, he said. It was a
ragged storm, too, but became a dangerous hurricane as it swept
across the Gulf to the coast of Alabama.
</P>
<P>
   Even if winds do not create much damage, the storm is expected
to bring torrential rains, wherever it makes landfall.
</P>
</TEXT>
