A0358 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e FT-STING-STILLASTAR-TEX     08-23 0408
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE>
EVERY LITTLE THING HE DOES IS MAGIC
</HEADLINE>
 FT-STING-STILL A STAR-TEX  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By MALCOLM MAYHEW 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There's something very strange about the top 10 zone of the pop
charts this week: Sting is on it.
</P>
<P>
   At a time when Britney won't budge, 'N Sync is unstoppable and
Papa Roach continues to threaten everyone, the middle-aged
Englishman seems a bit, well, out of place.
</P>
<P>
   He is not popular with kids.
</P>
<P>
   Kids are probably unaware of who he is.
</P>
<P>
   Heck, point to a 13-year-old who's even heard of the Police _
Sting's old band, that is, not who Eminem is always wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   Born Gordon Sumner, Sting does indeed look odd next to the
soundtrack to ``Nutty Professor II: The Klumps.'' What may be a
little odder is that Sting's disc, ``Brand New Day,'' will be a
year old next month. In other words, it's taken this long for it to
take off.
</P>
<P>
   Credit that to the single ``Desert Rose,'' a staple of adult
contemporary radio. ``Brand New Day's'' first batch of singles all
but flopped, temporarily dooming ``Day.'' ``Rose'' resurrected it.
</P>
<P>
   The song could not have come at a better time, as Sting has
embarked on a concert tour with ticket prices going up to the
ludicrous amount of $100. That's for one ticket.
</P>
<P>
   But Sting's career has always been a series of horror stories
that take a turn for the better and conclude happily.
</P>
<P>
   The onetime construction worker, tax clerk and teacher was a
fool, he was told at the time, to walk away from the Police, which,
in 1983 and '84, was the most popular rock group in the country,
with a multi-platinum album, ``Synchronicity,'' a string of singles
(including the immortal ``Every Breath You Take'') and a massive
world tour that would set precedents for other tours.
</P>
<P>
   But Sting would find fame as a solo artist. And as that solo
career began, Sting was dogged for abandoning the Police's
reggae-tinged rock for a jazzier, smoother, more polished sound.
</P>
<P>
   Again, naysayers were proven wrong: Sting's solo discs have sold
incredibly well and are anchored by numerous hits. Even if he
didn't play any Police material in concert _ he does, by the way _
his shows could easily be a greatest-hits disc played live. He's
had that many hit singles.
</P>
<P>
   And if ``Rose'' is any indication of his staying power, he'll
continue to do so.
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
</P>
</TEXT>
