A0363 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-HNS &LR;      08-23 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE'S IN SPOTLIGHT, BUT LIEBERMAN DAZZLES FLORIDA RETIREMENT
COMMUNITY 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By BENNETT ROTH 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMARAC, Fla. _ Al Gore may be the big shot on the Democratic
presidential ticket. But it was the man he tapped to be his running
mate, Joe Lieberman, who swept away the crowd Wednesday when he and
Gore dropped by a South Florida retirement community.
</P>
<P>
   As the first Jewish American on a major party presidential
ticket, Lieberman was greeted by the heavily Jewish crowd at the
Kings Point Community Center with the affection and enthusiasm
usually showered on a bar mitzvah boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like I'm in a roomful of family,'' Lieberman told a
crowd so large that many had to watch the event on a television
screen in an adjoining lobby.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's great to be in South Florida. Where else would the mayor
come up to me and say `shalom aleichem?' '' he said, referring to
the Hebrew greeting ``peace be with you.''
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman, an Orthodox Jew, sprinkled Yiddishisms throughout his
speech, at one time referring to himself and Gore as
``nuchschleppers'' _ or tag-alongs _ saying their wives, Tipper and
Hadassah, often appeared more popular with voters than the
candidates. Lieberman also described Gore as having a ``Yiddishe
neshoma'' _ a Jewish soul.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the speeches, the senior center band struck up a
rendition of ``Hava Nagila,'' as the enthusiastic crowds mobbed the
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   One woman grabbed Lieberman's hand and kissed it, leaving a
residue of bright red lipstick.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's like kissing the Torah,'' she exclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   Nancy Saylor, who watched the event on the television screen in
the lobby, said Lieberman was a good choice not just because he was
Jewish.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing negative has been said about that man,'' she said.
``He is just what we call a `mensch' '' _ a Yiddish word
characterizing a good or dependable person.
</P>
<P>
   Lieberman also played to the partisan sentiments of this
overwhelmingly Democratic crowd. The two-term Connecticut senator
ripped Republican opponent George W. Bush's $1.3 trillion tax plan,
arguing it would ``give the most to those who need it the least and
the least who need it the most.''
</P>
<P>
   He also mocked Bush for acknowledging this week that he had not
explained his tax plan well enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``The problem isn't explaining the tax cut plan. The problem is
the plan itself,'' Lieberman said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush spokesman Dan Bartlett responded, ``Senator Lieberman is
severely distorting and misrepresenting Governor Bush's tax plan
based on faulty numbers provided by the labor-backed group Citizens
for Tax Justice. Al Gore believes that 50 million Americans
representing more than half of all taxpayers don't deserve any tax
relief.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush spent a day off the campaign trail in Austin Wednesday. He
has campaign appearances scheduled Thursday in Louisiana and
Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Gore refrained from attacking Bush but suggested that he and not
his Republican rival was providing detailed explanations of his
campaign promises.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you want to hear about generalities and platitudes or do
you want to hear about specifics?'' he asked the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Tailoring his message to a crowd familiar with health care
needs, Gore promoted one piece of his $500 billion tax cut plan
that would provide a $3,000 a credit for long-term care.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also joined in the shtick when someone in the crowd yelled
``mazel tov'' after he mentioned the birth of his first grandchild
last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mazel tov,'' said Gore, repeating the Hebrew phrase used to
extend congratulations.
</P>
<P>
   Gore aides believe that having Lieberman on the ticket will help
them in states like Florida that have large Jewish populations. But
some analysts contend that the benefit will be only marginal since
Jews historically have voted Democratic.
</P>
<P>
   In Florida, the Jewish population, many of them retirees from
the Northeast who are clustered on the southeast coast, make up
about 6 percent of the state's voters.
</P>
<P>
   Even though George W. Bush's brother, Jeb, is the state's
governor, Gore campaign officials still hold they have a chance in
a state won by President Clinton in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   While Gore may have scored points with the crowd at the senior
center, most of those interviewed said they never were inclined to
vote Republican.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like having a president who doesn't have a Jesus Day in his
state,'' said Jeanne Hirschman, referring to Bush's designating
such a day in Texas last June.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Baer said, ``I would have voted for Gore in any case. But
Lieberman makes it nicer.''
</P>
<P>
   But Shirley Hirchbein disagreed with her friends who said that
religion wasn't a factor in their support of the ticket.
</P>
<P>
   She said Lieberman ``is a good man and the fact that he's Jewish
helps, don't kid yourself.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXXXEND OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
</TEXT>
