<DOCNO> NYT20000823.0328 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0364 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-BEAUTY-BOOK-REVIEW-NY     08-23 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAUTY-BOOK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`AMERICAN BEAUTY': PUTTING A STOP TO THE ART IN THE NAME OF
ACTIVISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: Publication notes appear at end of review.)  
 By RICHARD EDER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   We know that the greatest surgeons believe in something beyond
cutting, that the greatest generals believe in something beyond
war.
</P>
<P>
   With artists it's not clear: art for art's sake or for something
beyond? Even if it is for the beyond _ truth or transformation, say
_ do you get there by looking past the instruments (the surgeon
putting aside the knife for a moment; the general silencing the
guns) or by using them with greater exigency and abnegation?
Perhaps it is not the artist's, general's or surgeon's vocation
that is set aside, but the hyper-trophied modes and swollen
ambitions that encrust themselves in it.
</P>
<P>
   It was a generational question for the distinguished Polish poet
Adam Zagajewski. In the 1970s, along with many of his fellow
artists and intellectuals, he interrupted his modernist ironies and
aesthetic explorations _ involving mainly nonlethal clashes with
the communist censorship _ for outright activism.
</P>
<P>
   His group called itself Now. It sent rickety shuttle-loads of
the black-sweatered (the garb favored by these ex-aesthetes) to
unheated meeting halls in towns and cities around Poland. Instead
of poetry they talked about justice and political and economic
change. A police car stood outside, but in those erratically
repressive years the policemen rarely stepped inside.
</P>
<P>
   Now offered Zagajewski ``the bitter bread of urgency, of
contemporaneity,'' he writes in ``Another Beauty. ``It ripped me
from the lovely sphere in which time doesn't count, where I could
read Norwid one day and Kafka the next, as if the real, historical
worlds in which they lived were completely extraneous. It was a
descent from the clouds, a departure from the land of dreams, a
brutal encounter with the ugliness of the present.
</P>
<P>
   ``For this `now' was uncommonly ugly: a graceless moment in an
ugly country conquered by Moscow and sentenced to mediocrity in
virtually every domain.''
</P>
<P>
   He continues: ``I proclaimed the primacy of `obligation' over
pleasure, sobriety over reverie, society over the solitary reader
and poet. Amazingly enough, a program closer to self-flagellation
than to art began at some point to attract the attention of a
public that would no doubt have remained entirely indifferent if I
had stayed true to my leisurely, `eternal' dreams.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed. But Zagajewski, unlike some of his black-sweatered
fellows, has become neither a politician nor founder of a start-up
money pot. He remains a poet; one whose distinction is to reconcile
aesthetic exploration with what happened to him in Now's decrepit
train-and-van trips. ``If,'' he writes, ``such a thing can be
done.''
</P>
<P>
   Well it can be. If Zagajewski is not on the titan level of a
Czeslaw Milosz (his mentor in some respects), it may be because,
belonging to a younger, post-Stalin generation, he has not been
plunged into Milosz's depths, nor had to work back up from such a
profound sense of the tragic. He too is a healer, of sorts, but the
wound is not so deep and the healing not so uncanny.
</P>
<P>
   At its best, though, it is remarkable and shines through this
commonplace-book of sketches, reflections and bits of personal and
poetic history. Zagajewski places himself at an opposite end from
the French-Romanian E.M. Cioran, compiler of an epigrammatic
encyclopedia of despair. He, to the contrary, can write only out of
happiness. A touch of Panglossian uplift occasionally creeps into
``Another Beauty.'' Mostly the author _ sadder and wiser and
nonetheless hopeful _ is a far-from-gullible Candide.
</P>
<P>
   There are moments of self-mockery, phrased with comic
indirection. Zagajewski pictures himself typing a manifesto for
Now, while Sunday Mass-goers clack by beneath his window.
</P>
<P>
   ``The two kinds of tapping _ high heels and my typewriter _
mingled from time to time. There were no other sounds; the
blackbirds hadn't started singing yet. Carpenters didn't saw wood
on Sundays, ironworkers didn't labor in their cramped, noisy
shops.'' As for him, ``I churned out leaflets and counted on the
support of the working class.''
</P>
<P>
   The author describes the reading room at the Beaubourg library
in Paris. Every little while a loudspeaker breaks into the readers'
reveries, warning them to watch for pickpockets. ``Each reader
glances up involuntarily, struggling to understand what's going on.
But it's only pickpockets.'' He imagines the loudspeakers taking
over: ``Would the lady seated at table four please cease her
ecstasies over Baudelaire and pick up something pleasanter and
easier to read?''
</P>
<P>
   He writes evocatively of strolls through Krakow, an
architectural frontier between German Gothic and the lightness of
Northern Renaissance. He longs for Mediterranean light but is loyal
to his city's darkness. The stained glass windows in the churches
are splotches of black, he recalls, contrasting them with the
light-dazzled windows of Chartres Cathedral, which ``towered
proudly above a small provincial town like the Iliad over Greece.''
</P>
<P>
   There are melancholy portraits of his old professors, prewar
stars bypassed and impoverished when the communists took over. He
writes of a retired clerk who preserves his three suits by lying
down all day. ``If he used up anything it could only be oxygen and
time.''
</P>
<P>
   He touches on poetry and a summer evening musicale. He cites a
friend on what most impressed him traveling about the world: ``The
ubiquity of sparrows.'' The writer Alexander Wat is quoted:
``Compare French and German string quartets. You'll see at once who
has the stronger army.'' He evokes Krakow's cramped apartments,
where broken things are retained, just in case (counter to the
decreed utopian future) time were to run the other way suddenly and
tick-tock broken things back into repair.
</P>
<P>
   Amid this lovely bric-a-brac, we read of a devout aunt who made
friends with the parish priest next door and invited him to dinner.
The priest hit it off with her philologist husband, a devout
atheist. Friendship and regular dinners ensued. To the aunt's
bemusement it was not piety but the whet and flash of argument that
lured the visitor. A pleasant story, but beware the bomb concealed
when a poet is being pleasant. The priest was Karol Wojtyla.
</P>
<P>
   PUBLICATION NOTES:
</P>
<P>
   `ANOTHER BEAUTY'
</P>
<P>
   By Adam Zagajewski
</P>
<P>
   Translated by Clare Cavanagh. 215 pages. Farrar, Straus &AMP;
Giroux. $23.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-00 2015EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000823.0329 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 20:18 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0366 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-CHINA-INTERNET-1STLD-     08-23 0308
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHINA-INTERNET-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CHINA ARRESTS INTERNET CAFE OWNER FOR POSTING POLITICAL ARTICLES 
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS 2nd graf to correct spelling of Nontong to NANCHONG; subs
hed) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ The owner of an Internet cafe in southern China has
been arrested and charged with subversion for posting articles
critical of the Communist Party, the latest sign of the
government's campaign to tame the explosion of electronic
information.
</P>
<P>
   Jiang Shihua, a high school teacher who operated the cafe in the
city of Nanchong in Sichuan Province, is the third person in recent
months known to face serious charges for political statements on
the Internet. His arrest on Aug. 16, five days after he began
posting the articles under a pseudonym, was reported this week by
the Free China Movement in Washington, based on accounts by Chinese
television and Reporters Without Borders, a media watchdog group in
Paris.
</P>
<P>
   China's leaders have embraced the Internet as a key to
development but also fear it, and special ``Web police'' units have
been formed to search for illegal activities like fraud and
pornography as well as outlawed political debate.
</P>
<P>
   In another case, Huang Qi, who ran a Web site from Sichuan that
published statements on the student democracy movement that was
crushed in 1989 and other rights issues, was charged with
subversion in June.
</P>
<P>
   Another man, Qi Yanchen, of Hebei Province, has been charged
with the same crime for posting anti-government messages, according
to rights groups. None of the three arrested men has been tried,
but convictions in such cases are nearly certain and can bring long
prison terms.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, the authorities shut down New Culture Forum,
a Web site in Shandong Province that sponsored debate on the need
for democracy.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-00 2018EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000823.0330 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 20:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0367 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-AMAZON-CARS-800&AMP;ADD-N     08-23 1132
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMAZON-CARS-800&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AMAZON.COM PLANS TO SELL CARS ONLINE 
</HEADLINE>
  By KEITH BRADSHER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEARBORN, Mich. _ Amazon.com, one of the world's largest online
retailers, announced on Wednesday that it would begin offering a
car-selling service on the Internet, the latest and potentially
most serious challenge to the ability of automakers to control the
distribution of automobiles.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning early Thursday morning, Amazon shoppers will be able
to compare features for hundreds of models from various brands.
They will be able to configure a chosen car or light truck with
various options and then obtain a price quote and estimated
delivery date for their vehicle.
</P>
<P>
   But while buyers will be able to put down a deposit through
Amazon, using their credit cards, customers will buy the vehicle
itself from a local dealer, either at a dealership or by having
dealership employees deliver it.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon will market automobiles through an alliance with
Greenlight.com, a privately held online company owned by several
big chains of auto dealerships and by various venture capitalists.
In January, Amazon announced that it had bought a 5 percent stake
in Greenlight.
</P>
<P>
   By requiring customers to buy vehicles from dealers at the end
of the process, Amazon and Greenlight hope to circumvent
restrictive state laws that have entangled companies that have
sought to buy cars from dealers and actually resell them to
consumers. Greenlight has affiliated dealers in 27 metropolitan
areas who will provide the cars for the venture.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Bezos, Amazon's founder and chief executive, and Joel
Manby, the chief executive of Greenlight, said their companies had
carefully designed the plan to comply with state laws. Tweaking the
auto industry, they announced their plan on Wednesday at the
Automotive Hall of Fame, less than a mile from Ford's headquarters
in this southwestern suburb of Detroit.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon's shares rose 2 5/16 to 38 13/16.
</P>
<P>
   Consumers who buy from CarsDirect.com, another online car buying
service, pay all of the vehicle's price directly to the service,
which then passes the money on, after subtracting a small profit
margin, to a dealer, who delivers the car and its title directly to
the buyer. Because the company acts as a principal in the
transactions, it drew criticism from some state regulators and
recently decided not to do business in Texas and 10 other states.
</P>
<P>
   Manby said that Greenlight, by not acting as a principal in a
transaction, would be able to do business nationwide, including
Texas. He declined to say how much of the deposit that customers
pay Amazon would be forwarded to the dealers supplying the cars.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Kent, the enforcement director in the motor vehicle
division of the Texas Transportation Department, said that her
agency was allowing Greenlight to do business there.
</P>
<P>
   Ford Motor Co. quickly criticized the plan, saying that it did
not allow dealers to play a large enough role in selling the
vehicles. Stephen Lyons, Ford's general sales manager, said the
arrangement essentially amounted to brokering cars that are
purchased from dealers _ an activity that some states prohibit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their model isn't satisfactory to us in terms of how they
satisfy customers and bring dealers in,'' Lyons said. ``We view
them, as others, as electronic brokers, because what they do is
offer our vehicles.''
</P>
<P>
   General Motors announced plans a week ago to set up its own site
that would provide information on all brands of automobiles,
including those of rival automakers, but would refer customers to
dealers for actual sales. Terry Sullivan, a GM spokesman, said that
the automaker did not comment on other companies' Internet
ventures, but believed in general that dealers should handle sales.
</P>
<P>
   Automakers say they want dealers to sell their cars because only
dealers have the experience and knowledge needed to teach customers
about a new vehicle and then provide warranty repairs and other
service during subsequent years. The automakers have taken this
position partly because of pressure from multifranchise dealers,
who have warned that they may be less energetic in selling models
made by those automakers that do not fight back against online
sales.
</P>
<P>
   Automakers have the legal ability to create problems for Amazon
and Greenlight. Ford and GM have announced plans not to send
dealers new cars to replace cars that they sell through services
that the automakers view as brokers. Foreign automakers have said
that they want to sell cars mainly through dealers, although they
have not made specific threats to withhold new vehicles from
dealers that work with brokers.
</P>
<P>
   Lyons said that one of the dealership chains involved with
Amazon and Greenlight, Sonic Automotive, had already agreed not to
sell Ford vehicles through the service, while Ford is in
negotiations with a chain of 125 dealerships, Asbury Automotive,
which helped found Greenlight.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Online retailing of automobiles was dominated until recently by
former car dealers who set up specialty sites, like Peter Ellis,
who created Autobytel.com, the leading online auto retailer in the
late 1990s. But such sites have been struggling as they face
competition from bigger, more established companies.
</P>
<P>
   America Online recently allied itself with the nation's largest
dealership chain, AutoNation, which is controlled by Wayne
Huizenga, the Florida investor best known for having built Waste
Management, the garbage disposal company, and Blockbuster, the
video rental chain. Under a plan similar to Amazon's, America
Online will put an auto retailing link on its home page late next
month that will allow users to select cars from 300 AutoNation
sites around the country and another 900 dealerships that use
AutoNation's online buying program, AutoVantage. AutoNation sold $1
billion worth of vehicles last year to people who initially
contacted the company through its Internet sites.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jackson, AutoNation's chief executive, said he did not
regard Amazon and Greenlight as a serious threat. He contended that
it was impossible to make money without having a single company
that owns both the dealerships and the Internet referral service.
Automakers have not objected to AutoNation's arrangement because
dealers play a larger role in the transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Amazon has been struggling with huge losses that have been
draining its cash. Bezos said that Greenlight would pay $15.25
million to Amazon over two years as part of the arrangement. While
Amazon will audit Greenlight's customer satisfaction, Greenlight
will handle most of the auto retailing activities on the Amazon
site. Amazon had previously provided a link to Greenlight's site.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
