<DOCNO> NYT20000823.0334 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 20:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0371 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r e BC-CRENSHAW-RETROSPECTIV     08-23 1090
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CRENSHAW-RETROSPECTIVE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RETROSPECTIVE PLEASE THE MAN HIMSELF
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients.) 
(Eds: Fact box below. `Tonight' refers to Sat., Aug. 26, 2000) 
By DAVID BLOOM 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Across an expanse of 20-odd years, the glistening pop of
Marshall Crenshaw still shines sweetly, music with smarts and hooks
and, wow, a beat you can even dance to sometimes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's guitar-dominated, and it all starts with wanting to play
the guitar in the first place,'' Crenshaw said. ``It's like highly
nuanced, finely detailed, cool rock music, sort of, with really
good rhythms and just sort of adventurous and different sonic
textures from album to album, intelligent, groovy, passionate
stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, the album that first put Crenshaw on the pop firmament, his
eponymous debut augmented with several tracks, and a crackerjack
retrospective called ``This Is Easy: The Very Best of Marshall
Crenshaw,'' are hitting store shelves, while Crenshaw himself is
hitting the stage in a show tonight in Santa Monica's McCabe's
Guitar Shop.
</P>
<P>
   It's all been a chance for Crenshaw to review fruits of a
rewarding _ artistically if not always commercially _ career,
starting with that first album, which came out in 1982 to
overwhelmingly positive reviews.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are a lot of people who really love that record,''
Crenshaw said. ``I'm pleased about that, because it's been a long
while now since I made it and it's stood a test of time. I really
love it. It did make a big impact in its time.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Crenshaw isn't entirely happy with his work on that
first effort, despite the hosannas it received (and continues to
garner _ Daily News reviewer Glenn Whipp gave the reissue a
highest-possible four stars this week).
</P>
<P>
   ``I was raw and unformed as a singer, kind of groping vocally on
some of those tracks,'' he said. ``I have these criticisms of it,
but I'm fond of it.''
</P>
<P>
   At the time Crenshaw was writing the songs for his first album,
he was ``kind of rediscovering and dealing with a lot of rock `n'
roll stuff I'd loved in my childhood,'' he said. ``I was really
listening to a lot of rockabilly and getting back into stuff I knew
during childhood and was getting back to it as an adult.''
</P>
<P>
   He had been working as the understudy of the John Lennon
character in ``Beatlemania,'' on both the national tour and in runs
in Los Angeles and San Francisco. And it is the Beatles and Buddy
Holly and some of the earlier rock that influenced his writing of
the time.
</P>
<P>
   He took the big, open sounds and smacking rhythms of that music
and tried to adapt them to a more modern context.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the time I was getting there, I think,'' he said. ``I
had this real set idea of song structure, just bam-bam-bam and no
wasted motion. I did that for a while, but after about 20 songs
within those parameters, I had to bag it and throw away the rule
book.''
</P>
<P>
   With his second album, ``Field Day,'' he began exploring
different approaches, not always to the glee of fans he'd collected
with his debut. ``Field Day'' still had a couple of songs left over
from his earlier songwriting phase, including the transcendent
``Whenever You're on My Mind.''
</P>
<P>
   But ``For Her Love,'' another leftover of that initial
songwriting rush, ``really felt like I had to force it,'' Crenshaw
said. So he began trying other things.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could compose melodies really easily, and could go as deep
emotionally with (lyrics) as I could and stretch out,'' Crenshaw
said. ``That was the direction I went in 'Field Day.' I really
caught a ton of (grief) from people for the way my second album
sounded. But it was just a really great representation of my tastes
then.''
</P>
<P>
   He recorded five albums for Warner Bros. and another for MCA,
put out a collection of demos, a live album and two more recent
studio albums for the independent Razor &AMP; Tie.
</P>
<P>
   Along the way, he's played with artists such as Don Dixon, the
BoDeans and Was (Not Was); had his songs covered by artists as
diverse as Bette Midler and the Gin Blossoms; acted in ``Peggy Sue
Got Married'' and as Buddy Holly in ``La Bamba''; and helped put
together a book of good and bad rock movies called ``Hollywood Rock
&AMP; Roll.''
</P>
<P>
   Now 46, Crenshaw said the best-of collection, which Rhino is
also releasing, is another source of great pride, a chance for even
him to look back on his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually got really excited about it when it was all
mastered,'' Crenshaw said. ``I got my reference CD and listened to
it on a long plane ride home. I was just happy to hear it. It's a
really good body of work. I don't listen to my stuff, and I forget
what it sounds like. But there's a lot of different textures and
tracks as you go through it.''
</P>
<P>
   These days, with two children less than 4 years old and a place
in New York City, he leads a very different life than in the
knock-around years before he finally got serious about songwriting
in the early 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just being here, being back in the city, I'm taking in a lot
of information, and different kinds of information,'' Crenshaw
said. ``Kids change what I listen to.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, after reading that some kinds of music can improve
learning skills for young children, he started playing more jazz
and orchestral music, especially great pianists such as Bill Evans
and Fats Waller.
</P>
<P>
   But he said he'll always be a rocker, with none of the classical
and operatic pretensions of quasi-contemporary pop craftsmen such
as Paul McCartney, Pete Townshend, Joe Jackson and Billy Joel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not really drawn in that direction,'' Crenshaw said. ``The
first thing I always deal with when I write songs is the rhythm:
What's the tempo, what's the groove, what's the feel?''
</P>
<P>
   The past couple of years, he's been touring a lot on the East
Coast, often doing solo shows because he is ``really big on the
simplicity of the solo stuff. I don't have to cut any checks (for
other musicians). I don't have to worry about who's going to be the
bass player that night.''
</P>
<P>
   And he's pretty content, Crenshaw said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a sense of satisfaction now about it,'' Crenshaw said.
``Until I did this `Best of,' I had this ambivalence about the
records I've made. But now I just sort feel like it's a good body
of work. It's all kind of resolved for me at this point.'' &QL; 
--- &QL; 
Who: Marshall Crenshaw, with Bruce Henderson opening. &QL; 
Where: McCabe's Guitar Shop, 3101 Pico Blvd., Santa Monica. &QL; 
When: 7:30 and 10 tonight. &QL; 
Tickets: $17.50. &QL; 
Information: (310) 828-8037. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
