<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 20:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0373 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r e BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX     08-23 1073
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-PERKINS-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IF ELEANOR WERE TELEVISION, SHE'D BE PRIME TIME
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By KEN PARISH PERKINS 
 c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Her first dispatch arrived near midnight on a Sunday, a rambling
voice-mail message about faith and destiny and life being what one
does with blown opportunities and sucker punches strong enough to
disorient the senses. Not until the end of the message was there a
hint of Eleanor's utter disgust over my column about the weekly
sameness of ``Touched By an Angel,'' what I called its superficial
messages of hope and triumph, and my growing annoyance with the
character played by Della Reese.
</P>
<P>
   ``Systematically flawed'' was the way Eleanor described the
column's contents, picking off each paragraph like a sharpshooter
at a firing range. Convinced we'd viewed totally different shows,
she asked, in a straightforward manner: ``Are you mentally stable?
Who in their right mind doesn't like Della Reese?''
</P>
<P>
   For weeks, I thought Eleanor was a midnight caller, those
readers who call late so they miss you and thereby get what they
truly want: a one-sided conversation with themselves.
</P>
<P>
   How so untrue. Eleanor called again one morning on another
matter, then a few days later, and in the early evening a week
after that. Our conversations _ or verbal duels or testimonials _
would settle into a routine of two, three times a week, usually at
midday, after Eleanor's two eggs, scrambled, with toast and coffee,
and definitely after ``The View.'' (''I wish that chubby Star Jones
would get a man and shut her trap.'') Sometimes we'd talk five days
a week, depending on my output and how systematically flawed those
stories were.
</P>
<P>
   In due time, the conversations became less confrontational, more
passionate than heated _ and always interesting, to the point, and
edifying. We talked race, gender, children, sports, politics and
even compared the merits of Target, Kmart and Wal-Mart. We were
close on some issues, far apart on many others, a byproduct of two
lives shaped from very different molds. I liked her because she
didn't care about agreeing with me.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor often called herself a typical reader, although I always
told her that such a person does not exist. There is no ``typical''
reader, but there are people who pick up the paper every day who
know what they want out of it and who are less than thrilled when
they don't find it.
</P>
<P>
   Those who read TV columns are fanatics and cynics, the curious
and the bored; they are even people who sit and watch TV only when
they're too tired to think.
</P>
<P>
   There's the housewife in Arlington with a workaholic husband.
She simply likes to talk around 2 p.m., when house cleaning is done
and dinner is started and boredom has set in. There's the retiree
from Southlake, married 52 years to a man whom she has never seen
watch a TV program from beginning to end. There's the 16-year-old
from Arlington Heights High School in Fort Worth who thinks her
boyfriend is lazy and wonders if dating outside her race is social
suicide. There's the 20-year-old Texas Christian University student
who rewrites episodes of ``Frasier,'' then recites them over the
phone line.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, that was a good one _ well-thought out, well-researched,
well-written,'' Eleanor would sometimes say to me. Or: ``Boy, did
you miss the boat on that one. Not feeling well, are we?''
</P>
<P>
   Hers were often the rants of a demanding viewer and reader, so
much a lover of television that the squandering of its promise and
power angered her. She was smart and sharp and frustratingly blunt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Wait a minute,'' I said to her one day. ``You're telling me
that it's OK for networks to totally disregard viewers over 50?''
</P>
<P>
   She told me that it was, that it was a business decision, that
advertisers are right when they say older viewers are set in their
ways and should therefore be ignored, and that few viewers want to
watch ``old folks like us'' play TV characters. Eleanor's
assessment was built on the notion that young people can't relate
to older characters and older viewers don't want to.
</P>
<P>
   ``We never paid much attention to commercials or print
advertisements; she used the same product for the past 20 years as
long as it was available,'' Sadie, her youngest daughter, said the
other day. ``Same with TV shows. I don't think she's ever missed an
episode of `Law &AMP; Order.' '' Sadie told me that early life for
Eleanor was a two-room shack outside Greenville, S.C., a place kept
clean with old rags soaked in water pumped from a nearby well.
Eleanor came to TV late, after her marriage to Arthur, an insurance
executive, who died 10 years ago in a boating accident. Eleanor
never worked outside the home.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur's job brought them to Fort Worth, where they raised three
girls and a boy, now all grown.
</P>
<P>
   Sadie says Eleanor's life became centered on TV after she
developed breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We worried at first, but felt relieved, in a strange way, that
she was tied to something like TV programs,'' Sadie says. ``We'd
hear her talk out loud, `Oh, gotta call that Ken about this,' like
it had become her duty.''
</P>
<P>
   Remission brought more calls from Eleanor during the beginning
of last season. She fell for ``Once and Again,'' about
40-somethings navigating divorce, and the White House drama ``The
West Wing,'' which she called ``hokey'' but added, ``Oh, that
Martin Sheen is some looker.''
</P>
<P>
   Her favorite show was the '60s classic ``The Dick Van Dyke
Show.'' Her least favorite was ``Diagnosis Murder,'' Which made
sense, considering her respect for Van Dyke's talent.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor faded with the season last spring, as cancer returned
and series finales were being aired. The cancer had spread to her
lungs and other parts of her body. She died a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   When I heard the news, I thought of our last conversation, a
brief one concerning a column I'd written about the so-called
family hour. She phoned to say there was never such a thing, that
TV networks had always aired objectionable material at 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor cut the conversation short, saying she was tired and
needed to get back to her tube.
</P>
<P>
   She'd missed ``Law &AMP; Order'' the night before but had had a
neighbor tape it. ``Hear that?'' she said of the humming sound
vibrating from her old VCR. ``Time to go. You be blessed, you
hear?''
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
