<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 20:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0375 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-ARTHUR-PENN-ART-2T     08-23 1351
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-ARTHUR-PENN-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTHUR PENN TAKES `BONNIE AND CLYDE' SKILLS TO THE SIDE OF `LAW AND
ORDER' 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT12 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By BERNARD WEINRAUB   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOLLYWOOD, Calif. _ Few directors in the 1960s and '70s rivaled
Arthur Penn. His Broadway shows included ``Two for the Seesaw,''
``The Miracle Worker,'' ``Toys in the Attic'' and ``All the Way
Home.'' His work in Hollywood was equally celebrated, with
inventive movies like ``Alice's Restaurant,'' ``Little Big Man,''
``The Miracle Worker'' and the enduring classic ``Bonnie and
Clyde.''
</P>
<P>
   Then in the mid-'80s Penn's film career seemed to shrink. A bad
experience or two in Hollywood, his decision to live in New York
and not Los Angeles and, most important, the lack of interest among
studios in his socially aware films soured Penn on the movie
business.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was frustrating and more than a little humiliating,'' said
the trim 77-year-old director, who seems a decade younger. His more
recent experience in the theater was not much better. Penn said he
had found that Broadway seemed more hospitable to blockbuster
musicals than to serious drama.
</P>
<P>
   So it was a shock, Penn said, when Dick Wolf, creator of NBC's
``Law and Order'' and one of television's foremost producers, asked
the director to dinner in New York and offered him the job of
executive producer on that show. Penn's pay for the season is
likely to top $1 million, talent agents said.
</P>
<P>
   Given that television is flagrant in its discrimination against
writers and producers over 50, Wolf's decision to appoint Penn is a
breakthrough for the elderly. ``I think there's this vast pool of
guys who have had incredible careers and are much more talented
than a lot of people who are having movies green-lit right how,''
Wolf said.
</P>
<P>
   The average age of the writing staff on ``Law and Order'' is 46,
he said. ``That's ancient on television,'' said Wolf, 53. ``But I'm
doing dramas, not `Friends.' For serious writing, miles on the
odometer are beneficial.'' (For the second season in a row, Wolf is
also using 69-year-old Ted Kotcheff, director of ``North Dallas
40,'' as executive producer of NBC's ``Law and Order: Special
Victims Unit.'')
</P>
<P>
   In his new job, Penn, who has made a handful of television
films, will oversee the creation of each episode of ``Law and
Order,'' working mostly with the directors and actors. Penn's son,
Matthew Penn, is one of the directors on the show, which revolves
around the police and a district attorney's office in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Wolf recalled, ``When Ed Sherin, who had been doing this job for
seven years, decided to leave, it was, like, who do you get to
replace someone who was that integral to the daily running and
daily success of that show?''
</P>
<P>
   Wolf said that Lewis Gould, one of the show's producers, came to
him and said, ``You know who Matt's Dad is _ Arthur Penn.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And I said, `Wow, what a great idea,''' Wolf continued. ``So I
had dinner with him, and when we had coffee I said to him, `Do you
want to run ``Law and Order''?' And he said yes. As you can tell,
it was a very complicated negotiation.''
</P>
<P>
   Wolf said that what appealed to him about Penn was his obvious
experience and talent working with stage actors. The cast of ``Law
and Order'' includes such theater actors as Sam Waterston, Jerry
Orbach and, starting in the fall, Dianne Wiest. (She will replace
Steven Hill, who played a district attorney.)
</P>
<P>
   Beyond that, Wolf said, Penn's signature in his early television
movies, as well as ``Bonnie and Clyde'' and other films, was
focusing a sociological lens on various moments in American
history. ``Bonnie and Clyde,'' he said, was not merely a film about
some lovers on a crime spree, but a film about the Depression.
``His pictures operate on two levels _ and we needed that for this
show,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Penn described his role on ``Law and Order'' as serving, in a
sense, as a mentor to the show's directors. Directing episodes has
no interest for him, Penn said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would rather be available to the young directors and be able
to talk to them about the possibilities,'' he said. ``A lot of
directors in television have come up through the technical ranks.
They have all the technical skills in the world. They're not all
that familiar with actors. And on `Law and Order' you have
wonderful racehorsy actors like Sam Waterston, Jerry Orbach and,
now, Dianne Wiest.''
</P>
<P>
   Penn, who talked about his new job in a breakfast interview at
the Peninsula Hotel in Beverly Hills, has lived for decades with
his wife, Peggy, a therapist, in a duplex apartment on Central Park
West and in Stockbridge, Mass. Aside from their son, they have a
daughter, Molly, a former arts administrator at Lincoln Center, and
four grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   Penn said he had always considered himself closer to the theater
than films. His career began in the 1950s in live television, but
his only television work in recent years was directing a drama,
``Inside,'' about apartheid in South Africa, for the Showtime cable
network.
</P>
<P>
   Although his words are shaded in bitterness when he talks about
the movie business, Penn spoke quietly and with some humor. Of the
film studios, he said, ``I didn't particularly like what they are
doing, so it was a very amicable divorce in that respect.''
</P>
<P>
   He shrugged at the notion of meeting studio executives in their
20s and 30s and recalled the famous Hollywood anecdote about the
time that Fred Zinnemann, the director of ``From Here to
Eternity,'' ``The Nun's Story,'' ``A Man for All Seasons'' and
other classics, had a meeting with a young studio executive.
</P>
<P>
   The executive said, ``So Zinnemann, what have you done?'' The
director responded, ``What have you done?''
</P>
<P>
   Penn laughed briefly. ``That's the way it is.'' But then he
added: ``In a sense that's how I was responded to out here. I
hadn't ever been part of the Hollywood community, so I didn't have
all these friendships with movie stars who are getting pictures
made. I wasn't Tom Cruise's buddy or Matt Damon's buddy. Not to
single them out. But there's a kind of buddy relationship that goes
on now in terms of getting pictures made.''
</P>
<P>
   Penn still seemed unsettled by his experience on the 1966
western ``The Chase,'' with Marlon Brando, Jane Fonda and Robert
Redford. While Penn was rehearsing the play ``Wait Until Dark'' on
Broadway, the film's producer, Sam Spiegel, took over the editing
of ``The Chase'' in London.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a pretty abusive experience for a lot of people,'' Penn
recalled. ``I really lost my appetite for movies for quite a
while.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the years he has taught at Yale and periodically directed
films and plays. For the past six years he has been president of
the Actors Studio in New York, where he has developed a successful
graduate program.
</P>
<P>
   Broadway, he feels, is too dependent on mega-musicals like
``Cats'' and ``Saigon,'' with the result that talented writers have
turned elsewhere. ``The vigor of the playwrights is somewhere
off-Broadway now,'' he said. ``And what's happened is a whole
generation has bypassed New York and theater and come out here.''
</P>
<P>
   Penn's film work also includes ``The Left-Handed Gun'' (1958),
``Mickey One'' (1965), ``Night Moves'' (1975), ``The Missouri
Breaks'' (1976) and ``Four Friends'' (1981).
</P>
<P>
   Warren Beatty, who starred in ``Mickey One'' as well as ``Bonnie
and Clyde,'' said of Penn, ``He has the soul of an artist.'' He
added, ``His intelligence is the factor that resonates most
strongly, his intelligence and a lack of interest in pandering.''
</P>
<P>
   Penn acknowledged that some of his later films were
disappointments and that studios lost interest in the social topics
that fascinated him. ``In each instance there was a certain social
comment about conditions that were prevalent at the time,'' he
said. ``There doesn't seem to be that kind of social concern now.''
Instead, he said, he sees the country as ``just sort of without
issues.''
</P>
<P>
</P>
<P>
   Certainly Penn's most enduring film _ and one that redefined
crime movies with, among other techniques, its use of slow motion _
was ``Bonnie and Clyde'' (1967), about the Depression-era bank
robbers. The film, which starred Beatty, Faye Dunaway, Gene Hackman
and Michael J. Pollard, almost died after it was released. Bosley
Crowther, writing in The New York Times, said it was ``as pointless
as it is lacking in taste.'' Newsweek called it ``a squalid
shoot-'em-up.'' But a rave review by Pauline Kael in The New Yorker
and a drumroll of interest among college students turned the film
into a cultural phenomenon. ``Time magazine panned the movie in a
brief review and five months later put it on the cover,'' Beatty
said.
</P>
<P>
   Penn recalled with a laugh how Beatty, as producer of the film,
manipulated Jack Warner, the studio chief, into supporting it.
``Jack Warner didn't like the film, couldn't figure it out at
all,'' Penn said. ``Warren was very clever. He told him that the
film was an hommage to the gangster films of Warner's past. And
Jack Warner said, `What's an hommage?'''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
