<DOCNO> NYT20000823.0339 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 20:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0377 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-MEXICO-U.S.-FOX-ART-4     08-23 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-U.S.-FOX-ART-450(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOX HOPES TO SEE MORE AND BETTER-TRAINED MEXICANS MIGRATE TO U.S. 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By GINGER THOMPSON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CORONEO, Mexico _ For eight hours each day, in a desolate
warehouse with stone walls, some 12 men and a couple of women in
this village of squat adobe houses learn to build furniture with
circular saws and power drills.
</P>
<P>
   The government pays for the training and gives each aspiring
carpenter a small stipend, but the goal is not to prepare them for
scarce and poorly paid jobs at home. It is to give them skills they
can use when they migrate _ usually illegally _ to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   The program is one of many begun here in the central Mexican
state of Guanajuato by the former governor, Vicente Fox, who is
making his first visit to Washington on Thursday since being
elected president in a landmark victory in June.
</P>
<P>
   Fox plans to use his informal meetings with President Clinton
and the two U.S. presidential candidates _ Vice President Al Gore
and Gov. George W. Bush of Texas _ to encourage them to join in his
vision of a sea change in relations along the 2,000-mile border, in
particular one more open to the flow of Mexican laborers. And as he
does so, the voices of those workers he has helped train in his
home state will echo in the background.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mexico has many working hands and America has many jobs,''
said Claudio Torres Resendiz, 33, one of those being trained in
Coroneo. ``We do the work they need, and they pay us the money we
need to take care of our families. Both sides benefit.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. officials have so far been less than enthusiastic about
Fox's idea. And his job-training programs, like the one here, have
been criticized both within and outside Mexico as encouraging the
exodus of Mexican laborers for menial jobs in the United States.
Some 340,000 already migrate each year.
</P>
<P>
   But Fox defends his initiatives _ which mostly offer training to
Mexicans in low-skill positions as landscapers, construction
workers, factory workers and maids _ as a pragmatic way to increase
the skills and the earning potential of workers that Mexico simply
cannot sustain.
</P>
<P>
   A straight-talking son of ranchers and a former business
executive who focuses on the bottom-line, Fox considers the labor
force one of his nation's proudest and most lucrative assets. His
plans for the border, he says, would force the United States to
face up to its need for Mexican workers, rather than treating the
migrants' contributions to the American economy as a kind of dirty
economic secret.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the people, and people are an asset'' Fox said in an
interview at his family ranch in the state of Guanajuato, before
leaving for the United States. ``I know many people in the United
States want to see people as a burden, as a problem, but people are
an asset.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is why we are going to invest and invest heavily in
people,'' the president-elect went on. ``If we have talented
people, not only will Mexico progress, the United States will
benefit and progress.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   When asked to explain his visions for an open border and better
work conditions for migrants, the typically practical Fox turns
suddenly passionate and casts back to life here in his home state
of Guanajuato. It is the state with Mexico's third-highest rate of
migration to the United States. During various seasons of the year,
isolated villages almost completely abandoned by able-bodied men
and women as they go to the United States to work.
</P>
<P>
   The carpentry training program Fox began here is far from
cutting edge. Students work primarily with outdated tools and learn
the most rudimentary techniques while assembling tables and chairs.
</P>
<P>
   But for workers like Torres, who was one of those training here
and has worked illegally on peanut and cotton farms in Mississippi
for the last 15 years, the introductory workshop not only means the
chance to make more money abroad, it will allow him to seek work
with his head held high.
</P>
<P>
   ``Working in the fields is very hard, and the pay is getting
worse,'' he said. ``But I did not have the chance to finish high
school, I had to take whatever work I could get. I am trying to
better myself so I do not have to take that humiliation anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   During his campaign for president, Fox was widely criticized for
a private initiative that has sent some 300 men from Guanajuato to
work legally as landscapers on golf courses in Michigan over the
last three years.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more popular promises of former President Carlos
Salinas de Gortari, as he negotiated the North American Free Trade
Agreement with the United States and Canada, was that Mexico would
strive to increase exports of products, not people. But the
benefits of NAFTA have been felt less among Mexico's 40 million
poor, and the number of Mexican immigrants to the United States has
not significantly declined.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike many of his predecessors, Fox publicly accepts his
country's inability to offer its workers the kinds of salaries and
living conditions as those offered in the United States. Until his
administration is able to begin narrowing wage gap _ he has pledged
annual economic growth of 7 percent and to create 1.35 million new
jobs each year _ Fox wants more Mexican workers to be able to cross
the border without violence and harassment. And he wants to make it
easier for immigrants to invest more of their earnings from abroad
back home.
</P>
<P>
   An example of that kind of economic return stands at the
entrance of a village called Timbinal, where Napa Valley vineyard
workers funded the construction of a small apparel factory to
employ women who stay behind.
</P>
<P>
   One of the workers, Rosa Maria Sierra Lopez, 21, said her job at
the plant was the first thing in her life that made her feel
useful. But its not enough to make up for the pain that the
northern migration inflicts on her town and her home.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the men there, she said, spend more time in the United
States than they do at home. And each year, her 52-year-old father
risks his life by illegally crossing the United States border to
work in apple orchards in the American Northwest. It's a journey
he's made, Sierra said, since before she was born.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very hard for us to see him go,'' she said, pressing her
eyes closed to hold back tears. ``It's hard for all of us.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As expected, Fox's talk of opening the border to increased legal
migration has been met mostly with polite skepticism from officials
in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   And while analysts consider Fox's trip to be the beginning of a
long campaign _ one that Fox himself predicts could take 30 years _
none dismissed the president-elect's ideas as impossible. Labor
groups as well as immigrant activists have joined together to
support legislation proposed by Sen. Edward M. Kennedy, D-Mass.,
that would legalize some 1.1 million undocumented residents.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in the U.S. hear open border and they panic,'' said
Pamela Falk, a former staff director of the Western Hemisphere
Subcommittee in the House of Representatives. ``That's not what
he's trying to do. He's trying to adjust the laws to fit the
reality in a way that would be good for the American economy and
for Mexican workers.''
</P>
<P>
   John Bailey, director of the Mexico Project at Georgetown
University said: ``At first I thought Fox was pushing a nonstarter.
But my second reaction was that what he says is really interesting.
And even though he may not get everything he wants, he will get a
new conversation started.''
</P>
<P>
   Ismael Rojas, 65, doubts he'll see the day when the men in his
native La Calera will stop leaving their families to work in the
United States. He did it for 25 years _ most of that time as an
undocumented worker _ and his sinuses are still choked from his
work at an Illinois lumber company.
</P>
<P>
   He has retired to the sprawling house he built with his life's
earnings. There are two cars and a tractor parked inside a huge
shed in the back and the garden is full of fruit trees.
</P>
<P>
   Everything he has, he said, comes from his labor in the United
States. Now it's his sons who work up north. One earned legal
status under a broad amnesty passed by Congress in 1986; the other
has a seasonal permit to work at a golf course in Michigan.
</P>
<P>
   Like all fathers, he's happy to see that his sons do not have to
endure the insecurity and shame of living illegally in the United
States. Still, Rojas said, the advances are bittersweet.
</P>
<P>
   ``In Mexico, the choices are you can either abandon your
children to make money to take care of them, or you can stay with
you children and watch them live in misery,'' he said. ``Poverty
makes us leave our families. I want President Fox to create jobs,
jobs that are well-paid, so that our families can stay together.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
