<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 20:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0379 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-SUBMARINE-1STL     08-23 1240
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-SUBMARINE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN ADDRESS TO NATION, PUTIN TRIES TO CURB CRITICISM OF KURSK
DISASTER 
</HEADLINE>
  (SUBS to add new text to end of original article with details of
salvage efforts) 
(See also RUSSIA-ASSESS) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ As Russia grieved for 118 seamen lost in the remains of
the submarine Kursk, President Vladimir Putin moved decisively to
contain the incident's political impact, going on national
television Wednesday night to take responsibility for what some
Russians call a badly botched response.
</P>
<P>
   In an abruptly scheduled half-hour interview on the
state-controlled television network RTR, Putin said a family member
of a submarine crewman had told him that the sinking was his cross
to bear as president, and that ``this person was right.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In spite of the fact that I have been in office in the Kremlin
a little over 100 days, I feel the full sense of guilt and
responsibility for this crisis,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Putin said that Defense Minister Igor Sergeyev and the commander
of the navy's northern fleet had offered their resignations on
Tuesday and that they had been rejected, at least until experts
found out what caused the submarine to explode and plunge to the
Barents Sea floor just before midnight on Aug. 12.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to get an objective picture of the reasons for this
tragedy,'' Putin said. ``Only after that can we make some
decisions.''
</P>
<P>
   But at the same time, he broadly suggested that the tortuous
pace of the military's rescue effort, and his own seeming
diffidence at the start of the incident, played no role in the
sailors' deaths because they were doomed from the moment the
submarine went down.
</P>
<P>
   Putin's somber mea culpa and explanation were clearly intended
to quell criticism, which continued Wednesday even after he
returned from a tightly scripted visit to the Arctic town of
Vidyayevo to offer condolences to the families of the perished
sailors.
</P>
<P>
   The military has come under scathing attack for its inability to
pry open the submarine in a week of attempts, especially after a
crew of Norwegian and British deep-sea divers arrived and opened
the submarine's damaged hatch with apparent ease.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Putin has been criticized for staying on vacation
in the Black Sea resort of Sochi, once the preserve of senior
Communist Party officials, for days after one of modern Russia's
worst military fiascos began to unfold.
</P>
<P>
   The affair has dented Putin's once-bulletproof reputation for
competence and efficiency, though it is not clear whether the
damage is severe or lasting. A poll of 1,574 people released on
Wednesday by the All-Russian Public Opinion Center concluded that
one in five respondents attribute the incident to the Kremlin's
poor control of the military.
</P>
<P>
   A second poll suggested that Putin's popularity had also
slipped, but that almost two in three Russians still approved of
his performance, a level most politicians would envy.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   On Wednesday night, Putin insisted that it was premature to
accuse the military of incompetence, and that a naval rescue effort
began ``the moment contact with the submarine was lost.''
</P>
<P>
   Similarly, he said, Norway's offer to help in the rescue was
immediately accepted, at least in principle, and that the
much-criticized two-day delay in sending Norwegian divers to the
site was dictated by unnamed ``technical parameters.''
</P>
<P>
   One question that Putin said investigators would explore is why
the Russian navy was unable to mount the type of deep-sea diving
operation that Norway employed to open the hatch. Russia is not
capable of sending divers to the 350-foot depth at which the Kursk
now lies.
</P>
<P>
   While that alone would not have saved any crewmen, he said,
investigators need to study why the Russian navy was not prepared
to rescue sailors trapped in one of its own submarines.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin said Wednesday that Putin had sent the head of the
Federal Security Service _ the domestic successor to the KGB _ and
the government's general prosecutor to Murmansk, near the Kursk's
home port of Severomorsk, to oversee a preliminary criminal
inquiry.
</P>
<P>
   Although no evidence of a crime exists, military officials
continued to insist Wednesday that the most likely cause of the
Kursk's sinking was a collision with an unidentified foreign vessel
that they claim to have detected with sonar on the sea floor near
the submarine.
</P>
<P>
   A senior military official, quoted anonymously by the
semiofficial Interfax news service, said Wednesday that the navy
had dispatched three ships to scour the seabed off the Kola
Peninsula for pieces of a second vessel.
</P>
<P>
   Russian sources have variously hinted that a U.S. or British
ship might have been involved in the incident, but both nations
have flatly denied any role.
</P>
<P>
   On the day Putin had set aside for grieving over the naval
disaster, it was apparent Wednesday that the Kursk's sinking has
hit typically stoic Russians with unusual force. The Kursk incident
continues to consume newspapers and television news broadcasts,
which were filled Wednesday with somber music and roll calls of the
dead, and both local governments and individuals were massing
donations for the seamen's survivors. Flags everywhere were strung
at half staff.
</P>
<P>
   While Putin promised the families more than a dozen years of
military pay to compensate for their loss, the total pay will
amount to only about $7,000 per family, and charitable efforts to
increase that figure have sprung up across the country. In
Rostov-on-Don, Russian television reported, the government pledged
30,000 rubles, or about $1,100 per family, to the survivors of two
crewmen who had lived there.
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow, Patriarch Alexei, the leader of the Russian Orthodox
Church, led a service for the crewmen in which he urged the nation
to put aside finger-pointing and unite around the families of the
crew.
</P>
<P>
   ``I call on you today to come together before the face of the
common calamity,'' he said, ``not to split, not to look for the
guilty, not to draw fast conclusions, but to accept what happened
as our common cross. And the cross, no matter what it can be, has
to be carried.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Only in Vidyayevo were observances postponed _ at the families'
request _ until the bodies of the Kursk's crew are brought home for
burial. When that might be was unclear.
</P>
<P>
   With the sailors' fate now sealed, officials here and in Norway
began on Wednesday to address the knotty questions of whether and
when the huge submarine, now a grave for its crew and for two
nuclear reactors, can be safely raised from the sea floor.
</P>
<P>
   Experts in both countries agreed on Wednesday that the two
reactors, which were shut down in the Kursk's plunge to the seabed,
have not leaked radiation into the surrounding waters. But
environmentalists likened the submarine to a radioactive time bomb,
warning that sooner or later, a catastrophic leak was inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, some officials studying ways to salvage the
Kursk said any operation to raise the damaged submarine holds some
risk that the vessel would break apart as it rose to the surface.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the families pressed the government to recover the bodies
immediately, before the severe Arctic winter sets in in a few
weeks, and Russian officials were considering plans to cut holes in
the submarine to remove the dead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
