<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 20:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0380 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-BUSH-BLACKCOLLEGES082     08-23 0779
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-BLACKCOLLEGES0824-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Bush to visit black New Orleans school
 &HT;    By Mark Sherman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Gov. George W. Bush of Texas will step onto
traditionally Democratic terrain today, a historically black
college campus in New Orleans, as he is grappling with problems at
similar institutions in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Bush will campaign at Dillard University, a private college
whose president is Michael Lomax. Lomax came from Atlanta where he
was the Fulton County commission chairman. The governor will end
his day in Miami.
</P>
<P>
   For Bush, the stop at Dillard has symbolic value in a state that
both parties are targeting in the presidential election. His
appearance in front of a predominantly black audience is part of an
ongoing effort to portray his campaign as centrist and focused on
winning votes of minorities.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton staged a rally on the Dillard campus in the
weeks before his election in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's critics complain that he has only recently become
interested in the conditions at his state's two historically black
public colleges, Texas Southern University in Houston and Prairie
View A&AMP;M University.
</P>
<P>
   The schools have been chronically short-changed by state
officials, a problem that predates Bush's administration and that
also crosses party lines, said M. Christopher Smith, an expert on
historically black colleges at the University of Illinois,
Urbana-Champaign.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, the U.S. Department of Education civil rights
division said the state may still be discriminating against those
schools. Civil rights leaders, including the Rev. Jesse Jackson,
protested the funding disparities in March.
</P>
<P>
   In April, the Bush-appointed Texas Higher Education Coordinating
Board, which sets policy for public colleges, recommended giving
the black colleges an extra $380 million over 20 years, mostly for
new construction.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Bush signed an agreement with federal officials to
enhance education at the schools, including making them more
attractive to white students without compromising their historic
character.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he doubts Bush would have committed to making changes
without the pressure of the presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying it's not genuine, his new outreach,'' Smith
said. ``I'm saying it certainly is suspect.''
</P>
<P>
   Doug Hattaway, a spokesman for Vice President Al Gore, was more
blunt. Bush's interest in black colleges is part of ``an
election-year conversion'' after years of neglect, Hattaway said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did not make higher education a priority in Texas by his
own admission and that has hurt historically black colleges,''
Hattaway said.
</P>
<P>
   Ray Sullivan, a Bush campaign spokesman, disputed Hattaway's
comments. ``That's typical partisan attack rhetoric,'' Sullivan
said. ``Governor Bush has helped make those schools more
accessible, more affordable and more academically excellent.''
</P>
<P>
   The criticism also does not take into account Bush's actions
prior to his signing the agreement, said Don Brown, the Texas
commissioner of higher education.
</P>
<P>
   Bush had earlier made significant changes on Texas Southern's
Board of Regents, Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   And Bush and his aides pushed for including goals in the
agreement with the Education Department that will allow the state
to measure its progress every two years, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would just have to disagree that this is about any kind of
conversion,'' said Brown, who has worked in Republican and
Democratic administrations.
</P>
<P>
   Leaving aside the presidential politics, Lomax said he is
delighted to be ``on the radar screens'' of Republican politicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're very dependent on the federal government for important
financial support and you can't get that without being
bipartisan,'' said Lomax, a Democrat.
</P>
<P>
   He was among 75 presidents of black colleges who met this year
with Republican congressional leaders.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas situation is far from resolved. The Higher Education
Board is supposed to adopt a final plan in October, which then will
go to Bush.
</P>
<P>
   If he signs off, which is expected, the Texas legislature will
have to find the money in the state budget when it meets in
January.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond Pierce, the deputy assistant education secretary for
civil rights, said he is confident that Texas will honor the
commitment made by Bush.
</P>
<P>
   ``But let me say this. It's one thing to sign a commitment,''
Pierce said. ``It's another thing to actually execute it.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
