<HEADER>
A0381 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-SCI-WOMEN-HEART-NYT &LR;      08-23 1140
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-WOMEN-HEART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DISCOURAGING FINDING ON ESTROGEN THERAPY AND HEART DISEASE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.C., Calif., Mass., Md.)  By GINA KOLATA   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A new study being published Thursday has found that estrogen
replacement therapy does nothing to slow the progression of heart
disease in women whose arteries are already partially blocked.
</P>
<P>
   But another study, in the same issue of The New England Journal
of Medicine, cites the hormone therapy as a factor _ along with
diet and exercise _ in the decline of heart disease among women who
do not smoke. An editorial accompanying the studies says that women
will not know whether hormone therapy protects the heart until
larger studies are completed in several years.
</P>
<P>
   As many as 10 million American women take estrogen replacement
therapy; Premarin, an estrogen made by Wyeth-Ayerst Laboratories,
is the nation's best-selling prescription drug.
</P>
<P>
   The drug was approved for the treatment of menopausal symptoms,
like hot flashes, and for the management of osteoporosis, but there
had also been a widespread belief that the drug would protect
against heart disease, the leading killer of American women. Heart
disease is rare among premenopausal women, but its incidence begins
rising in middle age.
</P>
<P>
   In the first study, which involved 309 women, investigators
injected women's coronary arteries with a dye and then examined the
arteries with X-rays. They found that the women's arteries
gradually narrowed as the study progressed, whether or not they
took estrogen.
</P>
<P>
   Their results, experts say, complement those of another recent
study that found that estrogen replacement therapy did not reduce
heart attacks in women who already had heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. David M. Herrington, a cardiovascular epidemiologist at Wake
Forest University School of Medicine and the lead author of the
artery study, said he began the work in hopes of confirming the
belief that estrogen would help women with heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   An earlier study, called HERS, had already shown discouraging
results, but some researchers wondered whether that might have been
because the women in it took either a combination of estrogen and
methoxyprogesterone, or a placebo. Some experts proposed that if
the women took estrogen alone, the hormone would protect their
hearts. So the women in Herrington's study were randomly assigned
to take estrogen alone, estrogen plus methoxyprogesterone or a
placebo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was still hopeful that there would be an underlying effect
on the progression of atherosclerosis,'' Herrington said. Now, he
said, he thinks the question has been answered.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this study coupled with the HERS trial is a pretty
compelling combination of evidence showing that estrogen
replacement therapy is not effective in reducing the risk for heart
attacks or heart disease deaths or for slowing the disease that's
responsible for those heart attacks in women with established heart
disease,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Other agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think its very convincing that after three years in a well
designed study there was no evidence of benefit,'' said Dr.
Elizabeth Barrett-Connor, a professor of family and preventive
medicine at the University of California in San Diego.
</P>
<P>
   But these studies do not address the question of whether hormone
therapy at menopause can prevent the development of heart disease
in women who do not yet have it. Dr. Elizabeth Nabel, the
scientific director for clinical research at the National Heart,
Lung and Blood Institute, said she was withholding judgment on the
issue of the hormone therapy and heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   She noted that the average age of the women in the study of
artery narrowing was 65 and that they had entered menopause 23
years earlier. ``Would hormone replacement therapy possibly be more
effective if it was initiated at the onset of menopause?'' she
asked.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, she said, the women were followed for only three
years. ``It may be that protective effects may be apparent only
years later,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, most experts said, the data were not encouraging
and added that a new study of 25,000 women without heart disease
was also finding hints that estrogen might not help their hearts.
</P>
<P>
   In April, directors of that study, known as the Women's Health
Initiative, informed participants that those taking estrogen were
having slightly more heart attacks than those taking a placebo,
possibly because of estrogen's well-known proclivity to encourage
blood clots in susceptible women.
</P>
<P>
   The finding reminded scientists of data from the HERS study,
which looked for heart attacks in women who already had heart
disease. There, too, the women taking estrogen initially had more
heart attacks, but later the incidence of heart attacks declined so
that, in the end, estrogen had no effect on heart attack incidence.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Deborah Grady, a professor of medicine and epidemiology at
the University of California at San Francisco, said the preliminary
results from the Women's Health Initiative made it statistically
unlikely that hormone replacement therapy would turn out to prevent
heart disease. ``It's very unlikely in my mind that they will ever
be able to show an overall benefit,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, a study to be published Thursday alongside
Herrington's work on artery narrowing attributed a reduction in
heart disease among women in part to hormone replacement therapy.
While it was not a randomized trial _ the women chose to take
estrogen or not to take it _ it was huge. Dr. Walter C. Willett of
Harvard School of Public Health and his colleagues followed 85,941
female nurses for 14 years.
</P>
<P>
   But epidemiologists said that such studies could be misleading.
And, in fact, observational studies had previously indicated that
estrogen could slow the progress of heart disease, making it all
the more surprising when it did not and stunning some who believed
in the treatment.
</P>
<P>
   A decade ago, Grady was so convinced by observational studies on
estrogen's benefits and by biological reasons it might prevent
heart disease that she helped write guidelines for the American
College of Physicians recommending that women at high risk for
heart disease take the drug. Now, she says, studies like the one
today have convinced her that that advice is wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the elements were in place for hormone replacement therapy
to prevent heart disease,'' Grady said. ``Now it's starting to look
like it won't. It's kind of staggering for us epidemiologists.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, medical experts said, women should rely on
established methods of heart disease prevention, like keeping their
cholesterol and blood pressure low, eating healthy diets,
exercising and staying away from cigarettes.
</P>
<P>
   ``For primary prevention, lifestyle modification definitely
works,'' Nabel said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
