<SLUG> BC-INDIA-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CABINET MEMBER'S DEATH PUTS SPOTLIGHT ON INDIA'S HEALTH SYSTEM 
</HEADLINE>
  By CELIA W. DUGGER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW DELHI, India _ The death of a popular and lively leader of
India's governing party on Wednesday has shaken the capital's
political elite, many of whom believe that he got faulty medical
care at one of New Delhi's most prestigious private hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   P. Rangarajan Kumaramangalam, who at 48 was the nation's power
minister and a relatively young leader in the gerontocracy of the
Hindu nationalist Bharatiya Janata Party, was treated for a fever
four months ago at what is widely regarded as the city's premier
private hospital.
</P>
<P>
   But doctors there did not detect the cancer that contributed to
his death, acute myeloid leukemia, and say they do not believe that
he had cancer when he was there.
</P>
<P>
   While the quality of health care for hundreds of millions of
Indians is miserable, the country's elected leaders are expected to
get only the best. Government officials generally, and cabinet
ministers especially, are a privileged class, entitled to free
medical care, priority seats on trains and planes, use of
government cars and virtually rent-free housing, among other perks.
</P>
<P>
   So when Kumaramangalam, a fixture in the capital who was
universally and affectionately known by the nickname Ranga, lapsed
into a coma a week ago and was found to have leukemia only a few
days later, there was disbelief among his colleagues and the
journalists who covered him.
</P>
<P>
   The Hindustan Times, a national daily newspaper, wrote, ``The
common man may well wonder: if this is how a minister who has
access to the best doctors and hospitals in the country is treated,
what about the rest of us?''
</P>
<P>
   Leaders in the Bharatiya Janata Party, which heads the coalition
government, are calling for an investigation of Indraprastha Apollo
Hospital, which treated Kumaramangalam four months ago. The
hospital has strongly denied any errors in the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel that Apollo Hospital could have diagnosed his
problem,'' Madan Lal Khurana, former chief minister of Delhi and a
member of Parliament from the Bharatiya Janata Party, said on
Wednesday. ``His death could have been avoided.''
</P>
<P>
   Prime Minister Atal Behari Vajpayee, 73, and a parade of the
nation's aging political leaders called on Kumaramangalam's home.
Vajpayee said in a statement, ``The cruel hand of death has
snatched away from our midst a young and dynamic national leader.''
</P>
<P>
   Kumaramangalam, a longtime member of Parliament from the
southern state of Tamil Nadu and a strong advocate of the
privatization of government-owned enterprises, sought treatment for
a persistent fever four months ago at Apollo, which is part of
India's first corporate chain of hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital's statements about his care make clear that he was
treated as what is generally known here as a ``V.V.I.P.'' _ a very,
very important person.
</P>
<P>
   Provided with ``extreme care and all personal attention,'' he
was given a battery of tests, was treated with antibiotics for
malaria and left the hospital when he started feeling better,
according to a press release. ``After his discharge, we continued
following Sri Kumaramangalam's health because he was dear to us,''
the hospital said, using a Hindi term of respect for him.
</P>
<P>
   The hospital said that it had consulted medical experts in
Boston who agreed with its care of the minister, and that he had
not returned for recommended follow-up visits. ``Unfortunately,
probably because of his busy schedule, he did not come back,'' the
hospital said.
</P>
<P>
   Kumaramangalam's illness was diagnosed only a few days ago after
he was admitted to the All India Institute of Medical Sciences, the
country's premier public hospital, also in New Delhi.
</P>
<P>
   During his more than 30 years in politics, Kumaramangalam
traveled a long distance from his family's political roots in a
journey that mirrored India's own transformation from a centrally
planned, state-dominated economy to a more market-driven one.
</P>
<P>
   His father, Mohan, made his name as a prominent Communist
politician and member of Parliament who served as a minister in
Congress Party governments. He played a pivotal role in the passage
of an antitrust law that sharply limited the size of private
companies, a law that his son later helped repeal.
</P>
<P>
   And the father was instrumental in nationalizing the coal
industry, while the son recently proposed a law that would
privatize it. As power minister, Kumaramangalam, once a trade union
leader of electrical workers who fought privatization, has pushed
to turn over distribution of power to private companies.
</P>
<P>
   Kumaramangalam, who had a wife and two children, spent most of
his political life in the Congress Party but joined the Bharatiya
Janata Party in 1998 and became one of its most recognized
spokesmen in his typically relaxed television appearances.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
