<HEADER>
A0389 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-MOSES-GOSPEL-MUSIC-NY     08-23 1108
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOSES-GOSPEL-MUSIC-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLACKS AND JEWS FIND HARMONY IN RETELLING OF EXODUS
</HEADLINE>
 By JULIE FLAHERTY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The story of Moses isn't usually sung and danced by a
cast of African-Americans and Jews. Nor is it performed as a work
in progress with new casts at every performance. Yet this has been
one of the goals of Walter Robinson, a composer from Cambridge,
Mass., who has spent the last four years piecing together
``Moses,'' which through black music and dance tells the Old
Testament story of the liberation of the Israelites from slavery.
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of blacks and Jews, from professional singers to
children in choirs, have contributed to ``Moses,'' which has had
about two dozen performances in synagogues, churches and theaters
along the East Coast. Question-and-answer sessions usually follow.
</P>
<P>
   On one recent evening in the basement of Temple Israel in
Boston, a cantor in the show chanted a lament for the suffering of
the Israelite slaves. Three gospel singers sang backup. Soon
afterward an Israelite slave broke into a rap harangue. Pharaoh's
magicians engaged in a break-dance battle. By the time a jazz trio
crooned a seductive entreaty to build a golden calf, the audience
and performers were swaying with the rhythms of a Southern Baptist
church.
</P>
<P>
   ``The story of Moses is a universal story, with the universal
themes of freedom, liberation _ leaving the familiar and going
toward the unknown,'' Robinson said. ``Yet there is also something
universal about black music.''
</P>
<P>
   His audiences seem to enjoy and understand it. ``It was a real
thrill to look out and see young people tapping their feet and
clapping their hands,'' said Nancy K. Kaufman, executive director
of the Jewish Community Relations Council of Greater Boston, who
has been both a narrator and fund-raiser for the show. True, the
black teen-agers in the audience were a little more zealous in
their participation, she said, ``but the Jews were holding their
own.''
</P>
<P>
   Betty Cohen, the cantor at Temple Emanu-El in Long Beach, N.Y.,
said the crowd that turned out for a show there in June was second
only to attendance for the High Holy Days.
</P>
<P>
   The show rarely plays the same way twice. Those who saw it in
March at the Emerson Majestic Theater in Boston witnessed it at its
grandest, a musical spectacle with dancers, a full band and a
100-voice children's choir. More often the performances are pared
down, with street-clothes workshops for schools and community
groups.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the principal performers are black, but children from
local synagogues make up the choir and a female cantor usually
plays Moses' wife, Zipporah. At a workshop performance in July,
Rebecca Garfein, senior cantor at Congregation Rodeph Sholom in New
York City, sang ``I Feel Love Here'' with Don Corey Washington, a
professional singer from East Orange, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   There have been difficulties. Some people complained that there
were not enough Hebrew lyrics in the show, or that the nonblack
parts seemed more ``white'' than Jewish in their emphasis. Others
said that all the main characters should have been played by black
performers and that Robinson played favorites in selecting
performers instead of holding general auditions. In response
Robinson has tweaked the script, although he points out that the
show is intended to be a black retelling of the story of Moses, not
an amalgam of Jewish and black music. He says that casting will be
less personal once he has a producer. ``That, I want to be a much
wider process than myself,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson chooses his venues carefully to avoid neighborhoods
where Jews or blacks might feel intimidated. ``Unfortunately, over
time, everyone has become so separate, that they have built a sort
of fear reference to certain communities,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The suggestion for a musical about Moses, Robinson said, came
from Leonard Zakim, longtime regional director of the
Anti-Defamation League in Boston. But it was a performance of the
show ``Bring In da Noise, Bring In da Funk'' that inspired Robinson
to create the format and feel of his show. What that show did with
dance, he said, he knew he wanted to do with music.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson credits his grandfather, who took him to Southern
Baptist services as a child, for acquainting him with the spiritual
nature of music.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone would get on their knees when they prayed,'' he said.
``I would be there huddled next to my grandfather and all these
big, sweaty people would be moaning in prayer, and all these
wonderful melodies reaching out to God. It was just really, really
powerful.''
</P>
<P>
   He went on to worship with a variety of Christian groups, from
Baptists to Pentacostal to Charismatic Catholics, some of whom
denounced other denominations in their prayers, leaving him pained,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   After touring with Livingston Taylor as a bassist, he spent
eight years as a fellow at the W.E.B. Du Bois Institute of
African-American Research at Harvard, where he wrote an opera about
a slave who bought his own freedom, ``Look What a Wonder Jesus Has
Done.'' His folk song ``Harriet Tubman'' is a staple of school
choirs.
</P>
<P>
   But it was a grant from the Meet the Composer Foundation and
community sponsors in 1995 that set the ``Moses'' project rolling.
To the gospel, jazz and choral pieces he wrote, Robinson added rap
songs and break dancing by a troupe called the FloorLords. In the
show, a cadre of step dancers portray midwives who defy the
Pharaoh's orders to kill the first-born male Hebrew children. ``We
will not do it!'' they sing, echoing their words with their
stamping feet.
</P>
<P>
   The showman in Robinson longs to see his music make it to
Broadway, with star-quality performers and perhaps a
technologically dazzling burning bush. He has the ear of major
black dance and theater companies who may help it get there, he
said. In 1998 he received a grant for $35,000 from Steven
Spielberg's Righteous Persons Foundation and in December 1999, a
matching grant from that organization for $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   When the Tanglewood Festival Chorus performed ``The Ten
Commandments,'' a classical choral piece from the show, ``I was
immensely impressed and grateful and felt proud,'' he said. ``But
it's no less than when I go to a synagogue and see the kids
struggle and miss a line. Right now I'm blessed with both
opportunities.''
</P>
<P>
   And so he seemed as he scrutinized the jazz trio's rendering of
``Bring Your Gold Together,'' in which the wandering Israelites
decide to hedge their bets with the old Egyptian gods by building
an idol. ``You know, having a god we can see,'' they croon,
``eliminates anxiety.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
