<SLUG> BC-SEASIA-INVEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT HELD UP AS ASEAN WORRIES ABOUT FRAGILE ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
   By WAYNE ARNOLD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SINGAPORE _ The Association of South East Asian Nations is
declining to release a report that warns of dwindling foreign
investment in the region, at the request of at least one member, an
association official said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The annual report on investment, presented to a meeting of
Asean's 10 foreign ministers in Bangkok last month, is normally
made public. Some details in the report, however, have since
appeared in local news reports.
</P>
<P>
   Such a warning is no surprise, but the association's decision
not to release the report shows how sensitive the issue is.
Southeast Asia's economic recovery appears increasingly fragile,
reducing the region's attraction to foreign business and investors.
At the same time, imminent entry into the World Trade Organization
has raised the allure of China.
</P>
<P>
   ``Southeast Asia has fallen off the radar screen,'' said William
C. Belchere, head of fixed-income research at Merrill Lynch in
Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   The report, by Asean Secretary General Rodolfo C. Severino,
warns that Southeast Asia is rapidly losing foreign investment to
competitors elsewhere, especially China, and calls for urgent
efforts to promote regional economic integration to regain
competitiveness.
</P>
<P>
   According to one published report, the Asean report found that
foreign investment in the region fell 22 percent in 1999 after
falling 21 percent in 1998. Only Singapore enjoyed an increase
among the group, which includes Brunei, Cambodia, Indonesia, Laos,
Malaysia, Myanmar, the Philippines, Thailand and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   Vic A. Lactaoen, a spokesman at the association's headquarters
in Jakarta, said the report was not released at the request of
Singapore.
</P>
<P>
   Singapore's Ministry of Foreign Affairs denied having made such
a request, and said the decision not to publish the report was made
after the secretary broached the issue during an Asean committee
meeting before the ministerial meeting. The ministry spokeswoman
expressed surprise at the suggestion Singapore might have sought to
suppress the report, as its own foreign minister had offered a
similarly critical appraisal at the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign investors have been pulling out of the region's stock
markets for most of the year in favor of markets to the north.
Morgan Stanley Capital International now gives Hong Kong almost the
same weight as all of Southeast Asia in its model Asian index.
</P>
<P>
   Foreign lending, much of which finances foreign investment, has
also been falling from $384 billion in early 1997 to $205 billion
by the end of last year, according to the Bank for International
Settlements.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-00 2033EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
