A0391 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-U.N.-PEACEKEEPING-ART     08-23 0665
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-U.N.-PEACEKEEPING-ART-600(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. IS URGED TO UPGRADE PEACEKEEPING DEPARTMENT 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT10 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ A panel of international experts recommended
Wednesday that the U.N. peacekeeping department, under attack for a
series of disasters in recent years, be enlarged and
professionalized, with intelligence-gathering functions that were
essentially forbidden during the Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   The experts, appointed by Secretary-General Kofi Annan, urged
that more effort go into preventing situations from becoming crises
_ not waiting for instructions from the Security Council. They also
recommended that peacekeeping officials resist allowing larger
countries to exert too much influence over their day-to-day
activities. It is a vision certain to upset both U.S. isolationists
as well as some Third World leaders who fear that a stronger, more
independent organization would mean a new kind of colonialism.
</P>
<P>
   The experts' recommendations are contained in a report released
just ahead of a summit meeting of world leaders in early September
when the issue of how much power the United Nations should have to
intervene in nations torn by domestic crises is expected to be
debated with some passion. Last year, Annan provoked a storm of
protest by saying in a speech to the General Assembly that national
borders should not be inviolate when rulers were abusing their
populations.
</P>
<P>
   But even with a stronger peacekeeping department, the Security
Council will still exercise considerable power over operations, and
the whims of the most powerful five nations _ Britain, China,
France, Russia and the United States _ will continue to be a
factor.
</P>
<P>
   Even in a case like Rwanda, where up to 800,000 people died in
genocidal attacks on the minority Tutsi population in 1994 and the
United States prevented the deployment of an effective peacekeeping
operation, experts argue that if the peacekeeping department had
been better informed and more strongly staffed, a warning cable
from the Canadian commander on the ground might not have been given
short shrift by the big powers.
</P>
<P>
   In a case like Sierra Leone, where 500 ill-trained peacekeepers
walked into ambushes in May, Annan was left begging for military
expertise _ finally provided by the British _ because the
peacekeeping department did not have the people to do the job
itself and did not have a roster of ready professionals on loan
from governments to call on. The experts' recommendations follow
nearly a decade in which the United Nations has drifted in trying
to deal with peacekeeping problems. Their suggestions also call for
speeding up response time, so that a simple peacekeeping operation
could be launched in 30 days rather than several months, and
sending expert advance teams to areas where very complex military
and political situations prevail.
</P>
<P>
   Since the end of the Cold War, all kinds of new assignments have
been heaped on the peacekeeping department by the Security Council,
free of the paralysis caused by the perpetual checkmating of
initiatives by the Soviet Union or the United States when one camp
or another was involved _ as in Vietnam in the 1960s or Afghanistan
in the 1980s. Many of these assignments have not been practical,
and the expert panel concluded that the United Nations must learn
to ``just say no'' at times, rather than risk debacle.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are many tasks which the United Nations peacekeeping
forces should not be asked to undertake, and many places they
should not go,'' the report said. ``But when the United Nations
does send its forces to uphold the peace, they must be prepared to
confront the lingering forces of war and violence with the ability
and determination to defeat them.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The report, which concentrates heavily on practical measures to
fix the shortcomings of an overstretched, outdated peacekeeping
department, builds on specific earlier studies of the failures of
the United Nations and its member countries to deal with disasters
in Rwanda and Bosnia. The study paints a picture of an understaffed
department with a perennially ad hoc air about it, whose every move
is micromanaged by the 188-member General Assemby.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Holbrooke, the U.S. ambassador to the United Nations,
who has for months been advocating the strengthening of the
peacekeeping department, the core function of the organization when
its charter was adopted in 1945, welcomed the report as ``a big
step forward.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The United States doesn't agree with everything in this
report,'' he said in an interview. ``But we are prepared to support
it and to support a General Assembly resolution calling for its
aggressive implementation.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will always be people in the United States who view the
U.N. as an invasive force that weakens our sovereignty,'' he said.
``But this administration's view is clear: The U.N. is flawed but
it is indispensable. This report will, I hope, address some of its
flaws.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. expert on the review panel was J. Brian Atwood, former
administrator of the U.S. Agency for International Development and
now president of Citizens International, a private
democracy-building organization. The panel's other experts included
Colin Granderson of Trinidad and Tobago, who has directed missions
in Haiti for the Organization of American States; Dame Anne Hercus,
a New Zealander who headed a U.N. mission in Cyprus, and Richard
Monk, a British police official who was commissioner of a U.N.
police force in Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   Also on the panel was Gen. Klaus Naumann of Germany, former
chairman of NATO's military committee; Hisako Shirmura of Japan, a
former director of Latin American and European peacekeeping at the
United Nations; Vladimir Shustov, a former Russian representative
to the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe; Gen.
Philip Sibanda of Zimbabwe, a former U.N. commander in Angola, and
Cornelia Sommaruga of Switzerland, president of the International
Committee of the Red Cross from 1987 to 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The panel's chairman was Lakhdar Brahimi, a former foreign
minister of Algeria who has served as an international
troubleshooter and envoy of the secretary-general for nearly a
decade in crises from Afghanistan to Haiti to Zaire, now Congo.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Brahimi drew on his own experiences to
illustrate the weaknesses of the peacekeeping bureaucracy, which
his report says needs to be transformed into a meritocracy _ not an
easy task, he admits. For example, he said, in 1993, when he
returned to New York from overseeing the end of apartheid in South
Africa, he was asked to go immediately to Yemen, where a civil
conflict had broken out.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing I asked was, OK, what do we have on Yemen?''
he said. ``The answer was, Nothing. Not one thing.'' He had to buy
his own research material, in Arabic, on the scene.
</P>
<P>
   One of the panel's central recommendations is the creation of a
new information-gathering and analysis office within the United
Nations to create data bases and operate as a policy planning
staff. In facing crises, the report recommends more honesty in
assessing blame and less of a tendency to try to treat all sides of
a dispute as equally responsible in an effort to appear impartial.
</P>
<P>
   Another core recommendation is the creation of an integrated
task force for each mission that combines political analysis,
military operations, civilian police, electoral assistance, aid to
refugees and displaced people, public information, logistics,
finance and recruitment. Brahimi said that the United Nations, with
the help of member governments, needs to compile a roster of
experts in many fields who are ready to go to places like Kosovo,
Congo or East Timor to do development as well as peacekeeping work.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
