<SLUG> BC-E-BOOK-LIST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SIMON &AMP; SCHUSTER BECOMES THIRD PUBLISHER TO OFFER E-BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   By DAVID D. KIRKPATRICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Simon &AMP; Schuster on Wednesday announced a list of
electronic books that it will sell this fall, becoming the third
major trade publisher to make books available for downloading and
reading on a screen.
</P>
<P>
   Although no one knows whether consumers will pay for electronic
versions of trade books, Simon &AMP; Schuster, a unit of Viacom, joins
Bertelsmann's Random House imprint and Time Warner's trade
publishing division in plunging into the e-book business.
</P>
<P>
   Simon &AMP; Schuster's electronic books will include a handful of
titles sold exclusively in digital form, including a biography of
the winning presidential candidate written for children and set for
release at midnight after the election; a health guidebook produced
with the Harvard Medical School; a book elaborating on events in
``The Blair Witch Project''; books based on video games and books
related to Star Trek.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Romanos, president of Simon &AMP; Schuster, said the titles
were selected to capitalize on the potential for marketing to
groups active on the Internet, like fans of ``The Blair Witch
Project'' or Star Trek.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure we know how to reach an audience for an
electronic book online unless the subject lends itself to that kind
of promotion,'' Romanos said.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the list will be published simultaneously with new
hardcover books, including books by Stephen Ambrose, Bob Woodward,
Jesse Ventura and Jimmy Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Random House and Time Warner are creating imprints to publish
their electronic books, but Simon &AMP; Schuster is not. Romanos said
that the publisher wanted ``to pull everybody into digital
publishing's evolution rather than wait for individuals to put up
their hands and say, `I get it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Simon &AMP; Schuster will charge $5 to $15 for books sold only in
electronic versions, about the price of a trade paperback, and will
sell the other electronic books for the same price as their
hardcover versions. Those prices are somewhat higher than those
charged by Random House and Time Warner.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
