<HEADER>
A0398 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f BC-FAST-FOOD-EUROPE-NYT &LR;      08-23 1372
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FAST-FOOD-EUROPE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. COMPANY TRIES TO SELL EUROPE ON THE HOT DOG 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOHN TAGLIABUE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   FREGENE, Italy _ A blue and yellow umbrella flapped in the
breeze as Andrea Lupo, clad in a blue bathing suit and a deep tan,
ordered lunch with mustard, relish, onions and sauerkraut, to a
chorus of ``disgusting'' from a clutch of wide-eyed contemporaries.
</P>
<P>
   Asked how many hot dogs he had eaten on a recent afternoon,
Andrea, 14, grinned and, with playful exaggeration, replied, ``Oh,
60, maybe.'' His pals ordered theirs slathered in mustard or
swimming in ketchup.
</P>
<P>
   Andrea's appetite cheers hearts at a company not far from this
Italian seaside resort that is trying a curious culinary
experiment. If it succeeds, the Sabrett hot dog, icon of Broadway
and habitue of Madison Square Garden, will be added to Europe's
growing menu of American-style fast-food dishes.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the pushcart outside Gilda on the Beach, a beach club
and discotheque, sells 40 to 50 a day, and more than 200 in the
early hours of the morning, when the disco shuts down and exhausted
patrons grab a hot dog before heading home. The company, American
Food Products, began selling the hot dogs last spring, and now
serves soccer stadiums, amusement parks, discotheques, highway rest
stops and dozens of pushcarts in Italian cities.
</P>
<P>
   The reasoning behind the venture is as fundamental as, well, a
frank. While American fast-food products like the hamburger, the
donut and fried chicken have captured the palates of Europeans, the
humble hot dog, which despite its Germanic wurst resemblance is
considered the most American of them all, remains stranded on the
other side of the Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was thinking of the success of the hamburger,'' said
Pasquale L. Figorito, president of American Food Products,
explaining that the four original McDonalds restaurants in the
Italian capital, Rome, do $10 million sales a year. ``It's just
amazing,'' he said. ``The United States is known as a country for
hamburgers, but statistics show that in America, seven hot dogs are
eaten for every hamburger. So maybe we have fertile terrain.''
</P>
<P>
   This fertile terrain prompted a group of investors, including
some from the United States, to bid enough to win the exclusive
license for Sabrett hot dogs in Europe. Italy is the first market,
but Figorito says he plans to sell the hot dog elsewhere in Europe,
for example in Britain and Spain, if the Italian experiment
succeeds. To do so, American Food has registered a parent company
in Luxembourg. Within a year or so, he said, expansion could begin.
</P>
<P>
   Now, when Rome's rival soccer clubs, Roma and Lazio, compete in
the capital's Olympic Stadium, hawkers sell Sabrett's hot dogs in
the bleachers. At the recent Italian Open tennis tournament,
Sabrett's distinct yellow and blue umbrellas lured hungry fans. At
highway rest stops in northern Italy, the hot dogs are catching on.
``We're selling about 9,000 to 10,000 hot dogs a day,'' said
Figorito, an unabashed enthusiast of American food. His goal for
Italy, he says, is 60,000 to 70,000 a day, adding: ``My dream is
double that.'' Within a few years he hopes to have Sabrett hot dog
outlets, modeled on McDonalds hamburger restaurants and selling
steak fries, crinkle cuts and, maybe, potato knishes, in Italian
cities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought Italians would go for pickle relish,'' he
said. Still, he admits, not everything related to Sabrett's travels
well. The company slogan, for instance, ``We're on a roll,'' had to
be abandoned in Europe. ``It would take three years to explain
here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   For Sabrett, a unit of Marathon Enterprises Inc. in East
Rutherford, N.J., which produces about 1 million hot dogs a week,
that is small change. But Sabrett, which recovered last year from a
case of contamination of its products by listeria, a food-borne
bacteria, that is suspected of having caused two deaths, welcomes
the European expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Boyd G. Adelman, Marathon's executive vice president responsible
for Sabrett, said that while Sabrett's priority remains ``a
100-mile radius around New York,'' it had begun expanding
nationally, notably through wholesale clubs, like BJs, and was also
shipping small amounts of hot dogs to South Korea, Japan and
Mexico. ``We are expanding on an international scale, and Italy is
important,'' Adelman said.
</P>
<P>
   Figorito, 39, a big, mustachioed native of Elmwood Park, N.J.,
got to know Sabrett's products while growing up in New Jersey
before settling in Italy after finishing college. After meeting
Adelman through a mutual friend several years ago, he hatched the
Pygmalion-like idea of grooming the New York hot dog for its
continental debut.
</P>
<P>
   Yet first he had to deal with European bureaucracy. Sabrett
stepped into Europe at the height of a trade war between Washington
and the European Union over food products, like bananas, that
prompted the Europeans to cut the number of European inspectors in
U.S. food plants to one, from 16, making it unfeasible to consider
importing hot dogs from Sabrett factories to Europe. Instead,
Figorito signed up Cremonini SpA, an Italian company whose $1.2
billion of annual revenue make it one of Europe's biggest food
processing companies, to make the frankfurters at an Italian
factory using Sabrett's recipe. Since skinless, all-beef sausages
like Sabrett's are virtually unknown in Europe, where pork and
poultry dominate, Cremonini had to master Sabrett's technology,
Figorito said. The spices for the hot dogs, Sabrett's Adelman
added, are shipped from the United States, where they are mixed
``according to our age-old, secret recipe.'' The buns are baked in
Barcelona, Spain, by Bimbo SA, a unit of Earthgrains, the St. Louis
bakers, who also bake rolls in Europe for Burger King. Bimbo
modified its machines to slice Sabrett's typically hinged bun.
</P>
<P>
   Sabrett's pushcarts, too, good enough for Manhattan street
corners, could not meet European standards. Considered mobile
restaurants by European Union definition, the pushcarts had to have
a working sink and a locker for employee clothing. Figorito proudly
showed a redesigned cart, a tiny sink clinging to one side and a
miniature locker, perhaps big enough for a rolled up shirt, on the
other. Moreover, since European hygienic rules don't allow soft
drinks in cans or bottles to be stored in chopped ice, the way they
are in New York pushcarts, the European carts are outfitted with
small refrigerators. Three carts had to be handed over to European
inspectors for crash tests, to see how well vendors and customers
would survive a traffic accident.
</P>
<P>
   Not even Sabrett's onions and sauerkraut could survive the
European bureaucratic onslaught. Formaric acid used as a
preservative in the American-prepared onions is banned in Europe
and had to be replaced with citric acid. Europe also bans the use
of sodium benzoid, a common preservative in sauerkraut, so a
substitute had to be found.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the American Food investors are seeking to cash in on
Europe's unbroken appetite for fast food and the continued spread
of restaurant franchising. But they are also targeting Europe's
growing Islamic population, as immigrants from predominantly Muslim
countries in Africa and the Middle East arrive in search of jobs.
``As Europe grows more multiethnic,'' said Franco Pantaleoni, a
food industry consultant who helped set up American Food, ``we are
using more products that are pure beef.'' But he won't deny that
the biggest market is children.
</P>
<P>
   The hot dogs that sell at Gilda's for the equivalent of $2.50
are double what they cost in New York, where they sell for $1.25, a
steep price considering that the main target is young people. Yet
Sergio Lorina, 52, who operates the pushcart, said price was no
obstacle. ``Mainly kids eat them,'' he said, ``and the more daring
adults.''
</P>
<P>
   Marina Ciaralli, whose children Matteo, 12, and Marta, 9, were
munching on hot dogs with the works _ mustard and ketchup, relish
and sauerkraut _ agreed. The slice of pizza she was eating cost
about the same as her children's hot dogs, she said. Asked whether
she had tried a hot dog, she replied hesitantly, ``Not today. Maybe
tomorrow.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
