<SLUG> BC-LOVE&AMP;SEX-REVIEW-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A WINNER IN `LOVE &AMP; SEX'
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Eds: Fact box below) 
Our rating: 3 stars 
By BOB STRAUSS 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Taking a tip from Woody Allen, writer-director Valerie Breiman
based much of her debut feature, ``Love &AMP; Sex,'' on a funny
relationship _ that's funny ha-ha and funny insane, like
everybody's _ she once had.
</P>
<P>
   The results aren't ``Annie Hall'' calibre, but they are
remarkably more recognizably human than what passes for most movie
romantic comedy. ``Love &AMP; Sex'' is impolite, messy, obsessive and
embarrassing. It seems like love, in other words, not to mention
like everyone's other favorite subject.
</P>
<P>
   Famke Janssen, the strapping Dutch model last seen playing it
cool in ``X-Men,'' carries the film with a protean emotional
bewilderment and delightfully awkward physicality as Kate. A writer
for one of those monstrous women's magazines that are always making
up authoritative articles on what works with men, Kate one day gets
sick of all the fabrication and thinks back about where she's
personally gone wrong.
</P>
<P>
   Several quick vignettes _ her father-figure period with a
married guy during college, the cute-but-dumb action movie actor
liaison _ bookend the central disaster of her love life. His name
is Adam (``Swingers''' Jon Favreau), a painter of grotesque psyche
scapes. He started out all cuddly overconfident, stuck by her
through an unplanned pregnancy and devastating miscarriage, then
let his sexual paranoia _ Kate had a lot more experience going in _
scuttle what was shaping up as a pretty good thing.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after they broke up, things really got intense.
</P>
<P>
   Breiman approaches the usual ``Why are guys so weird and can't I
keep one?'' neurotics with a beguiling, shambling earthiness. The
film's title is not deceptive; when at a loss for how to express a
worrisome feeling, Kate unerringly goes carnal with often
uproarious consequences. Just one small but telling example: Of all
the jokey tongue-kissing that we've been subjected to in this
summer's comedies, this movie's kisses are the only ones that
actually make you chuckle instead of wince because they're
expressions of character rather than cheap grossout displays.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, ``Love &AMP; Sex'' has its share of pat gags,
like Adam's playmate parade of rebound bimbos who are each younger,
dumber and blonder than the last. But Breiman has a way of using
obvious jokes as springboards for smarter humor, and in much the
same way she can stretch standard contemporary rom-com dialogue
into very specific, personal revelation.
</P>
<P>
   All of this gives ``Love &AMP; Sex'' a shaggy, lived-in kind of
feeling. Very enjoyable ambience _ and if Breiman can recapture it
in future projects that she hasn't necessarily lived out, she'll be
a formidable voice in film comedy indeed. &QL; 
---- &QL; 
The film: ``Love &AMP; Sex'' (R; sex, language, nudity) &QL; 
The stars: Famke Janssen, Jon Favreau &QL; 
Behind the scenes: Written and directed by Valerie Breiman.
Produced by Timothy Scott Bogart, Martin J. Barab and Brad Wyman.
Released by Lions Gate Films. &QL; 
Running time: 1 hour, 22 minutes &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
