<SLUG> BC-FBC-ECAROLINA0824-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pirates fight for exposure despite 9-win season
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Ask Steve Logan how things are in Greenville, N.C.,
and he replies, ``Just hanging out, waiting on the next
hurricane.''
</P>
<P>
   Informed that Hurricane Debby was downgraded Tuesday to a
tropical storm, Logan was genuinely relieved. You'd be, too, if you
were the head football coach at East Carolina.
</P>
<P>
   It's been 11 months since the hurricane, and Hurricanes, hit
North Carolina. Last September, as Hurricane Floyd swept across the
state, the East Carolina Pirates had to spend a week in a hotel in
Columbia. Flooding in Greenville prompted ECU's game with mighty
Miami to be moved from Dowdy-Ficklen Stadium on campus to
Carter-Finley Stadium in Raleigh. There, in N.C. State's stadium,
East Carolina rallied from 20 points down to upset the No. 9
Hurricanes 27-23.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before, there was just as much chaos as you could invent,''
Logan recalled. ``Then we won the game and suddenly there was a
great story.''
</P>
<P>
   Another chapter, too, to the nice story Logan and his teams have
written since 1992, a year after ECU went 11-1 with quarterback
Jeff Blake orchestrating Logan's offense. In '92, once Bill Lewis
left for his three-year debacle at Georgia Tech, Logan moved up
from offensive coordinator to head coach. Ever since, East
Carolina's improvement has been evident. Even as the Pirates _ who
went 9-3 (4-2 in Conference USA) last season and to their third
bowl in six years _ continue to fight for more exposure while
upgrading their facilities, schedule and overall talent.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there were 15 teams that won nine or more (games in
'99),'' Logan said. ``Well, doggone, we were one of them. We've
come up in the world, but we're still in a very tenuous little
position here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are we good? Yeah. Hard to beat? Yeah. Can we lose? Yeah.
We've got 11 games this year. Any one of 'em, we could win it or we
could lose it. That's the world we live in. We just don't have the
numbers of elite athletes. But don't get me wrong. We've got some
doggone good kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Nine starters return from an offense that averaged 29 points in
1999.
</P>
<P>
   Leading tackler and inside linebacker Pernell Griffin (121
tackles) returns to a defense that lost both starting cornerbacks.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
