<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 20:54 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0413 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-SCI-DIABETES-ART-NYT &LR;      08-23 1242
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SCI-DIABETES-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORTING INCREASES IN DIABETES, RESEARCHERS WARN OF DEATH AND
DISABILITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: A graphic map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DENISE GRADY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The incidence of diabetes increased markedly in the United
States from 1990 to 1998, including a 76 percent rise in cases
among people in their 30s, researchers are reporting Thursday, and
they warn that the disease will take a harsh toll in disability,
death and medical expenses in decades to come.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors blame much of the rise on obesity, which is also
increasing steadily, with more than half of Americans now
overweight.
</P>
<P>
   The increase is almost entirely in Type 2 diabetes, commonly
called adult onset diabetes, which accounts for 90 to 95 percent of
all cases of the disease. Inactivity and weight gain can bring on
Type 2 diabetes, and doctors blame much of the current rise on
obesity, which is also increasing steadily, with more than half of
Americans now overweight. Type 1 diabetes, which accounts for most
of the remaining 5 to 10 percent of cases, is caused by a
malfunction of the immune system and is not linked to obesity.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers predict that Type 2 diabetes will continue to
snowball, because there is a delay between the development of
obesity and the onset of diabetes, which means that for many
overweight people it is just a matter of time before the disease
sets in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're having enough trouble taking care of people with
diabetes today,'' said Dr. Frank Vinicor, director of the diabetes
division at the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention, and an
author of the study, which is being published Thursday in the
journal Diabetes Care. ``It's going to get considerably worse in
the future.''
</P>
<P>
   Experts blame the rising weight on Americans' increasing
tendency to park themselves in front of TV and computer screens,
exercising too little and eating too much, particularly gigantic
portions of high-calorie foods. The study showed that the risk of
diabetes increased by 4 percent for every pound of excess weight.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the prevalence of diabetes rose from 4.9 percent of the
population in 1990 to 6.5 percent in 1998, an increase of 33
percent, according to the study. Hispanics had a 38 percent
increase in diabetes cases, compared to increases of 29 percent in
whites and 26 percent in blacks. In total, the percentages
translate into 13 million cases of diabetes. During the same time
period, the proportion of people who were overweight rose from 44
percent to 54 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Other studies have estimated that in addition to the diagnosed
cases, more than 5 million other Americans have diabetes without
knowing it, because the disease produces few or no symptoms in its
early stages.
</P>
<P>
   Severe complications make diabetes a substantial public health
problem. It is a major cause of blindness, kidney failure and leg
amputations, and it greatly increases the risk of heart disease and
stroke, the leading causes of death in the United States.
</P>
<P>
   The increases in people in their '30s and younger are
particularly worrisome, researchers say. The longer a person has
the disease, the greater the odds of complications. In the past,
Type 2 diabetes was seen mainly in people over 45. Today, doctors
say they are alarmed to find the disease even in teen-agers, as
more and more of them become obese.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of diabetes is estimated at $98 billion a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Expensive as we think health care is today, with these chronic
conditions coming on it's going to be very threatening to quality
of life as well as cost issues,'' said Vinicor. ``If we saw a 33
percent increase in infectious diseases like tuberculosis or AIDS,
I believe there would be an understandable demand for action. We
can't just view inactivity and overweight as purely a kind of
cosmetic thing. It's got to be viewed as a serious public health
issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Many measures are needed to fight the trend, Vinicor said,
offering several examples: ``We need to insure that people are
informed about healthy choices of foods, that when you build new
homes there are sidewalks where people can walk and be active, that
schools reinstate physical education and that cafeterias at schools
offer healthy foods.''
</P>
<P>
   He said research had shown that school-based programs to
encourage exercise could stop the development of obesity.
</P>
<P>
   Diabetes has been on the rise for several decades, but Vinicor
said the current rate of increase is slightly greater than in the
past. He said he thought the new study reflected a real rise in the
incidence of the disease, and not just increased diagnosis due to
better screening or a broader definition of the disease established
in 1997. If anything, he said, the figures are conservative,
because they were gathered by a telephone survey and therefore did
not include people too poor to have telephones, who are among those
with the highest rates of obesity and diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   The figures being reported Thursday come from a telephone survey
of 150,000 households in which people were asked their height and
weight and whether they had been told by a doctor that they had
diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   Not all overweight people become diabetic; in fact, the majority
do not. But the risk of the disease increases with the degree of
obesity. The main abnormality in diabetes is an excessively high
level of blood sugar, or glucose. Type 2 diabetes is most likely to
develop in people with a condition known as insulin resistance,
which the body cannot make proper use of the hormone insulin, which
normally helps glucose enter cells so that it can be used as fuel.
Insulin resistance is often associated with obesity but researchers
are not sure whether obesity causes insulin resistance, or vice
versa. Many scientists think that the tendency to become insulin
resistant is genetic. In any case, the body tries to overcome
insulin resistance by producing higher and higher levels of the
hormone, which is made in the pancreas. In some people, with
insulin resistance, most of them obese, the insulin-producing cells
simply wear out, leading to a shortage of insulin and high blood
sugar, the hallmarks of diabetes.
</P>
<P>
   Researchers think excess glucose causes trouble in part by
thickening the blood, which impedes circulation, and by binding to
needed enzymes and other important proteins and sabotaging their
function.
</P>
<P>
   Exercise and weight loss can lower insulin resistance and high
blood sugar and are commonly the first measures recommended to
treat Type 2 diabetes. Each can help, but the combination is more
effective than either one alone. They are also being studied to
determine whether they can ward off the disease in people at high
risk for it.
</P>
<P>
   Few people are able to stick to diets or exercise programs, and
those who do lose weight often regain it. Many people with Type 2
diabetes eventually need pills or insulin shots to lower their
blood sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Studies have shown that ``tight control'' of blood sugar,
keeping it as close to normal as possible, can forestall the
devastating complications of diabetes. But surveys reveal that few
patients achieve that degree of control. They do not receive
adequate treatment for high blood pressure or high cholesterol,
either, conditions that often accompany diabetes and that increase
the risk of cardiovascular disease.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
