<SLUG> BC-UNITED-MECHANICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNITED ASKS MECHANICS TO WORK OVERTIME 
</HEADLINE>
 (ATTN: Ohio, Calif., Ill., Wash.)  By PAM BELLUCK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHICAGO _ To help overcome delays and cancellations that have
plagued it this summer, United Airlines has issued an order
requiring mechanics at five airports to work overtime if asked.
</P>
<P>
   About 50 of the airline's 10,000 mechanics have been working
overtime this week in Chicago, Los Angeles, Washington and
Indianapolis to try to make sure flights are able to take off on
time, said a United spokesman, Chris Brathwaite. An order, called
an operational emergency, was also issued in Denver, but no
mechanics have been asked to work overtime there, Brathwaite said.
</P>
<P>
   The contract between United's parent company, UAL Corp., and the
International Association of Machinists and Aerospace Workers union
allows management to declare an operational emergency when overtime
hours are needed to keep the airline operating efficiently. United
and union spokesmen said the airline does not issue such an order
very often.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have planes backed up, we have out of service aircraft
which are causing cancellations, and we're calling a few mechanics
in to service the aircraft to keep them running on time,'' said
Brathwaite, adding that those working overtime are the most junior
mechanics. ``If it takes an extra hour for somebody to work to fix
a door knob or a broken seat, we need make sure our planes are in
good working order.''
</P>
<P>
   Frank Larkin, a spokesman for the machinists union, said that
United officials said in a conference call on Wednesday that ``they
had as many as 40 aircraft out of service, grounded and they were
going to be using mandatory overtime only as long as was needed to
correct the situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Larkin said: ``Emergency overtime is permitted in our contract.
The concern now is that it does not go from an actual emergency to
covering staffing needs. In this conference call the company said
it would use it as little as possible. Nevertheless we feel it has
the potential to do long-term damage.''
</P>
<P>
   United has been plagued by thousands of cancellations and delays
since the contract with its pilots expired in April. Few pilots
have been willing to work overtime and there is no clause in that
contract that allows United to require pilots to do so. Since July,
when a contract with the mechanics expired, the airline has
reported an increase in maintenance delays. United is seeking
disciplinary action against 36 mechanics that it says participated
in a sickout in Los Angeles on the eve of the Democratic National
Convention.
</P>
<P>
   United has apologized for the scheduling problems and has
canceled about 3 percent of its 2,400 daily flights through
September and announced a reduced flight schedule for the fall.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
