<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 20:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0415 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-GORE-FLORIDA-ART-NYT &LR;      08-23 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-FLORIDA-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE AND LIEBERMAN LAUNCH BID FOR FLORIDA BY COURTING JEWISH
VOTERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By KEVIN SACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   TAMARAC, Fla. _ They used their best Yiddish, not just the Jew
but the Southern Baptist as well. The band, a brassy if somewhat
anemic quintet (you were expecting the Rolling Stones?), played a
medley that ran from ``Rocky Top'' to ``Happy Days Are Here Again''
to ``Hava Nagila.'' And one adoring voter, a lady with silver hair
and red lipstick, told America's first Jewish vice presidential
nominee that kissing his hand was ``like kissing the Torah.''
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore and his running mate, Sen. Joseph
Lieberman, campaigned in southeast Florida for the first time
Wednesday, setting off a frenzy at a largely Jewish community
center and making a firm statement that they would compete
aggressively in this critical state.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't tell you how important Florida is,'' Lieberman told
the crowd that filled the 800-seat Cabaret Royale Theater in the
Kings Point Community Center and flowed over into an adjacent room.
``I honestly believe that Al Gore and I are going to win Florida
and as a result are going to win the election in November.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Lieberman were playing on long-established Democratic
terrain Wednesday in a state that is by no means the Democratic
stronghold it once was. But by traveling here _ Gore will be back
in the state on Monday _ the new Democratic team was able to test
its ability to excite party loyalists whose support will be vital
in November.
</P>
<P>
   By all indications, they succeeded, with a pitch that emphasized
their plans for a tax credit for long-term health care, for
prescription drug benefits under Medicare, and for protecting
Social Security. Their listeners rose to their feet with roars of
approval several times, some leaning on walkers and canes, and
mobbed the men after they finished.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Lieberman received an even warmer reception
than Gore. Some wept with pride as they greeted him. Others called
him a mensch. Sophie K. Gold, 72, said she was ``kvelling and
ecstatic'' when Gore selected Lieberman. ``I felt 10 feet tall,''
she said, ``and very skinny.'' Rep. Robert Wexler, who represents
this area, said that Lieberman was regarded as ``a rock star, like
Barbra Streisand'' in south Florida, and that his ability to turn
out votes would make the Democrats ``as competitive as anybody
could ever believe a Democratic ticket could be.''
</P>
<P>
   And Gore and Lieberman did their best to speak the crowd's
language. Lieberman introduced Gore as a ``Yiddishe neshoma,'' a
Jewish soul. All the attention paid to his wife, Hadassah, and
Gore's wife, Tipper, he said, made the candidates feel like
``nuchshleppers,'' or afterthoughts. Gore, for his part, greeted
the crowd with a hearty ``shalom aleichem.''
</P>
<P>
   For the most part, though, the Democrats were playing to voters
they had locked up well before the Lieberman selection. And in any
event, Jews comprised only 6 percent of the state's voters in 1996.
The most recent public polls, taken between the two party
conventions and before Gore's recent surge, showed Gov. George W.
Bush of Texas with a double-digit lead in Florida.
</P>
<P>
   Susan MacManus, a political scientist at the University of South
Florida, said she thinks the state is in play but would give a
slight edge to the Republicans. Gore, she said, is primarily
``coming to Florida to raise money and solidify his strongest
supporters.''
</P>
<P>
   David Colburn, a historian at the University of Florida, said
Gore would have difficulty overcoming the popularity and
organizational might of Bush's brother, Jeb, the state's governor,
and in surmounting the state's business-oriented, anti-tax ethos.
</P>
<P>
   And yet, all indications are that Gore is making a serious play
for Florida. His aides argue that the resources they are devoting
to the state are too significant to be dismissed as a mere head
fake aimed at seducing Bush into wasting time and money here. On
Monday, Gore plans to travel to Tallahassee, where Jeb Bush sits as
governor, to discuss health care. Florida also is one of 17 key
states where the campaign is broadcasting its first television
advertisement, a biographical spot that began airing on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush plans to visit Florida on Friday, and the
advertisements he began broadcasting this week also are airing in
Florida. ``We feel real good about our chances in Florida right
now,'' said Dan Bartlett, a Bush spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Florida is arguably the largest state that both campaigns view
as tightly contested. Gore holds an edge in California, a state
with 54 electoral votes that President Clinton and Gore won in both
1992 and 1996. New York, with 33 electoral votes, has been won by
Republicans only three times since 1960, and Clinton won the state
easily in the last two elections. Bush is expected to rout Gore in
his home state of Texas, which has 32 electoral votes. Two hundred
and seventy electoral votes are needed to win.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Florida, which has 25 electoral votes, and a history
of fickleness in presidential elections. The Democrats won the
state in 1996 and narrowly lost it in 1992. Once a Democratic
stronghold in local politics from the Panhandle to the Keys, the
state now has one U.S. Senator from each party, and its 23 member
congressional delegation includes 15 Republicans and eight
Democrats.
</P>
<P>
   Some Florida Democrats worried that Gore had signaled his
surrender in the state by not placing Sen. Bob Graham on his short
list of potential running mates. And Florida remains the locus of
what is considered, both inside and outside the Gore campaign, as
the vice president's most debilitating blunder _ his break with the
White House in calling for permanent resident status for Elian
Gonzalez.
</P>
<P>
   In a state where 18 percent of the population is 65 or older,
the largest proportion of elderly in any state, Gore used
Wednesday's appearance to promote his proposal for a $3,000 income
tax credit for long-term care. The credit would go either to
individuals whose disabilities or illnesses leave them unable to
care for themselves, or to family members who pay for their
relatives' care.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore campaign estimates that up to 5 million Americans would
be eligible for the credit. Aides to Gore project that the
initiative would cost $27 billion over 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   The plan is one component of Gore's $500 billion menu of
targeted tax cuts that would take effect over the next decade and
would primarily benefit middle-class Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, by contrast, would cut taxes by $1.3 trillion over 10
years, primarily through an across-the-board reduction in income
tax rates. The Bush plan includes a tax deduction for long-term
care insurance premiums, at a cost of $5.1 billion over five years,
and a new tax exemption, valued at $2,750, for each elderly spouse,
parent or relative that a caregiver tends to in the home. That
proposal would cost $2.3 billion over five years.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
