<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 20:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0416 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-WILDFIRES-GAVOLUNTEER     08-23 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WILDFIRES-GAVOLUNTEERS0824-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgians fighting Montana fires
 &HT;    By Charles Seabrook
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   MISSOULA, Montana _ For Bobby and Vickie Kitchens, the past few
weeks seem like a blur.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of this month, the two retirees from the U.S.
Forest Service were lounging in the sun on Tybee Island when
Bobby's pager beeped. The message, in short, said their help was
urgently needed to combat the raging fires charring western
Montana, and please get there as soon as possible.
</P>
<P>
   So Bobby, 61, and Vickie, 51, immediately headed home to
Acworth, Ga., hastily packed their recently washed fire clothes and
rushed to the airport.
</P>
<P>
   The call was not unexpected. Since he officially retired in 1994
as head silviculturist for the Forest Service's southern regional
office in Atlanta, Bobby Kitchens has helped fight more than two
dozen fires in 20 states. And in several of those battles, Vickie,
a retired fire service dispatcher, has been with him.
</P>
<P>
   Like thousands of other former and current Forest Service
workers across the country, Bobby Kitchens is certified for various
firefighting skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``Timber management was my day job; fire-fighting was my side
job,'' he quipped. ``Now that I've retired, I'm busier than ever
chasing fires.''
</P>
<P>
   And so for most of this month, he and Vickie have been among the
senior residents of a sprawling, 2,000-plus fire base camp about 60
miles south of Missoula and the rugged Bitterroot Valley, where
some of Montana's fiercest blazes are raging.
</P>
<P>
   They also are among scores of retired federal and state
government employees trained in firefighting who have donned work
clothes to help battle the worst wildfires the West has seen in
more than a century.
</P>
<P>
   At the fire base camp, Vickie has been documenting and filing
daily incident reports, while Bobby, a 32-year Forest Service
veteran, has been helping evacuate residents whose homes are at
risk, conducting community relations and helping coordinate
communications between firefighters in the field and at the base
camp.
</P>
<P>
   For the twosome, it has meant sleeping in a tent for most of
August, using a portable latrine the size of a telephone booth and
eating meals in a mess tent with hundreds of their fellow base camp
workers and firefighters.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we love it,'' said Vickie, as she and Bobby took a break
at the base camp this week inside a green canvas tent with a dusty
floor. ``It means that we don't sleep in our own beds as often as
we'd like, but we enjoy it.''
</P>
<P>
   What keeps Bobby coming back to fire after fire even in
retirement is what he said is the sheer adrenaline rush and the
adventurous nature of fighting wildfires.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know when or where you'll be called,'' he said.
``But even more than that, you get the satisfaction of knowing that
you are helping people when they really need it most.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, he and Vickie were looking forward to returning home
this week for a few days of rest and relaxation. The Forest Service
requires a mandatory time off period about every two weeks for
personnel battling the flames.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to see my grandchildren,'' Vickie said. She and Bobby
have six grown children. Next week, however, the couple expects to
be back in Montana helping fight the flames.
</P>
<P>
   Keith Wooster, heading home today, also is taking a few days
away from the smoke and heat of the Montana fires. ``But I'll
probably be back next Monday,'' he said. ``It looks like these
fires will be going through at least October.''
</P>
<P>
   Wooster is a certified wildlife biologist with the Chattahoochee
National Forest in North Georgia, but as a skilled firefighter he
is liable to be dispatched anywhere in the country to help put out
fires when they erupt.
</P>
<P>
   For most of August, he helped battle the Ryan Gulch fire about
30 miles east of Missoula that has blackened about 18,000 acres.
His main job at the base camp there is as a ``fire behavior
analyst,'' using weather information and other data to predict the
direction of the fire and determine how fast it is moving.
</P>
<P>
   He also has spent a lot of time in the rugged terrain of steep
mountain slopes on the frontlines. At the beginning of the week, he
and his colleagues slipped and slid down a precipitous slope to set
a backfire with kerosene torches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're trying to fight fire with fire,'' he explained. ``This
area is going to get burned by the wildfire if we don't burn it
first; what we are trying to do is make it burn under our terms.
That way we can control it and keep the wildfire from spreading.''
</P>
<P>
   When the backburn was set, Wooster and his colleagues watched
the orange flames rapidly consume the ultra-dry vegetation. ``This
is a textbook backburn,'' Wooster said proudly.
</P>
<P>
   By Wednesday, the Ryan Gulch fire was mostly contained and fire
officials were planning to release some of the crews, helicopters
and bulldozers fighting that fire to battle other conflagrations
raging elsewhere in Montana.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a good chance I'll be fighting another fire next
week,'' Wooster said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
