<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-ECLEFTIC24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Putting his best rap forward
 &HT;    By Sonia Murray
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   If Wyclef Jean's work with his record-setting rap group the
Fugees _ or as producer on the Carlos Santana song ``Maria Maria''
_ didn't convince you of his abilities, consider ``The Ecleftic''
Exhibit C.
</P>
<P>
   As in strong evidence that no matter how frequent rap records
seem to speak only of material possessions of late, they can still
say something meaningful about relationships and real issues.
Though hip-hop originated simply, with two turntables playing bits
or samples of other records, this album is proof that it can still
move forward musically. And, yes, Fugee fans, it could even be one
of the points you use to contradict the oft-heard argument that
these solo records must stop, and the group _ 1999's big
Grammy-winning vocalist Lauryn Hill, Jean, and the seemingly
disposable Pras _ should get back together and record.
</P>
<P>
   Since Jean's Grammy-nominated solo debut ``Carnival'' was
released in 1997, he's produced R&AMP;B's Whitney Houston, rap's
Canibus and rock's Sinead O'Connor. So we shouldn't be surprised
that here he's still mixing it up: bringing in country's Kenny
Rogers (somewhat awkwardly on the elementary crowd-rouser ``Kenny
Rogers/Pharoah Monch Dub''); WWF wrestler The Rock (comically on
the dig at material rappers, ``It Doesn't Matter''); and veteran
soul band Earth, Wind &AMP; Fire (dynamically on the simplistic tale
about struggling lives, ``Runaway'').
</P>
<P>
   But seven songs later it's just Jean and his skillfully-played
electric guitar, lamenting last year's police shooting of a fellow
Haitian, the unarmed Amadou ``Diallo.'' After revealing what he can
bring out of others and other genres, the sometimes sleepy sounding
rapper turns rough-hewn reggae singer here, revealing ``The
Ecleftic'' one at his musical and lyrical best.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ecleftic''
</P>
<P>
   Wyclef Jean. Ruff House Records/Columbia. 19 tracks. Grade: A-
</P>
<P>
   _Sonia Murray writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : More on Wyclef Jean and Columbia Records:
www.columbiarecords.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
