<HEADER>
A0419 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e BC-AUDIO-MINIS24-COX     08-23 0380
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AUDIO-MINIS24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CD mini reviews
 &HT;    By A. Scott Walton and Nick Tate
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QR;  JAZZ
</P>
<P>
   ``One Alone''
</P>
<P>
   Dave Brubeck. Telarc. 13 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: A
</P>
<P>
   It may not be until the sixth track of Dave Brubeck's first solo
piano release in five years that you wake up and realize that he's
still one of those singularly ingenious talents who can captivate
you playing all by himself. Until then, when ``Just Squeeze Me''
segues seamlessly through ``Harbour Lights'' to ``Things Ain't What
They Used To Be,'' it's not readily apparent that this release is a
gift to treasure. Throughout, Brubeck explores tunes best loved for
their vocal interpretations by the likes of Sinatra (``I'll Never
Smile Again''), Armstrong (``That Old Feeling'') and Ruth Etting
(``You've Got Me Crying''). But it's Brubeck's distinguished
virtuosity _ and the prospect of one day losing him _ that'll truly
bring a tear to the eye.
</P>
<P>
   _A. Scott Walton
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : More on Dave Brubeck:
www.schirmer.com/composers/brubeckbio.html
</P>
<P>
   More on Telarc: www.telarc.com/
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  SOUNDTRACK
</P>
<P>
   ``The Ballad of Ramblin' Jack''
</P>
<P>
   Jack Elliott, with Bob Dylan, Woody Guthrie and others.
Vanguard. 20 tracks.
</P>
<P>
   Grade: B+
</P>
<P>
   Soundtracks are rarely the main event; so often these days the
music has no bearing on the film. But this collection of rarities
from one of the nation's most enduring folk troubadours is a
riveting exception. The music is the main event in the new
documentary about Jack Elliott, whose pioneering flat-picking
guitar style, cultivated Oklahoma twang and gritty cowboy folk
sound bridged the gap between Woody Guthrie (who influenced him)
and Bob Dylan (whom he influenced). Produced by his daughter,
Aiyana, the film and album feature stellar Elliott performances
with the likes of Dylan, Guthrie and Johnny Cash. While poor sound
quality tarnishes some of these tracks, on the whole, ``Ballad'' is
a worthy accounting of this living legend _ a man Bill Clinton
recently (and rightfully) called ``An American treasure.''
</P>
<P>
   _Nick Tate
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : More on Ramblin' Jack Elliott.
www.vanguardrecords.com, www.RamblinJack.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
