<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Growing up a subject for critics awards
 &HT;    By Don O'Briant
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Georgia writer's memoir about growing up next to a junkyard
and a North Carolina author's novel about an Appalachian woman at
the turn of the century have won this year's awards from the
Southern Book Critics Circle.
</P>
<P>
   Baxley resident Janisse Ray received the nonfiction award for
``Ecology of a Cracker Childhood'' (Milkweed, $19.95), which
combines natural history and autobiography. The environmental
activist has a graduate degree from the University of Montana and
has published essays and poems in several magazines and literary
journals.
</P>
<P>
   Fiction winner Robert Morgan's ``Gap Creek'' (Algonquin Books of
Chapel Hill, $22.95), which was picked for Oprah's Book Club, is
the story of Julia Harmon Richards and her difficult first year of
marriage. The 17-year-old bride faces death, sickness, starvation
and a number of natural and unnatural disasters.
</P>
<P>
   Morgan's previous novels include ``The Hinterlands'' and ``The
Truest Pleasure.'' He teaches at Cornell University and will be a
visiting writer this fall at Appalachian State University in Boone,
N.C.
</P>
<P>
   The awards will be presented Oct. 13 at the Southern Festival of
Books in Nashville.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  New growth: Fans of Stephen King have been providing extra
doses of fertilizer to ``The Plant'' to keep the author's serial
Internet novel alive and well. Amazon.com, which is processing
payments for King, reports that some readers have been sending in
extra money for the $1 installments _ from $2 to $20 _ to make up
for deadbeat downloaders.
</P>
<P>
   As the second installment creeps onto the Web this week at
www.stephenking.com, 76 percent of the readers have upheld the
honor system and sent in their money.
</P>
<P>
   In the new chapter, aspiring author Carlos Detweiller,
distraught at having his novel rejected, retaliates by sending a
strange (and possibly flesh-eating) plant to the editors at Zenith
House.
</P>
<P>
   To keep up reader interest, King says he is considering making
future installments as much as six or seven times longer and
selling them for $2.50 each.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Busman's holiday: So what do publishing executives read when
they're on vacation? Publishing Trends newsletter surveyed some of
the major New York houses and found that most were reading books
from other publishers. Nina Hoffman, president of National
Geographic's Books and School Publishing Group, took along Anita
Shreve's ``The Pilot's Wife'' and Barbara Delinsky's ``The
Vineyard,'' but she also is reading the Harry Potter novels to
understand their appeal to adults. And what's on the list for the
folks at J.K. Rowling's publisher? Scholastic vice president
Michael Jacobs says he's reading ``Anil's Ghost'' by Michael
Ondaatje and ``A Good Walk Spoiled'' by John Feinstein. But, he
adds, he's listening to audio tapes of the Harry Potter books ``as
background music.''
</P>
<P>
   Don O'Briant writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail: dobriant(at)ajc.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
