<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-SMOKING24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    With some innovation, smoldering wood flavor can be added to
anything ... well, almost anything
 &HT;    By John Kessler
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   About 10 years ago I cooked in a restaurant where the owner,
perhaps unwisely, encouraged me to indulge in whatever cooking
obsession was gripping me at the moment.
</P>
<P>
   So I surprised everyone one evening with a Russian fish pastry
called coulibiac. Tempura-fried everything in sight. And spent a
fortune on the Mexican seed paste achiote.
</P>
<P>
   I played and played. When I created the infamous cream of taro
soup with sweetbreads, I almost had my creative license revoked.
</P>
<P>
   But then I discovered stovetop smoking. And some really
delicious things started to come out of the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Like many chefs at the time, I realized that I didn't need to
invest in a full outdoor smoking rig in order to impart the sweet
flavor of smoldering wood. It was easy enough to find a large pan
with a fitted lid, enclose wood chips and foodstuffs inside, place
it over a flame, and let the smoke work its alchemy.
</P>
<P>
   I smoked chicken. Tomatoes. Onions and shallots. And I racked up
success after success.
</P>
<P>
   True, I couldn't make decent ribs or turkey breast on top of my
stove. Nothing that required hours of cooking time. The very best
dishes were the ones that trapped the quick, intense billows of
smoke in a compliant host. A creamy vinaigrette made with smoked
tomatoes and a salad outfitted with fat, glistening smoked oysters
became my signatures.
</P>
<P>
   Chicken and salmon were good, as long as I partially cooked them
in smoke and finished them on the grill to retain their juices.
</P>
<P>
   I smoked and smoked. The designated smoking pan grew so black
with splotchy stains from the wood resin that we had to keep it
outdoors when we weren't using it or else it made the kitchen smell
like a smokehouse.
</P>
<P>
   After a while I tried smoking everything that wasn't nailed to
the floor or didn't run away in abject terror. I smoked ginger. I
smoked potatoes. And found absolutely nothing to do with them. I
knew my smoking craze was drawing to an end. And so I stopped.
</P>
<P>
   But I kept the recipes.
</P>
<P>
   John Kessler writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-00 2058EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
