<DOCNO> NYT20000823.0371 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 20:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0423 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-GARDENING-LIFE24-COX     08-23 1719
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GARDENING-LIFE24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Nature's bonsai designs outshine human sacrifice
 &HT;    By Lee May
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gardeners collect.
</P>
<P>
   By any means necessary, we will find a way to find a plant. We
beg for cuttings in the name of ``improving'' a friend's
``overgrown'' specimen, we ``rescue'' plants that seem threatened
(or out of place) where they're growing.
</P>
<P>
   I know gardeners who boast of the booty they get when flower
shows close and the stunning displays are given away. One friend
says he began a great rose garden with plants propagated from rose
stems he found in curbside trash.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of roses, the fine folks who sell plants at the Antique
Rose Emporium in Dahlonega, Ga., proudly call themselves ``rose
rustlers'' because they've propagated plants from roadsides and
abandoned homesteads and such. My favorite type, these are
sometimes called ``found'' roses.
</P>
<P>
   Who among us has not haunted nurseries, seeking a castaway plant
on its last stem, gasping for its last breath. Just before it is
relegated to the trash heap, we pounce, taking it home for a
pittance, loving not just the bargain but the challenge of nursing
it back to health, the thrill of accomplishing that.
</P>
<P>
   We who love bonsai are particularly keen on plants that
nurseries have a difficult time moving. Sell (or give) us your
gnarled, your stunted, your weird; they make great trees in trays.
</P>
<P>
   I remember the excitement of finding a little red pine at an
Atlanta nursery several years ago, figuring I couldn't afford it,
as it had a 5-inch trunk and was only about a foot high. When I saw
the price _ $12 _ I almost fell down rushing to the cash register.
</P>
<P>
   As good as such a find is, it doesn't approach what I saw
recently when I visited a bonsai garden in Lithonia, Ga.
</P>
<P>
   Bruce Winchester found a great tree growing not at a nursery but
in the wild near his home. His cedar proves what so many of us
appreciate: Nature, the most extraordinary of designers, can make a
much better bonsai than can any ordinary expert using a roomful of
tools and a headful of knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   Winchester, a maintenance worker at Georgia Perimeter College in
Dunwoody,Ga., had invited Jo Ann Yeager Adkins, Melanie and Michael
Brough, Marc Fitten and me to his garden on this blue-hot July
Sunday. As we strolled his rocky paths among the dusty miller,
petunias and celosia, we could see his devotion and work in the
aboveground displays of bonsai, including boxwood, pine, juniper
and bald cypress.
</P>
<P>
   Among the miniaturized trees and shrubs, that little found cedar
was the one that jumped into my attention. With fond recollection,
Winchester told us about it.
</P>
<P>
   Twelve years ago, with permission of the property owner,
Winchester went exploring and came upon two cedars. One had curled
around a rock, creatison, James Coburn and Robert Vaughn. And, of
course, McQueen, who was then the star of the TV western ``Wanted _
Dead or Alive.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie is an American version of the Akira Kurosawa classic,
``The Seven Samurai,'' with cowboys replacing samurai and rescuing
a tiny Mexican village from a rampaging Eli Wallach and his
marauding band of bandits. Reportedly, McQueen and Brynner didn't
get along, but Brynner huffily denied the rumors of a feud, saying,
``I don't feud with supporting players.''
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Blob'' (1958): Maybe not McQueen's finest movie but
certainly one of his most memorable. He was 28, but played a
high-school student who figures out how to defeat some deadly
Jell-O from outer space that, as one reviewer said at the time,
``eats you instead of the other way around.'' McQueen, who
considered himself a serious Broadway actor, was initially
reluctant to do the movie, but his first wife, Neile, assured him
it was so schlocky it would ``disappear at the drive-ins.'' To
McQueen's chagrin, the movie instead became a hit (it earned 30
times what it cost) and has remained a cult classic of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``Bullitt'' (1968): Before there was ``Ronin'' or ``The French
Connection'' or the zillion and one car chases that have inundated
movie screens in between, there was ``Bullitt's'' gravity-defying
hill-jumping chase through the streets of San Francisco. McQueen
plays a tough, goes-his-own-way police detective (sort of a
precursor to Clint Eastwood's Dirty Harry) who's investigating the
death of a Mafia mobster. His old ``Magnificent Seven'' co-star,
Vaughn, is his nemesis, a suavely corrupt political type. A
gorgeous newcomer named Jacqueline Bisset (with whom McQueen
supposedly had an off-screen affair) is his girlfriend. The
convoluted plot is loosely based on a book called ``Mute Witness,''
but the car chase is what everyone remembers. That and how totally
cool McQueen looks in a black turtleneck.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  ``The Great Escape'' (1963): It's the Steve movie. The one
that showcases everything from McQueen's brash, mocking,
street-rebel attitude to his aptitude for riding motorcycles (even
though it's his pal, stuntman Bud Ekins, who actually does the big
60-foot jump over the barbed-wire fence.) The movie reunited a lot
of the ``Magnificent Seven'' cast (Coburn, Bronson) and added
talents such as James Garner, Richard Attenborough, Donald
Pleasance, Gordon Jackson and David McCallum. It's based on the
true story of a heroic escape attempt made by some Allied officers
from a German prisoner-of-war camp during World War II. While it
was being filmed, McQueen was convinced that Garner was stealing
the picture and would emerge the big star. Garner would have his
day _ his role presages his ``Rockford Files'' character _ but it
was McQueen who came out of ``The Great Escape'' a bona fide movie
star.
</P>
<P>
   Other McQueen movies worth checking out: ``The Cincinnati Kid''
(1965), ``The Thomas Crown Affair'' (1968), ``The Getaway'' (1972),
``The Reivers'' (1969) and ``Papillon'' (1973).
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  O N T H E W E B : For more on Steve McQueen:
members.tripod.com/(tilde)stvmcqueen/
</P>
<P>
   Eleanor Ringel Gshion blends the interior with the outdoors via
glass and natural materials. ``I love being different.''
</P>
<P>
   The brick-and-redwood house, which the owners dubbed Sequoyah,
also lends the perfect backdrop for Dull's collection of
20th-century modern art.
</P>
<P>
   And Georgians will get to hang on to this rare gem among
Southern architecture, thanks to the efforts of the owners and
their interior designer, who persuaded them to revive it. The 1998
project, headed by Herbert Brito of the Atlanta design firm Brito
Serrato, has won a rehabilitation award from the Georgia Trust for
Historic Preservation. The house, among the youngest ever honored,
was cited as the state's best example of Wrightian architecture.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just so unusual for this city and this part of the
country,'' Baites said.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia claims none of the 270 Wright homes worldwide, which
makes Sequoyah all the greater a treasure among the ubiquitous
traditional-style homes that line Atlanta's streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``Herbert says we're ultimately custodians of things and only
pass them on to others,'' Dull said. ``That thought registered with
me as we took on the house, because in this city, it probably would
have eventually been torn down.''
</P>
<P>
   Brito stumbled onto the house on a tip from a friend and, had
the designer not just launched a major overhaul of his Midtown
condo, would have snapped it up for himself. Instead, he called his
friend Dull (rhymes with ``jewel''), who had been searching for
just the right house for his large-scale paintings, works of
mid-century artists such as Frank Stella and Robert Rauschenberg.
</P>
<P>
   ``When he saw it he got so excited he postponed a business trip
to New York,'' Brito recalled.
</P>
<P>
   The house had Wright written all over it _ the tranquil setting
nestled on a wooded embankment along Tanyard Creek, the
cantilevered decks, the glassed-in corners, the built-in
furnishings.
</P>
<P>
   And it should. In 1960, the house was then-24-year-old Green's
first, having just finished his training at Wright's famed studio
school, Taliesin. He designed it for banker Bill Copeland and his
family, the sole owners until Dull came along.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hadn't been lived in for a year so it was pretty much a
wreck,'' Dull said.
</P>
<P>
   Brito had met Green so he called him, and over lunch the two
pored over the architect's 40-year-old drawings. The house was in
good condition structurally but begged for updated kitchen and
baths. So the goals became to preserve the overall design while
accommodating the new owners' lifestyle.
</P>
<P>
   They accomplished that not so much ripping out walls but honing
in on details. While the exterior went untouched, hundreds of feet
of expensive redwood shiplap planks covering interior walls and
ceilings were removed, recut and coded so they could be properly
replaced in the kitchen and other rooms that were remodeled. Brito
designed wooden heating vents to replace metal ones so they'd blend
with the floor. He also created redwood-faced panels to conceal
recessed lights, making the fixtures barely noticeable in the wood
ceiling.
</P>
<P>
   Until now, the only structural change had occurred in 1987 when
Green was called on to enclose an upstairs porch as a study.
(Baites, managing director for Georgia State University's Rialto
Center for the Performing Arts, uses it as a home office.)
</P>
<P>
   Now, the mission was to find even more space within the 3,800
square foot house while leaving the exterior intact. To ensure no
detail went overlooked, Brito, who has extensive preservation
experience, served as general contractor for the six-month project.
</P>
<P>
   The tiny kitchen was converted to a bar/service area, while the
adjacent family room provided a larger space for a new kitchen.
Upstairs, two of the four bedrooms were joined to make an office
for Dull, who works for Anderson Consulting. A linen closet was
reconfigured to enlarge the master bath.
</P>
<P>
   The three bathrooms were updated with all-natural materials,
including granite vanities, slate floors and beechwood cabinetry.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every board got taken down, but we reused every scrap,'' Dull
said. ``We recycled everything, including the old kitchen cabinets,
which we moved to the laundry room.''
</P>
<P>
   Danny C. Flanders writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
