<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   United Airlines Requires Overtime for Mechanics
</P>
<P>
   To help overcome delays and cancellations that have plagued it
this summer, United Airlines has issued an order requiring
mechanics at five airports to work overtime if asked. About 50 of
the airline's 10,000 mechanics have been working overtime in
Chicago, Los Angeles, Washington and Indianapolis to try to make
sure that flights take off on time. An order, called an operational
emergency, was also issued in Denver, but no mechanics have been
asked to work overtime there. United and union spokesmen said the
airline does not often issue such an order. Shares of UAL, United's
parent, fell $1, to $47.63.
</P>
<P>
   Stocks Edge Up After Fed Decision
</P>
<P>
   Stocks closed modestly higher as investors surveyed a new
economic outlook that apparently includes stable interest rates.
The Dow Jones industrial average rose 5.50 points, to 11,144.65.
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index climbed 7.84 points, or 0.5
percent, to 1,505.97, and the Nasdaq composite index was up 52.80
points, or 1.3 percent, to 4,011.01.
</P>
<P>
   One Issue Seen Prolonging Strike
</P>
<P>
   An agreement to end a strike by employees of Verizon
Communications in several mid-Atlantic states was held up by a
single issue _ the type of work cable splicers and service
technicians can do in Pennsylvania, people close to the
negotiations said.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney's Business Record
</P>
<P>
   Just how successful Dick Cheney, the Republican vice
presidential nominee, was as chief executive of Halliburton is a
matter of considerable dispute, judging by a broad survey of his
record that included interviews with current and former company
executives.
</P>
<P>
   Simon &AMP; Schuster to Sell E-Books
</P>
<P>
   Simon &AMP; Schuster announced a list of electronic books that it
will sell this fall, becoming the third major trade publisher to
make books available for downloading.
</P>
<P>
   Senate Hearings on Tires to Be Held
</P>
<P>
   The Senate Commerce Committee is planning to conduct hearings on
the Firestone tires that were recalled, a Congressional aide said.
The committee will convene hearings next month to examine the
recent problems that caused Bridgestone/Firestone to recall about
6.5 million tires, the staff member said. Senator John McCain of
Arizona, chairman of the committee, requested the hearings.
</P>
<P>
   Profit Falls 74 Percent at Dillard's
</P>
<P>
   Dillard's, the department store chain, said that its
second-quarter profit plunged 74 percent, well below Wall Street
forecasts, as same-store sales declined 3 percent.
</P>
