<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TROCKS-DANCE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAN'T SAY TUTU MUCH ABOUT BALLETS TROCKADERO 
</HEADLINE>
   By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Les Ballets Trockadero de Monte Carlo may look nutty,
with its male ballerinas, over-the-top stage names and mostly witty
choreographic jokes. But on Tuesday night at the Joyce Theater, the
company presented the kind of dream repertory one seldom sees these
days. Although this second of two Joyce programs was mostly
classical ballet fare by the big guns of Russian and French ballet
in the 19th and early 20th centuries, there was also a dollop of
dance by that stalwart American avant-gardist Merce Cunningham.
</P>
<P>
   The centerpiece of the program was a new staging by Elena
Kunikova of Alexander Gorsky's ``Russian Dance,'' set to music by
Tchaikovsky. Fetchingly danced by Vanya Verikosa, the solo
incorporated a running gag with the kind of white handkerchief that
features in such folk dances. What made the joke funnier was the
way Kunikova incorporated folk-style moves into picking up and
dropping the handkerchief.
</P>
<P>
   One of the great pleasures of performances by the Trocks, as
they are affectionately known, is the exquisitely detailed
costumes. David Tetrault's gold and jewel-encrusted pinafore was
beautiful in itself, but the skirt rippled up to reveal a bright,
deep yellow underskirt that was a dazzling surprise.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Gonzales' costumes play an important part in the glittering
success of the Trocks' ``Paquita,'' staged by Kunikova after the
Petipa original. The tutus are a subtle rainbow of matte zinnia
colors that enhance the fundamental seriousness of this production.
The inept Igor Teupleze may look like Harry Potter as he wanders
cluelessly but amiably about the stage. But Olga Supphozova, the
company's reigning prima ballerina, proved that she is a seriously
accomplished dancer, rightly drawing cheers as she spun out what
looked like centuple multiple turns in the fouette section.
Supphozova also lives in her ballerina persona as she dances. One
reason audiences seem to love the Trocks so may well be that these
male ballerinas aim for the impossible with such success.
</P>
<P>
   The fine cast was completed by Sveltlana Lofatkina, Nadia
Rombova, a dogged little butterfly named Sylphia Belchick, and the
imposing Ida Nevasayneva.
</P>
<P>
   The dancing in Trutti Gasparinetti's staging of ``Le Grand Pas
de Quatre,'' an homage of sorts by Jules Perrot to four celebrated
ballerinas of the mid-19th century, is on the verge of becoming a
little broad. Less would definitely be more in Iona Trailer's
playing of Fanny Cerrito. Anya Marx is adorable as Lucile Grahn,
however, dancing with a sweetness that suggested why the Danish
ballerina, though contentious in her private life, was so acclaimed
on the stage. Fifi Barkova was amusingly stolid as Carlotta Grisi.
Nevasayneva, dancing the austere Marie Taglioni, protected her turf
with an awesomely chill ferocity that reminded one audience member
of every bad ballet teacher she had ever studied with.
</P>
<P>
   The evening opened with Gasparinetti's staging of the second act
of ``Swan Lake,'' which needs to lose a few of the pratfalls and
other ballet jokes, though its imitation of bad mime is hilarious.
The spunky little Maya Thickenthighya was a no-nonsense Odette,
with the artist formerly known as Prince Myshkin as her Prince
Siegfried. (Things tend to get complicated in Trockland.) Velour
Pilleaux, who bore a striking resemblance to Mme. Nevasayneva in
drag, was a silently cackling von Rothbart. He wore a red-and-black
cape that had the intricate dull glitter of jet beads, one of
Gonzales' most handsome designs.
</P>
<P>
   Cunningham? He was represented by his 1964 ``Cross Currents,''
staged by Meg Harper and danced to taped and live music ``after''
Conlon Nancarrow and John Cage. The entertainingly grim danseuses _
Rombova, Gerd Tord and Nikolai Legupski _ were upstaged by the two
uncredited musicians, whose contributions of found sound included
the crackling of candy wrappers and the manipulation of a
free-hanging zipper at several speeds.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
