<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBO-KRIKORIAN-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LUGINBILL: LEAGUE'S ON THE `UP AND UP'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DOUG KRIKORIAN  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The coach of the World Wrestling Federation-subsidized Los
Angeles professional football team, Mr. Al Luginbill, late of the
Amsterdam Admirals, is recalling that epic moment that would
inspire a storybook sporting season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to Anaheim to watch an Arena Football League game back
in 1996 to check out a receiver,'' recalls Luginbill. ``But what
caught my eye was the quarterback for the Iowa Barnstormers. The
guy's passes were amazingly accurate, and he just seemed to know
what he was doing out there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I talked to him after the season, but he told me he was
committed for another year with the Barnstormers. But I never
forgot him, and after the 1997 season I went after him again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I pitched him to 13 NFL teams, and only one, the St. Louis
Rams, expressed an interest in signing him. They did, and allocated
him to us. He had a terrific season in Amsterdam. We tied for the
league's championship with a 7-3 record, and two of the losses came
when he was out with an injury. I knew he was an exceptional
quarterback. But I must admit I never thought Kurt Warner would
have the kind of dream season he did last year for the Rams.''
</P>
<P>
   No one was prouder of Kurt Warner's achievements than Al
Luginbill, who watched all his games at a sports bar near his Del
Mar condominium and even was invited by the Rams to be their guest
for their match against the New York Giants.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kurt Warner seems to have what the John Unitases and Joe
Montanas had---tremendous game management,'' says Luginbill. ``He
has that knack for seeing everything on the field, and reacting to
what is happening. For sure, he's an accurate passer. But there are
a lot of accurate passers who simply don't understand how to play
the game.''
</P>
<P>
   As he assumes control of a new team that will perform in Vince
McMahon's fledging league, Al Luginbill realizes there are skeptics
who believe that there will be staged shenanigans and contrived
gimmicks befitting a McMahon promotion.
</P>
<P>
   Will Luginbill engage in a feigned feud with Dick Butkus,
another head coach in the XFL? Will he rant and rave during
interviews like the pro wrestlers do? Will he stalk along the
sidelines and spew Hulk Hogan venom when he disagrees with an
official's edict?
</P>
<P>
   ``No way I'd have taken this job if everything weren't on the up
and up,'' says Luginbill, who coached in Amsterdam for six seasons
and also was the head man at San Diego State between 1989 and 1993
(he had a 31-25-3 record). ``Sure, there are going to be some
different rules in this league, like the man in motion toward the
line of scrimmage on offense and the no-fair catch rule on punts
and the no kicks for the extra points. But as far as the actual
game competition, it's going to be totally legitimate.
</P>
<P>
   ``What caught my fancy about this league is that there is going
to be a level playing field. No one is going to have a financial
advantage like it was in the USFL (United States Football League)
when Donald Trump spent all that money to get good players for the
New Jersey Generals and George Allen did the same with the Chicago
Blitz.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this league, all the players are going to making about the
same---$50,000---and there's going to be a pre-season draft. I'm
really excited for the opportunity to be involved in something I
can foresee as being a big success.''
</P>
<P>
   The energetic Luginbill---he's 54 but looks at least 10 years
younger---already has put together his coaching staff, and a Long
Beach institution, Dave Levy, will be in charge of the offensive
line.
</P>
<P>
   A 1964 graduate of Corona High, Luginbill played football at Cal
Poly Pomona and was a head coach eight years at Pasadena City
College, guiding the school into the final Junior Rose Bowl in
1977.
</P>
<P>
   He also served as an assistant during two tours of duty at
Arizona State---he worked under Frank Kush and then Darryl
Rogers---before assuming control at San Diego State.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a coach who'll have a lot of rules, but I expect my
players to adhere to the ones I do have,'' says Luginbill. ``I want
my players to have fun. I see nothing wrong with guys celebrating
in the end zone after a score, but no way I want a guy celebrating
before he crosses the goal line.
</P>
<P>
   ``I also emphasize to my players that they're role models, and
that they must conduct themselves in a manner befitting their
status. If they don't, then they're off my team.''
</P>
<P>
   Al Lugbenbill was wearing a red XFL shirt when I had lunch with
him the other day, and his boss, J.K. McKay, the L.A. team's
general manager, wondered where he had obtained it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Got it from the league office,'' said Luginbill.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to get me one,'' said McKay.
</P>
<P>
   Look for XFL apparel soon to flood the Southern California
market, if Vince McMahon has anything to say about it since NFL
paraphernalia has been lagging in the wake of the 1995 departures
of the Rams and Raiders.
</P>
<P>
   ``My job will be the to coach the L.A. football team,'' says
Luginbill. ``I know I'm going to be miked during games, and that
everything I say has the potential to be heard on TV. I can't worry
about that. What I'm concerned about right now is finding me
another Kurt Warner.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
