<SLUG> BC-NY-STOLEN-COWS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK RUSTLERS CAUGHT WITH FIBERGLASS COW IN JEEP 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Conn.)   By ELISSA GOOTMAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The 500 life-size fiberglass cows that arrived on New
York City streets in June have inspired impassioned opinions. Some
people welcome the playful bovines, with their imaginative designs
by local artists. Others consider the whole cow parade thing just a
hokey import from Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, the cows inspired some old-fashioned rustling.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cow Hands,'' one of the fiberglass creatures in town for the
cow parade, and apparently the ideal tool for a practical joke, was
unfastened from its concrete base at West Houston Street and La
Guardia Place early Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The police arrived as ``Cow Hands'' was about to be loaded into
a blue Jeep Cherokee. The officers found Patrick Kraft, 24, of East
Windsor, N.J., and Michael Macisco, 23, of Stratford, Conn.,
apparently clearing their Jeep to make way for the cow, the police
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As I got closer to the Jeep, I could see that a statue of a
cow'' was leaning against it, Detective Andrew McDermott said.
While the two men were caught cow-handed, the police said, they
initially denied having anything to do with the blue and purple
stray, covered with white handprints.
</P>
<P>
   McDermott said the two soon confessed that they were plotting a
practical joke. They told the police that they were probably going
to station ``Cow Hands'' in front of a friend's Manhattan home,
although they were also toying with other ideas, the detective
said.
</P>
<P>
   At one point, they even considered placing the cow in front of a
vegetarian restaurant, McDermott said.
</P>
<P>
   By Wednesday afternoon, ``Cow Hands'' stood silently in the
Sixth Precinct station house, on West 10th Street, where she was to
be kept for 48 hours as evidence. Her green eyes pointed at the
front desk, which she appeared poised to charge. A stolen-property
invoice was fastened to her back with masking tape.
</P>
<P>
   Snapping a Polaroid picture for the station house scrapbook,
Officer Jon Goldin shook his head, saying that when he first saw
the cow at the station house, he figured it was a prop in a
publicity stunt. ``Well, that's life in a big city,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The bounty is hefty. Officials from the city and CowParade
Holdings, the parade organizers, were hoping that ``Cow Hands''
would fetch between $20,000 and $50,000 at an auction planned for
Sept. 28, whose proceeds are to be donated to six charities. Jerome
Elbaum, the president of CowParade Holdings, said a similar auction
in Chicago last year fetched an average price of $35,000, and the
most sought-after cow went for $110,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cow Hands'' was painted by the artist Edwina Sandys, who is
Winston Churchill's granddaughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's one of my best,'' Sandys said Wednesday, shortly after
learning of the attempted theft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know what the punishment should be for such a crime,''
Sandys mused, suggesting that the suspects do time ``working on a
farm or something.''
</P>
<P>
   The police said the two men were charged with grand larceny,
criminal possession of stolen property and criminal mischief, all
in the third degree.
</P>
<P>
   Since the cow parade began in June, about 50 of the 500 cows
have been damaged, Elbaum said, most from ``enthusiasm,'' some from
vandalism. In late June, the police discovered that the colorful
``Moo-Stripa'' cow had been removed from her spot in Forest Park,
in Richmond Hills, Queens. ``Moo-Stripa'' has since been recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the police arrested three New York teen-agers for a
decidedly rural form of mischief: cow-tipping, in John Jay Park in
Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   At a news conference Wednesday, Mayor Rudolph Giuliani said,
``Given the fact that on any given day you have 11 million people
in the city, the way in which the cows were treated was very
respectful.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
