<HEADER>
A0436 &Cx1f; tad-z
r d BC-FOOD-SMOKE-RECIPE24-C     08-23 2333
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOOD-SMOKE-RECIPE24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Simple stovetop method is really smokin'
 &HT;    By John Kessler
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   After a good amount of trial and error, I've devised this basic
method for stovetop smoking that works on all the following
recipes. Only the cooking times vary.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Soak wood chips in water for 10 minutes and drain. I don't
care for the resiny flavor of mesquite, so I always use hickory
chips.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Lay the chips out in the bottom of the designated smoking pot.
The chips should cover the bottom in a shallow layer _ 2 or 3 cups
should be plenty for any pot.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Cover the chips with a piece of aluminum foil _ heavy gauge is
best. Poke the foil with a small knife or skewer to create several
dozen slits. (The holes allow juices to drain to the bottom.)
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Add food to be smoked in a single layer and cover with a
tight-fitting lid.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Place pot directly on one or two (depending on size) burners
set on medium-high. The food should smoke at least 5 minutes for
flavor, but no more than 20 lest the burning wood turn the smoke
acrid.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Wait one minute before removing the lid or you'll get a blast
of smoke in your face.
</P>
<P>
   SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Smoked Tomato Dressing
</P>
<P>
   Makes about 2 cups
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   If there is one recipe on this page that could turn anyone into
a true believer in stovetop smoking, this is it. Talk about
versatile: This creamy, intriguing vinaigrette is sweet and tangy
like coleslaw dressing and would make a super change of pace on
shredded cabbage. Yet it stands up to bitter gourmet greens like
Belgian endive and radicchio. And, like all creamy dressings, it
loves nothing more than ice-cold iceberg and romaine, especially
with some blue cheese scattered on top. Then again, it's wildly
delicious on grilled fish.
</P>
<P>
   5 Roma tomatoes, halved
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 tablespoons peeled ginger, chopped
</P>
<P>
   3 tablespoons cider vinegar
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons sugar
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon kosher salt (or 1/2 teaspoon table salt)
</P>
<P>
   1 egg or pasteurized egg (or 2 liquid ounces egg substitute)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup vegetable oil
</P>
<P>
   Smoke the halved tomatoes for 10-12 minutes, using the technique
described above. When smoke has subsided, remove tomatoes and
transfer to a mesh strainer and place over bowl or sink. Let drain
for 10 minutes, until barely warm. Transfer to blender and add
ginger; blend 1 minute on high. Add vinegar, sugar, salt and egg;
blend 1 minute on high. With motor running, carefully remove
blender lid and drizzle in oil, slowly at first. Blend until pale
and creamy. Strain to remove skins, seeds and ginger bits. Chill at
least 30 minutes before serving.
</P>
<P>
   Per tablespoon: 67 calories, trace protein, 7 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 90), 1 gram carbohydrates, trace cholesterol, 63
milligrams sodium, trace fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Terrie's Lightly Smoked and Grilled Salmon on Vegetable
Fettuccine With Plum Tomato Vinaigrette
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 20 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Chef Paul Albrecht of Chef Paul's in Destin, Fla., gives salmon
an extraordinary flavor by lightly smoking it first, then grilling
it. Asian seasonings in the marinade play nicely against a plum
tomato vinaigrette.
</P>
<P>
   1 medium-size zucchini
</P>
<P>
   1 medium-size carrot
</P>
<P>
   1 medium-size yellow squash
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon dark sesame oil
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon sesame seeds
</P>
<P>
   4 (7-ounce) salmon fillets
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup teriyaki sauce
</P>
<P>
   Plum Tomato Vinaigrette (recipe follows)
</P>
<P>
   Cut zucchini, carrot and squash in strips the size of fettuccine
noodles and cook in salted water for 3 to 5 minutes, or until
tender; drain, then toss in sesame oil and sprinkle with sesame
seeds.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, marinate salmon fillets for five minutes in teriyaki
sauce. While salmon is marinating, prepare smoker. Smoke for 5
minutes, then wait 5 minutes before removing lid.
</P>
<P>
   On a grill or ridged skillet over medium-high heat, cook salmon
on both sides to desired doneness, 5 to 10 minutes total. Divide
vegetables among 4 plates and top each with a salmon fillet.
Drizzle 1 tablespoon Plum Tomato Vinaigrette around each fillet.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 331 calories, 39 grams protein, 16 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 43), 7 grams carbohydrates, 77
milligrams cholesterol, 261 milligrams sodium, 2 fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Plum Tomato Vinaigrette
</P>
<P>
   Makes 1 scant cup
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   4 plum tomatoes (fresh or canned)
</P>
<P>
   1 shallot
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons white wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   5 tablespoons extra-virgin olive oil
</P>
<P>
   Salt, pepper and granulated sugar to taste
</P>
<P>
   Cut tomatoes in pieces and blend in a food processor or blender
on high with the shallot, vinegar and olive oil until smooth, then
strain and season with salt, pepper and sugar.
</P>
<P>
   Per 1 tablespoon: 42 calories, trace protein, 4 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 89), 1 gram carbohydrates, no
cholesterol, 2 milligrams sodium, trace fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Smoked Chicken With Goat Cheese Stuffing
</P>
<P>
   Makes 6 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 2 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 30-40 minutes
</P>
<P>
   This chicken mostly finishes cooking in the smoker by the time
the skin turns golden brown _ after 18-20 minutes. Then it comes
out of the smoker and cools for a few minutes at room temperature
until easy to handle. You then stuff soft goat cheese under the
skin and finish cooking it in the oven. It emerges crisp,
crackling, juicy and captivating. Warm, Spicy Black Bean Salsa
(recipe above right) makes a wonderful bed for it, but this chicken
stands on its own.
</P>
<P>
   Legs are easy to stuff, but breasts take a little practice.
There is a neat trick: A thin membrane attaches the skin to the
meat, and if you don't puncture it, you can slide a good amount of
stuffing underneath. Always begin by wriggling your fingers under
the skin on the thick breastbone side and move toward the thin
backbone side.
</P>
<P>
   1 whole chicken (4-5 pounds, cut up)
</P>
<P>
   4 ounces (1 small log) soft, fresh goat cheese
</P>
<P>
   Kosher or sea salt
</P>
<P>
   Freshly ground coarse black pepper
</P>
<P>
   Prepare the stovetop smoker with soaked wood chips and aluminum
foil. Place the chicken pieces on top, cover and smoke over
medium-medium high heat for 18-20 minutes, or until the chicken is
bronzed and the internal temperature of the breasts registers 150
degrees on an instant-read thermometer. Remove from smoker and let
cool to room temperature. Preheat oven to 375.
</P>
<P>
   Stuff each piece of chicken under the skin with 1 ounce goat
cheese. Sprinkle skin with coarse salt and pepper. Roast in oven
for 12-15 minutes, until internal temperature of chicken registers
at least 160 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 408 calories, 47 grams protein, 23 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 52), trace grams carbohydrates, 142
milligrams cholesterol, 170 milligrams sodium, no fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Warm, Spicy
</P>
<P>
   Black Bean Salsa
</P>
<P>
   Makes 8 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   You can make this salsa ahead and reheat it in a saucepan. It is
a bit soupy, so serve it in a soup plate with the chicken on top to
pool the delicious juices.
</P>
<P>
   2 large tomatoes
</P>
<P>
   1/2 onion, chopped
</P>
<P>
   1 clove garlic, minced
</P>
<P>
   4 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon ground cumin
</P>
<P>
   1/2 teaspoon leaf oregano
</P>
<P>
   3 poblano peppers, roasted, peeled, seeded and chopped
</P>
<P>
   4 cups cooked black beans
</P>
<P>
   1/4 teaspoon red wine vinegar
</P>
<P>
   Salt to taste
</P>
<P>
   Place the tomatoes directly over a flame or burner and roast
until skin turns black and blisters. Set aside to cool. Remove most
of the skin and chop tomatoes coarsely. Set aside.
</P>
<P>
   Saute onion and garlic in large skillet in 1 tablespoon butter
until translucent. Add cumin, oregano, poblanos and chopped
tomatoes and stir until bubbling. Add beans, lower heat and simmer
for 10 minutes. Swirl in remaining butter and vinegar and season to
taste.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 179 calories, 9 grams protein, 5 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 24), 27 grams carbohydrates, 10 milligrams
cholesterol, 47 milligrams sodium, 10 grams fiber.
</P>
<P>
   APPETIZER
</P>
<P>
   Smoked Oysters
</P>
<P>
   Makes 4 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 5 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   I first ran this recipe in another newspaper, though I figured
few people would try it. Wrong. The last letter I got was two years
later, where one reader said the oysters had become an integral
part of her family Christmas dinner. If you like tinned smoked
oysters, these are a sensational step up.
</P>
<P>
   The oysters are first purified in salt, a time-honored Asian
technique that renders them sweet and clean. They are briefly
smoked to cook, then immediately immersed in olive oil flavored
with garlic and herbs. They can then be served over salad greens,
blended with cream cheese for a dip, tossed into a pasta or _ best
yet _ presented elegantly with a red pepper horseradish sauce
(recipe below).
</P>
<P>
   2 pints shucked Pacific oysters (the largest you can find)
</P>
<P>
   1 cup kosher salt
</P>
<P>
   1 1/2 cups olive oil
</P>
<P>
   1 head garlic, cut in half lengthwise
</P>
<P>
   2 large sprigs fresh rosemary
</P>
<P>
   2 large sprigs fresh thyme
</P>
<P>
   Drain the oysters and toss in a bowl with the salt. Let stand 5
minutes. Rinse very thoroughly in a strainer under running water.
Place the oysters in a single layer in the stovetop smoker and
smoke over medium-high heat for 8 minutes. During that time, place
the olive oil, garlic and fresh herbs in a large, heatproof bowl.
Transfer the hot oysters to the oil and let steep until they reach
room temperature. Transfer to a container and refrigerate until
ready to use. The oysters will keep for several days, as long as
they are immersed in the oil.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 200 calories, 18 grams protein, 10 grams fat
(percent calories from fat, 44), 10 grams carbohydrates, 131
milligrams cholesterol, 524 milligrams sodium, trace fiber.
</P>
<P>
   SAUCE
</P>
<P>
   Roasted Red Pepper
</P>
<P>
   and Horseradish Sauce
</P>
<P>
   Makes about 1 cup
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 2 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Here's a quick, pretty sauce to serve with cold seafood. Use red
horseradish if you want a lot of color for the presentation.
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup roasted red peppers (or jarred pimentos)
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup mayonnaise
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons prepared horseradish (red or white)
</P>
<P>
   1 teaspoon lemon juice
</P>
<P>
   Combine all ingredients in a food processor. Refrigerate until
ready to use.
</P>
<P>
   Per serving: 60 calories, trace protein, 6 grams fat (percent
calories from fat, 95), 1 gram carbohydrates, 6 milligrams
cholesterol, 72 milligrams sodium, trace fiber.
</P>
<P>
   MAIN DISH
</P>
<P>
   Pan-Smoked Shrimp
</P>
<P>
   With Orange Sauce
</P>
<P>
   Makes 2 servings
</P>
<P>
   Preparation time: 15 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Cooking time: 10 minutes
</P>
<P>
   Soak wooden skewers in water before using.
</P>
<P>
   12 large shrimp, peeled and deveined
</P>
<P>
   6 ounces snow peas (1 1/2 cups), strings removed
</P>
<P>
   Salt
</P>
<P>
   2 tablespoons butter
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup orange juice
</P>
<P>
   1 head baby bok choy, sliced 1/2 inch thick
</P>
<P>
   diagonally
</P>
<P>
   1 green onion, thinly sliced
</P>
<P>
   1/2 cup chicken or vegetable broth
</P>
<P>
   2 teaspoons cornstarch
</P>
<P>
   1 to 2 teaspoons water
</P>
<P>
   Pepper
</P>
<P>
   Cooked white rice
</P>
<P>
   Assemble smoker with 1 cup hardwood chips. Place over medium
heat.
</P>
<P>
   Thread 4 shrimp on set of 2 parallel skewers so shrimp are
stretched flat. Repeat with remaining shrimp, so that you have 3
sets of skewers.
</P>
<P>
   When wood chips begin to smoke, about 10 minutes, lay skewers on
rack and recover tightly with foil. If smoker is smoking too
forcefully, reduce heat. Smoke until shrimp have light tan hue, 4
minutes, then remove from smoker. Remove shrimp from skewers.
</P>
<P>
   Blanch snow peas in boiling salted water until crisp-tender, 1
to 2 minutes. Plunge in ice water to stop cooking and set color,
then drain well on paper towels.
</P>
<P>
   Bring butter and orange juice to boil in skillet over
medium-high heat; boil 1 minute. Add snow peas, bok choy, green
onion and broth. Saute until snow peas are almost tender, about 2
minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Mix cornstarch with just enough water to dissolve and add to
skillet, along with shrimp. Cook, stirring constantly, until shrimp
is opaque and sauce thickened, 30 seconds to 1 minute. Season with
salt and pepper to taste. Serve immediately over white rice. _ From
the Los Angeles Times
</P>
<P>
   Per serving (without rice): 248 calories, 16 grams protein, 11
grams fat (percent calories from fat, 39), 23 grams carbohydrates,
90 milligrams cholesterol, 579 milligrams sodium, 6 grams fiber.
</P>
