<HEADER>
A0439 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-TAX-NYT &LR;      08-23 1094
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-TAX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH SEEMS A LITTLE OFF TRACK IN WAKE OF DEMOCRATIC CONVENTION 
</HEADLINE>
  (Political Memo) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Gov. George W. Bush was supposed to be spending
this week focusing on education, the issue with which his campaign
is seeking the support of women and independent voters.
</P>
<P>
   But in his first days on the trail after the two parties'
conventions, he instead found himself reaching for big numbers and
defending his proposed tax cut in a manner that came across as
reactive and not entirely coherent.
</P>
<P>
   In that, and other ways, the brief period following the
Democratic National Convention has not been entirely flattering to
the Republican nominee.
</P>
<P>
   Following Vice President Al Gore's fiery pledge at the
Democratic National Convention on Thursday night to fight long and
hard for the presidency and the people he wanted to serve, Bush had
his chance to reclaim the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   But on Friday, his one public event was over by mid-afternoon,
and the high point on his remaining schedule was a run along one of
his favorite trails in allas. On Monday, after a day off, he told
reporters that one of the pleasures of his break was taking a nap.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, he added, ``Went to bed relatively early.''
</P>
<P>
   While this sort of thing represents a mere snapshot in time _
and comes in the two weeks before Labor Day, not the two weeks
before Election Day _ it has exposed some of the Texas governor's
weaknesses and quirks at a juncture when small impressions can
sometimes take on big significance as the attention to both
candidates intensifies.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's advisers said Wednesday that they were not concerned.
</P>
<P>
   One of them acknowledged that the Texas governor's largely
unprompted defense of his sweeping tax-cut proposal on Tuesday,
coupled with his admission that he needed to do a better job of
pitching it, had thrown the campaign off its chosen message.
</P>
<P>
   But the adviser said that the campaign would be back on track
later this week, with new education proposals on Thursday and a new
speech on international relations on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things like this happen,'' the adviser said. ``It's
overblown.''
</P>
<P>
   Another adviser said, ``If you look at our bad days versus our
good days, I'll take that equation any day.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``The great thing about this campaign is that it
always takes the long view.''
</P>
<P>
   These advisers and others said they had always expected the rise
in Gore's poll numbers and that the news media's spotlight on
anything and everything that looks like a sign of trouble in Bush's
campaign was an equally predictable part of the ever-shifting
dynamics of the race.
</P>
<P>
   But that equanimity itself raised questions.
</P>
<P>
   While Bush's advisers have taken great pains recently to talk
about how many states he planned to visit in late August, a
preliminary schedule for the next week and a half showed Bush
taking three days off of the campaign trail this weekend, traveling
just three days next week and then taking another three days off
before Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   Bush himself makes frequent comments about resting and sleeping
and a sensible pace, concerns that do not exactly portray him as a
ball of fire. His advisers sought to frame this as an advantage,
saying it casts him as a sensible man not utterly consumed by
politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore runs the risk of looking like he's just an absolute,
total political animal,'' one adviser said.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's acknowledgement that he had to sell his suggested tax
cut more forcefully than he has so far pointed to a different
problem: that a proposal that resonated with the Republican base in
the primaries could give pause to swing voters in the general
election. Many polls suggest that a tax cuts is low on a majority
of voters' wish lists.
</P>
<P>
   Although there was discussion in Bush's campaign before he made
that proposal last year about whether the size of it _ $1.3
trillion over 10 years _ was too large, Bush has promoted his plan
as a matter of unswerving principle and economic justice, and both
he and his advisers said he would not retreat from it.
</P>
<P>
   But some Democratic pollsters said that their research indicates
that voters, while happy to have some tax cuts, particularly for
middle-class Americans, worry about the effect of a large, broad
one on Social Security, Medicare and the economy in general. ``Bush
has walked into a significant trap of his own making on this,''
said Geoff Garin, a Democratic pollster.
</P>
<P>
   And one Republican strategist in Washington who sometimes
advises the Bush campaign conceded, ``What's Bush going to do? No
matter how hard he pushes his tax plan, it doesn't seem to catch
fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Several other Republican strategists and pollsters said that a
basic appetite among Americans for tax cuts was obvious in the fact
that Gore has offered a proposal totaling $500 billion over 10
years, and that Bush simply needed to push his plan in more
deliberate ways.
</P>
<P>
   During long stretches of time on the stump, especially recently,
he has often cast it in broad, ideological terms. John McLaughlin,
a Republican pollster, said that Bush ``has got to sell this as a
kitchen-table, pocketbook issue: This is what it means to  &UR; you &LR; .''
</P>
<P>
   Officials with the Bush campaign said that there were ample
signs that voters' desires for tax cuts had sharpened with
expanding surplus projections, especially if those voters were
convinced that cuts did not endanger entitlement programs like
Social Security and Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   Interestingly, Bush's unprompted defense of his tax cut this
week was an attempt to explain how spending and surplus projections
over the next week enabled him to accomplish that.
</P>
<P>
   But he stumbled over his numbers in a speech on Monday night and
then, when he revisited the topic with reporters on his campaign
plane the next day, went through the issue so quickly and
elliptically that aides had to come back to provide more detail on
his arithmetic, which turned out to be well in line with estimates
by the Congressional Budget Office.
</P>
<P>
   And that underscored a potentially larger concern for the Texas
governor, which has been on intermittent display since the
Democrats' convention: when he departs from the scripted eloquence
of a stump speech (and, sometimes, when he mangles the words within
it), he can seem fuzzy on specifics, less than forceful in his
thinking, tired.
</P>
<P>
   ``The minute he tries to get deep into the weeds, a la Al Gore,
who's excellent there, it runs counter to his personality,''
acknowledged one adviser.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
