<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0442 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u f BC-CMGI-PATRIOTS-BOS &LR;      08-23 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CMGI-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PATS, CMGI HOPE FOR WINNING TEAM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (f and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MEG VAILLANCOURT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ New England Patriots owner Robert Kraft tied his team's
image securely to the Internet Wednesday when he proclaimed that
the team's new stadium would be called CMGI Field.
</P>
<P>
   Kraft announced that CMGI Inc., the Andover-based Internet
giant, won the bidding war for naming rights to the stadium,
scheduled to open in 2002, with its offer of $7.6 million a year.
The annual payment equals the largest NFL naming deal to date,
FedEx Corp.'s 27-year contract with the Washington Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   But Kraft said the chief reason he chose CMGI was not the money,
but CMGI founder and chief executive David Wetherell.
</P>
<P>
   The 45-year-old Wetherell, an icon of the Internet community,
heads a network of nearly 70 Internet-related businesses, such as
AltaVista and Engage and controls a stake in dozens of other
companies, including the search engine Lycos.
</P>
<P>
   ``David Wetherell saw the opportunity of the Internet and went
on to create a portfolio of companies that touches every aspect of
our economy,'' Kraft said Wednesday. ``We feel that vision and
drive mirrors our goal with the Patriots. And for our fans, who've
put up with a substandard facility for almost 30 years, this
partnership signals the dawn of a new era.''
</P>
<P>
   Since the Patriots new $325 million stadium is privately
financed, the funds garnered from naming rights are crucial to the
team's ability to maintain a competitive edge.
</P>
<P>
   And while the rigors of New England's weather will delay the
introduction of so-called ``smart seat technology'' for a few
years, the new partnership is eventually expected to allow Patriots
fans in the new stadium to call up player statistics and view
instant replays from another camera angle on small seatback
computers.
</P>
<P>
   But what does Wetherell, a wunderkind of the New Economy, hope
to gain by spending $120 million for a 15-year naming rights
contract at a football stadium in Foxborough?
</P>
<P>
   Wetherell argues it's a cost-effective way for CMGI, the state's
seventh-largest public company in terms of stock market value but a
cypher to most consumers, to create brand identity. It also offers
the company a foothold in one of the most explosive growth
opportunities on the Web: sports and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   ``By partnering with the Patriots and the NFL, the number one
sports league in the world in terms of marketing, we are obtaining
an unmatched brand-awareness opportunity,'' Wetherell said.
</P>
<P>
   Team vice chairman Jonathan Kraft, who became friends with
Wetherell when the two men served on the board on an Internet
company several years ago, noted that NFL games are watched by more
than 100 million Americans each weekend.
</P>
<P>
   When the league's international media exposure is factored in,
it's estimated that the name CMGI Field will be seen or publicly
mentioned more than 2.6 billion times each year _ at a cost of less
than 2 percent of CMGI's annual advertising budget.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically, corporations have been able to build up their
brand names slowly,'' Kraft said. ``But with the Internet, you have
companies that didn't exist a few years ago generating billions of
dollars in revenues on international basis. They need to look at
strategies that can create global awareness almost overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   ``By putting its name on a NFL stadium, a company will be woven
into the fabric of pop culture in this country,'' Kraft said.
``Halfway through the football season, everyone will know the name
CMGI.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, high-tech companies have increasingly sought instant
status by buying the right to name a sports facility, dramatically
increasing the prices. PSINet, a Virginia-based computer-services
company, is paying $5.25 million a year to put its name on the
Baltimore Ravens new nest. Qualcomm, 3Com, PacBell, and Ericsson
also are now known as stadiums as well as high-tech companies.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, CMGI shareholders appeared eager to see the company's
name in lights. While the Nasdaq was up just 1 percent, shares of
CMGI were up 16 percent. Shares rose $6.19 to $43.94 in trading of
13.4 million shares, more than twice the company's three month
average. Aside from the Patriots deal, no other company news was
released Wednesday, CMGI officials said.
</P>
<P>
   A former mathematics major who founded CMGI when he took a small
textbook direct marketing company known as College Market Group
public in 1994, Wetherell is seen as having a particular genius for
on online marketing.
</P>
<P>
   But when asked whether CMGI would buy naming rights for the Red
Sox new ballpark, Wetherall, a fanatic baseball player in his
youth, demurred.``I think there will be a backlash to renaming
Fenway Park,'' he said. ``Like a lot of people, I think it would be
great if the team could find someone who wants to buy the naming
rights but will keep the name. ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-00 2119EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
