<DOCNO> NYT20000823.0383 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0443 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-FLA-REPORTER-NYT &LR;      08-23 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FLA-REPORTER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHEN HIS HEART STOPPED AT 92, MILT SOSIN FINALLY QUIT REPORTING 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICK BRAGG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Milt Sosin lived for the story.
</P>
<P>
   As a reporter in South Florida, he interviewed Fidel Castro when
Castro was just another guy with a beard, and Winston Churchill,
and Meyer Lansky. He was in the police station in Dallas when Jack
Ruby shot Lee Harvey Oswald, and was the first reporter to ride an
airplane into the eye of a hurricane.
</P>
<P>
   He outlived his newspaper, The Miami News, which went under in
1988, and for more than two decades worked for The Associated
Press, covering the wacky federal court beat in Miami. When he was
80 years old, he scooped the nation with the news that the
Panamanian ruler Manuel Antonio Noriega had been indicted by the
United States on drug charges. Only four months ago, he did it
again, breaking word of the first federal court ruling in the Elian
Gonzalez case. Last weekend, as he lay connected to an oxygen tank
in his Miami Beach home, he phoned The Associated Press with a
story idea.
</P>
<P>
   Sunday night, his heart stopped.
</P>
<P>
   And only then, his pen.
</P>
<P>
   He was 92.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever story I sent him on, he got it,'' said Howard
Kleinberg, who was Sosin's managing editor at The Miami News. ``He
wouldn't take no for an answer.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the journalist you see in the movies. I'm not sure
we'll ever see that again.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosin was a reporter who made his own news, created his own
legend. Remembering him this week, and gathering for his burial in
Miami Wednesday, his friends told Milt stories over and over. One
of their favorites:
</P>
<P>
   Sosin, who often referred to editors as ``amateurs,'' reacted
with his usual contempt when an editor at The News once ordered the
staff to write shorter, punchier paragraphs.
</P>
<P>
   He sat down at his old typewriter, banged out his answer and
stuck it on the bulletin board.
</P>
<P>
   ``Quit,'' it said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what reporter Milt Sosin did today.''
</P>
<P>
   Sosin was not a handsome man. He was tall and woefully thin, and
had a neck like a turkey's and a long, cadaverous face dominated by
a magnificent nose. He wore ascots and sport coats that looked as
if they had come from Goodwill, and drove a Jaguar. He smoked a
pipe.
</P>
<P>
   ``His sport coats were older than some of the lawyers he wrote
about,'' said Bill Cooke, a freelance photographer who chased the
news in Miami with Sosin for decades. ``He liked pastels.''
</P>
<P>
   He regularly beat his competitors, scooping them even when he
was old. In a time before cellular phones, when reporters raced to
the courthouse pay phones to call in news of a verdict, Sosin
carried a pad of yellow ``out of order'' stickers, which he would
slap onto a phone before going into the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   One day a young reporter, Martin Merzer, now with The Miami
Herald, sat beside Sosin in the courtroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, kid,'' Sosin asked him, ``have you filed yet?''
</P>
<P>
   Merzer told him the phone was out of order.
</P>
<P>
   Sosin reached into his pocket and showed him the pad of
stickers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had this wonderful, evil smile on his face,'' Merzer
remembered.
</P>
<P>
   Sosin often outsmarted editors who tried to change him.
</P>
<P>
   He was once given an assignment by The News that took him away
from Miami's warm winter, and bought an overcoat.
</P>
<P>
   ``He kept turning it in in his expense report, over and over
again, and they kept rejecting it,'' said Will Lester, now an
Associated Press political writer, who once worked with him.
``Finally he stopped. They asked him what happened, why he stopped
filing it. He told them: `It's in there. You find it.'''
</P>
<P>
   Broken into little pieces, in the itemized accounts of meals and
drinks and taxi rides, was Milt Sosin's overcoat.
</P>
<P>
   Kleinberg remembers his first confrontation with Sosin.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me, `You'll find some rum somewhere in this office,
and I'll expect you to keep it there,''' Kleinberg said. ``I told
him that alcohol is not allowed in the newsroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``And he told me: `I go out on fires for this newspaper. I get
wet for this newspaper. And when I come back, I need my shot of
rum. No rum, no fires. Your choice.'''
</P>
<P>
   Kleinberg told his assistant, ``Leave the rum there, for
Sosin.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
