<HEADER>
A0449 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l BC-SHOPPING-DESTINATION2     08-23 0842
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SHOPPING-DESTINATION24-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SHOPPING DESTINATION: Loganville
 &HT;    Friendly old town feels stirrings of growth
 &HT;    By Michelle C. Brooks
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOGANVILLE, Ga. _ Traffic zooms by on Ga. 20, but shoppers seem
oblivious to the busy highway. They are discovering unusual finds
at Braxton's Antique Mall, the Vintage Magnolia and the Cobblestone
Cottage lining this main street.
</P>
<P>
   Welcome to Loganville, a town of 6,500 on the brink of
revitalization.
</P>
<P>
   In 1898, the first train chugged into town on the
Lawrenceville-Loganville railroad line. Business soon flourished.
But in 1932 the railroad became a casualty of the Depression.
Loganville, 30 miles from downtown Atlanta, remained a stable and
quiet town. Now, comeback fever is in the air.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to recent openings of fast-food and grocery store
chains, large retail establishments such as Home Depot are planning
to move into the area. Natives speak proudly of embracing change
and welcoming newcomers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a great community spirit,'' says Betty McCullers,
president of the Loganville Chamber of Commerce. In addition to
applying for Better Hometown funds from the state, the city is
planning to fix sidewalks, increase parking and add streetlights.
</P>
<P>
   During a recent excursion, we shopped along a Main Street lined
with buildings that reflect the town's three centuries. Each of the
handful of shops is different, making it worth a closer look.
</P>
<P>
   Braxton's Antique Mall and Clock World begin the tour. The
nondescript building shared by both stores is deceptive: The
massive store has 20,000 square feet and 75 to 80 vendors in the
antique mall. There are choices galore. We found Wedgwood china
pieces: bud vases ($30 each) and small disheslace in its own right,
Loganville is fast becoming part of metro Atlanta. And when it
comes to shopping, let's just say this town named for an Irish
shoemaker is getting off on the right foot.
</P>
<P>
   If you go
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Getting there: From I-285 east, take Exit 39B, U.S. 78 east.
Continue east, passing through the towns of Stone Mountain, Lilburn
and Snellville until you reach Loganville. From I-85 north, take
the Pleasant Hill Road exit. Turn right onto Pleasant Hill Road and
continue until the turn on your right for Ronald Reagan Parkway.
Follow it to the end and turn right at Ga. 124. Go approximately
one mile on Ga. 124 to the intersection of U.S. 78 and turn left.
Continue on U.S. 78 until you reach Loganville.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Hours: Generally, 10 a.m.-5 p.m. Tuesdays through Fridays.
Hours vary on the weekends. Call ahead if you want to visit a
particular shop.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Parking: Available on the street, behind the stores and in
front of Braxton's Antique Mall and Clock World.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Restrooms: No public restrooms.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Handicapped access: Most stores are accessible, although the
sidewalks can be difficult to traverse in a wheelchair.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Information: Loganville Chamber of Commerce, 770-466-1601
</P>
<P>
   Where to eat
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Journey's End specializes in Southern fare. It is owned by the
people who own The Blue Willow Inn in Social Circle. The rotating
buffet includes staples such as fried green tomatoes, catfish,
green beans, collards and the essential fried chicken and sweet
tea. Located in the Loganville Town Shopping Center off U.S. 78.
Lunch is 11 a.m.-3 p.m. Mondays-Saturdays, $6.95; $3.95 children
4-11. Supper is 4:30-9 p.m. Mondays through Thursdays, $9.95; $3.95
children 4-11. 770-554-1770.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  Walden's Fish House. Get your sea legs at this seafood buffet
on Main Street. With over 45 items, house specialties include
hand-breaded catfish and shrimp, broiled fish fillets, baby back
ribs and sirloin strips. Current specials include all-you-can-eat
Alaskan king crab legs for $21.95. $14 for buffet, $17 for buffet
with oysters and crawfish; $21.95 for buffet with oysters, crawfish
and crab legs. Cash or check only. Open 5-9 p.m. Thursdays; 5-9:30
p.m. Fridays; 4:30-9:30 p.m. Saturdays; 770-466-1836.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  El Ranchero features authentic Mexican food, including
favorites such as chimichangas ($5.95), Enchiladas Supremas ($5.95)
and Carne Asada ($6.50). On U.S. 78 in the Loganville Town Center
shopping center. Open 11 a.m.-11 p.m. Fridays and Saturdays; 11
a.m.-10 p.m. Sundays-Thursdays; 770-466-2420.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond shopping
</P>
<P>
   After a day of shopping and eating, stroll through the lush
flora of Vines Botanical Gardens, a former private estate with 25
acres of gardens. 10 a.m.-5 p.m. Mondays-Sundays. $5; $4 for
seniors and children 5-12. Lunch is served at the manor house 11
a.m.-2 p.m. Tuesdays through Saturdays; brunch is served 11 a.m.-2
p.m Sundays ($18.95, $12.95 children). Arbor House gift shop
features garden gifts and collectibles. Open 11 a.m.-4 p.m.
Tuesdays-Sundays. 3500 Oak Grove Road (look for the large sign
facing U.S. 78). 770-466-7532; www
</P>
<P>
   .vinesbotanicalgardens.com.
</P>
<P>
   Michelle C. Brooks writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
