<HEADLINE>
SENATE HEARING PLANNED ON FIRESTONE RECALL  

</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Senate Commerce Committee is planning to hold
hearings on the Firestone tires that were the subject of a safety
recall, a congressional aide said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The committee, which oversees regulation of interstate commerce
and highway safety, will convene hearings next month to examine the
problems that caused Bridgestone/Firestone Inc. to recall 6.5
million tires, the staff member said.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. John McCain of Arizona, chairman of the committee,
requested the hearings, the aide said.
</P>
<P>
   As the recall continued on Wednesday, two more deaths were
blamed on the faulty tires. Garry Lynn Meek, 56, of Farmersville,
Calif., and his granddaughter, Amy Lynn Meek, were killed on Aug.
16 in Wyoming when the left rear tire tread peeled off causing
their Ford Explorer to skid and roll over. The tire was a Firestone
ATX 75R15, one of the brands that were recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Government data has indicated that virtually all the recent
deaths linked to Firestone tires now being recalled occurred when
sport utility vehicles, most of them Ford Explorers, rolled over
after the tires failed.
</P>
<P>
   The committee will invite a number of officials to testify,
possibly including federal transportation safety officials; Jacques
A. Nassar, the president of the Ford Motor Co.; and representatives
of Firestone, although no invitations have been sent, the aide
said.
</P>
<P>
   About two-thirds of the tires being recalled were put on SUVs
and trucks made Ford over the last decade.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Firestone acknowledged that millions of
tires manufactured since 1991 were prone to separating. The problem
has caused 46 deaths and 80 injuries and has led to 50 lawsuits and
a federal investigation. The company has said it will provide free
replacements.
</P>
</TEXT>
