<SLUG> BC-CANE-MAIN0824-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hurricane Debby loses as it heads for Florida Keys
 &HT;    By Tim O'Meilia
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Stumbling on the mountains of Hispanola,
Hurricane Debby lost its punch as it headed west into the peaks of
eastern Cuba today, which could reduce it to a barely tropical
storm force.
</P>
<P>
   If the projected path holds true Debby will aim for the central
Florida Keys Friday evening or Saturday morning.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could still be in for some nasty weather Friday or
Saturday,'' said National Hurricane Center forecaster Krissy
Williams.
</P>
<P>
   The official forecast is that Debby will have winds of about 45
mph when it reaches the Keys, Williams said.
</P>
<P>
   Debby became disorganized and weakened to maximum 50 mph winds
Wednesday as it rode along the north coast of Hispanola, the island
shared by the Dominican Republic and Haiti. Forecasters expected
the storm to weaken further as it reached the mountains of eastern
Cuba.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the hurricane center's computer models had the storm
moving along the north coast of Cuba but two projected it to move
south of Cuba where it could strengthen in the southern Gulf of
Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency managers in Monroe County ordered vacationers to
evacuate Wednesday, a precaution for the Florida Keys where 80,000
residents depend on a single highway. Public schools will be closed
today and Friday in Monroe as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to take the avenue of least regrets,'' Keys emergency
manager Billy Wagner said.
</P>
<P>
   Emergency workers evacuated dozens of people from riverside
shacks in the Dominican Republic and gusty rain tore roofs off
homes in Haiti as Tropical Storm Debby skirted the island of
Hispaniola. So far the storm has caused only one reported fatality,
a man in Puerto Rico who died on Tuesday when he fell off his roof
while taking down a television antenna before Debby hit.
</P>
<P>
   Road construction crews on South Florida highways will continue
working until a hurricane watch is issued, said Barbara Kelleher,
spokesman for the state Department of Transportation. At that
point, crews will be required to shut down projects and remove any
equipment or materials that could fly around in a storm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our maintenance people are already doing an inventory of all
our supplies, like chain saws and everything we may need,''
Kelleher said. ``We're gassing up any vehicles we would use after
the hurricane so we're ready to do.''
</P>
<P>
   On Florida's Turnpike, tolls will remain in effect until state
emergency managers order an evacuation, said Turnpike spokesman
Michael Washburn. Then, all lanes in construction zones will be
open to aid with any evacuation, Washburn said.
</P>
<P>
   Gasoline and food vendors at Turnpike service plazas brought in
extra supplies Wednesday in case the storm prevents deliveries for
a few days, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
