<SLUG> BC-VERIZON-STRIKE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WALKOUT'S END SAID TO HINGE ON ONE ISSUE 
 
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ An agreement to end a strike by employees of Verizon
Communications in several mid-Atlantic states was held up on
Wednesday by a single issue, people close to the talks said.
</P>
<P>
   After nearly all significant differences between Verizon and the
two unions representing workers were resolved and a most strikers
returned to work earlier this week, negotiators tried to define
what type of work cable splicers and service technicians can do in
Pennsylvania, people close to the talks said.
</P>
<P>
   The issue involves 2,000 to 3,000 of Verizon's 260,000
employees. The union apparently wants to limit the kind and amount
of work cable splicers can perform, while Verizon wants to deploy
cable splicers with greater flexibility, the company said.
</P>
<P>
   Cable splicers generally install and repair telephone cables and
are considered more skilled than service technicians, who connect
and repair telephone service on the outsides of homes and
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what it has come down to,'' said Eric Rabe, a
spokesman for Verizon, which was formed by the merger of Bell
Atlantic and the GTE Corp.
</P>
<P>
   In New York and New England, members of the Communications
Workers of America and the International Brotherhood of Electrical
Workers returned to work on Monday, while their colleagues in
states including New Jersey, Pennsylvania and Virginia remained on
strike.
</P>
<P>
   The unions began their walkout on Aug. 6, and Verizon ceded to
nearly all of the unions' demands in what was considered a pivotal
effort by labor to gain a foothold in a large high-technology
company.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
