<SLUG> BC-BKW-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: A BLAZING COMET AND LADY LIBERTY 
</HEADLINE>
   By HARVEY ARATON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ What had been a routinely sedate news media session
suddenly became a raucous and family-like reunion Wednesday when
Cynthia Cooper bounded out the runway at Madison Square Garden,
like a blazing Houston Comet across the New York City sky.
</P>
<P>
   First the woman they call Coop hugged the veteran Liberty
forward, Sue Wicks, once with feeling, a second time at a brassy
cameraman's request. Then she decided, ``I've got to see Spoon,''
and went looking for Teresa Weatherspoon, bumping into Vickie
Johnson first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, it's going to be a mistake when you retire,'' Johnson
said, pulling Cooper close with both arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least I get a chance to come a last time to Madison,''
Cooper said.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, she and the equally mercurial Weatherspoon began pawing
at one another, just as when they were roommates on national teams
and they would conduct killer pushup contests on hotel room carpets
until even they had exhausted themselves to the brink of sleep.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love her,'' Weatherspoon said, her body language affirming
that this was no case of preening for the purpose of promotion.
</P>
<P>
   What history these women share, and we don't just mean the last
four summers of toiling in David Stern's gender equity annex,
otherwise known as the Women's National Basketball Association.
Cooper's three-time champion Comets are at the Garden Thursday
night to play the Liberty in the league's best-of-three finals for
the third time but telling the story of the WNBA's most dominant
player from 1997 on would be like starting an American history text
at World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Besides her long friendship with Weatherspoon, the braided Miss
Liberty, Cooper played alongside Tari Phillips and against Sue
Wicks in the Italian league that so many American women had to call
home, away from home. And while summer prime time in the big boy
arenas was much too long in coming, those were the days, Wicks
could tell you, that Cynthia Cooper was a sight to behold.
</P>
<P>
   ``She got all the points,'' said Wicks, going all the way back
to the late-1980s. ``It was like Michael Jordan early on _
extraordinary, amazing. When I played against her, I would just
stand in the back of the zone, waiting for her to blow by everyone,
and just try to take a swipe at her. Take 10 swipes, maybe get one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now she's more efficient, good at getting everyone involved,
saving her energy. She's more like Jordan at the end of his
career.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone finishes up sooner or later, but few could understand
why the 5 foot 10 inch dynamo announced on July 4 that she had
decided to retire after this season, while still one of the
league's very best. She spent the ensuing days testily denying her
decision was related to displeasure voiced earlier about losing
shots to Sheryl Swoopes, among others.
</P>
<P>
   The pettiness exists even on teams that win the championship
every season, not just those perennial also-rans with Patrick Ewing
occupying the paint. The Comets, to their credit, managed to move
past or adapt to their internal strife, and returned to the finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever happens in the locker room doesn't matter,''
Weatherspoon argued. ``I've always said, `You don't have to like
me, just play basketball with me.'''
</P>
<P>
   While that sounded like sensible advice in the event the Knicks
can't unload the ever-alienated Ewing, Cooper was sticking with her
own departure script Wednesday, saying it didn't matter if anyone
believed or understood her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've had four years here, the experience that passed over some
others,'' she said. ``It didn't pass over me.''
</P>
<P>
   It is understandable why the American public and press might
believe women's basketball began with Stern's hip marketing, with
``We Got Next.'' But Cynthia Cooper is 37 years old, has played
professionally for as long as Ewing and has logged more
trans-Atlantic miles than Lindbergh could have dreamed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe she feels it's time,'' Weatherspoon said. ``If I had to
tell her, I would tell her it's not. But a lot of people have no
idea what she's already put into it.''
</P>
<P>
   Cooper has made decent money and speaks four languages but along
the way lost a brother to the streets, her mother to cancer and her
teammate and close friend, Kim Perrot, to a brain tumor last
summer.
</P>
<P>
   She knows the difference between substance and show, though game
and life do occasionally mix. A year ago this month, Cooper
dedicated a night to Perrot, and scored 42 points. That's a flair
for the dramatic we expected from another basketball great. If this
really is Cooper's farewell, no one in her extended family will be
shocked if she goes out the way Jordan did, too. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
