<SLUG> BC-MAYTAG-ELECTROLUX-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ELECTROLUX REPORTEDLY TRYING TO ACQUIRE MAYTAG
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Iowa) By DAVID BARBOZA   and ANDREW ROSS SORKIN  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Maytag repairman may be getting a new boss.
</P>
<P>
   The appliance maker based in Newton, Iowa, is negotiating to be
acquired by Electrolux, the Swedish maker of Frigidaire
refrigerators and other household products, for close to $4
billion, according to executives close to the company.
</P>
<P>
   The executives cautioned that a deal, which would create the
world's largest maker of ovens, dishwashers and washing machines,
is not imminent and that several other rivals have recently made
their own informal overtures to Maytag about a possible
combination.
</P>
<P>
   Takeover talks have been fueled by a change in the Maytag
Corp.'s bylaws in May that make it easier to acquire the appliance
maker.
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts say the combination would create a rival to
the Whirlpool Corp., the largest appliance maker in North America,
and General Electric. It is not known whether those companies have
contacted Maytag.
</P>
<P>
   Maytag and Electrolux could be a powerful combination, analysts
contend, because Maytag, which had worldwide sales of $4.3 billion
in 1999, has a powerful U.S. brand that has been strengthened by an
array of innovative, higher-priced products, such as Blodgett
commercial ovens and Neptune washing machines.
</P>
<P>
   Electrolux, which makes everything from farm tractors to ovens,
dishwashers and vacuum cleaners, is a major force in Europe. The
company had global sales of about $14.6 billion in 1999, and could
give Maytag the global reach it needs to sell overseas.
</P>
<P>
   Rumors have been swirling about a possible Electrolux-Maytag
deal for weeks following reports that Electrolux executives toured
Maytag's plants as early as June.
</P>
<P>
   The speculation sent shares of Maytag up $2.88 on Tuesday, to
$38.13, on volume of 1.5 million compared with average daily volume
of 528,141. The stock's volatility and volume simmered down on
Wednesday. Maytag closed at $37.31, down 81 cents. The American
depository receipts of Electrolux fell 44 cents Wednesday, to
$27.50.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Schwartz, a spokesman for Maytag, declined to comment. A
representative for Elecrolux could not be reached.
</P>
<P>
   People close to Maytag say that discussions between Maytag and
Electrolux have been going on for months and may have been held up
over price. Shares of Maytag, which were as high as $74 a share on
July 14, 1999, fell as low as $27 earlier this month because of
concerns that growth at the company had begun to slow.
</P>
<P>
   After several years of spectacular growth, Maytag executives
blamed the profit slowdown on weakness in its lower-priced products
as well as trouble in its Dixie-Narco vending machines division.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to ease concerns, Lloyd D. Ward, the chief executive at
Maytag, announced plans in September to reorganize the company's
operations to cut more than $100 million in costs over the next few
years.
</P>
<P>
   He also said Maytag would move aggressively into electronic
commerce, that it would work to create smart appliances that could
some day be connected to the Internet, and that new strategies were
aimed at selling more products into the international markets.
</P>
<P>
   Part of Maytag's problem, though, was strong competition from
Whirlpool, which has about 35 percent of the North American market,
and GE Appliances, which has about 27 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, analysts say that the success of GE Appliances success
in selling its products over the Internet and shipping the products
faster to market has shaken the industry and put increased pressure
on Whirlpool and Maytag.
</P>
<P>
   That such a deal with Electrolux is in the works has also
created a buzz in Iowa's newspapers, which have been reporting for
weeks about a possible Electrolux deal and the possibility that
Maytag would move its headquarters to Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   People close to Maytag say that any plans to move to Chicago
have been put on hold because of negotiations with Electrolux. They
also say that after heavy trading in Maytag shares last year,
insider trading among top executives has dried up, a hint that
executives are restraining from trading because a merger is in the
works.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
