<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-BASEBALL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CUBA STRONG, U.S. IMPROVED IN OLYMPIC BASEBALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HEATHER GRIPP  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Baseball may be America's pastime, but when it
comes to winning at the sport's international competitions, that's
Cuba's pastime.
</P>
<P>
   The addition of professional players for the 2000 Olympics in
Sydney is not expected to change that.
</P>
<P>
   With the U.S. and Japan leaving their best players home to
finish their respective professional seasons instead of sending
lineups comparable to the Dream Team that the U.S. used to regain
basketball supremacy, Cuba remains the favorite. But the
competition Cuba must overcome to win a third consecutive gold will
be the most balanced yet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cuba's showing up every year with these experienced
veterans,'' USA Baseball executive director Paul Seiler said.
``They're used to playing together and facing international
competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Cuba's still Cuba, but now everybody's showing up with older,
more- experienced players, too. It sort of levels the playing
field.''
</P>
<P>
   USA Baseball fielded its first team of professionals for the
1999 Pan American Games. The team of minor-leaguers finished second
to Cuba after showing its vulnerability with an opening-game loss
to lightly regarded Canada.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously if we were still out there with an amateur team, we
wouldn't have a prayer,'' Seiler said.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. team that former Dodgers manager Tom Lasorda guides in
Sydney may be a step up from previous years, but maybe not much.
Major-league teams had to approve players to participate, meaning
anyone likely to receive a September call-up won't go to Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy with the people I'm surrounded with,'' Lasorda said.
``People who have worked so very, very hard to try to come up with
a team that's going to be very successful over in the Olympics.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S.'s lone Olympic baseball gold came in 1988 when Cuba
boycotted and baseball was a demonstration sport. A 1996 bronze is
the only medal the U.S. has claimed since baseball became an
official Olympic sport in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   This year's eight-team field must overcome a Cuban team that
features essentially the same lineup that defeated the Baltimore
Orioles in a 1999 exhibition.
</P>
<P>
   Japan, which took silver in 1996, is sending a team containing
several professional all-stars.
</P>
<P>
   Korea is shutting down its professional league for a few weeks
to send its best players.
</P>
<P>
   The host Australians are also in the mix with a team led by
former Milwaukee Brewers All-Star catcher David Nilsson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're playing against men who know how to play the game,'' USA
Baseball co-chairman Bob Watson said. ``If we go out there with
talented prospects who don't have much experience, we're not going
to be able to compete. A mixture of youth and experience is key.''
</P>
<P>
   Olympic competition starts Sept.17 with the U.S. facing Japan.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
