<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 21:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0468 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-SC-RESTSTOPS0824-COX     08-23 0927
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SC-RESTSTOPS0824-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    South Carolina seeks help from Georgia to clean up reststops
 &HT;    By Kathy Scruggs
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ In the image game, South Carolina has won its share of
battles against big neighbor Georgia in recent years, boasting the
historic allure of Charleston, the carpet-green golf courses of
Hilton Head and more peaches produced each year than in the entire
Peach State.
</P>
<P>
   But even South Carolina promoters admit the state is losing
badly in an area most visible to tourists: Highway rest stops. Many
South Carolina rest areas are filthy and some of them are
considered dangerous, officials and travelers said. A rash of
robberies that began in February and culminated with a violent
attack on an elderly woman in Sumter County in June has forced
South Carolina officials to look for serious solutions_and they're
looking to Georgia to find them.
</P>
<P>
   Today, a task force formed by South Carolina Attorney General
Charlie Condon is visiting Georgia to tour rest stops, including
Rest Stop No. 63 off the westbound lanes of I- 20 in Columbia
County near Augusta. ``Our goal is to come up with some long-term
solutions,'' said Rick Daniel, spokesman for Condon's office.
``What Georgia is doing is really common sense stuff, such as
cutting back on their hours of operation, beefing up their lighting
and clearing out vegetation.''
</P>
<P>
   Twenty South Carolina counties host rest areas, and officials in
15 of those are participating in the attorney general's task force.
The governor has formed a separate task force. ``They need to do
something,'' said Debbie Hennessey of Atlanta who with her husband,
Bob Hennessey, stopped off last week at the Columbia County rest
area to use the facilities and buy a Coke from the vending machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``The ones in Georgia are always clean,'' she said. ``But we
ended up in one in South Carolina and it was filthy. It looked like
they hadn't picked up the trash in days.
</P>
<P>
   Crime concerns prompted the AAA Carolinas motor club to issue a
travel advisory on June 8 for I-95 rest stops at exits 135 and 141.
</P>
<P>
   David Kelley is a trucker who every week travels from Alabama to
Sumter, S.C., transporting black-meat chicken to Asian-food
markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like rest areas at night,'' Kelley said. ``It's too
isolated, so I tote a Deringer in my hip pocket.''
</P>
<P>
   A South Carolina brick mason is charged with attempted murder
after allegedly kicking open a stall door in the ladies room and
hitting a 63-year-old woman in the head five times and snatching
her purse containing $600 and credit cards. The victim's husband
was able to flag down a trooper after discovering his bloodied
wife, who was treated and released from a Sumter hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Two armed men robbed travelers from New York and Maryland at the
Sumter County rest stops on opposite sides of I-95 in May and are
suspected in February and April holdups.
</P>
<P>
   It was after these incidents that South Carolina officials
dusted off an informal survey distributed nationally in 1997 to
gather information on how other states better protected their
travelers.
</P>
<P>
   Forty-three states responded to the questionnaire inspired by a
rash of nuisance crimes including prostitution at a rest stop near
Charleston. Georgia's safety record impressed them as much as any
other state, Daniel said.
</P>
<P>
   Of the 43 states that responded to the survey, 28 states had
some type of security, from cameras to someone on duty; 13 states
had electronic security including ``panic buttons''; and a couple
of states had mini police precincts. North Carolina has had a
program in place since 1993 in which officers routinely get out of
their cars and walk around the state's 50 to 60 rest stops. Florida
contracted with armed security guards after a British tourist was
shot and killed in 1993 at a rest stop on I-10 in Monticello.
Immediately following that and a series of other tourists slayings
farther south, former Gov. Lawton Chiles deployed 500 auxillary
state troopers to monitor highway rest areas. Virginia was the only
Southern state other than South Carolina to report a violent crime
this summer. A 41-year-old carpenter was slain in July, allegedly
by two escaped Kentucky convicts he befriended at a northern
Virginia rest stop. Reportedly, they were later seen dumping his
body in the woods in Chatham County, Ga. ``Transients go from rest
stop to rest stop,'' said Louis R. Mizell Jr., chairman of Mizell &AMP;
Co. International Security in Bethesda, Md. ``It's the perfect
camouflage because everyone is a stranger.''
</P>
<P>
   Rest stops also offer criminals easy access and quick escape
routes onto the super highways. AAA authorities, Mizell and other
officials said travelers should avoid rest stops entirely in the
middle of the night and plan their stops to coincide with gas
fill-ups and meals in congested areas.
</P>
<P>
   Some states, including Georgia, have attendants on duty until 11
p.m. In Georgia, bathrooms are locked at 11 p.m., which discourages
late-night traffic and reduces potential hiding places for
criminals. Before that action, bathrooms were being used as a
``hot-bed for illicit sex and drug activity,'' said Jilayne Jordan,
spokesman for the Georgia Department of Transportation. ``It gave
(lawbreakers) kind of a club.'' ``Tourism and trucking in Georgia
are two of our biggest industries,'' Jordan said. ``If we can't
present them with something safe and inviting, we're kind of
shooting ourselves in the foot.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-00 2157EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
