<SLUG> BC-BOX-VARGAS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VARGAS COULD FACE CONFLICT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL ROSENTHAL  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Hillary Dozier, the prosecuting attorney in
Fernando Vargas' assault case, doesn't believe a settlement will be
reached before a scheduled Nov. 2 court date in Santa Barbara.
</P>
<P>
   That could complicate Vargas' fight schedule in a big way.
</P>
<P>
   If he gets past Ross Thompson on Saturday in Las Vegas, he's
expected to fight Felix Trinidad in what would be a huge
pay-per-view attraction on Dec. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Obviously, a court date a month earlier would make it impossible
for Vargas to fight no matter the verdict: He needs time to train.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's interesting to me,'' Dozier said.
</P>
<P>
   Vargas could avoid the conflict in one of two ways.
</P>
<P>
   One, the two sides could come to an agreement at a settlement
conference on Sept. 6. Obviously, that's what Vargas is hoping for.
He wants to put this behind him and move on.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll do what we can and hopefully everything will be all
right,'' Vargas said.
</P>
<P>
   However, Dozier said neither side has been willing to bend
enough to reach an agreement and he doesn't believe anything will
change on Sept. 6.
</P>
<P>
   And, two, if no settlement is reached, the trial date could be
moved back a second time.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's already had the date changed once,'' Dozier said. ``I
tend to think it would be difficult to say, 'Hey, let's change it
again.' He could certainly make a request, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he's signed (to fight Trinidad), he might be able to get
another continuance.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-00 2205EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
