<HEADER>
A0475 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT &LR;      08-23 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORLD-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   GERMANY: 3 DENY INTENT TO KILL
</P>
<P>
   Three rightist youths said they did not intend to kill Alberto
Adriano, an African, when they assaulted him in the eastern town of
Dessau in June. Speaking in court, where they have been charged
with murder, the youths admitted attacking Adriano and said they
were drunk at the time. A murder conviction requires proof of an
intention to kill. The case has become the focus of intense
interest as Germany combats a wave of anti-immigrant violence.
</P>
<P>
   AUSTRIA: HAIDER HITS OUT
</P>
<P>
   Joerg Haider, the driving force behind Austria's extreme right
Freedom Party, said the Czech Republic and Slovenia should not be
allowed to join the European Union until they revoke and disavow
decrees that led to the expulsion of ethnic Germans after World War
II. Haider, whose father was a committed Nazi, has often said that
German suffering in the war must also be recognized and suggested
that many who fought in Hitler's army were honorable, if ignorant,
men.
</P>
<P>
   NETHERLANDS: LOCKERBIE CASE DELAYED
</P>
<P>
   The testimony of a key witness in the Lockerbie bombing trial
was delayed until Monday so the defense can ask the CIA for
unedited versions of interviews with him. The man, identified as a
former Libyan spy named Abdul Majid Giaka who lives in the United
States under the witness protection program, is said to be the only
witness who can say one of two defendants checked a bomb-laden
suitcase on a plane in Malta in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   LATVIA: LANGUAGE LAW EASED
</P>
<P>
   Bowing to European critics, Latvia issued slightly more flexible
rules for a law requiring use of the Latvian language in most
activities. Among other changes, the new rules no longer require
lawyers and doctors to speak fluent Latvian, and allow other
languages to be spoken at international events. Russian-speaking
Latvians, more than a quarter of the population, largely oppose the
rules; some Europeans say the law does not meet the
anti-discrimination standards that Latvia must adopt to join the
European Union.
</P>
<P>
   SLOVAKIA: GYPSY MOTHER SLAIN
</P>
<P>
   Just three weeks after a United Nations report highlighted
racism against Gypsies in central and eastern Europe, a Gypsy
mother of eight was bludgeoned to death by three men in the town of
Zilina. Four daughters of Anastazia Balazova, 49, were injured.
Racial hatred and extreme-right groups have been growing in
Slovakia, where Gypsies make up 10 percent of the population, and a
similar situation exists in the Czech Republic, Hungary, Romania
and the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   MIDDLE EAST
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL: SHAS CHIEF'S SENTENCE UPHELD
</P>
<P>
   The Supreme Court denied a request for a new hearing on a
three-year jail term for fraud, bribery and breach of trust imposed
on Aryeh Deri, former leader of the ultra-Orthodox Shas Party. It
ordered Deri to begin his sentence on Sept. 3. Deri, a charismatic
former interior minister of Moroccan descent who built Shas into a
powerful legislative bloc, was convicted of taking bribes at the
interior ministry.
</P>
<P>
   WEST BANK: BIN LADEN LINK DENIED
</P>
<P>
   The leader of the militant Islamic group Hamas denied an
assertion by Israel that a Hamas member who was among 23 Arabs
arrested on terrorism charges had been sent to Pakistan for
terrorist training with the group headed by Osama bin Laden, the
Saudi-born Islamic militant. ``Hamas and I have no connection with
bin Laden,'' Sheik Ahmed Yassin told The Associated Press.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   CANADA
</P>
<P>
   CHURCH CHECKUP
</P>
<P>
   The United Church of Canada, which is being sued by hundreds of
former students of its Indian boarding schools, has decided to
submit all its ministers to mandatory police and sexual abuse
registry checks every three years. An attempt to lower the church's
liability insurance rates, the policy was adopted in the wake of
suits charging that sexual and physical abuse took place at the
church's schools in the 1950s and '60s.
</P>
<P>
   INDIA
</P>
<P>
   GANDHI TO SKIP NEW YORK
</P>
<P>
   The Congress Party president, Sonia Gandhi, leader of the
opposition in Parliament, has decided not to attend a meeting of
legislators in New York this month. Party officials say she has
pressing party business and also wants to be home when her
daughter, Priyanka Vadra, gives birth. Vadra, who dazzled audiences
when she campaigned for her mother last year, is carrying a child
that family loyalists hope will one day inherit the Nehru-Gandhi
political dynasty.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
