<SLUG> BC-FBN-DOLPHINS-MARINO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DAN MARINO WITH A SELLOUT CROWD   AND NO OPPOSITION 
</HEADLINE>
   By CHARLIE NOBLES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ The onetime Jets quarterback Ken O'Brien, among a host
of former players and a sellout gathering of 55,000 fans to pay
homage to the retired Miami Dolphins quarterback Dan Marino
Wednesday night, recalled one play in particular that defined the
man who went on to be the most productive passer in NFL history.
</P>
<P>
   It was 1985 at the Orange Bowl, where the Dolphins once played
their home games, and the Jets had just scored to take a 17-14 lead
with less than a minute left. At the time Marino was a third-year
pro.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody thought we had the game won,'' O'Brien said. ``I'm
on the sideline watching and all off a sudden I see Duper come up
to the line of scrimmage all by himself in bump and run,'' he said,
referring to the wide receiver Mark Duper.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear Marino calling an audible, because he sees what I see.
I start yelling at our defense, `Get back, get back.' I look over
at the coach, `Call a timeout.' But it was too late.''
</P>
<P>
   The long touchdown pass, one of a record 420 Marino threw in 17
NFL seasons, gave the Dolphins one of the 37 fourth-quarter
comebacks they achieved during No. 13's career.
</P>
<P>
   Marino retired after a largely acrimonious 1999 season with
then-Dolphins Coach Jimmy Johnson. Yet his impact on the franchise
was so pervasive that the Dolphins organized Wednesday night's
tribute to give fans a chance to honor him. Never mind the possible
threat of tropical storm Debby or Wednesday night's conclusion of
the highly successful television show ``Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   Pro Player Stadium, reduced to about 55,000 to accommodate a
concert featuring Hootie and the Blowfish and large video screens,
sold out in less than a week.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Marino, the other five quarterbacks comprising the
distinguished class of 1983 _ the Hall of Famer John Elway, Jim
Kelly, Todd Blackledge, Tony Eason and O'Brien _ all were here. So
were the Hall of Fame quarterbacks Joe Namath and Terry Bradshaw,
the Hall of Fame Coach Don Shula and some 50 former Dolphins.
</P>
<P>
   A local radio station encouraged fans to write their personal
thoughts about Marino on a giant card outside the stadium. It was
filled well before sundown, mostly with an outpouring of emotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Thanks for 17 glorious years,'' wrote Greg Gully of New York
City. ``See you in Canton in 2005.'' Canton, Ohio, of course, is
the site of the Football Hall of Fame. Marino, who passed for a
record 61,361 yards, will be eligible for admission in five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember when Danny came in and sort of set the world on
fire as a rookie,'' said Elway, the former Denver Broncos star.
``That set the bar awful high for the rest of us in the class. When
Danny's around now, we don't even talk about stats. We change the
subject.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly, formerly of the Buffalo Bills, noted that Marino was so
explosive and competitive that he represented a fear factor for
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ''You realized that you had to play error-free football to
win,'' Kelly said. ``You never could relax when you were playing
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Shula, the winningest coach in NFL history, said he is proud
that Marino was able to break all of the passing records in 13
seasons under him that it took Fran Tarkenton 18 seasons to set.
</P>
<P>
   ''It looked in his first practice that he was going to be
something special,'' Shula said. ``You could see the great arm and
quick release.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He just felt that no matter what the defense was that he could
somehow fit it in there,'' Shula said. ``He felt there was no
defense for the perfect pass.''
</P>
<P>
   Marino now has eased into some television work, with more free
time than he is accustomed to.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of course I've had second thoughts,'' Marino said about his
decision to retire. ``I've played football for more than 30 years.
It's a tough thing to face, but I believe in my heart that I made
the right decision.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
