<HEADLINE>
CAMPAIGN NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  
(ATTN: Calif., Ala.) (Eds: Mosemarie cq in 2nd item.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   THE DEMOCRATS
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON INCHES FROM LIMELIGHT: President Clinton is working hard
to leave the limelight to Vice President Gore, aides say. He
scrapped plans to travel to Atlanta Wednesday to celebrate the
fourth anniversary of the welfare reform law. It seems the Gore
campaign preferred that he not go, a message that William M. Daley,
the campaign chairman, passed along to John D. Podesta, the
president's chief of staff. Clinton did travel Wednesday to New
Jersey for two low-key political fund-raisers. But he kept the
focus on Gore and his running mate, Sen. Joseph Lieberman of
Connecticut, saying that the most important thing was for the two
``to go out and spread the message, engage in the debate and make
sure the American people know what the choices are before them.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By Marc Lacey
</P>
<P>
   THE INTEREST GROUPS
</P>
<P>
   LEWINSKY JOB OFFER: The job offer generated publicity all right,
but probably not the kind that the nonprofit organization wanted.
American Women Presidents, a new group based in Sacramento, Calif.,
that advocates election of a woman president and vice president,
offered Monica Lewinsky a job on Tuesday as its corporate vice
president. But hours later, the group rescinded the offer after
protests from women's groups and others. In its job offer, faxed to
Lewinsky's lawyer, Plato Cacheris, the group said that it was
disturbed that Lewinsky's career had been sidetracked since her
relationship with President Clinton and hoped that she could use
her name recognition to promote the election of women. But the
group's founder, Mosemarie Boyd, said she later decided against
risking her organization's credibility by offering a job to
Lewinsky and issued a statement apologizing for any inconvenience
and wishing Lewinsky well.
</P>
<P>
   _ By Todd S. Purdum
</P>
<P>
   THE STATES
</P>
<P>
   RUNOFF IN SELMA: For the first time in 36 years, Mayor Joe
Smitherman of Selma, Ala., was forced on Tuesday into a runoff
election, raising the serious possibility that the predominately
black city, infamous in the 1960s for its bitter civil rights
struggles, will be led next by a black mayor. Smitherman, 70, was
first elected mayor in 1964 and has since always managed to win
re-election the first time around, usually with the help of some
black voters. He has long maintained that no other white candidate
will ever be able to match that achievement and therefore he will
be the last white mayor of Selma. He was challenged on Tuesday, for
the third time, by James Perkins, a black businessman who got 43
percent of the vote, compared to Smitherman's 46 percent. Two other
black candidates got the remainder of the vote. Smitherman, who
will face Perkins in a Sept. 12 runoff, said he was disappointed
that he received fewer black votes on Tuesday than in the past.
</P>
<P>
   _ By David Firestone
</P>
<P>
   THE GREEN PARTY
</P>
<P>
   MAKING POWER AN ISSUE: Ralph Nader, the consumer advocate turned
Green Party presidential candidate, has been hammering hard on the
theme that corporations have far too much power. So when he got to
California this week, he saw major political opportunity in the
skyrocketing cost of electricity, which has recently doubled and
even quadrupled in some places following price deregulation by the
state. In San Diego, the first city to feel the effects of free
market prices, he charged that big corporations had dominated the
deregulation process and called on Californians to sieze back
regulatory control of the electricity industry and demand their
money back. The state legislature and Gov. Gray Davis, he said,
should push through a rate rollback law that does not include a
provision to compensate utilities for any money that might cost
them. ``Electricity deregulation really brings about a collision of
interests,'' Nader said. ``It pits the interests of consumers, who
are often unorganized and lack power, against the interests of
suppliers, who are usually very organized, powerful and have a lot
of money behind them.'' George W. Bush and Al Gore, he said, are
beholden to corporate influence.
</P>
<P>
   THE REPUBLICANS
</P>
<P>
   CHENEY IN CALIFORNIA: Dick Cheney also was in California
Wednesday, but the issues he hit hardest had nothing to do with
either corporate or electric power. Rather he emphasized three
themes that have become central to the Bush-Cheney campaign in
recent days _ bolstering education, the military and the nation's
sense of honor and integrity, the latter almost always a
none-too-subtle reference to President Clinton's conduct in the
White House. In Bakersfield, Cheney told a group of high school
students in the Junior Reserved Officers Training Corps that
``nothing is more essential to education than teaching character,''
and he suggested that permitting prayer in public schools would
help accomplish the job. ``We want our children to learn to read
and write, but we also want them to know right from wrong,'' Cheney
said. ``Certainly my time as secretary of defense taught me the
enormous importance, if you will, of character in terms of the
functioning of the U.S. military. No military organization can
survive without honor and integrity.''
</P>
<P>
   _ By Michael Cooper
</P>
<P>
   Compiled by B. Drummond Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
   THURSDAY'S SCHEDULES
</P>
