<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESIDENT CAMPAIGNS FOR NEW JERSEY   DEMOCRATS 
BY DAVID M. HALBFINGER  
</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOPEWELL, N.J. _ President Clinton flew through the New Jersey
suburbs on Wednesday, shuttling from a horse farm here to a horse
track in Cherry Hill _ with a stop in Princeton that paralyzed the
borough's streets at rush hour _ all to help a pair of Democrats
facing uphill contests for the House of Representatives in two
closely watched races.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton is eager for Democrats to retake control of Congress,
and he spent much of the day with Rep. Rush Holt, widely seen as
one of the most vulnerable Democrats in the House, before attending
a fund-raiser in Cherry Hill for Susan Bass Levin, that town's
mayor, who is challenging Rep. James H. Saxton, a 16-year
incumbent.
</P>
<P>
   At a reception for Holt on Wednesday night, Clinton said the
freshman congressman, a plasma physicist, was uniquely prepared to
deal with issues of genetics, computer science and other emerging
technologies. ``Even Republicans who may not agree with every vote
he cast ought to think long and hard before they replace him,''
Clinton said. ``You need someone who really understands all these
big, future issues.''
</P>
<P>
   Holt, who represents the wealthy, fast-growing 12th
Congressional District in New Jersey's midsection, is in an unusual
matchup: his opponent is Richard Zimmer, who held the seat for
three terms until he gave it up to run for the Senate in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer lost the Senate race to Robert Torricelli, but their
acrimonious contest gave Zimmer a statewide profile, and he remains
more familiar to residents in the district than Holt. According to
one survey by the Holt campaign, nearly 70 percent of voters did
not know who represented them, and a sizable number thought Zimmer
still did.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmer now leads Holt by 6 to 12 percentage points, depending on
which candidate's internal polls are to be believed. Holt said he
believed the gap was no reflection on his record.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I won in 1998, the other party just couldn't believe it,
and they still can't accept it,'' he said. ``They are determined
that this seat belonged to them, and that they are going to take it
back.''
</P>
<P>
   But Holt said his constituents had a rare opportunity to compare
his record with Zimmer's. He pointed to accomplishments such as
securing $40 million in federal money for open-space preservation
efforts, pushing to ban large trucks from two-lane roads, and
lobbying for money to build schools and hire new teachers. ``I
think I'm a good fit for this district,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton appeared with Holt at a jazz and Champagne reception for
about 350 people in Hopewell, where Holt was introduced by Jon S.
Corzine, the Democratic nominee for Senate.
</P>
<P>
   The reception was held on a 75-acre horse farm owned by Robert
Stockman, a venture capitalist, and his wife, Lisa, who is involved
in the Delaware and Raritan Canal Greenway, a land-preservation and
water-quality advocacy group.
</P>
<P>
   Holt's finance director, Neil Upmeyer, said the event would
produce more than $250,000 for the campaign, in addition to $1.8
million raised previously.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Holt is seen by both parties as one of the two most
endangered Democratic incumbents in November, along with Michael
Forbes of Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   Levin's campaign against Saxton in the Third Congressional
District, meanwhile, is still seen as something of a long shot,
even by New Jersey Democratic officials.
</P>
<P>
   Saxton has never faced a challenger with more than $1 million to
spend, and Levin, a prominent fund-raiser for New Jersey Democrats,
had raised more than $1.2 million for herself before Wednesday's
event. The reception at the Garden State Park racetrack _ a reprise
of a campaign stop Clinton made before his own election in 1992 _
was expected to draw 500 people and produce $200,000 for Levin,
said Sallie Stohler, her campaign manager.
</P>
<P>
   Another measure of Levin's strength as a candidate came in June,
when the New Jersey AFL-CIO endorsed her after some debate, despite
its predilection for backing incumbents.
</P>
<P>
   But David P. White, Saxton's campaign manager, said Saxton had
received more in campaign contributions from union members than
Levin had. And Saxton has also received the endorsements of the
Sierra Club and the League of Conservation Voters, which give him
high marks for his record on water-quality issues. Moreover,
Levin's campaign was shaken by a wholesale staff turnover a few
weeks ago, in which her hard-driving personality was said to have
played a part.
</P>
<P>
   ``Levin's an incredible fund-raiser, and she's certainly proved
her mettle, but Saxton's not inherently vulnerable,'' said Amy
Walter, who analyzes House races for the Cook Political Report.
``He's been there a long time, and he hasn't done anything wrong.
Incumbents have to help you. The district's trending Democratic,
and if it were an open seat it'd be very competitive, but
incumbents who lose to insurgent candidates are usually incumbents
who don't take them seriously. And he's taking this one very
seriously.''
</P>
</TEXT>
