<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 22:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0492 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-VICK0824-COX     08-23 1114
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-VICK0824-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Accolades rain on superb Hokies quarterback
 &HT;    By Jack Wilkinson
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   BLACKSBURG, Va. _ For nearly a half-hour, the conversation
zigzagged like a Michael Vick scramble, covering a range of topics:
</P>
<P>
   The Heisman Trophy. Vick's beloved pit bull, Champagne, who is
in heat and about to breed. FSU and the Sugar Bowl. Fishing.
Turning pro. Throwing left-handed and doing everything else as a
righty. His personal Web site. Improvising afield. The art of the
self-interview.
</P>
<P>
   And, of course, the lure of the nightlife in this college town.
Specifically, the perils of late-night shopping at the 24-hour
Wal-Mart, where autograph hounds sniff out Vick at any time of the
day or night. He can't go anywhere, not even the snack-food aisle
near midnight, without drawing a crowd.
</P>
<P>
   Now, the allotted 25 interview minutes up, Vick stood, shook
hands and left the tiny office in the Virginia Tech sports
information department. But not before glancing once more at the
computer screen on the desk. As the Heisman front-runner, the kid
who might redefine the quarterback position, walked out the door, a
visitor sneaked a peek at the screen saver that had periodically
distracted Vick.
</P>
<P>
   It was the cover of ESPN The Magazine's college football
preview, with cover boy Vick in full uniform, holding his helmet
and a football and standing beside the headline, ``Human
Highlight.''
</P>
<P>
   Perfect. As breathtaking and captivating a player as Vick is,
one whose talent and possibilities demand everyone's full attention
on every play, sometimes Michael Vick can't take his eyes off
Michael Vick.
</P>
<P>
   Let the hyperbole begin:
</P>
<P>
   The best thing to come out of Virginia since baked ham. ... A
new kind of quarterback, the next step in football's evolutionary
ladder. ... The most precocious dazzler to stroll a college campus
since Brooke Shields graced Princeton. ... I've never seen anyone
like him.''
</P>
<P>
   That's just a sampling of the gushing going on everywhere. That
last gush came from John Madden, who has seen _ and telestrated _ a
QB or two. ''Michael Vick is probably the best quarterback in
America,'' Syracuse coach Paul Pasqualoni said. ''There's not a
team at any level that's got an answer to him.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly not Pasqualoni's Orangemen last October, when Vick,
then a freshman, led Virginia Tech to its most resounding victory
in 77 years, a 62-0 humiliation of Syracuse. Sunday night, it's
George O'Leary and Georgia Tech's turn. The Jackets open the 2000
season here against the Hokies.
</P>
<P>
   ''I think they have, I don't know what the word is, a magical
quarterback there,'' O'Leary said. In Vick, they have one singular
sensation who merely led Virginia Tech to an 11-0 regular season.
It was the first in school history, prompting the production of
''Hokie Toasties'' cereal that can still be found on grocery
shelves throughout town. The kid nearly led the Hokies to the
national championship, rallying them from a 28-7 deficit against
mighty Florida State in the Sugar Bowl to a 29-28 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind that FSU won the game, 46-29, and its second national
title. The next day, Hokies coach Frank Beamer was in Houston and
giving a radio interview before accepting yet another
coach-of-the-year award.
</P>
<P>
   ''The guy said, 'You know, Florida State won the national
championship last night, and all my callers want to talk about is
Michael Vick,''' said Beamer, who understood the fascination.
''I've said, 'I can't wait to see the next great play.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Beamer saw so many last season, when Vick passed for 1,840
yards, ran for 585 more, accounted for 20 touchdowns and displayed
a combination of speed, cunning, cut-back ability, arm strength and
improvisation rarely, if ever, seen in a quarterback. Any
quarterback, on any level. Despite the loss to FSU, Vick's vapor
runs and his passing enabled the Hokies to finish No. 2 in the
final rankings, their highest finish.
</P>
<P>
   Vick was third in the Heisman Trophy voting behind Wisconsin's
Ron Dayne and Georgia Tech's All-American quarterback, Joe
Hamilton. Vick tied Georgia's Herschel Walker and the late Clint
Castleberry of Georgia Tech for the highest Heisman finish by a
freshman. Vick now is the preseason favorite to become the first
sophomore to win the Heisman. No one here would be surprised if he
did; nor would they begrudge him turning pro after this season,
which Vick probably will do if he wins the Heisman.
</P>
<P>
   ''I'm not really worried about that right now,'' Vick said. ''I
plan on being here for the next three years. Just leave it at
that.''
</P>
<P>
   No one believes that. Not from a kid who is 6-foot-1, 214
pounds, can throw the ball 70 yards and, in the spring, lowered his
40-yard time from 4.33 seconds to 4.25. The kid who shredded FSU's
top-rated defense for 323 yards total offense, including 225 yards
passing and 145 rushing despite losing a combined 48 yards on eight
sacks. It's been like that since high school in Newport News, where
Vick fell under the guidance of coach Tommy Reamon at Warwick High.
Reamon not only worked relentlessly with Vick from the 9th grade on
but encouraged him to work on his communication skills. So Vick
sometimes stood in front of a mirror and interviewed himself.
</P>
<P>
   ''I was just the reporter, and me,'' Vick said. ''I know it
sounds weird, but it wasn't long. I wasn't just practicing on my
speaking but in case I got into that situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Vick was interviewed constantly last year, from the moment he
flipped head-over-heels in the opener against James Madison for one
of his three first-quarter touchdowns in his 47-0 coming-out party.
Recalling when Vick and Blacksburg flipped for each other,
linebacker Nick Sorensen said, ''You were shocked, and then you
were ticked off. Like, 'Geez, that's unbelievable! But what are you
doing, you idiot?!' ``
</P>
<P>
   Vick kept doing stuff like that all season long. Fans held up,
''VICK 3:16'' signs. Vick became good buddies with Hamilton,
meeting the Jackets' quarterback at the Heisman weekend in New
York, then hanging out with him in Las Vegas, where Vick won an
ESPY as the nation's top college player.
</P>
<P>
   Now Vick begins his second season, after spending the summer
here working out when not making late-night trips to the Wal-Mart.
He was besieged for 60 autographs one night last week while
shopping for some furnishings for his off-campus apartment. ''He
can't go anywhere campus, town, everywhere without someone asking
him for his autograph,'' said cornerback Ronyell Whitaker. ''Even
if they don't ask, you hear whispers: 'That's Michael Vick.' ``
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
