<SLUG> BC-BKC-BRUNNER0824-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Brunner denied admission
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATHENS, Ga. _ Kenny Brunner's controversial past _ not his
academic transcripts _ probably prevented him from attending the
University of Georgia this fall.
</P>
<P>
   UGA president Michael Adams announced Wednesday that he would
not admit Brunner for the fall semester. Adams said the school
would consider the former Georgetown point guard's application for
spring semester, but only if the school received his official
academic transcripts and if the player met with a three-member
faculty committee.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not want to make a decision on an applicant without the
benefit of a complete academic record and transcript,'' Adams said
in a statement. ``Also, I do not want to decide on something as
important as a student's future on what may or may not have been
reported in the media.''
</P>
<P>
   Georgia basketball coach Jim Harrick said the school received
the rest of Brunner's transcripts late Tuesday. The transcripts
were faxed to Georgia from Compton College in California and a
school in Colorado, where Brunner took a mail-correspondence
course. But Georgia's admissions office can consider only official
transcripts.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia's late-enrollment period ended Tuesday. Brunner would
have needed permission from professors to enroll in classes this
fall.
</P>
<P>
   ``The transcripts are here, but they're not official,'' Harrick
said. ``They wanted official transcripts, which would take a day or
so. We got everything, but it was a little late.''
</P>
<P>
   If Brunner is accepted for spring semester, he could still play
for Harrick this season. Georgia's fall semester ends on Dec. 15.
Under NCAA rules, Brunner would be eligible to play the following
day. The Bulldogs' SEC schedule doesn't begin until Jan. 6.
</P>
<P>
   Harrick said Brunner was going to take a few days to consider
his options. He could try to enroll at a school that begins fall
classes at a later date, or he could remain in Athens and try to
enroll in Georgia in January.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's going to be his choice, as far as what he wants to
do,'' Harrick said. ``I'm going to give him a few days to consider
his options. I'm disappointed for the young man. We made a
commitment to him, his family, his coaches, everybody. He took the
decision very hard. It was a big blow for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Brunner and his uncle arrived in Athens on Friday after driving
from California. Harrick said he did not start recruiting Brunner
until he received permission from Adams and Georgia athletics
director Vince Dooley.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got permission to do everything, but I guess we just didn't
get it done in time,'' Harrick said.
</P>
<P>
   When media outlets reported last week that Brunner intended to
transfer to Georgia, the university inititated a background check
on him. Steve Shewmaker, the school's director of legal affairs,
started the inquiry on Aug. 17. The Bulldogs have been recruiting
Brunner in the spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``After talking to all of those people, virtually everything I
heard was positive,'' said Shewmaker, who served as a judge in
Kentucky for 16 years. ``I heard nothing alarming.''
</P>
<P>
   Brunner spent four months in 1998 in the Los Angeles City Jail
on attempted-murder and robbery charges that later were dropped. He
also was involved in an incident at Fresno State in which he
allegedly assaulted an acquaintance with a samurai sword. Those
charges also were dismissed.
</P>
<P>
   Adams' decision not to admit Brunner came only two days after
Georgia basketball recruit John Toombs was arrested in Athens on
misdemeanor charges of underage possession of alcohol and
disorderly conduct. Toombs, from Carver High School in Columbus,
could have enrolled at UGA as a partial qualifier, but he was
denied admission after his arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Harrick acknowledged that Toombs' arrest ``probably didn't
help'' Brunner's bid to enroll.
</P>
<P>
   Brunner was expected to start at point guard for the Bulldogs,
who struggled in Harrick's first season as coach. Without Brunner,
Harrick said freshman Rashad Wright of Statesboro probably would
start at point guard. Junior D.A. Layne and sophomore Ezra Williams
would start on the wings, with seniors Anthony Evans and Shon
Coleman in the frontcourt.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rashad Wright isn't a bad player,'' Harrick said. ``But you're
talking about Rashad playing in the SEC. The SEC isn't for boys;
it's for men.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
