<HEADER>
A0495 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-SURVIVOR-REVIEW-NY     08-23 0891
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURVIVOR-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOG-EAT-DOG REALITY, BUT MUST-SEE TV
</HEADLINE>
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Here is the standard line about the success of
``Survivor'': It is a reality game show featuring 16 ordinary
people on an island, plus one scheming villain to hiss at, as the
group votes one member off each week. But that conventional wisdom
is entirely backward.
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor'' is as remote from reality as its setting, Pulau
Tiga (likely translation: Island of the Product Placements) and as
meticulously structured as a novel by Agatha Christie (whose ``Ten
Little Indians'' plot it brilliantly mimics). And though its
characters may be genuine to their family and friends, to the
average viewer they are as real as Brad Pitt.
</P>
<P>
   The who-won hype surrounding Wednesday night's two-hour finale
(padded with flashbacks), obscures the reason the show has touched
a chord during its 13-week run on CBS. The fact that Richard Hatch
survived to win a million dollars is less revealing than how he
maneuvered into that position.
</P>
<P>
   ``How do you stay true to yourself and maintain integrity and
still play this game?'' asked Kelly Wiglesworth, who lost out to
Hatch, in an aside to the camera in the final weeks. She answered
her own question: ``You can't.''
</P>
<P>
   Last summer's television phenomenon, ``Who Wants to Be a
Millionaire,'' is the feel-good game show that says we're a happy
country pulling together. This summer ``Survivor'' sends a
countermessage: Trust no one. The people on the island endured by
voting together but in the end were forced to turn against one
another. The island was a microcosm of dog-eat-dog reality, staged
at a safe distance. Just as murder mysteries transform our fear of
death into a playful entertainment, ``Survivor'' turns the
competitive nightmare of contemporary life (in business, in love,
in friendship) into a benign television game.
</P>
<P>
   That visceral pull wouldn't have materialized if the show didn't
work as pure entertainment. Even the best orchestrated hype (which
CBS had) isn't enough to account for the endless chattering among
viewers. ``Survivor'' drew a gigantic audience with a combination
of sports challenges and the suspense of who gets kicked off the
island: Agatha Christie goes to the Olympics. (The island itself
was as realistic and as hokey as a haunted house.)
</P>
<P>
   And each episode was edited into a swift hour. ``Survivor''
never spent more than a few seconds watching someone eat rice.
``Elapsed time: 4 hours 11 minutes'' flashed on the screen after
the minutes spent in Wednesday night's contest about who could
stand the longest with a hand on a totem pole. Take away ruthless
editing, and you end up watching people feed the chickens, as they
have on CBS's tiresome ``Big Brother.''
</P>
<P>
   That totem pole contest, an ``immunity challenge,'' was part of
this game's most wickedly unpredictable feature. In each episode
one person won a contest and could not be voted out in that round;
so-called immunity was the wild card that made every rational
prediction moot. Kelly would have been gone weeks ago, but she won
four immunity challenges in a row to become one of the final two
survivors.
</P>
<P>
   But only part of the series' constantly growing ratings came
from the suspense. The show got progressively more gripping as it
became progressively more psychological. What started out as a
sporting challenge (build a hut, eat a rat) turned into a
tantalizing mind game.
</P>
<P>
   The truest voyeurism, after all, is looking into someone else's
thoughts, and that is what truly drove ``Survivor.'' The most
compelling moments were those in which the contestants spoke
directly to the camera, confidentially to us, letting us into the
secrets of their sometimes backbiting strategies.
</P>
<P>
   In one episode Colleen sits in a tree, looks sweetly into the
camera and says she'll vote Richard off the island because he's too
bossy. (What an innocent.) In a later episode Richard, the supposed
villain, looks into the camera and says coolly, ominously of
Gretchen, ``She has to go because she is bright and is strong, and
she is a threat.'' Gretchen is gone that night. The message about
who wins in life is unmistakable.
</P>
<P>
   The show's producers selected these contestants shrewdly, to
cover the social spectrum, from Sean, a neurologist, to Susan, a
truck driver so tough her husband boasted in an interview, ``She's
a man in a woman's body.'' It was a dazzling stroke to bring the
contestants videos from home a few weeks ago. Viewers saw Gervase's
little daughter toddling toward the camera and watched Jenna, the
mother of small twin girls, cry when she heard her video had not
arrived. Those humanizing moments were the equivalent of
up-close-and-personal profiles of sports stars.
</P>
<P>
   We do not actually know these people any better than we know the
latest celebrity interviewed on ``Entertainment Tonight,'' of
course. The irony is that the success of ``Survivor'' has made
these real people less real to us, as they have taken on the
flattened images of celebrities. (And their post-``Survivor''
show-business plans are just starting.) Richard has already
achieved a measure of fame. Say ``the naked fat guy,'' and everyone
knows who you mean. And admit it: you secretly like him. That may
be the biggest, most revealing ``Survivor'' secret of all.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
