<HEADER>
A0497 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-FBC-FSU0824-COX     08-23 0703
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-FSU0824-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Playing on and off the field
 &HT;    By Tom D'Angelo
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   TALLAHASSEE, Fla. _ Kevin Emanuel and Chris Woods, Florida
State's young interior linemen, recently found they share more in
common than the pressure of replacing the strength of last season's
defense.
</P>
<P>
   Emanuel, a 6-foot-4, 258-pound freshman, and Woods, a 6-3,
276-pound sophomore, could team up off the field, too, if football
does not work out. Both are musicians, something they haven't
advertised since arriving at Florida State.
</P>
<P>
   Emanuel is more skilled, having spent eight years playing the
piano and organ at his father's church in Garland, Texas. But when
you play such a violent sport, some find it hard to picture you
making sweet music.
</P>
<P>
   ``The kids teased me in high school,'' Emanuel said. ``They
would say, 'Man, I can't imagine you playing the piano. Mostly
girls play the piano.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Woods sang in the Orlando Boys Choir, was a master singer in
concert choir at Jones High School and plays the xylophone. But he
has one desire that Emanuel could help him with.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never told Kevin but I really want to learn how to play
the piano,'' Woods said.
</P>
<P>
   Florida State coaches are worried about Emanuel and Woods
learning how to play the defensive line, where Corey Simon and
Jerry Johnson dominated the last two years.
</P>
<P>
   Simon and Johnson anchored the Seminoles' defense, standing up
blockers enough to allow the starting linebackers to record 302
tackles last season, and breaking through those blockers for 30
combined tackles for loss. Simon was the sixth overall pick in the
draft, Johnson was taken in the fourth round.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have something to prove to the world,'' Woods said. ``Corey
and Jerry are gone and everyone is expecting the defensive line,
the interior, to be the weak link.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods, a backup last season with 27 tackles, replaced Simon at
nose guard. Emanuel won the tackle position with a strong spring.
He then increased his weight by 11 pounds, his bench press by 25
(to 435) and ran the 1.5 mile drill in 9:55. Both will debut as
starters in Saturday's Pigskin Classic in Jacksonville against
Brigham Young.
</P>
<P>
   Defensive line coach Odell Haggins hopes the strength comes in
numbers this season. Haggins says of the line, ``this is the most
depth, quantity-wise, I've had.'' But he added about the talent.
``Quality-wise, if they keep improving, it could be decent.''
</P>
<P>
   If not, Emanuel's and Woods' greatest hits could be off the
field. Gloria Emanuel says her son is ``gifted'' when it comes to
music. ``The toys that were intriguing to him was anything musical.
When he first started crawling his goal was to get on the stool
where he could play the piano,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Emanuel boosted himself on that stood and naturally started
playing when he was 2. He played in the orchestra in elementary
school and the cello in middle school. At the age of 9, he began
playing the organ and piano at the St. Luke AME Church where his
father, Rev. Lawrence Emanuel, is the pastor.
</P>
<P>
   But after entering high school, Emanuel, not surprisingly,
drifted toward football. Emanuel's cousin, Bert, is a Dolphins wide
receiver. He was the fifth rated defensive line prospect in the
country.
</P>
<P>
   ``I kind of regretted that,'' Gloria said from the Emanuel's
home in Waco, Texas. ``It was a conflict, but he said, 'I think I
can get a scholarship for my athletics.' When you look at the
music, there is quite a correlation to athletics. ... self
discipline, perseverance, creativity.''
</P>
<P>
   Emanuel, like Woods, has put aside his music to concentrate on
school and athletics. But both would like to retool their musical
skills, either while at school or after they graduate.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I go back home I help out my dad,'' Emanuel said. ``My
mom brought me up by telling me it's good to be able to do more
than one thing. I'll always be there for the church.''
</P>
<P>
   Woods is trying to convince Emanuel to play at his church in
Tallahassee.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've talked about it when he started going,'' Woods said. ``I
always tell him I'm going to tell the pastor he plays the piano.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
