<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 22:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0498 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e BC-TV-SURVIVOR-IMPACT-2T     08-23 0851
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-SURVIVOR-IMPACT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: R.I.)  
 `SURVIVOR' EXCEEDED EVERY EXPECTATION CBS HAD _ AND THEN SOME 
</HEADLINE>
   By BILL CARTER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With parties being thrown to celebrate it, news organizations
scheduling special coverage and viewers all over the nation waiting
in near breathless anticipation, a summer television series ended
Wednesday night accompanied by the kind of attention usually
reserved for massive national events, on the scale of the Super
Bowl or the Academy Awards.
</P>
<P>
   And all of it to learn that one contestant, Richard Hatch, 39, a
corporate trainer from Newport, R.I., had managed to win $1 million
dollars by enduring a made-for-television survival test on a island
off the coast of Borneo.
</P>
<P>
   ``Survivor,'' the CBS hit that built over a 13-week run to what
was expected to be the biggest single television audience ever
assembled for a summer television series, far eclipsed every
expectation the network had when it acquired the rights to the show
last year. Leslie Moonves, the president of CBS Television and the
man who decided to put the show on the air, said, ``It has beaten
our expectations by about double.''
</P>
<P>
   One indication of how big the show has been: Even before
Wednesday night's hugely anticipated finale, ``Survivor'' had
already surpassed the ratings for other television events this year
like the World Series, the NBA finals, the NCAA men's basketball
finals and the Grammy Awards.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike those events, for which networks pay huge fees _ in
the case of sports usually hundreds of millions of dollars a year _
``Survivor'' was acquired for what amounted to a bargain basement
price. CBS executives did not disclose the cost, but when ABC was
in the running to buy the show, it was priced at $700,000 an
episode.
</P>
<P>
   For such a modest sum CBS acquired a show that has generated
national discussions in homes and offices, endless reports on
television news programs (many on CBS but even more on its
competitors), cover articles in national magazines like Time and
Newsweek and front-page reports in dozens of newspapers.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time ``Survivor'' all but transformed CBS, long
considered the stodgiest network, into, of all things, a haven for
young-adult viewers. CBS, which was able to charge advertisers up
to $600,000 for every commercial in Wednesday's finale, is expected
to capitalize financially even more spectacularly in January, when
a second edition of ``Survivor'' starts immediately following the
Super Bowl, which will also be broadcast by CBS.
</P>
<P>
   But perhaps more significant, ``Survivor'' has demonstrated to
network executives that they can still be in the business of
reaching a truly mass audience. As they have faced increasingly
dire predictions that the coming onslaught of technological
advances in computers and new recording devices would put them out
of the business, network executives have in recent years pointed
more and more toward what they call ``event programming'' as their
island of survival.
</P>
<P>
   None of them even imagined that perhaps the best example of
event programming any of them could find would come from a show
about surviving on an island.
</P>
<P>
   Moonves pointed out that many of network television's
highest-rated shows are now events of a sort. From the departure of
cast members like George Clooney from ``E.R.'' to the season
finales of shows like ``Friends,'' networks have found themselves
more and more compelled to turn weekly shows into events that
viewers believe they cannot miss.
</P>
<P>
   ``But this event evolved naturally,'' Moonves said. ``That's
made it even more effective.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he believed the show managed to emerge as a national
phenomenon, Mark Burnett, the executive producer of ``Survivor,''
pointed to how well it worked as ``unscripted drama.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I always believed it was going to generate strong water cooler
conversation. Nobody could have predicted the ratings success. But
I knew that the premise _ a group of people marooned on an island,
where they had to survive by working together, and they had to work
against each other to win a million-dollar prize _ I knew that
premise was superior.''
</P>
<P>
   The premise had been put together over several years by a
British production company that had never even sold the idea to
television in Britain. Moonves said Burnett, who acquired the U.S.
rights from the British company, produced the show so skillfully
and cast it so well that it came together perfectly.
</P>
<P>
   ``It worked because it's an adventure, it's a game show, and
it's a great soap opera,'' Moonves said. ``And it may even have hit
home with people because the good guys did not necessarily win.''
</P>
<P>
   The four remaining contestants in last night's finale had
schemed together to eliminate the other contestants. ``The bad guys
are often the most compelling characters,'' Moonves said. ``And
people at home may have seen that and recognized what happens in
their own lives, in corporate society or whatever. They have been
thinking: `That's why I haven't succeeded. The bad guys are to
blame.'''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Crucial to the show's success, of course, has been the buildup
of suspense every week about which contestant would be eliminated.
But the suspense was almost entirely manufactured because the event
itself was long over even before the show went on the air in June.
It was taped in March.
</P>
<P>
   Still, despite all the avid interest, with journalists asking
questions and viewers bombarding the Internet with rumors, CBS
managed to keep the big secret about who eventually survived the
test until it was revealed Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Partly CBS used a bit of scheming of its own to accomplish that
feat. The network deliberately allowed false clues about the winner
to circulate, most of which were exposed as wrong when suggested
winners were eliminated one by one. That left viewers so confused
they were unwilling to believe any supposed revelation of the true
winner.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were sometimes active in the game of deception and sometime
passive,'' Burnett said. ``Sometimes the chips fell our way, and
sometimes we made them fall our way''
</P>
<P>
   None of the participants ever broke the honor code. All of them
_ as well as the show's crew members _ had signed contracts
threatening them with financial penalties if they leaked who had
won. But Burnett said he came to an understanding with the cast
members that he would not turn them into the cast of ``The Jerry
Springer Show.''
</P>
<P>
   He said: ``We had a meeting before the shooting started, just me
and them, and I said: `We're treating you with respect. I promise
you I won't put anything unnecessary on TV to cause harm to your
regular life.' I've kept my word completely. There are a number of
things which did actually occur or were said, or things revealed,
which were never on TV because it was unnecessary or would have
been sensationalism. By keeping my word I earned them keeping their
word.''
</P>
<P>
   Burnett said he had expected the formation of a voting alliance.
``It just seemed to be a very normal group-dynamic reaction. It
happens every day on your job and my job.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the role played by Richard Hatch, as leader of the
alliance who spurred his little group to knock off his main
competitors one by one, Burnett said: ``You can't predict that.
There's no way to cast a person knowing he would do that. But
demographically Richard fit because he was on the wealthy side, he
was highly educated, his job was corporate conflict management,
plus he was a gay single parent. All very interesting. Why he
reacted the way he reacted? Who knows?''
</P>
<P>
   Burnett is already hard at work planning ``Survivor II,'' which
will be set in the Australian outback. He is currently sorting
through more than 49,000 applicants for that cast.
</P>
<P>
   Will it be tainted by the new contestants' knowing how the first
one was won? Burnett doesn't think so. ``I think it may be even
more intriguing because it won't be a strong group playing an
alliance game versus an unwitting group.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that after one edition he was not yet ready to draw
``meaningful conclusions'' about how ``Survivor'' worked as a
social experiment. ``It is a social experiment, no doubt about
it,'' he said. ``But in order to make meaningful conclusions it's
going to take maybe three sessions.''
</P>
</TEXT>
