<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-ALCOHOL-BAN-495&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NYC BACKS OFF PLAN TO BAN ALCOHOL AT FESTIVALS 
</HEADLINE>
   By SHAILA K. DEWAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Less than two weeks after the administration of Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani announced a ban on alcohol sales along parade
routes, city officials have backed off a police proposal to end
such sales at street festivals. Instead, Wednesday they notified
the Feast of San Gennaro, the 11-day festival held in September in
lower Manhattan's Little Italy, that alcohol sales would be
permitted but that the number of vendors would be cut in half.
</P>
<P>
   The city had considered a ban on alcohol sales at all outdoor
events after the sexual assaults following the National Puerto
Rican Day Parade on June 11. The ban on such sales at large parades
came on Aug. 7, part of safety rules adopted in response to three
deaths at last year's West Indian American Carnival Parade in
Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   But Rosemarie O'Keefe, the commissioner of the Mayor's Community
Assistance Unit, which issues festival permits, said the city
agreed to the compromise for all street fairs after discussions
with the producers of San Gennaro, a festival now entering its 74th
year, which starts Sept. 14.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to cutting the number of alcohol vending permits to
half the number issued last year, O'Keefe said, the new policy
requires festivals to stop selling alcohol one to two hours before
their nightly closing time, limits sales to two drinks per person,
and restricts drink sizes to 12 ounces for beer and 4 ounces for
wine. In the past, there were no restrictions on the number of
permits, or the number and size of drinks. Alcohol booths shut down
at the same time as other vendors.
</P>
<P>
   The new policy came under immediate attack Wednesday, both from
organizers of parades, who complained of a double standard, and
from San Gennaro organizers, who were unhappy with the restrictions
on their permits.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks like one set of rules go for one group, and another
for the others,'' said Jean Alexander, the marketing director for
the West Indian American Carnival Parade. She said the carnival
will lose money because beer and liquor companies have withdrawn
their sponsorships.
</P>
<P>
   ``You don't have to have alcohol to have a carnival,'' Alexander
said. ``I could dance and play a flute all day long and never take
a drink.'' But she said the policy had larger implications for
tourism and the carnival parade's finances.
</P>
<P>
   Beer and liquor companies have withdrawn their sponsorships, she
said, and social clubs that participate are having difficulty
getting alcohol permits for fund-raisers for the elaborate costumes
that draw two million spectators to Eastern Parkway every year.
</P>
<P>
   The organizers of the Feast of San Gennaro were no happier with
the policy, saying the cut in permits would mean less revenue that
could be donated to charity at the end of the festival.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only explanation the city has provided is that this is a
`quality of life' decision,'' the festival said in a written
statement released Wednesday. ``We see it as dictating a `control
of life' policy.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   At first, the city told the festival there would be no alcohol
sales, said Arnold N. Kriss, the lawyer for Figlia di San Gennaro,
the nonprofit group that organizes the festival. But after
discussions, the city agreed to allow 33 permits instead of the 65
the festival had last year, when there were no limits on permits.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-two additional permits go to restaurants, which are
already licensed to sell alcohol but set up extra booths during the
festival, Kriss said.
</P>
<P>
   He estimated the loss to the festival at $100,000, adding that
San Gennaro had donated $800,000 to charities over the past four
years.
</P>
<P>
   City officials have argued that they are simply correcting an
inconsistency in the law, which forbids drinking on public streets
but has allowed vendors at parades and festivals to sell alcohol.
O'Keefe said no festival or parade organizers had complained
directly to the city about the policy, and one producer of several
festivals said he would not apply for any alcohol permits.
</P>
<P>
   The change in policy had been requested by the Police
Department, O'Keefe said, but community groups' opinions also
affected the decision.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just as many people as love these festivals don't like them,''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Kriss criticized the city for issuing the new policy only three
weeks before the feast begins, leaving his client without enough
time to litigate the change.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got us between a rock and a hard place,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he did not understand why the police could not
simply patrol festivals and parades. ``The New York Police
Department does a fine job,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But Lt. Stephen Biegel, a police spokesman, said it was a
``quality of life issue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We can take care of the problems,'' Biegel said. ``Wouldn't it
be better not to have problems at all? Why have problems from
alcohol, when we can eliminate the alcohol and get rid of the
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   City officials have said privately in the past that the new
policy is a response to the sexual assaults that followed this
year's National Puerto Rican Day Parade, in which women were
attacked and in some cases undressed by aggressive crowds of men.
</P>
<P>
   But O'Keefe did not attribute the change to any one problem.
``We've had a few incidents at a few events, and we just needed to
look at what's happened,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   She blamed crowd spillover, public urination, and destruction of
property. ``And I'm not saying it's because of the drunks,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The city was considering further restrictions on outdoor events,
she said, including reducing the number of city blocks used.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
