<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 22:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0501 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-TEXAS-SCRIMMAGE0824-C     08-23 0766
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEXAS-SCRIMMAGE0824-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A legend in the making
 &HT;    By Kirk Bohls
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ The phone rang at 11:15 at night a couple of
months ago and aroused Major Applewhite from a deep sleep.
</P>
<P>
   All manner of emergency must have raced through the Texas
quarterback's head as he groggily lifted the receiver. Someone in a
car wreck? Family member suffer a household accident? Mack Brown
wanting to move him to safety?
</P>
<P>
   His mind wasn't any clearer when the caller failed to identify
himself. Finally, the caller spoke up.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me ask you a question,'' the voice said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go ahead,'' Applewhite said.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a 6 route, if the guy covering me is on my inside hip,''
the caller posed, ``what do I do?''
</P>
<P>
   Applewhite, by now fully awake, shook his head in bewilderment
and then asked Roy Williams an 11th-hour question.
</P>
<P>
   ``Roy,'' Major said, ``are you about to go run routes?''
</P>
<P>
   Most special wide receivers are born, some are made, and a
precious few are intent upon meshing the two. Which brings us to
the inquisitive Roy Williams, freshman wide receiver, an actual
Longhorn for all of 11 days, and already a legend in the making.
</P>
<P>
   All Williams did Wednesday was catch two passes for 17 yards and
a touchdown. Here's even more important stuff. Both came on
checkoffs at the line of scrimmage, the first on a fade route for a
5-yard touchdown over Ahmad Brooks, who must have suffered from
Texas A&AMP;M deja vu, and the second on a quick screen off a corner
blitz.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's pretty good,'' Texas offensive coordinator Greg Davis
said. ``The thing that shocked us is his maturity and attention to
detail.''
</P>
<P>
   It's been a nice two weeks for the gifted rookie out of Odessa
Permian, meaning it should be a nice four years for Texas fans.
He's caught everything but a summer cold. He can go deep, go short,
go over the middle. He's physical enough to push off without being
flagged for pushing off. He's fast enough in his size 16 shoes to
outrun Texas' fastest cornerbacks.
</P>
<P>
   ``You got to strap it on against Roy,'' Longhorn safety Greg
Brown said. ``The seven on seven drills during the summer helped
the freshmen. They went against us all summer, so they're not
scared of us.''
</P>
<P>
   What makes his emergence even more satisfying is Williams isn't
alone. The company he's keeping at Longhorn practices has been
head-turning special. Maybe not Roy Williams-special, but good
enough that head coach Mack Brown has said he might not redshirt a
single one of the freshman wideouts and expects 'em all to
contribute early. Say, like Sept. 9 against Louisiana-Lafayette.
</P>
<P>
   The injury to tight end Bo Scaife only accelerated the
transition process for Williams &AMP; Co., which includes fellow
freshmen B.J. Johnson, Sloan Thomas and Tony Jeffery.
</P>
<P>
   Their progress was on display Wednesday when Texas dropped just
two passes _ one by Johnson, one by fullback Chad Stevens _ and
moved the ball crisply.
</P>
<P>
   Don't be surprised to see more short and intermediate pass
routes, more three-step drops by the quarterbacks. It worked
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson caught a pass on a long crossing route against Greg
``Hit Man'' Brown and then made a nifty sideline grab and kept in
bounds. Rookie Thomas made the first catch of the 75-play scrimmage
on a sharp post pattern.
</P>
<P>
   Even a couple of old-timers like redshirt freshman Artie Ellis
and senior Brandon Healy made plays to wow the crowd of 1,500 at
Royal Memorial Stadium, but inconsistent Montrell Flowers still
needs to hit his stride.
</P>
<P>
   ``All these guys are very talented,'' said the 225-pound Ellis,
who showed some power moves and ran over freshman safety Phillip
Geiggar at the end of a 20-yard gain. ``We expect a lot out of
'em.''
</P>
<P>
   All of this is to say that Texas has not junked its passing game
even though Kwame Cavil took his 100 catches to the Buffalo Bills.
If you're a hardcore Longhorn fan who's sweating things big and
small, put wide receiver way down your list.
</P>
<P>
   Never mind the fact that Texas ran the ball on the first eight
plays of the scrimmage. The pass-happy Davis confirmed that he was,
indeed, conscious at the time although he added, ``I was shaking a
little bit.''
</P>
<P>
   In all likelihood, no Longhorn will catch 100 passes this fall,
but don't lament. Davis said to look for a whole bunch of guys with
30 to 35 catches apiece, which won't make it easy for defenses.
</P>
<P>
   That said, we should also point out that Williams probably will
not be an All-American this season. Probably.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
