<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR THURSDAY, AUG. 24 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Thursday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-MIDEAST-ARAFAT-NYT (moved Wednesday, August 16)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, August
16 about a decision by Palestinian leaders to reassess their plan
to declare statehood on Sept. 13 misstated the timetable for an
Israeli-Palestinian peace agreement under the Oslo accords of 1993.
The accords spelled out a five-year interim process; they did not
specify a seven-year goal for a final agreement.
</P>
<P>
   BC-MIDEAST-U.S.-NYT (moved Friday, August 18)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Friday, August 18
about efforts by the American envoy Dennis Ross to revive
Israeli-Palestinian talks misstated terms of United Nations
Security Council resolutions passed after the 1967 Middle East war.
While Resolution 242 called for Israel's armed forces to withdraw
``from territories occupied in the recent conflict,'' no resolution
called for Israel to hand over all of east Jerusalem to a future
Palestinian state.
</P>
<P>
   BC-PRISON-RATES-NYT (moved Wednesday, August 9)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, August
9 about a slowing in the increase of the nation's prison population
misstated the number of federal inmates sentenced on various types
of charges in 1998. The article substituted 1990 figures from the
Justice Department report. Actually, of the 108,925 inmates in
federal prisons in 1998, 63,011 (not 30,470) were charged with drug
crimes, 12,656 (not 7,557) were charged with violent offenses and
8,627 (not 7,935) were charged with property crimes.
</P>
<P>
   BC-DEM-SHADOW-CONVENTION-NYT (moved Sunday, August 13)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Sunday, August 13
about celebrities who attended parties for the Democratic National
Convention misstated the location of a fund-raiser given by Stan
Lee, the creator of Spider-Man. It was at the home of Ken Roberts,
a radio and real estate investor, in the Brentwood section of Los
Angeles, not at Lee's home in Malibu.
</P>
<P>
   The article also listed two guests erroneously. While invited,
Stevie Wonder and Michael Douglas did not attend.
</P>
<P>
   BC-OBIT-MAGGIO-NYT (moved Monday, August 21)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service obituary sent on Monday, August 21
of the theater director Michael Maggio on Tuesday misstated the
title of the last play he directed. It was ``Boy Gets Girl'' by
Rebecca Gilman, not ``Boy Meets Girl.''
</P>
</TEXT>
