<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MASS-MOM-POLITICIAN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MASSACHUSETTS OFFICIAL VIOLATED ETHICS RULES BY HAVING AIDES
BABY-SIT 
</HEADLINE>
   (Eds: SUBS lede to delete `probable cause,' adds new 5th graf, She
said ..., with Swift saying she will not appeal, subs next graf,
The commission ..., to remove reference to no punishment being
recommended since she still may face punishment.) 
 (ART ADV: Photo  NYT8  is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CAREY GOLDBERG   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ The Massachusetts State Ethics Commission found
Wednesday that Lt. Gov. Jane Swift, who won her office in 1998 less
than three weeks after bearing her first child, violated ethics
rules by having two aides baby-sit away from the State House.
</P>
<P>
   But the panel cleared Swift on several other ethics charges
including improperly using a state helicopter to fly home to her
sick baby and using aides to help her move.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've made some mistakes and I'm very sorry for those mistakes,
and I have a lot of work ahead of me if, as I hope, I am to regain
the trust of the public,'' Swift said Wednesday night on WBZ radio.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've learned from these mistakes,'' she said. ``One of the
things I've learned is that I have difficulty publicly admitting
mistakes.''
</P>
<P>
   She said she would not appeal. The commission has the power to
fine or reprimand her.
</P>
<P>
   The commission's finding &UR;  &LR;  capped months of drubbing that Swift,
a Republican, has been taking here in Democrat-dominated political
circles, in the news and in coffee-counter talk. Her decision to
run for office while pregnant in 1998 made her a heroine to some
working women, a model of how women could do it all. But her
questionable use of the perks of office to help balance motherhood
with work _ and her defensive attitude when challenged _ prompted
anger from many supporters and scorn from opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Goldman, a Democratic political consultant, even printed
up buttons reading, ``Jane `not so' Swift: It Takes an Entire State
Government to Raise a Child.''
</P>
<P>
   The attacks on Swift have been further energized by widespread
talk that the governor, Paul Cellucci, a Republican, might take a
federal job if the next president is a Republican, in which case
Swift would become governor.
</P>
<P>
   But there seems to be even more at work in Swift's case, said
Elizabeth A. Sherman, director of the Center for Women in Politics
and Public Policy at the University of Massachusetts in Boston.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the one hand, we have to say that she is new to this high
level, she made some mistakes and, unfortunately, she suffered a
tremendous amount of vilification in the press and the court of
public opinion for it,'' Sherman said. ``That said, I also feel
that it's just been an extraordinary backlash against her.''
</P>
<P>
   Swift's troubles began in January when local newspapers reported
that she had relied on aides for personal services including caring
for her toddler daughter both in the State House and at home,
helping her move and picking up dry cleaning. They also disclosed
that she had used a state helicopter to avoid Thanksgiving traffic
and fly home to her sick daughter in western Massachusetts.
</P>
<P>
   State ethics rules bar officials from asking employees to attend
to their personal chores, because the workers could feel pressure
to obey. At first, in what many see as her biggest mistake, Swift
defended her actions, saying that she shared many of the dilemmas
of everyday working parents but that her schedule was unusually
demanding.
</P>
<P>
   When she was queried about aides' complaints that they felt
pressured into baby-sitting Elizabeth, she replied, ``I would be
stunned if there was anyone who was feeling pressure to spend time
with her and care for her.'' In fact, she said, staff members were
happy to spend time with the baby: ``She is adorable and engaging
and she's learned to blow kisses.''
</P>
<P>
   Her remarks alienated many working parents and some pointed out
that Swift has a stay-at-home husband, a flexible job and a
supportive superior in Cellucci _ and yet she still needed to call
on aides to help ``hold it all together.''
</P>
<P>
   Swift, 35, soon apologized, and apologized again, saying she was
still learning about being a mother and a lieutenant governor. She
asked for the ethics commission to examine her actions to see if
they violated state ethics rules. On Monday, and again Wednesday
night, Swift said she was sorry that questions about her ethics had
drawn attention away from her administration's political agenda.
</P>
<P>
   But her apologies did not stop a precipitous slide in her
popularity: She and Cellucci were elected with 51 percent of the
vote; a poll by The Boston Globe in February found that only 20
percent of respondents viewed Swift favorably, while 36 percent saw
her unfavorably.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In the bigger picture, said Sherman of the University of
Massachusetts, Swift's story will serve as a case study of how
women in politics are perceived, and may also have a ``chilling
effect'' on young women who consider entering politics, by showing
them the microscopic examination their behavior, including their
mothering, might endure.
</P>
<P>
   But, she said, the worst part of the baby scandal may be that it
became a missed opportunity _ Swift could have used it to ask what
resources are needed to help parents mix work and child rearing.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is a question that needed to be asked and answered, and
it's just hanging out there,'' Sherman said. She said Swift ``had
the opportunity to move that discussion forward, and she didn't,
because she felt embattled, besieged, defensive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
