<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-MCAULIFFE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 KEVIN McAULIFFE, 50, PRESS AIDE TO 3 NYC MAYORS  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Kevin McAuliffe, a speechwriter for three New York
City mayors and the editor of a collection of comments by Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani published this year, died Aug. 20 . He was 50 and
lived in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was a heart attack, his family said.
</P>
<P>
   McAuliffe worked as a speechwriter and press aide for Mayors
Edward Koch and David Dinkins. He also worked for a few months for
Giuliani before being dismissed in 1994 as a holdover from
Democratic administrations.
</P>
<P>
   McAuliffe compiled ``Sayings of Generalissimo Giuliani,''
quotations on subjects including crime and sending garbage to
Virginia, assembled for comic effect.
</P>
<P>
   At his death, McAuliffe ran a communications consulting firm.
</P>
<P>
   McAuliffe, born in the Bronx, graduated from Fairfield
University in Connecticut and received a master's degree in
journalism from Columbia University. He began his career as a
journalist in New England. He also wrote ``The Great American
Newspaper: The Rise and Fall of the Village Voice'' (1978).
</P>
<P>
   McAuliffe is survived by his wife, Paulette Theresa, whom he
married in April; his mother, Ethel; a sister, Alice Callahan; two
brothers, Daniel and Paul; and two nieces.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-00 2240EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
