<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLF-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LPGA NEEDS CHAMPIONSHIP SITE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ All season long the LPGA tour seemed caught in the
shadow of the PGA Tour in general and Tiger Woods in particular.
</P>
<P>
   Woods kept his date with history while the ladies just had
problems with dates.
</P>
<P>
   The situation turned critical this week when LPGA officials
announced that their season-ending tournament, the Arch
Championship, a.k.a. the Ladies Professional Golf Association Tour
Championship, formerly known as the PageNet Championship, needs a
new home.
</P>
<P>
   The tournament was called the PageNet Championship until Monday,
when Arch Communications, a nation-wide telecommunications company,
slapped its name on the event.
</P>
<P>
   And for good reason. Arch is swallowing up PageNet in a merger
scheduled to close during the fourth quarter so it made sense.
</P>
<P>
   The company seems golf friendly and sponsors players on both the
LPGA and PGA tours.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the acquirer of PageNet (which) will continue to operate
under the Arch name, it makes sense to continue the sponsorship
under (our) name,'' said Robert W. Lougee Jr., the company's vice
president of investor relations.
</P>
<P>
   While the sponsorship problems is solved, the event has vagabond
status, which is not a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``For such a prestigious event, this is late in the game to be
changing things,'' said a source familiar with the situation.
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1996 and played at Desert Inn Resort on the Las Vegas
Strip, the tour's championship also provided some season-ending
drama, typically deciding the tour's top awards.
</P>
<P>
   Tour officials knew in June that the venerable resort would
close but were under the impression the course would remain open.
</P>
<P>
   Seems the hotel staff bolted for other jobs.
</P>
<P>
   So now the tour is rolling the dice in search of another venue.
</P>
<P>
   Other courses in Vegas and some in Florida are in play.
</P>
<P>
   This is the final year of the PageNet-Arch sponsorship deal and
no one on Wednesday could say whether it will be extended.
</P>
<P>
   So the season's final event will probably be called something
like the Arch LPGA Tour Championship.
</P>
<P>
   Finding a course to play it on is also important.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concern of everybody involved is making sure the
championship that ends our season stays a world-class event,'' said
Leslie King, the tour's director of communications.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Stearns, International Management Group's tournament
director, and LPGA commissioner Ty Votaw are conducting the search.
</P>
<P>
   Stearns likes Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like to keep the Arch championship in Las Vegas,'' he
said. ``The Desert Inn Resort and the city ... have provided us
with a great venue to showcase this tournament.''
</P>
<P>
   Vegas does have lots of golf courses now, including hotel mogul
Steve Wynn's tony and exclusive Shadow Mountain and a new Jack
Nicklaus course, Reflection Bay at Lake Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   A decision should be reached soon, especially since ABC and ESPN
will provide television coverage.
</P>
<P>
   Turns out this date problem has been an ongoing thing this year.
</P>
<P>
   In the spring the Players Championship conflicted with the
LPGA's first major, the Nabisco Championship. The men grabbed most
of the headlines.
</P>
<P>
   In July, while Woods was having a jolly good time carving up the
Old Course in St. Andrews, Scotland, winning the British Open, the
U.S. Women's Open was taking place at the Merit Club in
Libertyville, Ill. (A quick quiz. Can you name the winner? See
below.)
</P>
<P>
   Again, Woods was front-page news while the women's tournament,
for the most part, gave up coverage to baseball and football
training camps.
</P>
<P>
   While the British Open got saturation, albeit earlier, TV
coverage, watching two major championships was probably too much
for all but the most serious of fans.
</P>
<P>
   Now golf's major business is finished for the year and the LPGA
still struggles with a date problem.
</P>
<P>
   Also high on the policy makers' agenda is deciding which of the
tour's other tournaments is worthy of being called a major.
</P>
<P>
   The fourth major, the du Maurier Classic, experienced its swan
song this year because Canada's tough new anti-tobacco legislation
prevents the title sponsor from participating in the event.
</P>
<P>
   So Votaw and his policy makers have some scrambling to do.
</P>
<P>
   Find another sponsor in Canada or just elevate the status of
another tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Hey, it's been done before. The du Maurier got the nod in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Trouble is, they can't make a hasty decision or else they could
be looking for a new major every couple of years since sponsors on
the LPGA tour can sometimes be fickle.
</P>
<P>
   King says lots of tournaments want the title, like the Wegman's
Rochester International and the JAL Big Apple Classic.
</P>
<P>
   The most natural seems to be the Weetabix British Open.
</P>
<P>
   All seem fitting candidates, three of the LPGA majors are named
after corporate sponsors, the exception being the U.S. Women's
Open.
</P>
<P>
   A decision will be made by the end of September and one
possibility is playing just three majors next year, not a good idea
from an historical perspective.
</P>
<P>
   So this date problem is not going to go away anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   And it is not the kind of spotlight the tour sought, or
deserves.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want to make sure the decision we make is the right one,
both from the standpoint of longevity and tradition,'' King said.
</P>
<P>
   Lots of moola: Last summer it was the ``Shootout at Sherwood.''
This time around its billed as ``The Battle of Bighorn,'' or Woods'
personal cash cow. The made-for-television event showcases Tiger
Woods and the challenger of the moment, who this year is Sergio
Garcia.
</P>
<P>
   It's a $1.5 million match-play event televised Monday night by
ABC. The winner gets $1.1 million.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
