<SLUG> BC-FBN-COLUMN-WINSLOW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON PRO FOOTBALL: WINSLOW USES TALENTS TO FIGHT HEART DISEASE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ill., Calif., N.Y.)   By THOMAS GEORGE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Kellen Winslow is acutely aware of what is happening
in his neighborhood, his town, his country and beyond. He is a Hall
of Fame tight end from the San Diego Chargers who can talk about
world events as deftly as he can about current NFL tight ends who
are fearless across the middle.
</P>
<P>
   Winslow was in Manhattan on Wednesday to lend his name to a new
cause that he knows affects his world and yours.
</P>
<P>
   Beginning Sept. 5, fans may vote on NFL.com for the player whose
performance from the previous week was the most gritty, the player
who exhibited the most heart. Each Thursday during the season, the
league will count the votes and award the All-Heart Player of the
Week award, part of an effort by the NFL to educate people about
heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a member of a high-risk group because I have had
hypertension in my family,'' Winslow said. ``This is something
people should know about and monitor. You can't address a problem
unless you know you have a problem. And especially in the
African-American community, I'm concerned about the tendency to go
for these kind of tests only after you get sick.''
</P>
<P>
   Winslow, 42, who lives in San Diego, is the perfect spokesman
for such a program.
</P>
<P>
   He grew up in East St. Louis, Ill., played football at the
University of Missouri and earned a degree in counseling psychology
there, played with the Chargers from 1979 through 1987 and then
earned a law degree from the University of San Diego. He was
inducted into the Pro Football Hall of Fame in 1995. He is
currently commissioner of the 21-team Indoor Football League and is
a college football analyst for Fox Net Sports.
</P>
<P>
   But there is one game, one singular achievement that will always
be Winslow's signature: a 41-38 overtime playoff victory for the
Chargers against Miami in the Orange Bowl on Jan. 2, 1982.
</P>
<P>
   In that game, Winslow caught 13 passes, a playoff record, for
166 yards, scored on a 25-yard reception and blocked a field goal
attempt. He was seemingly everywhere that night and played in a
soiled uniform, in a jersey that became untucked, and kept playing
despite several stitches in his bloody lip and despite losing 12
pounds of water weight.
</P>
<P>
   When coaches talk about playing football with passion, about
leaving everything on the field, they are talking about Winslow in
the Orange Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear about that game every day of my life, every time I
leave my house or even when I stay home _ somebody calls and wants
to talk about it on the phone,'' Winslow said. ``People have sent
me letters saying they named their kid after me, boys and girls,
because they want them to produce that kind of effort in their
lives. A man told me his wife was having a baby during the game and
would not leave for the hospital until he agreed to have a
miniature TV in the car. The funny thing is, I had played better in
other games. But I guess in that game I was pushed to the
mountaintop and passed that test. I could truly say that game I
gave my all.''
</P>
<P>
   Why isn't Winslow running an NFL franchise? He said that after
he gained his law degree he asked the Chargers for a chance in
their front office but was told there was no room for him. He is
bitter about that. ``I think it's something I could be good at,''
Winslow said. But Winslow had too much heart to let bitterness ruin
him. He moved on.
</P>
<P>
   The league will post five players each week as candidates for
the All-Heart award, sponsored by the NFL and Merck, the
pharmaceutical company, to make the public aware of the effect of
cholesterol in heart disease.
</P>
<P>
   Winslow said he would watch closely, because the nominees and
winners ``should not necessarily be the guy who catches 10 passes
and two for touchdowns.'' Winslow's early favorites for the first
winner?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd go with Junior Seau of the Chargers _ every play, every
game, he gives 100 percent,'' Winslow said. ``Jevon Kearse of
Tennessee, he has a nonstop motor and the motor is the heart.
Edgerrin James of the Colts runs, blocks and catches. Peyton
Manning of the Colts leads with discipline and character. Hey, and
I'd pick a coach like Dan Reeves, who has fought back from heart
disease in a manner few have.''
</P>
<P>
   Winslow said to keep an eye this season on four tight ends: Tony
Gonzalez of Kansas City, Bubba Franks of Green Bay, Rickey Dudley
of Oakland and Shannon Sharpe of Baltimore. He will do that, and
also looks at Washington, Tennessee and Tampa Bay as three teams he
believes are ahead in the Super Bowl race.
</P>
<P>
   ``This All-Heart Award will be about effort, performance and
desire,'' Winslow said. ``You know, respect is not about money,
fame or intimidation. It is something you earn.''
</P>
<P>
   As Winslow did. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-00 2246EDT &QL; 
