<SLUG> BC-SURVIVOR0824-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Indictment delivered, winner declared
 &HT;    By Phil Kloer
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ It came down to the snake vs. the rat, in island
lingo, and the snake ate the rat.
</P>
<P>
   Richard Hatch, the scheming corporate consultant who had become
the J.R. Ewing of ``Survivor,'' won the $1 million in a 4-3 vote in
Wednesday's two-hour finale of the pop culture phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
   Before the final vote, Susan Hawk, the Wisconsin truck driver
with a tongue like a bullwhip who had made it to the Final Four,
delivered a ripping indictment of the two finalists, Hatch and
river guide Kelly Wiglesworth, both of whom had been her friends
earlier in the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``This island is full of two things: snakes and rats,'' she
said.`` We have Richard the snake and Kelly, who turned into the
rat. I think we owe it to the island's spirits to let it be the way
Mother Nature intended it to be, to let the snake eat the rat.''
</P>
<P>
   After 13 weeks of ``Survivor,'' Hawk's tirade will be remembered
as the show's big moment.
</P>
<P>
   Nielsen observers had expected the finale to be watched by 35
million to 40 million viewers, which would more than cap
``Survivor's'' record run as the most-watched summer TV series in
history. CBS sold 30-second commercials for $600,000, more than
``ER'' or ``Friends'' gets during the regular season.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen castaways were set ashore on the island of Pulau Tiga,
and voted each other into exile one by one over 13 weeks, turning
the South Seas spot of land into Cutthroat Island rather than Pulau
Tiga.
</P>
<P>
   For Wednesday's finale, it had come down to the Final Four. They
were the original four members of what was called the Tagi Alliance
(for the name of their tribe), which threatened to crumble but
never did, as it picked off the former competing Pagongs one by
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now we're finished with the Alliance,'' Boesch said early in
the show. ``You're on your own.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday's first Immunity Challenge was called ``Fallen
Comrades,'' with host Jeff Probst asking the four trivia questions
about the players who had been voted out, such as ``What state is
Gervase from?'' and ``Who received only one vote at the first
Tribal Council?''
</P>
<P>
   Wiglesworth and Hawk tied at the end of 10 questions, but Kelly
won the tie-breaker and earned her fourth consecutive Immunity
necklace. Once again, the scheming of the other three, who had
agreed to vote out Wiglesworth, was foiled.
</P>
<P>
   The first vote was tied, two each for Hawk and Hatch. A
tie-breaker was held, with Hawk and Hatch not allowed to vote. Hawk
got both votes and smiled as her torch was extinguished. ``See you
guys later,'' she said to the three who remained, knowing something
that none of the others ejected could be sure about: exactly who
voted her off.
</P>
<P>
   The final immunity challenge was ``Hands On the Immunity Idol,''
as the trio, smeared with mud and starting at dawn, had to stand on
stumps and keep one hand on the carved totem for as long as
possible.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch took a calculated gamble and pulled his hand away after
only a couple of hours, losing the challenge deliberately.
</P>
<P>
   ``This game is about a lot of things, and one of them is mental
strategy,'' Hatch explained. ``It doesn't mean I'm giving up $1
million necessarily. Whoever is immune has to pick. ...For the
first time, it's out of my hands.''
</P>
<P>
   After four hours, Boesch accidentally removed his hand from the
idol while changing positions. Wiglesworth had won her fifth
straight challenge. ``That was a dumb move on my part,'' Boesch
said. ``I gave away a million bucks.''
</P>
<P>
   Since Boesch and Hatch would just cancel each other out, only
Wiglesworth voted. ``Tonight you are the queen of the island,''
Probst told her.
</P>
<P>
   The queen cast her vote against Boesch.
</P>
<P>
   As the two awaited the final decision, they stayed in character.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been some moral low points for me playing this game.
I've had some not-so-proud moments,'' said Wiglesworth, who was
always the most ambivalent member of the Alliance.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch, meanwhile, said he would be proud to get the $100,000
runner-up money. ``But I want the million. I really want the
million!''
</P>
<P>
   The jury of the last seven voted off consisted of: Hawk, Boesch,
Colleen Haskell, Gervase Peterson, Sean Kenaf, Jenna Lewis and Greg
Buis. The final vote: 4 for Hatch, 3 for Wiglesworth.
</P>
<P>
   Product placement has been prominent during the show's run:
Target, Pizza Hut, the U.S. Army and Bud Light all made it to the
island. On Wednesday, after months of touting just the $1 million
grand prize, suddenly it became $1 million plus a new Pontiac Aztek
SUV. ``See the Survivor winner drive one home tonight,'' a
promotional announcement said _ a pretty neat trick from an island,
which was never pulled off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've lost some weight, lost some muscle, lost some sanity,''
Wiglesworth said during Wednesday's finale, and millions of viewers
could relate to the loss of sanity, as ``Survivor'' spawned a fan
obsessiveness that permeated the Internet, the media and private
conversations all summer.
</P>
<P>
   Some summers are marked by a particular movie, beach book or pop
song on the radio that dominates the culture. This was the summer
of ``Survivor.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
