<SLUG> BC-NY-EXCHANGE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVELOPERS SHOW LITTLE INTEREST IN STOCK EXCHANGE COMPLEX
</HEADLINE>
 By CHARLES V. BAGLI    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ New York City officials are finding that the road to
building a trading complex for the New York Stock Exchange can be
long and bumpy.
</P>
<P>
   In response to solicitations by the Giuliani administration,
only two developers told the city on Friday that they were
interested in building the proposed $727 million,
1.9-million-square-foot trading complex and office tower on a block
bounded by Wall, Broad and William Streets and Exchange Place.
</P>
<P>
   Two other developers approached by the city's Economic
Development Corp. decided that the project was too complicated and
risky, according to real estate executives.
</P>
<P>
   And 20 months after Mayor Rudolph Giuliani announced plans for
the heavily subsidized project in the financial district, the New
York Stock Exchange has still not signed an agreement with the
Giuliani administration, although city officials say a deal is
imminent, as they have been saying for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we're getting close,'' said Michael Carey, president
of the Economic Development Corp. ``I continue to be optimistic
that the project will go forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Carey said he was close to concluding a deal to buy the site
from the property owners, J.P. Morgan and the Rockrose Development
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The state would condemn one other parcel on the block.
</P>
<P>
   Tishman Speyer Properties and Brookfield Financial Properties
both indicated interest in the project, but the Rudin real estate
family and Boston Properties took a pass.
</P>
<P>
   The city has told the applicants that it wanted to select a
developer by Sept. 1.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the American International Group, one of the
world's largest insurance companies, has expressed interest in
occupying a part of the office tower over the trading complex, real
estate executives and a city official said. But the company has
made no commitments and says it is unsure yet how much space it
needs.
</P>
<P>
   City officials are hoping that the sale of development rights
for the office tower will more than offset the projected $350
million cost of acquiring the block across the street from the
stock exchange's historic Wall Street home.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trick is to get a tenant,'' said one real estate executive
working with AIG. ``But this is not even close to being done. It's
very murky.''
</P>
<P>
   The proposed project has been clouded by rapid changes in the
financial industry _ toward electronic trading _ as well as by the
complicated nature of the deal.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, the stock exchange threatened to move to New
Jersey if the city could not help it expand beyond its cramped,
97-year-old quarters on Wall Street. Many urban planners and real
estate executives doubted that the exchange would relocate,
especially since most of the large investment banks that trade at
the exchange had invested in Manhattan real estate and received tax
breaks in exchange for promising to remain in New York.
</P>
<P>
   But Giuliani said the city could not risk losing the stock
exchange, and in December 1998, city and state officials agreed to
build a trading complex and provide $160 million in tax breaks. The
cost for the trading complex itself has since grown to $482
million.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, some securities analysts have questioned the
need for expanded trading floors, given the rapid growth of
electronic trading. Electronic networks now account for 37 percent
of the trades on the Nasdaq and about 3 percent of the volume on
the New York Stock Exchange, according to the Tower Group, a
research firm.
</P>
</TEXT>
