<SLUG> BC-PIPELINE-BLAST-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEADLY PIPELINE BLAST WAS NOT COMPANY'S FIRST
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
 By NEIL STRASSMAN 
 c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FORT WORTH _ El Paso Natural Gas Co. has experienced two deadly
pipeline accidents since 1970 caused by corrosion, according to a
review of federal records after last weekend's explosion in New
Mexico, which claimed 11 lives.
</P>
<P>
   The records show that the company has had 30 accidents caused by
corrosion since 1970. Two accidents involved fatalities in West
Texas, leaving three dead in one explosion and one in the other.
</P>
<P>
   Federal investigators discovered corrosion in the pipeline that
exploded early Saturday in southeastern New Mexico, killing members
of three generations of one family.
</P>
<P>
   In some locations, the pipe wall had been reduced to less than
half of its original thickness, company officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The federal Office of Pipeline Safety ordered the company
yesterday to close its pipelines near the Pecos River, about 30
miles south of Carlsbad, N.M., until the company tests the lines to
make sure they are safe.
</P>
<P>
   One of the previous deaths occurred in 1985 in Glasscock County
in West Texas. Ten years earlier, three employees were killed and
two others injured when a 12-inch gas line ruptured in Ector
County, also in West Texas, according to Office of Pipeline Safety
records that date from 1970, the earliest year such records are
available.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, National Transportation Safety Board investigators
said that they ``visually observed a significant amount of
corrosion'' at the bottom of the pipe in New Mexico, where the
rupture occurred and where it had been exposed by the explosion,
which blasted a crater 85 feet long, 45 feet wide and 25 feet deep
into the desert, 300 feet west of the river.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was some internal corrosion on the pipe,'' said John
Somerhalder, president of the El Paso Energy Pipeline Group. The
pipe wall, originally slightly thicker than 5/16 of an inch, had
been corroded to less than half its original thickness, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The pipeline group is a subsidiary of Houston-based El Paso
Energy Co., owner of the biggest U.S. network of interstate gas
pipelines. The group oversees all of the parent company's
pipelines, including the 10,000 miles of lines owned by the El Paso
Natural Gas Co.
</P>
<P>
   NTSB investigators said it was too early to say that corrosion
caused the leak that led to Saturday's pre-dawn explosion in Eddy
County, N.M. The pipe was one of four 30-inch El Paso Natural Gas
pipelines in the area. Three of the 50-year-old lines were in
service.
</P>
<P>
   A piece of the damaged pipe is being sent to Washington for
metallurgical tests, the investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   Pipeline company officials have said that the line was last
inspected Aug. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Amanda Smith, 25, remained in critical condition at a Lubbock
hospital yesterday, making her the explosion's sole survivor. Her
husband, two children and parents were among the dead.
</P>
<P>
   The New Mexico explosion comes as concerns grow about the safety
of the nation's 2.2 million miles of natural gas and petroleum
pipelines. Major accidents _ those involving a fatality, an injury
or more than $50,000 in property damage _ have increased as the
system of aging pipelines has deteriorated.
</P>
<P>
   ``These pipelines are rotting in the ground. They need to be
replaced,'' said Bob Rackleff, a county commissioner in Florida and
the president of the National Pipeline Reform Coalition, a new
watchdog group pushing for safer pipelines.
</P>
<P>
   The rules governing pipelines do not require the replacement of
aging lines and ``are terribly weak,'' Rackleff said.
</P>
<P>
   Office of Pipeline Safety records show that since 1970, El Paso
Natural Gas has had 205 pipeline ruptures: 55.2 percent of them
were caused by construction or material defects in the pipe, 21.5
by outside damage, 14.6 percent by corrosion and 8.7 percent
attributed to other factors.
</P>
<P>
   The records show that corrosion has caused ruptures in at least
three large pipes, ranging from 26 inches to 30 inches and made
between 1947 and 1953, pipes of the same size and age as the one
that ruptured last weekend, killing the campers and fishers on the
Pecos.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials did not respond to several questions about its
safety record regarding its 30-inch pipe and the corrosion-related
fatalities.
</P>
<P>
   The three 30-inch pipelines that cross the Pecos on two bridges
transported about 1 billion cubic feet of natural gas a day from
the West Texas oilfields of the Permian Basin to New Mexico,
Colorado, Arizona and California, said Norma Dunn, company
spokeswoman. The gas is used to run electric power generating
plants and by regional natural gas companies that distribute it
locally.
</P>
<P>
   Legislation to improve pipeline safety and protect heavily
populated regions and the environment is now stalled in Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Patty Murray, D-Wash., a sponsor of one bill and a strong
proponent of pipeline reform since three people were killed in
Bellingham, Wash., in 1999, called the New Mexcico explosion ``a
deadly reminder that Congress needs to improve pipeline safety this
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Generally, the pipeline bills seek greater enforcement authority
for the Office of Pipeline Safety, tougher inspections, better
operator training and more investment in research to prevent
accidents. The bills would also require pipeline companies to
release accident data to the public under strong community
right-to-know provisions. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Star-Telegram systems editor Michael Gerst contributed to this
report.  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Visit the Star-Telegram's online services on the World Wide
Web: www.star-telegram.com) &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
