<SLUG> BC-INTEL-CHIP0824-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Intel is developing new chip for wireless phones, devices
 &HT;    By Bob Keefe
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN JOSE, Calif. _ Intel Corp. is developing a new type of
communications chip designed specifically to conserve battery power
and operate at fast speeds _ two keys to the fast-growing future of
devices such as Internet-ready wireless phones.
</P>
<P>
   Intel's new semiconductor design - called XScale
microarchitecture - is based on its StrongARM technology used to
make chips for cell phones and other wireless communications
equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The design was developed by Intel's operation in Chandler,
Ariz., but will be used extensively by Intel engineers in Austin,
said Ron Smith, vice president of Intel's Wireless Computing and
Communications Group. Intel's handheld computing division is based
in Austin, and the 1,500-person design center it's planning for
downtown Austin is expected to focus largely on wireless chip
design.
</P>
<P>
   ``The combination of very lower power and high performance makes
(the new design) well-suited for Internet access devices, such as
handheld and portable applications where battery life is
essential,'' Smith said in announcing the new design at Intel's
annual developer forum in San Jose on Wednesday. He said chips
based on the design would probably be available by the end of the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Just as importantly, chips based on the new design are expected
to have the ability to operate on a wide range of power levels and
at various speeds. Chips could run on as little as one
ten-thousandth of a watt, for instance _ key for products such as
wireless phones and personal digital assistants _ and as fast as 1
gigahertz, making them viable for big-computers like Internet
servers. Typical cell phones today need about 1 watt of power when
they're being used.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've got the magic with this,'' said David Wu, an analyst
with investment banking and consulting firm ABN Amro Inc. ``Right
now you have lower power chips and you have high performance chips,
but you don't have both. This is going to be very good for Intel.''
</P>
<P>
   The new chip design is Santa Clara, Calif.-based Intel's latest
move aimed at increasing its share of the growing wireless market
as its PC chip business continues to slow along with sales of
personal computers in general.
</P>
<P>
   This year, consumers and businesses are expected to buy an
estimated 400 million wireless phones _ nearly double the number
purchased a year ago, according to figures from researcher
Dataquest Inc. By 2004, Dataquest predicts, sales will surpass 1
billion units.
</P>
<P>
   Intel is the world's biggest producer of computer chips but is a
mere bit player in the wireless chip business. Along with designing
new products centered on StrongARM technology, it
uncharacteristically has tried to buy its way into the wireless
market, making more than 20 communications-related acquisitions
over the past two years alone.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Christensen, vice president of Intel's Network
Communications Group, said the company plans to make even more
acquisitions to get new technology and engineers and is targeting
primarily smaller companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``In general we don't look at mega-acquisitions,'' Christensen
said. ``We look primarily at small acquisitions.''
</P>
<P>
   Intel acquired the licensing rights to StrongARM, in fact, when
it purchased most of Digital Equipment Corp.'s chip business in
1997.
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday, Intel's stock closed at $74.62, up $2.50.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
