<HEADER>
A0671 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-TALKS-NYT     08-23 0962
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-TALKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS STILL TALKING WITH SEATTLE ABOUT EWING
</HEADLINE>
 By CHRIS BROUSSARD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ General Manager Scott Layden continued to work the
phones on Wednesday as the Knicks sought to put together a deal
that would bring Glen Rice to New York and end Patrick Ewing's
increasingly ugly relationship with the franchise, its fans and the
news media.
</P>
<P>
   The parties in Seattle _ from Sonics management to Vin Baker to
his agent, Aaron Goodwin _ are frustrated because they believe the
deal would have been consummated on Monday were it not leaked to
the news media last weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks are frustrated because the fans' and news media's
rush to all but escort Ewing out of town will make it difficult and
uncomfortable if they are forced to welcome him back, something
that is growing more likely.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks, the Sonics and the Los Angeles Lakers scrambled on
Wednesday to resuscitate the four-team, 13-player trade that fell
apart Monday evening when the Detroit Pistons pulled out amid
criticism from fans.
</P>
<P>
   The three clubs tried to sweeten the deal for the Pistons, who
originally were to receive seven marginal players, but Detroit was
not moved.
</P>
<P>
   Pistons General Manager Joe Dumars told the Detroit news media
on Wednesday that he would be open to working with the three teams
if a better deal were made available, but that was unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, the Pistons asked the Knicks to include Marcus Camby
in the package, but New York declined.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Detroit is set to send Christian Laettner to Dallas
next week for Cedric Ceballos.
</P>
<P>
   With Detroit all but out of the picture, the clubs pressed for
either the Chicago Bulls or the Charlotte Hornets to get involved.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks, Sonics and Lakers all have interest in the Bulls'
center and power forward Dickey Simpkins and may have been looking
at involving him in the deal with a sign-and-trade agreement.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks and Sonics could work a two-team deal that featured
Ewing and Baker as the principals, but New York is less than
enthralled with Baker.
</P>
<P>
   Even at 38, Ewing is more productive than Seattle's declining
power forward, and the six years and $77 million remaining on
Baker's contract conjure up thoughts of the restrictive 12-year,
$84 million contract that Larry Johnson lugged to New York four
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the two teams want to get a deal done, they don't need
three or four teams,'' said Goodwin, who hoped that Baker would
become a Knick on Thursday before leaving for Hawaii to train for
the Olympics. ``If New York wants Vin and if Seattle wants Patrick
Ewing, then do a deal.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks would take Baker if they also landed Rice, but they
are hesitant to make such a move otherwise. The clubs continue to
talk, though.
</P>
<P>
   Another possible two-team deal involves the Knicks and the
Lakers. The clubs are believed to have discussed a trade that would
have brought Rice, the backup center Travis Knight and the reserve
guards John Celestand and Tyronn Lue to New York in exchange for
Chris Dudley, Chris Childs and another player, possibly the rookie
Lavor Postell.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers, however, balked at accepting Childs, who got into a
fight with Kobe Bryant in a game last season, and asked the Knicks
to replace him with a more enticing player, possibly Camby. That
forced the Knicks to step back.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks' interest in Rice is real, which implies that the
deal they are trying to make may be a prelude to another trade
involving Allan Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks are aware that they need a top-flight big man to
compete for a championship, and adding Rice would give them the
flexibility to package Houston and perhaps Camby in such a deal.
The obvious desirables would be Atlanta's Dikembe Mutombo and
Sacramento's Chris Webber, both of whom will be free agents after
next season and could pressure their teams to trade them.
</P>
<P>
   While the clubs work the phones, the possibility of Ewing
remaining with the Knicks increases.
</P>
<P>
   Seattle is perhaps the only team with which the Knicks can work
a deal that involves their onetime franchise player, and the delay
is making the Sonics bitter. They stand to gain not only Ewing but
Maurice Taylor, who would sign with Seattle for the $2.25 million
midlevel exception if Ewing joins the Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, if the Sonics did not extend Ewing's contract after
next season, which is likely, they could position themselves to be
nearly $20 million beneath the salary cap next summer, when Webber,
Mutombo and Dallas' small forward Michael Finley become free
agents.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics want desperately to part ways with Baker, who has
played poorly his last two seasons, and Goodwin has even gone on
record as saying that there is too much acrimony between the
parties for Baker to return to Seattle. Baker, who does not get
along with Sonics Coach Paul Westphal, is looking to play superbly
at the Sydney Olympics in hopes of enhancing his trade value.
</P>
<P>
   As unpleasant as things have become for Ewing in New York, his
situation is not as bad as Baker's and a reconciliation by next
season is not unfathomable. The Knicks will not trade Ewing for
substandard player, and they know that his 15 points and 10
rebounds a night are still of major value.
</P>
<P>
   Houston, who seems to let trade talk involving his name bounce
off his back, said he could see Ewing back in the starting lineup
despite the recent turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like we haven't been through this before _ trade
rumors and speculation,'' Houston said. ``If and when he comes back
we're going to still make it work and everybody has to be on the
same page. Just because something happens one day in the office
does not mean you come back for the rest of the week and complain
about it.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
