<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MISSING-BOYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BODIES OF TWO TEEN-AGE BOYS STILL MISSING 
</HEADLINE>
  By AL BAKER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CROTON-ON-HUDSON, N.Y. _ As helicopters and rescue boats
searched the Hudson River for two teen-age boys from a state
psychiatric center who were swept away on Tuesday, investigators
said that a counselor who had been warned to keep them out of the
water had led them down a steep, treacherous path to the river's
edge.
</P>
<P>
   There, at a rocky outcropping where the Hudson and Croton Rivers
converge _ a spot that local residents said had been the site of
many drownings over the years _ three of the six teen-agers in the
counselor's care suddenly leapt fully dressed into the treacherous
crosscurrents, the police said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   One boy managed to fight his way to shore right away, and the
counselor, Lenox Gabriel, who had yelled for the boys to get out
and then jumped in after them, was rescued by police officers. But
as of late Wednesday, the two other boys, Arimendi Lajara, 15, and
Cedric Florence, 17, had still not been found. Gabriel told the
police that they appeared to swim away from shore. Dozens of their
relatives gathered at the desolate site waiting for news. The
Westchester County police said the boys' survival seemed unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   The police said the incident, in Croton Point Park, 35 miles
north of New York, was being treated as an accident, although they
wanted to speak again with Gabriel, 47, who was listed in stable
condition at Phelps Memorial Hospital Center in Sleepy Hollow.
Officials there said he would not comment.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this point they are not anticipating any criminal
charges,'' Sgt. Donald F. McArthur said of detectives investigating
the case.
</P>
<P>
   It is not clear, McArthur said, where the other counselors were
when the boys jumped into the river. He said Gabriel told
investigators that he was the only adult with the six children at
the time.
</P>
<P>
   One of the counselors called the park headquarters to report the
emergency, and two police officers who had been in the park jumped
in to rescue Gabriel.
</P>
<P>
   The State Office of Mental Health, which operates the Brooklyn
psychiatric center and the group home on its grounds where the boys
are temporarily living, is also investigating, said Roger Klingman,
a spokesman for the office.
</P>
<P>
   Gabriel told a detective late Tuesday that he had walked the
boys down the near-vertical hill called Teller's Point at the
southernmost tip of the park to take them on a hike, not to go
swimming, the police said.
</P>
<P>
   The pathway is marked by rocks and tree roots that can be used
as footholds. It is thickly wooded and takes some skill to
navigate. ``No swimming'' signs are posted, officials said, but the
police said they were often removed by vandals. None were visible
on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The counselors asked park officials if swimming was allowed,
McArthur said, and were told twice _ at check-in on Monday and
earlier Tuesday _ that the water was off limits. Walking on the
cliff is not prohibited, he said.
</P>
<P>
   On Wednesday, helicopters buzzed overhead and boats scoured the
waterway, until their blinking emergency lights were barely
discernible through the gathering mist.
</P>
<P>
   The six boys on the outing are residents of an outpatient group
home on the grounds of the psychiatric center, in
Bedford-Stuvesant. The five-year-old home is a short-term or
transitional center for emotionally troubled teen-agers who require
round-the-clock supervision rather than hospitalization, Klingman
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
