<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VERIZON-STRIKE-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VERIZON SETTLES WITH OTHER UNION
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: N.J., Pa., Del., Md., W. Va., Va.)  (Eds: SUBS with new lede, updating throughout to reflect settlement
) 
BY SIMON ROMERO   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Verizon Communications and a union representing more
than 35,000 employees in several mid-Atlantic states settled an
18-day strike Wednesday night after the company agreed to reduce
requirements for mandatory overtime.
</P>
<P>
   The agreement came after nearly all significant differences
between Verizon and two unions were resolved and a majority of
strikers returned to work earlier this week in New York and New
England.
</P>
<P>
   An agreement in New Jersey, Pennsylvania, Delaware, Maryland,
West Virginia, Virginia and Washington was held up over the
overtime issue, in addition to local concerns like what type of
work cable splicers and service technicians can do in Pennsylvania,
people close to the talks said.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement reached Wednesday night between between
Verizon, which was formed by the merger of Bell Atlantic and GTE,
and the Communications Workers of America, customer service
representatives in these states will be required to work as much as
7.5 hours of overtime a week, down from as much as 15 hours. Other
union employees' overtime will be capped at 10 hours a week after
the contract is ratified, and eight hours in January.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the overtime concession, Verizon agreed to a
bilingual salary differential, in which workers who do jobs that
require more than one language will receive 3.5 percent more pay,
people close to the talks said.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, the communications workers' union and the International
Brotherhood of Electrical Workers, which together represented more
than 86,000 employees in the walkout, secured a number of
concessions from Verizon, including wage and benefit increases,
stock options, greater job security and more flexibility to
organize in the company's fast-growing wireless division.
</P>
<P>
   While union negotiators in New York and New England considered
these concessions a pivotal victory in their effort to gain a
foothold in high-technology industries, their counterparts in the
mid-Atlantic region wrangled over local issues like cable splicers.
Verizon apparently wanted to deploy cable splicers with greater
flexibility. A definitive agreement on this issue was not reached,
people close to the talks said.
</P>
<P>
   Cable splicers generally install and repair telephone cables and
are considered more skilled than service technicians, who connect
and repair telephone service on the outside of homes and
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're happy to put this strike in the past,'' said Eric Rabe,
a spokesman for Verizon.  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-00 2330EDT &QL; 
