<HEADER>
A0678 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-CHENEY-STOCKS-NY     08-23 0664
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-CHENEY-STOCKS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: CHENEY'S OPTIONS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, Aug. 24:
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cheney became wealthy at the helm of Halliburton Co. over
the past five years. At Wednesday's stock price, the value of his
shares, restricted shares and vested stock options granted him
during his tenure adds up to more than $30 million. That is
compensation awarded to Cheney for his past service, and is
perfectly appropriate, provided he sells these assets if elected
vice president and puts the proceeds in a blind trust to eliminate
any potential conflicts of interest.
</P>
<P>
   But Americans should wonder why the Dallas-based oil services
company went further and allowed Cheney to keep 400,000 more stock
options that he would ordinarily have had to work additional years
to acquire. Under the terms of his employment contract, Cheney
could have retired at age 62 and by that time would have earned
these additional options. But as part of his retirement package,
Halliburton's board of directors allowed Cheney to retire at age 59
and still keep these options. The board also accelerated the
vesting of some restricted shares. That special favor, worth at
least $6 million at today's prices and potentially a lot more,
would tie Cheney's financial fortunes to those of the company _ and
therefore to the price of oil _ well into a potential Bush-Cheney
administration. Cheney should have turned the favor down, and taken
only the substantial stake he had already earned.
</P>
<P>
   Halliburton is being generous to a fault. The purpose of an
employment contract and of stock options with staggered vesting
periods is to retain valued employees. There is no legitimate
reason for Halliburton shareholders to compensate Cheney for
leaving early to seek the vice presidency. Nor should they be asked
to supplement his government salary. Clearly, the company would not
be allowing Cheney to keep the additional options if he were going
to work for a competitor.
</P>
<P>
   Halliburton maintains that it is not treating Cheney any
differently than it would other highly valued employees who opt to
retire early. But the vice-presidential candidate is not just
another retiree. And while the company may be excused for wanting
to ingratiate itself with a man who could be the next president's
chief lieutenant, if not president himself someday, Cheney should
know better than to find himself in this situation. It is true that
there are no laws barring the arrangement, but it is a matter of
judgment.
</P>
<P>
   What makes the situation especially troubling is the nature of
the industry itself. Oil touches on everything from relations with
Venezuela to wildlife preservation in Alaska, from Middle East
politics to the automobile industry.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney has said he will do whatever is needed to avoid any
conflict of interest. He is reportedly conferring with lawyers
about how best to handle the thorny ethical issue posed by the
400,000 options, which are scheduled to vest late this year, in
2001 and in 2002. To his credit, Cheney has indicated he will place
his assets in a blind trust if elected vice president. But these
options cannot be transferred, not even to a trust. It is baffling
that a man of Cheney's supposed sophistication would not have
avoided this ethical minefield in negotiating his retirement
package.
</P>
<P>
   Cheney's lawyers and financial advisers may yet find a way to
prevent him from having a stake in future swings in the price of
oil. A Wall Street firm could sign a contract on his options,
locking in his proceeds from the sale of that stock now. But this
would not address the unseemly fact that Halliburton has been
unduly generous to a man who stands a good chance of becoming vice
president.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of lawyers and bankers, Cheney needs to summon all of
his gravitas and do the right thing. That means he should just say
no to any options that would vest after he is in office.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-00 2331EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000823.0447 </DOCNO>
