<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 23:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0680 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-WEST-FIRES-NYT     08-23 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-WEST-FIRES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A NEW APPROACH TO FOREST FIRES  

</HEADLINE>
  c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, Aug. 24:
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration will soon unveil a revised approach
to forest fires. Preliminary reports suggest that the policy will
be smarter than past federal strategies, and much smarter than the
recommendations flowing from President Clinton's opportunistic
Republican critics.
</P>
<P>
   A great deal of nonsense has been spoken about the fires now
raging across the Western United States. Emotional responses are
inevitable when nearly 5 million acres are burning. But there is no
cause for the political posturing in which some public figures have
engaged.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the governor of Montana, the House speaker and the
Republican candidate for president have all suggested that the
administration's efforts to reduce logging on public lands have
made the forests more vulnerable to fire. They have also urged that
Clinton's plan to ban road building in virtually all of the
unprotected roadless areas of the national forests, about 43
million acres, be put on hold. Both arguments serve the timber
industry and ignore reality. Some of the biggest fires are burning
not in wilderness areas but on land that has been developed or
logged.
</P>
<P>
   From what is known of the administration's deliberations, its
revised strategy will concede past mistakes, though not those
identified by its critics. It will recommend continuing the policy
of prescribed fires, or deliberate burns. It will sound some
cautionary notes about building subdivisions too close to nature.
Finally, it will offer something new and expensive _ a plan to thin
out the most fire-prone forests, maybe 40 million acres altogether,
by removing underbrush and small trees while allowing mature,
fire-resistant trees to remain.
</P>
<P>
   In general the policy makes sense, especially when set against
the errors of the past. The main culprit for the present disaster
is the Forest Service's policy of snuffing out fires on public
lands as quickly as possible. This policy took root in 1910, after
the so-called Big Burn in Idaho and Montana wiped out about 3
million acres, and in 1947 actually acquired a popular mascot,
Smokey Bear.
</P>
<P>
   The policy's great flaw was that it disturbed the natural cycle
in which fires periodically swept thorough forests, nourishing the
soil and clearing out underbrush and small trees while sparing
bigger trees. Suppressing these purgative blazes left forests
choked with excess vegetation that provided vast amounts of fuel
for future fires. Excessive logging had the same effect, removing
the biggest and most fire-resistant trees and leaving crowded,
fire-prone stands of young trees.
</P>
<P>
   The Smokey Bear approach was already losing credibility when a
huge fire, fueled partly by dense underbrush, tore through almost
half of Yellowstone National Park in 1988. Thereafter, and
especially under the present Interior secretary, Bruce Babbitt, the
government actually began setting fires in a pre-emptive effort to
prevent bigger fires. Earlier this summer one planned fire, in Los
Alamos, N.M., roared out of control. But the administration
attributes the Los Alamos fire to poor execution, not the policy
itself.
</P>
<P>
   The administration hopes that in time a combination of the new
thinning-out strategy and the older prescribed-burn techniques will
restore the nation's forests to less combustible levels of density.
Thinning out the forests will require a lot of machinery, manpower
and money. But it deserves reasoned debate, as far removed as
possible from partisan sniping.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-00 2332EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000823.0448 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-08-23 23:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0682 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-MEXICANS-VISAS-N     08-23 0497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-MEXICANS-VISAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: VISAS FOR MEXICAN WORKERS 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial for Thursday, Aug. 24:
</P>
<P>
   Mexico's president-elect, Vicente Fox, has some provocative if
premature ideas about cross-border immigration. His ultimate goal
is free movement of labor across an open border. But that is not
practical anytime soon. With the more than tenfold gap between U.S.
and Mexican wages, the migration would be all one way, as low-wage
Mexican workers competed with the poorest, least skilled Americans.
So for now, Fox would like to see Washington significantly increase
the number of temporary visas available to Mexican workers. In
exchange, Mexico would strengthen policies to discourage illegal
emigration to the United States. That is an experiment worth
discussing.
</P>
<P>
   America's current border enforcement policies are not working
well. The nearly $1 billion a year Washington spends to police its
southern border has not measurably reduced the flow of illegal
immigrants from Mexico. Around 340,000 Mexicans enter the United
States every year, well over half of them illegally. Traditionally,
illegal immigration has provided a safety valve for Mexican
governments and low-wage labor for U.S. employers. But it has also
been a source of diplomatic tension, particularly when would-be
immigrants are killed by border agents or unscrupulous smugglers or
die from the effects of heat and dehydration.
</P>
<P>
   Fox proceeds from the realistic assumption that the number of
Mexicans entering the United States each year, either legally or
illegally, will not fall below 340,000. But he would like to see a
significantly larger proportion of that total given legal status,
through the issuance of tens of thousands of additional work visas
annually. He would also like legal status granted to many Mexicans
who entered the United States illegally in the past.
</P>
<P>
   In return, Mexico could crack down on Central Americans who
cross its territory to enter the United States illegally, and
enforce racketeering laws against smuggling syndicates. Any
increases in the number of U.S. visas should be linked to evidence
of improved Mexican border enforcement.
</P>
<P>
   Some Americans fear that adding temporary visas for Mexicans
will drive down wages of low-income Americans, and that any amnesty
for those here illegally will only invite future illegal crossings.
But the border is already highly porous. Some experts believe that
a well-conceived program along the lines Fox suggests could produce
a long-term drop in illegal crossings. Legalized immigrants also
have greater ability to unionize and demand decent conditions,
making them less likely to undermine the status of low-wage
Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Vice President Al Gore and Gov. George W. Bush will both meet
the new Mexican leader during his current visit to the United
States. Both candidates should use the opportunity to learn more
about his immigration ideas.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
