r s BC-RAC-PACIFIC-LADN     08-23 1106
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-PACIFIC-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACIFIC CLASSIC HAS HAD ITS SHARE OF THRILLS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEL MAR, Calif. _ Now it can be told: Right up until post time
in 1991, it was no sure thing that the inaugural Pacific Classic
would even be run.
</P>
<P>
   Del Mar Thoroughbred Club chairman John Mabee and his wife Betty
owned local favorite Best Pal. They also owned San Diego County's
largest grocery-store chain. The Big Bear markets were being
picketed by political activists.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said they would disrupt the race if we didn't stop
selling Folgers coffee,'' Betty Mabee said Wednesday. ``We were
afraid they'd try to harm Best Pal.''
</P>
<P>
   A beefed-up presence by Del Mar security and sheriff's officers
in the saddling paddock was credited with discouraging the
protesters. The race went off without incident and Best Pal scored
a popular victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``If security hadn't been on the ball, it's hard to know what
would have happened,'' Betty Mabee said.
</P>
<P>
   The Pacific Classic will have its 10th running here Saturday.
Since those anxious hours before its debut, most of the excitement
has been confined to the racetrack.
</P>
<P>
   From Best Pal's breakthrough win in 1991, to trainer Bobby
Frankel's four consecutive victories in 1992-95, to Cigar's
historic loss in front of 44,000 fans in 1996, to the humbling
defeats of a succession of stars from out of state, the Pacific
Classic has squeezed a lot into its short history. For Del Mar, the
$1 million race has delivered national attention, and for the
Southern California thoroughbred circuit, it has filled a yawning
gap (or gaping yawn) in the stakes schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember, 20 years ago Del Mar was just a little country
track,'' said Joe Harper, the track's president, CEO and general
manager, overstating it just a bit. ``It had no national status
other than the fact it was the place where Seabiscuit ran once (in
1938) and where Bing Crosby sings a song (`Where the Turf Meets the
Surf'). We needed a signature race.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Del Mar was doing well at the gate,'' said marketing and
publicity director Dan Smith. ``It had a lot of good races, like
the Eddie Read (Handicap, a turf race) and the Del Mar Futurity
(for 2-year-olds), but it didn't have a big purse.''
</P>
<P>
   A million-dollar purse has bought plenty of status.
</P>
<P>
   The 1-mile race for 3-year-olds and up - modeled on the Santa
Anita Handicap and the Hollywood Gold Cup - has drawn its share of
thin fields. This year's seven-horse lineup, headed again by
General Challenge, might be the most-glaring example. That's the
drawback of being isolated on the geographical fringe: Unless
there's a national series and purse bonus to entice out-of-towners,
any California stakes can wind up a locals-only affair.
</P>
<P>
   Another knock on the Pacific Classic: None of its winners has
gone on to confirm his quality by winning the Breeders' Cup Classic
in the fall (although 1993 winner Bertrando did finish second to
Arcangues at the Breeders' Cup). That's a logical result of having
eight out of the nine runnings won by non-favorites.
</P>
<P>
   But overall, the Pacific Classic has done better than its
counterparts at Santa Anita and Hollywood Park at attracting
top-quality horses. Its deepest fields were those in 1991, when
Best Pal defeated Twilight Agenda, Unbridled, Festin, Farma Way and
Itsallgreektome, and 1994, when Tinners Way beat Best Pal, Dramatic
Gold, Slew of Damascus, Stuka and Bertrando.
</P>
<P>
   The star of all Pacific Classic runners is Cigar. The two-time
Horse of the Year's attempt at a 17th consecutive victory, which
would have broken a tie with the great Citation for the recognized
North American record, made the 1996 Pacific Classic the West
Coast's racing event of the decade.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Owner Allen) Paulson said he wanted to bring Cigar home for
the big one,'' Harper remembered. ``I kept thinking, `He has so
many homes - I hope he means the one in Del Mar!' ''
</P>
<P>
   Cigar arrived from New York on the Thursday before the race with
the panache of a thoroughbred Beatle. A San Diego news helicopter
followed his van from the airport to the barn. His appearance
seemed to transcend the sport.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd of 44,181, a Del Mar record by nearly 10,000, filled
the parking lots by 11 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the most excitement I've seen at this racetrack,'' said
William Murray, the novelist (``Tip on a Dead Crab,'' ``I'm Getting
Killed Right Here'') and New Yorker magazine correspondent who has
been coming to Del Mar since the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Cigar, bet down to 1-10, didn't provide exactly the history the
fans came to witness. He and jockey Jerry Bailey chased a fast pace
and were outfinished by 39-1 Dare and Go and jockey Alex Solis.
</P>
<P>
   A year after Richard Mandella-trained Dare and Go became the
longest shot to win, Mandella's Gentlemen became the only favorite
to win.
</P>
<P>
   Cigar's second-place finish epitomized the Pacific Classic's
reputation as a slayer of visiting giants. Among the notable
invaders to lose have been 1990 Kentucky Derby winner Unbridled
(third in 1991), Jolie's Halo (who slipped and dumped his rider at
the start in 1992), Concern (fifth in 1995) and Touch Gold (fifth
in 1998).
</P>
<P>
   Their poor record no doubt has put off some Eastern horsemen.
</P>
<P>
   But the dominance of local horses has been a delight for the
denizens of Del Mar. Particularly Frankel, the Hall of Fame trainer
whose exploits with a procession of upsetters made him the only man
to win the same million-dollar race four years in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's (given) Del Mar a race people pay attention to,'' Frankel
said.``I don't think it's got the charm of a Whitney (the major
summer handicap at Saratoga), but it is a big race.''
</P>
<P>
   Frankel-trained Tinners Way is the only horse to win the Pacific
Classic twice (1994-95), but he didn't win another major race.
Going for three in 1996, he was pulled up with an injury and
promptly retired. Frankel horses finished first and second in 1992
(Missionary Ridge, Defensive Play) and first, second and fourth in
1993 (Bertrando, Missionary Ridge, Marquetry).
</P>
<P>
   If Frankel has been the Pacific Classic's greatest trainer so
far, then Hall of Famer Eddie Delahoussaye (rider of Tinners Way
and three other in-the-money finishers) is its greatest jockey, and
Tinners Way and Best Pal (also third in 1993 and second in 1994)
are its greatest winners.
</P>
<P>
   And to think: Best Pal might never have made it to the starting
gate.
</P>
<P>
   After those inaugural jitters, when a dispute over coffee nearly
intruded on the race, the Pacific Classic has amounted to much more
than a hill of beans.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-08-23-00 2351EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
