<HEADLINE>
NTSB SAYS 747 DESIGN CONTRIBUTED TO FLIGHT 800 CRASH 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JAMES WALLACE  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Boeing's design of the 747, as well as its overall
philosophy for fuel tank safety, contributed to the likely cause of
an explosion that destroyed TWA Flight 800 in 1996, the National
Transportation Safety Board ruled Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   Wrapping up the most expensive investigation of any plane crash,
the board said Boeing erred in the initial design of the 747 when
it placed air conditioning units directly under the plane's center
fuel tank without providing a way to reduce the heat they may
transfer to the tanks.
</P>
<P>
   Before the Paris-bound TWA jet took off, it sat on the ground at
Kennedy International Airport for about three hours with its air
conditioning units running, which heated fuel vapors in the nearly
empty tank to dangerous levels.
</P>
<P>
   As expected, the board said the probable cause of the crash was
an explosion of those flammable vapors from a short circuit in the
aging wiring on the 25-year-old jumbo jet, though the exact
ignition source could not be determined.
</P>
<P>
   NTSB Chairman Jim Hall, in closing remarks after the board
adopted the staff's 25 findings and four recommendations to the
Federal Aviation Administration, said the accident has its roots in
decisions made years earlier by Boeing and the FAA.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the final analysis,'' Hall said, `` ... the 230 men, women
and children on board TWA Flight 800 lost their lives, not as the
result of a bomb or missile or some other nefarious act, but as the
result of a tragic accident _ an accident triggered by an ill-fated
sequence of events in the center wing tank of an aging aircraft
that was set in motion years before by the manufacturer's and the
FAA's design and certification philosophy.''
</P>
<P>
   The conclusion is controversial. Many people still believe a
missile shot down the plane. The board went to great lengths at the
two-day meeting to lay out what it said was overwhelming evidence
Flight 800 was not brought down by a criminal act.
</P>
<P>
   Rather, the likely cause of the explosion was a short circuit
outside the center fuel tank that allowed explosive voltage to
enter the tank through electrical wiring associated with the fuel
quantity indication system, the board ruled.
</P>
<P>
   Michel Breistroff from Paris, whose son Michel, 24, had been
about to join the French Olympic hockey team, he is not convinced
the plane was brought down by a mechanical problem. He said he had
lingering doubts about a missile or some other nonmechanical means.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have been explaining to me but inside my head I don't
fully believe what they are saying. I wish I could be convinced so
I could be free,'' said Breistroff, one of about 70 family members
of crash victims who attended Wednesday's meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The plane exploded about 11 minutes after take off from Kennedy
the evening of July 17, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Lychner of Houston, who lost his wife, Pam, a former TWA
flight attendant, and his two young daughters, Shannon and Katie,
found little comfort at the hearing and the board's conclusion
about the likely cause of the accident.
</P>
<P>
   ``The presentation by the NTSB has been excellent but there have
been no surprises,'' he was quoted as saying in an Associated Press
story. ``The center fuel tank blew up and killed my family and the
loved ones of the other family members. That is not supposed to
happen, is it?''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, it might not have happened had Boeing and the aviation
industry focused not only on possible fuel tank ignition sources,
but the potential for fuel vapors to explode, said Bernard Loeb,
the safety board's longtime director of its office of aviation
safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``This accident would not have occurred, but for the flammable
vapor in the center wing tank,'' he said. ``We believe that perhaps
the most valuable lesson that can be learned from this accident _
and our best hope for preventing similar accidents in the future _
lies in recognizing this fact.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Hinderberger, director of airplane safety for Boeing who
attended the meeting with two other Boeing commercial airplane
executives, said he did not disagree with the board's findings of
probable cause, though he believes the industry's fuel tank design
philosophy has proved sound.
</P>
<P>
   ``We feel as we have stated from the beginning that the most
appropriate way to ensure fuel tank safety is to eliminate all
possible ignition sources,'' he told reporters after the board
meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``And we have also said an additional level of protection can be
obtained by reducing the exposure to flammable fuel vapors. So
seeing a probable cause or finding or recommendation that goes
along the lines of eliminating ignition sources and reducing
flammable fuel vapors would appear to me to be consistent with our
submission (Boeing's report to the safety board) and our stance all
along.''
</P>
<P>
   All of Boeing's planes other than the 717, formerly the
McDonnell Douglas MD-95, have air conditioning units, known as
packs, located directly below the center wing tank.
</P>
<P>
   McDonnell Douglas jets have air conditioning units in the front
or rear of the plane. Airbus jets have air conditioning packs under
the center wing tank, but the design incorporates a ventilation
system that cools the heated air given off by the units as the
plane climbs.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the Boeing design, Hinderberger said, ``I hate to
stand here in front of you after all the hard work that has been
done over the last four years and wind the clock back 30 years and
say a mistake was made.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have all learned a lot in last four years that was outlined
over the last two days and we all have opportunities to move
forward in fuel system safety,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA is looking at tank ventilation as well as a ground-based
system that would pump inert gas into the fuel tanks, which would
greatly lessen the chance the fuel vapors could become flammable.
</P>
<P>
   That was one of 11 recommendations previously made by the board
to the FAA based on early information from the TWA crash
investigation. Only one of those recommendations remains classified
as open, the board said Wednesday. That is a recommendation to
require temperature probes in the fuel tanks so pilots can monitor
the temperature of the fuel.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA says that would not be necessary if the ground inerting
system proves workable, or if the center wing tanks can be cooled
by direct ventilation.
</P>
<P>
   Much of Wednesday's board meeting focused on wiring problems
found on airplanes, including the TWA jet, and the board's four new
recommendations to the FAA reflected its concern about wiring.
</P>
<P>
   The board called on the federal agency to review aircraft wiring
systems on all U.S. certified aircraft and determine which ones are
critical to safety and then require whatever safety revisions are
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA and the aviation industry have launched aging-aircraft
programs to better understand the issues.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Swaim of the board's aviation engineering division
presented an alarming report at Wednesday's meeting on problems
found with wiring recovered from the TWA jet. That included exposed
wiring where the insulation was broken or worn away, which can
result in a short circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators then looked at wiring on more than a half dozen
other jets and found similar problems, especially on older planes,
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Swaim said investigators found a number of foreign objects in
the wiring of the jets inspected. The objects included a dinner
knife that likely slipped through a gap in the passenger cabin
wall. Objects also inclued screwdrivers and coat hangers, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators also found metal drill shavings in both old and
new planes, he said. These shavings can cut through a wire and
cause a short circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Shavings were even found on the fuel quantity indicator in the
fuel tank of a new 747-400 that had not yet been delivered, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Hall asked Dr. Vernon Ellingstad, director of science labs at
the board, to look at aircraft accidents over the past 20 years to
determine if there is any correlation between the accidents and
older airplanes.
</P>
<P>
   The chairman said he wanted to know if there is any ``safety
benefit'' to providing the public with information about the age of
the planes on which they fly. He asked for the report by Nov. 15.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have not seen that the industry is paying the type of
attention it needs to pay to older aircraft,'' Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   John Goglia, one of the board's five members, complained there
is no system in place for reporting airplane wiring problems.
</P>
<P>
   Before he joined the board, Goglia spent about 30 years as an
airline mechanic.
</P>
<P>
   Goglia's voice was choked with emotion as he told the audience
of bringing other mechanics to view a 93-foot section of the TWA
jet that was reconstructed in a hangar from the hundreds of
thousands of pieces of wreckage pulled from the bottom of the
Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   In his closing remarks, Hall recalled the 1963 crash of a Boeing
707 in a Maryland cornfield. The fuel tank on the jet exploded
after the plane was struck by lightning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I recently came across the following quotation: `It is
recommended that every effort be expended to arrive at a practical
means by which flammable air/vapor mixtures are eliminated from
fuel tanks.' This was presented to the FAA by our predecessor
agency, the Civil Aeronautics Board, on December 17, 1963,
following the crash of Pan American Flight 214 near Elkton,
Maryland,'' Hall said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost 40 years later, it is imperative that at long last, the
aviation community move with dispatch to remove flammable fuel/air
mixtures from the fuel tanks of transport category aircraft.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
